<HEADLINE>
UNDESERVING L.A. IS ON THE MONEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Two cities were bidding for the affections of a
very wealthy, very insular few. One city had the concrete plan, the
other, all the right connections. We don't need to tell you who won
out in the end. Connections beat concrete plans sure as paper beats
rock.
</P>
<P>
   But enough about Salt Lake City and how it was aced out for the
1998 Winter Olympics by Nagano, Japan, setting into motion all the
bribes that padded the U.S. city's successful 2002 bid.
</P>
<P>
   Houston is the city standing today on the wrong side of the
tracks, wounded and wondering what the heck just hit it. Did anyone
get a glimpse of that NFL gravy train?
</P>
<P>
   Like Salt Lake City eight years ago, Houston had all the
infrastructure in place. Nearly $200 million in public funds had
been earmarked for a new $310 million stadium with a retractable
roof in the eighth-largest television market.
</P>
<P>
   Then Hollywood mogul Michael Ovitz signed on with one L.A. bid
and Eli Broad, the second-wealthiest man in a city that wears its
opulence on its fitted silk jacket sleeve, attached his bank
account to another. And all of the sudden the NFL owners couldn't
see the town for the tinsel.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of taking note of a populace altogether ambivalent about
pro football, the NFL owners saw the SECOND-LARGEST TELEVISION
MARKET in flashing neon lights. In the end it didn't matter that
L.A.'s two divergent bids are a perfect metaphor for the city they
represent, the NFL owners awarded Los Angeles an NFL franchise,
contingent on its settling on a stadium and locking in financing
and community support by Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously money _ specifically the currency that comes with
higher overall television ratings and advertising rates _ was the
only thing that really mattered. Which raises the question, who's
chaperoning these football lords, Paul Tagliabue or His Excellency,
Juan Antonio Samaranch?
</P>
<P>
   As the Olympics apparently have for years, the 32nd NFL team was
awarded to the highest bidder rather than the most qualified bid.
Let's face it; it's hard to top 5.5 million television homes.
</P>
<P>
   Billionaire Bob McNair, who headed Houston's bid, is a
businessman above all else. So he could see where the vote was
headed before it became official on Tuesday. Thus, his lament:
``We've done everything they've asked us to do and we've done it in
a first-class way. You get frustrated, disappointed, but that's
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Tell Salt Lake City about it. That city was sitting awfully
pretty in 1991 before Japanese business interests collected a few
million dollars to give to IOC president Samaranch's pet project,
the Olympic Museum, and effectively bought the 1998 Games.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Lake City Olympic organizers wised up after that. They
played the game by the IOC's house rules, greasing palms all the
way to the 1995 handshake with which they sealed the 2002 bid.
</P>
<P>
   Among the hundreds of thousands of dollars allegedly doled out
in cash or trips or gifts to IOC members and their families by the
Salt Lake Olympic Organizing Committee was a junket to the Super
Bowl for IOC member Phil Coles of Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Hmmmm. Any NFL owner game for a free trip to the Sydney 2000
Summer Games courtesy of Australian Rupert Murdoch? You know him;
the mate who owns the Fox network, which has a long-term television
deal with the league that just awarded a franchise to the city that
currently claims as its wealthiest resident . . . Murdoch.
</P>
<P>
   More than one can play that game, which is why you can expect
McNair to get in the NFL's hair the next few months. Even before
Tuesday's vote, he had let it be known he intends to go after
another city's franchise if Houston didn't get its own.
</P>
<P>
   He already has begun the courting process, writing nine owners
who are facing stadium issues and letting them know that if they
don't find love in their respective cities, then he and all of
Houston are standing by, with open checkbooks, open hearts and open
arms.
</P>
<P>
   An open checkbook bought Salt Lake City a second shot. Why not
Houston?
</P>
<P>
   Buried under the money trail is the unvarnished truth; L.A. no
more wants or deserves the NFL than Nagano residents wanted or
deserved the Winter Olympics. Sporting spectacles, whether they're
held once every four years or once every fall weekend, ought to be
bestowed upon the appreciative, not shoved down the throats of the
apathetic so that an elite few can pick gold out of their teeth. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
