<HEADLINE>
RODMAN'S TEAMMATES TOLERANT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Dennis Rodman could trade the blackjack tables for
the basketball court by the end of the Lakers' current road trip.
In the meantime, he can take solace in the fact he plays for an
extraordinarily understanding team.
</P>
<P>
   While the Lakers played the first two games of a six-game road
trip, Rodman was excused to tend to ``personal business,'' presumed
to be marital problems with wife Carmen Electra.
</P>
<P>
   Then he was spotted in Las Vegas. Somehow, even that didn't
bother the Lakers, who subscribe to a new-age brand of therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's his psychologist, you know what I mean?'' Kobe Bryant
said. ``For me, it's basketball, for him it's gambling and doing
other things. . . . He's by himself. He's not fortunate like I'm
fortunate to have a strong family. If I had a problem, I'd go to my
family.''
</P>
<P>
   But seeking peace of mind at Caesar's?
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's his outlet, that's his outlet,'' Bryant said.
``Nobody's gonna say it's right, nobody's gonna say it's wrong.
It's his business.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Kurt Rambis said he heard Rodman might rejoin the team by
the end of the road trip, which concludes Monday in Dallas, but
he's not assuming anything.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman's camp, meanwhile, perhaps preparing to go into spin
mode, has hired a public relations firm to handle inquiries over
his absence. The firm issued the following statement: ``Dennis
appreciates the level of interest that people have taken in his
life. He's currently resolving personal matters and looks forward
to rejoining the Lakers with the same intensity that he's displayed
throughout his career. Dennis also appreciates the support of his
teammates and the Lakers' management.''
</P>
<P>
   Make that ``unconditional support.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal dismissed reports of Rodman's gambling trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in the most gossipy city there is, so you never know.
. . . I don't know if he was in Vegas or not,'' O'Neal said. ``But
if he was, that wouldn't be the right thing to do. But you never
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Reinforcements: The Lakers have hired Dave Wohl as an assistant
coach for his second tour of duty with the team. Wohl, a Lakers
assistant from 1982-85, fills the vacancy created when Rambis was
promoted to head coach after the dismissal of Del Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Wohl, a former head coach of the New Jersey Nets and assistant
for five teams, most recently served as vice president for
basketball operations for the Miami Heat, from 1994-96.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just here to help all of us out, to add his experience as
a former player, coach and general manager. He brings a lot of
knowledge and experience to the table,'' said Rambis, who played
under Wohl with the Lakers. ``To me it was a no-brainer.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohl will join the team in time for Thursday night's game in
Cleveland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
