<P>
   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, March 17.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-NUKE (Washington) _ In advance of Russian Prime Minister
Yevgeni Primakov's visit to the United States next week, the two
nations are working out details on an agreement involving nuclear
security. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   EURO-ASSESS (Brussels) _ A news analysis: What does the
resignation of the European Union's executive body mean, and why
does it matter? By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-U.S.-AHERN (Dublin) _ A profile of Bertie Ahern, the
Irish prime minister, who meets with President Clinton at the White
House on Wednesday (St. Patrick's Day). By James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-FOSSIL (Sterkfontein Caves, South Africa) _ Deep in the
dark, dank caverns here, Dr. Ronald J. Clarke, a man with a long
list of academic credentials, is at work. He is sprawled against a
rock face, lying on an old camping mattress, his tools scattered on
a nearby ledge: a few sharpened nail punches, some dental picks,
Super Glue, a old jam jar full of lacquer. With a rusting hammer
and his tiny chisels, he tap, tap, taps, gentle millimeter by
millimeter, chipping the rock away from around his discovery.
Embedded in the stone is a skeleton perhaps 3.6 million years old _
a skeleton that may help answer some of the enduring questions
about human evolution. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SETTLEMENT (ELI, West Bank) _ From this entrenched Jewish
settlement on a bluff above the Palestinian territories, the vista
is dotted for miles around with what Israelis and Palestinians call
``facts on the ground.'' Almost every hilltop bears a scattering of
mobile homes, evidence of the continuing and willful expansion of
the Jewish presence in the West Bank. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.
Photos [NYT14,15) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SLEEP-ELDERLY (Undated) _ About 25 percent to 35 percent of
older Americans have troubles sleeping, but their fitful nights are
often viewed as a normal part of aging and go untreated by their
doctors or caretakers. Now, researchers report that insomnia in
older adults can be effectively treated with cognitive-behavior
therapy, with sleeping medication, or with a combination of the
two. The therapy proved longer lasting than drug treatment, the
researchers report Wednesday in the Journal of the American Medical
Association. By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   CHESS-BLACK-GRANDMASTER (New York) _ Twenty years ago, when
Maurice Ashley was 14 and living in Brownsville, Brooklyn, he was
soundly defeated in an offhand game of chess. Embarrassed and
angry, he dug up a paperback on the game, intending to brush up, to
learn a trick or two. Instead, he fell deeply in love. On Monday,
he reached the pinnacle of his passion: He became the latest of the
world's 470 grandmasters, and the first black person to reach the
game's highest rank. By Barbara Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT21) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   HARVARD-ANGST (Cambridge, Mass.) _ For the first time anyone
here can remember, Harvard College is wondering whether it should
find a way to get students out of their rooms and away from their
books to _ gasp _ relax and socialize. By Julie Flaherty.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT17) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RENO-COUNSEL-LAW _ Attorney General Janet Reno has decided to
announce at a Senate hearing on Wednesday that the independent
counsel statute is ``structurally flawed'' and should be abandoned,
a striking reversal from her past embrace of the 21-year old
Watergate-era reform law, Government officials say. By David
Johnston and Don Van Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN-EARNINGS (New York) _ Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co., the last
major, private investment bank on Wall Street, outlines plans to
sell 13 percent of its shares to the public for as much as $3
billion to bankroll an expansion in an increasingly competitive
industry. Goldman's current partners would own 47 percent of the
firm, the remaining employees would own 10 percent. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   WASTE-ECO-PARKS (Undated) _ More and more companies have begun
to buy their neighbors' wastes, or sell their own, and now economic
development agencies and private developers are building so-called
eco-industrial parks around the concept. Some are doing it to
attract jobs, others to reduce trash flows, still others simply to
make money. The principle: One company's waste can be its
neighbor's raw ingredient. By Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT25,26,27) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   FORECASTS-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ The strong performance of the
economy so far this year has pushed the earnings forecasts of many
strategists higher. For example, Bruce Steinberg, chief economist
at Merrill Lynch, turned his earnings growth prediction on its
head, flipping to an increase of 3.5 percent from a decline of 5
percent. But his colleague, Richard Bernstein, says the direction
of earnings is down, not up. Disagreements within one shop are not
unusual, but this difference in direction does show how confusing
the earnings outlook might be for investors _ and how quickly it
can change. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   AMFAR-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ A giant ad-agency company is
enlisting in the fight against AIDS to battle not fear or ignorance
but a perception that the fight is finished. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HEAVY-METAL (Asbury Park) _ Heavy metal lives _ scenes from
festival in Asbury Park. By Ben Ratliff.
</P>
