immigrant.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BOX-BERKOW-COLUMN (New York) _ Sports of The Times column: As
the history of the sport makes clear, the appeal of boxing is
rooted in its corrupt nature. The Holyfield-Lewis draw is just
another chapter. By Ira Berkow.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING (Moved in ``d'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LAYER-CAKE (Undated) _ The layer cake, an American icon, is in
dire straits. Decades of supermarket cake mixes have inflicted some
real harm at home, of course. Most bakeries, with their airy cakes
frosted in sugared shortening, have simply failed to hold up their
end of the bargain. And high-end restaurants, where the layer cake
once played such a proud role, have left it for dead, a casualty of
the war among today's dueling pastry chefs. By Milissa Clark.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT1,2) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   LAYER-CAKE-HISTORY (Undated) _ On the history of the layer cake.
</P>
<P>
   AMISH-COOKING (New York) _ Amish. For centuries, the word has
been associated with devout religious belief, barn raisings and
Kelly McGillis churning butter for Harrison Ford. Now it has a new
connotation. Just listen to Mark Spangenthal, the chef at the
Screening Room, explaining why he brought his Amish chicken dish
from The Markham, his old restaurant, to the Screening Room:
``There is nothing more American than the word Amish,'' he said.
``I don't want to say sexy. Sexy isn't the right word. But it looks
real nice on the menu.'' By Rick Marin.
</P>
