</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S L.A.'S TEAM TO LOSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By BOB KEISSER &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   PHOENIX -- It's fourth down and six months to go for Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   National Football League executives and owners, fearful of
losing any chance of returning to Los Angeles in the foreseeable
future, pushed through a resolution here Tuesday giving L.A.
approval for an expansion team if it meets certain conditions in
the next six months.
</P>
<P>
   The league's 12-member expansion committee will meet in Los
Angeles in the next two-to-three weeks to scout the two stadium
site locations, Carson and the New Coliseum, and meet with the
proposed ownership teams led by entertainment leader Michael Ovitz
(Carson) and L.A. businessmen Ed Roski and Eli Broad (Coliseum).
The committee's first mandate is to reach a consensus on one L.A.
site and stadium project.
</P>
<P>
   The conditions are both specific and vague. The committee will
want to see specific documentation for the construction of a
state-of-the-art stadium, hard financing plans for both the stadium
and franchise fee, and the source and commitment of all public
investments and relationships.
</P>
<P>
   The more vague conditions include a commitment from the L.A.
business sector in terms of PSL and luxury suites sales; expansion
of ownership teams to include more L.A.-based business leaders;
veiled hints for more public money; and more interest from the
common fan in regards to the NFL's return to L.A.
</P>
<P>
   If neither L.A. group satisfies the league's conditions by
September 15, the expansion committee will recommend that a 32nd
team be given to Houston and businessman Robert McNair.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good compromise. We've tightened up the window to
benefit Houston, and to clear up some things that are not clear in
Los Angeles,'' said Jerry Richardson, the Carolina Panthers owner
and co-chairman of the expansion committee. ``If we just went to
Houston, we'd never know if we could have gotten something done in
L.A.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bringing the committee to L.A. will give them a close look at
both sites and come back to the full ownership with a consensus. We
don't have an answer for all of our questions right now. It's a
short window to learn, but we have to start somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Both L.A. groups welcomed the news and considered it a personal
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thankful to have the NFL come back to Los Angeles,'' said
Ovitz, the former Hollywood agent and Disney Co. President. ``I'm
pleased that we have achieved this part of our goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, it's (L.A.'s) to lose. We'll continue to do our
best to make this happen. We're looking forward to showing the
league everything in our deal. We'll follow the league's cues.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome the league coming out and going through all parts
of our project,'' said Roski, the L.A. Kings owner. ``Each time
we've been asked questions or given suggestions, we've followed
(the NFL's) lead and answered them. We're there. We have a plan, a
facility and the financial capability.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing standing in our way. I think fans in L.A. have
been waiting for this, and you'll now see a groundswell of
support.''
</P>
<P>
   The conditional resolution was devised and endorsed by
Commissioner Paul Tagliabue, vice-president of development Roger
Goodell, and a handful of key owners Richardson, New England's Bob
Kraft, Denver's Pat Bowlen who felt the league needed to explore a
return to L.A. fully before expanding somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``L.A. is an important city,'' said Bowlen. ``We're looking for
a deal. We want to know if either of these bids are viable. I'm
optimistic one is, because we should be in L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong sentiment arose for Houston during the course of two days
of meetings, leading to the conditional terms and shorter window.
``We do not want to appear to be abandoning Houston,'' said
Steelers' owner Dan Rooney.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've (L.A.) got six months to get their house in order. I
want to see real interest in L.A., that they want a team and that
they have the wherewithal to build a stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue's promise to owners, sources said, was that a return
to L.A. would improve TV ratings (and subsequently rights fees) and
produce a larger franchise fee than another city.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue said Tuesday that ``I would be surprised if other
(L.A. business) people did not come into the picture'' with the
league's resolution. ``We'd like to see businesses come in like
they did in Carolina (when the Panthers won an expansion team) and
Cleveland.''
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue said the league hasn't urged the L.A. groups to merge
their forces, but the league expects a consensus. Once the league's
committee makes a decision, it expects the losing group to support
the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Roski said he invited Ovitz to join his group two years ago and
that the invitation still stands. He said that while he, Broad and
the handful of other equity owners can handle the financial side,
he's willing to add other business leaders to the ownership group
if the league feels it's necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Roski said he's not in a position to join any Carson group. He
has an exclusive contract to put a team in the Coliseum. Ovitz has
only a memoranda of understanding with Carson at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz spokesman Peter Levin said ``we take all of our cues from
the league. But we feel our proposal is great. If it were not for
Michael Ovitz, I don't think the NFL would even be looking at Los
Angeles. He deserves credit for stimulating the interest the league
has for L.A. today.''
</P>
<P>
   Carson city officials remain optimistic about their chances.
They expect to meet with Ovitz in the next few days to discuss the
NFL's visit and firm up their portion of all agreements, which
include a $150 million bond issue and a $30 million cash
contribution. A source close to the city said it may have access to
additional RDA funds if necessary, at no tax cost or liability to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. City Councilman Mark Ridley-Thomas said there is no other
public money available for the Coliseum. ``The public financial
investment already there is significant and should not be
minimized,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The state has invested $120 million in infrastructure around the
Coliseum, the federal investment in facility upgrades (as a result
of the Northridge earthquake) are worth $100 million, and the land
where the Coliseum sits is worth $85 million.
</P>
<P>
   The city has invested $40 million in new money via a
Redevelopment Agency and ticket surcharges. And terms of an
operating arrangement will turn the operation of the facility from
the unwieldly Coliseum Commission to Roski and his group.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no more public money available,'' he said. ``The
league needs to be more flexible in regards to where the money
comes from. It has been our contention from the start that the
public should not have to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
