<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MEETING-EXPANSION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LA GETS CONDITIONAL NFL NOD  
 INVESTORS FACE SEPT. 15 DEADLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Until at least Sept. 15, the NFL loves LA.
</P>
<P>
   But the league, which hasn't had a team in the Los Angeles area
since 1995, is giving the two groups trying to bring an expansion
team there a six-month deadline to meet the owners' conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Denver Broncos owner Pat Bowlen, attending the league meeting at
the Arizona Biltmore on Tuesday, called the Sept. 15 deadline, a
``drop-dead'' date.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it doesn't work in LA, we'll immediately move on to
Houston,'' said Carolina Panthers owner Jerry Richardson, chairman
of the expansion committee.
</P>
<P>
   The owners didn't choose between Los Angeles ownership groups _
entertainment mogul Michael Ovitz, who wants to build a stadium on
a former municipal landfill in Carson, Calif., or real estate
developers Edward P. Roski Jr. and El Broad, who want to rebuild
Los Angeles Coliseum. But they did say they expect to narrow the
decision to one site after visiting Los Angeles in two to three
weeks. The team would start play in the 2002 season.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL also announced that it would look at realigning into
four eight-team divisions beginning for that season.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the NFL chose a conditional deal in Los Angeles when a
more solid one was presented by Houston businessman Bob McNair,
Cincinnati Bengals President Mike Brown said the league felt it
needed a team in the nation's second-biggest city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to have a team there,'' Brown said. ``I don't know
if they can get it done, but they should at least try. It's the
best thing for the league.''
</P>
<P>
   The owner's resolution to place the league's 32nd franchise in
Los Angeles, which lost the Rams to St. Louis and the Raiders to
Oakland in 1995, passed by a vote of 29-2. The Raiders and Buffalo
Bills were the only dissenting votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do own the Los Angeles opportunity,'' said Al Davis,
president of the general partner of the Raiders who has filed a
lawsuit against the league claiming that he still owns the rights
to the market.
</P>
<P>
   Carmen Policy, president of the Browns, said the owners aren't
worried that Davis' suit could scare the league from putting an
expansion team in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Categorically, no,'' Policy said. ``. . . They are the Oakland
Raiders. They can't be the Oakland Raiders and the Los Angeles
Raiders at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners weren't specific as to what conditions Los Angeles
has to meet other than providing the necessary funding for a
state-of-the-art stadium and more commitments from the Los Angeles
business community.
</P>
<P>
   ``What financial plan?'' Bowlen said. ``We haven't seen any
financial plan.''
</P>
<P>
   An NFL spokesman said the owners want to see the Los Angeles
business community pledge to sell luxury suites, club seats and
personal seat licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Roski thinks his deal at the Coliseum will eventually be
selected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we've gotten the project together,'' he said. ``We
think the venue is great. We think the ownership team brings a lot
to the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Some owners don't necessarily agree. San Diego Chargers owner
Alex Spanos said teams don't want to return to playing in the
Coliseum, which the Rams left in 1980 and the Raiders left in '95.
</P>
<P>
   Roski said if the owners prefer Ovitz as an owner and the Carson
site, he wouldn't be an obstacle to Los Angeles meeting the
league's deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're focused on getting an expansion team in LA,'' Roski
said. ``We're not going to stand in the way to get LA a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said Houston officials, who already have committed
nearly $200 million toward a $310 million facility, shouldn't take
the decision as ``gloom and doom.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair said he still is optimistic Houston might get the
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a deadline established is something we hoped for,''
McNair said. ``I think it will be a challenge for LA to get it
done. It was a challenge for us, and we have a lot more passion for
football than they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said it was up to the league to ``rekindle the
interest and create the passion of the NFL in Los Angeles. We have
to start somewhere. I don't think we help rekindle the interest and
passion if we go to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   In other business:
</P>
<P>
   NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue also announced that 49ers owner
Eddie DeBartolo will be fined $1 million and remain suspended
through next February for ``lying'' about being involved in
riverboat gambling in Lousiana.
</P>
<P>
   The owners are keeping the annual Thanksgiving Day games in
Dallas and Detroit and will vote on instant replay today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
