<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-OWNERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL OWNERS PICK LOS ANGELES OVER HOUSTON 

</HEADLINE>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Houston's yearlong wooing of the National Football
League turned to heartbreak Tuesday when league owners spurned its
plea for an expansion team in favor of aloof Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   By a 29-2 vote, the NFL approved a resolution to award Los
Angeles its 32nd franchise if that city can cobble together a
satisfactory ownership team and stadium deal by Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   League officials said that deadline could be extended if a deal
is close to completion by then.
</P>
<P>
   If negotiations fall short _ and many believe that the passive
Los Angeles football market can't swing a deal _ the league's
Expansion Committee will recommend that Houston get the expansion
team.
</P>
<P>
   Houston businessman Bob McNair called the decision a small
victory for Houston. He said he had feared that Los Angeles would
be given 10 months. His exclusive agreement with the Harris
County-Houston Sports Authority expires Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Los Angeles' tepid response, and its aversion to
using public dollars to build a stadium, McNair believes he still
has a chance to get the expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he also will continue trying to buy an existing
team and move it to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Asked after the vote if Los Angeles could get the deal done in
time, a smiling McNair said, ``It will be a challenge. It was a
challenge for us, and I think Houston has got much more passion for
football than Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Expansion Committee Co-chairman Jerry Richardson, owner of the
Carolina Panthers, said the committee will go to Los Angeles within
three weeks to begin working on a deal.
</P>
<P>
   The league set up three vague criteria that must be satisfied
before Los Angeles gets a team. They are:
</P>
<P>
   _ A consensus about a specific site and stadium project in the
greater Los Angeles market.
</P>
<P>
   _ An agreement for the construction of a state-of-the-art
stadium that addresses the issues of financing, facility management
and other key items.
</P>
<P>
   _ Commitments from the business community to actively support
the re-establishment of a successful NFL franchise in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Roski, the only one of the three primary Los Angeles players
in town Tuesday, said that he was not sure exactly what his
proposal lacked and that a deal can be done now to satisfy the
league's criteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready to go today,'' Roski said. ``We have an existing
facility. We don't have to purchase the land. We don't have any
bond issues. We have the fan support and political support and
corporate support. We're ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   One issue NFL officials said they will explore is exactly who
has control of the Coliseum, a point that could cause the league to
deal only with Roski.
</P>
<P>
   Several team owners would prefer to work out a deal in Los
Angeles, then sell it to the highest bidder, as they did for
Cleveland last year, when Al Lerner bid $530 million for an
expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   Roski said he has an exclusive two-year agreement for the
Coliseum, which appears to be the league's preferred site in Los
Angeles, but would waive it if it were in the city's best interest.
</P>
<P>
   While NFL officials won't directly come out and say it, the
league seems to want Los Angeles to commit public funds, thus
reducing the amount a new owner would have to put into a stadium
and increasing the expansion fee, which 31 team owners would share.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution approved Tuesday says that the ``NFL shall
immediately establish a public-private partnership in the greater
Los Angeles market to work toward satisfying the foregoing
condition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be some kind of public support,'' said San Diego
Chargers owner Alex Spanos.
</P>
<P>
   Under Houston's deal, which includes $195 million in public
dollars to subsidize a $310 million, retractable-roof stadium,
McNair says he can afford an expansion fee up to $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   Roski has said that neither Los Angeles nor the state of
California can fund a Coliseum deal because of the political
climate. He also said he can afford a $500 million franchise fee
and pay for a $350 million renovation of the Coliseum, all with
private funds.
</P>
<P>
   But there is disagreement within the Roski-Broad team, said a
source close to the group. Eli Broad has indicated he believes the
Los Angeles market can only afford a $400 million expansion fee if
it must also pay for a $350 million stadium update.
</P>
<P>
   League officials have discussed providing a low-interest loan to
help build a stadium, but only if the city provided some tax
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Such a plan was considered to help troubled teams in Boston,
Chicago and Philadelphia, but many owners are not willing to help
other teams after having to put together their own deals in smaller
cities.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, while Los Angeles is considered the better city
because it is a much larger television market, Roski will not
promise to do the same thing McNair has done to guarantee that all
home games are televised.
</P>
<P>
   McNair last week promised that all home games would be sold out
during the first five years, which would avoid potential television
blackouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that is important,'' Roski said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Los Angeles television market is attractive, many
owners did not want to discard a done deal in Houston that many
believe is one of the sport's best.
</P>
<P>
   Voting against the resolution were Oakland Raiders owner Al
Davis, who believes he still controls the Los Angeles market
despite leaving it four years ago, and Buffalo Bills owner Ralph
Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   During an emotional expansion committee discussion early in the
day, Houston received verbal support from Tennessee Titans owner
Bud Adams, who moved his team there three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion Houston will have a team at some point,'' Adams
said.
</P>
<P>
   Adams' opinion was shared by many owners who believe that the
league must eventually be in both cities. McNair had hoped the
league might expand to 33 teams, giving each city an expansion
club, but that proposal was ignored by owners who don't want to
dilute the talent pool or share TV revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Houston officials expressed optimism that the city would
eventually get an NFL team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am disappointed that the NFL did not recognize the benefits
of coming to Houston and award a franchise to this city outright,''
said Houston Mayor Lee Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles may have a bigger media market, but Houston is a
great market and has the best deal and the best fan support.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the game is not over. There is no guarantee that Los
Angeles will be better-organized six months from now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
