<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-WOOD-CURSE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURSE OF THE CUBS  
 WOOD'S INJURY LATEST GLOOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - There's nothing to support a hex. Nothing but the
cackle of a Billy Goat, the great collapse in '69, the shrieks of
Ron Santo as Brant Brown flubs a flyball.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing but a curse known as the Ex-Cub Factor, a library
book-ended by Donnie Moore and Bill Buckner. Nothing but the
missing void in Ernie Banks' career or the bumbling fate of Leon
Durham or the shadows that still follow Don Young.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing but Lou Brock-for-Ernie Broglio. Or an icon broadcaster
who died, missing out on Sammy in the White House and the biggest
party in years.
</P>
<P>
   And, now, the terrible twist in the legend of Kerry Wood.
</P>
<P>
   To truly know misery, you must be a Cubs fan. Only you can
appreciate how a gift from heaven blows out his arm, reduced to one
year of rehabilitation, minimum. How a phenom sent to save the
future is facing serious questions about his own. How Kerry Wood
might turn out to be an apparition, the cruelest tease of all.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, this is sad. In the stardust of 1998, Kerry
Wood was Kid Whiff, the next dominant pitcher in baseball, the
unassuming face from Texas destined to become the millennium's
version of Nolan Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   He once struck out 20, turning the baseball world on its ear. He
was Rookie of the Year. He bought a home in Scottsdale. He had the
world bailing out in the batter's box.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, after one pitch in his exhibition debut, Wood once
again complained of discomfort in his elbow. He threw only
fastballs that day, lasting only four outs. And later that night,
he was despondent that the pain was still alive, under the surface,
waiting to explode.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel awful for that young man,'' team broadcaster Steve
Stone said. ``I know he was extremely disappointed before he found
out what was wrong. Just the fact that he still had pain in his
arm.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely, they are fuming inside Tribune Tower, wondering where
this went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Was it at Grand Prairie High School in Texas and a coach who
rode him like a mule, once starting Wood in both games of a
doubleheader?
</P>
<P>
   Was it an inevitable breakdown of a power pitcher diagnosed with
bad mechanics?
</P>
<P>
   Or was it the botched decision to start Wood in Game 3 of last
year's playoffs, down two to the Braves in a series they couldn't
possibly win, ``after'' he had been shut down all of September
because of elbow problems?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe those five innings on a cold night in October mean
nothing. Or maybe a botched decision has tragic consequences.
</P>
<P>
   This is certain: Last season, Cubs Manager Jim Riggleman was
consistently booed for adhering to pitch counts, thus robbing
Wrigley Field patrons of complete games and the chance to hang K's.
Earlier this spring, he vowed that Wood would not exceed 200
innings in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   For the Cubs to risk everything for so little in last year's
postseason is wretchedly inept. And some people should know better
than to tempt fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to comment on that,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, no one knows when Wood's arm gave out. After striking
out 20 on a magical day at Wrigley, he came to Arizona and blew
away the Diamondbacks. After that, he won games, but the dominance
was missing. And now he's on the shelf for one year, maybe two.
</P>
<P>
   There are elbow specialists, advancements in medicine, reason to
hope that a 21-year-old has plenty of time to recover. But will he
ever be the same? The velocity? The breaking ball? Will he ever
have the ammunition to be like Ryan? To be great?
</P>
<P>
   Because, for a while, he was. As dominant as any young prospect
in memory, a kid who struck out 573 hitters in 445 innings since
breaking into the minor leagues, a symbol that the hex might be
history.
</P>
<P>
   Except it only gets worse.
</P>
<P>
   So the organization that hasn't been to the World Series in 91
years can wait 'till next century. And pray that the curse only
spanned the 1900s. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
