<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-FLORIDA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DONOVAN MAKES GATORS BELIEVE  
 COACH'S WORK ETHIC MODEL FOR PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Billy Donovan still hears his father's voice in the
back of his mind. Do more. Don't quit. Work hard.
</P>
<P>
   It drove him as a player in Long Island, where he wore out
basketballs and would sneak into gyms to play.
</P>
<P>
   It drove him at Providence, where, prodded and challenged by
Rick Pitino, he shed 25 pounds and shot and dived and passed the
Friars to an unbelievable Final Four run in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   It drives him now at Florida, where he works endless hours,
snagging recruits away from national powerhouses and convincing
them to go to Gainesville, where, they say, there are only three
seasons: football, football recruiting and spring football.
</P>
<P>
   Now, driven by Donovan's passion, the Gators are two games from
the Final Four, a place they haven't come close to since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Florida began this season with four freshmen in the starting
lineup. Two, a pair of former McDonald's prep All-Americans, will
start Thursday in an NCAA West Region semifinal game against
Gonzaga at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Coach Donovan is the best coach in America,'' freshman
guard Teddy Dupay said. ``He constantly challenges us. He doesn't
see limits in people. He believes we can get so much more out of
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   That belief complements the Gators' ability to hit three-point
shots _ they were among the top five three-point shooting teams in
the nation _ press, play hard defense and run an up-tempo system
that Donovan learned from Pitino.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the fact that Billy made himself a good basketball
coach,'' said Florida Athletic Director Jeremy Foley, who hired
Donovan in 1996. ``I thought his work ethic was second to none. Now
that I've seen it firsthand, it is second to none.''
</P>
<P>
   Donovan, 33, still has a thick Long Island accent and talks so
fast that it is hard to keep up with all the names he mentions,
guys who took the challenge and made themselves better players
since he came to Florida two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan was slow, short and chunky growing up in Long Island,
but he had an insatiable desire to be a basketball player.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Bill Donovan, who played at Boston College in the
early '60s, told him the only way he would make it would be to
outwork the next guy. He had to take more shots, run more gassers,
play more games.
</P>
<P>
   One time in college, feeling guilty for taking a day off, he
couldn't sleep. He cut the padlock off his old high school's gym
doors at 1 a.m. and played until 4 in the morning. When he left, he
put a new lock on the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did a lot of things out of fear,'' Donovan said. ``I didn't
want to look back on my career and realize I hadn't done enough.''
</P>
<P>
   After his sophomore year at Providence, after Pitino was hired
as head coach, Donovan was told that he would never play for Pitino
if he didn't lose weight. He went from bench warmer his junior year
to a fearless point guard and an honorable mention All-American his
senior year in '86-87, when he averaged 20 points and was the
outstanding player of the Southeast Region in the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Known as Billy the Kid, he still looks as if he could put on a
college uniform and knock down the threes.
</P>
<P>
   Clean shaven, his black hair slicked back, he also looks as if
he could be working on Wall Street, which he did after an NBA
career that lasted 44 games in '88 in a mop-up role for Pitino with
the New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   He was cut by the Knicks, lasted five weeks during the '88
preseason with the Utah Jazz and, after a short CBA stint, settled
in behind a desk on Wall Street, trying to convince people to give
him their money to invest. All the while, he missed basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really hard being away from it,'' he said. ``I couldn't
get basketball out of my blood. That's always been my life. That's
my passion.''
</P>
<P>
   He jumped at Pitino's offer to help him at Kentucky in '89. In
1994, Donovan became the youngest head coach in the nation when he
was hired by Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   In his first season, Marshall won 18 games and captured the
North Division championship in the Southern Conference. Marshall
won 17 games the next season, and Florida came after Donovan when
Lon Kruger left to become the coach at Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan said Pitino advised him not to take the Florida job.
That became just another challenge for Donovan, who after 13-17 and
14-15 seasons has the Gators at 22-8.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Pitino) said, `Listen, they're not even close to getting to
the NCAA Tournament, let alone the Final Four,' '' Donovan said.
``He said people there probably think it's a year away, and the
expectations would be enormous.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, Donovan received a telegram in Seattle from
Pitino wishing him luck in the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   A nonstop recruiter, Donovan hooked recruits that many people
didn't believe he could get. Freshmen Mike Miller, a forward, and
Dupay came in with McDonald's All-America credentials. They lead
the team with scoring averages of 12.3 and 11.1 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   Another freshman, Udonis Haslem, is the third-leading scorer at
10.7 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   Another McDonald's All-American, 6-foot-2 point guard Brett
Nelson out of West Virginia, arrives in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Many thought the Gators would be hard-pressed to get into the
tournament this year, especially without star point guard Jason
Williams, who transfered from Marshall to be with Donovan, only to
be kicked off the team last season for failing a drug test.
Williams now starts for the Sacramento Kings.
</P>
<P>
   But Donovan's energy has rubbed off, and the Gators are having a
blast playing Billyball, running and shooting threes, playing hard
defense and winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when I first took the job, a lot of people said it
would take five years to rebuild and get us in position to really
compete and win,'' Donovan said. ``We've been fortunate that the
younger guys have really stepped up and the guys returning have all
improved.''
</P>
<P>
   A little work. That's all it takes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
