r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-BELLE-GOMEZ-AZR &LR;      03-17 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-BELLE-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELLE MAY BE AN ENIGMA, BUT ONE WITH STAR POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. - Like it or not, we cannot take our eyes
off Albert Belle. We can't help ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball fans have always been fascinated with the game's power
men. Whether it be Babe Ruth, Mark McGwire or even Jose Canseco,
there's just something about a human being who can pick up a wooden
stick and swat a baseball more than 400 feet that captivates us.
</P>
<P>
   We want to find out what separates these giants of the game from
the rest of the minions who plod along making their sensational
defensive plays or spraying their singles.
</P>
<P>
   So it should not come as any great surprise to Belle that we are
so intrigued with wanting to know what makes him tick.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, of course, is that the Baltimore Orioles' new right
fielder isn't the least bit interested in letting anyone inside his
complicated and highly intelligent mind.
</P>
<P>
   Every spring Belle says this year will be different, that he
will be more accessible and friendly toward all. Every season, the
``interview season,'' as he puts it, ends abruptly. Usually still
during the spring.
</P>
<P>
   So we are left to look in from the outside, separated by this
impenetrable wall that Belle has constructed around his persona. We
poke and prod this player who has made himself an enigma with nary
an acknowledgement that we exist. This goes for fans as well as
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Belle was sailing along this spring, chatting occasionally with
reporters, until he had one of his incidents last week. He was
frustrated after an 0-for-3 afternoon and stormed into the
clubhouse, sending equipment flying.
</P>
<P>
   After the incident was widely reported, Belle cut off all
interviews _ he said for the season. Before Tuesday's Grapefruit
League game between the Orioles and St. Louis, Belle politely
(honest) declined to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Using the Belle scale, this particular event was tame. Unlike
several of his other episodes, it came in front of no fans. There
was no chasing down of delinquent pranksters in his vehicle or
throwing a baseball at a fan's chest. There wasn't even a verbal
attack of a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   This was simply Belle being Belle. In turn, he was offering a
glimpse of his inner workings _ which by no means should be
interpreted as a defense for his actions.
</P>
<P>
   Belle is as complex a personality as there is in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   He routinely does the`` New York Times'' crossword puzzle. He
was an above-average accounting major (can anyone imagine him
sitting behind a desk with a calculator?) at Louisiana State
University. It's just that Belle approaches the game far
differently than anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to visualize everything,'' Belle told ``The Arizona
Republic'' during a rare interview last spring. ``The only reason I
will ever change is because I want to, not for the public relations
department, or my family or the press. I don't want to give up free
time.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways we are living in the Albert Belle era. It can be
argued that he is the most feared hitter playing today. Since 1991,
Belle has more home runs, RBIs, doubles, extra-base hits and total
bases than anyone. That includes Barry Bonds, Ken Griffey and Juan
Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface it may appear that Belle has nothing more than a
savage approach to hitting. He stands in the batter's box staring
down the opposing pitcher with unwavering and fierce eyes. It's as
if he's telling the pitcher of the impending pain he is about to
apply to the baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, we know so little about Belle other than he has produced
some of the most astonishing numbers ever generated, like his 103
extra-base hits in 1995, more than any player in the last 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal isn't to win any popularity contest,'' Belle said. ``I
know I'm not the most popular player. Some people have it in for
me, and that's just the way it is. I'm not a player who is in it
for the money or fame and fortune. I just want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   That is probably at the crux of Belle's flare-ups. His intense
competitive nature usually takes over his frame of mind. Some 30
years from now, we will be watching highlights of Belle's career
and reminding our grandchildren of the fury with which Belle
played.
</P>
<P>
   The future will probably be kind to Belle, whose career may very
well take him to Cooperstown. If he doesn't want to stop for the
endorsements and flowery tributes, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   One thing cannot be taken away: Belle remains the most lethal
bat and the least known person in the game. And that's the way he
wants it. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at 602-444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
