<HEADLINE>
ASU FRESHMAN LEADING WAY INTO NCAA FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Out of an Arizona State wrestling recruiting
class ranked fourth nationally, only Eric Larkin was immediately
ready for the big time.
</P>
<P>
   Hector Torres (heavyweight) and Christian Luciano (174 pounds)
are redshirting at weights where ASU needed help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure they couldn't have been ready this year, but it's
just a risk, especially at heavyweight,'' Coach Lee Roy Smith said.
``You can give someone a complex and ruin them for the rest of
their career.''
</P>
<P>
   Larkin, though, was different.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 junior national champion in freestyle and two-year
Greco-Roman champ brought not only credentials that couldn't wait
but a growing body bursting to get out of the 133-pound division.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the last time we'll see him there in all
probability,'' Smith said. ``He could grow into 149 before it's all
said and done. We knew we had one true freshman capable of being an
All-America and that the team needed him at that weight class.''
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the struggle to maintain his weight, especially
given a rib injury that took him out for almost a month, Larkin has
been brilliant. He goes to the NCAA Championships, Thursday through
Saturday at Penn State, as the Sun Devils' top-ranked qualifier
(No. 3) and with their best record (26-3).
</P>
<P>
   Smith thinks all six of his wrestlers could place in the top
eight to make All-America and that the Sun Devils, third in the
Pac-10, have a chance to be back in the top 10 for the first time
since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The hopes for an individual champion, the eighth in school
history, rest with Larkin and Casey Strand (184 pounds).
</P>
<P>
   Strand (33-5), a two-time All-America off fifth- and sixth-place
finishes at 167, was upset by Oregon's Doug Lee, 7-5, at the Pac-10
Championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``He let the match get away from him,'' Smith said. ``It
released some concerns that he has and knows he can't go to the
mats with. He's really put most of his marbles into putting
together the best tournament of his career. That's his mindset, and
the way you would want it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other ASU qualifiers are Matt Azevedo (26-12) at 125, Mark
Perryman (20-6) at 141, Quinn Foster (23-10) at 149 and Steve
Blackford (26-12) at 165.
</P>
<P>
   Of those, the biggest surprise is Perryman, a transfer from Cal
Poly-San Luis Obispo, who made nationals in 1997 at 134. He has won
13 of his last 15 matches, including a Pac-10 title run, and is
ranked 11th in what Smith said is perhaps the deepest weight class.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel real confident that no matter who he's competing
against and no matter how many matches he has to confront good
people, he will be able to perform up to his ability each and every
match,'' Smith said. ``He's as strong conditioningwise as anybody
we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Larkin's only losses are to Iowa State's second-ranked Cody
Sanderson, 6-2, and, 7-5, including riding time, and a medical
forfeit Dec. 29 at the Midlands Invitational when the rib injury
occured.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Sanderson) pretty much controlled the first match and kept
pressure on me,'' said Larkin, out of Tucson Sunnyside High School.
``I felt I could have beat him the second time.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably no one will stand atop the podium at 133 without going
through Oklahoma State senior Eric Guerrero (26-0), a two-time
national champion at 126. He and Larkin missed each other in a Jan.
10 dual in Tempe because of the Larkin's injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Larkin) has everything to gain,'' Smith said. ``He can
afford to go out and put all the cards on the table because he's
got plenty more chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero is critical to No. 1 Oklahoma State's hopes of holding
off No. 2 Minnesota to win a 31st NCAA title, the most of any team
in any sport.
</P>
<P>
   No. 5 Oklahoma knocked off the Cowboys, coached by Lee Roy
Smith's brother John, to win the Big 12 Championships. Iowa and
Minnesota finished ahead of Oklahoma State at the 1998 nationals. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
