<HEADLINE>
SHANAHAN SAYS DRAFTING QBS HIGH IS RISKY BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - This won't be good news for NFL coaches planning to
take a quarterback in the top 15 picks in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mike Shanahan, coach of the past two Super Bowl champions in
Denver, said quarterback usually is the ``worst evaluated''
position in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guy will take somebody in the first round, and you rank
him as a fifth-round player,'' Shanahan said Tuesday during the
coaches breakfast at the NFL meetings at the Arizona Biltmore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another guy you have ranked in the fourth round is taken as
one of the top 10 picks.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan uses Kansas City Chiefs starter  &UR; Elvis Grbac, a
seventh-round pick of the San Francisco 49ers, as an example of
quarterbacks who were poorly evaluated in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   In this year's draft,  &UR; Tim Couch of Tennessee is expected to be
the first pick.  &UR; Akili Smith of Oregon,  &UR; Donovan McNabb of Syracuse
and  &UR; Daunte Culpepper of Central Florida also are expected to be
taken early.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan said his philosophy is to take a quarterback every
other year regardless of how deep the team is at the position.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you see a quarterback in the third, fourth or fifth that
you feel is a second-round draft choice, why not take him?''
Shanahan said.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan, who has made few mistakes evaluating talent with the
Broncos, said he had  &UR; Jake Plummer rated higher than the 11th pick
in the second round, which is where the Cardinals took him two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had Jake a first-round draft choice,'' Shanahan said. ``He's
not big or strong or fast, but Jake could always make plays.'' &QL; 
Unhappy camper &QL; 
Green Bay General Manager  &UR; Ron Wolf, whose team received four
compensatory picks in the draft, is upset the picks weren't higher.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers received a third-round pick, two fourths and a
sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to take away Pro Bowl players, how are we
supposed to replace those with fours?'' said Wolf, who lost
cornerback  &UR; Doug Evans, defensive lineman  &UR; Gabe Wilkins, punter
 &UR; Craig Hentrich, safety  &UR; Eugene
 &UR; Robinson, offensive guard  &UR; Aaron Taylor and running back  &UR; Edgar
Bennett in free agency a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The object is to replace them with threes. Obviously, the
object would be to replace them with ones or twos, but they (the
league) deem that not necessary. Plus, I don't think Einstein could
arrive at how they come to these (decisions).'' &QL; 
Invitation issued &QL; 
Seattle Coach  &UR; Mike Holmgren said the Cardinals asked about
scrimmaging with the Seahawks before their Aug. 28 preseason game
in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The teams would work out in Cheney, Wash., but Holmgren said he
likely will turn down the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buffalo also asked, but this being our first year in this
system, I don't think we're going to work with anybody,'' Holmgren
said. ``I want to do it with the Cardinals in the future.''
Tennessee Coach  &UR; Jeff Fisher, whose team plays a preseason game at
Sun Devil Stadium the weekend of Aug. 21, said he would be
interested in practicing with the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   The teams could work out in Flagstaff before the Cardinals break
training camp on Aug. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping spree &QL; 
 &UR; Steve Zucker, the agent for free agent offensive tackle  &UR; Richmond
Webb, has been shopping his client at the meetings and asked the
Cardinals on Tuesday whether they were interested.
</P>
<P>
   Zucker was told the interest was minimal.
</P>
<P>
   Webb, who has spent his entire career with the Miami Dolphins,
is their franchise player. So the Dolphins can match any offer for
him.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals lost starting offensive tackle  &UR; Lomas Brown to
free agency but have said they plan to use a high pick in next
month's draft on an offensive tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Short shots &QL; 
Cleveland Browns President  &UR; Carmen Policy congratulated Cardinals
owner  &UR; Bill &UR; Bidwill on the NFL's resolution Monday that would give
the Valley a Super Bowl in 2004, 2005 or 2006 if the Rio Salado
Crossing stadium is built. ``I think that might be the first thing
ever done unanimously in this league,'' Policy said.
</P>
<P>
   The Carolina Panthers have inquired about free agent wide
receiver  &UR; Eric Metcalf, who played for the Cardinals last season.
</P>
<P>
   Former Cardinals offensive lineman  &UR; Ernest Dye, a 1994
first-round draft pick who was out of football last year, worked
out for the Pittsburgh Steelers on Tuesday in Phoenix. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
