<HEADLINE>
PLUMMER'S PRESENCE EARNS MONDAY NIGHT GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - For the first time since 1995, the Cardinals will have
a Monday night game next season, NFL sources said Tuesday at the
league meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals won't know their opponent and whether the game
will be at home or on the road until the schedule is released in
the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks real good for them,'' the source said. ``Something
could still happen that would change things, but I really like
their chances. They were better than a .500 team last year and have
(quarterback) Jake Plummer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, 9-7 last season, had their first winning season
in Arizona and won at Dallas in the NFC playoffs, their first
playoff victory in 51 years.
</P>
<P>
   They haven't played on Monday night since former Coach Buddy
Ryan's last game, a 37-13 loss to Dallas on Christmas night in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Their only other Monday night game since moving to Arizona in
1988 was a loss that first season to Dallas in the home opener.
</P>
<P>
   It was speculated earlier that if the Cardinals played on a
Monday night next season, they would meet the San Francisco 49ers
or the Buffalo Bills.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cardinals played the 49ers, the game could be billed as
Plummer, who has been compared to a young Joe Montana, against
Montana's old team.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer would be matched against veteran scrambling quarterback
Doug Flutie against the Bills.
</P>
<P>
   Both games are scheduled for Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer's agent, Leigh Steinberg, said he hadn't been told that
the Cardinals would play on a Monday night, but he said it would be
a big step for the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of credibility and building a national reputation,
nothing other than a Super Bowl has more value than ``Monday Night
Football'','' Steinberg said. ``The audience is not the narrow
genre of the hard-core football fan. It extends beyond that to a
real enormous prime-time audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reputations are made, images are established, on ``Monday
Night Football.'' If `The Refrigerator' (William Perry) scores a
touchdown on a regularly scheduled game on local TV, he doesn't
become `The Refrigerator.' '' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 0024EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
