r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-REDWINGS-     03-17 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-REDWINGS-ADV-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES REV UP FOR DEFENDING CHAMPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the heels of a disappointing 5-5 tie against the Carolina
Hurricanes when the Coyotes regurgitated a three-goal lead in the
game's final 12 minutes, most coaches would be worried about their
team's mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   But Coyotes Coach Jim Schoenfeld has no such concerns tonight as
the Coyotes test the Detroit Red Wings, winners of two consecutive
Stanley Cup titles, at Joe Louis Arena.
</P>
<P>
   And, surprisingly, he said avenging an embarrassing 7-2 loss to
the Red Wings 12 days ago in Phoenix isn't a major factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Detroit, because of who they are, provides a situation where
you are naturally revved up for the game,'' Schoenfeld said. ``You
go into games with them with a sense of, `If we don't play our
best, we're going to get blown out of here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a high-energy game, an emotional game and when you
have all these elements, the expectations are high. When you go
into the Joe (arena) you know anything less than your best won't
get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, the Coyotes already are going into the ``Joe''
with less than their best.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes are without three of their top six defensemen
(Gerald Diduck, Jyrki Lumme and J.J. Daigneault) and three solid
forechecking forwards (Juha Ylonen, Brad Isbister and Dallas
Drake). Drake suffered a strained shoulder against Carolina and
will be lost for seven to 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a team in the NHL that will exploit so many missing
parts, and the weariness it creates, it's Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have great depth and balanced scoring on four lines,''
said Schoenfeld, who added Carolina provided the same challenge
(with lesser talent) and basically wore the Coyotes down in the
final period.
</P>
<P>
   All that was needed was a quick review of the game statistics to
see as much. Defenseman Keith Carney logged 28 minutes and 28
seconds. Teppo Numminen, who's playing but is still suffering pain
and stiffness from a fractured foot, logged 27:06, and Deron Quint
and Oleg Tverdovsky each played more than 23 minutes as Schoenfeld
chose to spot play Jamie Huscroft and Brad Tiley to provide brief
relief.
</P>
<P>
   In their last meeting in Phoenix, Red Wings left wing Brendan
Shanahan celebrated three times as he registered a hat trick.
</P>
<P>
   Those were scenes the Coyotes' Numminen doesn't want to see
repeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see someone celebrating like that, you know it has
been a long night,'' Numminen said. ``You find yourself saying, `Do
it somewhere else, please, but not here.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But they have so much talent and so many good skaters that if
you don't play your best game and shut them down in the neutral
zone, they will really take it to you. It's not just the one line
they have. They have four good lines, which makes it important we
play good defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Numminen, who owns the second longest active regular-season
consecutive game streak in the NHL with 282, said maintaining the
streak has not been a factor in playing through the foot injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``The streak doesn't matter, really,'' he said. ``Actually, I've
had no choice but to play because we have so many people out. Had
the situation been different, maybe I would have made a different
choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when Jyrki went down it left us without a big offensive
threat on defense, so I had to play. It gets sore and stiff, but I
try not to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Bobby Smith took a load off the Coyotes'
shoulder by ending speculation before Monday's game that
Schoenfeld's job was in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody _ players and coaches _ is used to it at this time
of year,'' forward Mike Sullivan said. ``The demand is for
everybody to win games right now, and if you don't, everyone's job
is at stake. It's part of the territory, and you cope and handle it
the best you can.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Shoney has done nothing to lose his job. It's the 20 guys
in this room who lace up their skates and ultimately decide the
team's fate. Every game is important now, but it's most important
we get back to playing to our potential. If we do that, the wins
and losses will take care of themselves.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
