<SLUG> BC-RAC-TRAINERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETTLEMENT REACHED WITH TRAINERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The California Horse Racing Board and the state Attorney
General's office reached a settlement Tuesday with three trainers
who had horses test positive for the steroid clenbuterol.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the trainers was fined $1,500 by the board. Four related
cases remain unsettled.
</P>
<P>
   Trainers Vladmir Cerin, Peter Eurton and Declan Jackson agreed
to the sanction through their attorney Robert Forgnone. Deputy
Attorney General Dana Cartozian, represented the CHRB, said
spokesman Mike Marten.
</P>
<P>
   The accusations were filed against Cerin, Eurton and Jackson
last September after clenbuterol, a steroid that clears breathing
passages in short-of-breath horses, was detected in urine samples.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's cases were settled at Forgnone's request.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have six cases in this,'' Forgnone said. ``Now we're working
on the other three.''
</P>
<P>
   Testing positive were the Cerin-trained Ruhlman's Opus and
Jackson's Speedball, on June 10, 1998; and Eurton's The Smokester,
a June 14 winner.
</P>
<P>
   All three have been disqualified by the CHRB, Forgnone said.
Their owners must return any prize monies they earned.
</P>
<P>
   Hearings for other trainers in the case are still scheduled,
Marten said. Paco Gonzales will go before the court May 24. Darrell
Vienna and Bruce Headley will be heard June 7. Ted West's case is
scheduled to be heard June 14, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Forgnone also represents Vienna, Headley and West.
</P>
<P>
   Among the horses testing positive was Free House, currently the
NTRA's No.1 ranked thoroughbred.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 0028EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
