<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THUMB INJURY SETS BACK PROSPECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ The Diamondbacks thought they had used enough repellant
to not be affected by the injury bug, but they were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman  &UR; Junior Spivey, one of the organization's
promising young players, will be out for 8-10 weeks because of torn
ligaments in his left thumb.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old Spivey, who is expected to play at either
Triple-A Tucson or Double-A El Paso in 1999, suffered the injury
during a pre-game workout Monday at Tucson Electric Park. He is
scheduled to have surgery Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was diving after a ground ball and just landed wrong on my
glove hand,'' said Spivey, who is a member of the 40-man roster and
had two hits in seven at-bats this spring. ``I was feeling pretty
good about the way I was playing, but now I don't feel too good.
I'll just have to try to keep my spirits up.'' &QL; 
Johnson maintains pace &QL; 
Left-hander  &UR; Randy Johnson gave up a bunt single to the Chicago
White Sox's &UR; McKay Christensen to lead off the bottom of the first
Tuesday, but gave up no hits thereafter in four innings of work. He
walked one and struck out five.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight was two strikeouts of slugger  &UR; Frank Thomas, the
first time on a breaking ball and the second time on an inside
fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is pleased with the way his slider is developing,
particularly at this point in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fastball is obviously my strength, but you can't go out
there and throw 125 fastballs,'' Johnson said. ``You have to be
able to have another pitch to set that up, and mine is the breaking
ball. I thought I threw that pitch pretty well today. It seems to
be coming around.''
</P>
<P>
   He threw 58 pitches Tuesday and topped out at 98 mph. Pitching
coach  &UR; Mark
 &UR; Connor said Johnson likely will throw 75 pitches in his next start
Sunday, followed by about 90 and 100-105 in his last two starts,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to get at least seven or eight innings in my last
start (March 31),'' Johnson said. ``The stronger your body gets,
the more confident you become.''
</P>
<P>
   Another goal for Johnson is to get some more at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've only had one this spring, and that was a walk (by the
Chicago Cubs'
 &UR; Jon Lieber),'' Johnson said. ``I need to get some more swings.''
</P>
<P>
   He told Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter that before Tuesday's game, and
Showalter muttered under his breath, ``Don't worry about it, big
guy. Just throw the ball over the plate.'' &QL; 
Short stops &QL; 
Outfielders  &UR; Jason Conti and  &UR; Rob Ryan were optioned to Triple-A
Tucson. More moves could be coming over the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder  &UR; Bernard Gilkey, out since March 7 with a strained
left calf, is expected to return to action Thursday against Oakland
at Tucson Electric Park.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter was pleased with the pitching effort of left-hander
 &UR; Troy Brohawn, who made his first start of the spring and gave up
one run on three hits, walked one and struck out two against
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing action in the outfield for the White Sox in the
split-squad game was  &UR; Scott Lydy, a graduate of Mesa Mountain View
High School who began his career in the Oakland organization. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
