r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-CARLSON-AZ     03-17 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-CARLSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARLSON MAKES PITCH FOR D-BACKS JOB  
 RIGHT-HANDER THROWING WELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ The race for spots in the Diamondbacks' middle-relief
corps continues to be wide-open, and right-hander Dan Carlson is
right in the middle of it.
</P>
<P>
   If Carlson's name rings a bell, it should. He pitched for the
San Francisco Giants' Triple-A affiliate in Phoenix for parts of
five seasons, winning 13 on three occasions, before going to Tampa
Bay in the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   He struggled in 10 games with the Devil Rays and again at
Triple-A Durham before hooking on with Arizona as a minor-league
free agent and non-roster invitee to the spring camp.
</P>
<P>
   The 29-year-old Carlson has appeared in four games for the
Diamondbacks this spring and given up three hits in 5 innings.
</P>
<P>
   He is scheduled to pitch two more innings today against the
Chicago Cubs at HoHoKam Park in Mesa, following right-hander Todd
Stottlemyre and right-hander Frank Castillo (a former Cub) and
preceding right-hander Vladimir Nunez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the Diamondbacks had scouted me for the expansion
draft, so I was surprised when Tampa took me instead,'' said
Carlson, who was in Australia participating in Christian baseball
clinics when he received the news in November of 1997. ``Things
didn't work out in Tampa, so coming here was my No. 1 goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come into a camp as a non-roster guy, you're
sometimes lucky if you get to throw once in a `B' game. But I've
already pitched five innings in four games, and I can honestly say
that they've really given me a chance. I think I've pitched well so
far, but I have to continue to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is competition, but for me, it's competition against the
hitter. You have to worry about getting him out. You can't play GM
(general manager) and worry about what the other pitchers are
doing''.
</P>
<P>
   Carlson's success this spring has come with his slider and the
refinement of his sinker pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sinker, especially,'' Carlson said. ``I'm not the type of
guy who has a 95 mph heater. I have success by keeping ahead in the
count and using my location.''
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks pitching coach Mark Connor said Carlson ``is right
there'' in the battle for a middle-relief spot.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Buck Showalter said he ``has opened some eyes. He's been
impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Carlson, Diamondbacks third baseman Matt Williams grew up
in the San Francisco organization. Though Williams is a bit older
(33), the two crossed paths on many occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a guy that you wouldn't know was there, not flashy, just
the type of guy who goes out and gives it everything he has,''
Williams said. ``He has good stuff. A good slider and a fastball
that moves in pretty good on the right-handed hitters. He's the
type of guy you want to root for to make the club.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlson, who was a third baseman early in his career at Mt. Hood
(Ore.) Junior College and then became a pitcher, was a starter
during most of his minor-league career. When he was called up to
the majors, he was used in relief. He knows that's where he has the
best chance to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different mentality, to be sure,'' he said. ``I've sat
a couple times for anywhere from eight to 13 days before getting up
to throw. But you have to be ready all the time. You have to
prepare the same way every day.''
</P>
<P>
   While he thinks he would be a good fit on what he calls a
quality staff, he also knows he could end up playing here for the
Triple-A Sidewinders this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't be disappointed, not at all,'' he said. ``If I come
down here and pitch well, I could get called back up at some
point.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
