<SLUG> BC-BBO-CACTUS-ATTENDANCE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBS LEAD SURGE IN CACTUS CROWDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LES POLK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Cactus League attendance is up 19 percent this year
over 1998, spurred by Sammy Sosa fever, better weather and the
major leagues coming off a banner season.
</P>
<P>
   Through Monday's games, Sosa's team, the Chicago Cubs, who play
in Mesa, were leading the major leagues in spring attendance,
averaging 11,326 per game, a 34 percent increase over last year.
The Cubs are expecting more than 12,000 fans at today's game in
Mesa against the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs have taken the major league spring attendance lead away
from the New York Yankees, who are averaging 10,256 this season and
led the majors last year.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Cactus League has four of the top five teams in
spring attendance, according to Major League Baseball figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's starting off really well,'' said Robert Brinton, who
heads the Mesa Convention and Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Brinton said he thinks the Cubs will break 1997's season
attendance mark of 157,000. And in one less home game, 15 vs. 16.
</P>
<P>
   The other four teams in the Cactus League who are in baseball's
top five this spring include the San Francisco Giants (averaging
8,121, up 33 percent), Seattle Mariners (8,022, up 32 percent) and
the Diamondbacks (7,845, up 20 percent).
</P>
<P>
   The only team down in average attendance is the Milwaukee
Brewers. However, team officials said earlier this month that
advance sales for the month of March were ahead of last year and
that they expect to finish ahead of last year's figures. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
