</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-BUCKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS LIKE FANS' BOOS IN ROUTING BUCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ The Suns heard the booing again Tuesday night. And
this time they loved every bit of it. For a change, it wasn't aimed
at them.
</P>
<P>
   With the Suns playing some of their best basketball of the
season, leading by 32 points in the first half on the road, and en
route to a 110-92 drubbing of the Milwaukee Bucks, the Bradley
Center fans gave their team an earful.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what that feels like,'' Suns guard Jason Kidd said.
</P>
<P>
   They also know what it feels like to win on the road. The
victory, which came so easily Kidd didn't need a triple double or
even to play in the fourth quarter, was the seventh in 10 road
games this season for the Suns. They're just 5-7 on their
homecourt.
</P>
<P>
   It's a quirk that's hard to figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fans must be (ticked) off,'' said forward Tom Gugliotta,
who scored 19 points and took down seven rebounds in the victory.
``I think we're just more alert at the beginning of the game on the
road. It's a natural tendency on someone else's court.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know you can't afford to get into a hole. On our court, we
haven't had that same approach. Hopefully, we can learn from this
and understand what it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns, who won their last home game against Houston, got off
to a good start on a four-game road trip that continues tonight in
Charlotte. And they did it with an impressive all-around
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix shot 53.5 percent, moved the ball offensively as well as
the Suns have all season, pounded the Bucks on the backboards,
43-27, and, beat them in transition. Clifford Robinson led six Suns
who scored in double figures with 20 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they showed signs of three-game fatigue,'' Suns Coach
Danny Ainge said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Milwaukee's third game in three nights, but the Bucks
also are a team in transition. The Bucks had won six straight games
and had a record of 12-5 before they worked two trades to move
disgruntled point guard Terrell Brandon and obtain point guard Sam
Cassell from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, Cassell is out for at least 10 days because of a
bone chip discovered in his ankle. And since the deal, the Bucks
have lost four in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like the first exhibition game of the season, we got to look
at a lot of people and play a lot of people,'' Bucks Coach George
Karl said. ``We just had a gone game.''
</P>
<P>
   Forward Glenn Robinson had another way of putting it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got our (butts) kicked,'' he said. ``We have to stop
the bleeding, keep our heads up and play like we did six or seven
games ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns looked like a whole new team, too. A better one.
</P>
<P>
   They were advertised as a club loaded with unselfish, skilled
passers at every position. But the blowout of the Bucks provided
the first real glimpse of that potential.
</P>
<P>
   It was particularly evident in the first half when the Suns ran,
shared th e ball, moved in their halfcourt sets and made extra
passes to find an open shooter.
</P>
<P>
   The result was 65-percent shooting in the first quarter and a
33-15 Phoenix lead. The Suns had to know they were in good shape
with that kind of output when Kidd had only one first-quarter
assist. But eight other players had at least one as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got guys who can pass and guys who are comfortable at
different positions,'' Gugliotta said. ``That should be a huge
asset. Guys were moving the ball, looking for each other, and
everything was flowing.''
</P>
<P>
   The onslaught continued in the second quarter as the Suns built
their lead to as much as 32. They lost interest during a few
stretches in the second half, but coasted down the stretch with
rookies Toby Bailey, Pat Garrity and Gerald Brown all in the game
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at our best when everyone touches the ball and makes the
extra pass,'' Kidd said. ``In the first quarter, everybody had
their hands on the ball. Everybody made the extra passes. It was a
great way to open the road trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Ainge agreed the ball movement was critical, but the Suns were
moving, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to move the ball, but if the bodies are
standing still it doesn't make any difference if you make the extra
pass,'' Ainge said. ``When they double-down (defensively), we were
getting good passing and slashing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns were equally effective in the open court and, with Kidd
running the break, they took the ball to the basket against a
Milwaukee lineup that's short on shotblockers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running was their biggest asset,'' Milwaukee guard Ray Allen
said. ``They beat us back, got fouled and dictated the course of
the game.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
