<SLUG> BC-NY-TIMES-LANDMARK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER TIMES BUILDING IS NAMED A LANDMARK 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A craggy, Romanesque tower in lower Manhattan where
all the news became fit to print was designated a New York City
landmark on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-story building at 41 Park Row was the home of The New
York Times until 1904, when the newspaper moved to Times Square. It
has been owned since 1951 by Pace University, which uses it for
classrooms and offices.
</P>
<P>
   Once part of a powerful trio towering over City Hall Park _ the
nearby World Building and Tribune Building were demolished long ago
_ 41 Park Row was designed by George B. Post and completed in 1889.
It resembles an elongated Roman aqueduct, with row upon row of
vigorous arches carved from Maine granite and Indiana limestone.
</P>
<P>
   ``So beautiful that it charms the naive and the refined, the
ignorant and the most learned in art; the Times Building is The New
York Times expressed in stone,'' Moses King declared in his 1893
guide book to New York City.
</P>
<P>
   It was at 41 Park Row that Adolph S. Ochs arrived from
Chattanooga in 1896, finding an anemic publication with a
circulation of 9,000. After he bought The Times, Ochs added the
motto, ``All the News That's Fit to Print,'' first to the editorial
page, then to the front page, where it remains.
</P>
<P>
   Even before The Times moved uptown, the architect Robert
Maynicke planned alterations that left 41 Park Row much as one sees
it today. The mansard roof was removed and three floors were added.
The entrance lost the inscription ``Times Bvilding'' but kept an
ornamental clock with Roman numerals and Gothic hands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 0039EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
