r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TERRORIST-BUST-LADN     03-17 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERRORIST-BUST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. VISA RING LINKED TO TERRORISTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PETER HARTLAUB AND GREG GITTRICH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ An immigration fraud ring suspected of trying to
help members of Iran's most notorious terrorist group enter the
United States was shut down Tuesday with 29 arrests, authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said Bahram Tabatabai of Sherman Oaks ran the ring
out of a Ventura Boulevard office building with 14 other people,
charging hundreds of immigrants up to $12,000 for fake visa and
asylum applications. Court documents say they forged documents
including birth certificates and even newspaper articles to help
immigrants who wouldn't typically be let into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   According to prosecutors, some of those who applied for
political asylum under the scheme were actually members of
Mujahedin-e Khalq, an Iranian terrorist organization suspected in
the takeover in 1979 of the U.S. embassy in Tehran and now closely
allied with Saddam Hussein in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Alejandro Mayorkas declined to say whether many of
the group's members entered the country or how many were involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have taken a step toward preventing people identified as
terrorists from coming into this country,'' Mayorkas said. ``The
evidence suggests hundreds of applications were processed
throughout the past year.''
</P>
<P>
   Tabatabai and 14 others _ many of whom lived in L.A.'s San
Fernando Valley _ were arrested without incident Tuesday and
charged with conspiracy, submitting false statements to the
Immigration and Naturalization Service and trafficking in
fraudulent identity documents.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen others were arrested Tuesday by INS officials on
suspicion of entering the country illegally with the help of the
fraud ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I emphasize that they have not been charged with a terrorist
act,'' said FBI Assistant Director Timothy McNally. He said
attempts to help known terrorists ``draws big questions as to what
their motivations are.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the defendants could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The terrorist group is considered the Iranian government's
primary opposition and has waged a series of terrorist attacks on
the country's Islamic leaders and their allies for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Now based in Iraq and working closely with Saddam Hussein, the
group is believed to be a key player in the takeover of the United
States embassy in 1979, according to University of Southern
California professor Richard Dekmejian, an expert on Middle Eastern
politics and terrorist groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of its strength comes from Iraq. Saddam Hussein is its
major benefactor,'' Dekmejian said. ``They are spread out in
European capitals and have significant military forces in Iraq.
Every so often, they mount attacks across the Iranian border with
support from the Iraqi government.''
</P>
<P>
   The Iranian government has demanded repeatedly that the United
States crack down on the group, which prompted the State Department
in 1997 to begin listing the group as one of 30 international
terrorist organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Tabatabai is the head of International Management Network,
located in the 16600 block of Ventura Boulevard, according to court
papers. The company advertised in foreign newspapers, offering to
help immigrants in the Middle East and Europe obtain temporary and
permanent visas.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, FBI and INS agents meticulously searched Tabatabai's
Encino offices on Ventura Boulevard, his home in Sherman Oaks and
Encino-based Tehran International Weekly Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   According to employees at Worldwide Electronic Bankcard Corp.,
which is located across the hallway from Tabatabai's office, about
40 federal agents and police quietly entered the office around 8
a.m. Later in the day, several people unsuspectingly knocked on the
office door and were searched and detained by the agents, the
witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   Residents in the 14600 block of Morrison Street where Tabatabai
lives peeked out windows and gawked as federal agents packed boxes
into a white moving van.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I thought it involved stolen cars or auto parts
because he always had fancy cars coming in and out. I couldn't
believe it when I heard terrorists,'' said one resident. ``It's
scary and not a normal thing to see around here.''
</P>
<P>
   In October 1996, a confidential informant who worked out of the
business began cooperating with investigators. More information was
gathered by a second informant and an undercover police officer.
</P>
<P>
   Among those arrested was Shahbod Noori, editor of Tehran
International Weekly, who is accused of placing fake newspaper
advertisements and articles to promote the fraud.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, prosecutors allege, Noori's paper ran an
advertisement for an art exhibit that didn't exist, so
International Management customers could get temporary tourist
visas citing plans to attend the event.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the defendants forged college transcripts,
military records and bank records and would create new identities
for clients with U.S. arrest records or those who had been rejected
for asylum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to say that this immigration fraud ring was a little
more sophisticated than the usual,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney
Kenneth White.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 0054EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
