<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3270 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-SOSA-TEX     03-17 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SOSA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAY IT AGAIN, SAMMY: SOSA HAS NOTHING, EVERYTHING TO PROVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, Ariz. _ The co-savior of the national pastime is
dispensing one-liners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sammy, a moment of your time,'' the foghorn-voiced fan behind
the dugout bellows.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you, my neighbor?'' Sammy replies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sammy, who's the best player in the game right now?'' the
radio guy asks in the crowded, postgame news conference that's
become a daily ritual at the Chicago Cubs' spring-training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael Jordan,'' Sammy quips.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone laughs heartily.
</P>
<P>
   When you're Sammy Sosa, and you've engaged Mark McGwire in a
thrilling duel for the single-season home-run record, a duel
credited with resurrecting an entire sport, even your lame jokes
get the same kind of response as a Jerry Seinfeld zinger.
</P>
<P>
   But seriously, folks.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa is well aware of what he and McGwire did last year. McGwire
hit 70 homers and got the record. Sosa hit 66 homers, but also
batted .308, drove in 158 runs, and got the National League
most-valuable-player award.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of the home-run chase was brought home in dramatic
fashion when he was watching a tribute to Joe DiMaggio. The magical
summer of '98 was compared to the summer of '41, when DiMaggio hit
in 56 consecutive games and Ted Williams batted .406.
</P>
<P>
   ``That year, everybody paid a lot of attention to Joe
DiMaggio,'' Sosa said. ``The same thing happened last year with
Mark and I. Everybody was looking at the sports stations to see
what Sammy did, or what Mark did. We made a lot of people happy,
and baseball was forgiven a little bit. Now, everybody's excited,
and I hope we do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, that's the tricky part.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa enters the season with nothing to prove. He passed Roger
Maris' 37-year-old home run record by five. His RBI total was the
highest in the NL since 1928.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done everything a player could ask for,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he has everything to prove. He has raised the
bar so high that to return to pre-1998 levels, say the 36 homers
and 119 runs batted in of '97, might be seen as a disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs manager Jim Riggleman knows that 1998 was a season for the
ages and that Sosa isn't likely to duplicate it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looking for any particular numbers,'' Riggleman
said. ``It's such a game of statistics that I know the fans will
be, and the rotisserie leagues will be, so it will be an issue
externally. Internally, I don't think it will be. If you told me
Sammy will have an average Sammy Sosa year, I'd take it right now.
Whatever those numbers are, I'd take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Sosa's first full season with the Cubs in 1993, those
numbers are 39 homers and 110 RBI. Most players would take those
numbers, but most players aren't coming off a 66-homer, 158-RBI
season.
</P>
<P>
   With pitcher Kerry Wood, the 1998 rookie of the year, out for
the season, Sosa becomes even more valuable. It's hard to see the
Cubs getting back to the playoffs without Wood, even if Sosa has
another 66-homer season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll keep Sammy on the field, put a glass case around him,''
said Cubs reliever Rod Beck.
</P>
<P>
   But Riggleman wants to guard against Sosa pressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internally, we have subtly let Sammy know just go play,''
Riggleman said. ``Hopefully he'll have an injury-free year again,
and when you look up at the end of September it's going to have
been a real good year. His physical talent will take care of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   That talent is on display in spring training. Sosa's second
preseason homer was a mammoth shot that easily would have been all
the way out of Wrigley Field. He has five home runs, leaving him
tied with (you guessed it) McGwire for the spring lead.
</P>
<P>
   But also on display is a little extra weight around the thighs,
rear and waist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a few extra pounds,'' Sosa admitted.
</P>
<P>
   That can happen when you live large in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa joined President Clinton at the White House for the
lighting of the national Christmas tree. He sat with the first lady
at the state of the union address. He presented a bat to New York
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. He made appearances, went to banquets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixty-six is a lot of home runs,'' he said. ``A lot of people
wanted to shake my hand; a lot of people needed me to go and spend
some time with them. It was like a holiday to me. I was having
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he did find time to work out, and the extra weight seems
more firm than flabby.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spring training, almost all of the players come in
overweight,'' he said. ``For me it's not overnight. It's just a
little bit of muscle. I feel great. I feel physically and mentally
strong, and I can handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Riggleman says he isn't worried about Sosa's condition,
physically or mentally. He says he knew that despite all the
off-season distractions, Sosa would arrive in camp ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``His goal last year was to get us to the postseason, first
ahead of everything else,'' Riggleman said. ``I know he feels that
way this year. But he's also got some long-term goals that don't
allow you to relax too much. His long-term goals don't allow for
any down periods. He will always be pushing it.''
</P>
<P>
   The reminders of 1998 are everywhere, from the constant
attention of the fans, to the camera crew filming his every move in
and around the batting cage, to the constant references to ``last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sosa already is trying to forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody will remember 1998,'' he said. ``But I have to put
that away. They paid me for last year already. I have to come back
and do my job in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   He sees his job as taking the Cubs to the postseason again, but
beyond the first round this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that I've missed is going to a World Series,''
he said. ``That's my thinking right now. I'm going to hit a lot of
home runs; everybody knows that. But I want to make it to the World
Series.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Cubs to make it back to the playoffs, let alone the
World Series, Sosa is going to have to hit a lot of home runs and
drive in a lot of runs again.
</P>
<P>
   He has nothing to prove, and he has everything to prove.
</P>
<P>
   ``After it happened last year, I say to myself nothing is
impossible,'' Sosa said. ``I'm not saying it's going to happen
again, but I feel great. I believe in myself. I'm going to do
everything I can, go out there and do my job, and take the club to
the playoffs if I can.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
