<HEADLINE>
KNICKS DEFEAT CLIPPERS, 113-89
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By the fourth quarter on Tuesday night, with fans
emptying out of the stands at about the same rate the coaches were
emptying their benches, the Knicks showed in one glittering play
all that they could be.
</P>
<P>
   A steal, Chris Dudley throwing an unlikely over-the-shoulder
outlet pass, Chris Childs making an unselfish assist and Kurt
Thomas swooping to the basket for an uncontested dunk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the ball ripped through the basket, Thomas also shredded the
net, leaving it dangling. On the bench, Allan Houston and Larry
Johnson covered their faces with towels to suppress their laughter.
With the net hanging down in pieces, Madison Square Garden
resembled a forgotten playground. Perhaps making that fact more
evident was the opposition, the Los Angeles Clippers, a team that
would have a hard time getting next on any court in the city. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The basket, which came as part of an early burst in the fourth
quarter, helped put the Clippers out of their misery for the 20th
time in 21 games this season. The Knicks began the game with a 14-0
run and only had to wait for the 48 minutes to tick off the clock
before putting a 113-89 victory in the books, their most lopsided
triumph of the season.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It gave the Knicks three victories in three nights, making them
the fifth team in the National Basketball Association this season
to win on back-to-back-to-back nights. The Knicks never appeared
tired, though, raising the lead to as many as 32 points in the
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Latrell Sprewell enjoyed the easy run, scoring 31 points off the
bench, his high as a Knick, one night after scoring 28 in
Milwaukee. Houston added 24 points and Johnson chipped in 20 before
they became spectators in the opening minute of the fourth quarter,
the second straight game that the three topped the 20-point mark. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The victory had Knicks Coach Jeff Van Gundy, as close to giddy
as he might get, joking: ``We've played three excellent games in a
row. I wish we could play again tomorrow.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While he might get an argument from his players, who will get a
well-deserved and much-needed day off on Wednesday, the starters
could have begun their rest after the opening minutes as the Knicks
raced to a 19-2 lead. They never trailed as they topped the century
mark for the second consecutive night.
</P>
<P>
   The strain of three games in three nights took its toll on
Johnson, who an hour after the game remained on the trainer's table
receiving treatment, unavailable to the news media. A team
spokesman said he had not been injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great and I think everyone else feels the same,''
Sprewell said. ``We're on a roll right now. We want to come out and
play well, especially after a good road win. We feel good about
ourselves right now.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the lowly Clippers offered the opportunity for a letdown, the
Knicks avoided that by crushing the visitors' hopes almost as soon
as the opening tip was won. While the Knicks have denied that Van
Gundy's job was tenuous, he presumably recalled that he got the
position three years ago this month, two days after Don Nelson
ended his tenure in New York by losing at home to the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   With Los Angeles entering this game with a 1-19 mark, a home
loss could have erased any assurances that his position was safe.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy stressed the danger in a walk-through that the Knicks
conducted just two hours before the start of the game. He made
comparisons between the Nets and the Clippers and let his players
know that if they consider the Nets a dangerous opponent, then the
Clippers should be regarded that way, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight could have been a night where we let one slip away,''
Van Gundy said. ``Other than a little slip in the second quarter, I
thought we really took care of business.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the Clippers look like a playground grouping that never met
before the game, the Knicks looked like Princeton on a good night,
scoring the first 14 points and starting it with four consecutive
3-point field goals. The lead stretched to 19-2 over the first
seven minutes, with Johnson scoring 11 points in the run, before
the Clippers inched back in, closing the gap to 31-21 at the end of
the quarter.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers got as close as 6 in the second quarter, with
Maurice Taylor scoring almost at will against Marcus Camby. But the
Knicks opened it up again, this time thanks to the work of
Sprewell, who scored 18 points in the quarter. By halftime, the
lead was 59-42.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
