<HEADLINE>
OFF-SEASON INSTRUCTION BENEFITS ZAUN
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRADENTON, Fla. _ Catcher Gregg Zaun, who resides in Weston,
Fla., moved to Arlington in mid-January to become a pupil of
Rangers hitting instructor Rudy Jaramillo.
</P>
<P>
   Zaun sees a better hitter two months later.
</P>
<P>
   The switch-hitter strengthened his bid to become the Rangers'
backup catcher with Tuesday's performance in the Rangers' 10-5
victory against the Pittsburgh Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   Zaun went 3-for-4 with a solo home run and two run-scoring
singles to improve his batting average to .400 (6-for-15) this
spring, and he credits Jaramillo for enhancing his ability to
handle off-speed pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Three of Zaun's past four hits came on off-speed pitches. ``I've
never been able to stay back on them during my career before,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Zaun, who enters the season with a career batting average of
.234, received three simple-to-remember checkpoints. Jaramillo
suggested Zaun keep his hands back, plant his front foot earlier
while striding toward the pitcher and stay square to the baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes it as easy as you can make it,'' said Zaun, who once
considered himself a fastball-only hitter. ``I'm putting myself in
a position now to hit a lot of different pitches thrown in a lot of
different locations.''
</P>
<P>
   Zaun sought Jaramillo's help based on the success of Rangers
hitters in recent seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just couldn't ignore the fact that these guys rake,'' Zaun
said. ``There had to be something else to it. These guys are great
hitters, but someone helps them stay consistent.'' PIRATES HIGH ON
MORRIS
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Warren Morris, whom the Rangers traded with
right-hander Todd Van Poppel to Pittsburgh for right-hander Esteban
Loaiza in July, could be in the Pirates' Opening Day lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we were giving up a good player in Warren Morris,''
Rangers general manager Doug Melvin said earlier this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers acknowledge Morris will likely be a productive
major-league hitter,, but some in the organization expressed
concerns about his defense.
</P>
<P>
   Morris worked extensively with Bill Mazeroski for two weeks this
spring. The Pirates invited the eight-time Gold Glove recipient to
their camp as a special instructor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked good to me,'' Mazeroski said of Morris, who is
competing with Mike Benjamin to become the Pirates' second baseman.
``He's got pretty good actions around the bag, and he has a good
idea of what he is doing. He's a good kid who's willing to learn,
and I think he has a chance to be a good second baseman.'' BULLPEN
STRONG
</P>
<P>
   Danny Patterson threw only 18 pitches to record six outs
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the best I've seen Patty throw this spring,'' manager
Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson, who allowed only a walk, recorded one strikeout and
induced a ground-ball double play.
</P>
<P>
   Oates also used left-hander Mike Munoz for a late-inning
situational matchup with Brian Giles, a left-handed hitter. Munoz
retired Giles and departed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did what I wanted him to do in a normal game situation,''
Oates said. RANGERS 10, PIRATES 5
</P>
<P>
   Five seventh-inning errors led to the Rangers' six-run inning.
Right fielder Alex Hernandez committed two of the errors, and left
fielder Emil Brown, second baseman Jeff Patzke and first baseman
Kevin Young each committed one. Rangers infielder Jon Shave drove
in one of the six runs with a triple.
</P>
<P>
   At the plate: Pirates starter Francisco Cordova hit shortstop
Royce Clayton and right fielder Juan Gonzalez with pitches during
his erratic first inning. Center fielder Ruben Mateo hit his first
home run of the spring.
</P>
<P>
   On the mound: Aaron Sele threw 59 pitches in his three-inning
appearance. Oates prefers that his pitchers complete an inning with
15.
</P>
<P>
   In the field: Third baseman Rob Sasser started a 5-4-3
ninth-inning double play on a ground ball that bounced high over
his head. The 6-foot-3 Sasser leaped to catch the ball, gathered
his feet and delivered a chest-high throw to second baseman Kelly
Dransfeldt.
</P>
<P>
   On the bases: Mateo broke for second base too early on a
hit-and-run and was caught stealing, nn
</P>
</TEXT>
