<HEADLINE>
TRANSFER FINDS HIS NICHE, SPARKS SOUTHWEST MISSOURI
</HEADLINE>
 MISSOURI-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When he transferred from Miami of Ohio to Southwest Missouri
State, Danny Moore was looking for a better situation, a better
fit. The idea of making history _ as an individual and with the
Bears _ wasn't part of the equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't like the situation, it wasn't working out for
me,'' said Moore, who transferred in 1995 and sat out the 1995-96
season. ``I wasn't getting a lot of playing time. Now, I'm at a
school where we've done something that's never been done before.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore, a senior center, has been an integral part of Southwest
Missouri State's surprising run to the NCAA Tournament's Sweet 16.
He had 39 points and 29 rebounds in the Bears' first two East
Region victories. His ability to score and rebound will be crucial
if 12th-seeded Southwest Missouri State (22-10) has any chance
against top-seeded Duke in Friday's regional semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been incredibly consistent. Great players learn how to do
that,'' Southwest Missouri State coach Steve Alford said of Moore.
``He gives us presence in the middle that good teams have to
have.''
</P>
<P>
   In high school, Moore's team defeated New Castle, Ind., in the
playoffs. New Castle was coached by Sam Alford, whose son Steve had
just taken over as head coach at Southwest Missouri State. Steve
Alford, who hired his father as an assistant, had three scholarship
players. He needed bodies, the bigger and more talented the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam Alford knew who I was, he remembered me from high
school,'' Moore said. ``When they heard I was transferring, they
got in touch with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore was unhappy at Miami under Herb Sendek, who is now the
coach at North Carolina State. In Alford's motion offense, the
versatile Moore has found a suitable outlet for his talents.
</P>
<P>
   At 6-foot-11 and 243 pounds, Moore has the ability to score down
low with his back to the basket, and to step away from the
body-banging in the lane and shoot facing the basket.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's second-round victory against Tennessee, Moore scored
25 points, including two 3-pointers. Tennessee also made the
unusual _ and, as it turned out, disastrous _ decision of guarding
Moore with a single defender.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny's a great inside presence,'' Southwest Missouri State
point guard William Fontleroy said. ``The other team has to
double-team Danny. If not, Danny can score with the best of 'em
one-on-one. When he's on his game _ passing, kicking from the
double teams _ that just makes it easier for the rest of us to
score from the outside.''
</P>
<P>
   For his career, Moore has averaged 17 points and six rebounds.
He's the first player in Southwest Missouri State history to lead
the team in scoring and rebounding three consecutive seasons. Also,
he's the only Bear to score at least 500 points in three
consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Moore and his teammates realize the enormous challenge they face
against Duke. For the third consecutive game, the Bears will be
underdogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to take it serious, but it's not the end of the
world if we lose,'' said Moore, who is from Shelbyville, Ind.
``This is the first time the school's ever gotten this far, be
happy for that. We'll try our hardest, try to win, but if we lose,
we still had a great year.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, in Moore's case, career.
</P>
</TEXT>
