<SLUG> BC-NCAA-ELIGIBILITY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE DENIES NCAA BID ON ELIGIBILITY ISSUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Confusion reigns and questions abound after the NCAA lost
another battle in court over its eligibility standards for freshmen
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District judge Ronald Buckwalter on Tuesday denied the
NCAA's request to delay the enforcement of a court order that
stripped the organization of its rules on initial eligibility.
Buckwalter made the original ruling last week, saying the NCAA's
use of standardized test scores was racially and culturally biased.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, NCAA officials said the original ruling would cause
``chaos,'' with more than 300 Division I schools left to make their
own decisions regarding eligibility standards for incoming
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were advised that there are no initial eligibility
standards. We're awaiting further guidance from the NCAA,'' Big 12
Conference commissioner Kevin Weiberg said. ``I can't ever recall
an issue that has as broad-based an impact as this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, each institution will have to rely on its best
judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckwalter's ruling, which came about from a suit filed by four
black athletes against the NCAA, eliminated Proposition 16. That
rule, which went into effect Aug. 1, 1996, required a high school
diploma and a minimum grade-point average in 13 core academic
courses, with the GPA contingent on an indexed, sliding scale with
scores on either the SAT or ACT.
</P>
<P>
   Buckwalter's ruling last week only struck down using
standardized tests as minimum requirements, but did not rule out
altogether the use of standardized tests.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA will continue the battle in court. It will seek a stay
from the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit. It will also
appeal Buckwalter's original ruling. The stay ruling could be
resolved within a week; an appeal could take months.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, the questions are numerous. Tuesday, the NCAA held a
conference call with commissioners. Some time this week, it hopes
to issue guidelines that will answer some questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very complicated and confusing situation,'' said TCU
athletic director Eric Hyman, who spent Tuesday afternoon trying to
find some answers. ``The judge's ruling is clear, but the
ramifications are unnerving, unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the forseeable future, we're going to go on a case-by-case
decision as far as admitting athletes who we think would be
successful at TCU. That's really all we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiberg said the Big 12 office hasn't fielded many calls from
its schools, but his advice would be to follow the judge's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA board of directors could alleviate some of the
confusion. The organization's highest rule-making group, made up of
presidents and chancellors, plans to meet over the next few weeks.
It will decide whether to adopt interim legislation or try to come
up with another solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the NCAA has a chance to put in place interim
legislation, I would say anyone is eligible, subject to each
institution's eligibility and admittance standards,'' Weiberg said.
</P>
<P>
   In its court arguments Tuesday, the NCAA argued that the chaos
created by the ruling and the decision could play havoc with the
men's and women's basketball tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   In his eight-page ruling, Buckwalter said he doubted his ruling
would significantly harm an organization that should be equipped to
handle policing its membership after ``almost 100 years of
administering intercollegiate athletics.''
</P>
<P>
   Technically, student-athletes ineligible under Proposition 16
guidelines are now eligible. However, schools might be wary of
using those players because if the ruling is overturned, those
schools could face forfeiture of games and/or loss of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the court's denial of our request for a stay, our
membership is left with many unknowns about how to address
eligibility standards,'' NCAA president Cedric Dempsey said. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
