<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NCAA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A POLITICIAN WHOSE LEAD WE SHOULD FOLLOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the mayor of Waxahachie, Texas, Charles Beatty might not deem
it politically correct to answer to the nickname ``Hatchet.'' But
some 30 years later, he's still Hatchet to me.
</P>
<P>
   In compiling a personal list of the most ferocious hitters ever
seen on a college football field, Chuck Beatty of North Texas State
ranks right at the top, and this dates to the late '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Hatchet was a hatchet while playing the monster position _ half
linebacker, half strong safety _ in a storied era of North Texas
football.
</P>
<P>
   As a bad student with a bad attitude, I was flunking out of NT
the same year (1964) Hatchet entered as a freshman football and
basketball player. With no known educational skills, the only work
available was as a sportswriter for a Dallas newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, I was covering a ``Mean Green'' team that
sent an astonishing 12 players to the NFL, including Hall of Famer
Joe Greene. Like Greene, Beatty also ended up with the Pittsburgh
Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   But there was always more to Chuck Beatty than just football.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, I received an invitation to a University of North
Texas (as the Denton school is now known) distinguished alumni
awards dinner. Among those to be honored is Hatchet. The only way I
qualified for attendance was through Beatty, who included me on his
guest list.
</P>
<P>
   And even though we are talking about three decades ago, a
totally different world, there is a parallel here with the latest
controversy in college sports over Proposition 16.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge in Philadelphia opened a sack of snakes last
week by halting the NCAA from using minimum standardized test
scores in freshmen eligibility requirements _ otherwise known as
Prop 16 _ ruling ACTs and SATs are racially biased.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the judge denied the NCAA a stay on that ruling. You
know what _ he might be right. Either way, I'll have to leave that
controversy for the deep thinkers.
</P>
<P>
   But this we all know _ because it's history repeating itself _
what the judge has done is delivered the prey from the mouths of
lions to the teeth of tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Remove admission standards, and a certain number of college
coaches will feed upon the victims. Just use them for athletic
purposes, and then throw them back on Mean Street, never to be
heard from again. The meat-on-the-hoof syndrome will return to
college athletics.
</P>
<P>
   In the '60s, it was prevalent. In the '70s, it mushroomed. And
out of that jungle came a Dexter Manley, who could star on the
football field at Oklahoma State but couldn't read the newspaper
stories written about his gridiron greatness. Manley's plight
became a celebrated case, but it was hardly an isolated incident.
</P>
<P>
   If all jocks, then and now, had only been like Chuck Beatty ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing scared me more,'' Hatchet said Tuesday, ``than the
horror stories of the ex-football player having to try and make
something out of the rest of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days of Texas segregation, Beatty graduated from
Waxahachie Turner High School, and because of his football and
basketball skills, had the opportunity to continue on to NTSU. But
in that era, players had to be players. Scholarships would
disappear quickly if athletic advancement didn't occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to sit in the dorm and listen for the suitcases
hitting the sidewalk,'' Beatty said.
</P>
<P>
   As Beatty became a stellar football player, he also became a
focused student. Coming from a small, black high school in
then-rural Texas, Hatchet would today be considered one of the
academic underprivileged the Philadelphia judge exemplified when he
struck down Prop 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I felt like I was prepared for college, and considered
myself a good student,'' Beatty said.
</P>
<P>
   After his senior season, Beatty was only 10 hours away from
completing his degree, although that went on hold when he was
drafted by Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Beatty played there four seasons, went to the St. Louis
Cardinals in 1972, and then played a couple of years in the World
Football League.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the time came to join the real world in '76, I returned
to NT for those 10 hours,'' he said. ``With the rest of my life
staring me in the face, I became a very focused student.''
</P>
<P>
   With a degree in hand, Beatty went to work for the executive
office of the Boy Scouts in Dallas, and has been there 22 years.
Meanwhile, he returned to his Waxahachie roots, was elected to the
City Council in 1995 and then elected mayor two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being mayor is all about priorities,'' he said. ``We are a
fast-growing city of 22,000 that wants to maintain the quality of
life, but also expand in the right directions.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, 53 years old, my man Hatchet has come a long way from old
Waxahachie Turner and NTSU. This mixing of athletics and academics
can work for all, provided certain coaches aren't given too many
athletics-only temptations. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
