<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-RAPTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAPTORS BEAT NETS, 100-85 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The smiles worn by John Calipari's enemies in the New
Jersey Nets' organization turned to grimaces and frowns tonight. In
a display that was as shocking as their 3-18 record, the Nets were
run out of Air Canada Center by the Toronto Raptors.
</P>
<P>
   A day after Calipari was fired by the team's principal owner,
Lewis Katz, the Nets were blasted, 100-85, by a young and
undisciplined squad with an 8-12 record. In was the Nets' eighth
straight loss and the 14th in their last 15 over all.
</P>
<P>
   With the interim coach Don Casey calling the plays, little
changed. The Nets shot air balls and bricks, used paper-thin
defense and seemed confused.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Raptors dunked with style, blocked shots with
authority and mocked their wretched guests with a host of arrogant
mannerisms on the court. It was so bad that the usually mellow
Casey stomped his feet in disgust at the 4-minute-16-second mark of
the third quarter when the Nets were trailing by 62-48.
</P>
<P>
   The act was the most demonstrative one of the night for the
61-year-old Casey, who looked almost like a Calipari clone. As the
Nets missed open shot after open shot in shooting 37 percent from
the field, Casey frantically ran his fingers through his hair,
screamed orders and turned his back on the action in dismay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm saying to myself, `Boy, what a seat this is when you move
over 12 inches and walk in somebody else's shoes,''' Casey said.
``You look bad when you miss shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Jayson Williams, who grabbed 14 rebounds but missed four of five
shots, was able to keep a sense of humor about the situation.
``Casey's got to be careful, stomping his feet at that age,''
Williams said. ``The bones are fragile. The heart is weak. I don't
want to go through three coaches in two days.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets melted like a snowman on a sunny day. They never had a
lead and, after shooting 17 percent in the second quarter, trailed
by as many as 19 points before halftime. The open shots they got
because of Casey's new plays went for naught as they made just 6 of
26 shots (23 percent) in the third quarter and watched the Raptors
open the lead to 27 points. Clearly, Calipari and his three deposed
assistants _ Johnny Davis, Kenny Gattison and Jack Haley _were not
the only problem with the free-falling Nets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new start, but it's been a long week,'' said Kendall
Gill, who missed 7 of 11 shots and scored 14 points. ``We're trying
to play hard for Casey, for ourselves and for the organization,
but. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   In a scene that was reminiscent of Sunday's events in Miami,
where Calipari toiled under the critical eyes of the club's
officials sitting courtside, the team president, Michael Rowe,
watched Tuesday night's carnage from a seat near halfcourt. Rowe,
one of Calipari's biggest detractors, was jovial before the game,
but as the rout unfolded his expression became somber.
</P>
<P>
   And the usually collected Keith Van Horn screamed at Williams
and Lucious Harris about poor defense while the Nets walked off the
court for a timeout trailing by 14 points with three minutes left
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're not shooting the ball well, you have to play good
defense,'' said Van Horn, who recorded 17 points and 11 rebounds.
``But we made a lot of little mistakes on defense tonight and it
got frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn followed Stephon Marbury, who led the Nets in scoring
for the second time since joining the team two games ago. The point
guard made some dynamic moves in recording 22 points and 8 assists.
But that was no consolation for Marbury, who once again was visibly
disappointed with his new team.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the native of Brooklyn insisted he had no regrets about
leaving the playoff-bound Minnesota Timberwolves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy where I'm at,'' Marbury said. ``I know things are
going to get better. I just know that I fell into an unfortunate
situation. It's very easy to get down, but I'm really happy. I
think we have a really good team. Right now, we just don't have any
concepts and by us not having concepts, we're just out there
playing basketball. We're not playing an NBA game.''
</P>
<P>
   Help might be on the way Wednesday, when the new assistants Jim
Lynam and Eddie Jordan will join the team. They will replace the
ill-prepared rental assistants, Hal Wissel and Mike O'Koren. There
will be no rest for the weary with games the next two nights,
Wednesday against Dallas at Continental Arena and Thursday in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Lynam is believed to have a shot at becoming the Nets' next head
coach. He coached in Philadelphia from 1988 to 1992 and in
Washington from 1994 to 1997, serving under John Nash, now the
Nets' general manager, in both situations. Jordan coached
Sacramento for a year and a half before being replaced after last
season.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie Vince Carter led the Raptors with 20 points and 15
rebounds. Doug Christie, who scored 12 first-quarter points,
followed with 18, and Tracy McGrady had one of his best
performances of the season in recording 14 points and 13 rebounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
