<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
START IS NICE FOR LAKERS' RICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Glen Rice came to Kurt Rambis with a simple
request: Put me in, coach. Now.
</P>
<P>
   After two games with the Lakers, Rice declared himself ready to
start. The rookie coach was in no position to argue with the NBA's
premier shooting ace, so Rambis consented Tuesday _ and let Rice
make him look like a sage.
</P>
<P>
   Rice started, found his shooting stroke early and promptly
unleashed it on the Minnesota Timberwolves, scoring 22 points,
eight in the fourth quarter, to carry the Lakers to a 107-101
victory.
</P>
<P>
   On the scale of difficult decisions Rambis has made as head
coach, this one ranked down there with choosing which glasses to
wear.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he'd feel more comfortable starting,'' Rambis said.
``I said, `OK.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Simple job.
</P>
<P>
   All Rice did in return was hit 4 of 10 3-pointers, even with
Kevin Garnett's gangly limbs stretching over him. His eight points
in the fourth came in a 2-minute, 14-second span, with 3-pointers
on either end of it, giving the Lakers a 98-95 lead that they never
relinquished.
</P>
<P>
   ``The confidence was rolling, the legs were feeling good, and I
had too much daylight,'' said Rice, who hit 8 of 17 shots overall.
``Even before the game, I was feeling that my legs were really
getting much stronger. I've always said that once I got my legs up
under me the shots were gonna go in. I just had to maintain my
concentration, stay focused and keep shooting the shots.''
</P>
<P>
   The more he did, the more they started to hit net instead of
iron. And for the Lakers, who gave up Eddie Jones' slashing and
defense to obtain Rice's 3-point cannon, it was a beautiful sight.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota, as per usual, was trying to double-team Shaquille
O'Neal in the low post. But now, for the first time, O'Neal knew he
could flip the ball back outside with confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, I need a couple 3s from you right now,'' O'Neal
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rice was happy to comply.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Shaq) was saying, `Get open. Get open. Get open.' I was like,
OK, I'm getting open. A lot of credit to the big man,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal got 24 points himself, and Kobe Bryant scored 21 _ 11 in
the fourth quarter _ as the Lakers won their 11th in the past 12
games.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't come as easily as Rice's shooting spree. The
Timberwolves dominated the second quarter and took a 54-47 halftime
lead by out-thugging the Lakers in the paint, scoring 15
second-chance points.
</P>
<P>
   At the half, Minnesota had collected 18 offensive boards and
outrebounded the Dennis Rodman-less Lakers 32-19. Four of five
Wolves starters scored in double figures, led by the front line of
Garnett, Joe Smith and Dean Garrett.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Garnett finished with 22 and 21 points, respectively,
but Travis Knight, J.R Reid and Rice slowed them just enough in the
second half to pull out the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against an athletic, young team like Minnesota, big long guys
inside, you gotta get into their body, make it a physical game. We
did that in the second half,'' Reid said. If Garnett or Smith
rolled into the lane, ``just hit 'em. Bump 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest was up to the finesse guys. And those 3s must be
infectious. Along with Rice, Derek Harper and Bryant both hit
3-pointers in the late fourth-quarter run. Bryant's wide-open 3
effectively put the game away, 103-97, with 1:21 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers had entered the game in a 4-for-30 (13.3 percent)
slump from the arc. With Rice's elbow and legs near full strength,
that stat seems unlikely to repeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glen's always been a deadly shooter. I'm just glad he's with
me,'' O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was coming,'' Reid said of his onetime Charlotte
teammate. ``It was only a matter of time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
