<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TCU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURN OF BILLYBALL HAS HORNED FROGS ENJOYING NIT RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Yes, you heard right. Billyball is back.
</P>
<P>
   And so is almost everything that goes with it: the playground
dunks, the pressure-the-ball defense, the look-out-here-we-come
transition game, the you-betcha-we're-going-to-score-100-points
attitude, the so-loud-you-can't-hear-yourself-think crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah, and the victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billyball's an attitude more than anything,'' Horned Frogs
guard Ryan Carroll explained.
</P>
<P>
   A return to Billyball has TCU (21-10) a step away from the
National Invitation Tournament semifinals and a trip to New York. A
Horned Frogs' victory against Oregon (18-11) in a game starting at
8:37 p.m. Wednesday at Daniel-Meyer Coliseum gets them on that
plane bound for Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billyball's hard to play,'' said Horned Frogs coach Billy
Tubbs, his name defining his style. ``What we're doing right now is
so easy to coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Carroll: ``It's Billyball lite.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all of the running, slamming, scoring and intense fun of
Billyball without the full-court pressure, the what-shot-clock
approach to offense and the man-to-man-or-bust approach to defense.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, maybe, Billyball needed a new look.
</P>
<P>
   The main ingredient _ the swagger, as Lee Nailon likes to call
it _ had been missing for a while. It certainly wasn't there two
weeks ago when Brigham Young upset TCU in the first round of the
Western Athletic Conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, it hadn't been around for almost a month leading
up to that game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what happened,'' Tubbs said, ``I think we got
disappointed, and we let that disappointment get to us. Some
disappointing things happened to us that we didn't handle
particularly well. Instead of stepping up, we went into a
semidepression.''
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs admits that after losing to BYU he feared returning for
practices to get ready for NIT games that many were predicting
instead of NCAA Tournament games that many had been expecting.
</P>
<P>
   At least a week of practice was ahead of them, and he wasn't
sure how his players would respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fun?'' Horned Frogs guard Prince Fowler said. ``There wasn't a
lot of that going around.''
</P>
<P>
   But a funny thing happened in those practices, a thing that
Fowler tries to explain but can't quite do in one word. ``It was
more like the way things were,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   They'd shoot around before practice like most folks do in their
back yard, with Derale Wilson providing comic relief with his
constant commentary. They'd scrimmage like they used to do on
playgrounds as kids, with Fowler providing the trash talk.
</P>
<P>
   They'd look at coach Tubbs, like they always do, to get their
lead on how to act.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's hard to believe,'' Fowler said, ``but he's having
fun. He's relaxed. When he's relaxed, we're relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in there, the pressure evaporated and the fun
returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a tribute to our players how they've responded,''
Tubbs said. ``We're having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Billyball is back, and maybe better than before.
</P>
<P>
   Cornhuskers coach Danny Nee conceded as much Monday after a
101-89 loss to TCU. It's the same style he remembers playing
against when Tubbs coached Oklahoma, only suited to Tubbs' current
personnel. It's the style that convinced TCU guard Vladimir Jaksic
to come to transfer to TCU.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure I hear of Billyball,'' Jaksic said. ``There was lots of
scoring and lots of running and lots of people in the stands
cheering, just like against Nebraska.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like Billyball is back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time,'' Fowler said. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
