<SLUG> BC-K-SWISS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATHLETIC FOOTWEAR COMPANY'S 1998 EARNINGS SOAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Take a strong earnings report, add a pending
stock split, and you get an energizing concoction that's sent
athletic shoe maker K-Swiss Inc.'s share price on a record sprint.
</P>
<P>
   The company reported Feb. 8 its 1998 profits nearly tripled to
$12.5 million, or $2.20 per diluted share, from 1997's $4.2
million, or 70 cents per diluted share. Sales for the year rose 39
percent to $161.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   K-Swiss also announced at that point that K-Swiss shareholders
could look forward to a two-for-one stock split and a 50 percent
increase in the quarterly cash dividend. The split, effective March
26, applies to stockholders of record as of March 15, according to
chief financial officer George Powlick.
</P>
<P>
   The result? The company's stock price has posted gains in almost
every session since Feb. 8 and nearly doubled in value from
$34.625. The upward trend ended Tuesday, when profit-taking pushed
the price down $3.125 to $61.875.
</P>
<P>
   The company has attributed the healthy results in part to an
accelerated marketing and advertising campaign. K-Swiss shoes are
carried by the major athletic footwear retailers, including
Footlocker, Powlick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having very good success with respect to our footwear
being in tune with the market -- it's resulted in very strong
earnings and accelerated results,'' he said. ``Our backlog is
growing very fast, also.''
</P>
<P>
   The backlog grew by 117 percent over the year, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Among K-Swiss's strongest selling styles during the year were
Sentir and Altezo. Another popular seller is the Classic, developed
in 1966 as the first all leather tennis shoe, said Kim Moore,
product manager for the company.
</P>
<P>
   The product has remained popular for a number of reasons, not
the least of which is that it's all white and has not changed over
the years. That means that retailers who carry the line don't have
to worry about it going out of style, forcing them to dump the
shoes into their sale bins.
</P>
<P>
   And retailers don't have to carry a minimum size run because
every sale automatically triggers an order for new stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Classic leather tennis shoe is the cornerstone of
K-Swiss,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
