<SLUG> BC-TRAIN-CRASH-ART-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-790(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
13 KILLED AS AMTRAK TRAIN COLLIDES WITH TRUCK IN ILLINOIS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for inserts and rewriting throughout)   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Locator map
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOURBONNAIS, Ill. _ They were just settling in for the night,
comfortably ensconced in the first-class double-decker sleeper car
of a train with a famous name, The City of New Orleans. They had
boarded in Chicago, just two hours before, and their train, its
legend celebrated in a popular American folk song, was due to pull
into New Orleans in the late afternoon of the next day.
</P>
<P>
   But in a single horrifying instant, everything changed. At 9:47
p.m. on Monday, Amtrak's City of New Orleans smashed into a
semi-trailer truck at a railroad crossing in this rural town about
55 miles south of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday afternoon, 13 passengers had been found dead, most of
them in the sleeper car. Some people were still unaccounted for,
and officials said on Tuesday night that the number was either
three or four. There were no signs that those people were alive.
</P>
<P>
   The first five cars of the train were mangled, twisted like
empty soda cans after the train hit the back of the truck and
derailed. Flames burst out, visible from miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure at this point I can collect my thoughts enough to
tell you what was going through my mind,'' said Michael
Harshbarger, chief of the tiny Bourbonnais fire department. ``I
don't think I've ever seen anything quite like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board, which is in charge of
investigating the crash, said on Tuesday night that in preliminary
interviews, the train engineer said he saw the truck go around the
closed gates at the crossing. Investigators also said the truck
driver told a different story, saying the gates started to close
after he was in the crossing. A safety board official, John Goglia,
said investigators were particularly interested in a set of tire
tracks. If the tracks match the truck's tires, he said, they would
indicate that the truck did try to go around the closed gate.
</P>
<P>
   Officials were releasing no details about the dead, whose bodies
were being kept in an old lumber company warehouse turned makeshift
morgue. But a woman in Nesbit, Miss., confirmed that four of those
killed _ a woman, her granddaughter and two other children _ were
returning home to Nesbit after a shopping trip to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   There were 116 people injured, federal investigators said, with
49 of them still hospitalized on Tuesday night. All the survivors
were rescued Monday night, among them a group of 20 teen-agers from
Mississippi and their chaperones, returning from a ski trip to
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The train was carrying 196 passengers, 19 Amtrak employees and 2
employees of the Illinois Central Railroad, which manages the
railroad crossing.
</P>
<P>
   The truck driver, who was using a probationary permit after his
license had been suspended because of speeding tickts, was heading
east across the train tracks when the train hit. The collision
shattered the trailer section of the truck, which was packed with
heavy steel bars from a nearby steel factory. The driver was
treated and released, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The safety board said on Tuesday night that the train had been
traveling at 79 miles an hour, the maximum allowed on this stretch
of track. The train was blowing its whistle and had engaged its
emergency brake, Goglia said.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day on Tuesday, rescue crews that had rushed
here from miles away continued to comb through the tangled metal,
hampered by piles of crushed debris and the need to make sure the
wreckage would not shift and endanger the rescuers themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The once-gleaming sleeper car had been slammed up onto one of
the train's two locomotives. It was broken down the middle and
ravaged by fire, Harshbarger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interior is filled with debris from the fire, and it's
necessary to search through that debris to find victims,''
Harshbarger said. ``It's simply a matter of digging with the gloved
hand, turning pieces of debris over in order to find someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Allen, 80, who was traveling with his wife from their home
in Winona, Minn., to visit their son in Florida, described the
frightening confusion of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was this violent jerking motion and all of a sudden we
just stopped and the lights went out,'' said Allen, who was riding
in one of the last of the train's 14 cars and had just settled down
to read a book. He heard a loud, grating noise and then, he said,
``All we could see was the smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   The crash was the third-deadliest accident in Amtrak's 26-year
history. The worst was a 1993 crash that killed 47 people when a
train plunged into a bayou near Mobile, Ala. In 1987, two trains
collided near Chase, Md., killing 16.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Thirty investigators from the safety board arrived on Tuesday
morning and were trying to determine what caused the accident.
</P>
<P>
   The truck driver, John R. Stokes, 58, of Manteno, Ill., a town a
few miles north of here, had had his commercial driver's license
suspended in January because he had received three speeding tickets
in 12 months, said David Druker, a spokesman for the Illinois
secretary of state's office.
</P>
<P>
   But because it was Stokes' first suspension he was allowed to
take a safety class and receive a temporary probationary permit.
Barring any problems, he would have got his regular license back on
March 25. His only previous infractions were two speeding tickets,
Druker said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth R. Wykle, the administrator of the Federal Highway
Administration, said the agency would investigate the safety
compliance record of the company Stokes was driving for, Melco
Transfer Inc. of Peotone, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
