<SLUG> BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARSON WONDERS ABOUT OVITZ ABSENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Carson City Manager Jerry Groomes and Michael Padilla,
a member of the Carson Economic Development Committee, sat in a
corner of a large hotel ballroom here Tuesday and watched the NFL
pass before their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Owners like the honorable Dan Rooney and sincere Ralph C. Wilson
walked by, given wider berths by the media horde out of respect.
They watched the dowager owner of one team that vacated Southern
California, Georgia Frontiere, walk by attended by her
long-suffering aide, Marshall Klein.
</P>
<P>
   A moment or two later, the man who took the other team away from
Los Angeles, Al Davis, walked out and sparred with the media the
way a torero teases a bull. He took their questions and turned them
around. He dropped more cryptic comments than an episode of the
``X-Files.'' He asked reporters where they were from, as if
geography meant something to him.
</P>
<P>
   Groomes and Padilla, each wearing a blue hat with ``Carson 32''
on it, watched Ed Roski, the Kings owner and the man at the head of
the New Coliseum expansion proposal, and his colleagues work the
room.
</P>
<P>
   One, two, five, seven, 10... somewhere around 10, they stopped
counting all of the Roski-related personnel in the room. They were
severely outnumbered and they had every reason to wonder why.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Ovitz, the man who came to Carson and said he wanted
them as a partner in landing a NFL franchise, was supposed to be
the showman. He's the guy with the entertainment portfolio, the man
who knows how to put on a show. This looked like his turf, but he
wasn't around.
</P>
<P>
   The man who negotiated David Letterman's move from NBC to CBS
and just pocketed two agents from his old agency to work for his
new management company, was not here to work the room. He had
returned home, reportedly because the league told him he didn't
need to hang around.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, on the day the league conditionally agreed to put an
expansion team in L.A., the men in the Carson hats wondered what it
all meant, whether Roski's presence meant more than Ovitz's
absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it means anything,'' said Padilla, a large man
with an appetite to make things happen. ``I just hope the league
knows what we have to offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the commissioner (Paul Tagliabue) came to visit, he liked
the interest people showed at the press conference. But we can do
more. We can do a lot more. Maybe we need to remind them what we
have to offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Carson, he said, has a lot to offer. Its vision is no less
intriguing as the Coliseum's. It doesn't have the tradition of the
old stadium, but it also doesn't have the baggage. In terms of
cutting-edge synergy, the idea of a mall and stadium complex puts
most cement doughnuts to shame.
</P>
<P>
   Carson also has fresh money. The city's pledged investment is
$180 million, $30 million of it in cash and $150 million via bonds,
bonds that have already unofficially received a good rating and
attracted interested buyers.
</P>
<P>
   But the undercurrent Tuesday afternoon clearly favored Roski and
the Coliseum. Three years ago, the NFL said it would sooner gargle
pesticide than return to the Coliseum. For Roski and Co. to still
be standing on the day the league said it might return was a hell
of an achievement.
</P>
<P>
   They have their own vision, and while unrealized, it's larger
than Carson's. Beyond a new Coliseum inside the shell of the old
Coliseum, an entire sports and entertainment corridor is being
built from the inside out, running from Dodger Stadium to the
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Eli Broad, Roski's partner, is a partner in redevelopment of
downtown, including the building of Disney Hall on the west side of
the Harbor Freeway and the Coburn Art School on Grand Avenue. As
part of the Staples Center deal, Roski has 20 acres of undeveloped
land that runs down Figueroa and around the Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Roski/Broad utopia would see a 1,400-room hotel and major
retailers filling those 20 acres, as well as people-friendly links
from site to site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people working on this know downtown will never be defined
by its commercial office space,'' said Michael Collins, executive
vice president of the L.A. Convention and Visitors Bureau, one of
many Roski-tied people at the meetings. ``But it's ground zero as
an entertainment and sports center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The climate in L.A. doesn't allow for the city funding a new
stadium. But in the next 3{ years, there will be $5 billion worth
of infrastructure in making it a sports and entertainment complex.
If they looked, they'd see exactly the kind of thing the league
says it would like in every city.''
</P>
<P>
   Carson can offer its own vision. It just isn't sure if it's
ground zero in the NFL's eyes. The league deadline for development
of L.A. might be six months, but the next 30 days will separate the
two L.A. groups.
</P>
<P>
   Carson wants to play. It just hopes its quarterback shows up. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 0147EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
