<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3301 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAIN-CRASH-ART-2NDLD     03-17 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAIN-CRASH-ART-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BOURBONNAIS, ILL.: Peotone, Ill.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one answered the door or the telephone at Stokes' house on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Goglia said Stokes had said in early interviews that he did not
see the train or the warning lights until he had started driving
across the tracks and that the gates closed before he could get out
of the path of the train. But Goglia said investigators needed to
conduct more interviews with Stokes before they could say whether
that was his complete version of events.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators will also re-interview the engineer, who said he
saw the truck try to get around the gates, Goglia said. The
engineer is among those hospitalized, and Goglia said his
medication made it difficult to interview him more thoroughly on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation confirmed that the truck had not been
overloaded, Goglia said, adding that the steel bars extended seven
feet beyond the trailer bed, a distance that is within the legal
limit but may have made the crash worse.
</P>
<P>
   Goglia also said investigators had taken blood and urine samples
from Mr. Stokes, administered a breath test for alcohol and checked
his schedule for the past 72 hours to see whether he was getting
enough rest. They did not say whether any of those test results
were in. Investigators will also compare the time that his truck
left the plant with the time of the crash to see how fast he was
going.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators will also examine whether cars parked near the
crossing might have obstructed the truck driver's view of the
train, Goglia said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the crossing's equipment, including gates, two signal
lights and a bell, was functioning properly Monday night. The
warning equipment started when it was supposed to, 27 second before
the train was due to come into the intersection.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Burke, a spokesman for Illinois Central, said it would not
have been possible for the truck to become trapped by the closing
gates, because the gates would have hit the truck and broken.
</P>
<P>
   Goglia said investigators checked the warning equipment's
history over the last 12 months and found only one malfunction, an
instance when the gates stayed down after the train had passed. He
said there had never been a time when the gates did not go down or
malfunctioned in any other way.
</P>
<P>
   There have been three previous fatal accidents at this railroad
crossing, in 1964, 1968, and 1988, according go the Illinois
Commerce Commission. State officials say that is a relatively good
safety record, given the number of trains that cross the
intersection, about 40 a day, traveling at speeds of 25 to 79 miles
per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Jolene M. Molitoris, administrator of the Federal Railroad
Administration, said the crossing was considered a good
intersection.
</P>
<P>
   A City of New Orleans train passes this way every night, pulling
out of Chicago about 8 p.m. It makes a few stops in Illinois, a
stop in Memphis and another Tennessee city, and virtually turns
into a local train in Mississippi, until it reaches New Orleans at
3:30 p.m. the following day. Another City of New Orleans train
makes the trip in reverse every day.
</P>
<P>
   The City of New Orleans was the main northbound train of the
great black migration from the South in the 1940s and 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   And it was celebrated in a folk song written by Steve Goodman
and made famous by Arlo Guthrie. The song croons about men dealing
cards in the club car, mothers rocking their sleeping babies and
the train ``passin' trains that have no names, freight yards full
of old black men, and the graveyards of rusted automobiles.''
</P>
<P>
   The chorus _ ``Good Morning America, how are you?'' _
memorialized the romance of the railroad age.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The modern-day City of New Orleans is a comfortable ride,
especially in the sleeping car, where passengers have a
``hospitality hour,'' a morning paper delivered to them and an
attendant on call 24-hours.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, all that was forgotten in the macabre accident
scene, where investigators were looking for answers.
</P>
<P>
   Safety board officials said they had interviewed the driver and
the train engineer and sent the train's black box to Chicago to be
analyzed. They plan to retest the crossing gates and lights and the
sensor on the tracks that trips the gates.
</P>
<P>
   They said the investigation was complicated by the presence of
two train cars on the side tracks, one full of steel and the other
full of furnace residue from the steel plant. The cars had been
struck in the derailment and were making the search for evidence
more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The four people from Nesbit, Miss., who were killed had gone to
Chicago so the granddaughter, Jessica Bonnin, 12, and her two
friends could shop at a store that carried the American Girl dolls,
which feature historic details, and their accessories.
</P>
<P>
   The grandmother, June Bonnin, had opened a bed and breakfast
with her husband while she was still recovering from non-Hodgkin's
lymphoma.
</P>
<P>
   Among those injured was Ashley Bonnin, Mrs. Bonnin's daughter
and Jessica's aunt. She was hospitalized in stable condition.
</P>
<P>
   As the hours passed in Bourbonnais on Tuesday, rescue workers
faced a stiff winter wind as they clambered on top of the upended
and fractured train cars, searching for any glimpse of the missing.
</P>
<P>
   Others had worked all night, helping the survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people were coming off the train searching for their
family members,'' said Karen Brzezicki, a firefighter and paramedic
for the Bourbonnais fire department and one of the first workers on
the scene. ``That was the hardest part, people searching for their
children. This is one of those things you don't want to see and you
hope you never have to see again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
