<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-SIDEBAR-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIDERS' DAVIS HOVERS OVER NFL MEETINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By BOB KEISSER &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   PHOENIX -- For anyone familiar with Los Angeles' tortured NFL
past, the presence of Al Davis and John Shaw sharing a hotel lobby
and talking about the NFL's latest flirtation with L.A. made one
reach for the antacids.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, the Rams' President, engineered the move from Anaheim to
St. Louis for Georgia Frontiere. Raiders' owner Davis took the
Raiders back to Oakland at the same time. The NFL vacancy sign on
L.A.'s lawn was hammered in by these two men, and now they were
passing judgment on an expansion proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm optimistic that (L.A.) can get an expansion team,'' said
Shaw. In spite of the area's long, failed history of civil
civic-team relationships? ``I (ital) hope (end ital) they can get
an expansion team.''
</P>
<P>
   As Shaw spoke, Davis walked by and said ``John, tell them
there's no difference today than there was (four) years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' comment fell cryptically on most ears, those who do not
recall the NFL once gave its blessing to Hollywood Park building a
stadium for the Raiders. The league gave Hollywood Park and R.D.
Hubbard a time deadline and conditions to meet, just as it did to
Carson and the Coliseum Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Park didn't meet its deadline, the proposal died, and
Davis moved the Raiders back to Oakland. In Davis' view, the
league's resolution Tuesday looks familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles has its own problems to solve,'' he said,
declining to elaborate but obviously considering the demerits of
the Coliseum and Carson proposals -- little public cash for the
Coliseum, and a perceived environmental problem in Carson.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so does the league.''
</P>
<P>
   That referred to Davis' suit in state court claiming that he won
territorial rights to L.A. in court and still owns them despite
having returned to Oakland. Davis believes the league sabotaged the
Hollywood Park proposal because it didn't want the Raiders in a new
stadium that would also serve as a future Super Bowl site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want damages,'' he said about the suit. ``I want to be
somewhere we can prosper and win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders have a lease in Oakland with 16 years remaining, but
Davis believes he can break it based on non-performance by the city
of Oakland and the group hired to handle Private Seat License (PSL)
sales.
</P>
<P>
   League attorney Frank Rothman says the suit is baseless and has
no impact on any expansion decisions. But the league's six-month
window for L.A. could be perceived as a stall until the suit
progresses further in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You said that, not me,'' Davis said, enjoying the repartee
even as he tried to distance himself from it. ``What everyone
forgets is that L.A. would have a team and a state-of-the-art
stadium if Hollywood Park had been given the chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't want to get into that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
