<SLUG> BC-FRANKLIN-TELECOM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANKLIN TELECOM TO JOIN AMEX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Franklin Telecom is moving up in the world by
switching from the lowly OTC Bulletin Board to the American Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The telecommunications and Internet services company announced
Tuesday that it has met the higher capital standards and scrutiny
of the national exchange. Franklin, which has been trading on the
OTC as FTEL, will start trading at 8:30 a.m. Thursday under the
symbol FCM on the Amex.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Frank Peters has been asked
to ring the opening bell at the exchange that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It brings us to a whole new level,'' said Tom Russell, chief
financial officer of Franklin. ``We'll get broader exposure to the
financial markets because it's on a national exchange. (Our stock)
will get more stability.''
</P>
<P>
   Franklin could not have joined Nasdaq because it did not meet
its $4 stock price requirement, but Wall Street cheered the
announcement anyhow with Franklin's stock rising 34 cents, or 12
percent, to $3.25.
</P>
<P>
   The American Stock Exchange, which wants to attract cutting-edge
tech firms, was particularly attracted to Franklin's Internet
business, Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-year-old company makes equipment that allow phone calls
over the Internet. It is developing a voice-enabled Web site, which
allows an Internet user to click on it and be connected by phone to
the person or company behind the site. Russell said the site will
be helpful for technical support because a user can click on the
Web site and be connected by phone to technicians.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin's subsidiary, FNet, is developing long-distance phone
services transmitted over the Internet. ``An ISP (Internet service
provider) can add this equipment to their site and almost turn into
a phone company,'' Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   An ISP such as Earthlink or Prodigy hooks customers up to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin's sales have shot up in its most recent quarter,
hitting $1.24 million in the second quarter ended Dec. 31 compared
with $284,000 in the year-earlier period, but it continues to
operate in the red. It lost $1.29 million in the second quarter,
compared with $868,000 in the year-earlier period.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
