<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3314 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UW-BENDER-SPI &LR;      03-17 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UW-BENDER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VANDERBILT COURTS HUSKY COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HOLLY CAIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For the second time in as many years, University of
Washington men's basketball coach Bob Bender is being courted by a
big-time program.
</P>
<P>
   Last year it was Texas, this week it's Vanderbilt University.
The Nashville, Tenn., school received permission from Washington
athletic director Barbara Hedges to talk with Bender, and Tennessee
newspapers already are referring to him as the leading candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want it to be where I'm labeled as someone who is
always looking,'' Bender said Tuesday, confirming his interest in
the Vanderbilt job. ``In the case of Vanderbilt, there's the
connection with Duke and it's a private school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, this is their inquiry, but as you get more involved
you find out what will be factors and what won't. I'll have a
better idea when I talk to them (Vanderbilt).''
</P>
<P>
   Bender's assistant coaches said he had not addressed them about
his Vanderbilt candidacy. And Bender, who amassed an 85-83 record
in six years with the Huskies, said he had not yet made any plans
to visit the school this week but has spoken with Vanderbilt
athletic director Todd Turner by phone.
</P>
<P>
   Delaware coach Mike Brey withdrew his name from Turner's
consideration Monday, leading the media to put Bender atop Turner's
wish list. Mercer Island native Quin Snyder, a top Duke assistant
coach, is another prime candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Appalachian State coach Buzz Peterson, Southwest Missouri State
coach Steve Alford and New Mexico's Dave Bliss also are being named
as potential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Hedges is out of town and was unavailable for comment. Turner,
however, confirmed Tuesday afternoon that he has spoken to Hedges
and Bender, but he declined to give details on the search itself.
</P>
<P>
   He has been tight-lipped about his hunt since Jan van Breda
Kolff resigned as Vanderbilt coach Feb. 25 after a 104-81 record
and one NCAA tournament appearance in six seasons. Van Breda Kolff
struggled to retain Vanderbilt basketball's status as ``the game''
in town with competition from Nashville's newest tenants, the NHL
Predators and NFL Titans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't scheduled a visit, we've just had a preliminary
conversation,'' Turner said of Bender. ``Coach Bender has done such
a great job coaching and developed such a great reputation he will
be a candidate for many coaching jobs, and we're certainly
interested in him ...''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder acknowledged Tuesday that he, too, is interested in
talking to Vanderbilt and said his boss, Duke coach Mike
Krzyzewski, has encouraged him to pursue a head coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel as if personally my career has evolved to a point where
I'm ready to pursue some head coaching vacancies,'' Snyder said.
``I've been given the go-ahead and that's part of coach's
(Krzyzewski) desire to grow and prepare those who have worked for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder also has held discussions with San Diego State about that
school's coaching vacancy, but he withdrew his name from
consideration two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   With top-ranked Duke in the midst of an NCAA tournament run,
Snyder said he doesn't want to be a distraction to the Blue Devils'
title hopes, calling a national title his ``first priority right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bender will get a chance to explore those so-called
``factors'' of employment that could lure him back east, where he
played (1978-80) and served as an assistant coach (1984-89) for
Duke. Turner, too, has Atlantic Coast Conference ties as a former
North Carolina State athletic director.
</P>
<P>
   A bigger salary, a returning team and a new basketball complex
are among Vanderbilt's draws.
</P>
<P>
   Turner reportedly is prepared to offer a $500,000 salary
package, compared to the approximately $370,000 Bender made this
past season at Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Another consideration for Bender is a solid young program at
Vanderbilt, a member of the ultracompetitive Southeastern
Conference. Nine of the Commodores' 10 players return for the
1999-2000 season, while this year's 17-12 Husky team loses two top
players in center Todd MacCulloch and guard Donald Watts.
</P>
<P>
   And while UW's Hec Edmundson Pavilion will undergo a $39 million
renovation in time for the 2000-2001 season, Vanderbilt is starting
a $25 million refurbishing of its own arena, complete with a new
basketball practice facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``For what he has done for our program, and with his
personality, he is going to be a candidate for any job,''
Washington assistant coach Eric Hughes said. ``How serious he is
about this job, I don't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
