<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3324 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHTICK-DANCE-2TAKES-$     03-17 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHTICK-DANCE-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE MY REVISED DANCES. PLEASE.  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Md.)   (af)  
 Christopher Reardon's most recent article for Arts and Leisure was
about the composer-turned-choreographer Lucia Dlugoszewski.  
 By CHRISTOPHER REARDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Talk about a tough crowd. Last fall, the
choreographer Danial Shapiro invited some friends and colleagues to
a preview of his new solo, ``Shtick,'' at the Southern Theater in
Minneapolis. Set to klezmer music and Henny Youngman jokes, the
dance was conceived as an upbeat sequel to his 1996 elegy about
Jewish ghettos and concentration camps, called ``What Dark/Falling
Into Light.''
</P>
<P>
   With the first public performance just two nights away, Shapiro
was looking for a pat on the back, and maybe a little constructive
criticism. Instead he learned what a lonely place the stage can
be. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized right away that I was in trouble,'' he recalled
during a recent interview. ``It was one of the most humiliating
showings I've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it was bad,'' added Joanie Smith, his wife and creative
partner, offering little consolation. ``I think, in the great
tradition of comedians, you bombed.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was only an eight-minute piece,'' Shapiro went on. ``But as
I kept dancing I noticed that people were drifting toward the
exits. And these were our friends.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``No, worse,'' said Ms. Smith. ``Half of them were on our
payroll.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many choreographers would have cut their losses right there.
Yet, like the Borscht Belt comedians who inspired ``Shtick,''
Shapiro has doggedly reworked his material in the hope of getting
it right. A couple of key insights helped salvage the piece in time
for a public performance barely 48 hours after the preview.
</P>
<P>
   After months of further alterations, New Yorkers will see a
third version when Shapiro and Smith Dance opens a weeklong season
at the Joyce Theater on Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro's persistence reflects a tendency that's on the rise:
the urge to revise work that has already been shown publicly. Once
the badge of amateurs and perfectionists, this rethinking has
become for many artists an integral part of the creative process.
</P>
<P>
   Whether more choreographers are now going back to the drawing
board after opening night is hard to say, but among those who do,
many _ from Liz Lerman to Doug Varone to Mark Dendy _ cite cultural
and esthetic imperatives that were unheard of one or two
generations ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Lerman and Ann Carlson, the act of revision has almost
become an art form in itself. Others, like John Kelly and Varone,
mess with success because they find the idea of a single,
definitive version of their work too constricting. And some, like
Shapiro and Ms. Smith, see failure as a catalyst, if not a
springboard to success. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything isn't so precious to us that we have to make art
with a capital A,'' said Dendy, whose dark pageant about a gay
dancer in psychotherapy, ``Dream Analysis,'' went through several
successful iterations last year. ``There's a very intense sense of
play, and we're not afraid to go back and make changes.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dendy and his peers know, of course, that they are not the first
to embrace playfulness and change. Or the first to tailor their
work to fit new casts and venues. Or even the first to cope with
austere budgets, tight deadlines and the pressure to create
something new each season. In dance, these are givens. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, every performance of every dance is a revision; the
nature of the art form makes it so. ``Dance only exists on the
body, when it's happening,'' said Eliot Feld, whose troupe, Ballet
Tech, returns to the Joyce Theater on April 6 for a five-week
season. ``There really is no dance until it's performed, so our
discourse with ourselves is necessarily a public one.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The direction of this discourse shifted, though, with the advent
of post-modern dance in the 1960s, as Trisha Brown and others began
to equate form and content. The upshot, three decades later, is a
partial demystification of dance making.
</P>
<P>
   The old Romantic notion of the artist as a solitary figure
touched by a divine spark has given way to a sense that creative
work relies as much on craft and conscious choices as it does on
sudden insights. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This emphasis on process could make a relic of the dance canon.
If a choreographer's work is never done, critics, peers and the
public may have a hard time agreeing on its significance. By
contrast, there was a positive consensus about Martha Graham's
``Appalachian Spring,'' George Balanchine's ``Agon'' and Alvin
Ailey's ``Revelations'' when they were first performed. But many
choreographers have grown wary of such categorical truths. It's the
journey that thrills them, not the destination. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to fix and change until there isn't anything more to
learn from it,'' said Ms. Lerman, who showed her latest
work-in-progress, ``Hallelujah,'' this past Friday at the Lisner
Auditorium in Washington. ``Once I reach that point, of course, the
work tends to fall out of the repertory rather quickly.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even harder to pin down is Varone's ``Aperture.'' Just as light
can behave as a wave one moment and a particle the next, this 1994
trio has come to lead a dual existence. Varone initially set it to
a piano etude by Shubert, and sometimes he still stages it that
way. But in an effort to show how music can shape our perception of
movement, he often substitutes a different score: Janis Joplin's
gravelly rendition of Gershwin's ``Summertime.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell the dancers not to change the movement or the intent,''
said Varone, who presented the Joplin version last month at the
World Financial Center's Winter Garden. ``What the dancers perform
is the purity of the Shubert, but what the audience sees is the
grit of the Joplin.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Premieres are seldom the best indication of what is happening in
a dance, said David White, executive director of Dance Theater
Workshop in Manhattan. ``Some works are way stations,'' he
explained. ``The artist may be taking chances on a new set of rules
and approaches that she doesn't have a firm handle on yet. Those
works can be problematic, and they may not be worth revisiting. But
what I'm interested in is what comes next. Did it take her
somewhere new?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
