<HEADER>
A3325 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     03-17 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK IN RIGHT, BUHNER FIELDS SOME TOUGH REALIZATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ Maybe Jay Buhner thought this would be the fun
part.
</P>
<P>
   After beating the clock in his comeback from elbow surgery in
September, after a grueling winter of successful rehab and
countless lectures from Mariner doctors, coaches and friends about
how Buhner must take it slowly, maybe he thought his improbably
quick return to right field would make everything feel all right
again.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Buhner started in right field for the Mariners in their
6-3 Cactus League win over the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, an important bit of order was restored to the M's, who
besides a number of other woes last season desperately missed their
ringleader right fielder in 90 of 162 games. Then came the ``Tommy
John'' surgery that was supposed to sideline Buhner for the early
months of the 1999 season, too.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, though, was as much a reality check for Buhner as an
affirmation of his rightful place in the universe. Right field, the
place he calls his home, felt a little cold, a little strange. If
he was looking for instant confirmation that his place in the
constellation of big-time baseball players was safely fixed, Buhner
came out a little leery.
</P>
<P>
   After he trotted out to right, after he tamped down the plush
green grass with his cleats, after he heard cheers from Buhner
Boneyard fans sitting on the berm behind the right-field wall at
the Mariners' spring training park, Buhner heard a voice in his
head.
</P>
<P>
   The voice was talking about some wacky and unfamiliar stuff,
like: Take it slow. Don't do anything stupid. Be smart.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner's private mantra made him realize that for all the hard
work he had put in just to make it back this far, this fast, the
toughest part is just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   A player who notched his stardom by playing with reckless
abandon must play with caution, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not out of the woods yet. My goal is to be out there in
right field on opening day. Until I'm out there, realistically, I'm
not where I need to be. Just got to be smart. Don't do anything
stupid. Keep working. Build my arm strength up. But I can't say
it's over yet.''
</P>
<P>
   No one expected Buhner back this fast, although he has his
reasons _ not the least of which is that he is in the last year of
his contract.
</P>
<P>
   The team owns an option for 2000, and Buhner, who said he felt
terrible not being able to earn his money last season, wants to
prove he will be a bargain for the M's, who can re-sign him for
$6.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, if Buhner had a longer deal, or if the M's were certain
to pick up his 2000 option, he might not be trying quite so hard to
play most if not all of the 1999 season in right field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't jeopardize my team'' by doing something he wasn't
ready to do, Buhner said. But he does have a desire to reclaim his
career, to make sure he goes out on his own terms.
</P>
<P>
   But now his right arm, the one with the new tendon in the elbow,
must be dealt with carefully _ tough for a man whose right arm, as
much as his bat, defines him as one of the game's best outfielders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my pride and joy. I mean, I'm known for my arm. You
read a lot of the baseball cards. On the back, it says: Known for
his strong, cannon-like arm. I've made a name, no doubt about it,
for throwing,'' Buhner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to toot my own horn, but I don't get the opportunity
to throw out as many guys anymore because a lot of guys don't want
to test me. But that might change this year. I've got to be
prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Buhner seemed sobered by the test he got during his
five innings in right field. In the top of the third, Cubs third
baseman Gary Gaetti sliced the ball down the right-field line,
giving Buhner a chance to see how he would react. Buhner could not
resist doing a little more than he should have, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the one ball down the line. I got a good jump on it,
good angle and I saw (second baseman Carlos Guillen) but he seemed
like he was about 10 feet away from me,'' Buhner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something told me to throw it to him, and then when I let go
of it, I threw it to (first baseman) Butch (Huskey), who was
halfway to home plate, just to kind of give it a test. That's when
I came into the dugout and said, `Easier said than done.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners will try to slow Buhner down some. He will DH
Wednesday, have a day off Thursday, head back to right field on
Friday, have another day off Saturday, then switch between right
and left fields for the rest of spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, on the same day Buhner took back right field for the
Mariners, there was news out of Chicago that 1998 National League
Rookie of the Year Kerry Wood would likely miss this entire season
due to a tear in his elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner, a fellow Texan, was particularly sympathetic to what
lies ahead for Wood. When Buhner got to first base Tuesday on a
fielding error, he exchanged words with Cubs first baseman Mark
Grace about Chicago's brilliant young power pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Gracie, just do me a favor, just make sure that every
day you talk to the kid (Wood) and make him feel like he's part of
the team, because for me that was the hardest thing. When you're
away from the team, you're not able to go out and perform. That's a
lost feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Buhner took a huge step toward making sure he isn't
lost anymore. It was worth the hard work and the rush, even if this
hellion of a ballplayer knows he must take it slowly _ for now,
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
