<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3326 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHTICK-DANCE-2NDTAKE-     03-17 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHTICK-DANCE-2NDTAKE-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: somewhere new?''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Ms. Lerman, one key to making good dances is getting useful
feedback, a commodity she has found to be in short supply. So
several years ago she devised a structured way for talking about
creative work, which she calls the ``critical response process.''
Speaking by phone from her studio in Takoma Park, Md., she said it
typically entails having a choreographer sit down with a dozen or
more people (usually peers, sometimes audience members, but seldom
reviewers) who saw her work the night before.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of an hour, a moderator leads them through a
series of seven increasingly frank exchanges, moving from positive
reactions to neutral questions to charged opinions. In the final
stages, which are optional, the discussion turns to thematic issues
(``Hallelujah,'' the subject of such a forum yesterday, deals with
darkness, faith and pets) and ways to make revisions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The aim is not feel-good therapy or choreography by consensus
but a higher level of critical discourse, Ms. Lerman said. And the
process is not limited to dance. Visual-art curators at the Walker
Art Center in Minneapolis and actors at the New York Theater
Workshop have given ``critical response'' a try. ``With good
feedback, you want to get right back to work in the studio,'' she
said, explaining its appeal. ``With bad feedback, you just lie in
bed for three days.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro didn't have three days. But he had two, and he wasn't
inclined to waste them. The morning after his preview last October,
he sat alone in his studio and jotted down some of the thoughts
that ran through his mind the night before: ``I'm sorry. I can do
this. If you'll just give me a second chance.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, Shapiro, 41, and Ms. Smith, 46, make dances together
and share the choreographer's credit. Since starting their
eight-member troupe in 1987, they have come to be known for their
zany brand of social commentary. Relying on iconic props and
physical abandon, they have often explored domestic dysfunction,
beginning with ``George and Betty's House'' and ``Family.'' Lately
their attention has turned to language and religion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Our work evolves in stages,'' said Shapiro. ``We take on very
complex ideas and wrestle with them over time; it can take two or
three years. We've always done it that way, but we didn't realize
until recently that it was our process. We just thought we didn't
get the work done on time.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He knew his self-deprecating humor wouldn't save him last fall.
``Shtick'' already had enough punch lines, he said. What it lacked
was a countervailing sense of vulnerability. Then it occurred to
him that his list of apologies might serve as a monologue that made
the risk of failure palpable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The preview was a horrible experience,'' he said. ``But then I
realized it was inextricable from the character of the piece,
which, after all, was about a comedian in the Catskills trying to
win over the audience.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That epiphany underscores the couple's chief difference from
Alwin Nikolais and Murray Louis, who employed them as soloists from
1978 to 1985. Essentially, they take Nikolais' maxim _ ``Dance is
about motion, not emotion'' _ and turn it on its head. ``We start
with emotion,'' said Ms. Smith. '`The dance follows.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many choreographers would not have made the effort to fix
``Shtick.'' ``If a ballet doesn't work, it just doesn't work, and
you move on,'' said Feld. Shapiro's instincts also contradicted the
legendary dance instructor Bessie Schonberg, who died in 1997 at
the age of 90. ``Bessie always said, `Don't go back; do another,'''
he said. ``It's good advice, but sometimes you can't do another.
You've fallen into something that's really feeding you.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Shtick,'' which he and Ms. Smith see as a character study for
a larger dance still to come, isn't finished yet. Nor is it the
only dance on the program to undergo such a public transformation.
``Notes From a Seance,'' a Victorian-style tale about a religious
charlatan and a sham scientist, has also appeared in many
incarnations. (Like ``Shtick,'' it has music composed by Scott
Killian.)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Notes'' first appeared at the Joyce in 1997, as a short
romantic duet called ``Piano.'' Last year at Dance Theater
Workshop, it returned as ``Piano _ a Melodrama,'' a 75-minute romp
about the Russian mystic Helena Blavatsky, who invented theosophy.
</P>
<P>
   For the latest version, Shapiro and Ms. Smith have trimmed 20
minutes by cutting and overlapping several passages, shuffled
casting for some of the solos and added new visual elements. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The original duet doesn't survive, but it got us here,'' said
Ms. Smith. ``Without it, I never would have had the courage to
choreograph to Beethoven's `Moonlight Sonata.''' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such breakthroughs are the couple's primary reason for revising.
``In dance you can endlessly tinker, but I don't find it that
productive,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not just tweaking,'' added Shapiro, in what could serve
as a manifesto for many choreographers today. ``We're looking for
ways to get serious ideas across as they become increasingly clear
to us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
