<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3327 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SANTA-FE-MUSIC-2TAKES     03-17 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANTA-FE-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAMBER MUSIC, TRADITIONAL ARTS, VIRTUAL SANTA FE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Lawrence B. Johnson is the music critic of The Detroit News.  
 By LAWRENCE B. JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What began as a New York appearance by performers of the Santa
Fe Chamber Music Festival has evolved into a virtual weekend in the
historic capital of New Mexico: a three-day musical and cultural
holiday, beginning on Thursday, mostly within the confines of the
Metropolitan Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   And as befits Santa Fe, where controversy flows back through
history to the city's founding in 1610, the music is likely to be
accompanied by a note of political discord.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Wilson, the author of the provocative book ``The Myth of
Santa Fe,'' will lecture on the emergence of the cultural profile
that provides the city with its chief industry: tourism. David
Warren, a Pueblo Indian and retired deputy director of the National
Museum of the American Indian at the Smithsonian Institution, will
discuss the Met's current exhibition of Indian art, ``Native
Paths.''
</P>
<P>
   Another hot topic: chili. Betty Fussell, a food historian, will
retrace the converging influences of the Spanish and American
Indian diets that shaped Santa Fe cuisine. Robert Morean, the owner
of the Santacafe, and his chef, David Sellars, will bring a taste
of the real thing, preparing an appetizer and main course for
diners at the Mark Hotel, near the Met, on Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of serving up Santa Fe whole came to Marc Neikrug, the
artistic director of the chamber music festival, as he pondered the
fact that neither his group nor its musical fare bore the unique
stamp of their Southwestern locale.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do I make it Santa Fe instead of seven musicians from New
York coming back to play at the Met Museum?'' he said he had asked
himself, referring to the likes of the pianist Max Levinson, the
violist Cynthia Phelps and the cellist Peter Wiley. ``Well, maybe
we aren't all from New York, but you see the problem. Actually,
it's the same problem everywhere. Travel around Europe, and see
who's performing, and you'll find that 80 percent of the people who
play concerts in the world live within five blocks of each other on
the Upper West Side.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the conventional chamber music repertory offered no
particular connection to Santa Fe, Neikrug said, he chose works for
the Met concerts on Friday and Saturday that at least engaged
ethnic issues: Brahms' G minor Piano Quartet, with its touches of
Gypsy music; Hebrew songs by Ravel; the Third String Quartet of
Viktor Ullmann, an Austrian Jew who perished in the Nazi
concentration camp at Terezin, and a collection of Arabic songs
composed by the young Egyptian baritone Kamel Boutros, who will
sing them.
</P>
<P>
   In Wilson's view, the absence of Southwestern and American music
from Neikrug's programming is not an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of the whole range of activities in a given cultural
setting,'' he said, ``only a small proportion become public symbols
of ethnic identity: usually cuisine, often architecture, sometimes
music. New Orleans, for example, brings to mind the French Quarter,
certainly the cuisine, jazz and zydeco music.
</P>
<P>
   ``But music in Santa Fe, a distant outpost in the period of the
Spanish Baroque, largely consisted of a guitar and a fiddle playing
dance music. Its history is one of struggle and defending against
raids by Comanches and Apaches. It was a culture of poverty. The
music was folkloric.''
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, Wilson said, European-style classical music has
become an expression of modern Santa Fe. The summerlong chamber
music festival has presented 26 seasons; the highly successful
Santa Fe Opera has filled summer nights since its founding in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all its adobe appearance, Santa Fe is a very modern city
whose citizens watch television and use the Internet,'' Wilson
added. ``A component of its population are followers of classical
music.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Neikrug said, he wanted to bring a vivid sense of Santa
Fe to the Met. ``I was left with the same question: How can I
recreate as much of the Santa Fe experience as humanly possible
without the audience being there physically.''
</P>
<P>
   For the answer, Neikrug, who was born in New York but lives in
Santa Fe, turned to two fellow townsfolk, Wilson, an Iowa native
educated at Yale University and the University of New Mexico, and
Warren, who was born in the Santa Clara Pueblo, near Santa Fe, and
earned a doctorate in Latin American colonial history at the
University of New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Warren said that his first impulse was to focus on Pueblo arts
but that the richness of the Met's ``Native Paths'' exhibition
prompted him to present a wider perspective on American Indian
crafts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to cause people to look at Native American art in
slightly different ways than they might,'' he said. ``For one
thing, it's important to remember that the objects that the public
in general regards as art were actually created for specific
purposes, whether practical or ceremonial. The concept of esthetics
isn't really a part of Native American culture.''
</P>
<P>
   And on that point rests a contemporary hot button. From the
viewpoint of American Indians, Warren said, the wealth of material
accumulated in collections like ``Native Paths'' represents an
ancient patrimony. And increasing public consciousness of that
view, reflected in the return of many items to Indians' hands, has
stimulated what Warren called a cultural renaissance in American
Indian society.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just as true of the Pueblos as it is of other tribes
throughout America,'' he said. ``While it's quite important in
principle that cultural and intellectual material be restored, it
also has a direct bearing on contemporary cultural and artistic
development. This is unprecedented, and the effects are yet to be
fully appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks to the return of classical pieces, a revitalization of
traditional arts is occurring that may not be immediately evident
to the public. But there is a new force at hand, which is the
Native American sense of responsibility to its own traditions. It's
almost a paradox. The more rapid and complex and technological the
world we enter, the deeper grows the sense of tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Warren added, American Indians in general _ more than 500
tribes across the country _ are not all clamoring to recover the
objects of their patrimony now held in museums or private
collections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many tribes have said, for whatever reason, that they do not
need to have them returned,'' he explained. ``They are only
concerned that the objects are properly cared for and to help the
public gain a better understanding of the things they see. It's
really a new relationship between the tribes and the museums, a
mutual sense of responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, in his book, grapples with a different sort of borrowing
from American Indian heritage: the romantic image.
</P>
<P>
   ``Santa Fe is an El Dorado, an exotic outpost glowing in the
sunset, a tourist magnet that has enjoyed a boom since the 1980s,''
he said. ``And look what the mystique of Santa Fe is based on:
Pueblo and Spanish culture. Yet those are the people of Santa Fe in
need. It's not legitimate to use those icons as advertising images
to attract people, then not pay attention to the people being
displaced by gentrification and a real-estate boom.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracking the community's course from its founding by Pedro de
Peralta as a Spanish territorial capital, Wilson's critical history
underscores Santa Fe's character as a melting pot and analyzes the
forces that have contributed to what he portrays as a conflicted
and ultimately mythic self-image.
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico was rejected in its bid for statehood several times
before it was admitted to the Union in 1912, along with Arizona. At
one point, Congress contemplated lumping the two territories
together as a single new state, Montezuma.
</P>
<P>
   Predominantly white America took a dim view of the predominantly
Mexican and Indian mix of New Mexico, Wilson writes. Thus occurred
a historic split in personality, as the state, holding out Santa Fe
as its crown jewel, offered the look and feel of Anystate, U.S.A.,
to Congress while selling its Western exoticism to tourists.
</P>
<P>
   In 1920, Santa Fe consolidated its bid for tourism by adopting
what Wilson calls a myth that prefigured the Disneyland ideal: from
that time forward, the entire community (or at least 90 percent of
it) would present the same adobe facade to the world.
</P>
<P>
   Or rather, stucco mixed with adobe pigment. But it would be one
face, one lure, one myth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do see that as symbolic of the larger problem, but I also
have to say I feel a certain degree of optimism about the city,''
Wilson said. ``I live there. I see its remarkable cultural
vitality: the museums, restaurants, bookstores, opera, chamber
music, the walking zones, the artist colony. And I think we're
starting to see some understanding among our political leaders that
they need to take an active role in counteracting displacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Above all, I'm not trashing tourists and amenity migrants,''
he said, defining the latter as ``people who move to nice places
like Aspen, Colo., Santa Barbara, Calif., and Santa Fe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us take our turn at being a tourist,'' he said. ``I'd
just like to see people be more aware of the economic impact we can
have, and not accept the stereotype.''
</P>
<P>
   Neikrug, the chamber music festival director, who has trimmed
his role to that of cultural partner for this Santa Fe immersion,
said: ``I'd like to take something like this everywhere we tour.
Everyone is looking for a broader experience. That's my goal with
programming for the Santa Fe Chamber Music Festival, to offer
dimensions beyond great music played well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
