<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3329 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      03-17 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY AFFAIR: DAVID BELL DRAWS ON PRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ There's a new nickname in the Mariners clubhouse
this spring. Pitching coach Stan Williams coined it for infielder
David Bell. It's ``Gus,'' and Bell loves it.
</P>
<P>
   Gus Bell was David's grandfather and his hero. Buddy Bell is
David's father and best friend. The Bells are one of only two
families _ the Boones are the other _ with three generations of big
leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   Williams pitched against Gus in the '50s and '60s, a fact not
lost on David, who has asked Williams for his memories.
</P>
<P>
   This year, for the first time in his major league career, Bell
is wearing No. 25, just like Gus and Buddy.
</P>
<P>
   Woody Woodward, the man who traded for David Bell last August,
roomed with Gus on the Milwaukee Braves in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   ``He couldn't have been a better guy,'' said Woodward, M's vice
president of baseball operations. ``He was all business, a real
professional. I can see things in David that remind me of Gus,
because he's very business-like on the field. He knows how to play
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Aug. 31, the day rosters froze for postseason play, the
Cleveland Indians traded Bell for second baseman Joey Cora, who had
struggled in '98, had no future with the Mariners and, Woodward
thought, had no trade value.
</P>
<P>
   Cora has retired. Bell has a two-year contract with Seattle. It
might turn out to be one of Woodward's simplest and best moves.
Bell can play anywhere in the infield and has impressed the M's
this spring with his glove and bat. He is perhaps the best example
of the club's recent emphasis on adding depth and versatility.
</P>
<P>
   The trade marked the second time Cleveland dealt Bell for
late-season help. He was shipped to St. Louis in July 1995 and
returned to Cleveland on waivers last April. He started at second
base for much of the year, ranking third in the league defensively
and batting .261 with 10 homers.
</P>
<P>
   Bell is grateful to the Indians simply for drafting him. A
160-pound high school third baseman in Cincinnati, he was a good
fielder but only a contact hitter, and he was surprised when the
Indians took him in the seventh round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never knew I'd hit a professional home run when I first
signed,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   He hit his first homer in his second pro season and cherishes
the memory. Gus and Buddy drove from Ohio to Myrtle Beach, S.C.,
where Bell's Columbus, Ga., team was playing. He wanted to make
them proud, and did. The kid was on his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``They knew the odds against a major league career,'' Bell said.
``They didn't make any predictions, because if I didn't make it,
they didn't want me any more disappointed than I already would be.
I think they thought I would, but they didn't tell me that. It was
more just encouragement. They never said anything negative.''
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Bell tried not to push his sons into baseball. In fact,
says Bell, a former All-Star who played for four teams from
1972-89, sometimes he wishes his boys hadn't taken up the family
business, which he knows can be so tough.
</P>
<P>
   But all three have; besides David, son Mike is in the New York
Mets system, and Rick is with the Los Angeles Dodgers. None was
more passionate about the game than David, who was born the year
Buddy made the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would buy him toys, but he wouldn't play with anything but
a ball and bat,'' said David's mother, Gloria. ``Big Wheels,
trucks, blocks _ forget it. They would just sit there and go to
waste until Michael came along.''
</P>
<P>
   When David was 6, Buddy started taking him on road trips. By the
time he was a teenager, David had seen every park in the AL, and
his memories of each remain vivid.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first trip was to Seattle and Minnesota,'' he said. ``The
Kingdome was the first dome I'd ever been in, and I thought it was
the greatest place in the world. I'd probably get a few arguments
now, but I thought it was a huge amusement park. What more could
you want?''
</P>
<P>
   For David, it was more than fun and games. He studied his Gold
Glove dad in the field, taking special note of how quickly he
released the ball. That lesson carries over today: Bell uses a
glove with almost no pocket so he can throw the ball the instant he
receives it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the best I ever saw,'' David said of Buddy. ``I try to
be as good as him, but I don't think I'll ever be that good.''
</P>
<P>
   An adoring son, David never went to bed without knowing how
Buddy had done that night. A loving father, Buddy was the
disciplinarian but never let an argument fester overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Now, David and Buddy talk several times a week, and only
sometimes about baseball. It is a friendship, David said, built on
endless parental support and the realization he's so much like his
dad, both on and off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Funny how that works. Buddy takes after his father, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``David was having a problem with one of his coaches in
school,'' said Buddy, now minor league field coordinator for the
Cincinnati Reds. ``I'd just had enough of it. My dad told me, if
you don't go up there and support your son, who's going to? That
always made a lot of sense to me. He's never going to know what it
means to be loyal and supportive unless you show him the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Buddy's playing career lasted through David's junior year in
high school, and it was Gus who took his place at David's games.
David had a similarly close relationship with Gus as he did with
Buddy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my grandpa could be more the hero, because everything he
did was positive,'' David said. ``He could hang out with us. We did
a lot together. He pretty much lived for us playing the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Gus, who played 15 major league seasons, had one rule: no
negativity allowed. David smiles when he thinks of how his
grandfather could find the good in anything he'd done. In a game
where every hitter fails most of the time, such encouragement was
invaluable.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never said one negative thing to me my whole life,'' David
said. ``And in baseball, that's so important. It was always
encouragement, everything was positive. He played a huge part in me
getting to the big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Gus Bell lived just long enough to see his grandson's dream come
true. David was the last player added to Cleveland's opening day
roster in 1995, making the team because of an injury to Sandy
Alomar. Buddy was an Indians coach.
</P>
<P>
   The team was in Detroit when Gus, 66, suffered a heart attack.
David left the team for two days and saw his grandfather, who was
not well but was able to talk, and knew David had played in the
majors. Later that week, David Russell ``Gus'' Bell died.
</P>
<P>
   David batted only twice for the Indians that year, and he didn't
even get a hit. But no two at-bats could have meant more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to bring him back or anything, but it was a big
deal to me, because he was there for me all along,'' Bell said.
``It seemed like it was just as important to him as it was to me. I
just felt like I'd made him happy, made him proud.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
