<HEADER>
A3330 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIEGO-RIVERA-ART-2TAK     03-17 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIEGO-RIVERA-ART-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A CHAMELEON OF MODERNISM, YEARS OF GROPING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ For a moment, picture the Mexican muralist Diego
Rivera as he was in 1907: obscure, a shy, virginal art student
boarding a Spanish steamer, the Alfonso XIII, and heading for the
port of La Coruna in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   He had a small pension to study abroad from the governor of
Veracruz, who among other things, we have learned since then, was
involved in the slave trade, though about that matter Rivera was
either oblivious or unconcerned, probably both. He was just focused
on a career.
</P>
<P>
   Picasso and Braque had invented Cubism in France, but at that
point Rivera's knowledge of modern art, gleaned from art school in
Mexico, was second-hand Spanish Symbolism. Later Rivera remembered
himself, ``as if I were watching from somewhere in space, outside
myself, a 20-year-old dolt, so vain, his face covered with youthful
pimples, wishing to be the owner of the universe, like all other
snotty youths of his generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Standing at midnight on the very bow of the Alfonso XIII,
watching the ship break the seas to leave behind a wake of lace,
and declaiming some fragments from Zarathustra at the top of his
voice _ that is the most deplorable and sublimely pathetic thing I
have ever known. That was me.''
</P>
<P>
   Or it was as he wished us to think he had been, because, after
all, we can never entirely trust Rivera's own subsequent accounts,
which were wild, self-aggrandizing fantasies, even when they were
ostensibly self-mocking. The more charmingly ridiculous he could
make himself seem as a young man, the more remarkable we might
believe his transformation to be. Even so, the basic description is
plausible: the gifted yokel on a voyage of self-discovery.
</P>
<P>
   The big Diego Rivera retrospective, organized by the Cleveland
Museum of Art with the Consejo Nacional para la Cultura y las Artes
and the Instituto Nacional de Bellas Artes in Mexico City, leans
particularly on these early years, before Rivera returned from
Europe to Mexico and started painting the murals for which he
rightly became most famous. The point: that the murals have
obscured the value of his previous work.
</P>
<P>
   And certainly they have, though never entirely. His pictures
from Europe have always been more or less familiar. They are true
tours-de-force of youthful arrogance and facile ambition,
chameleonlike: Rivera, once settled in Europe, seems to have made
variations on almost all the new art he came across _Gauguin,
Pissarro and, of course, Picasso.
</P>
<P>
   The first half of the exhibition looks virtually like a group
show, Rivera testing out one style after another, with an alarming,
lapidary ease.
</P>
<P>
   There's his watercolor of a tree a la Mondrian, for example, and
his ``Catalan Landscape,'' after Seurat. His fine ``View of
Toledo,'' a variation on El Greco in the blocky mode of Braque's
Estaque pictures, casts the city in an engulfing pink light, its
cathedral rising on a granite promontory above the deep gorge of
the Tagus river.
</P>
<P>
   His portrait of Adolfo Best Maugard nods toward Spanish
salonists like Zuloaga (the figure's a fop in top coat and leather
gloves, his body stretched and twisted like taffy), but the style
is closest now to Robert Delaunay.
</P>
<P>
   And so on. After finally making his reputation among the Cubists
in Paris, Rivera abandoned that style as well to become, like
Picasso, a Neo-Classicist in the manner of Ingres, having realized,
no doubt, that the winds of fashion had shifted after World War I.
It's not meant to diminish Rivera's talent to say that he was
sensitive to fashion and the marketplace. An artist can be
calculating and affecting at the same time, a condition that
describes Rivera throughout most of his career.
</P>
<P>
   The formal connections between his early pictures and his murals
have always been fairly clear. Beginning in the 1920s, back in
Mexico, Rivera adapted European modernism to a new kind of public
art. The faceting and collapsing of three-dimensional form and its
dispersal across the picture plane, the free adaptation of scale
and the general mechanistic symbolism: all these aspects of Cubism
served Rivera's purposes.
</P>
<P>
   He became more successful than Picasso at transforming Cubism
from easel scale to mural scale because he mixed Cubism with other
art _ with what he had learned from the frescos of Giotto, for
example, and above all with the giant decorative schemes at ancient
Mexican ruins. These works gave him not only native source material
but also an essential abstract architecture for the organization of
vast, multiscene compositions.
</P>
<P>
   His new art fused ancient and modern ideas to match Mexico's
post-colonial self-image, and in a way that also conveyed a
particular hieratic solemnity and spiritual weight. The murals were
political pronunciamientos, expressed with the force of conviction,
which came across as a form of faith.
</P>
<P>
   By stressing the early work, the exhibition can't be said really
to reinvent Rivera for us, though it does clarify what was good
about him when he was young: his energy, elegance and coloristic
subtlety, above all. Shows justify themselves by emphasizing some
new discovery or twist on history, and maybe in Rivera's case there
is a particular virtue in highlighting his temporary role as a
Cubist in Paris because it gives his legacy, and by association,
Mexican art, a different slant or prestige.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But it is for the murals that he will always be best known
because they made him a national artist and turned him into perhaps
the only painter of the century, Picasso aside, whose fame allowed
him to be a kind of global diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   He actually wanted to be an artist for the whole of the
Americas, if that were possible. He saw the potential of creating
an American art celebrating American engineering, which he felt was
the truest indigenous attribute. ``American engineering,'' he once
said, ``is the real artistic expression of the genius of this part
of the world,'' and by this part of the world he meant the
continent, including the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But at this task he was not successful. He precipitated the
infamous debacle at Rockefeller Center, where his mural was
destroyed after he refused to remove a portrait of Lenin in it.
Another mural, commissioned by Edsel Ford (a tribute to, among
other things, American engineering), was a public-relations fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   Laid-off automobile workers in Depression-era Detroit did not
embrace the idea that a painter, especially a foreign painter,
never mind that he was a Communist, had been paid $10,000 for a
picture extolling the virtues of modern industry.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years Rivera had his successes in the United States,
but his general failure to achieve here what he had achieved in
Mexico evidently stung him until his death, in 1957, at 71. The
hack work he churned out during his last decades (a surprising
amount of it is in the show) conveyed a cynicism perhaps born of
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   He had basically given up mural painting by the 40s. He made
money by becoming portraitist-of-choice to rich Mexicans and
tourists from the United States. The last decade of his life
produced the occasional portrait like the exquisite one in this
show of Enriqueta Davila, austere and luminous, but mostly these
were years in decline.
</P>
<P>
   He had been right about the United States in at least one
important respect: he recognized that engineering was close to the
heart of our identity _ engineering but not painting. There are, it
is remarkable to realize, no great paintings with which we identify
as a nation, the way Mexicans identify with Rivera's murals, or for
that matter Italians with Michelangelo or Titian. aybe we're too
much enamored of the free market or too diverse culturally.
</P>
<P>
   But on the other hand, we link ourselves as a country with feats
of engineering, with the Hoover Dam and the Brooklyn Bridge and
even with Wright's Guggenheim Museum. They seem closest to the
pragmatic core of our national psyche.
</P>
<P>
   Probably because we have no equivalent to his art, we tend to
underestimate Rivera's achievement. One might say that the
circularity of his career mirrored the evolution of a century in
which cultural diversity yielded to an international style,
modernism, only to give way to a renewed respect for diversity.
</P>
<P>
   A provincial, Rivera made himself into a European modernist in
order to become a local artist again, but of course of a different
kind: modern Mexico could envision itself through his imagination,
as we, in turn, have come to see a nation through him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
