<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3332 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUGIMOTO-ART-ANTIQUES     03-17 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUGIMOTO-ART-ANTIQUES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTOS AND DECOR FIND INSPIRATION IN JAPANESE ARTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RITA REIF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most people view the things they collect as a diversion from
what they do for a living. But for the Japanese photographer
Hiroshi Sugimoto, the traditional Japanese art he collects is
absolutely essential to the art he creates: compelling mages of
seascapes, waxworks, life-size Buddhas and the gilded interiors of
motion picture palaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to set my own standards of quality for my
photographs by comparing them with the art I collect,'' said
Sugimoto, 51. He also seeks to achieve in his work the same level
of spirituality that he finds in the medieval Japanese paintings,
plaques and calligraphies that he owns.
</P>
<P>
   While Sugimoto's photographs are exhibited widely, the art he
collects is rarely displayed, even in his homes in Tokyo and New
York. (He has divided his time between the cities since 1971.)
</P>
<P>
   Now he has lent three pieces to ``Crosscurrents: Masterpieces of
East Asian Art from New York Private Collections,'' an exhibition
that opens on Wednesday and remains through July 11 at the Japan
Society Gallery in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Organized with the Brooklyn Museum of Art by Amy G. Poster, a
pan-Asian scholar who heads the museum's Asian Art Department, the
show, of 71 objects from 32 collections, explores dominant themes
in Japanese, Chinese and Korean art: the sacred and ritualistic,
the literati tradition, the tea ceremony and nature. The show
demonstrates how each of the three cultures has transformed those
themes.
</P>
<P>
   Initiated a year ago by Alexandra Munroe when she became the
director of the Japan Society Gallery, the exhibition consists of
objects from collectors in the New York metropolitan region and was
timed to open on the eve of the International Asian Art Fair, a
central event in Asian art week in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York has become the undisputed world center for the
collecting and connoisseurship of Asian art,'' Ms. Munroe said.
``This is the first comprehensive survey of New York's collections
of East Asian art.''
</P>
<P>
   Buddhism is the most prevalent theme in sacred and ritual art in
these countries; thus the various works on view have so many
similarities that their national origins are difficult to identify.
</P>
<P>
   Each of Sugimoto's objects expresses Buddhism distinctively. A
rare 15th-century scroll painting mixes ancient Buddhist and Shinto
images: a deer with noble bearing, acting as a messenger of the
gods, is depicted descending from heaven on a cloud under images of
a golden disk and Buddhist deities as the moon rises in the
background against low hills, flowering trees and a darkened sky.
</P>
<P>
   A palm-size painted disk from the 13th century is a study of a
bodhisattva, a disciple of Buddha, seated cross-legged on a
flowering lotus, holding a book in the left hand, a sword in the
right. The image, rendered in circles within circles, illustrates a
Buddhist teaching: wisdom grows from the muddy earth to blossom in
the light of Buddhist revelation.
</P>
<P>
   And an early 13th-century calligraphy of a poem written by an
aging Buddhist monk, Myoe Koben, conveys, in visionary language and
rivulets of ink, his distress as he dreams about a Zen master
lusting after a young woman, or possibly a boy.
</P>
<P>
   The calligraphy is Sugimoto's most recent acquisition and
currently the object he most appreciates. ``He is one of my
favorite poets in all Japanese history and one of the rare
spiritual beings among Buddhist poets,'' he said of Myoe Koben.
``They call him the Japanese St. Francis, and as a 20th-century man
I am trying in my work to deal as he did with nature and the
spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Artworks excite him most when they are new, Sugimoto said. But
he sometimes loses interest quickly, so he tries to live with
pieces before making any purchase final. ``I hang the most recent
purchase in my room and try to spend as much time as I can with it
for a few days to make sure that the impact remains for more than a
night,'' he added. ``It's like a love affair.''
</P>
<P>
   Sugimoto's collection is small: at most, 30 works. And unlike
wealthy Westerners who display their objects together in lavish
settings, he shows his pieces in the austere Japanese style,
preferably one at a time. ``Isn't it more sophisticated if you
focus instead on one object appropriate to the day?''he said. ``Who
needs 100?
</P>
<P>
   ``The art depends on whom you are inviting, the weather, the
season, the food being served,'' he added. ``And I keep a record of
what has been shown and to whom, so that I do not duplicate
anything. Guests get to see different artworks. It's a multimedia
performance, especially when there is a moon viewing. Without this
stimulation, I could not exist as an artist.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Munroe discovered what Sugimoto was talking when she visited
his Tokyo apartment last July. ``The moon rose in the early
evening, and his terrace became a moon-viewing platform,'' she
said. ``Looking at art in that kind of setting when the moon comes
to visit is a highly refined spiritual experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
