<HEADER>
A3333 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-RECKLESS-2TAKES-$A     03-17 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-RECKLESS-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNGER MAN, BOSS' WIFE: IT'S WORTH A SEQUEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Jill Gerston's most recent article for Arts and Leisure was about
the A&AMP;E series ``Biography.''  
 By JILL GERSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A successful middle-aged management consultant in a stale
marriage has a torrid affair with a sexy young surgeon, wreaking
wicked fun and tumult all around.
</P>
<P>
   It is the sort of May-December romance that Hollywood typically
casts with an aging male actor and a dewy-eyed actress young enough
to be his daughter. Think Harrison Ford and Anne Heche, Warren
Beatty and Halle Berry, Woody Allen and Elisabeth Shue. But when
seen through the lens of British television, the age gap is given a
fresh twist, along with sardonic dialogue, flawed characters, a
complicated plot and love scenes that are more discreetly sensual
than voyeuristically explicit.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the case with ``Reckless,'' a production of Granada
Television presented last year on ``Mobil Masterpiece Theater,''
starring Francesca Annis, the acclaimed British stage actress, and
Robson Green, a heartthrob from northern England who is one of
Britain's most popular television actors. Ms. Annis is 54; Green is
34.
</P>
<P>
   The six-hour series, which also features Michael Kitchen as the
arrogant, philandering husband, was a huge hit in England. When it
was broadcast here in early 1998, The New York Times critic Caryn
James called it ``a deliciously tangled story of passion,
infidelity and civilized revenge.'' ``Reckless'' was such a success
that Granada made a two-hour sequel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Masterpiece Theater'' begins rebroadcasting the original
series on PBS next Sunday night, followed by ``Reckless: The
Sequel'' on April 18.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Reckless,'' set in present-day Manchester, isn't the
sort of classic bustle-and-breeches fare that ``Masterpiece
Theater'' is known for, Rebecca Eaton, the executive producer of
the series, said it was still in keeping with the series'
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Masterpiece Theater' made its fortune on series about people
falling in love with the wrong people, which is just what happens
in `Reckless,''' she said. ``It's a modern love story that is as
high a quality as any classic.''
</P>
<P>
   The story revolves around Owen (Green), a brash young doctor who
is infatuated with Anna (Ms. Annis), an alluring businesswoman whom
he later discovers is married to his boss, Richard (Kitchen), the
pompous chief of surgery at his hospital.
</P>
<P>
   When Anna discovers that her husband is having an affair, she
takes up with Owen, setting off a conflagration of passion,
jealousy, revenge, lies and gossip. Can such mad love last? The
sequel picks up the messy love triangle a year later.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Abbott, who created ``Reckless'' and its sequel, said his
intention was to get away from the ``slow, turgid, obsessional
relationships'' previously seen on British television and to
celebrate romance for its own sake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were out to prove we could bring a love story back
to television and have some fun with it,'' said Abbott, a writer
and producer of the British series ``Cracker'' and the creator of
the detective series ``Touching Evil,'' which stars Green.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott drew on his own experience in writing ``Reckless.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea for the story came from my second marriage, to a
woman who was 10 years older,'' he said in a telephone interview
from his home in Manchester. ``I met my wife when I was 21 and she
was 31. It was a wonderful relationship, but the whole thing was
dogged by her friends, who thought there was something not right in
her going with a guy 10 years younger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People were always looking around the corner for when it would
fall apart,'' he added. ``They did that for years and years, and in
the end it doomed the relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had relished writing the sharp, cynical dialogue of
supporting characters tut-tutting the age difference between Anna
and Owen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had such fun writing Michael Kitchen's speech in the sequel
when he screams through Owen's letterbox that every time he looks
at a woman, he'll be suspect by Anna,'' he said. ``That was the sum
voice of all the cynics who plagued us.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most Hollywood films in which the age gap between older
actors and their younger leading ladies is lightly touched on, if
at all, the age difference between Anna and Owen becomes part of
the story line in ``Reckless.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Had we not acknowledged the age difference and made it a
stumbling block, I don't think the audience would have bought it
for one minute,'' said Abbott. ``We took their cynicism and aired
it through the voices of the characters.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding the perfect twosome to play Anna and Owen with passion
and intelligence, so crucial to the success of ``Reckless,'' wasn't
easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally, I saw Owen as 24 and Anna as 40, so we were
looking at actors younger than Francesca and Robson,'' Abbott
recalled. ``They were all quite disappointing. They could play the
sex and the excitement, but they couldn't capture the shock and
fear of finding yourself in love with someone so much younger or
older.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Francesca was older than quite a few actresses we had looked
at, but she was the most robustly intelligent about the whole thing
and understood every twist and turn, probably for obvious reasons
in her private life,'' he said, alluding to Ms. Annis' long
relationship with the actor Ralph Fiennes, 36. ``Once we knew we
liked her, we could go with an older actor.''
</P>
<P>
   Green, who shot to stardom in the British drama series
``Soldier, Soldier,'' playing a fun-loving private, said he had
been attracted to ``Reckless'' not only because it was ``a
full-tilt romance'' but because it offered an opportunity to shed
his cheeky lad image.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reckless'' was a device that helped change the public
perception of who I was,'' said Green, speaking from the
headquarters of his production company in Newcastle. ``Owen was a
grown-up, a romantic, a man of great integrity. `Reckless' made me
into an actor in people's eyes instead of this one character from
`Soldier, Soldier.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Annis, who agreed to do `Reckless' when the part of Owen
changed from ``toy boy'' to mature doctor, said she liked the fact
that the romance centered on ``consenting adults, professionals,
with no children involved.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't have had the feel-good factor that you do if
there were children involved,'' said the actress whom ``Masterpiece
Theater'' fans know from her role as Lillie Langtry. ``People
really loved it. I had people coming up to me in the supermarket
asking, `Is she going to go off with Owen?'''
</P>
<P>
   Why don't we see more pairings of sensual 50-year-old actresses
with roguishly charming 30-year-old actors?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm generalizing, but on the whole Europe reveres grown-up
women more than America, where they have an obsession with being
very young,'' said Ms. Annis. ``In Europe, women are considered in
their prime between 38 and 50. Catherine Deneuve _ what a lucky
young man to be paired with her!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember once talking to the head of a studio about using a
film star who was about 40 at the time, and he said she was a great
actress but was too old,'' she said. ``I asked why and he said,
`What young man would want to hold her hand?' That's the way they
look at it in Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   After ``Reckless'' became a hit, Granada wanted Abbott to write
another six episodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story was completely told as far as I was concerned,'' he
said. ``How could I better the frenzy of the first series? They
have each other, and, as everyone knows, there is no drama in
people being happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he agreed to do a two-hour sequel that finds Anna
and Owen, after living together for a year, planning to be married
within a week. The wedding announcement infuriates Richard, who
rushes back from a conference in Iceland to prevent the lovers'
walk down the aisle.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the supporting characters from the series are back _
Owen's cantankerous father, Anna's Alzheimer's-afflicted mother _
plus new ones, including Richard's uptight parents and Owen's
ex-fiancee.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott raises the emotionally charged issue of children in the
sequel (Owen wants them, Anna is resigned to not having any), which
could jeopardize a happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all reality, I think the baby thing would crop up,'' he
said. ``Had they broached the subject in the first `Reckless,' they
probably never would have gotten around to talking about marriage.
But we bring that question to the fore in the sequel.''
</P>
<P>
   Abbott, who never expected the original ``Reckless'' to be such
a smash, said he was stunned that the sequel was just as big a hit
in Britain. ``A television critic, who had once suggested about a
movie I had written that my computer be taken away from me, wrote
that in this case I deserved free drinks for life,'' he recalled.
``I obviously believe in people falling in love, age
notwithstanding.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
