<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3335 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAHAI-CARNIVAL-2TAKES     03-17 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAHAI-CARNIVAL-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEWING TO BOTH MUSICAL AND RACIAL ROOTS IN BRAZIL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALVADOR, Brazil _ In Salvador, the capital of Brazil's state of
Bahia, which has one of the richest carnival traditions in the new
world, all the connoisseurs of Bahia's Carnaval have the same thing
jotted down in their agendas: to attend the start of the Ile Aiye
parade.
</P>
<P>
   Ile Aiye (pronounced Ee-leh Eye-eh) is one of the various
carnival organizations, called blocos, that sponsor floats and
parades throughout the six-day street festival that engulfs this
city.
</P>
<P>
   But of all of them it is perhaps the purest. Its
percussion-and-voice band has refused to go pop, sticking to the
slow, stately Ijexa rhythms _ an African sort of samba associated
with the Afro-Brazilian religion of candomble. It insists on
walking through the streets rather than riding on a sound truck the
way other bands do.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike the rest of the ``blocos afro'' that followed Ile
Aiye's lead, springing into existence since the 1970s, Ile Aiye
stubbornly stresses the ``afro'' part: it still does not admit
whites, or even mixed-race Brazilians, into its organization.
</P>
<P>
   But that policy doesn't keep people of all skin tones from
visiting Ile Aiye's headquarters, a small two-story house on a
steep hill in the city's large black neighborhood called Libertade.
Inside the house recently, the group was preparing for its big
night.
</P>
<P>
   In the back room, where strips of paper hanging from the ceiling
marked it as a house of candomble, this year's young ``queen'' of
the bloco was being fitted with an elaborate headdress of silvery
fabric. In an anteroom, four women, elders of Ile Aiye, sat dressed
in the fluffy white costumes associated with the state of Bahia.
</P>
<P>
   At the appointed moment, the women filed out into the street,
throwing hominy and popcorn and flour around them. Some 150
drummers in red, white, black and yellow shirts _ the colors of Ile
Aiye _ assembled into a column in the street, with a conductor at
the head. The drummers started a slow, thick, lurching two-beat
rhythm, with the emphasis on the second beat.
</P>
<P>
   Fireworks exploded from the crest of the hill. A trumpet fanfare
sounded from the second-floor balcony of the house, and a number of
officials _ including Antonio Carlos Santos de Vovo (known simply
as Vovo), Ile Aiye's leader, and Antonio Imbassay, the mayor of
Salvador, released doves into the air. The rhythm quickened, and
then Ile Aiye set off on a 12-mile march, which ended in the center
of town six hours later.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Ile Aiye's 25 years offers a window on some of the
ambiguities of racial politics in Salvador, Brazil's oldest city.
Depending on whom you're talking to, race is either the most
overrated or underrated topic in the city, whose government is
predominantly white but whose population is 75 percent black.
</P>
<P>
   Racial discrimination is illegal, and for an outsider it's as
easy to see Salvador as a multicolored paradise of racial tolerance
as it is to notice that the darkest-skinned people live at the
bottom of the economic ladder.
</P>
<P>
   Ile Aiye's founding was an act of courage: at the time, Brazil's
military dictatorship forbade any kind of social activism or
protest. But now its policy of limiting membership to only the
darkest black Bahians seems hard to justify, at least to a North
American.
</P>
<P>
   Even Margareth Menezes, a popular singer from Bahia, has been
denied admission; she was judged not black enough. In a region with
a wide range of skin tones, only the darkest are considered black
at all.
</P>
<P>
   But Bahians, for the most part, don't see Ile Aiye's exclusion
policy as an insult; they consider its beautiful Afro-Brazilian
music acts as a sort of cultural home base that's very much needed
in the increasingly commercial atmosphere of Carnaval. The group's
music is best heard on a new disk just released on Natasha records
in Brazil, called ``Ile Aiye 25 Anos,'' only the fourth recording
the Ile Aiye has made.
</P>
<P>
   Vovo, the group's leader, talked about the history of Ile Aiye a
few days after the march in the Bahian vacation house of the singer
Caetano Veloso, a longtime supporter. Vovo is a tall, heavyset man
in his 50s, and he spoke in a soft, quick Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
   He said the idea for a strictly black bloco occurred to him and
a friend in 1974, when Brazil was absorbing the racial-pride songs
of James Brown and Bob Marley. ``We wanted to create a group whose
name was `Black Power,''' Vovo said as Veloso translated. ``But we
wanted that in Yoruba. A man from the Federal Police who lived in
Libertade, an acquaintance of ours, advised us not to use this name
because it could be dangerous for us.'' (During Brazil's
anticommunist military dictatorship, anything that looked like a
cultural movement could be considered Communist.)
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I talked with my mother and some other friends about
choosing a name,'' Vovo continued, ``and finally we arrived at Ile
Aiye. It means `big house' in Yoruba, but in our minds it means
`black world.'''
</P>
<P>
   The bloco's theme song, written by Paulinho Camafeu, a member of
Ile Aiye, and made famous by Gilberto Gil's recorded version in
1977, carries the message of pride that suffuses Ile Aiye. ``What
bloco is this?'' go its translated lyrics. ``I want to know/ It's
the black world that we have come to show you/ We're crazy blacks,
we're really cool ... / White, if you knew the value of black/
You'd take a tar bath and become black, too.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ile Aiye rehearses once a week during the year, and sometimes
more than a thousand people come to dance, sing and join in with
the group; during most of the year, rehearsals are free and open to
the public. Closer to the time of Carnaval, admission is charged,
but it's clear that the bloco offers a healthy counterbalance to
the pop commercialism of the wealthy blocos, like those built
around the groups Crocodilo and Banda Eva, which charge hundreds of
dollars for upper-middle-class Brazilians to wear their special
shirts and to dance inside a cordoned area behind its sound truck
during Carnaval.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the city has given Ile Aiye increasing respect and
financial support.
</P>
<P>
   The days of the segregated carnival _ when whites in Bahia would
celebrate in private balls _ have been gone for more than 20 years.
But there is still an undercurrent of tension about racism in
Bahia. This year, even TV Globo, the powerful conglomerate that
owns radio stations, newspapers and a national television station
in Brazil, flirted with the subject in a news story.
</P>
<P>
   There is widespread speculation that some of the wealthier
blocos unofficially exclude blacks and poor Bahians by means of
their admissions process: they ask for a photograph and residential
address before allowing applicants to participate and buy a shirt.
</P>
<P>
   In TV Globo's report, which was shown during Carnaval this year,
Vovo was seen on television affirming these speculations,
presumably as a talking head in opposition to racism. But there is
obvious hypocrisy at play: Vovo is the leader of the only group in
Bahia that officially turns people away because of the color of
their skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two or three days after the television show,'' Vovo recalled,
smiling at the irony, ``I was on a radio station here giving
another interview, and it occurred to me that the only racist in
Bahia is me.''
</P>
<P>
   The night of the march, a yellow flier was handed out by a
member of Ile Aiye. It accused the local government of favoring the
commercial groups when handing out money to the blocos. There was
no indication that it was an official document of the bloco, but it
was widely distributed.
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, on a reviewing stand in downtown Salvador, the
mayor waved the flier away as a piece of rabble-rousing, denying
that there was an imbalance in financial support.
</P>
<P>
   ``This piece of paper doesn't represent any major thought,'' he
said. ``It's just an idea from a small group or an individual. The
blocos afro, like Ile Aiye _ they're not businesses; they're from
the heart. They try to send a message of peace, of freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   He measured the commercial blocos against the blocos afro:
``Both are important to the city: one increases the economy, and
the other maintains the identity. And the government has to help
the group that doesn't have enough money to put on a show.'' Two
days later the mayor encouraged Ile Aiye to arrive downtown at 8
p.m. sharp, so as to pass in front of the television cameras during
prime time.
</P>
<P>
   Ile Aiye's exclusionism even extends to its repertory: it plays
no songs written by members outside the group (with the sole
exception of ``Um Canto de Afoxe Para O Bloco do Ile,'' composed in
1982 by Veloso, who is considered white, and his son Moreno).
</P>
<P>
   The group's expression of black power has softened a little; it
now includes songs that Vovo calls ``Afro-romantic.'' One of them,
``Deusa do Ebano,'' is on the ``Ile Aiye 25 Anos'' record. ``I have
wandered alone,'' the lyrics go. ``You're not here in the street/
and I am nothing without you/ I'm going to Ile Aiye to find you/
oh! my beautiful black woman/ oh! my ebony goddess/ the black
culture of Ile Aiye is inscribed on her naked body.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Bahians understand that Ile Aiye's racial policies are a
form of benign idealism; Vovo says that if they should ever be
ruled illegal, he would change them in a heartbeat. In the
meantime, he's sticking to the way things are. On his car is an Ile
Aiye sticker that reads, somewhat cryptically, ``Do not forget: the
path of stubbornness is backed by faith.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 0214EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
