<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 02:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3341 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLOSER-THEATER-$ADV21     03-17 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLOSER-THEATER-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGING FOR LOVE, FINDING ONLY SEX AND SOLITUDE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANDREA STEVENS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American sex industry as theatrical muse? Well, why not? In
1996, the British dramatist Patrick Marber brought his first play
to America, ``Dealer's Choice,'' a black comedy in which six men
play poker around a table while competing in a savage survival of
the slickest.
</P>
<P>
   One night in Atlanta, where the play was part of the Olympics
festival, the all-male British cast, as Marber remembers it, ``went
on a boys' night out to a strip club.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an up-market strip joint,'' Marber said. ``The concept
didn't exist in London then, though it does now. They've all been
imported over _ these lap-dancing clubs, where the notion is that
it's a sexual transaction and a money transaction. Kind of like a
human casino. A casino of flesh.''
</P>
<P>
   Marber, who is now 34, was curious: ``The men there were not the
kind of cliched meatheads you'd expect, but just ordinary
professional men like myself. I wanted to take it on, on some
level.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is ``Closer,'' his bitter, darkly comic prize-winning
English play about sex and longing. Underlying themes of betrayal
and competition are signified early on in a notoriously ribald
scene in which two male strangers correspond in a cyberspace chat
room, one posing as a sexually hungry woman, the other happy to
believe it.
</P>
<P>
   The play, which won the triple crown in England _ the Olivier,
The Evening Standard and the Critics' Circle awards _ opens on
Thursday at the Music Box Theater on Broadway. Natasha Richardson
co-stars with Rupert Graves, Anna Friel and Ciaran Hinds, the lone
holdover from London. The author is directing, as he did with
``Dealer's Choice.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Sunday night between rehearsals, Marber described
how he wrote his second play, about four people who meet, pair off,
switch partners and separate. Compact, with dark hair and very
white skin, he spoke intensely, rarely hesitating. ``The first
scene that got written was the strip club. I had this girl who is a
stripper and I had this guy. I found out who she was; I found out
who he was. I had two instruments, but the play didn't sing with
just two. At one point, there were three couples, and then I
realized I didn't need three; I needed two for a string quartet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of if A meets B, and then meets C, how's D going to
feel about it? Some critics of the play have said it's algebra and
not true to life. Of course it's not true to life; it's a play.
It's kind of virtual reality.''
</P>
<P>
   After composing the first draft, Marber said, ``I read Noel
Coward's `Private Lives' again and thought, `Yeah, there are
parallels here.' It owes a lot to Racine. I directed a version of
`Andromache' in London, and I was very taken with the rigorousness
of his structure. I'd also done an updated version of `Miss Julie'
for British television. So the sexual politics were in my mix, and
stuff in my friends' lives, in my own.''
</P>
<P>
   An Oxford graduate, Marber tried the life of a stand-up comic
for a few years, a job he describes as lonely. Loneliness is a
subject that also interests him. ``The condition of `Closer' is
solitude,'' he said. ``None of the characters know each other at
the beginning, and none are going to see each other again at the
end. It is quite influenced by a book by Roland Barthes called `A
Lover's Discourse,' where he talks about the nature of love being a
condition of solitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's why the play is called `Closer,' because it was
the idea that the closer you get to someone, you might feel your
own solitude more deeply. The condition of being in love is to feel
your own being more profoundly, and to recognize your own singular
humanity. I think we all have that feeling when we're in love.''
</P>
<P>
   Is he?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   How does he know?
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose when I say the words, it doesn't feel like I'm
lying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
