<HEADER>
A3342 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RACHEL-GRIFFITHS-FILM     03-17 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACHEL-GRIFFITHS-FILMS-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LIVE-WIRE CLIMBER FROM AUSTRALIA  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Margy Rochlin's most recent article for the Arts and Leisure
section was about the director Risa Bramon Garcia.  
 By MARGY ROCHLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Even before she made her first movie, Rachel
Griffiths's face was famous. She first realized this back home in
Australia while sitting in a Melbourne movie house watching Martin
Scorsese's 1991 remake of the thriller ``Cape Fear.''
</P>
<P>
   In it, Robert De Niro's oily convict stalks a teen-ager played
by Juliette Lewis, who has the same high forehead as Ms. Griffiths,
as well as the same full mouth, large eyes and short dark hair.
Being presented with so many similarities writ so very large was
almost too much for Ms. Griffiths.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she came on the screen, I turned to my best friend and we
both went, `This is (italics)scary,'''(end italics) said Ms.
Griffiths, who, had she felt like it, could have held an impromptu
autograph-signing session afterward. ``When I walked out of the
theater, everybody was just staring at me.''
</P>
<P>
   In the business of acting, such look-alike recognition can be a
minus when just starting out. But with a co-starring role in the
international hit ``Muriel's Wedding'' three years later, Ms.
Griffiths made the first big step toward helping the public connect
her own name to her face. For her portrayal of Muriel's party-girl
sidekick, Ms. Griffiths took home her country's version of the
Oscar for best supporting actress and wound up with theatrical
representatives wrangling deals for her around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zimbabwe is the one country in the world where I don't have an
agent,'' kidded Ms. Griffiths. ``But I've been told not to take it
too personally. I think there's a revolution going on there.''
</P>
<P>
   In the span of seven months Ms. Griffiths will have appeared in
three British films _ ``Hilary and Jackie,'' ``Among Giants,''
which opens Friday, and Hanif Kureishi's June release ``My Son, the
Fanatic'' _ and one worldwide television event.
</P>
<P>
   At the Academy Awards ceremony Sunday night, a camera will be
trained on Ms. Griffiths as she finds out whether she has won the
Oscar for best supporting actress for her performance in ``Hilary
and Jackie.''
</P>
<P>
   As pressurized as this moment will be, it may not compare to
what ensued last January, when Ms. Griffiths found herself in the
middle of ``a furor,'' as she called it, over ``Hilary and
Jackie.'' The film is based on ``Genius in the Family,'' a scathing
tell-all memoir co-written by Hilary du Pre and her brother Piers
about their revered cellist sister Jacqueline du Pre, who died of
multiple sclerosis in 1987. (The book has been released here under
the same title as the movie.)
</P>
<P>
   Details include how Hilary du Pre's husband, Christopher Finzi,
slept with Jacqueline to help her overcome her shaky emotional
state.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Griffiths arrived in London for the British premiere of
the film, she found herself repeatedly defending Hilary, whom Ms.
Griffiths portrays.
</P>
<P>
   The media frenzy was sparked in part by composer Andrew Lloyd
Webber's cellist brother, Julian Lloyd Webber. Julian, portraying
himself as one of Jacqueline's close friends, was widely quoted
denouncing the film's depiction of Jacqueline (played by Emily
Watson) as ``deeply sordid'' and ``sick.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hilary du Pre has nothing but praise for Ms. Griffiths's
portrayal of her as a caretaker for her sister (and expresses
disdain for Julian Lloyd Webber, saying in a telephone interview
from her home in Berkshire, England, ``Jackie absolutely loathed
him and loathed his playing.'')
</P>
<P>
   As for what it was like to spend two hours watching Ms.
Griffiths act out all the love and despair of her caretaker
relationship with her sibling, Ms. du Pre could only rave.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like she crept into my soul and became me,'' said Ms.
du Pre, who has, at last count, seen ``Hilary and Jackie'' 11
times, sobbing all the way through on each occasion, she said.
``She has amazing ability,'' she said of Ms. Griffiths. ``You know,
Rachel is a loud, very noisy person. I'm quieter.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it is unlikely that Ms. Griffiths would ever get lost in
a crowd. Seated in the patio restaurant of Hollywood's Chateau
Marmont hotel, she is dressed in an ankle-length gray skirt, a
sleeveless blouse and the kind of tennis hat most often found on
the heads of old men. To a skinny, bespectacled man leaning out of
his hotel room window, Ms. Griffiths yelled, ``Hey, sexy!'' (He
turned out to be the director of ``Hilary and Jackie,'' Anand
Tucker.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Griffiths is accustomed to being cast as the live wire,
taking parts like the pig farmer's lusty daughter in ``Jude'' or
the spiteful debutante in ``My Best Friend's Wedding'' and making
the most of her brief moments onscreen. In fact, it took a lot of
coaxing by Tucker to convince her that she was right for the role
of the self-restrained housewife Hilary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just couldn't see me in the role at all,'' Ms. Griffith
said. ``I mean, I'd love to be the beautiful, quiet, enigmatic
type, but I'm not.''
</P>
<P>
   What she is, however, is harder to define. Ms. Griffiths, 31, is
the only daughter of Anna Griffiths, an arts and education
consultant and her ex-husband Edward, a welfare fund-raiser. Born
in the coastal town of Newcastle, the Griffiths clan (she has two
brothers, Ben and Sam) moved to Melbourne when she was 6.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond that there is almost no question about Ms.
Griffiths's background too innocuous to receive the ``I don't talk
about that'' response. Thank Blythe Danner, Gwyneth Paltrow's
mother, for this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just read this great interview where Gwyneth said her mother
told her never to talk about her love life, her family or the
movies that she might have said no to,'' Ms. Griffiths said.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the Danner Principle doesn't cover the discussion of
one's artistic training. ``A really great apprenticeship,'' was how
Ms. Griffiths characterized her stint with a government-subsidized
regional theater company after graduating from Victorian College of
the Arts in Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
   At age 23, she starred as a spy on a television series called
``Secrets.'' ``I got to be passive and watchful,'' said Ms.
Griffiths, who three weeks after the series was canceled, could be
found on the ``Muriel's Wedding'' set, reverting to the good time
girl that her co-stars know, and apparently love.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's fearless,'' was how the actor Pete Postlewaite responded
when asked about his partner for his first romantic leading role,
in ``Among Giants.'' In the film, written by Simon Beaufoy (``The
Full Monty''), Postlewaite plays a lonely middle-aged foreman who
falls for Ms. Griffiths's free-spirit rock climber Gerry when he
hires her for his crew of day laborers painting electrical towers
along northern England's rolling hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once Rachel decides to do something, she just goes for it,''
said Postlewaite, noting a scene in ``Among Giants'' in which the
lovers shed their clothes and wander through an abandoned water
cistern. ``What a day! There were no inhibitions!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty comfortable in my body, except when I start to
think, `Have I got cellulite?''' said Ms. Griffiths, whose hazy
retelling of her and Postlewaite's bare frolic had nothing to do
with Ms. Paltrow's mother's rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the scene, we're supposed to be walking drunk and naked
through this glorious site,'' said Ms. Griffiths. ``So we just had
a couple of beers, Pete and me. I can't really remember the day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
