<SLUG> BC-TV-ITS-LIKE-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING ON THE WAR BETWEEN THE COASTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21)
</HEADLINE>
 (af) 
By BRUCE NEWMAN  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the ceaseless civic sniping between New York
and this redoubt of surface charm and deep faults, everybody always
talks about the weather, but nobody ever does anything about it.
Until now.
</P>
<P>
   In what at first appears to be a new skirmish in this culture
war, the ABC sitcom ``It's Like, You Know ... '' surveys the L.A.
landscape _ where the people are as convertible as the cars they
drive _ and quickly runs up the flag of surrender.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the transplanted New Yorkers in this show explains to
a newly landed apostate: ``You're going to be like everyone else,
talking about how you hate L.A.,'' how the people are so dumb, so
plastic, so silicone, how you have to drive to take a walk, the
murder trials last two years, and the marriages last two months.
Then ``one warm afternoon, you play softball and you think to
yourself, `My God, it's January.' ''
</P>
<P>
   What charms beyond the weather this city holds for its tired,
its poor, its brain-dead, non-softball-playing huddled masses are
to be revealed, elliptically, during a six-week trial run of ``It's
Like, You Know ... '' beginning this Wednesday night at 8:30.
</P>
<P>
   It somehow makes sense that the stranger in this strange land
should be played by the most irritatingly smug New Yorker
imaginable, which naturally led the show's producers to Chris
Eigeman, who came to prominence nine years ago as the chatty churl
in the Whit Stillman film ``Metropolitan.''
</P>
<P>
   Eigeman suspects that his performance in that conversation piece
about New York debutantes had a lot to do with his being cast as
Arthur, the thinly disguised alter ego of Peter Mehlman, the
creator of ``It's Like, You Know. ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people in the world who don't think I'm an
actor at all,'' says Eigeman, flexing his supercilium subtly.
``They think that `Metropolitan' was a very, very well-produced
documentary.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear to Eigeman, and others, what these same people
will make of ``It's Like, You Know ... ,'' which eviscerates Los
Angeles with great affection _ and affectation. There is already a
body of thought that the show may be too different from everything
else currently on television to find a sizable audience.
</P>
<P>
   And some of that skepticism comes from people involved in making
the show. A.J. Langer, who observed the protracted death throes of
``My So-Called Life'' as a regular on that ABC series, worries that
the network may be similarly ambivalent about this show.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same thing is happening,'' says Ms. Langer, who plays a
process-serving masseuse this time. ``The network is scared of the
show. They don't know what to do with it, because it's smart and
it's not like anything else they've seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Ted Harbert, one of the show's executive producers, who
dropped the ax on ``My So-Called Life'' when he was president of
ABC Entertainment in 1995, seemed to be experiencing doubts about
his show's prospects not long ago as he watched an episode unfold
on a sound stage here. ``I haven't seen this on TV,'' Harbert said,
sounding worried. ``I hope that doesn't kill us.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehlman's is a fretful presence on the set. He is a wraith in
gym shoes, with inverted chevrons of graying hair rising from the
sides of his head like quotation marks. But the flag he planted at
the comedy mountaintop as a writer for six seasons on ``Seinfeld''
seems to have immunized him against the bullying of network
executives. He has urged a similar calm upon Harbert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `Look, you've gone from the Joint Chiefs of Staff
to the antiwar movement,''' Mehlman says. ``I think Ted's got a
case of Stockholm syndrome right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Harbert may have fallen in love with his comedy captors, but the
question is, will anybody else? In the same way that ``Seinfeld''
was a show famously about nothing, ``It's Like, You Know ... ''
seems to want to be a show that is funny without jokes. One early
episode consists entirely of the cast gathered around a television
set, watching a high-speed car chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never leave that room,'' Eigeman says proudly. ``We sit
there and stare at a television for 22 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some audiences may find this alarming, of course. ``Can you bury
a joke so far that people don't even see it?'' Eigeman asks. ``We
want that moment when an audience realizes, `Oh, that was a joke.'
''
</P>
<P>
   In that way, Mehlman is not exactly risk-averse. ``Peter is very
adamant about not wanting to conform to the same formulas as other
television shows,'' says Evan Handler, who plays Shrug, an idler
living off his trust fund. ``But I don't think people are going to
look at it and go, `Wow, this totally rips up the genre.'''
</P>
<P>
   It seems far likelier that audiences will look at Handler's
character and his talkative friends and see a sort of Bizarro L.A.
version of that other sitcom. ``I've already accepted that the
comparisons are inevitable,'' Mehlman says, ``but I think they are
reflexive, rather than well thought out.''
</P>
<P>
   In its embrace of the unconventional, ``It's Like, You Know ...
'' rather insistently asserts its own intelligence. And yet Mehlman
has posed for himself the further difficulty of doing a highbrow
comedy about a city that he avers may be better known for its
other, lesser brows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate the physical beauty of Los Angeles,'' says
Mehlman, who moved here from New York a decade ago. ``It's a mass
amount of the people that I have some disdain for. I have the same
attitude about L.A. and New York as I do about men and women. I
always overestimate women and reflexively underrate men. So when a
woman in New York is not bright, it's heartbreaking. And when
somebody in Los Angeles is bright, I'm shocked. Shocked. I see L.A.
as a very corrupting place.''
</P>
<P>
   He says that as if it's like, you know, a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   Like the sites of other city-specific series, Los Angeles was to
be an important character in the show. There would have been no way
to do that without taking into account the local preoccupation with
plastic surgery, and yet Mehlman's artistic vision did not include
an endless procession of breast-implant jokes. From that conflict
came his master stroke: he would co-opt the joke itself by
furnishing the show with the reupholstered face of Jennifer Grey.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Grey had the time of her life in the 1987 film ``Dirty
Dancing,'' her career borne aloft by the almost painfully adorable
role of Baby Houseman, a sheltered teen-ager having her first
grown-up romance in the Catskills. But when it came time to field
the offers that usually follow such a triumph, there weren't any.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought maybe people were having trouble casting somebody
who looked so specifically Jewish,'' Ms. Grey recalls. So in 1989
she decided to ``get a little something done.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Grey insisted on having a nose with some character, not the
usual Hollywood bob. ``I was really a fiend about making sure it
didn't look like a nose job,'' she says. And it didn't. But when a
small piece of cartilage shifted in her nose, the doctor who had
performed the original surgery offered to fix it. ``I didn't even
tell anybody I was doing it,'' Ms. Grey says. ``I thought it was
like having a tooth pulled. But when I came to, I didn't look like
myself again. Ever.''
</P>
<P>
   The newly pug-nosed Ms. Grey was virtually unrecognizable. ``It
was like being in the witness protection program,'' she says.
``Everywhere I went, no one knew who I was. Even ex-boyfriends I'd
run into would have this kind of spooked look on their face.''
</P>
<P>
   So when Mehlman offered her the role of Jennifer Grey, the
wacky-actress-next-door, in his new comedy, Ms. Grey was just happy
that somebody finally considered her right for the part.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
