<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-GRIZZLIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAKER SUBDUES GRIZZLIES; PAYTON EJECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For the first time this season the Sonics were without
their best player when they needed him the most.
</P>
<P>
   But, boy, is it nice to have Vin Baker these days.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly working his way back into all-star form, Baker catapulted
the Sonics past the Vancouver Grizzlies 87-85 Tuesday night at
KeyArena. Baker's tip-in with .05 seconds left in the game
completed a come-from-behind effort that sent the Sonics to their
third straight victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was tremendous,'' Sonics coach Paul Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   Baker also was in the most opportune position down the stretch.
Especially, since star point guard Gary Payton had been ejected and
missed the game's final 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Baker finished off a 31-point, seven-rebound night by getting
his left hand on Detlef Schrempf's missed layup attempt. The Sonics
(12-9) had wrangled with the Grizzlies (4-19) all night, and it was
perhaps fitting that the final play fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   When the Sonics got the ball with 15.7 seconds left and the
scored tied 85-85, it was intended that Baker score off a lob to
the basket. When Vancouver took that away, Schrempf drove the
baseline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Detlef made a great move to the basket, and how the ball came
out I don't know,'' Baker said. ``I was just fortunate to be in the
right place at the right time. I'm not really creative with my left
(hand), but it happened to fall in at the right place with the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   When the game-winning basket fell, he acknowledged a frenzied
crowd with his right fist pointed skyward.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third straight solid outing for Baker, who shot 13 of
19 from the field. Suddenly, what was once a season-long slump is
starting to turn around. Baker matched his season-high scoring
total. He scored 31 points March 1 on the road against Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming out of my struggles, I want to be kind of cool about
it. ... I want to come out of it and act like I've scored 30
before,'' said Baker, who wore a permanent smile. ``But on a
game-winner, I couldn't control it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics were fortunate that Baker was even around down the
stretch. He played the final 10:34 with five fouls.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics trailed 83-77 late in the fourth quarter when they
rallied. They went on a 12-0 run the down the stretch that Baker
capped with a dunk to put Seattle ahead 85-83 with 36 seconds left
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver rookie Mike Bibby came right back and tied the game
with a 10-foot jumper.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sonics got a lucky tip with .05 seconds,'' Bibby said.
``It was lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Luck or not, the Sonics can finally boast of clutch late-game
performances. After losing five straight games, many of which
escaped the Sonics down the stretch, they have put away their last
three opponents in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   A loss the Grizzlies, now losers of 13 straight, would have set
the team back.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would have been a horrible loss,'' Sonics guard Hersey
Hawkins said. ``This would have hurt more than any loss this year.
You have to beat teams you're supposed to beat. I don't know how
many people anticipated that we would win the game. But it was
defense. We found a way to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver had dominated the paint with their front line of
Bryant Reeves (21 points) and Shareef Abdur-Rahim (21 points). But
the Sonics held the Grizzlies to just one field goal in the final
2:34.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone on the floor for the Sonics stepped up after the team
lost Payton with 3:49 left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver's Felipe Lopez tried to deny Payton the ball on an
in-bounds play. The two got tangled when Payton threw a forearm
toward Lopez's head. Referee George Toliver immediately whistled
both players for technical fouls.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said they fouled each other while the ball wasn't in
play,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Payton's second technical foul. He drew his first with
1:20 left before halftime when he was admonished for jawing with
Lopez at the free throw line during a dead ball.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics trailed 61-57 when Payton departed the game after
collecting 12 points, five rebounds and three assists. He was
unavailable for interviews after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver attacked every rebound and loose ball as if it were
free money. The Grizzlies regularly went hard to the basket and
scored most of their points inside the paint. Vancouver won the
rebounding battle 50-46, which included a 22-14 edge on the
offensive glass. The Grizzlies also finished with a mere nine
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   After the first quarter, the Sonics led just once early in the
third. They never led in the fourth until Baker's dunk in the final
minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``A sloppy win is a lot better than a well-played loss as far as
I'm concerned,'' Westphal said. ``I'm not quite sure how we ended
up winning that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
