<HEADER>
A3351 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NELSON-APPRECIATION-S     03-17 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NELSON-APPRECIATION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ROSEMARY NELSON'S FATAL PASSION FOR JUSTICE  &HT;     By FRANK VIVIANO 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Rosemary Nelson knew she was a marked woman. ``She won't
be around when your case gets to court,'' one of her clients was
warned by a police department employee last winter. ``She'll be
dead by then.''
</P>
<P>
   The professional in Nelson, the fiercely committed human rights
lawyer who defied Northern Ireland's gunmen for 16 years, refused
to be intimidated _ even after anonymous midnight telephone calls
and scribbled death threats had become as predictable as the chill
winter rains that sweep across her native County Armagh.
</P>
<P>
   But the mother and wife in her was racked with fear. ``I have to
be careful,'' she told me last May, her voice trailing off in the
midst of a detailed conversation about alleged police ties to
terrorists. ``I have a husband and three children. I have a life.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday afternoon, the 40-year-old Nelson's life ended when a car
bomb ripped her apart as she backed out of her driveway in Lurgan,
her hometown 30 miles south of Belfast. The Red Hand Defenders, a
renegade Protestant Loyalist paramilitary organization, claimed
responsibility for the assassination.
</P>
<P>
   Her 8-year-old daughter, Sarah, heard the explosion from her
desk at the Tannaghmore Primary School, less than a block away from
the family home. Sarah's two brothers, Gavin, 13, and Brian, 11,
were on a school field trip to France.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah and her parents had spent the weekend relaxing in the
countryside of County Donegal, across the border in the Irish
Republic, a rare family vacation. Nelson's car was left sitting in
the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Holidays were rare because Robert Hamill had been kicked to
death by 15 Loyalist thugs in nearby Portadown while officers from
the Royal Ulster Constabulary (RUC) watched from a parked police
car. Because Catholic residents of Portadown had been barricaded in
their homes several times each year, while police led Loyalist
marchers through the neighborhood singing violently anti-Catholic
battle songs. Because another human rights lawyer, Pat Finucane,
had been assassinated by masked gunmen under mysterious
circumstances in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson took on these cases and dozens more, with an intensity
that left too little time for the family she adored and that made
too many dangerous enemies.
</P>
<P>
   She was convinced that the thread tying the cases together _
``the most dangerous enemy,'' she said _ is the RUC, ``a state
security apparatus that has become a greater threat to civil
society in Northern Ireland than the paramilitaries of either
side.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from being a detached guarantor of justice, Nelson said, the
RUC was an active participant in the Loyalist campaign to keep
Ireland divided at any cost. ``It was first established as the
military wing of the Unionist parties,'' she noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, the RUC remains more than 90 percent Protestant, which
is a major reason why we have a peace agreement in Northern Ireland
but no real peace,'' she was quoted in May for a Chronicle story.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be no genuine civil society here until we
understand, clearly and completely, the role that the security
forces have played in dividing our communities and fomenting
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson gave testimony before the U.S. Congress in October at
hearings on the intimidation of lawyers in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Although RUC spokesmen insist that the force is nonpartisan,
recent reports by the United Nations, Human Rights Watch, the Law
Society of England and Wales and Amnesty International have all
found evidence of systematic police abuse in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Defectors from Loyalist terrorist groups have charged that RUC
officers helped them track down IRA members.
</P>
<P>
   RUC chief Ronnie Flanagan has promised an independent
investigation of these claims, and also of charges that RUC members
were responsible for death threats against Nelson. He said that
David Phillips, a police chief in Kent County, England, and FBI
investigators would work on the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amount of information pointing to official collusion
(between the RUC and Loyalist paramilitaries) is staggering and
cannot go unanswered,'' Julia Hall, a spokeswoman for Human Rights
Watch in New York, told the Lawyer magazine last April.
</P>
<P>
   Mountains of that information came from Rosemary Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   In newspaper jargon, Nelson was an expert source, an insider who
shared her vast knowledge of Northern Ireland's tortured society
with reporters. The Chronicle's coverage since 1992 owed a great
deal to her, on or off the record, and to an extensive network of
human rights activists _ both Catholic and Protestant _ that
radiated out from her bare-bones office on William Street near the
Lurgan railroad station.
</P>
<P>
   If she spoke on the record, which was most of the time, the
personal danger soared. ``Yes, there are threats, particularly when
I am involved in highlighting issues, when there is a lot of
attention,'' she acknowledged to Irish News reporter Steven
MacCaffery just last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But like so many people who take enormous risks in the interest
of truth, Nelson was much more than ``an informed source'' for
those who came to rely on her, much more than the stiff cardboard
robot that the term ``activist'' suggests in the terse language of
a newspaper article.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, and above all else, she was my dear friend,'' Sinn Fein
spokeswoman Dara O'Hagen said two hours after Nelson died. ``I sat
on her front steps with her a few days ago, laughing about
something, sipping a beer.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Hagen couldn't finish the conversation, and neither could I.
Rosemary Nelson affected people that way. She was the struggle
between commitment and fear, between a passion for justice and the
passions of a mother and wife, made deeply, heartbreakingly human.
</P>
<P>
   Now her three children are motherless and her husband is a
widower.
</P>
<P>
   There are events that a journalist can't reconstruct in words,
``certain things that can't be explained in human terms,'' as
Nelson herself put it the final time we spoke. Her killing is one
of those things. I can't put myself into the mind of someone who
waited patiently for a family of five to leave town, then loaded a
mother's car with explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Her clients in the Garvaghy Road Residents Coalition had heard
rumors that Nelson was targeted, and they asked the British
government to provide special surveillance and other protection for
her in December. The request was turned down without explanation.
</P>
<P>
   In the British press, which often quoted Nelson, her description
was usually pared down to ``Irish Nationalist,'' and it infuriated
her. ``That's a political label and I'm not a politician,'' she
liked to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's justice I care about, not labels. I believe in the rule
of law, and not the gun or the bomb.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
