<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 03:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3354 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EASTER-PROTEST-SFCHRO     03-17 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EASTER-PROTEST-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC ARCHDIOCESE PROTESTS EASTER STREET PARTY BY SISTERS
OF  PERPETUAL INDULGENCE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By YUMI WILSON 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence are hoping
to take over a block of Castro Street on Easter Sunday to celebrate
their 20th anniversary _ but not if San Francisco's Roman Catholic
Archdiocese has anything to say about it.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Healy, spokesman for the archdiocese, said allowing a
group that ``mocks the Catholic Church'' to close a public street
on the holiest day of the Christian year is just as reprehensible
as ``allowing a group of neo-Nazis to close a city street for a
celebration on the Jewish Feast of Passover.''
</P>
<P>
   Healy said Tuesday that the archdiocese wants the Board of
Supervisors to rescind a vote earlier this month shutting down
Castro Street between 17th and 18th streets on Easter, April 4, for
the party.
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial last week in the archdiocese's official
newspaper, Catholic San Francisco, Healy wrote that the
supervisors' vote showed ``extraordinary insensitivity to people of
all faiths. ... This group has garnered a reputation for outrageous
behavior by mocking religious life, ridicule of Catholic
institutions and profane references to sacred liturgies.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister MaryMaye Himm said Tuesday that the group had no
intention of calling off the celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really appalled at the insensitivity of comparing us to
neo-Nazis, which totally invalidates the Jewish struggle against
Nazis,'' Himm said. ``The comparison is offensive not only to
myself but to Jewish people everywhere, and the Catholic Church
should be ashamed for promoting such an absurdity.''
</P>
<P>
   He said of the party, ``There are no pagan rituals. We're having
a stage show, dancing to bands and rereleasing a safe-sex pamphlet
that came out in 1981. The goal is education and celebration.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence is a flamboyant theater
troupe of 30 gay, lesbian, transgender and straight members who
dress like nuns. The group came together 20 years ago to
``promulgate universal joy and expiate stigmatic guilt,'' Himm
said.
</P>
<P>
   The group had asked the Department of Parking and Traffic for
permission to close a block of Castro Street on Easter Sunday _ the
day ``we were formed,'' said Himm. The department refused, saying
some merchants had raised parking and traffic concerns, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That is when Board of Supervisors President Tom Ammiano and
Supervisor Mark Leno, both of whom are openly gay, drafted a
resolution to overturn the denial.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisors unanimously approved the resolution March 1, saying
the group had done a number of good things for the poor, homeless,
sick and youths.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, the group is a volunteer organization, which has
the mission of doing good deeds truly, though obviously with some
humor, in the spirit of those in the religious order,'' Leno said.
</P>
<P>
   Healy applauds the group for its fund-raising programs but says
that to close a public street on Easter Sunday for a group that
``mocked the pope during his 1987 visit with a theatrical exorcism
in Union Square'' is not acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Archbishop William Levada was out of town Tuesday, but Healy
said Levada supports his position and would like to see supervisors
rescind their vote.
</P>
<P>
   Leno, however, made it clear that he stands by his vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all have to lighten up a little bit,'' he said.
``And it's not to say that everyone is going to feel good about the
sisters. But I can feel comfortable about my vote, because they do
good work and offer no disrespect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
