<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 09:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3488 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-IOC-SAMARANCH     03-17 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-SAMARANCH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IOC backs Samaranch: Amid vote-buying scandal, Olympics chief
gets an overwhelming vote of confidence
 &HT;    By Bert Roughton Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lausanne, Switzerland _ Meeting in a historic emergency session
to confront the Salt Lake City bidding crisis, the International
Olympic Committee today gave its longtime president, Juan Antonio
Samaranch, a resounding vote of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   In a secret ballot taken behind closed doors, the IOC endorsed
Samaranch by an overwhelming margin of 86-2.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch has come under severe attack from critics outside the
IOC in the wake of the vote-buying scandal stemming from Salt Lake
City's successful bid for the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   While critics have called for Samaranch to resign, the
78-year-old Spaniard has insisted he intends to serve out the rest
of his term until 2001 if IOC members continue to support him.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech to the members gathered here, Samaranch accepted
responsibility for the scandal and urged the IOC to expel six
members whose behavior has been found unethical by an internal
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   He told the members that the damage done by the Salt Lake
scandal had seriously harmed public opinion of the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a virtual firestorm that has consumed the world
media,'' he said. ``Bidding cities which may have acted improperly
are a matter of the past: It is the IOC which now is on trial.''
</P>
<P>
   After expressing their support for Samaranch, the IOC began
hearing statements from the members recommended for expulsion by
the IOC executive board. The expulsions were expected to be
approved by similarly large margins. It would be the first time in
105 years the IOC has forced any of its members to give up their
positions.
</P>
<P>
   The members recommended for expulsion are Siuli Paul Wallwork,
Western Samoa; Agustin Arroyo, Ecuador; Jean-Claude Ganga, Republic
of Congo; Zein El Abdin Ahmed Abdel Gadir, Sudan; Lamine Keita,
Mali; and Sergio Santander, Chile.
</P>
<P>
   Most have said they did nothing wrong and some have challenged
the legitimacy of the investigations that have condemned them.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC is eager to get the scandal behind it to forestall
external campaigns for reform, particularly in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Anita DeFrantz, the senior U.S. IOC member, received
a letter from Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) reminding her that
Congress may act if the IOC does not take strong enough measures
during this week's emergency session.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the strongest terms, let me communicate to you my hope that
the IOC will move quickly to adopt reforms necessary to provide
transparency and accountability to the IOC organization and
processes,'' he wrote. ``Without such independent action, the
demand from Congress to act will be irrepressible.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain noted that the IOC enjoys special tax status that allows
it to pay no taxes and permits corporate sponsors to write off the
cost of their sponsorships. McCain has said before that these
advantages could be removed if the IOC doesn't clean up its act.
</P>
<P>
   IOC officials hope the gravity of expelling its members, coupled
with clear indications that it enact important reforms, will be
enough to forestall an assault in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Francois Carrard, the IOC director general, acknowledged that
the IOC is paying close attention to events in Washington. ``We
have been following and reading the recommendations which we got
from various sources,'' he said. ``We believe that the action which
is being undertaken now should be of the nature to satisfy those
who are considering certain measures.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
