<SLUG> BC-SPECIALS-BUDGET-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No. 424 - March 17, 1999   ENTERTAINMENT
SUMMARY -- No. 424 -- March 17, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. WHAT YOU WON'T SEE AT THIS YEAR'S OSCARS At this year's 71st
Academy Awards Ceremony on March 21, the usual parade of
overdressed actresses and over-choreographed dance numbers is
expected. But there's plenty we won't see : Oscar taboos and
precautions that go on behind the scenes. After more than 25 years
covering the big night, Ivor Davis lists 10 things you can bet you
won't see when you tune in this year. 900 words. (N/A Great Britain
and Australia.)
_______________________________________________________________ 2.
ACADEMY AWARDS QUIZ : OSCAR GOES TO WORK What does it take to win
an Oscar? Test your knowledge with this quiz. By S. Burelison.
1,300 words + photos.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
STEVE MARTIN: STILL WILD BUT NOT AS CRAZY There was a time when
comic actor Steve Martin made a movie or two every year. These days
he's becoming more and more active offscreen, particularly as a
writer. A turning point was ``Picasso at the Lapin Agile,'' (1995,)
the highly acclaimed stage play that explored the creative and
scientific processes. ``In a weird way I think the writing has
helped my acting,'' he says. Interview by Ian Spelling. 1,300 words
+ photo. 4. STANLEY KUBRICK : THE MAN WHO INVENTED THE FUTURE When
Stanley Kubrick died on March 7 at age 70, he left behind a
dazzling body of work - and a legacy of almost total silence. In
four decades as a filmmaker, Kubrick virtually never agreed to be
interviewed. In 1968 however, shortly after the release of his
seminal science-fiction film ``2001 : A Space Odyssey,'' the
director was interviewed by Playboy magazine and talked about
``2001'' and ``Dr. Strangelove'' (1964,) his visions of the future
and his philosophy of filmmaking. Excerpts from this interview are
available in a long and short version of 4,200 words or 1,500 words
+ photos. By Eric Norden. From 1968 Playboy magazine. (PLEASE CHECK
WITH US ON AVAILABILITY YOUR COUNTRY.) 5. CLIMB EVERY MOUNTAIN The
brave new world of digital television, which allows dozens of
channels to be received via existing TV aerials, has a major flaw :
there are too many homes that it cannot reach. But now the physics
of electromagnetic waves is being exploited to make digital TV
available to almost as many people as can recive analogue TV
signals. By Barry Fox. From New Scientist magazine. 500 words. (N/A
Brazil, Australia, New Zealand.) 6. SCOT FREE : ROBERT CARLYLE HAS
GONE HOLLYWOOD,
</P>
<P>
   AND HE'S HAVING A BALL Scottish actor Robert Carlyle plays the
villain in the latest James Bond film ``The World Is Not Enough.''
The international success of ``The Full Monty'' made Carlyle a
movie star, a development which he never expected. ``Filming that
strip scene was the most terrifying thing in my whole life,'' he
says. Interview by Cindy Pearlman. 1,300 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
MELANIE'S EDGE Like the diva movie queen she is - and Melanie
Griffith remains a star, despite whatever happens at the box office
- she has never got in trouble for breaking the rules. Interview by
Merle Ginsberg. From W Magazine. 1,000 words + photo. 8. FORCE OF
ATTRACTION : BEN AFFLECK TRIES HIS HAND AT ROMANTIC COMEDY He isn't
even 27 yet but Ben Affleck has already won an Academy Award,
become an international celebrity and had a much-publicized romance
with one of Hollywood's hottest actresses. Interview by Jeanne Wolf
and Shep Morgan. 1,300 words. (N/A Japan.) 9. 'STREET'-SMART : A
BEHIND-THE-SCENES LOOK AT
</P>
<P>
   'SESAME STREET' AT 30 ``Sesame Street'' celebrates its 30th
anniversary this year. Two generations of children have been raised
on this popular TV show. (The computer generation is as interested
in it as were the children of 1969.) The winning combination seems
to be that it is educational, safe and entertaining. By Ian
Spelling. 1,300 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 10.
BRITNEY SPEARS : TEEN POP'S REIGNING PRINCESS Britney Spears is the
newest addition to pop music's cult of youth, with her blonde hair,
big brown eyes and innocent yet sexy girl-next-door image. At 17,
she is a teen pop superstar with a No. 1 album, a double platinum
single and a video on MTV. Interview by Tamara Conniff. BPI. 1.000
words + photo.`
