<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BREWERY18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gov. Bush's staff can't recall talk of Stroh closing
 &HT;    By Jo Lee Ferguson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ Union officials representing Longview Stroh
Brewery employees said they think they had a productive meeting
last week in Austin when they talked to Gov. George W. Bush and his
staff members about the troubled brewery.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, Bush's staff doesn't recall talking with the
union representatives about the brewery, which could close unless
another company buys the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Gardner, secretary-treasurer and business manager of the
Teamsters union Local 745 in Dallas, said he and other Teamsters
officials met Wednesday with Bush and some of his staff members. He
said they presented the governor with a petition asking for his
help in keeping the brewery open.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Stroh Brewery Co. announced it was selling its
brands and assets to Miller Brewing Co. and Pabst Brewing Co., but
Longview Stroh Brewery was not included in the sale. Stroh said the
plant could close nine months after the sale is finalized in April
if a buyer isn't found.
</P>
<P>
   If the brewery closes, it will mean the loss of more than 300
jobs and significant revenue losses for local government and
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was pretty anxious to get something done for the economy
down there and everything,'' Gardner said. ``That's the first time
I've met with him, and he's a pretty genuine person.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Gardner, Bush said he was going to work on the
Stroh Brewery issue and contact Longview's economic development
corporation. He said the governor seemed to be ``pretty impressed''
with the petition the Teamsters presented him, and their meeting
lasted about 50 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was real productive,'' Gardner said, although he
added that he could not talk about some of the issues that were
discussed during the meeting. ``He's going to do everything he can
do within his power to facilitate a purchase (of the plant) ...''
</P>
<P>
   However, Scott McClellan, a spokesman for the governor's office,
said the staff member who attended the meeting was not aware of any
discussion about the Longview Stroh Brewery. Bush was out of town,
so McClellan could not ask him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very informal meeting,'' McClellan said.
</P>
<P>
   T.P. O'Mahoney, Texas Workforce Commissioner representing labor,
said he, too, didn't hear any discussion about the Longview Stroh
Brewery or Longview, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   The Local 745 union representatives are newly elected, he said,
and the meeting ``was just a courtesy call just to come down and
chat about areas of concern.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor has had similar meetings with other union
representatives, O'Mahoney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it would have been appropriate anyway (to talk
about the Stroh Brewery),'' he said. ``This wasn't a business
meeting. It was just a courtesy call.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
