<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    They huffed and they buffed
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ University of Texas custodian Eric Meuth lifted
his arms over his head like he'd just wrestled a bull to the ground
at the rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   And no wonder. Meuth had just run a floor buffer through the
twisting buffer driving course without knocking over any peanuts
Tuesday at The Custodial Tournament of Champions VII.
</P>
<P>
   Teams of residence hall custodians from UT, Texas A&AMP;M, Texas
Tech and Southwest Texas State competed at UT's Jester Center in
six janitorial games _ peanut herding, the toilet tissue toss, the
soaked sponge relay, the trash can relay, window wipeout and the
buffer race.
</P>
<P>
   This year Southwest Texas State dusted the competition to win
the traveling trophy for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The key to success in buffer driving is to make it through the
zigzag course without hitting the Styrofoam cups filled with
unshelled peanuts that line the course.
</P>
<P>
   When buffing a floor, keeping a tight grip on the handle is
important, Meuth said. `` 'Cause if you don't, it can hit a dry
spot and really hurt you,'' said Meuth, 29, who was running the
buffing course for the Texas Diamond Devils, one of two janitorial
teams representing UT.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the events test janitorial skills. Then there's the
soaked sponge relay where team members _ there are five per team _
pass a sponge to each other over their shoulders, with one of them
squeezing the water into a bucket. The team collecting the most
water wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just like to get wet,'' said A&AMP;M custodian Gloria Ealoms,
explaining why she enjoys the sponge event.
</P>
<P>
   While the custodians take winning seriously, they have a good
time. Teams dress in team T-shirts. Custodians lead each other in
cheers. ``We got spirit, yes we do. We got spirit. How 'bout you?''
They shake cowbells and wave pompoms.
</P>
<P>
   They also practice their events. ``This is the Olympics _ for
us,'' said Donneal Dembo, 43, a UT custodian and member of the
Texas Vipers, one of the two UT teams.
</P>
<P>
   On your mark. Get set. Sweep. It was that kind of a day. As A&AMP;M
custodian Sabrina Edwards swept peanuts down the course with a
24-inch dust mop in the peanut-herding competition, her Aggie
teammates on the sidelines cheered her on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's go, Brina, let's go. Let's go Brina, let's go.'' they
chanted. Then, when a UT broom handler began sweeping, those same
Aggies chanted, ``Lose them peanuts, lose them peanuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Peanut herding is a time event done by teams of two. It starts
with Custodian No. 1 pushing 25 peanuts with a dust mop around the
27-inch-wide course. After Custodian No. 1 tags Custodian No. 2,
Custodian No. 2 pushes the peanuts back around the course, along
with 25 additional peanuts that had been sitting on the ground in
front of him.
</P>
<P>
   If a peanut escapes out of bounds, five seconds are added to
your time.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the window wipeout, featuring teams of two
custodians scraping and washing lipstick, shaving cream, toothpaste
and other gunk off windows.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, judges check closely for stains.
</P>
<P>
   This year's event suffered one minor scandal. The trash can
relay had to be rerun after several appeals were lodged. Seems one
of the trash bags being used by the Tech team blew away, and the
A&AMP;M team picked it up and used it.
</P>
<P>
   The Southwest Texas State team designed the trash cans with
toilet seats on top for the toilet tissue toss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis Rodman doesn't have anything on us,'' said Isabel
Aldape Jr., custodial services manager at Southwest Texas State.
</P>
<P>
   The tissue toss, another event with teams of two, starts when
the custodians load a cardboard box of toilet paper onto a dolly.
The dolly is rolled to a table where one of the custodians cuts
open the box with a box cutter.
</P>
<P>
   This custodian hands rolls of toilet paper one at a time to the
other custodian, who tries to toss the rolls of TP into the toilet
seat hole 20 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Texas State and UT's Diamond Devils tied for first in
the tissue toss with seven buckets each. So I guess you could say
they wiped up.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jkelsostatesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
