<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jeff Gordon's faith shows science, religion can mix into
powerful fuel
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ It's my theory that stock car racing caused the
latest intellectual fad on college campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Success in stock car racing would appear to be grounded in
science through the relentless pursuit of the limits of chemistry,
physics, aerodynamics, structural engineering and such.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the first thing the winning driver does after he
crawls out the window of his colorful No. 24 Chevrolet is to thank
God.
</P>
<P>
   Science takes a back seat to the supernatural when credit for
NASCAR Winston Cup victories is handed out, at least by NASCAR
champion Jeff Gordon, who seems to win most of the races.
</P>
<P>
   This habit of giving thanks to God for winning another pile of
money doesn't sit too well with the other two dozen or so drivers
who, by implication, were not as deserving of God's divine
intervention as was Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's crew chief, Ray Evernham, also is quick to give credit
to God for all the victories, which aggravates all the other pit
crews to no end.
</P>
<P>
   God-fearing can be the only explanation for why no one ever
blames God for causing 30 other drivers to lose, but that's par for
the course whether the person being interviewed is the winner of a
sporting event or the lone survivor of a plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon and Evernham may be thanking God for giving them a better
understanding of science than their less blessed opponents.
</P>
<P>
   They also may be thanking their Supreme Being for giving them
better depth perception, quicker reflexes, superior coordination,
more stamina, better looks and more overall natural (God-given)
talent than other NASCAR crews.
</P>
<P>
   Still, nothing makes people madder than being patronized by
holier-than-thou sermonizers.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I like Gordon. If God likes Gordon, who am I to
argue?
</P>
<P>
   Outside of NASCAR circles, Gordon has lots of fans. And Gordon
is unquestionably responsible for much of the explosion of
popularity of stock car racing, which is why I theorize that Gordon
and stock car racing are behind the newest intellectual pursuit of
the relationship between science and religion on college campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, I would think that putting science and religion
together in the same course of study would be the equivalent of
simultaneously whistling and drinking water. It would be
interesting entertainment but would serve of no real purpose.
</P>
<P>
   There is fact-based science and faith-based religion. One is a
study of the natural and the other is a musing of the supernatural.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean that scientists don't have faith-based
religious beliefs or that priests can't be preeminent scientists.
</P>
<P>
   That also doesn't mean that scientists can't make ethical
decisions such as those that involve cloning and genetic
engineering just as it doesn't mean that preachers can't be
disciplined logicians.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the considerable overlap, it seems to me that at the
extremes the two disciplines have irreconcilable differences
regarding how they arrive at their conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this is part of the intellectual appeal at U.S.
universities where decidedly non-NASCAR types are pursuing Jeff
Gordon's science-religion conundrum.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota academician Ian G. Barbour recently received a $1.2
million Templeton Prize for Progress in Religion for his work in
pioneering the interdisciplinary study of science and religion.
Barbour promptly gave gave $1 million of his prize award to the
Berkeley, Calif., Center for Graduate Theological Union that has
been in the forefront of bringing together religion and science.
</P>
<P>
   It was not reported whether Barbour gave thanks to God for
coming in first in the run for the Templeton Prize for Progress in
Religion. But if he did, he would be in good company.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco,
Texas. E-mail: RNethaway(AT)mail.wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
