<HEADER>
A3539 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS18-TAKE     03-17 2142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS18-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 1)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at
</P>
<P>
   q&AMP;a(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: My children and I were planning a camping vacation to
Yosemite National Park in July, but I'm concerned after hearing
about three women being abducted there. Is Yosemite advising
visitors to do anything?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. As previously reported, the three women were last seen
Feb. 15 near a restaurant and motel outside the park. Yosemite
officials say everything is operating normally inside the park, and
no special advisories have been extended. ``All we can do is tell
visitors to take the normal precautions that any traveler anywhere
would take,'' said park spokeswoman Kathy Farrier.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, however, continues to ask anyone with information
concerning the women's whereabouts to call 1-800-435-7883.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did the American Airlines pilots union actually pay the
multimillion-dollar contempt-of-court fine levied against it last
month?
</P>
<P>
   A: The union hasn't been fined yet. On Feb. 10, U.S. District
Judge Joe Kendall found the Allied Pilots Association members in
contempt of court for ignoring his order to return to work, and
said he intended to assess fines and damages. The union gave the
court a $10 million deposit toward those fines and damages. On Feb.
17, Kendall extended to May 12 his temporary restraining order. He
also delayed his decision on how to punish the union for originally
ignoring his order to return to work and continued the damages
hearing until April 12.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How is the Dow Jones Industrial Average calculated?
</P>
<P>
   A: Myron Greene, publisher of the Mutual Fund Timing Guide,
explains that in 1896, when Dow Jones &AMP; Co. began computing its
industrial average, it was a simple average of the prices of 12 of
the leading stocks of the day. Such an average is easy to
calculate, but a problem arises when one of the component companies
splits its stock. Suppose the average consists of only two stocks,
each priced at $30 a share. Obviously, the average price is $30.
Now suppose that one of the stocks is split two for one. Each
shareholder ends up with two shares for each one previously held,
but each share is worth only $15, so nothing has really changed for
the shareholder. The split will affect the average, however,
because the new value will be the average of $30 and $15, or
$22.50. It will appear, incorrectly, that the average has suffered
a 25 percent decline.
</P>
<P>
   The method used by Dow Jones to correct this problem is to
change the divisor used to compute the average. In this example,
the sum of $30 and $15 is divided by 1.5 rather than 2, giving the
same value for the average ($30) as before the split. The divisor
also is adjusted when the number of stocks in the average changes
or when a stock in the average is replaced. Because of numerous
adjustments over the past 100 years, the value of the divisor today
is 0.2252. To compute the average, the prices of the 30 stocks in
the average are added together and divided by 0.2252.
</P>
<P>
   Q: During World War II, I spent some time on Corregidor in the
Philippines. What is it like there now?
</P>
<P>
   A: The rocky, fortified island at the entrance to Manila Bay is
one of the only battlefields of World War II readily available to
the history-minded visitor to Asia. Its charms are one of the
better-kept secrets of the region.
</P>
<P>
   The island, sometimes called the Gibraltar of the Pacific, has a
population of about 230. Ruins of the military installation and
ordnance can be inspected by visitors, most of whom come by boat on
day trips from Manila. Those who pay a small surcharge can see a
light and sound show in the shaft of the Malinta Tunnel, which
served as Gen. Douglas MacArthur's headquarters from December 1941
to March 1942. The island has a war museum and memorial, and there
are elaborate plans for restoration. Lodging is available at the
Corregidor Inn.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the real last name of England's royal family?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's Windsor or Mountbatten-Windsor. The dynastic name of
Saxe-Coburg-Gotha (German: Sachsen-Coburg und Gotha) was that of
the German-born husband of Queen Victoria, who died in 1901. Her
husband was Albert, prince consort of Great Britain and Ireland.
Their eldest son was Edward VII. During the anti-German atmosphere
of World War I, George V declared by royal proclamation, on July
17, 1917, that all descendants of Queen Victoria in the male line
who also were British subjects would adopt the surname of Windsor.
</P>
<P>
   Queen Elizabeth II's children normally would have borne their
father's surname, Mountbatten (which itself had been anglicized
from Batternberg). In 1952, however, soon after her accession,
Queen Elizabeth II declared in council that her children and
descendants would bear the surname Windsor. On Feb. 8, 1960, this
decision was modified to the effect that offspring other than those
styled prince or princess and royal highness should bear the name
Mountbatten-Windsor.
</P>
<P>
   Q: After reading about the Los Angeles faults and watching
``Volcano'' and ``Meteor,'' I wonder: Are there any geologically
stable areas in the United States?
</P>
<P>
   A: Some areas are at less risk than others for such natural
hazards as earthquakes, but obviously there are no absolutes. And
someone fearing earthquakes might move from the Far West to the
Midwest only to face varying risks of tornadoes, or to the South or
East to fret about hurricanes. Meteor strikes are impossible to
predict.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Geological Survey maps of the United States depict several
states as free of designated earthquake regions: Florida,
Mississippi, North Dakota, Minnesota and Michigan. These are mostly
earthquake-free: South Carolina, Oregon, Texas, South Dakota,
Nebraska, Indiana, Kentucky, West Virginia and Pennsylvania. The
Geological Survey maps show these states as being free of hurricane
or tornado regions: Washington, Oregon, California, Nevada, Idaho,
Utah, Montana, New Mexico, North Dakota, West Virginia, Vermont,
New Hampshire and Maine. Naturally there could be, and have been,
exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   If you're thinking of moving, check the book ``Places Rated
Almanac,'' which has maps and text on climate, natural hazards and
weather extremes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I greatly admire Oprah Winfrey. What is her educational
background?
</P>
<P>
   A: After graduating from high school in Nashville, she attended
Tennessee State University in Nashville, majoring in the English
language arts. She had won an Elks Club oratorical contest when she
was 16 that guaranteed her a full scholarship to Tennessee State.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I saw an item about an herbal substitute for Viagra,
apparently being produced in China. Can it be purchased in the
United States?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not yet, but herbalists in New York already are predicting
strong sales when the product, called Weige (Big Brother),
eventually makes it to these shores. More than 40 agents across
China have gained permission to sell it, according to a report in
China Daily, and nearly 100 foreign traders have asked for samples
and hope to become agents outside China.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese company behind Weige says it's safer, healthier and
cheaper than Viagra. Its packaging is designed to look foreign,
featuring a photograph of an Adonis statue, flying doves and
cavorting women in bikinis. Jiang Wei, chairman of Shenyang
Feilong, the drug company, predicts big sales in China: ``We are
going to sell 100 million pills this year. Our Weige works better
than Viagra, and it is all herbal, so it does not have any side
effects.'' In China, a packet of eight Weige pills sells for $11.
Weige hasn't undergone independent clinical trials, but Jiang said
tests had been performed on volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was Ronald Reagan's first film?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was ``Love Is On the Air'' (1937). Reagan played a
small-town radio announcer, Andy McLeod, who told too much in his
news broadcasts about corrupt local politicians and was demoted to
children's programs. But McLeod persevered, exposed the crooks, and
won the girl, portrayed by June Travis.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you explain the origin and meaning of the ``Esq.''
designation that some men use after their name? Are there certain
requirements for using it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Esquire is the slightly older version of squire, as taken
into English at the time of the Norman conquest from the French
esquier, meaning ``shield bearer.'' The earliest squires, or
esquires, were candidates for knighthood. After the flowering of
knighthood had passed, the words Squire and Esquire (now with
capital letters) were used to designate men slightly above the rank
of tradespeople. Since they often were looked to as leaders, they
often served as magistrates in local courts, and the term Squire
came to be used more and more as a form of address for judges and
other local dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
   Today it's rarely seen, at least in the United States, except as
a courtesy title for some attorneys. There aren't any requirements
about the use of Esq., but since it's basically limited to the
legal profession, anyone else tacking it onto his (or her) name
might be accused of trying to pass himself off as a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the name of the agency Jane Fonda founded to fight
teen pregnancy, and how may I contact it?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's the Georgia Campaign for Adolescent Pregnancy
Prevention. Write to G-CAPP, One CNN Center, Suite 610, North
Tower, Atlanta, GA 30303; or call 404-524-2277.
</P>
<P>
   Q: During his moviemaking days, actor Charlton Heston, president
of the National Rifle Association, played everything from Moses to
Admiral Nimitz. Did he ever serve in the military? What about Rep.
Bob Barr (R-Ga.), who is on the NRA's board?
</P>
<P>
   A: After graduating from high school in 1941, Heston enrolled at
Northwestern University in Evanston, Ill., on a drama scholarship.
After completing two years, he left college to enlist in the Army
Air Corps. He spent most of his three-year tour of duty stationed
in the Aleutian Islands, where he was a radio-gunner on bombers. As
reported previously, Barr was never in the armed services.
</P>
<P>
   Q: At the recently concluded Clinton impeachment trial, Chief
Justice William Rehnquist stated two words, possibly in Latin, when
he sounded the gavel to indicate the end of the trial. What were
those words?
</P>
<P>
   A: Rehnquist uttered the expression sine die, which means
``without day'' or ``without assigning a day for a further meeting
or hearing.'' It's traditionally spoken when a legislative body
adjourns without appointing a day on which to assemble again.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article about a forecast for drought and fires this summer
mentioned something called the Palmer Drought Severity Index. I've
never heard of that. Who was Palmer? How is the index calculated?
</P>
<P>
   A: The PDSI was developed in the early- to mid-'60s, and was
first published in 1965 by Wayne C. Palmer, a meteorologist with
the U.S. Weather Bureau's Office of Climatology. It depicts
prolonged _ meaning months and years _ abnormal dryness or wetness
and reflects the general long-term status of water supplies in
aquifers, reservoirs and streams. It compares the actual amount of
precipitation received in an area during a specified time period
with the normal or average amount expected over that same period.
The index is calculated based on precipitation and temperature
data, as well as the local available water content of the soil.
Human impacts on the water balance, such as irrigation, aren't
considered.
</P>
<P>
   While the PDSI has been used for years, and is ``ingrained
within a lot of legislation and a lot of agencies within the
government,'' a newer index has been developed to provide drought
data more quickly, said Mark Svoboda, a climatologist with the
National Drought Mitigation Center at the University of
Nebraska-Lincoln. The SPI, based only on precipitation, provides
data within six to eight weeks, Svoboda said, which sometimes can
be handier than the more complex PDSI formulation.
</P>
<P>
   Details are available online at http:enso.unl.edu/ndmc, under
the drought watch section.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In connection with Joe DiMaggio's death, I noticed that all
three brothers who played Major League baseball had the same middle
name: Paul. Was their father named Paul?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. Joe was the eighth of nine children and the fourth of
five sons of Joseph Paul and Rosalia DiMaggio. His two ballplaying
brothers were Dom and Vince. Their parents had come from Isola
della Femmine, off the coast of Sicily, where the father's name was
spelled Giuseppe Paolo DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   (More)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
