<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 10:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3540 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS18-TAKE     03-17 1653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS18-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 2)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: How can fans send a note of encouragement to Joe Torre, who
has been diagnosed with prostate cancer?
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to the Yankees manager in care of his team: New York
Yankees, Yankee Stadium, Bronx, NY 10451.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How old is Elizabeth Dole? Absolutely no one has mentioned
it, either on television or in the newspaper. Her husband is in his
late 70s. She has got to be too old to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   A: Her age is no secret and has been included often in
Journal-Constitution articles, such as one published Jan. 15 when
she stepped down as president of the American Red Cross. But for
the record, here it is again: She's 62. She will be 63 on July 29.
Bob Dole will be 76 on July 22.
</P>
<P>
   You may be a ``what if'' kind of person, wondering what if she
decides officially to run as the Republican candidate for
president, and what if she wins the nomination, and what if she
wins the election and takes office Jan. 20, 2001. If all that were
to happen, she would be 64 on that date. The oldest president
inaugurated the first time was Ronald Reagan, who was 69 years and
349 days old when taking office on Jan. 20, 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the codes stamped on the bottom of canned goods? It
is done in a way to keep consumers from knowing the expiration
date?
</P>
<P>
   A: Codes on canned goods aren't a way to conceal expiration
dates; they provide manufacturers with information they need to
ensure product safety. Using the code, the manufacturers can
identify the plant where the product was processed, the processing
line it was run on, and when and where the product originated.
</P>
<P>
   Commercially canned goods are safe to eat even after long
periods of storage unless the cans are bulging, leaking or badly
rusted. Perhaps you could write dates on cans to help with your
``first in, first out'' system of rotating stocks. For the best
quality _ flavor, texture and color _ canned goods should be used
within a year of purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Last December, a Royal Caribbean cruise ship was involved in
an accident off St. Maarten that caused serious damage. I never
heard an explanation of the accident, or whose fault it was. Do you
have any information?
</P>
<P>
   A: The accident occurred the night of Dec. 14-15 when the
Monarch of the Seas struck Proselyte Reef less than a mile outside
the entrance to Philipsburg harbor, opening a 3-by-60-foot gash in
the hull. The vessel, which had sailed from San Juan, Puerto Rico,
had made an unscheduled stop at St. Maarten to evacuate a passenger
who had an apparent heart attack. As it was leaving, in darkness,
the ship struck the shoal and began taking on water, so the crew
decided to run it aground on soft sand. Reports indicated three of
the Monarch 's 18 watertight compartments had filled with water.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Caribbean officials couldn't immediately explain the cause
of the accident, because the reef is identified on all navigational
charts and has a floating buoy with a light that flashes every
seven seconds, as well as a radar reflector. While not ruling out
human error, officials of the line praised the expertise of Tore
Myrha the captain, and his experience with the company.
</P>
<P>
   All 2,557 passengers were summoned to muster stations by alarms,
outfitted with life jackets and taken ashore by tender boats. No
one was reported hurt, and the company gave passengers refunds and
a certificate for a future cruise. The ship is undergoing repairs
in Mobile, Ala., and is expected to return to service at any time.
The accident, meanwhile, remains under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When the legal precedents recently set in the trial of
President Clinton are used for reference in future court cases,
with what name, as in ``Roe v. Wade,'' will this case be referred
to?
</P>
<P>
   A: The federal civil rights case involving Paula Jones is cited
as ``Paula Corbin Jones v. William Jefferson Clinton, et al.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read that Joe DiMaggio's baseball career was interrupted by
three years of military service. What branch was he in, and did he
see combat?
</P>
<P>
   A: DiMaggio didn't see combat. He served for 31 months in the
physical training program for Air Corps cadets in the United States
and Hawaii, but was forced to spend much of the time in a hospital
with stomach ulcers. As a married man older than 28, the Yankee
outfielder was classified 3-A in the World War II draft, but in
February 1943 he enlisted in the Army and ``swapped his
$43,500-a-year baseball salary for a private's $50 a month,'' as
reported in Current Biography (1951). DiMaggio rose to the rank of
staff sergeant.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did it happen that President Abraham Lincoln, a
Republican, had Andrew Johnson, a Democrat, as a vice president?
</P>
<P>
   A: In 1860, after Lincoln was elected president, Johnson, who
was serving in the Senate, surprised many Southerners by declaring
his loyalty to the Union. When Tennessee seceded in June 1861,
Johnson was the only Southerner to remain in the Senate. In 1862,
after Union forces had captured most of Tennessee, Lincoln
appointed Johnson military governor of his state, and at Johnson's
urging, Tennessee became the only seceding state to outlaw slavery
before the 1863 Emancipation Proclamation.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's loyalty to the Union was rewarded with a vice
presidential nomination in 1864. (Lincoln's original vice
president, Republican Hannibal Hamlin of Maine, was dropped.)
Delegates to the National Union convention in Baltimore _ the
Republican nominating convention expanded to include Democrats
loyal to the Union _ hoped that having a southern Democrat on the
ticket would attract support from northern Democrats and voters in
border areas. Lincoln and Johnson defeated Democrats George
McClellan and George Pendleton by an electoral vote of 212 to 21.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I noticed on C-SPAN's coverage, and in a newspaper photo
Tuesday, that the American flag on the casket of Justice Harry
Blackmun had 48 flags, not 50. Is there an explanation?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. Kathy Arberg, Supreme Court spokeswoman, said the flag
draping Justice Blackmun's casket was the same one that was used on
his father's casket in 1947. The flag didn't get its 49th star (for
A-- aska) until 1959, and its 50th (for Hawaii) until 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard that a Boeing 737 experienced a major rudder
malfunction at high altitude. According to the crew, if it had
happened while on final approach, the plane probably would have
crashed. As it was, it made an emergency landing in Baltimore. Do
you have any details?
</P>
<P>
   A: The 737-200, flown by Metrojet, US Airways' new discount
carrier, was cruising at 33,000 feet during a flight Feb. 23 from
Orlando to Hartford, Conn., when it experienced what the National
Transportation Safety Board called ``flight control anomalies.''
</P>
<P>
   The plane started to bank and the pilots saw that the control
wheel had turned left and the rudder pedals were offset, causing
the 737 to start an ``uncommanded roll.'' After switching to backup
systems, the pilots were able to bring the plane back into level
flight and make an emergency landing at Baltimore-Washington
International Airport. None of the 117 people aboard _ 112
passengers, five crew members _ was injured.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation is continuing, but is being hampered because
the aircraft's flight data recorder had already recorded over the
period when the roll started, according to the safety board.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did baseball great Joe DiMaggio get his nickname ``Yankee
Clipper''? What does it mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: He was called that because of his graceful fielding (think of
a clipper ship moving smoothly and gracefully on the water) and, of
course, his team, the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've read where a basketball team is a ``dark horse'' in the
NCAA tournament. How did this term originate?
</P>
<P>
   A: Its first appearance was believed to be in Benjamin
Disraeli's ``The Young Duke'' (1831), as a racing term indicating
more than the color of a horse: ``A dark horse, which had never
been thought of, rushed past the grandstand in sweeping triumph.''
Given Disraeli's popularity as a novelist and public figure, it
wasn't long before the term was introduced in American politics to
describe a candidate about whom little is known, or who wins
unexpectedly. The Democratic convention of 1844 produced the first
political ``dark horse'' in James Polk, who went on to become
president, and by 1865 the term was in wide use.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I thought I saw an obituary for Mr. Rogers of children's TV
programming fame. But the other day a news show reported that he
had received an award. So, is he dead or alive?
</P>
<P>
   A: Fred Rogers is very much alive. The board chairman of Family
Communications Inc., he continues to write and produce several
weeks' worth of new programs each season for Mister Rogers'
Neighborhood, the longest-running children's programming on public
television.
</P>
<P>
   A brief bio: Fred McNelly Rogers was born in 1928 in Latrobe,
Pa. After graduating from Rollins College in Florida in 1951, he
was hired by NBC in New York as an assistant producer. In 1952 he
married Joanne Byrd, a pianist and fellow Rollins graduate. Rogers
moved to Pittsburgh in 1953 and developed a program called ``The
Children's Corner'' for WQED, the nation's first
community-supported public TV station. During its seven-year run,
Rogers attended Pittsburgh Theological Seminary and in 1962 was
ordained by the Pittsburgh Presbtytery.
</P>
<P>
   He then went to Toronto, where he developed a children's series
called ``Misterogers,'' and after returning to Pittsburgh he
expanded it. ``Mister Rogers' Neighborhood'' was born.
</P>
<P>
   Far from slowing down, Rogers is about to go online, opening a
new ``neighborhood'' in April: http://www.pbs.org/rogers/
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
