<HEADER>
A3561 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARROT-HOWTOCARVE18-C     03-17 0145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARROT-HOWTOCARVE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CARROT FLOWER
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. Using a large, room-temperature carrot, pare the carrot to
make five flat sides. This takes about three swipes with the peeler
on each face. Place the knife at one rib and cut down at a 45
degree angle to the center of the carrot. Turn and make the same
cut at the next rib. Be sure to begin each cut at the same level,
as though there were a band around the carrot.
</P>
<P>
   2. When the cuts have been made at all five ribs, hold the
carrot in both hands and twist the end. It should come off as a
five-pointed flower. Continue up the carrot at -inch intervals to
make more flowers.
</P>
<P>
   The carrot flowers can be stored in water in the refrigerator
for as long as five days. Use to garnish salads.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
