<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOOD STUFF
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ONE GOOD BOOK
</P>
<P>
   If you want to explore other possibilities for garnishes, pick
up Present It: New Ideas for Stylish Garnishes, edited by Deborah
Gray (Running Press, $14). Color pictures and step-by-step photos
lead the way to garnishes ranging from chile flowers and scallion
brushes to clever vegetable coils and cucumber fans.
</P>
<P>
   ONE GOOD GUIDELINE
</P>
<P>
   S o you're no good at eye-balling the thickness of a steak or
fish fillet, which is a basic guideline to cooking times. There's
no need to haul out a ruler. All you need is your index finger. As
a rule, the measurement from the tip to the first joint on an adult
is to 1 inch. Measure yours once. Then all you have to do is point
your index finger at the counter alongside the food and you'll know
how thick it is.
</P>
<P>
   Irish cuisine via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   In case you didn't get enough of All Things Irish on St.
Patrick's Day, Knight Ridder News Service points to what's promoted
as the Internet's most compre- hensive Irish recipe site:
www.irishfood.com.
</P>
<P>
   An authentic Irish Omelet (which, naturally, calls for potatoes)
is one of the stars. Others include Dressed Cabbage Oatmeal Bacon
Pancakes and Irish Whiskey and Ginger Cream.
</P>
<P>
   For more recipes, log onto our online parnter, Active Dayton, at
www.activedayton.com
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
