A3563 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARNISH-HOWTOCARVE18-     03-17 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARNISH-HOWTOCARVE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stylized offerings are several cuts above the norm
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Paula Sideras is a Dayton caterer known for her
pretty garnishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important to me. I never send a plate out
ungarnished,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Her tomato roses and other vegetable flowers draw sounds of
appreciation from party-goers whose usual idea of a garnish is a
sprig of parsley.
</P>
<P>
   How difficult is it for a home cook to duplicate those artful
radish chrysanthemums and Aztec mushrooms?
</P>
<P>
   To find out, I followed her lead while a photographer took
pictures of Sideras performing skills she has honed since she
graduated from the Cincinnati Culinary Arts Academy in the early
'80s.
</P>
<P>
   First, let me say that I'm a home cook who's comfortable when
all four burners are on high, but I don't have any tolerance for
tedious procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the teacher convinced me, by example, that at least some
of these garnishes are easy _ and quick. I managed to turn out
three credible vegetable flowers the first time around .
</P>
<P>
   Credible _ not perfect. Sideras' hands move with graceful
precision. She holds a carrot like a delicate bird. I tend to
clutch it tightly and she suggests a change in position.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your knife slips you'll cut your wrist,'' she warns. I move
the carrot to a less threatening distance.
</P>
<P>
   And when I make the cuts as suggested, the carrot flower twists
out neatly.
</P>
<P>
   No special tools are needed for this art, just a cutting board,
a sharp paring knife, a swivel peeler and chopsticks. The
chopsticks are used as a knife guide while making the chrysanthemum
radish.
</P>
<P>
   The peeler is used to pare a carrot into a five-sided vegetable
(six-sided is acceptable, Sideras said, when she noticed my slight
mistake).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not necessarily bad,'' she said, obviously in the role of
an encouraging teacher. ``It just won't be the same flower.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a knife is needed for the tomato rose and Aztec mushroom,
and the rose turns out to be surprisingly easy to create. Peeled
just the way we peeled apples at Halloween _ into one long peel _
it is simply wrapped and flipped, and voila, there's a rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I teach class I do this and people always say `Oooooh!'
'' Sideras says.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Aztec mushroom seems to take more practice _ plus a bit
of luck and a disposition toward precision.
</P>
<P>
   QUICKTIP
</P>
<P>
   Before starting, always place a damp towel under the cutting
board so it doesn't slip while you work.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
