<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3564 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RADISH-HOWTOCARVE18-C     03-17 0145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADISH-HOWTOCARVE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RADISH CHRYSANTHEMUM
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. Lightly trim the stem end of the radish, leaving the green
center for colorful effect. Cut a slice off the root end to make a
flat base. Put the radish between chopsticks so the knife doesn't
cut all the way through. Make cuts -inch thick across the radish
and take care at both ends not to slice completely through. If cuts
are too shallow the radish won't ``bloom''.
</P>
<P>
   2. Turn the radish and cut a grid across the radish slices,
again cutting through to the chopsticks. Soak the radishes in cold
water in the refrigerator overnight so they open to resemble a
flower.
</P>
<P>
   3. Garnish the radish mums with radish leaves, which are edible.
They are pretty on relish and sandwich trays.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
