<HEADER>
A3565 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-IFL-WINSLOW18-COX     03-17 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-IFL-WINSLOW18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Autograph seekers will love these teams
 &HT;    By Sean McClelland
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Mention the name Kellen Winslow to football fans
of a certain age and a clear image leaps to mind of this player,
completely spent, white towel draped over his head, being assisted
from the field by two teammates. He had just driven the San Diego
Chargers past the Miami Dolphins, seemingly with every fiber of his
existence.
</P>
<P>
   Nary a day passes when he isn't reminded of that Jan. 2, 1982
overtime playoff game. ``Good thing we won,'' laughed Winslow, who
played nine years as a tight end for the Chargers and entered the
Pro Football Hall of Fame in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, in his role as commissioner of the Indoor Foortball
League, Winslow helped the Dayton Skyhawks, newest of eight IFL
franchises, drum up interest for their inaugural 12-game season
beginning April 2 at Hara Arena against Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   It's a far cry from the NFL and Winslow admits he didn't know
quite what to think when approached about the job. But now he's
thinking about further expansion _ to 12 or 16 teams by next year _
and says a cable TV deal for the league is possible, in part
because ``networks are in dire need of programming.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a market for it,'' Winslow said prior to a spirited
press conference at the Doubletree Hotel in downtown Dayton. ``This
is just the beginning. Eventually, we can manage 20 teams and still
have a great product. They've really thought this thing through,
right down to the last nickel.''
</P>
<P>
   Sole IFL owner Keary Euckland is taking pains to keep costs
down. Teams travel by bus only _ Winslow jokes that he's the only
one allowed to fly, only because he lives in San Diego _ and
players make $200 per game, which means they all hold full-time
jobs. ``It's a grueling schedule for them,'' Winslow said, ``but
really no more demanding than college. They're just working rather
than taking classes.''
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying Winslow on the dais were Skyhawks general manager
Walter Briggs and head coach Earnest Wilson, who used his time _
and then some _ to describe the backgrounds and aspirations of
nearly the entire 44-man training camp roster. Handed a note
telling him to wrap it up, Wilson crumpled it into a ball and
tossed a short pass _ symbolic of his desire to put the players
first. ``Anytime I can talk about my players, I will,'' Wilson
said. ``That's what it's all about. We're going to be good. That's
all I can say.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the players have local ties, including quarterback Eric
Boykin. The former Meadowdale High star is a likely starter, as is
6-foot-1, 315-pound fullback William Houston, a Trotwood-Madison
grad who played at Ohio State and briefly with the Indianapolis
Colts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team is going to be so community based, you will not
believe it,'' Briggs promised. ``Our players won't leave the field
_ and this is a league rule _ until every autograph is signed. No
one here is Michael Jordan.''.
</P>
<P>
   Winslow, a late bloomer who played only one year of high school
football, said he encourages players to be realistic while not
losing touch with their dreams. For some, the IFL can be a path to
the NFL. For many, it will be a hobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone finds a level,'' said Winslow, who has stayed close
to football as a broadcaster in recent years. ``The lucky ones, one
or two, will get a chance to move up _ if they have the ability.
Meanwhile, we're giving them a chance to continue playing a game
they love.''
</P>
<P>
   Sean McClelland writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
