<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3566 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOMATO-HOWTOCARVE18-C     03-17 0233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOMATO-HOWTOCARVE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TOMATO ROSE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. Use a small paring knife to make a quarter-sized cut across
the bottom, but do not cut completely through. Begin to peel the
tomato in a -inch-wide strip, cutting slowly in a continuous
circular fashion. It's important to keep the knife as close to the
surface as possible without cutting through. If you take too much
flesh it won't be as delicate a flower. Use the thumb of your other
hand, positioned on the peel as a guide, and you can feel if the
knife is going to come through. If the peel breaks, just continue
on. The break is easy to disguise. When all the peel is removed,
cut it away from the tomato.
</P>
<P>
   2. Lay out the long spiral of peel and grab the tail. The rose
is created by wrapping the peel in reverse order, flesh side in.
Form a little cone and wrap in a fairly tight circle. If the peel
is in two pieces, just overlap a half inch and continue. Place the
quarter-size piece on top. Grasp the rose in both hands and flip it
over.
</P>
<P>
   3. The finished rose can be used to garnish antipasto platters,
plates of sliced tomatoes, bread salad _ any dish that incorporates
tomatoes. In summer, use red, yellow and pink tomatoes for a
colorful bouquet. Basil or fresh bay leaves add a finishing touch.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
