<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3567 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAITI-FLOPS-$ADV21-CO     03-17 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-FLOPS-$ADV21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HAITIANS STILL RILED AT U.S. OVER NOTORIOUS PIG PROGRAM
 &HT;    With HAITI-FAILURE-$ADV21.
 &HT;    With Photos; Graphic.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., March 21 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti _ For the life of Remy Felix, he just
can't shake the so-called ``pig story.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many other poor Haitians, Felix -- who lives in the
sprawling slum of Cite Soleil --still bitterly recalls how the
United States, alarmed by an outbreak of African swine fever in the
early 1980s, persuaded the Haitian government to slaughter every
pig in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Felix said the resulting economic fiasco did little to endear
the United States to many Haitian farmers. Sadly, it is also
indicative of how the U.S. Agency for International Development
(USAID), which administers foreign aid programs for the U.S. State
Department, has sometimes miscalculated here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those people tried to destroy Haiti,'' Felix said angrily. ``I
remember my family suffering much.''
</P>
<P>
   The story goes like this: Nearly 20 years ago, Haiti officials
had between 300,000 and 400,000 pigs destroyed after U.S.
scientists detected swine fever in Haitian black Creole pigs. By
the late 1970s, hundreds of thousands had already died of swine
fever -- a fatal and highly contagious disease that causes internal
hemorrhaging in the animals -- and fears erupted that it might
spread throughout the hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   By 1984, after the U.S.-supported slaughter, the country was
declared free of the fever. That is when USAID implemented a
controversial plan to spend $5.8 million to replace the black pigs
with white pigs from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   USAID officials argued that the pigs would grow larger, and that
their meat could be exported. What's more, farmers were generally
reimbursed for their loss when a pig was slaughtered and should
look at the new imports as an opportunity to boost their income.
</P>
<P>
   It sounded feasible, and even desirable. Traditionally, pigs had
been an important economic mainstay here. So much so that Haitians
used the same word for both ``pig'' and ``bank.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the new American pigs were shipped in, the farmers
found that they needed a wheat-based, vitamin-enriched feed that
farmers could ill-afford. Also, many of the pigs couldn't survive
the heat. As a result, many of the farmers suffered major economic
losses.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the Haitian government had to import the tougher,
better-adaptable black pigs from Jamaica and other parts of the
Caribbean to replace the depleted population.
</P>
<P>
   ``Haitians politicized this issue, saying we were trying to kill
all their pigs, but actually the farmers were paid quite well,''
said Ernest Preeg, U.S. ambassador to Haiti from 1981 to 1983.
</P>
<P>
   As for the American ``bourgeois pigs,'' as the Haitians called
them, the farmers did get some use out of them. They often served
them up as dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
