</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Thursday, March
18, 1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors won't have to look at every day's budget,
Cox's features budgets have daily themes according tothis schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   Thursday for Friday: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion, science &AMP; health, and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   THE LAYOUT'S DONE FOR YOU: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are
available for purchase in paginated form:
www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   GANGS.COM _ As if drive-bys and turf wars weren't enough, street
gangs are now flashing their colors and flourishing on the
internet. Websites for the Bloods, Crips, and Folkes have been
popping up with the history of their sets, streaming video pictures
of their members and listings of their favorite guns. We talk to
the webmaster who is responsible for designing many of these sites
and to the police to find out if these gang banging web surfers are
for real, or just posers. (Harris, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
25.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS-QUESTIONS _ Q&AMP;A on the news, in two takes. (Bessonnette,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (l, a)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD
</P>
<P>
   COXNET FOOD _ If you don't have a jar of cumin nestled between
the salt and pepper, you are definitely out of step with the times.
Sales of cumin skyrocketed 62 percent between 1995 and 1997,
according to McCormick &AMP; Co., the country's major spice purveyor.
That makes it the fastest-growing spice in this country, outpacing
other spices, which grew a more modest 17 percent. (Heller, Dayton
Daily News) Art includes 3 column color photo of different colored
Cumin seeds.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CUMIN BOX _ How do you pronounce Cumin? (Heller, Dayton Daily
News)
</P>
<P>
   RECIPES _ Moroccan Spiced Steaks, Cumin Cheese Toast, Orange
Avacado Salad.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSPICE _ There is such a wealth of knowledge about herbs and
spices that one could make a lifetime study of these fascinating
plants. And for eons, people have done just that. In ancient times
in many societies, knowledge of herbs and their uses both in
medicine and in cooking set a person apart as a wise and valued
member of the group. Today, these people are on the Internet. There
are many hundreds of excellent sites where individuals, herb
societies and educational institutions share their collected
knowledge for you to explore. (Parham, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD NOTES _ Food fanatics who read the New York Times or
magazines such as Gourmet and Saveur have heard of Piquilla
Peppers, the sweet, slightly piquant beak-shaped peppers from the
Spanish Pyrenees. Given that trendy chefs are so eager to feature
them, it's surprising to learn that the fire-roasted pimientos are
a canned product. (Staff, Cox News Service, N.Y. Times News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet FOOD page for the current week. This
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-FOIL _ Here's a kitchen tool that can help you get meals on
the table faster than ever and eliminate almost all need for
clean-up _ and it's a lot cheaper than a microwave or convection
oven. Wer're talking about alumimum foil. We show you how to make
whole meals in foil packets. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
WITH COLOR PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-FOIL-RECIPES _ Recipe page to go with Foil story
centerpieced on AJC weekly food section. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN _ A weekly beer column by the Michael
Skube of the Atlanta Journal-Constitution. This week: Phoenix
Brewing Company. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-CYBERSPICE _ A weekly column looking at the plethora of
recipes on the Internet. (Parham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-GARNISH _ Dayton food stylist turns tomatoes, radishes,
carrots and mushrooms into works of art. (Heller, Dayton Daily
News). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TOMATO-HOWTOCARVE _ Carving instructions for tomatoes. (Heller,
Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   RADISH-HOWTOCARVE _ Carving instructions for radishes. (Heller,
Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   CARROT-HOWTOCARVE _ Carving instructions for carrots. (Heller,
Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-GOODSTUFF _ Food briefs. By Ann Heller. (Heller, Dayton
Daily News). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   PIZZA-CLASS _ It looks so simple. But can you do it? And have it
come down in one piece _ not on the floor or your head _ suitable
for cooking and eating? We're playing on March Madness and getting
an Austin, Texas pizza restaurant to teach two or three high school
basketball players to toss pizzas, then let each of them give it a
try. (Crider, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   SXSW-AWARDS _ AUSTIN _ The opening night scene from the Austin
Music Awards show at Austin Music Hall, where townies congratulate
themselves and festival goers choose between schmoozing and going
to the first night of showcases. Bands playing the awards show are
Meg Hentges, Resentments, Kinky Frieman, Reckless Kelly w.Joe Ely,
David Garza and Monty Warden/Kelly Willis/Robinson brothers.
(ChrisR, Austin American-Statesman). 15.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SXSW-EDTV _ (15, photo) live coverage of the ``EDtv'' benefit
premiere at the Paramount. Matthew McConaughey, Ron Howard, Ellen
DeGeneres, Anne Heche, Woody Harrelson are just a few of the
celebrities who are expected to be in attendance at this red-carpet
event that is biggest hoopla of SXSW film festival. (Garcia, Austin
American-Statesman). 15.
</P>
<P>
   BLACKART-SHOW _ News story on opening of ``to conserve a
legacy'' art show at the Studio Museum in Harlem. The show is a
major exhibition of African-American art drawn from six
historically black colleges, including Atlanta's Clark-Atlanta
University. (Fox, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WEEKEND AT HOME
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-OSCARS _ Sometimes Oscars are given out for past work _ so
here's a quick roundup of past films from some of the major
nominees you might need to catch on video to level Sunday's playing
field. For example, Judi Dench in ``Mrs. Brown,'' Lynn Redgrave in
``Georgy Girl'' and Ian McKellan in ``Richard III.'' Longino.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-STREEP _ Video of the week: ``One True Thing'' (Grade: B-)
with Oscar nominee Meryl Streep. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-MINIS _ List some of the minis here. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-SPOTLIGHT _ Spotlight on Streep: ``A Cry in the Dark,''
``Death Becomes Her,'' ``The Deer Hunter,'' ``Ironweed,''
``Sophie's Choice.'' (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-NEW _ New releasess: ``The Waterboy'' (Grade: C),
``Bulworth'' (Grade: B-), ``Living Out Loud'' (Grade B+), ``Polish
Wedding'' (Grade: B-). (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-RENTALS _ Top rentals (No. 1 is ``There's Something About
Mary'' plus coming next week: ``Bride Of Chucky,'' ``Mighty Joe
Young,'' ``Pleasantville,'' ``The Temptations.'' plus coming
through April 27 (list includes ``Elizabeth'' and ``American
History X.'' (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-RINGEL _ (Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AUDIO-ORTON _ Beth Orton, ``Central Reservation.'' Grade B+.
(Dollar, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AUDIO-ELTON _ Elton John, others, ``Aida'' soundtrack Grade B-.
(Janich, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AUDIO-RDP _ Roundup of reissues on Capricorn, other items.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
