<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3613 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     03-17 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, March 17, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Thursday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION (San Francisco) _ As San Francisco moves
warily away from using racial preferences in school admissions,
students from three public high schools debated the fairness of
affirmative action. The panel discussion focused on San Francisco
Unified's 15-year- old federal desegregation plan, which is being
phased out by court order and bars the district from using race in
admissions. By JULIAN GUTHRIE.
</P>
<P>
   COPS-BLACKS (San Francisco) _ African Americans file 27 percent
of complaints against San Francisco police even though they make up
only 11 percent of the city's population, according to a new report
by the Office of Citizen Complaints. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   HALLINAN-OBIT (San Francisco) _ Vivian Hallinan, the preeminent
peace activist, wife of the late legal legend Vincent Hallinan and
matriarch of San Francisco's best known Irish political family,
whose members include prominent criminal defense lawyer Patrick
Hallinan and San Francisco District Attorney Terence Hallinan, has
died. By SETH ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OSCARS (Undated) _ ``Eeew'' is an accurate reaction to some of
this year's Oscar nominees. While it's one of the closest recent
collections of races _ the only guarantee is that it will take more
than three hours for all the horses to round the track _ most of
the options just seem staid, safe, conservative. By
</P>
<P>
   TV-C-SPAN (Undated) _ Let's hope you've gone out and bought your
Champagne before it's all gone. Millennium schmennium. We're
talking about history being made on Friday: The 20th anniversary of
C-SPAN. Oh, you can laugh. You can use trusty old C-SPAN as the
butt of a bad joke. But not here. We know C-SPAN for what it truly
is _ the country's most underappreciated network. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DOW-MILESTONE (Albany, N.Y.) _ What does the Dow Jones
industrial average crossing the 10,000 mark _ even if only for a
minute _ mean to most Americans far away from Wall Street? It
probably means the most to consumer confidence in the health of the
overall economy, which in itself is an important influence on the
business world, observers say. By JO-ANN JOHNSTON.
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN (San Francisco) _ The Cult of Greenspan descended on
San Francisco. Attired in suits and golf slacks, the Fedheads and
groupies _ thousands of bankers in town for a conference _ filled
Moscone Center for a fleeting glimpse of The Man. It takes a lot to
get a rise from bankers. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan
did it Tuesday with a shy grin and a half-hour of dull speech. By
EDWARD IWATA.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CRYSTAL-WORLDS (Wattens, Austria) _ Millions of people
worldwide collect tiny Swarovski Silver Cystal figures. Now, in
Wattens, Austria, where the company is based, a spectacular
underground Crystal Worlds has become Austria's second most popular
tourist attraction. By HARRY SHATTUCK. (Photo available on NYT
database.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ The deaths of eight tourists in Uganda
in early March serves as a reminder that as our travels become more
wide-reaching _ and as tour companies seek to satisfy our yearnings
_ they don't always occur without risk. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IRISH-FOOD (Undated) _ Whoever started the rumor that the Irish
can't cook apparently never had an Ulster Fry. More commonly known
as an Irish breakfast, the traditional ``fry'' is nothing less than
a massive assortment of food piled on a plate and historically
served up with a spot of tea. By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   IRISH-WHISKEY (Undated) _ The luck of the Americans. The Irish
are now competing with the Scots in the spirit industry's fastest
growing niche market: single-malt whiskey. And without a doubt, we
are the big winners. Not that the Irish don't know a thing or two
about distilling smooth sipping whiskey. By DOUG BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKW-PERROT (Houston) _ Shortly after learning she had lung
cancer and brain tumors, Kim Perrot discovered something else: She
has thousands of new ``teammates.'' The Houston Comets point guard
has received thousands of calls, cards, letters, e-mails, flowers,
packages and other support from around the world. ``It means a
lot,'' Perrot said while opening her mail. ``It just shows that
people really care.'' By BRUCE WESTBROOK. (Photo available on NYT
database.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Air passengers in upstate New York
are being gouged by the airlines. The one sure way out of this is
creation of a regional airport authority to supplant the local
fiefdoms in Buffalo, Rochester, Syracuse and Albany _ a monster
authority serving 6 million New Yorkers to give upstate the air
passenger clout to force reasonable fares out of the airlines. By
DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   WONG-COLUMN (Oakland, Calif.) _ The claim that Wen Ho Lee was a
spy for China while working in the Los Alamos National Laboratory
sends chills through many Chinese Americans, especially those in
sensitive technology-related jobs. By WILLIAM WONG.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
