<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES GIVE UPSTATE NEW YORK ROUGH RIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The last time I flew out of Albany International
Airport, the flight attendants went through this big production in
the front of the plane. They were showing us how to put on those
little orange cups _ the ones supposedly attached to oxygen tanks
somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I don't think those little masks are there to
deliver oxygen. If you fly in and out of anywhere in upstate New
York, the masks are really there to muffle your howls of agony over
how much you had to pay for your ticket.
</P>
<P>
   The fares are shocking, outrageous, disgraceful, appalling,
dismaying and ... and ... well, they're just too high _ to the
point of criminality.
</P>
<P>
   I'm worked up over this because, for a few years now, I've been
paying to fly a kid back and forth to college in Colorado. My least
favorite spot on this planet is Newark Airport in New Jersey. But
that's where the kid comes in and out of. If we flew him in and out
of Albany International, then we couldn't afford to pay his tuition
to go to school in Colorado in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   But, to save 400 bucks each way? For that kind of money, we
would fly him in and out of Calcutta, which isn't all that
different from Newark, by the way, although it does lack the
glamour. The fact is that every study on this, and there have been
a number of them, shows that upstate New York air fares are
completely out of sight. They are stratospheric _ among the highest
in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines view service to and from this part of the country _
and to everything in the Midwest that isn't Detroit or Chicago, by
the way _ as profit lines. This is where the airlines squeeze out
the bucks. This isn't just about how much it costs me to fly my kid
back and forth to college, although, might I add, that is a matter
of monumental consequence. It's really about jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses need reasonable air fares. Lacking them, they have
one more reason to head somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Given how expensive it is to do business in the Empire State
anyway, and how rotten the upstate New York economy remains despite
the national boom, why do New York politicians permit this to go
on? Well, supposedly, this will be the year that Congress and the
state Legislature will tackle the issue of how astonishingly
expensive it is to fly in any out of upstate New York airports.
</P>
<P>
   The state's congressional delegation is pressuring President
Clinton's Transportation Department to approve more frequent
low-fare flights for this region. Sen. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y.,
is pushing for airline deregulation at four major airports that are
regular destinations for Albany fliers. The idea is to effectively
reduce fares from here to there.
</P>
<P>
   State Senate Majority Leader Joe Bruno has established a task
force to find a way to lower upstate air fares. And Assembly
Speaker Shelly Silver has put together his own air fare committee.
So, wonderful, now we have pleading letters to the Clinton
administration _ which will be on a huge, celebratory drunk for the
next two years after winning this impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   And now we have committees. I feel so reassured.
</P>
<P>
   The one sure way out of this is creation of an Upstate New York
Airport Authority to supplant the little local authorities in
Buffalo, Rochester, Syracuse and Albany _ a monster authority
serving 6 million New Yorkers to give upstate the air passenger
clout to force reasonable fares out of the airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that upstate New York contains more people than all
of Massachusetts, but Logan Airport in Boston has decent fares
because its negotiating efforts are not fragmented as they are in
upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure, local control is a wonderful thing. Yeah, OK,
patronage is the American way. But this is serious business. These
politicians are killing upstate New York economically with this
stuff, just killing us.
</P>
<P>
   And then stifling our screams with those little orange cups.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
