<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-MILESTONE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW MILESTONE HAS RIPPLE EFFECTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JO-ANN JOHNSTON  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ So much waiting and hoping, and all over a
number.
</P>
<P>
   What does the Dow crossing the 10,000 mark _ even if only for a
minute _ mean to most Americans far away from Wall Street? It
probably means the most to consumer confidence in the health of the
overall economy, which in itself is an important influence on the
business world, observers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These types of things have a ripple effect, even as far away
as Lark Street,'' John Samatulski, the new director of the Lark
Street business improvement district, said Tuesday shortly after
the Dow Jones industrial average topped 10,000 for the first time,
then fell back. People are more willing to shop and dine out if
they feel the economy is robust, which is how they interpret such
bullishness on Wall Street, Samatulski said.
</P>
<P>
   The 10,000 mark is strictly a ``psychological barrier,'' but an
important one, said Hany Shawky, who heads the finance department
at the State University of New York at Albany.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tells people that this crazy market is OK and is going to
keep going up,'' Shawky said.
</P>
<P>
   To some people, that's shorthand for: it's safe to spend more
money, Shawky said. That's because the Dow would not have risen if
it were not for the combined effects of influences such as low
inflation, low unemployment, an improved economic climate with U.S.
trading partners _ bits of good economic data that, on their own,
lack the sizzle and the hype of the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the rosy fortunes of a limited number of big stocks on
the New York Exchange do not reflect the much broader picture,
noted Edward LaVarnway, director of investment strategy at First
Albany Corp. Two-thirds of the stocks in the broader Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index have declined in value recently, he said.
</P>
<P>
   So there is no sense in assuming that just because the Dow hit
10,000 _ briefly _ this is a good time to buy any stocks, he said.
Investment decisions should still be guided by long-term goals and
a person's age, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And the optimistic Shawky agreed that some of the brighter
stocks are too expensive to consider buying now because of inflated
prices.
</P>
<P>
   The price-inflation factor creates another psychological impact:
fear. Analysts who quite soberly point out that the difference
between 9,900 and 10,000 is, in reality, negligible are worried
that the market and the Dow index are overhyped. And that could
lead to a disappointing fall in stock values of 20 to 30 percent,
said Mark Arbeter, a technical analyst with Standard &AMP; Poor's
Personal Wealth publication.
</P>
<P>
   Alternately, the market might just ``go sideways'' for the next
six to 12 months, which would also be disappointing to investors
who had come to expect big returns from now on, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations aren't likely to increase their capital spending on
plants or equipment just because of the Dow hitting 10,000, Shawky
said. ``The companies are more realistic,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
