u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-ENVIRONMENT-WEB-$     03-17 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-ENVIRONMENT-WEB-$ADV14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET EVENS THE PLAYING FIELD IN ENVIRONMENTAL BATTLES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By EUNICE MOSCOSO  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They have maps, cartoons, news articles, search
engines and more links than a chain fence. With elaborate Internet
sites, environmental groups have gained a public relations
advantage over the better-funded farm industry.
</P>
<P>
   Basic information about harmful pesticides and about water
pollution from livestock, poultry and dairy farming are available
on the Web sites of groups such as the Sierra Club and the Natural
Resources Defense Council.
</P>
<P>
   But the environmentalists are using the diverse powers of the
Internet to grab attention in other ways:
</P>
<P>
   _ Users can click on a U.S. map and get specific information
about animal waste problems in their state and county.
</P>
<P>
   _ They can e-mail pre-written letters to the Environmental
Protection Agency and the U.S. Department of Agriculture urging
tougher regulations.
</P>
<P>
   _ They can listen to recorded ``citizen's stories'' about the
horrors of living near a large livestock farm.
</P>
<P>
   _ They can link to reports tying animal waste to the toxin
Pfiesteria, which has killed thousands of fish on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   _ With the North Carolina Environmental Defense Fund's ``poop
counter,'' they can even get an up-to-the-second estimate of how
much manure has been produced by North Carolina's 10 million hogs.
</P>
<P>
   Senior attorney Daniel Whittle said the Web page lets the North
Carolina group counter the millions of dollars spent by hog farmers
on lobbying and in advertising against candidates who favor more
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Environmental groups just cannot match the resources the
industry has,'' he said, ``so we saw the Web as an ideal tool to
get people informed.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups are heavily linked on the Internet.
National groups have links to each other and to state groups which
have links to local grassroots organizations.
</P>
<P>
   In response to increasing attacks from environmental groups, the
National Pork Producers Council has devoted space on its Web site
to proving that pork farmers and producers are good stewards of the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When somebody is contending that something is true and it
isn't ... we try to correct it in any way we can _ that's one
way,'' said Steven Cohen, spokesman for the 85,000-member group.
</P>
<P>
   The site includes detailed answers to charges from environmental
groups, followed by extensive citations of research studies.
</P>
<P>
   Some other livestock groups, however, have not been so quick to
use the Internet for such serious issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Web pages for the National Broiler Council, which represents
most of the nation's chicken farmers and producers, carries lighter
fare. It teaches how to reinvent classic chicken recipes, how to
handle poultry safely, and how Vitamin B in chicken is good for the
heart.
</P>
<P>
   The pages for the National Turkey Federation, which represents
about 95 percent of the nation's turkey farmers and producers, are
similar. The main page features a ``Chef of the Month'' and leads
to 12 links about ``Cooking with Turkey'' and 15 on ``Culinary
Trends.''
</P>
<P>
   Some farm associations, such as the Texas Farm Bureau, have
``legislative updates'' on their sites, along with information on
crop insurance and market trends. But most state farm bureau sites,
which are rarely linked to each other, are dedicated to member
services and education programs.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
