<HEADLINE>
AMERICA ONLINE GROWING UP _ AND OUT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  With COX-AOL-GRAPHICS-0314 
By MARY BETH REGAN  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DULLES, Va. America Online President Stephen M. Case was piecing
together a struggling online company in 1994 when he heard of a hot
new Internet startup, Netscape Communications. He desperately
wanted to buy that company.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he's had to wait five years to do so.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, (March 17) Netscape shareholders are expected to
approve the sale of their company to AOL in a stock deal worth more
than $8 billion. If the deal is also cleared by the Justice
Department, it would catapult AOL into new business markets and
solidify its position as a major player in online advertising and
electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``This industry is like looking at a 17th century geopolitical
map of Europe,'' says James Kimsey, AOL's founder and former
chairman, and now head of its non-profit foundation. ``Everyone is
trying to marry off his daughter to strengthen alliances. There's
no doubt Netscape is a key strategic play for us.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL is the nation's largest online service, with 16 million
members. Netscape's Netcenter is one of the most frequently visited
Internet sites. Once the companies are combined, AOL can use
Netscape's Internet browser to lessen its reliance on Microsoft,
whose Windows operating system is one route to AOL. The deal also
should help the consumer-focused AOL atpipe we use,'' says Kimsey.
</P>
<P>
   AOL's anywhere, any way strategy is aimed at developing an
online media company whose services that can be accessed from
devices ranging from computers to cell phones to pagers.
</P>
<P>
   ``AOL could even be on your electric toothbrush one day,'' jokes
Matt Korn, the company's senior vice president of network
operations.
</P>
<P>
   That strategy could be key to holding onto AOL's dominant online
position, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today there are any number of ways to access the Internet
--phone lines, cable lines, ADSL lines and wireless,'' says Bill
Whyman, an Internet analyst with Legg Mason Research Technology
Team in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The value is who controls the customer relationship,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   The man behind AOL's drive to build that needed loyalty is Case.
When Case joined AOL's predecessor, Quantum Computer Service, in
1983, he was 24 and the company was nothing more than a
cyber-experiment. Since then, he has guided the company through a
handful of near-death experiences _ including an uproar created by
subscribers frustrated over troubles connecting to AOL _ and more
recently to better-than-expected financial results.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, fiscal-year revenue has climbed to $2.16 billion
from $98 million, and earnings per share to a split-adjusted 14
cents a share from less than 1 cent per share. Wall Street expects
revenue for the fiscal year that ends in June to hit $3.9-$4
billion, and earnings of about 33 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   The company also is growing overseas. AOL International now
operates in the United Kingdom, Germany, Switzerland, Canada, Japan
and Australia. It will launch AOL Hong Kong this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The international markets are like watching the U.S. market on
fast-forward,'' says Jack Davies, president of AOL International.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts attribute AOL's success to a handful of key decisions.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Case started mass-mailing 250 million free AOL disks to
the public. A risky move, it has been credited as helping make AOL
one of the best known consumer brands in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, he changed the pricing structure from a per-minute
charge to a flat fee. Today the service costs $21.95 monthly. As a
result, members are staying online longer-- up from an average of
14 minutes online per day then to an average of 55 minutes daily
now.
</P>
<P>
   The same year, there iness decisions. The company has responded
by has increasing its lobbying force from two to five people. And
it is in the process of setting up its first political action
committee to give money to candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The company also has been instrumental in setting up the Open
Net Coalition, staffed by Vice President Al Gore's former
technology staffer, Greg Simon, and former National Republican
Committee chairman Rich Bond, to lobby for government intervention
in the cable wars. AOL and others, including MindSpring
Enterprises, want regulators to force cable companies to make their
lines available to competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what's really going on here is that they are trying to
slow down the deployment of broadband technology because they are
not in a position to dominate that market,'' says James Cicconi,
AT&AMP;T's general counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Ulric Weil, managing partner of the Arlington-based Friedman,
Billings, Ramsey brokerage firm isn't concerned AOL will be left
behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``AOL will do a deal when they have to,'' he says. ``AOL
wouldn't even get out of bed for the numbers these cable companies
have.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
