<HEADLINE>
IT'S IRELAND VS. SCOTLAND ON THE SINGLE-MALT FRONT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The luck of the Americans. The Irish are now competing with the
Scots in the spirit industry's fastest growing niche market:
single-malt whiskey. And without a doubt, we are the big winners.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Irish don't know a thing or two about distilling
smooth sipping whiskey. Black Bush, Jameson's, Paddy's, Powers and
Tullamore Dew are all excellent examples of the Emerald Isle's
ability.
</P>
<P>
   But they are also blends, vatted with less costly grain whiskeys
in order to lower production costs as well as price. During the
past decade, their sales have been dwarfed by single-malt Scotch
whiskeys, which, by shrewd marketing, have captured the American
imagination like no other spirit in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking high-end, conspicuous consumption, of course.
Forty or more dollars a bottle. Is it only a coincidence that sales
of single-malt Scotches and pricey sport utility vehicles are
occurring at the same time the stock market is soaring?
</P>
<P>
   No matter. The Irish are entering the fray. Let us welcome them.
Knappogue (pronounced nuh-Pogue) Castle, named after the castle on
Ireland's west coast in County Clare, has during the past year
slowly become available in the United States. The sole importer is
Great Spirits in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   It is a superb single malt, crisp and clean with delicate malt
notes. Many of the Scottish single malts use peat in the malt
drying process, while Knappogue does not. Hence, it is less smoky
and less intense than, say, Lagavulin, Cragganmore or Talisker.
</P>
<P>
   Knappogue Castle 1991 has a suggested retail price of $32, about
20 percent less than most of its Scottish competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The distillery also produces a 1951, which was aged 36 years in
oak sherry casks and bottled in 1987. It is regarded as the finest
and rarest Irish whiskey available in the world, according to
whiskey expert Jim Murray. At $600 per bottle (yes, six big ones),
it better be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
