<HEADLINE>
DEVICE MANAGER, SITES HELP KEEP DRIVERS UPDATED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
c.1999 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Q: Where and how does one check to make sure one has
the latest drivers? If the latest drivers are found to be needed,
where does one locate them?
</P>
<P>
   A: Both Windows 95 and 98 have a feature called the Device
Manager that lets you see what's connected to your system and what
resources it is using. You can also use the Device Manager to
upgrade and remove drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Device Manager also will tell you the date on your drivers, if
you know where to look.
</P>
<P>
   To get to Device Manager, right-click on the My Computer icon,
choose properties, then click on the Device Manager tab. You'll see
a list of components on your system.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, let's find the date on the driver for your video
card. Double-click on Display Adapter _ the item will open to show
you your particular brand and model. Double-click on it.
</P>
<P>
   At the dialog box that appears, click on the Driver tab. You'll
then see the date for the driver.
</P>
<P>
   Next, go to the Web site for the maker of that device. Let's say
you have a Viper V550 video card from Diamond Multimedia. You'd go
to Diamond's Web site (www.diamondmm.com), find the support area
where new drivers are listed and find the one for the Viper V550.
</P>
<P>
   Download it into your computer. If you're unsure about how to
download software, see the Web site mentioned in this week's Other
Voices column offered by CNet _ it's a step-by-step tutorial for
downloading software.
</P>
<P>
   Many Web sites also have instructions, or one may be included in
a README.TXT file that comes with the drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've upgraded all your drivers, check the Web sites at
least once every 60 days to see if there are newer drivers. Video
drivers are upgraded frequently.
</P>
<P>
   You can also check at any of several Web sites that track
updates, including Frank's World o' Windows at
www.conitech.com/windows/, WinDrivers at www.windrivers.com and The
Driver Zone at www.driverzone.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the Feb. 5 Help Line in the Technology Section, you
supplied an answer to a question about why Windows reports a
6.4-gigabyte hard disk as 5.9 gigabytes. Your answer, I think,
misses the mark. Manufacturers use a factor of 1,000 when
converting bytes to kilobytes, megabytes and gigabytes. If a
manufacturer builds a disk of 6,400,000,000 bytes, they report its
size as 6,400,000 kilobytes, or 6,400 megabytes, or 6.4 gigabytes.
</P>
<P>
   Windows, on the other hand, uses a factor of 1,024 for each of
the conversion steps, so in Windows terminology, 6,400,000,000
bytes is equal to 6,250,000 kilobytes, or 6,103 megabytes, or 5.96
gigabytes.
</P>
<P>
   Although both expressions refer to exactly the same capacity _
in this case, 6.4 billion bytes _ the manufacturer's terminology
makes it sound bigger than Windows' terminology. Just more
marketing hype.
</P>
<P>
   A: Actually, we are both right. However, you are more right than
I am. And it's not marketing hype, but a difference in the way they
are counted.
</P>
<P>
   According to Western Digital, the largest manufacturer of PC
hard drives, there are two ways to count bytes _ decimal, which is
what the drive and BIOS makers use, and binary, which Windows uses.
That accounts for most of the difference.
</P>
<P>
   However, as indicated by the frequently asked questions document
at www.westerndigital.com/service/FAQ/win98.html, some megabytes
indeed are lost to formatting overhead. In some cases, a computer
BIOS may also claim a cylinder _ a segment of drive space _ for its
own purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Got a question about your computer? Maybe Dwight Silverman can
help. Send e-mail to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call
713-220-2000 and enter access code 1001.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
