<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWSERS ANONYMOUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yes, Hiawatha Bray is my real name, though some refuse to
believe it. I've had people compliment me on dreaming up such a
splendid pen name, one that makes me sound mysterious and exotic.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I'm about as exotic as the south side of Chicago. And
being named Hiawatha Bray can have its disadvantages for an
Internet journalist. When I post a message on the Internet's Usenet
bulletin board system, seeking tips on how to beat a computer game,
I sometimes get replies like this: ``Are you THAT Hiawatha Bray?
Your column stinks. Get a clue! P.S. Love your nickname.''
</P>
<P>
   You can see why I sometimes post Usenet messages anonymously.
The ability to communicate across the world without having to
identify yourself is one of the Internet's most attractive
features. It's also proving to be one of its most troublesome.
</P>
<P>
   Anonymity is often the enemy of clear communications. For one
thing, it liberates people to engage in rude on-line ``flame
wars,'' secure in the knowledge that their vulgarity won't earn
them the black eyes and busted lips they deserve.
</P>
<P>
   Others use their anonymity to spread information that's just not
true, or information that was supposed to remain confidential.
Lately certain aggrieved parties have fought back through the
courts, thereby demonstrating how flimsy Internet anonymity can be.
</P>
<P>
   In our own back yard, Raytheon Co. is suing 21 employees for
disclosing company data in a message board run by the Yahoo
Internet service. Trouble is, Raytheon doesn't know who the
employees are. So it's gone to court to subpoena their identities
from Yahoo. If the subpoena is issued, Yahoo says it will comply.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in no way trying to harm freedom of expression,'' says
Raytheon spokesman Dave Polk. ``We're trying to protect proprietary
information.'' But civil libertarians fret about a chilling effect
on Internet free speech.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Rotenberg, Georgetown University law professor and
executive director of the Electronic Privacy Information Center,
notes that courts have upheld the right of political activists to
preserve their anonymity. But companies like Yahoo that provide you
with Internet services usually require that you identify yourself,
and the courts say that this personal data can be subpoenaed.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to complain about this. I have no patience with people
who give away company secrets or spread hurtful lies on the
Internet, then cower behind the shield of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   And yet anonymity can be a godsend for the battered spouse
looking for help, the corporate whistle-blower, the journalist
looking for tips. If cases like Raytheon's continue to mount, will
any on-line anonymity be left to us?
</P>
<P>
   Just a bit. E-mail offers some hope of secrecy, through
``anonymous remailers'' that route e-mail through several
computers, making it very hard to trace. But because of the
complicated path your message takes, it can take hours or days for
a remailed message to arrive. In addition, you can't use remailers
to post Usenet messages without a fair amount of technical
knowledge and a good deal of work.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are Internet discussion sites that don't care who you
are, and don't collect any personal info, not even your real name.
There are places like the geek hangout Slashdot
(http://www.slashdot.org), where you can publish criticisms of the
latest technologies under the generic nickname ``Anonymous
Coward.'' Or consider Free Republic (http://freerepublic.com), a
rambunctious conservative Web site that welcomes anonymous insults
of liberals in general and President Clinton in particular.
</P>
<P>
   There are many such places on-line, but all in the minor
leagues. Major providers of free e-mail like Yahoo collect
information about you, if only to sell you something. I use one of
these free accounts to post my ``anonymous'' Usenet messages, but
I'm not anonymous to the company that provides the service. I'd
better watch what I say about Raytheon.
</P>
<P>
   These secret Web accounts are about as anonymous as license
plates: Civilians can't read them, but techies and cops sure can.
But they do offer some protection from unwanted junk mail, as well
as a chance to dream up a clever new name for yourself _ a severe
challenge for me. How do you top Hiawatha?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(E-mail Hiawatha Bray at bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-11-99 1336EST &QL;
</P>
