<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-WEBTV-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG CAM ON CAMPUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers 
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
 By NATHAN COBB   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Mike Kaplan, aka Smoot, allowed the Web camera to be
installed in his Brandeis University dorm room last month, thereby
giving all the world an Internet peek at his life, it was the kind
of exposure he certainly didn't mind. Indeed, it was enough to make
the 20-year-old junior forget that he'd recently been rejected as a
candidate for ``Real World,'' MTV's slice of twentysomething life.
Being seen on the Net would do just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I'm on camera,'' Kaplan announced proudly in his journal,
which accompanies the online snapshots of his fourth-floor room in
Ziv Quad. ``Go me.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to WebDorm. True, there are no dining halls here, no
vending machines, and little that would pass for partying. But,
hey, this is virtual college life, with tiny cameras in about two
dozen dorm rooms across the country sending snapshots every 30
seconds to a commercial Web site (www.webdorm.com). WebDormers, who
use aliases, can also chat online with visitors, post their musings
in their journals, and receive messages in a ``guestbook.'' But the
principal hook here is clearly the spherical black QuickCams which
make semi-stars out of just plain undergrads.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Lioy, known as NeonQueen around the WebDorm, keeps her
camera on top of three CDs, which rest atop a computer printer,
which squats on top of a small desk, which is tucked into the
corner of a jam-packed Emerson College dorm room in downtown
Boston. Lioy, an 18-year-old freshman majoring in TV production and
says that kickboxing is just about her favorite thing to do,
decided to become a WebDormer for a common reason: ``It seemed like
a cool thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do normal teenage stuff,'' is the way Lioy describes her
dorm life. ``I sleep, eat, read, do homework, talk on the phone. To
the other college students who watch me online, I'm someone. .
.what's the word?. . .someone to identify with.''
</P>
<P>
   As tiny as Lioy's room is, the QuickCam covers only a portion of
it. That's fine with Jessica Fogel, Lioy's roommate, who strongly
perfers to stay out of camera range. ``I don't really get it,''
Fogel muses of the desire to appear on the Net or to sit at a
distant computer and shmooz online with WebDormers. ``But if these
people are having their fun, why not?''
</P>
<P>
   (One WebDorm visitor from New Hampshire recently expressed his
skepticism in a different way. ``All that time on the computer
could be spent doing something constructive, like drinking,'' he
wrote.)
</P>
<P>
   WebDorm is part of Woburn-based CollegeWeb.com, a small company
which was founded last June by Alex Chriss, now a 21-year-old
senior at Tufts University. Chriss's motivation _ besides signing
up advertisers _ was to counter what he calls the ``lazy,
beer-drinking, party-animal'' stereotype of college students.
Participants are not paid (although they can keep their cameras
after a semester as WebDormers), and they're chosen after filling
out an email questionnaire. ``There are no real rules, but we do
ask them not to do anything illegal,'' Chriss says. ``If it ends up
being boring, well, that's real college. This isn't scripted. It's
not Hollywood. There are no explosions and there's no sex, although
the WeDormers can show whatever they want to show as long as it's
not illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   Spend some time in the WebDorm, however, and you'll discover
that they don't show much. Voyeurs will be sorely disappointed.
Cameras are frequently pointed at desks, and always away from
bathrooms. They tend to reveal the likes of cluttered closets,
music posters, or someone watching TV. Frequently there aren't even
any human beings in the pictures. Or there might be a sign, to wit:
``I'm on Spring break!! Back on 3/6/99 :)''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Chriss's ``real college'' can be _ and is _ highly
edited by its participants. At Brandeis, Kaplan readily admits he
enjoys the idea of being on camera, but he never forgets its
presence. ``I'm very careful of where I stand when I don't have any
clothes on,'' he points out. He's also cautious when his girlfriend
visits. ``Obviously, we're not going to broadcast something
indiscreet,'' he says. ``There are times when we point the camera
someplace less. . .interesting.'' (There's no audio track in the
Webdorm.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, neighbors who visit their WebDorm friends are given
fair warning. ``You're on camera while in this room,'' a sign
announces at each door. Says Chriss: ``This is not a candid
camera.'' Still, a cameo appearance on the Net carries a certain
cache. ``All my friends want to come over and sit in front of the
camera,'' says Brian McGunagle (screen name: Jose), a 20-year-old
sophomore WebDormer at Trinity College in Connecticut. ``They think
being on the Web is like being on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   WebDorm's conservatism comes as good news to Sandy Lioy, Katie's
mom. When her daughter told her last month that she was taking her
dorm life online, Sandy Lioy was a tad concerned. ``I was worried
that someone might find out who she is and track her down,'' she
says. ``Maybe I'm overprotective, but I'm her mother. I was also
worried about her privacy. But now that I know she can just show as
much of the room as she wants to, I feel better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, now I can check up on her. Like, one day she put a
sign over the photo of her room. It said, `I'm doing homework now.
Don't bother me.' So I wrote in her guest book, `It does my heart
good to see your parents' money being put to good use.' ''
</P>
<P>
   WebDormers and WedDorm administrators are armed with the
technology to boot out any virtual visitors whom they feel are
acting inappropriately, and Chriss admits this has happened on a
number of occasions. At the University of New Hampshire,
19-year-old sophomore Amanda Patrick (``Sassy'') says that one
thing being a WebDormer has taught her is that ``There are a lot of
weirdos out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been guys who've asked me and my roommate to flash
the camera,'' Patrick laments. ``And there was a guy who said he
was in his 40s who was coming on to my roommate. We kicked him out,
but it was a little disconcerting.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Chriss reports that there is no shortage of college kids
who want to matriculate at WebDorm. ``We've had hundreds of
applications since the site went up,'' he says. ``It's become a
celebrity symbol.'' He also talks of expanding to foreign
universities, and of someday forming a WebDorm alumni association.
``We even got an email from a professor who asked us, `Hey, why
don't you have a `ProfessorCam?' '' Chriss says.
</P>
<P>
   WebDormers must depart their virtual college after a semester.
Katie Lioy, for one, has mixed feelings about graduation. ``I've
gotten to meet some interesting people and I do get attention,''
says the Emerson freshman as she hunkers down in front of the
camera in her well-crammed dorm room. ``But this is just a new
hobby, really. Once it's over, I'll find something else to do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-11-99 1333EST &QL;
</P>
