<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Column: Old Files Are Never Forgotten  
 By David Einstein   
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Question: &LR;  I have a Windows 95 computer that I am thinking
about donating. But before I do, I want to make sure that my hard
drive is completely erased. I've heard that files deleted in the
usual way can still be recovered. What can I do to ensure that all
the files have been purged?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  You heard right. Files can often be recovered even
after you've sent them to the recycle bin and emptied it. In order
to completely expunge data from a disk, you should overwrite it
multiple times with other information. Fortunately, there are some
free downloads that can do that for you. Two popular ones are
BCWipe from Jetico and Eraser from Sami Tolvanen. (There's also a
good $30 shareware program from East Technologies called Eraser.)
All of these programs are at www.hotfiles.com.
</P>
<P>
   Blame the Batteries
</P>
<P>
   Q: The clock in my PC has been slowing down lately. I suspect
it's a battery problem and would appreciate confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yep, your system's battery is probably the culprit. You
should replace it now, because if it fails altogether, you might
not even be able to start your computer. That's because the battery
makes it possible for the computer to retain critical system
information even when it is turned off.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing to do is contact the company that made the PC and
find out what kind of battery it has and whether or not you can
replace it yourself. If not, you'll have to take it to the service
center in a computer store.
</P>
<P>
   Fight the Power
</P>
<P>
   Q: There are so many types of surge protectors available, rated
at various levels of protection. What is the minimum necessary to
protect my computer?
</P>
<P>
   A: I get this question a lot during winter, when lightning
storms tend to knock out power lines. A basic surge protector just
prevents a sudden surge in power from reaching your computer
system. A typical unit is a specially rigged strip of outlets that
lets you plug in four or six devices, and costs less than $20.
</P>
<P>
   If you're using your PC when the lights go out, however, a surge
protector won't prevent the loss of documents you're working on.
For that, you need an uninterruptible power supply, or UPS. This
device uses a battery to keep your system alive long enough for you
to save any in-progress work and shut down your PC and any
peripherals properly. More-expensive ones can even let you continue
to work for a half hour or so.
</P>
<P>
   UPS units cost from less than $100 up to several hundred
dollars. American Power Conversion, a leading maker of UPS devices,
has a feature on its Web site (www.apcc.com) that helps you
determine what level of protection you need.
</P>
<P>
   Meet the Twain
</P>
<P>
   Q: My publishing software refers to my scanner as a Twain
device. What in the heck does that mean?
</P>
<P>
   COL. 1 of COMPUTE1 (78543 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: Twain stands for Technology Without an Interesting Name.
Honest. It also stands for an interesting American writer. In the
computer world, Twain is a technology standard that allows many
different types of scanners and digital cameras to work with
software such as programs for publishing and managing digital
images.
</P>
<P>
   If you're able to use your scanner with your software, then
don't worry about Twain. All it means is that you've got a good
thing going.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ICON UPDATE &LR; : It turns out that Quicken 99 does let you get rid
of the icon that it puts in the Windows system tray. Open Quicken,
select Options from the Edit menu, then choose Internet
connections. In the dialog box that appears, go to the section
labeled Background Downloading and change the option from ``Enable
for shorter, faster Internet sessions'' to ``Don't use background
downloading.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; TIP OF THE WEEK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most stores won't let you return software for a refund once it's
been opened. So it helps if you know what you're getting before you
commit any cash. Many software companies let you download demo
versions that you can try before you buy. To see if a demo version
is available for a particular program or game, check out the
software maker's Web site, or search for the title in an online
software library such as www.hotfiles.com or www.download.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to computers(at
sign)sfgate.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-10-99 2130EST &QL;
</P>
