r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRISH-FOOD-HNS &LR;      03-17 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISH-FOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCK OF THE IRISH BEGINS AT BREAKFAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whoever started the rumor that the Irish can't cook apparently
never had an Ulster Fry. More commonly known as an Irish breakfast,
the traditional ``fry'' is nothing less than a massive assortment
of food piled on a plate and historically served up with a spot of
tea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Breakfast was the big meal of the day,'' said Harold Qualters,
the great-grandson of Irish immigrants who is now general manager
of the Troy Pub &AMP; Brewery in Troy, N.Y. ``People think of it as
staple, hard-working and lacking in refinement, but it was an
honest and healthy meal.''
</P>
<P>
   More healthful in fact than today's morning fare.
</P>
<P>
   The typical Ulster Fry contains a fried egg, two bangers, two
rashers, two slices each of black and white puddings, scones or
potato farls, a couple of sauteed mushrooms and a slice or two of
roasted tomato. If everything except the egg, mushrooms and tomato
sound a little foreign, here's a brief primer on Irish cuisine:
</P>
<P>
   _ Bangers: Ireland's version of sausages. These links of ground
pork are much leaner than American sausages and lack the sage and
other spices that flavor our version. They fry to a rich golden
brown color, leaving very little fat in the pan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rashers: Instead of bacon, the Irish fry up thin slices of
boneless pork loin. Again, less fat than Americans usually eat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Potato farls: These, Qualters said, are a bit like Irish soda
bread but made into rolls instead of a loaf.
</P>
<P>
   _ White pudding and black pudding: Puddings in the British Isles
are not the custard-like mixtures we're used to. Irish white
breakfast pudding is a mixture of ground pork, oatmeal and
flavorings formed into a roll and steamed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Black pudding (WARNING! Here's where people get a little
squeamish) is colored and flavored with the blood of pigs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a breakfast to keep you going until lunch,'' said
Qualters.
</P>
<P>
   And the Irish have a tradition of making more food than is
needed for any meal. Perhaps it's because in ancient times, Brehon
Law decreed that strangers were to be fed and entertained by Irish
families, regardless of the family's economic stature. At mealtime,
the front door was left open to welcome travelers, according to
Bord Bia, promoters of Irish food exports.
</P>
<P>
   From the humble, yet hearty beginnings of the Ulster Fry, Irish
breakfasts have evolved into more sophisticated fare. Qualters, who
ran an Albany restaurant that featured Irish breakfasts, served up
a dish he called Celtic Eggs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was similar to a typical rarebit (cheese sauce on an
English muffin), but scones made with green onions took the place
of the English muffin. The scones were topped with a rasher of
Irish bacon, a poached egg and a cheese sauce made from Blarney
cheese and Harps (Irish made beer),'' Qualters said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Qualters substituted just poached salmon (revered in
Irish mythology as a source of wisdom) for the rasher and
Hollandaise sauce with chives and capers for the cheese sauce. A
lighter, yet still hearty meal. Other Irish mornings included items
such as Potatoes O'Brien (fried spuds with onions and red and green
peppers) cooked into an omelet with Blarney cheese. Or, even
simpler, a breakfast of scrambled eggs, salmon and scones.
</P>
<P>
   So, next time you think the Irish can't cook, look in your
pantry and count the number of cereal boxes you have. Then think of
the Ulster Fry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BUTTERMILK SCONES
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 4 to 6)
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 cup buttermilk, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups unbleached flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 400. Lightly coat a baking sheet with cooking
spray. Stir the baking powder into a little of the buttermilk to
dissolve. Mix the baking soda, flour and remaining buttermilk using
a wooden spoon. Add the salt and baking powder solution and mix
thoroughly. Roll out dough on a lightly floured surface and cut
into scones, about 2 inches in diameter. (Recipe makes 12 to 15
scones.) Place on prepared baking sheet and bake for 15 minutes or
until lightly browned. Split the scones, spread with lashings of
butter and serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   (Note: According to the author, ``lashings means liberal
quantities, some where between oodles and scads.'' Source: ``Irish
Country Cooking'' by Malachi McCormick, Clarkson Potter, 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Though not as interesting as Qualters' cheese sauce made with
beer, this recipe will suffice when making Celtic eggs at home.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHEESE SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 4)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon margarine
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups milk, warmed
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups grated Blarney cheese (see note)
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter in a medium saucepan. Add flour, salt and pepper and
stir to mix thoroughly. Gradually pour in warmed milk and, stirring
constantly, bring mixture to a rolling boil. Add in cheese and stir
until cheese is melted and mixture is smooth.
</P>
<P>
   (Note: Blarney cheese is a semi-hard Irish-made cheese. If
desired, substitute a good Finlandia Swiss or shredded cheddar
cheese.)
</P>
</TEXT>
