 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Snap launches site about Holocaust 
(Eds: Sunday night means 3/14.) 
By Frances Katz  
c. 1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somewhere at the intersection of commerce and content, Web
portal Snap found itself a conscience.
</P>
<P>
   The NBC/CNet-owned Web portal has launched its extensive
Holocaust Resource Center to coincide with NBC's airing of the
Steven Spielberg film ``Schindler's List'' on Sunday night. Users
who want to access the resource center should go to
http://www.snap.com and type in ``holocaust'' in the search box.
</P>
<P>
   The Holocaust Resource Center is a well-organized site built to
help educate viewers about the Holocaust and help promote
Spielberg's nonprofit Shoah foundation, which documents stories of
Holocaust survivors.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a pleasant experience. Categories such as
``concentration camps'' aren't easy to click on, and an eerie sense
of gloom pervades.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the kind of thing that's designed to drive
traffic,'' says Edmond Sanctis, Snap's chief operating officer.
``The film is incredibly powerful and an important film. From our
perspective, it's something we are proud to be associated with as a
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Snap, like its portal competitors Yahoo!, Lycos, Exite and
Netscape's NetCenter, has been unabashedly about commerce and
utility. The site has the usual assortment of sports scores, stock
quotes, shopping and e-mail ``sticky products'' designed more for
utility and return visits than anything else. In the portal arena,
where ``sticky products'' are everything, a site devoted to
commemorating horrific acts of human cruelty and suffering is no
sticky product.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true most of our messaging to the public has been
whimsical and practical ways to be useful and have fun,'' says Snap
Executive Producer Katharine English. ``But we are all information
junkies anyway; this was a chance to bubble up to the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   English says Snap and other portals in the business of
collecting and organizing information are the ideal companies to
build informational and educational sites for users that don't
necessarily have anything to do with selling books or NCAA Final
Four pools.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what the Internet does best,'' she says. ``Think about
how much information you can access _ it's awesome. It's
overpowering. But the days of feeling awed by the power of
information have largely waxed and waned in the age of commerce and
utility and giant corporate mergers. But all this information
hasn't gone away. Look at the number of new sites that launch every
day. The Internet isn't just about mergers and stock quotes.''
</P>
<P>
   English says content is what drives the Web, though new users
probably don't know that yet. ``People who are coming online today
think it's all about e-mail and gaming, but it's not. It's about
accessing rich, deep areas of Internet information.''
</P>
<P>
   English is right. Before portals were all about news, weather,
sports and shopping, they were simple ``search engines'' that
helped Web surfers hunt down the volumes of information on the Web
they could never locate on their own.
</P>
<P>
   It is true the Holocaust Resource Center isn't going to draw as
much traffic as ESPN SportsZone, GeoCities or even Mr. Showbiz, but
Snap doesn't care. The company says this is an opportunity to
gather its resources and use them to help educate and inform Web
surfers who are moved by the film and want to learn more.
</P>
<P>
   However, everyone at Snap is quick to say this isn't a publicity
stunt or a gimmick to get viewers to leave their TVs and log on to
Snap. The site will be up long after the movie has aired and will
remain a resource on the site indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get some mileage from this on air, that's great, but
that's not why we did it,'' English says. ``It's really about
bringing to the front the kind of work this team does every day
that isn't that high profile and raising awareness to the Shoah
Foundation in another venue _ online. When you stop to think about
it, we're all so commerce-driven here in Silicon Alley start-up
land. More people think of their stock options rather than teaching
kids to read.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's an opportunity to give people access to information
they never had before. This is where the Internet is really alive.
Somebody took the time to assemble this information,'' adds
English. ``This is also where the power of convergence of TV and
online media really manifests. We have the opportunity to drive
people to television and tell them to watch this very important
film based on a true story.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably hundreds of thousands of people who have no
idea who Oskar Schindler is. But if they have been touched by the
power of this painful yet uplifting kind of story, it doesn't have
to end for them there. They can go online and take it a step
further and find a place to get involved or try to understand how
something like this could have happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always talk about convergence, but from my perspective
this is just the beginning. It's our opportunity to weave this
information into users' minds,'' English says. ``It should be
people like us (who build these sites). ``We have access to this
information. It shouldn't be buried; it should be high profile.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-15-99 1100EST &QL;
</P>
