 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Astronomy sites offer assistance in searching night sky 
By Bill Husted  
c. 1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For many people, the answers are in the stars.
</P>
<P>
   Forget horoscopes and the Academy Awards and go outside tonight
and look up. Those little sparkling points of light _ the stars _
and those larger lights that do not twinkle _ the planets _ have
provided answers and beauty since the first humans walked the
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   To learn about them and enjoy them, you need nothing more than
your eyes and mind (if you throw in your heart, they'll be even
more beautiful). In fact, most astronomers recommend that novices
postpone buying a telescope and spend some time just observing
using the naked eye or binoculars and a good star chart. A star
chart is simply a map of the skies that helps you find and identify
the larger objects.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find many useful resources on the Internet. While you'll
eventually want to buy a star chart, you can get online help
locating objects in the sky at a page called Stig's Sky Calendar at
http://www.skycalendar.com
</P>
<P>
   /skycal/index.html. (If you use a search engine, you'll find
several charts of the night sky on the Net).
</P>
<P>
   Now that you know what it'll take to get started, you'll want to
read a little bit about astronomy. In this case, too, you'll
eventually want a good book for beginners. But you can find plenty
of information online. Let's start with the Beginner's Guide to
Naked Eye Astronomy at http://user.icx
</P>
<P>
   .net/(tilde)ngc457/nakedeye.htm. You'll learn the basics that
can make watching the skies more enjoyable.
</P>
<P>
   Continue your education by hitting the back button on your
browser to go to a more general section of The Beginners Guide (or
simply type in http://user.icx
</P>
<P>
   .net/(tilde)ngc457/beginner.htm). This page offers all sorts of
useful information _ everything from star charts, to advice on
selecting a telescope or pair of binoculars, to articles that will
help you identify the constellations. Knowing the constellations is
a great help, since you can use them as landmarks to the rest of
the wonders of the sky. Since it's fairly easy to recognize the
major constellations, you'll save a lot of time as you search the
skies.
</P>
<P>
   If your interest in astronomy continues, a couple of things are
likely to happen. You'll eventually want a telescope, and you'll
also have questions about astronomy that aren't answered in the
books you own or the Web pages you find.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet can help in both areas.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with the search for a good telescope. Let's suppose
you don't have an unlimited cache of money. There's a terrific page
called How to Choose a Quality Telescope for Under $500 at
http://www.eecs.uic.edu
</P>
<P>
   /(tilde)dlent/btel.html. This site is exceptional because it
literally leads you by the hand in a series of pages that begin
with explaining the basics of the optics telescopes use. You'll
learn there is more than one type of telescope and find out about
the advantages and disadvantages of each type. Finally, after your
education is complete, you'll wind up on a page that gives you
addresses for some reputable companies that sell telescopes. One
bit of advice to take to heart: Avoid any telescope that costs less
than $100. The optics will be so bad you'll be better off using
your naked eyes or binoculars.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's find some places where you can get direct answers to
your questions. Several astronomy groups offer this service
including: Curious About Astronomy? Ask an Astronomer at
http://astrosun.tn.cornell.edu
</P>
<P>
   /students/kornreich/curious
</P>
<P>
   /curious.html and Outer Orbit: Ask an Astronomer at http://
</P>
<P>
   www.outerorbit.com/ask
</P>
<P>
   /index.html.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
