<HEADER>
A3705 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-ELTON18-COX     03-17 0260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-ELTON18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Headley is the star by far on John's `Aida'
 &HT;    By Kathy Janich
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether on disc or onstage, Elton John's ``Aida'' has one
shining moment. It's Heather Headley snap-crackle-popping her way
through ``Elaborate Lives,'' an anthem of forbidden love and its
dicey consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Hers is the brightest jewel on this pop version of John and
lyricist Tim Rice's stage musical, the genuine article among what
is mostly costume jewelry. Joining Headley are cast member Sherie
Scott and popsters Sting, LeAnn Rimes, Tina Turner, the Spice
Girls, Boyz II Men, Shania Twain, Lenny Kravitz, Janet Jackson and,
of course, Elton, who gets to sing more than anyone else. (His
game, his ball?)
</P>
<P>
   Although enjoyable, this ``Aida'' is a puzzle. Just who is it
for? It's more show music than pop but probably won't sate either
audience. It's more money grab than artistic vision, its heart and
ego at odds, much like the legend's Egyptians and enslaved Nubians.
</P>
<P>
   Yet who can't see the fun in the Spice Girls' ``My Strongest
Suit,'' a fashion-forward pastiche on clothing, makeup and
accessories? Or the truth in the John-Rimes love duet ``Written in
the Stars''? Or the drama in Twain's ``Amneris' Letter''? The disc
is truly a mixed bag. We wonder, will it sell?
</P>
<P>
   ``Aida''
</P>
<P>
   Elton John, various artists.
</P>
<P>
   Rocket. 15 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Kathy Janich writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
