<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3706 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-ORTON18-COX     03-17 0303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-ORTON18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Orton's emotions shine through
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tech-friendly folkie Beth Orton has a voice that cuts through
static. She's not demonstrative or hydraulic, but she wins you over
almost immediately with her unvarnished realness and low-key
vulnerability. It's an interesting quality for the British singer
to have, because she's been aligned with the burgeoning electronic
dance music scene _ lending guest vocals to the Chemical Brothers,
for instance _ that thrives on souped-up artifice. On ``Central
Reservation,'' her second album, Orton comes across as a late '90s
exponent of the soulful introspection that guided Van Morrison and
Joni Mitchell in the early '70s.
</P>
<P>
   And like those artists, she's not confined to the coffeehouse
idiom _ she knows how to twist syllables free of their meaning,
opening up the realm of pure suggestion. She's mutable, slipping
from the chimey ambience of the opening ``Stolen Car'' (a piece
whose arrangement recalls those of retro-heartbreak specialist
Chris Isaak), to the strings-and-vibes laden ``Pass in Time'' (an
``Astral Weeks''-ish hymn, featuring forgotten '70s singer Terry
Callier), to a dance remix of the title track (tweaked by Ben Watt
of Everything But the Girl).
</P>
<P>
   Lyrically, there are no earth-
</P>
<P>
   shaking revelations. A line such as ``All your pain just turns
into release/All your doubt becomes your own belief'' probably
wouldn't sell a condolence card, but Orton can make you listen to
it and nod along because of the feeling she puts behind it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Central Reservation''
</P>
<P>
   Beth Orton. Arista/Deconstruction. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
