<HEADER>
A3707 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-RDP18-COX     03-17 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-RDP18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Audio roundup
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton, Miriam Longino and Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Fuse'' Joe Henry. Mammoth. 11 tracks. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   There's a whole mess of Joe Henry's devoted fans who don't care
a whit that he's related by marriage to Madonna (wife Melanie is
the Material Diva's sister). They appreciate the North Carolina
songsmith for his adventurous, expansive body of work, which seems
to morph into thrilling new shapes with each album. Henry's eighth
release ripples with a soulful groove that is far removed from the
earnest country-rock of his critically lauded 1993 album ``Kindness
of the World.'' Such trip-hoppy tracks as ``Angels'' and ``Fat''
suggest a marriage between Leon Russell and the Sneaker Pimps. Best
of all is the title cut, a languid ballad with a '70s R&AMP;B flavor.
Henry's easy command of myriad styles should give even his
chameleonic sister-in-law pause.
</P>
<P>
   _ Doug Hamilton
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ``Always Never the Same''
</P>
<P>
   George Strait. MCA. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Dipping into George Strait's new CD is like a trip to the
springhouse _ you know exactly what you're going to get, and it
tastes great every time. The main drawback in this collection of
solid country is that only a couple of tracks are standouts from
the usual down-home Strait meal: the clever Kostas tune ``One of
You'' and the sweet love song ``That's Where I Wanna Take Our
Love,'' by Dean Dillon and Hank Cochran. Strait is one of those
stars whose talent is so consistent it can often become redundant,
like vacationing at the same beach house for 10 years in a row. In
fact, the title track is a lazy reworking of a shuffle off Strait's
last CD, ``We Really Shouldn't Be Doing This.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Miriam Longino
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  R&AMP;B
</P>
<P>
   ``100% Ginuwine'' Ginuwine. 550 Music. 16 tracks. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Here's how you break ``100% Ginuwine'' into its individual
parts: First, there's a whole lot of Timbaland. The producer, who
made his debut on Ginuwine's million-selling 1996 debut, ``The
Bachelor,'' twists and turns his keyboard in less predictable
directions than the chaotic drum machine sound that's become his
signature. Give Ginuwine an equal share of credit for proving as
limber vocally as the bouncy production on ``What's So Different?''
and approaching the emotive ability of Sam Cooke on ``None of Ur
Friends Business.'' The re-
</P>
<P>
   mainder is a tolerable hodgepodge of clever scenarios (``Fin-
</P>
<P>
   al Warning''), an uninspired cover (``She's Out of My Life'')
and a kind of vulnerability rarely revealed by male R&AMP;B artists.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton, Miriam Longino and Sonia Murray writes for the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
