<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-NEW18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In stores this week
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton, Steve Murray, and Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service``The Waterboy'' (PG-13) _ A
<TEXT>
watered-down comedy. After a successful stab at romantic comedy in
``The Wedding Singer,'' Adam Sandler returns to his lowbrow roots
with this ``Happy Gilmore'' rewrite about a bayou bumpkin who
becomes a college football star. It's dumb and predictable, which
would be OK if there were more laughs. But Kathy Bates is hilarious
as Sandler's domineering mama. Grade: C
<P>
   _ Doug Hamilton
</P>
<P>
   ``Bulworth'' (R) _ Provocative, funny and unbalanced _ just like
politics. Director, star and co-writer Warren Beatty plays the
titular senator from California, who breaks down while watching his
latest re-election commercials. Hiring a hit man with himself as
the target, he returns to campaigning, where his meltdown becomes
very public. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   ``Living Out Loud'' (R) _ A suddenly single fortysomething
(Holly Hunter) leaves her tony Upper East Side co-op and ventures
into new territory, a cross-town jazz bar, where she becomes
friends with the resident torch singer (Queen Latifah), and has a
``kinda'' relationship with her building's elevator operator (Danny
DeVito). The tone is bittersweet, the story unresolved, but the
performances are fresh and funny. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _ Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   ``Polish Wedding'' (PG-13) _ Though it played the art-house
circuit, this is more like a ``Moonstruck'' wannabe than anything
Christina Ricci has done lately. In Detroit, a large Polish family
wrestles with everything from adultery to teen pregnancy. Director
Theresa Connelly's film may be shaky and cliched, but her strong
cast (Lena Olin, Gabriel Byrne and Claire Danes) comes to her
rescue. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _ Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton, Steve Murray, and Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes
for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
