</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-OSCARS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unrewarded roles may aid actors at Oscars
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cramming for Sunday's Oscars? Sometimes it pays not only to see
the nominated films but to take a quick gander at an actor's
previous work on video.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar history is littered with winners who often won for earlier
films. Elizabeth Taylor copped her first Academy Award in 1960 for
the lame ``Butterfield 8,'' not because she was great in it but
because she was sick and reportedly near death. Plus, she had been
overlooked three times in the '50s for Oscar-worthy performances:
1959's ``Suddenly, Last Summer,'' 1958's ``Cat on a Hot Tin Roof''
and 1957's ``Raintree County.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Michael Caine won a best supporting actor trophy for
``Hannah and Her Sisters.'' He probably deserved it. But it helped
that he'd previously been nominated for best actor _ and lost _ for
even better performances in 1972's ``Sleuth'' and 1966's ``Alfie.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this year's acting nominees deserve to be in their races.
But a few might have an edge based on history. To accurately gauge
Sunday's playing field, check out some of their earlier work on
video.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Robert Duvall (``A Civil Action,'' supporting actor) _ Prepare
to be amazed.
</P>
<P>
   Duvall has more than held his own in a steady flow of
tremendously powerful films filled with powerful actors. ``To Kill
a Mockingbird.'' ``The Godfather.'' ``The Godfather, Part II.''
``Apocalypse Now.'' ``The Great Santini.'' ``Network.'' ``MASH.''
``Tender Mercies'' (which won him a best actor trophy in 1983).
</P>
<P>
   While he does light up the screen in ``A Civil Action,'' it's
more likely he's nominated this year for losing last year.
</P>
<P>
   Check out ``The Apostle.'' It's the film Duvall nurtured on his
own, financed on his own, made virtually on his own and marketed
pretty much on his own. He played a preacher confronting his own
demons, copped a best actor nomination and promptly lost to Jack
Nicholson's showy performance in ``As Good as It Gets.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Judi Dench (``Shakespeare in Love,'' supporting actress) _
Everybody's talking about her limited screen time as Queen
Elizabeth in ``Love'' and whether that might rule her out of this
year's race.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar doesn't work that way.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, Beatrice Straight won for roughly five minutes of
screen time, the bulk of that in one scene, as the jilted wife of
William Holden in ``Network.'' In that one scene, Straight hijacked
the film.
</P>
<P>
   So does Dench in ``Shakespeare in Love.'' Plus, on video she's
got a stellar performance in ``Mrs. Brown,'' the film that brought
her a best actress nod last year. She lost to Helen Hunt's _ again
_ showy performance in ``As Good as It Gets.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Brown,'' Dench plays a different queen _ Victoria. The
results, though, are nearly identical. She commands every frame
she's in.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ian McKellen (``Gods and Monsters,'' actor) _ His fine-tuned
performance as ``Frankenstein'' director James Whale in ``Gods and
Monsters'' is surpassed by his remarkable portrayal of political
evil in 1995's Nazi-laced rendition of ``Richard III.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lynn Redgrave (``Gods and Monsters,'' supporting actress) _
She's a curious stitch in ``Gods and Monsters'' in the watchable
role of Whale's tic-laden housekeeper, but 33 years ago she was
equally noticeable as an ugly-duckling mod in Britain's groovy
``Georgy Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   The role landed her a nomination for best actress, a race in
which she promptly lost to Elizabeth Taylor (``Who's Afraid of
Virginia Woolf?'').
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ed Harris (``The Truman Show,'' supporting actor) _ As the
godlike tele-artist Christof in ``Truman,'' Harris shows the
ethereal side of his acting that moviegoers haven't really
witnessed before.
</P>
<P>
   But what they have seen are rock-solid characterizations,
including the manic salesman in 1992's ``Glengarry Glen Ross,'' the
focused mission chief in 1995's ``Apollo 13'' (he was nominated for
supporting actor but lost to Kevin Spacey in ``The Usual
Suspects'') and the cheating husband seeking redemption in 1984's
``Places in the Heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
