<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-STREEP18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `True'-blue Streep is only thing slick weeper has going for it
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``One True Thing'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   If there's ever a time to catch ``One True Thing,'' it's now.
</P>
<P>
   Meryl Streep is nominated for an Oscar for her pitch-perfect
characterization of the dying homemaker mom from Anna Quindlen's
book. Trouble is, the movie strikes too many false notes to be the
three-hankie weeper it wants to be.
</P>
<P>
   The drama centers on Renee Zellweger, playing career-journalist
Ellen Gulden, dubbed by her colleagues to be ``cold and
insensitive.'' She's the opposite of her mom (Streep), and once
they're thrown together it's clear Ellen can't keep up.
</P>
<P>
   Streep's performance is terrific, but the movie suffers from
generic slickness. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
