<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 12:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3744 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      03-17 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 Special to The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; SWIMMING WITH JONAH &QL; 
 &UR; Audrey Schulman (Avon, $22)
</P>
<P>
   Schulman's first novel, ``The Cage,'' was the harrowing story of
a woman who joined a magazine expedition to northern Canada, where
she took photographs of polar bears from inside a metal cage set on
the ice. It was a rite of passage of sorts for its protagonist _ an
emergence into a strength and resilience that she did not know she
had _ and there is a similar transformation in Schulman's new
novel. Jane Guy, daughter of a prominent doctor and a beautiful
ballerina, cannot get into medical school in the United States and
so is accepted _ because her parents can pay an exorbitant tuition
_ at ``the boot camp of medical schools'' on a tiny Indonesian
island. The school is meant for problem students, rich students,
those who failed, for one reason or another, to gain acceptance
elsewhere. The tactics of the teaching staff involve psychological
abuse, which seems even worse in the dense, tropical atmosphere of
the island, the heat and humidity that make test papers come back
sweat-stained from the hands of the teachers who graded them. There
is a sense of desperation in Jane and the other students as they
dream of leaving this dreadful school. Jane begins to change,
however, coming into a new self-awareness and even bravery.
Ultimately, she is transformed in this story of an unsettling,
menacing place and the things it brings out in the people who are
trapped there. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; SUCH A PRETTY, PRETTY GIRL &QL; 
 &UR; Winston Groom (Random House, $23.95)
</P>
<P>
   ``Book reviewers can be pissy, can't they?'' a character says in
Groom's new novel, and it's especially true when a reviewer finds
herself locked in a room with a book like this one. Groom
(``Forrest Gump'') has produced a rather poor imitation of the old
detective novels we love, which brings up the obvious question: Why
take this detour if you can still have the real thing? The
narrator, an Oscar-winning screenwriter named Johnny Lightfoot,
meets up with an old flame, Los Angeles news anchor Delia Jamison,
who has ``worn well'' in the 20 years since Johnny saw her last
(she still has those ``wide, lush, Deborah Norville lips,'' we're
happy to say). Trouble is, poor Delia is getting anonymous letters
and phone calls from someone who obviously knows her _ he's
familiar with her sexual habits, but so are half the men in Los
Angeles _ and is demanding that she wear certain clothes during a
broadcast or leave the top buttons of her blouse undone. Even
though her husband's best friend owns a detective agency, and even
though Johnny Lightfoot writes screenplays for a living, Delia asks
Johnny to help her out. He's a novice sleuth but smart enough to
know that ``no trap is as deadly as the one you set for yourself.''
In this case, that would be his lingering feelings for Delia
Jamison. The narration is plodding and the climax is dopey, and not
even the lovely Delia can save the day.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ROBERT FROST &QL; 
 &UR; Jay Parini (Holt, $35)
</P>
<P>
   He once said, memorably, that each of his poems was ``a
momentary stay against confusion.'' Robert Frost struggled
throughout his life with depression and self-doubt, but he was
also, Parini writes, ``a man of immense fortitude, an attentive
father and an artist of the first order who understood what he must
do to create a body of work of lasting significance, to `lodge a
few poems where they can't be gotten rid of easily,' as he often
said.'' This sympathetic reading of Frost's life and work was a
labor of love for its author _ ``one of the few books,'' Parini
says, ``that I have ever finished with deep reluctance.'' Included
is a section called ``Frost and His Biographers,'' in which Parini
suggests that Frost has not been well-served by the people who have
written about him. Early profiles and biographies portrayed him as
a farmer-poet full of homespun wisdom, a persona Frost himself
promoted. Then came Lawrance Thompson, Frost's official biographer,
who portrayed Frost as a monster (the word appeared more than once
in the three-volume work, giving reviewers the image of Frost as a
selfish, egomaniacal, cruel man _ ``a more hateful human being
cannot have lived,'' one wrote in the ``New York Times''). Later,
there was reaction against Thompson, including ``Robert Frost: A
Literary Life Reconsidered,'' by William H. Pritchard. Parini says
his own book ``sets the record straight here and there, putting in
place a fresh mythos, one that combs the facts in a certain
direction but does not preclude a future biographer (and there will
be many) from combing the same material differently.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WORK WOULD BE GREAT IF IT WEREN'T FOR THE PEOPLE &QL; 
 &UR; Ronna Lichtenberg (Hyperion, $22.95)
</P>
<P>
   We can see you now, nodding as if Lichtenberg was in your head
when she thought up that title. It's her premise that no one can
avoid office politics, and it's OK to be good at them. She even
sugarcoats it: Being good at office politics ``means you know how
to turn individual agendas into common goals.'' Where, you ask,
does the back stabbing come in? Between the lines. Actually, this
is a funny book, with subject headings such as ``Politics in the
Time of Cholera'' and ``How to Suck Up'' and ``You Are Where You
Eat'' and ``Come Blow Your Own Horn.'' We learn that hair and nails
are political tools for women (in certain parts of the country,
Lichtenberg says, ``you want your hair to be blonde, immobile, and
to extend as far from your skull as possible''), and watches and
shoes are strategic choices for men. She also includes some short
quizzes, which New &AMP; Notable took and failed. Like so many worker
bees, we have a lot to learn. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(You can reach correspondent Anne Stephenson at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net, via e-mail.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
