<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-PERROT-ART-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
FANS HELP GIVE WNBA's PERROT STRENGTH IN BATTLE AGAINST CANCER 
 
(Photo available on NYT database) 
 
By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Shortly after learning she had lung cancer and brain
tumors, Kim Perrot discovered something else: She has thousands of
new teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Since revealing her illness last month, the Houston Comets point
guard has received thousands of calls, cards, letters, e-mail
messages, flowers, packages and other support from Houston and
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot,'' a smiling Perrot said while opening her
mail, which was piled high on the desk of Comets and Rockets owner
Leslie Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those who have written and said prayers _ we're all on a
team now. They're part of my team, and I feel good, because if I'm
praying and doing what I need to do and other people are praying
for me, I can't lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA's Web site link to Perrot had to be discontinued when
it was overwhelmed by more than 5,000 e-mail messages. Other
electronic mail has been forwarded to Perrot from local TV and
radio stations and the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   A book-size print-out of the electronic messages is being
compiled for Perrot by Megan Bonifas, Comets manager of media
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked and saddened at the news of your illness,'' a
man e-mailed from Oakland, Calif. ``But I was encouraged by your
attitude and determination.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone I know is talking about what a fighter you are,''
wrote a Houston fan. ``No one expected you to become starting point
guard for the Comets. Take that fiery determination and hustle and
focus all that energy and talent on this new fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Banners and cards have also arrived from radio stations, Texas
Children's Cancer Center Families and Special Olympics. Many who
wrote wanted to share their own experiences about battling disease.
</P>
<P>
   Perrot, 32, had surgery Feb. 24 to remove a golf ball-size brain
tumor. She now is undergoing 2{ weeks of radiation treatment for
smaller tumors and soon will start six months of chemotherapy for
lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ritsuko Komaki, who is overseeing the treatments, said
Perrot's excellent health improves her chances and she is
``confident'' the remaining tumors can be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   While Perrot's doctors are optimistic, hospital spokeswoman Jane
Brust said the treatment is ``a process, and they're cautious about
long-term results or giving a long-term score card. It will be a
while before there's a real clear picture of how she's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Perrot isn't approaching her recovery in quiet seclusion.
She has quickly resumed her public life, which now has an even
larger stage.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night she attended gospel singer Kirk Franklin's
Compaq Center concert, where 10,000 fans joined in prayerful
support.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Perrot also resumed her motivational speaking
appearances at area schools. In the basketball offseason, she talks
to students about fitness, education, diligence and saying no to
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Her illness won't change that message, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life has a plan, and this is just another chapter,'' Perrot
said. ``It all revolves around the same thing _ the struggles I've
had _ and how throughout those struggles I've always won the
battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is another battle. It's just a bigger battle. I will
still tell my story.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, she is reading up to 50 cards and letters each night
and plans to read ``every single one of them, word for word.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone took time to write me, to send their blessings and
prayers, it's more than fair for me to read what they sent.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot hopes to find a way to respond to each person, perhaps
with help from the Comets media staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's possible, we'll send every single person a thank-you
note,'' she said. ``I can't individually write everyone, but I do
want them to know that I received their letter and read it and am
thankful for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellow cancer sufferers Darryl Strawberry of the New York
Yankees and Eric Davis of the St. Louis Cardinals also have called
to offer support, as did comedian Bill Cosby, representatives of
the Rev. Jesse Jackson's Rainbow Coalition and WNBA president Val
Ackerman. And she's received flowers from the Rockets' Charles
Barkley and the Indiana Pacers' Reggie Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Perrot doesn't distinguish between celebrity supporters and
everyday fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every prayer, every letter, means the same in my heart,'' she
said. ``I've had celebrities call _ people I didn't know, had only
seen on TV _ but I've also been touched by all the people who wrote
to share their story about a family member or a friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one means more than the other. All of this means a lot to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot did give special thanks to the Comets and Rockets
organizations for their support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Becoming a Comet _ that right there changed my life.''
</P>
<P>
   She has already resumed light workouts at Westside Tennis
Center, where the Comets and Rockets practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not 100 percent where I'd be if I didn't need surgery, but
I'm doing the right things, taking it slowly and doing what my body
allows me to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``My training isn't as intense as it would be, but that's OK.
I've got to start somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot hasn't circled her calendar for the Comets' training camp
in mid-May, ``because a year ago I wouldn't have circled it,
either,'' she said. ``I'm just living like I would normally.''
</P>
<P>
   At 5-feet-5 and without being a draft pick, Perrot was a
long-shot to make the team. But she persevered and quickly evolved
into the Comets' quarterback and emotional leader on the floor
through two championship seasons.
</P>
<P>
   While this tenacity reflects a positive outlook Perrot has
nurtured since long before her illness, the ordeal has sparked an
even better attitude, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today I was walking my dog, and I picked up a flower just to
appreciate it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a positive person, but not to the point where
one flower, one breath, meant so much. I took the little things for
granted. Now I appreciate nature and just breathing because I'm
fighting for my life.''
</P>
<P>
   She feels the huge outpouring of support has boosted that
battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see us all as a team,'' Perrot said. ``I play for the
Comets, a two-time champion, and now I have a worldwide team.
</P>
<P>
   ``These cards and letters have given me strength. It's
unbelievable _ amazing. Words can't describe what this support does
for me. It has touched me immensely, and I thank God for that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
