<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW EXPLORATIONS CAN BRING RISKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They never intended to make a political statement. They only
wanted to see the gorillas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight tourists slaughtered by rebels in Uganda,'' headlines
relayed the tragic story early this month.
</P>
<P>
   Two Americans. Four Britons. Two New Zealanders. No doubt
exhilarated by the opportunity to stretch the limits of their
travel experiences, to broaden their educations, to savor the
thrill of a new and exotic encounter with nature.
</P>
<P>
   Just like so many others among us.
</P>
<P>
   But victims instead of a band of Hutu guerrillas angered by
American, British and Ugandan support for the present government of
Rwanda, its neighboring East African country.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ALWAYS A DANGER &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Did these tourists sense the perils of their journey? We may
never know. They were by all accounts sophisticated, experienced
travelers. Even though the project they came to visit dates only to
the 1990s, several thousand people before them had traveled without
incident to and from Bwindi Impenetrable Forest, a national park
tucked into the southwestern corner of Uganda that is home to about
320 mountain gorillas, half the world's remaining population.
Reports indicate that new guerrilla threats against U.S. and
British visitors had not been forwarded to tour companies.
</P>
<P>
   This tragedy serves as a reminder that as our travels become
more wide-reaching _ and as tour companies seek to satisfy our
yearnings _ we're not always shielded from risks. We've learned
this in other foreign countries, and in our own.
</P>
<P>
   Does this mean we should avoid extending our horizons? An
emphatic no. Should it heighten our awareness, encourage us to
learn as much as possible about a nation or a region or a people in
advance of a trip? A resounding yes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
IT'S A SMALL WORLD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Consider how times have changed:
</P>
<P>
   A half-century ago, we fantasized about seeing the Eiffel Tower,
Vatican City, the beaches of Hawaii and the glaciers of Alaska. A
trip to the Great Wall of China or Peru's Machu Picchu was beyond
our wildest imaginations.
</P>
<P>
   Now that television and the jet airplane have shrunk the world,
our appetites are whetted not just for these wonders but also for
deeper explorations. No place is too remote, too mysterious, for
our desire to taste adventure, to appreciate nature and to
understand distinct human cultures.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought in the late 1960s and early '70s that
Vietnam would emerge as one of the most popular Asian vacation
destinations for Americans? Or that a Marriott hotel would beckon
visitors to Moscow? How likely was it a decade ago that U.S.-based
tour companies would now be sponsoring organized excursions to
Iran? How long before Cuba is reopened to mainstream U.S. tourism?
</P>
<P>
   Through years of war and internal conflict, Uganda hardly seemed
a place many of us would relish visiting. But, according to one
leading authority, Bwindi represents ``an exemplary ecotourism
project.''
</P>
<P>
   Martha Honey, director of the peace and security program at the
Institute for Policy Studies in Washington, D.C., and author of the
newly released ``Ecotourism and Sustainable Development: Who Owns
Paradise?'' (Island Press, $25 paperback, $50 cloth), lived for
several years in Tanzania, just across the Ugandan border. Her
earlier books include ``War in Uganda: The Legacy of Idi Amin''
(Lawrence Hill), written with husband Tony Avirgan and published in
1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've walked across Uganda; I've taken many steps in that
national park,'' Honey said during a recent visit to Houston. ``The
people of Uganda were doing so much right with tourism there. The
World Wildlife Fund has spent considerable time and effort in the
park. The local villages were involved in getting people to the
camps. And unlike in many other places, a large percentage of the
profits from tours were being retained for the park and for
community development.''
</P>
<P>
   Though tours usually operated at 100 percent _ and with a price
tag of about $150 for one hour of viewing _ only small groups were
allowed to track the gorillas made famous by the 1988 movie
``Gorillas in the Mist,'' which focused on mountain gorillas in
Rwanda. According to Honey, Ugandan officials had successfully _
and honorably _ resisted pressure from tour companies to allow more
people (and thus more potential income) into the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was raising 40 percent of Uganda's tourism profits,''
Honey said of the Bwindi project. ``That will be dead now. (Indeed,
most tour companies have temporarily canceled trips to the area.)
Tourism in neighboring Kenya and Tanzania will be affected, too.
And the mountain gorillas may well be slaughtered by the human
guerrillas.''
</P>
<P>
   One lesson for tourists, Honey suggested, ``is the need to be
more conscious about what politics we support when we travel. This
is important not only for our personal safety but because travel
does make a political statement. It was that way in South Africa
during apartheid. In Uganda today, these marauding bands don't like
our politics, and they're out to get Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's important, too, Honey said, ``to recognize that this is
an isolated situation. We have to let people know that not all
places in that area are dangerous, that Tanzania and Kenya aren't
dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, we can only hope that Bwindi _ and the mountain
gorillas within _ will someday be safe again to visit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
