<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTONBOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOINT COMPOUND WILL SMOOTH BEAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for Indianapolis and all needing; moved March 11.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Q. The rough-hewn beams in my family room are almost black. I
not only want them smooth, but I'd also like to paint them lighter.
I would not want to box them in because that would make them too
big for the room. I've heard that you can apply joint compound to
smooth them out and then paint. Would that work?
</P>
<P>
   JANE WISLEDER, Hingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You betcha. You answered your own question. The roughness of
the beams will allow the joint compound to stick well, even
resisting peeling when the wood expands and contracts. To make sure
the compound will resist peeling, apply as thin a coat as possible.
The more coats, the smoother the finish, but it is better to stick
to one, two at the most. Paint with two coats of a flat or eggshell
latex wall paint.
</P>
<P>
   Q. My Corian countertops are scratched, and I was told to sand
out the scratches. I power-sanded and made a mess; the surface is
now very uneven, with different glosses. What did I do wrong, and
is there any way I can improve the surface?
</P>
<P>
   M.S., Andover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I think that while sanding is good to take scratches and
stains off Corian, power-sanding is not. Try steady, overall
hand-sanding with the finest sandpaper you can obtain, or emery
cloth. Or, use one of those stiff plastic scrubbers of a coarse
consistency; the kitchen Scotch pads are not stiff enough. If you
are reluctant to do that, call the dealer or Dow, the manufacturer;
they might have additional suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have some metal casement windows that have no
weatherstripping; the windows close with a metal-to-metal contact,
not very good for weather-tightness. Where can I find a retrofit
seal for such casements?
</P>
<P>
   PETER ZIMMERMAN, Concord, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I suggest using self-adhesive foam tape. Press it in place on
the frame where the window closes on the frame. This way the window
will press against the foam, compressing it when the window is
closed. With this method there will be no frictional wear on the
foam. It will simply be compressed, which does not amount to much
wear and tear.
</P>
<P>
   Window places might carry a weatherstrip just for metal windows.
</P>
<P>
   Q. My 1961 house has a septic tank, which is OK, but my
neighbor's failed the state's Title 5 test, so I am a little leery
of mine. Now we are getting sewers in the street. Are there any
negatives to a hookup to city sewers?
</P>
<P>
   JOHN HART, Natick, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Absolutely none, in my opnion, and I speak from experience,
having had a cesspool for some years that was creating a dismal,
smelly swamp in the back yard. I had good reason to go to sewers
when they came in, and I think I was the first in my block to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   It would be wise for you to be the first (or second, after your
neighbor) to hook up. It'll cost a sum to hook up, and the annual
sewer charge will nearly equal the water bill, because sewer usage
is calculated on water usage, but I think you will be happy with
it.
</P>
<P>
   And there is a bonus: Your septic tank won't need pumping out
anymore. Of course, the savings won't equal your annual sewer
charge, but you'll rest easy knowing there is no septic system to
fail.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's the best time to start painting the outside of my
house? Is there anything more to preparation than scraping and
sanding?
</P>
<P>
   ANDREW WALL, Somerville, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Paint when the temperature is 50 degrees Fahrenheit or higher
and will stay that way, and below 90 degrees. This information is
on the can of stain or paint. Scraping old paint and sanding are
the two most important parts of preparation. And you can start
anytime while waiting for painting weather. Another important part
of preparation is to wash or power-wash with detergent and water
after sanding.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
