<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES-CANDIDATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPITALIST RETOOL: FORBES TRIES FOR A WIDER APPEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The first impression of Steve Forbes's presidential
campaign is that he seems little changed from his failed 1996
effort. He has many of the same sound bites. He promotes the same
17 percent flat tax proposal, again disputing those who say it
especially benefits the wealthiest Americans. He retains the same
awkward, engaging smile.
</P>
<P>
   But the publisher of ``Forbes: A Capitalist's Tool,'' who
Tuesday filed his candidacy papers and campaigned in New Hampshire,
in fact has carefully retooled his strategy. The man who once
called Christian Coalition founder Pat Robertson a ``toothy flake''
now spends much of his time portraying himself as the true
religious conservative. The man who in 1996 suggested that only
late-term abortions be banned does not shy away from urging that
nearly all abortions be made illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, at a time when some consultants say a Republican can win
only by running toward the middle, Forbes is sprinting to the right
as fast as he can. Forbes, whose net worth has been estimated
between $500 million and $1 billion, is making a classic investment
gamble, investing millions of his dollars on one sector, wagering
that the conservative Republican activists will determine the
party's nominee.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to woo social conservatives is only part of Forbes's
new game plan. Like a businessman studying a company's failure,
Forbes has analyzed his failed 1996 bid and found that he was
destined for defeat because he relied too much on his money and too
little on grass-roots support. This time around, while Forbes
certainly will keep on spending his money, the big difference is
that the publisher has spent much of the past three years seeding
his operation with grass-roots supporters and hiring some of the
best political operatives money can buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I ran in '96, we were very late getting in,'' Forbes said
in an interview. ``We did not have the kind of grass-roots
organization in the early states. This time we will have the
ability to get grass-roots efforts in all of the early states.''
</P>
<P>
   The grass-roots support has not suddenly sprung up, but rather
has been carefully nurtured by Forbes through his creation three
years ago of a private group called ``Americans for Hope, Growth
and Opportunity.'' The group has 145,000 donors and members, many
of whom now are considered likely Forbes supporters. Significantly,
the group paid for campaign-style ads featuring Forbes that have
helped keep his message alive in key primary and caucus states.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said his effort to reach out to members of groups such as
the Christian Coalition does not mean he has had a change of heart
on social and religious issues. Instead, Forbes said, the move
reflects his frustration in 1996 at being unable to get past what
he considers the unfair opposition to his candidacy by leaders of
some conservative groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time I went to the rank and file,'' Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, the 2000 campaign is tailor-made for a
candidate such as Forbes. The primaries are so front-loaded next
year that many analysts believe the nomination will be secured
within a few weeks after the first-in-the-nation New Hampshire
primary. Only two or three of the best-financed candidates are
likely to have the money to run simultaneous commercials in
California, New York, and other states that will all hold primaries
in a two-week period after New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The potential trouble for Forbes is that he may be running the
right kind of campaign for 1996, but not for 2000. Tuesday, for
example, Forbes stood in front of the New Hampshire State House in
Concord and signed a pledge against enacting new taxes at a time
when the state is changing its attitude on the issue, as indicated
by the legislature's recent move toward passage of the first income
tax.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, meanwhile, still faces many of the same questions from
1996 about whether his tax plan mostly benefits the rich. Notably,
Forbes did not directly address that question on his campaign web
page, which was introduced with much fanfare Tuesday. (The site is:
http://www.forbes2000.com).
</P>
<P>
   The web page, for example, provides a chart that explains the
benefits for families earning $70,000 or less, but it does not say
how it will affect those making more than that. That is a telling
omission, according to Robert McIntyre, director of the
labor-backed Citizens for Tax Justice.
</P>
<P>
   According to Forbes, the flat tax will result in the elimination
of income taxes for those earning $30,000 or less, a 70 percent cut
for those earning $40,000, and a 27 percent cut for those earning
$70,000.
</P>
<P>
   But McIntyre said all people in those groups could wind up
paying more taxes because of levies on health insurance benefits
and other items. Moreover, McIntyre said, wealthier people,
especially those earning more than $185,000, would get huge tax
cuts because Forbes would eliminate the tax on capital gains,
dividends, and interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is huge at the high end; if you are a millionaire, your
tax cut would be in the hundreds of thousands of dollars,''
McIntyre said. ``The top marginal rate of 39.6 percent would come
down to 17 percent, and his plan to eliminate the tax on capital
gains, interest, and dividends means there would be no tax on much
of the rich's income.''
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre said he is also troubled by the estimated $200
billion-a-year drain on the Treasury that he said would result from
the plan. Forbes has countered that the tax cut would unleash so
much money and enterprise that government revenues could actually
increase.
</P>
<P>
   To allay fears that his plan would raise taxes, Forbes said
taxpayers would have the option of filing under the flat system or
the old progressive rate.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes also is bound to face questions about how the plan will
affect him personally. In 1996, Forbes's holdings were reported by
Fortune magazine at around $440 million, and some analysts say the
soaring stock market of the past several years may have doubled
that amount. Forbes declined to say how much he is worth, but one
of his spokesmen, Greg Mueller, put it this way: ``The Clinton
economy has been good for a lot of people, no question about it.''
</P>
<P>
   That raises the question of whether a candidate selling a
Reaganesque vision of a tax cut and supply-side economics can
succeed when the economy is rolling along. Mueller said that while
times are good, there is so much uncertainty in markets such as
Asia that the time is ripe for a person with Forbes's experience on
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose, Forbes may be the 800-pound gorilla in the race
whom no one can ignore. That is because Forbes has proven he is
willing to spend his money on some of the most negative campaign
commercials in recent campaign history, which in 1996 helped doom
the candidacy of Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   While Forbes's ads were effective against his opponents, they
also appeared to have backfired, transforming Forbes's image from a
straight-talking outsider into just another attack dog politician.
Forbes, however, would not rule out running similar ads next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think that the worst thing in the world he could do is
go and launch an (ad war) against some other candidate,'' said
Republican consultant Stuart Stevens, who worked for Dole in 1996.
``The guy would simply sit there on the launch pad and blow up. He
wouldn't get any altitude at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes will get altitude, however, by implementing his plan to
get around the $1,000-per-person federal limit on campaign
contributions. He says he will contribute his own unlimited funds
and will avoid spending restrictions by refusing to accept federal
matching funds. As a result, Forbes theoretically could spend more
than the rest of the combined Republican field. That has prompted
Texas Governor George W. Bush to say that he might also refuse
matching funds, setting the stage for what likely will be the most
expensive presidential campaign in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did assure my five daughters I wouldn't spend a penny more
than necessary,'' Forbes said, as he laughed and declined to be
more specific.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
