<HEADER>
A3796 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERBIA-TOWN-BOS &LR;      03-17 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERBIA-TOWN-BOS </SLUG>
  
 SERB-HELD TOWN SHOWS DARK SIDE OF MILITANCY
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   FOCA, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ It may be a cynical joke _ or a
serious warning. The first thing a visitor sees upon crossing the
bridge into Foca are the words ``Mafija Centar'' _ Mafia Center _
spray-painted on the side of a building.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most defiantly pro-Serbian towns in Republika
Srpska, the Serb-controlled sector of Bosnia, Western visitors are
not welcome. The New York-based Human Rights Watch describes Foca
as ``a closed, dark place'' and the previous, if not current,
hideout of several war crime suspects.
</P>
<P>
   As an international force struggles to maintain peace in this
former Yugoslav territory, where hundreds of thousands of people
died during a brutal 3 1/2-year war, Bosnia remains tense. The
rival ethnic groups of Serbs, Croats, and Muslims share the land,
but in bitter separation and mutual distrust. Foca, tucked in the
southern corner of the Serb-run fragment, is a glaring example of
how much needs to be done to return this region to a peaceful state
safe for all three ethnic groups, observers say.
</P>
<P>
   French soldiers in NATO's Stabilization Force warn Western
journalists not to stay after dark in Foca, which the Serbs call
Srbinje. Anti-Western sentiments there have been at an all-time
high, officials and aid workers say, since the NATO troops shot and
killed the war crimes suspect Dragan Gagovic in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people here are united'' in solidarity with their
neighbors, including those who may be wanted for mass rapes and
other war crimes, said Radisar Mashic, head of the local radio
station. He proudly passed out hand-drawn postcards of the mountain
town, then told visitors, ``Of course, your safety here cannot be
guaranteed.''
</P>
<P>
   Foca, whose population was mostly Muslim before the 1992-95 war,
is almost all Serbian now, and the few applications submitted by
Muslims who want to return to their homes have not been processed,
local officials and aid workers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``A civil war is a dirty war, and a lot of dirty things
happened,'' said Llubo Veljovic, the president, or mayor, of Foca.
``There were crimes on each side,'' he added, refusing to answer
directly whether his neighbors committed what international
monitors say were some of the most brutal atrocities of the war.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, a collection of Serb civilian, police and military
hard-liners took over Foca, using a propaganda campaign to convince
local Serbs that they were in danger of a Muslim fundamentalist
coup, according to a report by Human Rights Watch. The group,
calling itself the ``Crisis Committee,'' established a network of
detention centers where non-Serbs were detained, tortured or raped,
and then expelled, killed or ``disappeared'' from Foca, the report
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Nine local men _ including now-dead Gagovic _ have been accused
of war crimes, and the ``wanted poster'' issued by the
international tribunal that is trying charges of war crimes in the
Hague includes five men whose last known address was Foca. Though
no one in the current political leadership is on the public list of
indicted suspects, it is impossible to know whether any are on the
tribunal's secret list.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic tension and violence are nothing new in Foca. During
World War II, it was the scene of assaults and killings by both
Serbian nationalists (known as Cetniks), and Croatian Nazi
sympathizers (the Ustashe), said Colin Soloway, political analyst
for the Sarajevo-based International Crisis Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of bad memories in that area'' that only serve
to heighten the boiling ethnic hatred, he said. Foca also has
strategic importance, he added, since it was a gateway from
landlocked Serbia to the Croatian port of Dubrovnik, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But now, the town ``is run by war criminals, basically,''
Soloway said. ``It's really a thugocracy. Foca is run by rackets
and criminal gangs,'' and locals not affiliated with the gangs live
in constant fear, he said.
</P>
<P>
   To an outsider, even on a short visit, Foca oozes hostility.
When two Westerners entered a local cafe recently, the music
literally stopped, and all heads turned to glare at the strangers.
</P>
<P>
   Death notices honoring Gagovic, the alleged war criminal, are
pasted all over town, with the notation that he was ``killed in a
sneaky way by NATO troops.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a great deal of distrust toward (NATO troops) and
the international community'' since Gagovic's death, said Veljovic,
the municipal president. On his office door is a sticker with the
face of Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic, another war crimes
suspect. ``Don't Touch Him!'' it reads.
</P>
<P>
   Balkan watchers say an international presence throughout Bosnia
is critical to keeping the shaky peace. But since the Gagovic
episode, few foreigners come to Foca, except for the armored French
vehicles that patrol the town during the day.
</P>
<P>
   The Organization on Security and Cooperation in Europe, one of
the international groups monitoring the fragile peace, has closed
its Foca office for safety reasons. So has the International Police
Training Force, which was brought in to train the local police.
</P>
<P>
   After Gagovic was shot, locals trashed the office of the police
training force, which remains empty. Humanitarian aid workers are
afraid to go into Foca and operate from nearby towns, venturing
here only occasionally, and only in daylight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regret'' the destruction of the police training office, the
town president said. ``But you have to look at the cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Locals are furious at the death of Gagovic, who had five
youngsters in his car when he was shot. ``Couldn't they just shoot
four flat tires?'' asked Veljovic, who had been a good friend of
Gagovic.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Chamberlain, the stabilization force's spokesman, said
Gagovic tried to speed through a checkpoint to avoid arrest. ``He
was using his car as a weapon,'' Chamberlain said.
</P>
<P>
   If international troops attempt more arrests, Foca's residents
will defend their neighbors, predicted Mashic, the radio station
owner.
</P>
<P>
   The very existence of a secret list of indicted war criminals
rankles deeply here. It ``doesn't fit a civilized Europe,'' said
Veljovic. ``How do I know I am not on the secret list?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 1346EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
