<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3797 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOMESTIC-RECANT-BOS &LR;      03-17 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMESTIC-RECANT-BOS </SLUG>
  
 N.H. DOMESTIC ABUSE CASE GOES FORWARD AGAINST VICTIM'S WISHES
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   DOVER, N.H. _ Robin Needham looked haggard that afternoon last
June when she tearfully described how her boyfriend beat and raped
her in the early morning hours.
</P>
<P>
   Needham's upper lip and nose were swollen and red. She hadn't
slept or showered and it showed as she haltingly answered questions
on videotape for a solid hour while a police detective looked on
from another room.
</P>
<P>
   Days later, she recanted: she was drunk, she explained. She hit
him, she said. There was no rape, no attack.
</P>
<P>
   It was, some rueful observers concluded, just one more example
of a battered woman defending her abuser, a pattern as predictable
as the nearby tides.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than simply drop the case, frustrated prosecutors,
convinced that Needham was a victim of both her violent boyfriend
and misplaced loyalty, did something surprising: They tried the
case anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the boyfriend, 26-year-old Terry Johnson, is locked up in
the Strafford County Jail facing the possibility that he will spend
the next 40 years of his life in state prison. Attorneys on both
sides of the case agree that his appeal will reach the state
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   And Needham, who testified in defense of her boyfriend, but
whose videotaped complaint was used to convict him _ is on the
verge of giving birth to Johnson's baby, their second child
together and her fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not right that he's in jail,'' she said. ``The
allegations are false. He's an innocent man and he shouldn't be
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Observers nationwide are watching this case with deep interest.
The Needham case is part of a nationwide trend toward ``victimless
prosecutions,'' according to Sandra Matheson, director of
victim-witness assistance in the New Hampshire attorney general's
office. But this case takes that logic one step further, because of
the judge's controversial decision to allow the jury to see the
videotaped complaint that the witness later disavowed _ a decision
which, if upheld, could give prosecutors a powerful new tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``It represents a historic reversal where the advice from police
was to avoid getting involved,'' said Murray A. Straus, who is
co-director of the Family Research Laboratory at the University of
New Hampshire, and who has been conducting national surveys on
domestic violence since 1975. ``The old training manual said,
separate the warring parties and get out of there as fast as you
can.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is also bound to spark a vigorous debate in the courts.
``This is novel and basically reverses several hundred years of
Anglo-Saxon jurisprudence by permitting an out-of-court statement
to convict a person,'' said John E. Durkin, Johnson's attorney in
the New Hampshire public defender's office.
</P>
<P>
   Still, county attorney Lincoln Soldati, frustrated at having
been unable to help battered women because they refuse to
cooperate, has no such second thoughts. It is common, he said, for
women to recant or blame themselves when they have a violent bond
with their boyfriend or husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very sad case in a lot of ways, and unfortunately, it's
quite typical of what we see in domestic violence cases,'' said
Soldati, without regret. ``I have no misgivings about the case.''
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between Needham and Johnson was passionate from
the beginning. The two met at a club in Dover called Pure Platinum,
Needham recalled. She didn't like him at first, she said, but he
quickly won her over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just exchanged numbers and the next day he came over and he
was living with me from then on,'' said Needham.
</P>
<P>
   Violence did not become a part of the relationship, said
Needham, until the young couple moved from Kittery to Sanford,
Maine, about six months after they met. She was pregnant, she said,
and he was having an affair with another woman. The two fought and,
she said, she was just as much to blame as was he.
</P>
<P>
   The night that put Johnson in jail _ which was not his first
incarceration on charges of beating Needham _ began with another
argument over another woman, said Needham. When she told the police
that June night that Johnson had beat and raped her, she was
motivated by revenge, she told the jury. She had been drinking, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the jury believed the prosecution and found Johnson guilty
of four counts of aggravated felonious sexual assault, one count of
simple assault, and one count of violating a restraining order.
Johnson is scheduled to be sentenced on March 29.
</P>
<P>
   Specialists in domestic violence say her change of heart is
typical of an abusive relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Battered women really love their abusers,'' said Grace
Mattern, executive director of the New Hampshire Coalition Against
Domestic and Sexual Violence.
</P>
<P>
   Needham and Johnson, though, are strenuously insisting that
justice has gone awry. Needham, in fact, was so aggravated that she
called her local newspaper, Foster's Daily Democrat, to say her
boyfriend was innocent and insist that she had lied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm angry because I feel like I'm getting nowhere,'' she said
Wednesday, sitting at a table in her kitchen while a friend minded
her three girls, ages 7, 4, and 16 months, in the next room.
</P>
<P>
   During a telephone interview from prison, Johnson said the
experience has made him see more clearly. He now freely admits that
he had been having an affair behind Needham's back, and he said he
was drinking and doing drugs, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a God, and I know there is, he put me here because
he said, `Terry, you have to wake up, you have to do the right
thing and take care of your family and stop living this other
life.' I'm not mad at anybody. I just feel I was unfairly
convicted.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he loves Needham and forgives her for what she did
to him. He also said he feels a terrible pain that he cannot be
with his girlfriend for the birth of their child.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like I got justice. I feel I got shafted because
I did not commit this crime,'' he said. ``If things don't work out,
I've got to serve the rest of my life for something I did not do.''
</P>
<P>
   With Johnson in prison, instead of working as a stocker at an
Exeter warehouse, no money is coming into the household. Last
Tuesday, Needham received an eviction notice to leave her modest,
third-floor walk-up on the edge of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want him to come home,'' she said, insisting that she had
changed and so had Johnson. ``It won't happen anymore. It won't be
abusive anymore. He's seeking the Lord and I'm not drinking
anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
