<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3802 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CRYSTAL-WORLDS     03-17 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CRYSTAL-WORLDS-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLECTORS TAKE A SHINE TO CRYSTAL WORLDS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT database) 
(Eds.: Accent mark needed over e in Andre) 
 
By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATTENS, Austria _ As in other parts of the world, Americans
have become serious collectors of tiny, intricately crafted
Swarovski Silver Crystal figures.
</P>
<P>
   Butterflies and bumblebees, penguins and pandas, trains and
planes and automobiles _ each miniature piece possesses an almost
magnetic appeal.
</P>
<P>
   And this represents only one small aspect of the crystal empire
founded more than a century ago by Daniel Swarovski in the small
town of Wattens, about a 30-minute commuter-bus ride west from
Innsbruck in the Austrian Tyrol.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Swarovski's legacy is heralded at the spectacular
subterranean Crystal Worlds, situated in the shadow of the company
headquarters where Swarovski crystal is still cut. It is one of
Austria's most popular tourist attractions, with 2 million visitors
since its opening in late 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Distinct lighting, music and architecture combine to generate a
surreal atmosphere within a labyrinth of rooms and passages
designed to showcase crystal in previously unexplored dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   Designer Andre Heller described his objective as ``an attempt to
create a contemporary chamber of wonders; a collection of rooms to
astonish and amuse, rooms that would serve both as force fields and
sources of inspiration for those with sensitivity to respond to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say this is not your typical museum or exhibition
center.
</P>
<P>
   The entrance is through the head of a crystal-eyed ``giant'' _ a
masterpiece of landscaped art on an artificial hill _ that spouts
water into a small pool.
</P>
<P>
   Among the first displays is the world's largest crystal stone,
15 inches in diameter, weighing 300,000 carats.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby rests the world's smallest stone, three-hundredths of an
inch in diameter and observable under a microscope.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the entrance foyer: a stele, or stone slab, decorated
with black cut crystal stones by U.S. graffiti artist Keith Haring;
love poems written on rings of crystal by John Brekke; Salvador
Dali's famous ``Time Running Out'' pendulum clock done in crystal;
a Statue of Liberty figure by Niki de St. Phalle (with a huge
crystal piece replacing the flame); and two paintings by Andy
Warhol titled ``Gems.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially striking is a wall packed with 12 tons of crystal
stone, rising more than 12 feet from the floor and extending more
than 50 feet in width.
</P>
<P>
   Most rooms and passages were redesigned late last year. Among
them:
</P>
<P>
   _ A spiritual Planet of Crystals is touted as the world's first
three-dimensional theaterlike spectacle that can be perceived
without technical aids. Sparkling crystals are in perpetual motion
above and below the observer. A cosmic soundscape helps give the
impression of a walk through space.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the Crystal Dome, 590 mirrors create the illusion of being
inside a giant crystal.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Kaleidoscope Room offers insight into the infinite variety
of the crystalline image. Eight different kaleidoscope systems
employ media ranging from water to shards of glass.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Crystal Theater is a bizarre fairy-tale setting of motion
and color in which diverse figures are decorated with crystal
stones.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the Crystal Calligraphy room, blown-glass tubes climb the
wall in letterlike shapes.
</P>
<P>
   _ An ``ice passage`` is paved with crystal cubes of 30 facets,
with images changing each time the floor is touched. As more people
move about, whatever is seen is dissolved only to come back in
changed shapes and colors.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Eno Room is a chapellike environment and features a cross
section of the pulsating light, sound and video objects developed
by composer-producer Brian Eno, co-founder of the Roxy Music pop
group and acclaimed for his work with David Bowie, U2 and other
artists. Chairs are provided for meditation.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal Worlds was created to commemorate Swarovski's 100th
anniversary in 1995. A native of Bohemia, Daniel Swarovski settled
in the Austrian Tyrol region and developed a machine that cut
crystal jewelry stones with new precision. The company _ now headed
by fourth-generation Swarovski family members _ is the world's
leading manufacturer of full cut crystal, the largest supplier of
crystal jewelry stones for the fashion, jewelry, lighting and
cosmetics industries and also specializes in optical precision
instruments and grinding tools.
</P>
<P>
   Production of a tiny crystal mouse in 1976 marked the beginning
of the Silver Crystal line of collectibles. Several miniature
pieces are created _ and others retired _ annually, and about
400,000 individuals have joined the Swarovski Collectors Society.
</P>
<P>
   Society members are admitted free to Crystal Worlds, receive
exclusive access to a VIP lounge and qualify for a discount on
purchases in the facility's large gift shop. (Prices for individual
pieces are generally lower in Austria than in the United States.)
</P>
<P>
   Tours are offered in several languages, including English, when
demand is sufficient. Or ask for a printed guide in English and
proceed through chambers at your preferred pace. Regular adult
admission is 75 Austrian shillings (about $6 in U.S. currency),
with discounts for groups of 10 or more. Children under 12 are
admitted free when accompanied by an adult. The facility is
wheelchair-accessible. Hours are 9 a.m.-6 p.m. daily except
Christmas and New Year's days.
</P>
<P>
   Save some time for exploring the surrounding grounds. One
highlight on the side of the artificial hill is a maze of trees
modeled after designer Heller's left hand. Nearby is a children's
playground and park.
</P>
<P>
   To reach Crystal Worlds by car from Innsbruck, take Highway A12
to the Wattens exit and follow the brown signs that read
Kristallwelten (about two minutes from the highway). Parking is
free. Or buses marked ``Wattens'' depart about every 30 minutes
from a terminal adjacent to the Innsbruck train station. Some
walking is involved from the closest bus stop.
</P>
<P>
   Several restaurants and cafes offer tasty and inexpensive
lunches in downtown Wattens, about a 10-minute walk (or short bus
ride) from Crystal Worlds.
</P>
<P>
   Call 011-43-5224-51080 for more information. Or access
www.swarovski-crystalworld.com on the Internet. For brochures and
general tourism information about Austria, call 212-944-6880 or
access www.anto.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
