A3803 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      03-17 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE TOWN'S GUARDIAN; SAFE SHOTS; SHAPED BY TV 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My only run-in with the law occurred when I was 11 or so and
joined a bunch of other desperadoes one weekend in the liberation
of some ice cream bars from a freezer in our elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   I've been more or less rehabilitated since then, but I'll never
forget that squirmy, shamed feeling when a police officer we all
respected, a fixture in our lives, sat us down for a good
talking-to. It was as if we had let (itals)him(unitals) down.
</P>
<P>
   A good cop can wield that kind of moral authority, and can
generally occupy a special place in the life of a small town.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy O'Connor of Northampton, Mass. was one such good cop, at
least as depicted by Tracy Kidder in a wonderful excerpt from his
new book, ``Home Town,'' in the April issue of The Atlantic
Monthly.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor was the kind of cop who radiated enough menace to put
the fear of God into the toughest gang members, and enough
compassion to warn a disabled junkie about some dangerous smack
circulating on the street. Before he left in 1997 to join the FBI,
he was part of the town's social glue, responding cheerfully to
situations lesser cops might blow off: a dog locked in a car, a kid
throwing snowballs at passing cars, an accident victim needing some
follow-up at the local hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The Northampton that O'Connor patrolled day after day was a
different place than the Northampton he grew up in, but that didn't
stop him, Kidder writes, from ``playing ombudsman to the lost, the
needy, the unsteady, in his home town.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidder's gift is to show us the town through O'Connor's eyes and
the cop himself through the author's eyes. To judge by the 90-point
byline they give him on the cover, the editors of the Atlantic are
mighty glad to have Kidder back in their magazine. Readers should
be too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In this era of celebrity worship, when magazine sales can hinge
on which famous face adorns the cover, the publicists who control
access to the stars have gotten drunk with power _ and it is
editors and photographers who suffer the hangover.
</P>
<P>
   That's the tale told by a Hollywood-based magazine editor who
complains in American Photo that megalomaniacal publicists are
``the number-one issue affecting the profession.'' The editor
(writing under a pseudonym for fear of retribution at the hands of
vengeful flacks) says showbiz publicists demand veto power over the
photographers whom magazines wish to assign; pressure photographers
to sign away their right to pictures without compensation; and
insist on controlling every aspect of photo shoots, issuing orders
regarding the makeup, wardrobe, and hairstyles for their clients
(at the magazines' expense).
</P>
<P>
   This could all be just inside baseball were it not for the fact
that the flacks' mania for control is robbing us readers of any
magazine photography with a vestige of spontaneity. ``Look at your
nearest newsstand: All the faces are perfect,'' the editor notes.
``All the covers are interchangeable.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV history is hot these days, what with Entertainment Weekly
recently publishing a pair of special issues devoted to the ``100
greatest moments in television'' and the ``100 greatest TV shows of
all time.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Life, the picture magazine, pays homage to the picture
medium with Todd Brewster's pithy summation of the ways TV has
transformed America. This is meant for a quick skim; a much fuller
exploration of these themes is contained in Steven D. Stark's
indispensable ``Glued to the Set: The 60 Television Shows and
Events That Made Us Who We Are Today.'' But Brewster, a producer of
ABC News' upcoming ``The Century'' documentary series, is not a bad
field guide to television's milestones and their meaning (though
his ABC affiliation does make a reader wonder about the shot he
takes at CBS's Dan Rather).
</P>
<P>
   Brewster rightly points out that ``when people in Maine looked
at the same thing as people in California night after night, a
different sense of nationhood was imprinted on our consciousness.''
Given the disintegration of network television's hold on that
consciousness, it appears that another change in our cultural
identity is in store.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The occupation of bounty hunter has always seemed like a
fascinating anachronism, a holdover from the Wild West days. That
impression is further fortified by Harmon Leon's report in P.O.V.
on his brief undercover stint as one.
</P>
<P>
   Bounty hunters chase fugitives, or ``skips'' as they are called,
and sometimes the encounters prove deadly. When Leon asks his
instructor why bounty hunters can't just shoot at the fugitives'
kneecaps, the instructor ``stares me down like I'm a yellow-bellied
wimp'' and barks: ``There is no `shoot to wound' or `in the
kneecaps.' You shoot to kill!''
</P>
<P>
   Also in P.O.V., celebrated figures opine on what the magazine is
pleased to call the ``seven vital virtues'' (in contrast to the
seven deadly sins, get it?). So we get moderately interesting
essays from Norman Mailer on audacity, Sammy Sosa on sportsmanship,
America Online chairman Steve Case on perseverance, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Poignantly, we also hear from Joe Torre on the virtue of
patience. The Yankees manager notes that it took him 37 years in
the major leagues to win a World Series and says that ``no matter
what happens to me from now on, nothing is going to rain on my
parade.'' Thursday Torre is scheduled to undergo surgery for his
recently diagnosed prostate cancer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
