<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3804 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-DAUBACH-BOS &LR;      03-17 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-DAUBACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAUBACH IS A LATE BOOMER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Ill.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ He was 18 years old when the New York Mets
made him their 19th-round draft pick in 1990. Brian Daubach was the
first (and still is the only) kid ever drafted out of Belleville
West (Ill.) High School, which made him kind of a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, casual sports fans and well-meaning family and
friends don't know how it works after a young man is drafted. They
assume that when you are selected by a big league team, you will be
playing in the majors the next year. They look for your name in the
box scores right after you leave home.
</P>
<P>
   What they don't know is that only a small fraction of those who
sign professional contracts ever see a day in the majors. Instead,
most of these young men live a life of long bus rides, fast-food
restaurants, and hanging curveballs. The road to the majors is
paved with bush league body parts _ the sore arms and broken hearts
of those who never made it.
</P>
<P>
   And that is why those friends and relatives don't know how much
it can hurt when they ask, ``What happened to Brian? Why isn't he
playing for the Mets yet?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I get that a lot,'' says Daubach, now a 27-year-old first
base/outfield hopeful in the Red Sox' Camp Tranquility. ``But it's
out of your control. People don't understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Daubach's dad, Dale, is a letter carrier for the US Postal
Service in Belleville.
</P>
<P>
   ``People (itals)don't(unitals) understand,'' agrees Dale
Daubach. ``They think he should have been in the big leagues by
now. But Brian loves it. He wouldn't want to do anything else. Even
if he had to keep playing minor league ball, he'd be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no time for a big sendoff party when Brian got drafted
nine years ago. Within a week, the kid was off to play for the
Mets' affiliate in the Gulf Coast League. He hit .270 there, then
the trail took him through Kingsport, Pittsfield, Capital City, St.
Lucie, Birmingham, Norfolk, and Charlotte. Brian kept the folks
posted with regular phone calls, and the local paper trailed his
career.
</P>
<P>
   He never has been married. This helps. There was a regular girl
a few years ago, but this is no life for a young married couple.
Daubach is certain that if he'd married, he would have given up
baseball. He says the minor league life is lonely, but you can get
by on $18-per-day meal money. And there's no family to move from
Fort Myers to Pawtucket to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   A late bloomer, Daubach found his power stroke three years ago.
He hit 26 homers in 1996 and 21 in '97. Playing for the Florida
Marlins' Triple A affiliate in Charlotte last year, he led the
International League with 35 bombs, 124 RBIs, 315 total bases, 84
extra-base hits, and a .634 slugging percentage.
</P>
<P>
   The lowly Marlins called him up for the proverbial cup of coffee
at the end of their 1998 train-wreck season. But he played
sparingly. The Marlins didn't think much of his defense (this past
Sunday, Daubach misplayed a wind-blown pop that landed near first
base for a single), and he went to the plate only 15 times, getting
three hits (his first big league hit was an RBI double off Curt
Schilling), none of them homers. After the season, he was released.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't shock me,'' he says. ``They had young guys they
wanted to protect.''
</P>
<P>
   He played winter ball for Red Sox first base coach Dave Jauss
and helped Licey win the Caribbean World Series. Daubach had a
chance to play in Japan, or sign a minor league contract to play
for the Yankees' Triple A club. Instead he opted to try out with
the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, it's working out pretty well. In his first nine spring
training games, Daubach hit .389 with one homer and six RBIs. The
homer was a two-run shot off the Blue Jays, a ninth-inning
game-winner. In light of injuries (Reggie Jefferson, Midre
Cummings, Jeff Frye), Daubach appears to be in the mix to make the
team as a lefthanded-hitting first baseman/outfielder/DH.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody who's still here has a chance to make the team,''
says ever-evasive manager Jimy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Jauss adds, ``He can hit. And he can learn to hit more with Jim
Rice around and some of the veterans we've got here. You've got to
learn to hit when you're not a good defensive player and can't run.
But if he makes this club, it's because we've had some injuries and
he's earned it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, the Sox had some luck with a spray hitter who
was labeled ``career minor leaguer.'' Wade Boggs got his break when
regular third baseman Carney Lansford broke his ankle. Boggs this
year is expected to crack his 3,000th hit.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach isn't going to quit if he doesn't make the team this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, everyone wants to play in the majors,'' he says.
``But I enjoy playing and competing. I've enjoyed every day of
this. I've got zero regrets. There's a lot of people like myself
who played eight or nine years in the minors. Whenever I'm done
playing, I'd like to be a coach.''
</P>
<P>
   He could coach young men how to hit. And how to be patient.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
