<HEADER>
A3806 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-17 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM SATIRIST TO SAD SACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gone (itals)and(unitals) forgotten _ that would be the legacy of
Al Capp, the comic strip artist and innovator whose broad humor and
bedrock misanthropy ruled the ``funny pages'' for over four
decades, from 1934 to 1977. He's as forgotten here in his adopted
hometown _ he wrote ``Li'l Abner'' from 122 Beacon St. in Boston,
on the edge of the Emerson College campus _ as elsewhere in
America, where his face once graced the cover of Time and Life
magazines, and his strip ran in 900 papers across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper readers of a certain age, who forgave Capp his human
and ideological divagations, call him the greatest American
political satirist of the 20th century. In 1952, John Steinbeck
(who, like Capp, would later be ostracized for backing the wrong,
i.e. American, side in the Vietnam War) wrote that ``Capp may very
possibly be the best writer in the world today,'' and recommended
him for a Nobel Prize.
</P>
<P>
   Capp was ``edgy,'' to use the modish term; irascible, difficult,
an enemy of cant. He made a fan in West Barnstable's own Alexander
Theroux, who has just published an admiring, 62-page monograph,
``The Enigma of Al Capp,'' available from Seattle's Fantagraphics
Books. This is probably as close to a biography as Capp will ever
come and serves as a useful reminder for today's graying hipsters
that the marvelously talented Garry Trudeau was anticipated by a
one-legged man who chain-smoked Benson &AMP; Hedges and considered
Richard Nixon one the great presidents of our time.
</P>
<P>
   One terrible event transformed Al Capp's life. At age 9, while
hitching a ride on an ice truck in New Haven, he fell off and had
his left leg severed by an oncoming trolley car. ``The nightmare of
my life,'' he said. For more than 60 years he hobbled through
marriage, fame, and eventual disgrace on a series of ungainly
prostheses. John Updike, a fan, wrote that Capp's accident cost him
``permanent banishment from the paradise of the normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a casual observer sees that Capp's art became obsessed with
legs, mainly women's legs, in their Betty Grable-esque rendition.
Updike: ``The ebullient, at times raunchy exaggeration of bodies
that is one of Dogpatch's striking features related, surely, to the
somatic awareness induced by Capp's missing limb and its painful,
awkward substitute.''
</P>
<P>
   The comic strip was indeed populated by hilarious grotesques:
the virginal, voluptuous Daisy Mae; Fearless Fosdick, the dead-on
Dick Tracy spoof; bulb-nosed Lonesome Polecat, the dispenser of
Kickapoo Joy Juice; the unlucky Joe Btfsplk, always drawn with an
accompanying rain cloud, and the buxom Moonbeam McSwine, who
prefered the company of hogs to men.
</P>
<P>
   Vilified at the end of his life as a man of the right, Capp made
his name as a man of the left. He saved his most vicious thrusts
for the potbellied exploiters of the Eisenhower era: the pompus,
reactionary Senator Jack S. Phogbound; the pork oligopolist J.
Roaringham Fatback; and the nemesis of all newspaper laborers,
Rockewell P. Squeezeblood, who ran a fictional cartoon syndicate.
``It's my belief that the comic strip Li'l Abner is one long fable
about greed,'' writes Theroux, who notes that Capp supported the
Adlai Stevenson and John Kennedy presidential campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   That all changed in the 1960s. Youth culture threw Capp a
curveball. He wittily lampooned the ubiquitous student
demonstrators as members of S.W.I.N.E. _ Students Wildly Indignant
about Nearly Everything, and tagged his Cambridge neighbor Joan
Baez with the monicker ``Joanie Phonie.'' He even suggested that
the Mafia might supplant the lily-livered Harvard administration
and clamp down on student protests, double-quick.
</P>
<P>
   But frequently, Capp missed the target. He trashed the Peace
Corps. He trashed welfare mothers. He trashed blacks. ``Let them
clean up their own ghettos,'' he wrote. ``I grew up in a Jewish
ghetto and loved it. . . . I know what it is to be imprisoned _ by
a wooden leg. . . . For chrissake, every man has his black skin,
every man has his wooden leg.''
</P>
<P>
   The end came quickly. His erratic behavior with young women led
to an adultery conviction in 1972. Hundreds of newspapers dropped
his strip. After Capp's disgrace, Updike met him, deflated, on a
near-empty shuttle flight to New York. Capp joked that if the plane
crashed, the newspaper headline would read ``ONLY EIGHT KILLED.''
Updike remembered the meeting in a poem, ``The Shuttle:''
</P>
<P>
   (itals)Now Al is dead, dead,
</P>
<P>
   And the shuttle is always crowded.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 1357EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
