<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3808 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORE-QUADS-2TAKES-ART     03-17 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORE-QUADS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THIS FAMILY, IT'S A QUADMIRE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITMAN, Mass. _ It's 7:30 on a Saturday morning, and the four
brightly colored booster seats at the kitchen table are already
filled by Andrew, Elise, Stephen, and Thomas McDonough. Leisurely
working their sippy cups, the four 2-year-olds are watching their
yawning father turn frozen waffles into breakfast. They are still
bleary-eyed and subdued, a condition that makes Joe McDonough a tad
uneasy. ``Are you all going to behave this morning?'' he asks,
warily glancing at the four upturned faces.
</P>
<P>
   If this were a summer's day, Joe and Kathy McDonough might load
their quadruplets into the family van _ (itals)every(unitals) quad
family owns a van _ and head for Nantasket Beach or Castle Island.
Things aren't so simple during the winter, however, what with four
hats, four coats, eight mittens and eight boots to wrestle the kids
into. Still, they're all going somewhere today, if only to Shaw's
or BJ's for groceries. ``They need to get out of here as much as we
do,'' Kathy McDonough says, nodding toward the table.
</P>
<P>
   But right now the kids are waking up in earnest. And so are
their parents. Another day of living with quads has begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thomas, why aren't you eating?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stephen, are you throwing food?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Elise, cover your mouth when you do that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Andrew, get that fork out of your ear. Andrew!'' There are
apparently no quintuplets in Massachusetts, but homes like the
McDonoughs' small and well-kept three-bedroom Cape, located on a
quarter of an acre of land on a dead-end street, are increasingly
common. The McDonough kids were one of 560 sets of quadruplets born
in the United States in 1996, a year when the number of
``higher-order multiple births'' (triplets and up) grew 19 percent
over the year before. Over the previous 10 years, such births had
already more than doubled, and there's no reason to think the
numbers aren't still growing. Call it the multiple baby boom.
</P>
<P>
   Reasons? More women are being treated for infertility with drugs
and techniques that increase the likelihood of multiple gestation.
More women are having children at an older age, which also
increases chances of multiple delivery. And more low birth weight
babies are surviving, thanks to improvements in intensive care.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts, one of only a handful of states that requires
that insurers pay for fertility services, is frequently at or near
the top of the multiple-birth pack. (It ranked fourth in all
multiple births in 1996, the last year for which figures are
available). But bringing four babies from the hospital still isn't
most folks' idea of parenthood. ``This wasn't supposed to happen to
us,'' says Kathy McDonough, who is 37. ``This is supposed to happen
to other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a day-care center where the kids never go home. Ever.
``People can try to tell you what this is like,'' Kathy McDonough
adds, ``but it's not until you live the life yourself that you can
really understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That first winter, 1996 to 1997, was the worst.
</P>
<P>
   For eight months, either Joe or Kathy had to be awake at all
times. It took three hours to feed the four babies, and then it was
time to begin again. Joe's brother, Jack McDonough, describes the
first months this way: ``Every 24 hours you have 32 diaper changes,
32 feedings, and 128 burps.''
</P>
<P>
   The quads all contracted a respiratory virus, and stomach flus
swept through the tiny house like a plague. So did ear infections.
``Don't tell me they're not contagious,'' Kathy says. ``The walls
were pink with amoxicillin because everyone was throwing up so
much.'' Kathy herself eventually spent six days in the hospital.
``I just never had a chance to go to the doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   Then as now, Joe worked late afternoons and evenings as a
customer service rep for Boston Gas. Then he was on duty at home
from midnight until 8 a.m., while Kathy slept, whereupon he'd go to
bed himself until it was time to go back to work at 3 p.m. Kathy
once missed two nights of sleep in a row and ``felt like I was
having a stroke.'' If one of the kids was picked up, the other
three immediately cried for similar attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very, very hard at first,'' says Joe, 36. ``Kathy and I
would get mad at each other, but we really weren't mad at each
other. It was the stress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You never sat down,'' Kathy says. ``And you always had a baby
in your arms.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth,'' Joe adds, ``going to work was a
relief.''
</P>
<P>
   They certainly hadn't planned any of this, hadn't forseen that
their living room would one day feature a changing table, a diaper
disposal, four potty chairs, and piles of clean laundry waiting to
be put away. They'd been married for seven years by 1995 and
already had a 4-year-old daughter, Caroline. One or two additional
kids would be nice, they thought, but not more. Kathy had had
trouble conceiving Caroline, and when the fertility drugs she was
using _ primarily the ovulatory stimulants Clomid and Metrodin _
failed to do the job after nearly two years, she and Joe were ready
to give up and remain a family of three.
</P>
<P>
   But, lo, the drugs finally worked. And when Kathy went for an
ultrasound test at South Shore Medical Center, knowing she was
carrying two mature eggs, she thought she might even be having
twins. When she saw the technician stiffen during the test,
however, she knew something more unusual was happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many?'' asked Joe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you ready to hear?'' asked the technician.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I wasn't ready to hear four,'' Kathy recalls. ``I laugh
when I get nervous, and I was laughing my head off. They looked
like four tiny caterpillars.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe and Kathy then went through a round of advice from doctors
who told them the dangers of higher-order multiple births, of the
significantly higher mortality rates and the increased chances of
birth defects. Selective reduction _ reducing the number of fetuses
_ was strongly suggested. But Joe and Kathy adamantly refused.
(Both are Roman Catholic, but say they were influenced more by
making a decision about which fetuses would survive and which
wouldn't.) The quads were born about eight weeks prematurely on
April 26, 1996, via caesarean section, at Massachusetts General
Hospital. They all weighed between 3 and 4 pounds. They have had no
serious health problems, although they are facing minor auditory
processing and motor planning issues, not uncommon among preemies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe this has happened for a reason,'' Kathy says.
``The thing is, I just can't figure out what that reason is right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew (the ringleader), Stephen (the sly one), and Thomas (the
shy one) all sleep in a tiny second-floor bedroom, their cribs in a
row. Elise (the mother hen) shares a room with Caroline, who's now
7. The rooms are too small for much more than sleep, so there's a
downstairs playroom known as ``The Pen.'' It's a small area to
patrol, although not when eight legs are involved, and not when
eight eager hands might open a window to fetch some snow or cover
their bodies with Baby Magic. ``You think you're watching them, and
suddenly they prove to you that you're not,'' says Joe. ``If you
hear all of them laughing together, you know you're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 1358EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
