<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3809 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORE-QUADS-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     03-17 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORE-QUADS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 WHITMAN, Mass.: ... in trouble.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joe and Kathy's darkest fear is that one of them will be home
alone with the quads and run short of, say, milk (usage: nearly 6
gallons per week) or diapers (about 100 each week). Even a short
trip to the local convenience store is a major organizational feat.
And, like the parents of other quadruplets, Kathy and Joe have
learned that you must split up when you go to a shopping mall,
because if you travel with quads so many people rush up to you with
questions and comments that a 45-minute stop can become a
three-hour layover.
</P>
<P>
   Even when you do get away, you don't really get away. People at
work ask you about The Quads. Friends stop you on the street to ask
about The Quads. Family members call to inquire after The Quads.
(The first photo of the quartet was in such demand that it required
70 copies.) ``Our 15 minutes of fame are our kids,'' muses Joe.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on their ninth wedding anniversary, Joe asked Kathy:
``You want to go out to BJ's or Shaw's?'' Actually, they went
bowling.
</P>
<P>
   Having a child obviously changes a parent's life, but having
four children at once alters it completely. It's a matter of saying
everything four times or hiring teenage babysitters in pairs. It's
a matter of pretty much giving up golf because you no longer have
any free time, of foregoing restaurants because they're such a
hassle, or of not even thinking about taking a family vacation
anymore. Sometimes Kathy gets together with other multiple-birth
mothers, a select group of women who've found each other primarily
through a local support group called Triplets, Moms, and More
(www.tripletsmomsandmore.org). ``But I notice we don't really get
invited anywhere anymore,'' she says, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The change also hasn't been easy for Caroline. Her wished-for
trip to Disney World has been permanently placed on hold. Her
college fund has become an emergency fund and was used last
Christmas to pay for presents. And although she clearly cares for
her four sudden siblings, she sometimes resents the attention they
get. ``Babies, babies, babies!'' she once blurted. ``I'm so sick
and tired of babies!'' Another time she told her mother, ``I don't
want God to put any more babies in your tummy.''
</P>
<P>
   The McDonoughs' income is modest. (Kathy works part-time in the
collections division of the Internal Revenue Service.) The family
can get by, but there's no nest egg stashed away. Not anymore. The
quads will soon need beds, which means their parents will likely
need a loan. And college? ``I'm going to give them tennis rackets
and golf clubs and tell them to practice,'' Kathy declares.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that the parents of quads will tell you is that they
couldn't do it by themselves and that, luckily, they often don't
have to. There is something about higher-order multiple births that
brings out volunteers and even small cash donors, folks who are
eager to help. ``We got money from people we barely knew,'' marvels
Joe. People sent hand-knit sweaters, cases of diapers, even cribs.
``At one point we had more swings than babies,'' Kathy reports.
Even baby-care companies chipped in, sending the likes of Pampers,
Huggies, and _ yes _ Baby Magic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Relatives and friends also showed up at the door, often working
regular shifts. ``My father, who has four kids and had never fed a
baby in his life, fed these kids,'' Kathy says. Helpers would
occasionally stay until midnight and come back at dawn the next
day. ``Everyone wants to help so much because they're so amazed by
quads,'' Kathy says.
</P>
<P>
   Such help still turns up _ two or three women regularly come on
Thursday nights so that Kathy can go out, for example _ but not as
often. Maybe the amazement has worn off, or maybe there's just a
sense that the McDonoughs are coping. After all, this winter has
brought only a single ear infection and just two rounds of stomach
flu.
</P>
<P>
   On most nights, Joe is working and it's up to Kathy to put the
quads to bed. Lately this has become like herding cattle: she must
track down reluctant strays, point them in the right direction, and
hope she hasn't lost any of the others in the meantime. ``Don't
want to go to bed!'' Andrew announces one recent evening at 8:15,
which clearly reflects the majority point of view.
</P>
<P>
   During the next hour or so, Kathy asks, begs, pleads, and
demands. The three boys, in particular, would clearly rather be
somewhere other than in their cribs. Andrew climbs out and is
discovered lying atop his parents' bed. A few minutes later, he
crawls under Thomas's crib. So Stephen gets out of
(itals)his(unitals) crib to report this news to his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't want to go to bed!''
</P>
<P>
   At 9:05, the telephone rings. It's Joe, calling from work. But
someone's on the upstairs phone. ``Andrew! Andrew! Hang up the
phone!'' Kathy says into the mouthpiece. ``Stephen? Is that you,
Stephen?''
</P>
<P>
   By 9:15, the sound of silence finally fills the small house.
Kathy stands in the kitchen, hoping it will last. ``Somebody told
me I should keep a journal,'' she says softly. ``Well, by the time
I get them settled down for the night, I'm not about to sit down
and write a book.''
</P>
<P>
   In 10 hours or so, the four 2-year-olds will wander one by one
into the kitchen once again, groggy and in search of breakfast.
Another day will begin, the kind very few parents can possibly
understand. Or maybe they can. Says Kathy McDonough: ``I have
friends who say to me, `When I'm having a bad day, I think of you.'
''
</P>
</TEXT>
