<HEADLINE>
NCAA'S HALL OF SHAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So you've gotten the men to stop throwing beer bottles and salsa
at you after you blocked the TV during a last-second, game winning
shot to engage them in thoughtful dialogue about why idiot men's
college basketball programs are glorified while smart female
players are ghettoized on ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   Nervous? I feel your tremors. Last week, a friend took me to the
National Collegiate Athletic Association men's tournament at the
Fleet Center. He also invited me to a pregame pub party.
</P>
<P>
   When I arrived at the pub, the host said, ``We heard you were
coming. Your column this morning was required reading for this
party.'' I immdiately felt like marinated lamb chops. Despite the
din, I could hear my heart pounding oh-oh, oh-oh, oh-oh. I saw beer
glasses everywhere and reflexively began ducking.
</P>
<P>
   Then the host said, ``We liked it.'' It was my lucky day. The
host and some of the other men were racism and sexism diversity
trainers. We went into the Fleet Center to root for Lafayette,
which has a 100 percent graduation rate.
</P>
<P>
   You are not so lucky. Diversity for the men in front of you is
Bud and Bud Lite. The next game is about to start. Room rage is
rising again. Arms are cocked with more bottles and Tostitos.
</P>
<P>
   You need a trump card. Slap this scorecard on the coffee table.
You don't need to say ``Read it and weep!'' or ``Analyze this!''
Throw it down. Stand back. Watch testosterone cry.
</P>
<P>
   --Category: The Titanic. Where graduation rates sink to the
depths of Leonardo DiCaprio's body. This is for a graduation rate
of 30 percent or less. Final Score: Men 21 teams, Women 0.
</P>
<P>
   The wreckage includes Cincinnati (0 percent), SW Missouri St.
(0), Alabama-Birmingham (7), Temple (9), Texas (9), Arizona (15),
Murray St. (18), Louisville (18), Arkansas (18), Arkansas St. (18),
Auburn (20), Alcorn (20), Maryland (23), Syracuse (25), Texas-San
Antonio (25), Oklahoma (25), Minnesota (27), Oklahoma St. (27),
Connecticut (29), New Mexico St. (29), and New Mexico (30).
</P>
<P>
   --Category: Sinsinnati, UCon, and the Temple of Doom. These are
the schools that shamelessly profit from black athletes with no
expectation they will graduate. This is for schools that graduate
less than 40 percent of African-American players.
</P>
<P>
   The Final Score: Men 33 teams, Women 7. The 33 men's teams, over
half the entire field, had an average black graduation rate of 17
percent. How can Jesse Jackson or the NAACP stand for this?
</P>
<P>
   The plantations, with notations of teams under 20 percent, were:
Auburn, Syracuse (0 percent), Ohio St. (0), Murray St. (0),
Samford, Louisville (10), Maryland, UConn, Texas San Antonio,
Missouri, New Mexico (17), Iowa, Alabama-Birmingham (0), Arkansas
(13), Minnesota (11), Gonzaga (0), Alcorn, Florida A&AMP;M, SW Missouri
St. (0), Tennessee, Delaware, Temple (0), Cincinnati (0), Texas
(0), Purdue, Rhode Island, Arizona (11), Oklahoma, Kentucky, New
Mexico St. (0), Washington, Miami (Ohio) and Arkansas St. (14).
</P>
<P>
   --Category: 60 Watts and Brighter. The number of schools with
GRs of 60 percent or higher. The Score: Women 47, Men 15.
</P>
<P>
   The men's schools were Indiana, George Washington, St. John's,
Siena, Florida, Penn, North Carolina, Stanford, Duke, Charleston,
Wisconsin, Lafayette, Michigan St., Mt. St. Mary's, and Villanova.
</P>
<P>
   The women's schools were: Tennessee, Boston College, Ohio St.,
Texas, Virginia Tech, St. Peter's, Tulane, St. Joseph's, Duke,
Stanford, Maine, Old Dominion, UConn, St. Francis, Xavier, Oregon,
Iowa St. Santa Clara, Southern Methodist, Liberty, Illinois,
Louisville, Clemson, Purdue, Marquette, Kansas, Alabama, North
Carolina, Arizona, Florida, Rutgers, Dartmouth, Mississippi St.,
North Carolina St., Texas Tech, Stephen Austin, Central Florida,
Penn St., Virginia, Notre Dame, St. Mary's, Evansville, Nebraska,
UCLA, Wisconsin-Green Bay, SW Missouri St., and Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   --Category: The Weaker Sex. Of the 19 schools with teams in both
the men's and women's tournaments, the women's team outgraduated
the men's team by a score of 15 to 4.
</P>
<P>
   The men's victories were: Stanford, 100-77; Duke, 83-79; North
Carolina, 77-73, and Florida, 69-60. The women's victories were:
Evansville, 92-50; UCLA, 60-42; Ohio St., 100-31; Cincinnati, 38-0;
Tennessee, 67-38; Louisville, 67-18; Kansas, 69-50; Auburn, 54-20;
Texas, 65-9; Florida A&AMP;M, 53-32; UConn, 62-29; SW Missouri St.,
60-0; Arizona, 67-15; Purdue, 62-50; and Kentucky, 53-33.
</P>
<P>
   --Category: New England: The gradation average for the six New
England women's teams (Boston College, Maine, Northeastern, Holy
Cross, UConn, and Dartmouth) vs. the average for the two New
England men's teams (Connecticut and Rhode Island). The Final
Score. Women 72, Men 33.
</P>
<P>
   And men are whining about Title IX? Please. If these were real
scores, the men would be ridiculed. Coaches and athletic directors
would be fired. The men's tournament would be declared as corrupt
as the Salt Lake Olympics and the Holyfield fight.
</P>
<P>
   So this scorecard is for you, for the quixotic mission of
goading the primordal asylum to stop cheering and start jeering the
Sinsinnatis, the UCons, and the Temples of Doom during March
Madness. Tell them if they don't watch out, a federal judge just
may banish the men to ESPN2. That would really make testosterone
cry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
