<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-DILLER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN IF LYCOS DEAL FAILS, DILLER COULD BENEFIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barry Diller has lost out on big deals before. The New York
media baron who helped create the Fox Television Network in the
1980s is also known for his unsuccessful attempt to take control of
the Paramount movie studio five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But in his latest effort _ a bid to assume control of Internet
portal Lycos Inc., Diller seems to have learned something about
self-protection.
</P>
<P>
   The terms of his controversial bid for Lycos Inc. give Diller's
USA Networks Inc. the option to buy 17.5 percent of the company,
even if a rival suitor emerges. That could prove valuable to Diller
if Lycos's biggest shareholder, venture capital firm CMGI Inc.,
succeeds in arranging a counterbid, as its chief executive has
pledged to do. By the same token, an ongoing role for Diller in
Lycos might discourage another buyer from joining a counteroffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big obstacle,'' said one person familiar with CMGI's
attempts to arrange a challenge to Diller's bid.
</P>
<P>
   David Wetherell, CMGI chief executive, says he has talked with
at least four parties who may be interested in topping the offer
USA Networks made for Lycos on Feb. 9. Under that pact, Lycos would
merge with elements of USA Networks like its Home Shopping Network
and the Ticketmaster service.
</P>
<P>
   Before the deal was announced, Lycos's shares had traded as high
as $137 apiece on expectations that the company, as the last big
independent portal, could attract a rich offer.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal disappointed investors, even though many stock
analysts have come to endorse it. After Lycos shares sank as low as
83 7/8, Wetherell stepped down from the Lycos board of directors
and began campaigning publicly against the agreement. As reported,
Wetherell believes he has enough support from other major
shareholders to block the proposed deal.
</P>
<P>
   Diller has said he won't renegotiate the terms of the Lycos
agreement now, but a spokeswoman for USA Networks said Tuesday if a
higher bid emerges, USA Networks would consider making an even
higher offer.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Diller does nothing, a clause in a USA Networks
filing to the Securities and Exchange Commission on Feb. 26
suggests Diller would be protected if a competing bidder emerges.
The clause allows Diller's USA Networks to purchase up to 7.56
million shares of Lycos, or 17.5 percent of the company, at $127.14
apiece, near the stock's closing price the day before the deal was
announced. Other rights assigned to Diller-controlled Ticketmaster
Online-CitySearch Inc. could bring the total stake in Lycos to 19.9
percent, the filing states.
</P>
<P>
   Exercising the options would require USA Networks to come up
with as much as $961 million in cash. Still, even individuals close
to Lycos concede the options would prove profitable to Diller if a
rival bid valued Lycos at more than $127 per share _ roughly the
price at which the USA deal originally valued Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Birnbaum, a partner at the Foley, Hoag and Eliot law firm
who specializes in mergers &AMP; acquisitions, said that ordinarily, a
would-be buyer would regard a challenge like Wetherell's as
``exactly what you don't want to happen'' after a merger agreement
is reached. But under Diller's arrangments, he said, that may not
be the case.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the price of Lycos, based in Waltham, Mass., dropped
1/4 to 105 1/2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 1406EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3821 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOP-LYCOS-BOS &LR;      03-17 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOP-LYCOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME SHOPPING FIRMS DON'T GET RESPECT, JUST REVENUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cubic zirconia merchants are starting to earn some respect.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Home Shopping Network Inc. and QVC are best known
for the kitschy rhinestones they advertise on cable television. But
savvy marketers and investors now see their vast customer databases
as potential gems in the burgeoning world of electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Home Shopping Network alone has more than 20 million customer
names and credit card numbers on file _ more than three times as
many as giant on-line bookseller Amazon.com is estimated to keep.
</P>
<P>
   That reach, combined with Home Shopping's ability to fill tens
of thousands of orders a day, is a key reason some analysts back a
controversial merger proposal under which Home Shopping's parent,
USA Networks Inc., would take control of Lycos Inc., the
Waltham-based Internet portal.
</P>
<P>
   Another home-shopping channel, Minneapolis-based ValueVision
International Inc., recently received a $56 million investment from
General Electric Co. and its NBC broadcasting unit to develop
content allied with NBC's other on-line interests like CNet and its
Snap.com service.
</P>
<P>
   Forward-looking Internet investors often scoff at the business
models of the home-shopping channels. In their view, the revenue
and profits these companies generate can't support the huge market
valuations investors place on companies that describe themselves as
pure Internet plays and benefit from the potential of the new
on-line mediums.
</P>
<P>
   But the recent interest from NBC and Lycos suggests that at its
heart, electronic commerce won't be much different from the
business model pioneered by companies best known for hawking
costume jewelry: draw the attention of far-flung buyers with flashy
programs, then ship them goods quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody with expertise in fulfilling customer orders should be
feared in the on-line world,'' said Ken Cassar, an analyst with
Jupiter Communications. Said Chris Charron of Forrester Research,
``The portals as a whole realize the importance of e-commerce, and
they're looking for players who already know the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Uncertainty over the future of Lycos illustrates just how
complex it has become to value home-shopping services. Officially,
the chief executive of Lycos' largest investor, CMGI Inc., withdrew
his support for the pending merger last week because he felt the
agreement with USA Networks didn't assign enough value to Lycos
shares. Instead, CMGI chief David Wetherell said he would try to
assemble a higher bid for control of Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   But even Wetherell agrees that USA Networks and its Home
Shopping Nework unit have something to offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody on the (CMGI) board saw the potential value of the
pieces that were coming together,'' Wetherell told investors on a
conference call last Thursday. He added that he has received
hundreds of e-mails from other investors opposed to the terms of
the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of a sweeter bid boosted Lycos shares 14 percent
last Wednesday, but they have dropped back slightly since then.
Tuesday, they closed at 105 1/2, down 1/4. CMGI shares, which hit a
high of 199 11/16 on March 8, fell 11 7/8 Tuesday to 180 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in home-shopping channels stems from the revenue they
generate. The two largest are QVC, jointly owned by cable
television companies ComCast Corp. and Tele-Communications Inc.,
followed by Home Shopping Network Inc. Together they are estimated
to have sold about $3 billion worth of goods in 1998. In contrast,
the largest seller of consumer goods over the Internet, Amazon.com,
had revenue of about $650 million in its most recent fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, home-shopping services already had begun to establish
themselves on the World Wide Web, even before the recent flurry of
interest. The third-ranked home-shopping channel, Shop At Home
Inc., recently struck a deal with Oracle Corp. to create a Web site
featuring collectibles and baseball cards.
</P>
<P>
   In Minneapolis, ValueVision executives say the company recorded
several million dollars worth of sales through its Web site during
the 12 months ended Jan. 31, up from ``a couple hundred thousand''
for the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   When the company first set up its Web site in 1997, its goal was
limited to attracting consumers who saw ValueVision's infomercials
on cable television, said Steve Sedahl, the company's manager of
electronic commerce. But now live video feeds over the company's
Web site means consumers with advanced PCs and modems can watch the
shopping show on line through a video link over the Internet.
Inadvertently, that also helped attract interest from NBC, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Lycos vice president Thomas E. Guilfoile cited Home
Shopping Networks' ability to process as many as 30,000 customer
orders in 24 hours as a powerful draw. The network once moved $24
million worth of computers in a single day, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now Lycos must convince a majority of its investors that the
potential benefits of an alliance with USA Networks will, in the
not-so-long run, benefit shareholders more than any deal Wetherell
might cobble together.
</P>
<P>
   Wetherell said he has as long as four months to arrange a deal
before Lycos holds a shareholder meeting to vote on its merger
agreements. He is currently vacationing in the Caribbean,
indicating a competing proposal might not be imminent.
</P>
<P>
   But industry observers think time might be on Lycos's side if
Wetherell can't find another interested buyer quickly. One ironic
possibility is NBC, which previously passed on a deal for Lycos but
now could combine the search engine with the its newly acquired
interest in ValueVision.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Hiawatha Bray of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
