<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3831 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-TOTENBERG-BOS &LR;      03-17 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-TOTENBERG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER-DAUGHTER BOND IS TOTENBERG'S BIGGEST REWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA MATCHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWTON, Mass. _ Nina Totenberg, legal affairs correspondent for
National Public Radio, likes to tell the story about the time her
sister, Jill, was writing a college entrance essay. It began, ``My
father was an immigrant,'' Nina recalls. ``To which he responded,
she says, affecting her thickest Polish accent, ``I vas
(itals)not(unitals) an immigrant. I vas an invited guest of the
United States government!''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking by phone from her office in Washington, D.C., Nina
laughs when she tells the story, which she considers quintessential
Roman Totenberg.
</P>
<P>
   When he tells his version of the story at home in Newton, Roman
Totenberg, 87, chuckles, amused at an image of himself as a peasant
among the huddled masses. ``She made me sound like someone just off
the boat!'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Technically speaking, the Polish-born Totenberg _ a renowned
violinist and teacher _ (itals)was)(unitals) an immigrant when he
came to the United States in 1938 (even though, yes, three years
earlier he'd been an invited guest on a monthlong US concert tour.)
</P>
<P>
   It is in this context that on Friday he will be among eight
immigrants honored in Washington at the Fourth Annual Immigrant
Achievement Awards, sponsored by the American Immigration Law
Foundation. The awards are given to American immigrants who have
distinguished themselves by ``making a difference in communities
around the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Totenberg, who many years later still rolls his r's and
pronounces his w's as v's, easily satisfies the requirement. His
musical career, which began when he tutored his first violin
student at the age of 11 (the student was 10), continues to be
prodigious. He has been an important figure on the international
concert circuit; has made hundreds of recordings; and has been a
dedicated teacher known for his exacting and generous spirit. A
star pupil as a young man of the legendary Carl Flesch in Berlin,
Totenberg has been hailed as one of the last remaining links to
pre-World War II violin playing, which has since been dominated by
Russian teaching and style.
</P>
<P>
   He still gives concerts, though ``not very much,'' he says
dismissively. ``Only about 10 a year. I used to play 60 or 70.''
But his parallel career of teaching continues to flourish.
Totenberg still works full-time at Boston University's School for
the Arts where he has taught for 38 years and where he cochairs the
string department. Three years ago he won the University's top
teaching honor, the Metcalf prize for excellence.
</P>
<P>
   But this week's award is especially sweet for Totenberg because
the event will be hosted by his beloved daughter, Nina, a respected
NPR reporter who broke the Clarence Thomas/Anita Hill story. At 55,
she is the eldest of his three daughters: Jill, 51, is a business
executive in New York, and Amy, 48, is a prominent Atlanta
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each one of the girls, in their fields, is remarkable,'' says
Roman Totenberg, launching a sort of preemptive strike lest a
visitor inquire only about Nina. ``Jill is an executive, so to say.
She tells them how to run the company. Amy has won many important
cases, all by herself.''
</P>
<P>
   It is clear immediately that his love for music is matched, no,
surpassed, by his adoration of the three grown girls whose
photographs are displayed throughout his spacious home, along with
mementos of his career _ the signed photograph of Franklin D.
Roosevelt, the photo of himself with pianist Artur Rubinstein, the
framed note from physician and musician Albert Schweitzer.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Nina with whom he has the most poignant bond. Both
father and daughter recently lost their spouses. Melanie Totenberg,
Roman's wife of 57 years, died 2 1/2 years ago. Last August, Nina
lost her husband, former Colorado Senator Floyd Haskell. When
Haskell died at 82 of pneumonia, it was her father to whom Nina
reached out. Haskell died on an airplane while he and Nina were
returning from a vacation in Maine; the pilot then returned the
plane to Bangor, and Nina says one of her first thoughts was to ask
the control tower to call her father to meet her at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Roman Totenberg was in Maine, though more than an hour away from
Bangor. Nina says he drove ``85 miles an hour'' and stopped only
when he got to the tarmac so he could meet her. ``He was very
tender and sweet,'' she recalls. ``We went to a Catholic Hospital,
and later one of the nuns said to me that he had been standing in
the waiting room while I was with Floyd, and saying, ``That's my
daughter and there is nothing I can to do help her.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Nina, ``He is an incredibly perceptive, sweet human being.
He played at Floyd's funeral. I can't tell you how wonderful he has
been to me. He has a very light touch, just when I need him the
most.''
</P>
<P>
   The continued vitality of her father _ a man she says is a
unique combination of ``hypochondriac and stoic'' _ continues to
astound her. ``He cleans my clock in tennis; I can't get a point
off him most of the time,'' she says. ``Once, when he jumped and
put a shot away on me, I said to him, `Don't you understand you're
supposed to be old?' ''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Totenberg calls Nina his ``grown-up little girl. .
. . There are many occasions when a parent is the last resort to a
child. When something is wrong, each daughter calls and says,
``Daddy, fix it!''
</P>
<P>
   And can he fix it? ``I think I can,'' he says, beaming.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone rings. Totenberg, dressed this Saturday morning in
a dapper burgundy jacket, colorful tie, and pocket handkerchief,
hurries over to answer it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello darling,'' he says happily. It is Nina, checking in as
she and her sisters do almost every day. ``Daddy, I wanted to say I
was sorry about Yehudi Menuhin (the violinist who died last
week),'' Nina says. ``Didn't you see him last spring? I knew he
wasn't well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I was upset,'' Totenberg says, walking back and forth in
his sunny study while speaking on a cordless telephone. ``He was in
the best of moods when I saw him. He was terribly friendly with his
students. He was with his daughter Mira.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Mira _ we went swimming (as children) in their
swimming pool in California,'' his daughter replies. ``I remember
that it had a slanted bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(itals)She(unitals) did not have a slanted bottom,'' Totenberg
quips.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pool did,'' Nina groans, in mock exasperation. The
conversation turns to Nina's plans for the day (marketing, buying a
new CD player), and to the temper tantrum that Jill's newly adopted
daughter was having when Nina called the other day. The little girl
is named Melanie, for her late grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to talk to you,'' Totenberg signs off.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, darling daddy,'' Nina says.
</P>
<P>
   Both of them are looking forward to May, when they will take a
vacation to Europe together. But first there is Totenberg's sojourn
to Washington this weekend, to receive his award.
</P>
<P>
   Nina has lined up ``a busy social schedule'' for the two of
them. There is the Friday night awards dinner, then on Saturday,
lunch with Attorney General Janet Reno (``he is mad about her and
she is mad about him''), and dinner with friends. Sunday and Monday
will be consumed with other lunch, dinner, and party engagements.
</P>
<P>
   Then, newly invigorated, he will head back to Boston. Roman
Totenberg must return to work, after all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
