<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-SALEM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LITTLE-KNOWN WONDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Given the success of Holy Cross, Northeastern, and
Boston College this year in women's basketball, it's easy to forget
about Salem State.
</P>
<P>
   Easy, but not fair.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Holy Cross making its seventh trip in 14 years to the NCAA
Tournament is impressive. The surprise NCAA debut of Northeastern
was a great story; the breakthrough year at The Heights was a joy.
And of course, perennial powerhouse Bentley is at it again, back in
the Division 2 Elite Eight.
</P>
<P>
   But when Salem State meets the College of St. Benedict (Minn.)
in Friday's semifinals in Danbury, Conn., the Lady Vikings will
make their fourth appearance in the Division 3 Final Four, and
we'll bet you didn't know that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just do it silently,'' said junior Dee Jackson, the
team's leading scorer (13.6 points per game) and two-time
Massachusetts State College Athletic Conference player of the year.
``And then, people will know.''
</P>
<P>
   Know this: In 17 years, this is the 16th NCAA Tournament
appearance for the Lady Vikings, whose 76-60 victory over rival
Williams last weekend to advance to the Final Four gave it a
school-record 24 straight wins in a single season.
</P>
<P>
   And this: Tim Shea, in his 18th season at the helm, sets the
tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very low-key,'' explained sophomore Melissa Smock. ``We
don't get worked up as much as we would if he were screaming. We're
basically the same.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you need to be a fanatic,'' said Shea, which
seems to sum up both his personality and his program.
</P>
<P>
   After inheriting a program hovering around .500 in 1980-81, Shea
_ a Salem native who left his coaching job at Salem High School
with a three-year record of 70-3 and a state championship to coach
the Lady Vikings _ immediately turned things around, posting a
16-11 mark in his first season. The next year, his squad was 23-7
and went to the NCAAs for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably had half a dozen Salem High players those first two
or three years,'' said Shea of the quick rise. ``That gave us a big
head start.''
</P>
<P>
   Sustaining it was another matter. Shea put 22,000 miles on his
1998 Oldsmobile last year (``If I'm going to drive all that way, I
like to be comfortable'') checking out New England high school
games. ``Even at our level, recruiting is the name of the game,''
he said. A national championship in 1986 _ we'll bet you didn't
know that, either _ got the school's name out there a bit more, but
only a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we'd have it made,'' said Shea, now the
fifth-winningest active Division 3 coach in the country, ``that
those recruits would be walking in the door. But that wasn't so.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because the strength of Salem State's program,
ironically, puts it neither here nor there: it can't offer
scholarships, because it plays in Division 3, but neither can it
promise a recruit a lot of playing time in return for her tuition
check.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we lose very good players because those kids want to
go somewhere and play right away,'' said Shea. ``Which is why we
have to do a lot of driving. We've got to find the right type of
kid: If she wants to put up a lot of stats, this isn't her type of
program. We don't have a lot of big scorers here, because we
usually put a team on the court that's pretty balanced.''
</P>
<P>
   What Shea calls ``dressing up'' the program helps: road trips
over the years to Puerto Rico, San Diego, Colorado Springs,
Ireland. But to a large extent, Shea's secret is a keen eye and
vivid imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are players out there who get passed over left and
right,'' he said. ``You don't make it to this Final Four level
without some scholarship-level players on your team. I think we
have two or three players that some people missed the boat on.''
</P>
<P>
   One is Katie Duffey. A forward when she came out of Winnesquam
Regional High School in New Hampshire, Shea has her playing the
point. ``If she had played point guard in high school,'' he said,
``I don't think we would have got her.''
</P>
<P>
   Another is Smock, 5 feet 5 inches and slight at that. ``I'm sure
people were scared away from Missy by her size, but she can play,''
said Shea. ``I'd match her up with any 3-point shooter around.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Shea's
how-to-succeed-in-basketball-without-losing-your-mind philosophy.
Hard practices? You bet. But after two hours, it's over. No
mandatory weight lifting. No year-round monitoring. No videotape. (
Well, the team will watch some of St. Benedict on the bus down to
Western Connecticut State University in Danbury, site of the Final
Four, but only because the bus happens to have a video player.) No
chalk talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe in overdoing it,'' said Shea. ``The only
requirement is, you need to be able to play on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to argue with an 18-year record of 423-90 and
counting, but a couple of victories this weekend would be
especially nice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the players are confident,'' said Jackson, who was the
first female at Lynn English to score 1,000 points, graduating in
1995 with 1,172 and attending Drexel on partial scholarship for a
year before coming home. ``We figure we played so hard during the
season that we deserve to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   And deserve to be noticed as much as their Division 1 and 2
sisters, even though Shea said neither he nor his team mind not
getting as much ink. ``You'd have to have a major ego to have that
bother you,'' he said. ``They don't see me irritated about it, and
I don't think they are. In our own little world, we are being
recognized.''
</P>
<P>
   The world just got a little bigger, coach. Hope you don't mind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
