<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-KHALID-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EL-AMIN MIXES PIZZAZZ, SKILL FOR CONNECICUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Sometimes, he responds to reporters' questions as if
he's leaving a detailed answering machine message, trying to get in
as many words as possible before the darn thing clicks off.
</P>
<P>
   So tell us, Khalid El-Amin, are you and the other Connecticut
Huskies playing your best basketball now, in the NCAA West
Regional?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing good basketball that's what's scary about this
team we haven't even played our bestbasketballyetwe've
beenplayinggreatdefensivelybutwe've beendoingitinspurts,'' said the
sensational sophomore point guard following the Huskies'
second-round victory over New Mexico that vaulted it into this
week's Sweet 16 round.
</P>
<P>
   So much of what El-Amin does on the court mirrors his rapid-fire
verbiage. Often he comes at you with a quick, continuous barrage of
points or passes. He moves his 5-foot-10-inch, 203-pound frame so
well that he makes more slender players wonder why they're chasing
his shadow.
</P>
<P>
   And he blends boyishness with a maturity and court sense beyond
that of most 19-year-olds. It is as if someone put Damon
Stoudamire's skills and Magic Johnson's court awareness and
enthusiasm in John Bagley's body.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early to compare him to our greatest players, but
he's been terrific for us, obviously,'' said UConn coach Jim
Calhoun, whose top-seeded Huskies (30-2) meet fifth-seeded Iowa
(20-9) in Thursday night's regional semifinals in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just flow in the game,'' said El-Amin, last season's Big
East Rookie of the Year and a second-team all-conference selection
this year. ``Early in the game I hit some shots and I just continue
to make shots through the whole game.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Huskies' 91-66 first-round victory over Texas-San
Antonio, El-Amin was a passing whiz, distributing the ball from
various angles and at various speeds for 10 assists. He directed an
offense that shot 55 percent from the floor and put four players in
double figures.
</P>
<P>
   In the 78-56 victory over New Mexico, El-Amin helped lead the
scoring charge, frustrating the Lobos with quick pull-up jumpers
and finishing with 21 points on 8-of-16 shooting, including 3 of 7
from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really go out there and say, `I'm going to do this,
I'm going to do that,' '' he said. ``It's just a game and a feel,
and whatever I feel like doing, I'm going to out there and do the
best I can.''
</P>
<P>
   His impact at UConn was almost immediate. The much-ballyhooed
recruit scored 23 points in his first and third collegiate games,
then had back-to-back 29-point efforts in his sixth and seventh
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just knew what I could do, and I didn't want to come out and
change my game in any way, shape, or form,'' said El-Amin. ``I
wanted to come out and do the things I'm capable of doing, and
Coach has given me the confidence to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most difficult side has been the academics side of it.
Basketball is going to take care of itself. As long as you work
hard and continue to do the things you're good at, you're going to
be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, El-Amin has served notice that he is the catalyst
on a team that includes Big East Player of the Year Richard
Hamilton. Entering the NCAAs, he was second on the team in assists
to Ricky Moore, which Calhoun said shows his willingness to allow
another exceptional passer to contribute to the offense.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, El-Amin he often saves some of his best outings
for big games. Against Michigan State on Dec. 5, he won the battle
of college basketball's most heralded guards, outplaying Mateen
Cleaves by scoring 20 points on 7-for-12 shooting and dishing out 6
assists in an 82-68 victory. Cleaves finished with 6 points on
2-for-15 shooting, with 7 assists.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin's best effort undoubtedly came in a 70-59 victory at
Stanford Feb. 6. Hamilton was injured and the Huskies were coming
off their first loss of the season, a 59-42 home setback to
Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin played well despite being the target of verbal abuse,
some of which was quite personal. In addition to teasing him about
his frame with chants such as ``Doughboy'' and ``Fat Boy,'' fans
reportedly derided El-Amin for being a Muslim and the fact that he
has been married twice and has two children.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin responded by registering game highs in points (23),
assists (5), and steals (5). He pointed to the scoreboard when the
game was over.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the Dec. 12 contest against Pittsburgh. El-Amin,
who said that Pitt fans directed racial slurs at him, hit a runner
with two seconds left as the Huskies won, 70-69, then he stood atop
the scorer's table and taunted them back before Calhoun pulled him
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of those kids who at times is 12,'' said Calhoun,
``but most importantly a lot of times on the court he's 30 and he's
got an insight and feel for the game a lot of kids don't have.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it gets personal like that, it does bother me,'' said El
Amin. ``But all the `Fat Boy' taunts and things like that, that's
cool, that's part of college basketball and I accept that. But then
it gets personal, then that's not showing any class and I think I
have to speak up about that.''
</P>
<P>
   UConn came into the NCAAs with several concerns: injuries to
Jake Voskuhl and Albert Mouring, the effects of altitude at this
first-round site, and Calhoun's last-minute gastrointestinal virus.
Yet in both games, El-Amin set the tone, and his team followed his
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't want my season to end,'' said El-Amin. ``I
wanted to come out and just play as hard as I can, and try to let
the other guys feed off me so we can definitely have a tremendous
run in this tournament. So I just try to come out and lead by
example.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
