<HEADLINE>
SLOC'S ROMNEY KEEPS IT SIMPLE AND FRUGAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (s and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ Mitt Romney hadn't known about the
vaulted ceiling, the gilded chandelier, the marble floors, the
burnished wood, the sumptuous draperies. All he knew was that his
staff had booked him into a hotel called the Beau Rivage. Nobody
told him that the lobby alone looked like Versailles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next time,'' Romney said, ``I think I'll be in the
Movenpick.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday, when he made his first report to the
International Olympic Committee's executive board, Salt Lake City's
new chief organizer had never been to Olympic headquarters. He had
never met IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch. He wasn't sure if
he should go bilingual.
</P>
<P>
   ``My French is a little rusty,'' Romney confessed, ``and I
didn't want to offend.''
</P>
<P>
   No worries there. Romney was the most popular man to show up at
the Chateau de Vidy in ages. On the eve of the most wrenching day
in IOC history, when its members are expected to expel six of their
colleagues for taking payoffs and gifts from the Salt Lake bidders,
IOC officials were delighted to see anybody from Utah who was
talking about 2002 and not 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``He presented easily and comfortably,'' said board member Kevan
Gosper of Australia after Romney had provided what is usually
considered a routine status report. ``He was quite front-footed and
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   And Romney was alone. That was a symbolic shock to IOC members
who are used to seeing a platoon of organizing committee officials
at their meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not spend travel money to have an entourage,'' Romney
declared.
</P>
<P>
   With the Salt Lake Organizing Committee still several hundred
million dollars short of breaking even, Romney has a new
philosophy: ``Profit, pride, and pageantry come second.'' After a
month on the job, he has chopped $14 million from his $1.45 billion
budget, imposed a hiring freeze, and told trustees that their free
lunches are over. And the IOC members will have no chauffeured
limousines at the Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be Blazers and Tahoes driven by volunteers,'' Romney
said.
</P>
<P>
   Romney says he'll apply the same spartan symbolism to himself.
He could have spent the week in this charming lakeside city,
chatting up IOC members over champagne and chateaubriand. Instead,
he arrived Tuesday morning, had lunch with Samaranch and the board,
and was headed home as dawn broke Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, the IOC was to decide whether to formally
expel the members who were ``excluded'' by the board here in
January. The cases will be heard in alphabetical order _ Agustin
Arroyo of Ecuador, Zein El Abdin Ahmed Abdel Gadir of Sudan,
Jean-Claude Ganga of the Republic of Congo, Lamine Keita of Mali,
Sergio Santander (Fantini) of Chile, and Seiuli Paul Wallwork of
Western Samoa. They will be taken up individually, with two-thirds
of the 91 votes necessary for expulsion.
</P>
<P>
   Romney saw no point in hanging around for the IOC's public
bloodletting, which stems from payoffs made by his Salt Lake
predecessors, and he wouldn't comment on anything mentioned in the
IOC, US Olympic Committee, or SLOC reports involving the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see my job to be focused entirely on 2002 and to spend no
time evaluating, investigating or speaking about the problems of
the past,'' Romney said. ``That will be left to those who had been
holding the reins during that time. I'm not going to dwell on the
past because I wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   But what the IOC does or doesn't do will have a decided impact
on the SLOC, which still needs $350 million from sponsors, many of
whom are wary of being linked to tarnished Olympic rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need aggressive action, both substantive and symbolic
action, on the IOC's part,'' Romney acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC has promised that it will push through dramatic reforms
both this week and later this year. Besides expelling six members,
on top of the four who have already resigned, the IOC is expected
to change the way it selects host cities, allowing the full
membership (which already has been banned from visiting bidders) to
vote only for two finalists chosen by a smaller group. The
committee also will set up an independent outside panel to oversee
its ethics and take steps toward opening its books and reforming
the way its members are chosen.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the members leave the Palais de Beaulieu Thursday,
SLOC's chief organizer will be back in the shadow of the Mormon
Temple, tinkering with the budget and trying to persuade local
sponsors to sign on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 1414EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
