<SLUG> BC-FLEET-BANKBOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURRAY SEEKS TO ALLAY FEARS AT BANKBOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It was a sight few in the crowded BankBoston Corp.
auditorium had likely ever imagined: The chief executive of
archrival Fleet Financial Group, Terrance Murray, taking the stage.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the hard-edged, street-fighting Murray was viewed
from BankBoston's venerable halls not only as an enemy but as the
brash antithesis of BankBoston's patrician culture.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, just a day after announcing Fleet would acquire
BankBoston to create the nation's eighth largest bank, Murray set
foot in enemy territory and received an unanticipated standing
ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to tell you, I never expected to be introducing Terry
Murray in the BankBoston auditorium to a standing ovation,''
Charles Gifford, BankBoston's chief executive, told employees who
stood in the auditorium's aisles and jammed a lobby outside.
Gifford will become chief operating officer of the proposed $178
billion Fleet Boston Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Joking with Gifford as if they were old friends, Murray took
questions for an hour from BankBoston employees in 38 BankBoston
offices around the world where the meeting was broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   He said the arduous job of merging banks of such size and vastly
differing cultures would take a year and a half. But he played down
the differences between the former rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that in time you're going to find we're not as
sharp-edged as you think we are, and we're going to find you less
warm and fuzzy than we think you are,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Murray sought to allay fears of Fleet's ``slash-and-burn''
reputation in eliminating jobs at banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``BankBoston has been more artful than we may have been in the
past, and there is something to be learned from that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet identified $700 million in potential cuts through job
eliminations and consolidations as it researched the deal, but
Murray said $600 million in cuts is ``a more reasonable'' figure to
expect. Fleet has said some 5,000 jobs will be cut, many of them
through attrition and hiring freezes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll try to go about that in a business-like and humane
way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he warned that managers will be forced to make
tough decisions about job eliminations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't achieve those (cost cutting goals) the market is
going to kill us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to questions from employees in Brazil and Argentina,
Murray said he expects BankBoston's prized Latin American
operations to grow in the next three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected drop in Fleet's stock price as Wall Street
reacted unenthusiastically to the deal was caused by arbitrage
traders who had anticipated the merger and bet on it ahead of time,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a question possibly suggestive of fears about life under
Fleet management, one employee asked if Murray planned to abolish a
BankBoston tradition, casual day.
</P>
<P>
   Murray quipped that during negotiations Gifford had offered to
lower the bank's price in order to continue allowing employees to
dress down once a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've frankly never heard of the concept,'' Murray said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
