<HEADER>
A3883 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-FOIL-RECIPES18-C     03-17 2326
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-FOIL-RECIPES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gourmet or family-friendly, meals go together beautifully when
you finesse them with foil
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether you are in the mood for a gourmet entree like Tarragon
Chicken Breast With Mushroom Sauce or a family feast like Cajun
Sausage and Beans, the secret to success is in the packet.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking in foil packets creates moist, steamy dishes quickly.
And cleanup goes even quicker. There are only a few things to keep
in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Regular foil will work fine, but heavy-duty foil is better,
particularly if you want to place the packets directly on the oven
rack or grill grate.
</P>
<P>
   Check out the directions here for making a packet _ but don't be
afraid to perfect your own folding method. Just be sure to leave an
air pocket inside so heat can circulate and create a tight seam so
juices won't leak.
</P>
<P>
   Some like to spray the foil lightly with cooking spray. You may
choose to put the packets on a baking sheet or right on the oven
rack or grate. And be careful when opening so your hands won't get
steamed.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Bay Scallops With Roasted Bell Pepper
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 8 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Because of their small size, bay scallops are quickly overcooked
when sauteed on the stovetop. Here, Jacqueline Mallorca, author of
``The Perfect Dinner: Fine Food Cooked With Foil'' ($22.95, Fair
Oaks Press), offers a quick steam in a foil packet with fresh,
aromatic vegetables as a better way to enjoy these tiny, sweet
gifts from the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil spray
</P>
<P>
   2 yellow bell peppers, broiled, peeled and sliced in 3/4-inch
diamonds
</P>
<P>
   4 green onions, including pale green leaves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 small ripe tomatoes, peeled, seeded and chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons capers, drained
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 pounds tiny bay scallops
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. For each serving, lightly spray the
center area of a 16-inch length of foil with olive oil. Combine one
quarter of the bell pepper, onion, tomato and capers to one side of
the center of each piece of foil. Top with a quarter of the
scallops, season with salt and pepper and sprinkle with 1
tablespoon parsley. Spray with olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Fold the foil pieces over the scallops and vegetables; then fold
and tightly crimp the edges together to form packets. Place the
packets on a baking sheet and bake for 8 minutes. On a dinner
plate, slit open the packet's straight side and withdraw the foil,
leaving the scallop mixture and its aromatic juices on the center
of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, spoon rice around the scallops and over the juices.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 167 calories, 25 grams protein, 1 gram fat (percent
calories from fat, 8), 12 grams carbohydrates, 47 milligrams
cholesterol, 336 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Cajun Sausage and Beans
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20-25 minutes in oven or 12-14 on grill
</P>
<P>
   For a Cajun kick, try this spicy, hearty beanie-weenie combo.
Perfect for an overnight camping trip, or a chilly March evening
when you want something simple yet substantial.
</P>
<P>
   1 pound kielbasa sausage, cut in 1/4-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   2 cans (15 ounces each) black beans, rinsed and drained
</P>
<P>
   1 can (14 1/2 ounces) diced tomatoes with garlic and onions
</P>
<P>
   1 medium green bell pepper, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons Cajun seasoning (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cayenne pepper (optional)
</P>
<P>
   4 sheets (12 by 18 inches each) heavy-duty aluminum foil
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 450 degrees or preheat grill to medium-high.
Combine sausage, beans, tomatoes, green pepper, seasoning and
cayenne. Center one-fourth of bean mixture on each sheet of foil.
Bring up sides of foil and double fold. Double fold ends to form
packets, leaving space for heat circulation inside.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 20 to 25 minutes on a cookie sheet in oven or grill 12 to
14 minutes in covered grill.
</P>
<P>
   Note: To make your own Cajun seasoning, combine 1 teaspoon
garlic powder, 1 teaspoon salt, 3/4 teaspoon dried basil, 3/4
teaspoon thyme, 3/4 teaspoon cayenne pepper, 1/2 teaspoon onion
powder and 1/4 teaspoon pepper. _ Reynolds Kitchens
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 379 calories, 19 grams protein, 20 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 48), 31 grams carbohydrates, 47
milligrams cholesterol, 932 milligrams sodium, 10 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Far East Spiced Chicken
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 18-22 minutes in oven or 14-18 minutes on grill
</P>
<P>
   Apricots and a Far East blend of cinnamon, coriander and cumin
make this chicken a special treat _ quick enough to make on a
weeknight.
</P>
<P>
   2 sheets (12-by-18-inches each) heavy duty aluminum foil
</P>
<P>
   Nonstick cooking spray
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   2 skinless, boneless chicken breast halves
</P>
<P>
   1 medium red bell pepper, cut in strips
</P>
<P>
   4 green onions, cut in 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup apricot preserves or orange marmalade
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons orange juice
</P>
<P>
   Garlic salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   10 dried apricots, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup rice, uncooked
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 450 degrees or preheat grill to high. Spray
sheets of foil with nonstick cooking spray.
</P>
<P>
   Combine cinnamon, coriander and cumin. Sprinkle and rub
seasoning over chicken, turning to coat evenly. (You may not need
to use all of the spice mixture.) Center one chicken breast on each
foil sheet. Top each with half the red pepper strips and green
onions. Drizzle with apricot preserves and orange juice. Sprinkle
with garlic salt. Wrap and seal foil to form two packets, leaving
room for heat circulation inside packets. Bake 18 to 22 minutes on
cookie sheet in oven or grill 14 to 18 minutes on high in covered
grill.
</P>
<P>
   Serve over Apricot Rice Pilaf: Stir apricots into uncooked rice
and then cook following rice package directions. _ From: The
Reynolds Kitchens
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 717 calories, 44 grams protein, 5 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 6), 124 grams carbohydrates, 96
milligrams cholesterol, 99 milligrams sodium, 5 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   VEGETABLE
</P>
<P>
   Herbed Vegetable Packet
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20-25 minutes in oven or 15-20 on grill
</P>
<P>
   This is a no-fuss, no-muss way to cook up a medley of veggies
fast. And if you are grilling out and simply don't want to turn on
the oven inside, these packets will work well on the grill, too.
</P>
<P>
   1 sheet (18 by 24 inches) heavy-duty aluminum foil
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   3 cups broccoli florets
</P>
<P>
   2 medium carrots, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 medium yellow squash or zucchini, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon garlic salt
</P>
<P>
   2 ice cubes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons margarine or butter
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 450 degrees or preheat grill to medium-high.
Center onion, broccoli, carrots and squash on foil. Sprinkle with
basil and garlic salt and add ice cubes. Dot with margarine. Bring
up sides of foil and double fold. Double fold ends to form a
packet, leaving room for heat circulation inside. Bake 20 to 25
minutes on cookie sheet in oven or grill 15 to 20 minutes on
medium-high in covered grill. _ Reynolds Kitchens
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 103 calories, 3 grams protein, 6 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 54), 11 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 622
milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina Barbecue Pork
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 1 3/4 hours
</P>
<P>
   This Reynolds Kitchens recipe is ideal if you need to feed a
crowd and plan to have the grill hot for a few hours. If not, you
can cook the pork for the first 1 1/2 hours in the oven at 375
degrees, and then finish over high flames on a gas grill for the
last 20 minutes. The result will be tender, tangy meat with a smoky
char.
</P>
<P>
   For the seasoning rub:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons paprika
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds boneless pork loin or shoulder roast
</P>
<P>
   1 sheet (18 by 24 inches) heavy-duty aluminum foil
</P>
<P>
   For the vinegar-pepper sauce:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon crushed red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   Hamburger or sandwich buns
</P>
<P>
   Preheat grill to medium. Combine sugar, salt, paprika and
pepper. Sprinkle and rub seasoning over roast, turning to coat
evenly. Put roast on foil.
</P>
<P>
   In a bowl, combine cider vinegar, 2 tablespoons sugar, red
pepper flakes, salt, cayenne and Worcestershire sauce. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Bring up sides of foil and double fold. Double fold one end to
seal. Through open end, add 1/2 cup vinegar-pepper sauce; reserve
remaining sauce. Double fold remaining end, leaving room for heat
circulation inside packet.
</P>
<P>
   Grill 1 1/2 hours or until roast is tender on medium in covered
grill. Carefully remove steamed roast from foil and place directly
on grill. Reserve 1/2 cup vinegar-pepper sauce to use on
sandwiches. Brush roast generously with remaining sauce. Continue
grilling 15 to 20 minutes on medium in uncovered grill, brushing
with sauce and turning every 5 minutes to cook evenly. Remove roast
from grill. Slice or shred roast while warm. Combine with reserved
sauce. Serve shredded pork on hamburger buns. Top with coleslaw, if
desired.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (with bun): 393 calories, 31 grams protein, 18 grams
fat (percent calories from fat, 41), 26 grams carbohydrates, 84
milligrams cholesterol, 868 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Foil-Baked Salmon
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 25-30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   When you buy expensive fish, the last thing you want is to end
up with something dry and indelicate. That's why fish is one of the
best foods for cooking in foil packets _ it creates a nice, moist,
steaming environment. This recipe calls for sauteing the vegetables
in a pan first _ an extra step, but it's worth it.
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter or olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 large carrot, cut in 1/4-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, cut in 1/4-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   2 celery ribs, cut in 1/4-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   2 shallots, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced parsley (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dried tarragon
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   Nonstick cooking spray
</P>
<P>
   6 salmon fillets (about 1 1/2 inches thick and 5 to 5 1/2 ounces
each)
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In a skillet, heat butter or olive
oil. Add carrot, onion, celery and shallots and saute until tender,
about 10 minutes (do not brown). Stir in parsley and tarragon and
season lightly with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Cut 6 sheets of aluminum foil (about 12 by 30 inches each) and
fold crosswise in half to form a double thickness. Lightly oil each
foil sheet or spray with nonstick cooking spray. Place a fillet in
the center of each foil rectangle. Top each fillet with an equal
amount of vegetables. Drizzle wine and olive oil in equal amounts
over each fillet. Bring the sides of the foil up to meet over the
fish. Fold the edges together, then fold over tightly to form a
seal, but leaving room inside.
</P>
<P>
   Place packets on the lower middle level of the oven and bake for
about 15 minutes (allow 10 minutes per inch of fillet thickness).
If fillet sizes vary, place packets with thicker slices in the back
so that thinner fillets may be easily removed from the oven first.
Fish is done when flesh feels springy to the touch, flakes with a
fork and is opaque all the way through. Serve in packets at the
table, or slide each fillet and its juices onto a dinner plate. _
Primary Color
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 281 calories, 29 grams protein, 16 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 51), 4 grams carbohydrates, 78
milligrams cholesterol, 78 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Tarragon Chicken Breast With Mushroom Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Here, chicken in packets gets a gourmet treatment with tarragon,
sherry and a mushroom cream sauce. Your guests will wonder how your
kitchen can look so clean after such a classy meal.
</P>
<P>
   Foil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter or margarine, softened, divided
</P>
<P>
   2 large shallots, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dried tarragon
</P>
<P>
   8 white mushrooms, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons pale dry Spanish sherry or favorite vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   2 fresh boneless, skinless chicken breast halves (about 5 ounces
each)
</P>
<P>
   Place baking sheet in oven. Preheat oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Grease the centers of two 16-inch-long pieces of foil with 1/2
tablespoon butter each.
</P>
<P>
   In a skillet, melt remaining butter. Add shallots and cook 2
minutes, until just softened. Stir in tarragon and mushrooms, and
saute until barely cooked, about 3 minutes. Stir in sherry and
season with salt and pepper to taste. Add cream and let it simmer
for 30 seconds, stirring frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer one-fourth of the mushroom sauce to one piece of foil,
to one side of the center. Top with chicken breast and another
fourth of the sauce. Fold foil over the chicken; then fold and
tightly crimp the edges together to form a D-shaped packet. Repeat
with second foil packet. Transfer packets to the hot baking sheet
and bake for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   On a dinner plate, slit open the packet's straight side and
withdraw the foil, leaving the chicken and mushroom sauce on the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with steamed rice. _ ``The Perfect Dinner: Fine Food
Cooked With Foil''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 458 calories, 36 grams protein, 33 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 64), 4 grams carbohydrates, 138
milligrams cholesterol, 329 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
