<TEXT>
<P>
   Home Section stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Thursday, March 18:
</P>
<P>
   BARBARA-BARRY-DESIGN (Los Angeles) _ In a town that cultivates
surface glow over darker depths, Barbara Barry, the designer, known
for her green tea- and mahogany-hued interiors that look like
colorized stills from Hepburn and Tracy's ``Desk Set,'' has the art
of presentation down cold. And when it gets chilly, despite the gas
fire, Ms. Barry quickly produces matching cashmere shawls. ``I want
to help people live a beautiful life. Design is a religion for
me.'' By Julie V. Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   GRAZER-HOME (Hollywood) _ What happens when one of Hollywood's
most successful producers, Brian Grazer, buys a home in the high
reaches of Pacific Palisades and starts overhauling the interiors?
He behaves like _ what else? _ a successful Hollywood producer. By
Bernard Weinruab.
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD-MALL (Hollywood) _ How do you create a mall that gives
tangible form to an illusion? How do you make it an attraction that
draws both the tourists that celebrities wish to avoid and the
celebrities that tourists yearn to see? How do you create a theater
there that can be queen for one day (for the Academy Awards) and a
working girl for the rest of the year? These were just some of the
many conundrums facing developers and designers of Hollywood and
Highland, a mammoth urban entertainment and retail development that
will have a new Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences theater
as its anchor in March 2001. By Frances Anderton.
</P>
<P>
   LOS-ANGELES-DESIGN (Undated) _ The winter months have seen an
avalanche of books on Los Angeles design, ranging from Monacelli's
new, definitive and splendid ``Frank O. Gehry: The Complete
Works,'' so heavy you would need a few work-outs to lift it, to
two, yes, two compendiums from the Spanish company Editorial
Gustavo Gili on R.M. Schindler, among the first of several
immigrants to plant the seeds of European Modernism in Los Angeles
in the 1920s. By Frances Anderton.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Gardening questions answered. By Leslie
Land.
</P>
<P>
   TULIPS (Undated) _ ``You never know why a love affair starts,''
said Anna Pavord, a British garden writer who has had quite an
affair with the tulip. Moreover, she said, ``an affair can't be
sustained over a long period unless that object of your affection
is mysterious and endlessly fascinating, revealing things you
didn't know _ it's such an incredibly complicated flower.'' By Ann
Raver.
</P>
<P>
   EDTV (Undated) _ Ed and Ray Pekurny are not what you'd call
stylish dudes. Ed's idea of an accessory is the beer bottle hanging
around his neck. Ray wants to own a gym, and he has the gross tank
tops and baggy sweats to prove it. Matthew McConaughey and Woody
Harrelson play the blue-collar Pekurny brothers in Ron Howard's new
movie, ``EDtv,'' which opens on March 26. Part ``The Truman Show,''
part Bud Lite commercial, this amiable romantic comedy imagines
what would happen if a cable network trained its cameras on a
Regular Guy 24 hours a day and turned his life into the ultimate
reality-television show. By Rick Marin.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other stories
from our partners: Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox News
Service, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona
Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles
Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
