<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3885 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN     03-17 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Against all odds: Demise of Phoenix a sad event
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ We had come to pay respects, mourners in the midst of
the usual merriment. An evening at Phoenix Brewing Company was
always a grand time, but there would be no more. When the Atlanta
restaurant closed earlier this month, some were shocked, many
surprised and anyone who'd been there just plain sorry.
</P>
<P>
   This was Atlanta's showcase brewpub, by acclamation the crown
jewel. Among the 11 area restaurants brewing their own beer on
premises, none came close to matching the German lagers that
Phoenix brought off with finesse and style, and none even attempted
the cuisine that earned Phoenix a reputation as one of Atlanta's
premier places to dine. The most thoroughly satisfying meal I've
had in Atlanta might have been a dish of Chilean sea bass prepared
by former chef Kevin Fonzo, accompanied by a couple of glasses of
Sprouse's assertive, hoppy pilsner.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, after four years of glowing reviews, it failed. Bills
incurred at its opening finally were too much to repay, even when
business was doing well.
</P>
<P>
   And so a table of friends and admirers gathered on a Sunday
evening, most invited by brewmaster Glen Sprouse to have a last
beer or two on the house. There was a moment when a tall glass of
the Seven Sisters Munchener, Phoenix's signature beer, stood almost
like a memorial to the brewpub that set for itself the highest
standards. Soon a pilsner was poured from the conditioning tank,
not quite ready but as ready as it was going to get. What a shame,
someone said, that Sprouse's majestic maibock _ the most complex
beer anyone has brewed in Atlanta _ would not be on hand when May
rolled around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in the business 30 years and this was my best
work,'' said Warren Bruno, one of Sprouse's partners and a veteran
Atlanta restaurateur. ``I've sold and closed restaurants and moved
on, but when we closed Phoenix, I wept.''
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants fail for myriad reasons _ competition, quality of
food and service, location. None of these could be laid at
Phoenix's door, even if its location in back of the Prado Shopping
Center was less than ideal. ``We were just undercapitalized, that's
the long and the short of it,'' Bruno says. ``We started out in the
hole and could never climb out of it. And we never had a budget for
promotion and advertising. That hurt us, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix was 8,000 square feet _ large for an upscale/casual
dining restaurant _ and it seated 240 people. When it opened four
years to the day it closed, it had the feel of elegance and the
prices to go with it. Game and seafood entrees ranged from $17 to
$24. The cozy bar was off to the side, secluded from the dining
area.
</P>
<P>
   Impressive as it was, the traffic of people willing to spend $25
and more for dinner, especially on a weeknight, was on the steady
side rather than of the packed-house kind. With its ambience and
the menu, Phoenix was not a place that attracted a younger, singles
crowd. A remodeling two years ago gave the place a looser, pub
atmosphere, and it was not long before the dreaded chicken wings
were on the menu. Anything to stay alive.
</P>
<P>
   Business quickly picked up. But it was not enough to reduce the
taxes incurred at the outset, the mounting debt service on loans,
the electricity bills that ran deep into four figures every month.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we opened,'' Bruno says, ``we were what brewpubs had
evolved to in California.''
</P>
<P>
   They are not there yet in Atlanta, and only an optimist would
believe they ever will be. Five years from now, Bruno says, there
might well be more brewpubs in Atlanta _ maybe as many as 15 or 20
_ ``but they'll be chains, places like Hops. There won't be
anything like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed there won't.
</P>
<P>
   BREAK HERE
</P>
<P>
   The resuscitation of Ringwood
</P>
<P>
   All beer begins with yeast, although mass-market beers such as
Budweiser, Miller and Coors have so little you'd never know it. Not
many beers have Ringwood yeast, a strain developed 200 years ago
and still breathing. The strain was resuscitated in the late '70s,
when an Englishman named Peter Austin opened a small brewery in the
Hampshire town of Ringwood, employing open-fermentation and
brick-clad brew kettles. Since then microbreweries on four
continents have bought the Peter Austin System, as it's called, and
produced ales of a distinctly English character.
</P>
<P>
   New Knoxville ales are among the few in the Southeast that use
Ringwood yeast (Water Tower brewpub in Kennesaw (Ga.) also uses
such a system). The British style is firm yet restrained,
preferring balance to over-the-top hoppiness. New Knoxville's India
Pale Ale is an excellent domestic example, the Ringwood yeast
imparting a slight dryness and a noticeable estery character.
</P>
<P>
   A still more interesting example is New Knoxville Porter, a
re-creation of a porter brewed in that city a century ago. The
brewery's name, in fact, harks back to a Tennessee brewery that
produced mostly ales in the days before Prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   Less hoppy than some porters from American micros, New Knoxville
is robust in an understated way and nicely accented by a
bittersweet finish. It hints at a time when English-style ales were
as common in the South as pilsners in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Jounral-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
