<HEADER>
A3887 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE18-COX     03-17 1797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With spring's arrival, celebrate religious customs
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ During the Easter/Passover season, which is one of the
most significant and meaningful times of the year for both
Christians and Jews, the Internet presents a wonderful opportunity
for each to deepen their understanding of the other.
</P>
<P>
   A flickering candle and the question, ``Why is this night
different from all other nights?'' welcome you at
http://www.holidays.net/passover/, a well-done site, especially for
those who want to familiarize themselves with the Passover
observance.
</P>
<P>
   For bunnies, bonnets and Easter egg hunts, you will have to look
elsewhere, but at http://www.njwebworks.com/easter/index
</P>
<P>
   .shtml, you will find a serious look at the religious
significance, history and traditions of the most significant date
on the Christian calendar. At
http://www.sweetgifts.com/aprilhol.htm, find a complete rundown of
both observances.
</P>
<P>
   A common thread through much of the Internet material on Easter
and Passover is the use of food _ symbolically, in ritual, in
celebration and as a means to pass down ancient stories.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Easter story as told in the New Testament took place
during the Jewish Passover _ indeed the Last Supper of Christ and
his disciples was a Passover meal _ many of the themes of Passover
transferred to what was to become the Easter observance.
</P>
<P>
   One food that holds very different but deep significance to both
Christians and Jew during this season is bread.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps there is no food as beloved or meaningful to Jews around
the world as matzo. To partake of this simple, unleavened flat
bread or cracker is to rise above symbolism and eat the bread of
ancestors who were commanded by Moses 3,000 years ago to flee Egypt
to freedom in such haste that they had no time to let the bread
they were preparing rise.
</P>
<P>
   You can learn all about matzo and meet the Manischewitz family,
who have been commercially producing matzo for more than 100 years,
at http://www.manischewitz.com/.
</P>
<P>
   A wonderful essay on the eating of matzo can be found at
http://www.rj.org/uahc/congs/la
</P>
<P>
   /la002/matsheat.html.
</P>
<P>
   And, at http:// www.marketnet.com/kosher
</P>
<P>
   /matzoh.html, you will find fascinating information (especially
if you're unfamiliar with it) on keeping a kosher home and dietary
preparations for the Passover observance.
</P>
<P>
   A very different kind of bread plays a central role in Easter
celebrations, especially among some Orthodox Christians. Easter
bread, a sweet yeast bread rich in eggs, butter and other
ingredients, is symbolic of Christ himself. It is sometimes baked
as a round loaf decorated with a lamb or braided cross. Sometimes
the entire loaf is braided into a circle, giving it a crown effect
. For instructions, see http://www-inst.eecs.berkeley
</P>
<P>
   .edu/(tilde)isk/netmagic.d/easter.html.
</P>
<P>
   Hot Cross Buns (see recipe) are another old Easter tradition,
usually served on Good Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Two excellent sites that you may want to visit to compare the
foods of Easter and Passover are http://www.fwfs.com/april.htm and
http://
</P>
<P>
   www.citipage.com/wjac/kitchen/hk6.html.
</P>
<P>
   You will learn, for instance, that horseradish in the Jewish
tradition signifies the bitterness of slavery and in the Christian
tradition, the passion of Christ. For Jews, salt at the Passover
table signifies tears shed during enslavement and for Christians,
fasting and self-denial and a reminder of Christ's words ``You are
the salt of the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   For Passover recipes, visit:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  http://www.eskimo.com/(tilde)jefffree/recipes/. This archive
contains nearly 8,000 Jewish recipes, including many for Passover.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  http://www.marketnet.com/mktnet/kosher
</P>
<P>
   /recipes/passover/index.html contains assorted Passover recipes
and links to more.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  http://baking.miningco.com/msubjew.htm. Primarily desserts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  http://www.marketnet.com/mktnet
</P>
<P>
   /kosher/recipes/passover/index.html. Some especially good
chicken recipes.
</P>
<P>
   For Easter foods, visit:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  http://www.orthodoxchurch.com/recipes
</P>
<P>
   .html, which features recipes for an Orthodox Christian dinner
feast.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  http://www.kitchenlink.com/cgi
</P>
<P>
   /publicframes?page &QC; /sf04961 takes you on an Easter recipe hunt.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  http://carpatho-rusyn.org/recipes.htm. Authentic and
traditional Russian Orthodox Easter recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Although Easter and Passover are based on the beliefs of people
of different faiths with different rituals and customs, by visiting
sites relating to both, you may also see how both are bound
together.
</P>
<P>
   Easter is about renewal. Passover marks a new beginning. Both
celebrate a hope common to us all.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   My Caramel Matzo Crunch
</P>
<P>
   Makes 15 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 18 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling/chilling time: 35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   If you are terrified of Passover baking, just make this. It's a
winner, and you do not need any special techniques or even a candy
thermometer to make it.
</P>
<P>
   4 to 6 unsalted matzo boards or sheets
</P>
<P>
   1 cup unsalted butter or unsalted Passover margarine
</P>
<P>
   1 cup firmly packed light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup chocolate chips or coarsely chopped semisweet chocolate
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Line completely with foil a large
18-by-12-inch cookie sheet with sides. Cover bottom of pan with
baking parchment _ on top of foil. This is very important as
mixture becomes sticky during baking. Line bottom of pan evenly
with matzo boards, cutting extra pieces of matzo as required to fit
any spaces on the cookie sheet as evenly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Combine margarine or butter and brown sugar in a 3-quart,
heavy-bottomed saucepan. Cook over medium heat, stirring
constantly, until mixture comes to a boil. Continue cooking 3 more
minutes, stirring constantly. Remove from heat and pour over matzo
and spread evenly with a metal spatula.
</P>
<P>
   Place in oven and immediately reduce heat to 350. Bake 15
minutes, checking every few minutes to make sure mixture is not
burning. If it seems to be browning too quickly, remove from oven,
lower heat to 325 and return to oven to cook.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from oven and sprinkle matzo boards immediately with
chocolate. Let stand 5 minutes, then spread melted chocolate over
matzo. While still warm, cut into squares or odd shapes using a
large knife. Chill in refrigerator until set, about 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This makes a good gift. You can also serve it in confectioners'
paper cups as a candy.
</P>
<P>
   Variation: You can also use coarsely chopped white chocolate, or
a combination of chocolates, and sprinkle toasted almonds on top as
the chocolate sets.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 202 calories, 1 gram protein, 13 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 57), 22 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 7
milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Mushroom Matzo Farfel Pie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 52 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 5 to 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon seasoned salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 cup hot water or vegetable bouillon
</P>
<P>
   16 ounces (1 box) matzo farfel (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup finely chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons broth for sauteing
</P>
<P>
   1 pound mushrooms, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 medium zucchini, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 ribs celery, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons potato starch beaten with 6 tablespoons water
(to replace 3 beaten egg whites)
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In a large bowl, stir together
seasoned salt and water. Stir in matzo farfel and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In Dutch oven over medium heat, saute onion in broth until soft,
about 4 minutes. Add mushrooms, zucchini and celery and saute until
mushrooms are wilted, about 3 minutes. Remove from heat and fold in
potato starch/water mixture. Stir this mixture into the reserved
matzo farfel mixture. Season to taste with freshly ground pepper.
Spread in a greased 10-by-10-by-2-inch casserole dish. Bake,
covered, for 30 minutes. Uncover and bake another 15 minutes, or
until the top is browned. Let stand for 5 to 10 minutes before
serving. Cut into wedges or spoon to serve. _ Natalie Frankel,
Milwaukee
</P>
<P>
   Note: Matzo farfel is coarse crumbs made of matzo flour; it can
be found in the Passover section at the supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 208 calories, 6 grams protein, trace fat (percent
calories from fat, less than 5 ), 44 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 118 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Hot Cross Buns
</P>
<P>
   Makes 30 buns
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Rising time: 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 12-17 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally served on Good Friday (the Friday before Easter)
and during Lent, Hot Cross Buns are good anytime.
</P>
<P>
   2 packages active dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup warm (110-115 degrees) water
</P>
<P>
   1 cup warm (110-115 degrees) milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup softened butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   6 1/2 to 7 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dried currants
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup raisins
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   1 egg yolk
</P>
<P>
   1 recipe icing (below)
</P>
<P>
   In large mixing bowl, dissolve yeast in warm water. Add warm
milk, sugar, butter, vanilla, salt, nutmeg and 3 cups flour. Beat
until smooth. Add eggs, one at a time, beating well after each
addition. Stir in currants and raisins and more flour (3 1/2 to 4
cups), enough to make a soft dough.
</P>
<P>
   Turn dough out on a floured surface and knead until smooth and
elastic, about 6 to 8 minutes. Pat into a ball and place in a large
greased bowl, turning over to grease top of dough. Cover with a
damp towel or plastic wrap and let rise in a warm place until
doubled in size (about 1 hour).
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Punch dough down and shape into 30
balls about the size of a large lemon. Place on greased baking
sheets. Using a sharp knife, cut a cross, or X, on the top of each
roll. Cover again and let rise until doubled (about 1 hour).
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, beat 2 tablespoons water and egg yolk together
and brush over the rolls. Bake for 12 to 17 minutes until nicely
browned. Cool on wire racks for 1 hour. Drizzle icing over the top
of each roll following the lines of the cut cross.
</P>
<P>
   For the icing: Combine 1 cup confectioners' sugar, 4 teaspoons
milk or cream, a dash of salt and 1/4 teaspoon vanilla extract.
Stir until smooth. Adjust sugar and milk to make a mixture that
flows easily.
</P>
<P>
   Tip: Put icing in a small plastic bag and snip off a corner to
drizzle neatly.
</P>
<P>
   Per roll: 164 calories, 4 grams protein, 3 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 18), 29 grams carbohydrates, 37 milligrams
cholesterol, 122 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
