<HEADER>
A3888 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-FOIL18-COX     03-17 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-FOIL18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't let lifestyle foil plans for complete meal: Aluminum
cookery's quick, and cleanup easy
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've had one of those
``better-get-a-million-things-done-before-the-new-millennium'' kind
of days.
</P>
<P>
   How you'd just love to settle down to a glass of wine and a nice
home-cooked dinner. But you're not up for any heavy-duty cooking.
And the prospect of scrubbing pots and pans afterward is simply too
much to bear.
</P>
<P>
   There is a silver lining here. And in all likelihood, it's
already in your cabinet _ right next to the wax paper and plastic
wrap.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, we're talking about aluminum foil. Tear off a sheet, plop a
thawed chicken breast or piece of fish on top, add veggies and
seasonings, then roll up into a packet. Bake it, serve it and _
here's the best part _ when you've finished dinner, simply crumple
and toss the foil in the trash.
</P>
<P>
   Sound like a cooking technique from a Girl Scouts handbook? It's
probably in there.
</P>
<P>
   But in case you think this method is for quick-but-not-great
food, check out a new cookbook, ``The Perfect Dinner,'' by longtime
San Francisco Chronicle columnist Jacqueline Mallorca ($22.95, Fair
Oaks Press).
</P>
<P>
   Mallorca points out that today's foil-packet cookery is the
natural descendant to the classic cuisine en papillote _ cooking in
parchment paper. And her book includes several recipes sure to meet
gourmet standards, such as bay scallops with roasted bell peppers
and tarragon chicken breast with mushroom sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the folks in the aluminum foil industry are eager to
help prove that point. And because you can customize each packet,
it's an ideal way to prepare that thawed chicken to satisfy the
``onions-are-awful'' kid, the ``mushrooms-are-gross'' teenager and
the ``no-salt-please'' spouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have such hectic lifestyles these days, they want to
get in and out of the kitchen,'' said Pat Schweitzer, a home
economist in the Reynolds Kitchens. She co-stars with fellow
economist Betty Thompson Morton in commercials for Reynolds Wrap.
``With foil packets, you can make individual meals quickly and
really cut down on the cleanup time.''
</P>
<P>
   Morton and Schweitzer have created a number of recipes, such as
the Cajun Sausage and Beans or Far East Spiced Chicken recipes
inside, that make the most of the foil-packet method. Many more can
be found at the Web site http://www.reynoldswrap.com.
</P>
<P>
   There, you'll also find directions for making foil packets,
though directions are hardly needed. In most cases, you don't
tightly wrap food, as you might a baked potato. Rather, you encase
the food in the foil, leaving an air pocket so steam can develop
but creating a tight seam so juices don't leak. Sometimes you add a
sauce or a few ice cubes to help create moisture and add flavor.
</P>
<P>
   The foil-packet method works especially well for boneless
chicken breasts, fish fillets, beef slices and pork chops. You can
combine them with vegetables that are compatible and cook the whole
meal in one stroke. It's best to cut vegetables into small pieces,
especially carrots and potatoes, so they will cook through.
</P>
<P>
   While the packet method works beautifully in the oven, it has
its drawbacks on the grill. Sure, cleanup will be easier. And the
delicate fish or small veggies won't slip through the grate. The
wrap, though, likely will limit the amount of smoky flavor that is
the advantage of grilling.
</P>
<P>
   But for those who've always had trouble cooking up tender, juicy
ribs outdoors, Schweitzer touts the foil-packet method. First, cook
the ribs in a foil packet for up to an hour, allowing the steaming
process to soften and cook the meat. Then unwrap the ribs and cook
them directly on the grill, brushing with sauce, to finish.
</P>
<P>
   We liked the method for using foil to make North Carolina-style
pork barbecue and offer that recipe inside _ along with others we
tried from Reynolds Wrap and from Mallorca's cookbook. All need no
more than a vegetable or salad and perhaps some bread to make a
complete meal.
</P>
<P>
   TIPS FOR COOKING WITH FOIL PACKETS
</P>
<P>
   There are many advantages to cooking with foil packets,
including saving time. Foil conducts heat to its contents without
delay, so many entrees cook in only 10 minutes. Here are some tips
to keep in mind:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Packets can be assembled and refrigerated for up to three
hours in advance. Bring them to room temperature before they go
into the oven, or add two minutes to the cooking time.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Always cook foil packets in one layer on one baking sheet
positioned on the center rack.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bake only as many packets at one time as you can reasonably
handle.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For most dishes, preheating the oven and baking sheet is
critical. (Allow 10 to 15 minutes for an oven to preheat.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Some experts claim that the shiny side of the foil will
deflect some oven heat while the dull side absorbs it. But others
detect no difference.
</P>
<P>
   Source: ``The Perfect Dinner: Fine Food Cooked With Foil,''
Jacqueline Mallorca ($22.95, Fair Oaks Press)
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
