<HEADER>
A3889 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP18-COX     03-17 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nothing dull about these delicious cakes for teatime
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Marietta Fields of Marietta (Ga.) must have been
thinking of Mother Dull's Tea Cakes when she asked our readers for
their help finding ``an old-fashioned tea cake like my grandmother
made for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Many sent Mrs. S.R. Dull's recipe from her often-reprinted book,
``Southern Cooking.'' A few others came in, too, but they didn't
sound quite right, because Fields remembered her grandmother using
buttermilk and soda.
</P>
<P>
   We tested the tea cakes in Mrs. Dull's original recipe _ with
their high-cholesterol combination of butter and lard _ from the
copy passed along by Betty Berrey of Duluth. The recipe makes a
delicious, not-too-sweet tea biscuit that can be sweetened to taste
with filling, frosting or a dusting of sparkling sugar.
</P>
<P>
   We don't know what we'll do with that leftover lard. But the
extra buttermilk probably will find its way into some of those soft
pretzels in this week's Low-Fat Cooking column.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Mother Dull's Tea Cakes
</P>
<P>
   Makes 54 large cookies
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup lard
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup butter
</P>
<P>
   2cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   3eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   About 5 cups all-purpose flour, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In a large mixing bowl, cream the
lard and butter. Gradually add sugar and mix well. Add beaten eggs
and stir in completely.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, sift 1 cup flour with the baking soda and
baking powder. Add to the sugar mixture and combine thoroughly. Add
the buttermilk and vanilla. Stir in enough additional flour to make
a soft dough, about 4 cups.
</P>
<P>
   Turn dough out onto a lightly floured board and knead until
smooth. Roll out 1/4 inch thick and cut with a cookie or biscuit
cutter. Place on ungreased cookie sheets, about 1 inch apart, and
bake 10-12 minutes until set and edges begin to color. (Using a 3
1/2-inch cutter, this makes 54 cookies.)
</P>
<P>
   Per cookie: 106 calories, 2 grams protein, 4 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 34), 16 grams carbohydrates, 18 milligrams
cholesterol, 56 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe request
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Susan W. Vaughn of Conyers is looking for a recipe for Hot
Water Corn Bread. After reading about it in a cookbook that
extolled the bread's unique texture, caused by the hot water, she
was disappointed to find that the book didn't contain the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
