<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3901 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-BRIBERY-0318-C     03-17 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-BRIBERY-0318-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POWERFUL LEADER OF ISRAEL'S ULTRA-RELIGIOUS JEWS CONVICTED OF
BRIBERY
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ After a four-year trial fraught with incendiary
ethnic overtones, an Israeli court Wednesday convicted of bribery
the political leader of the country's Sephardic ultra-orthodox
Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Arieh Deri, 40, rose quickly to top posts in the government of
slain Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin and would later lead his
fast-growing movement into its close alliance with current
right-wing Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   The Moroccan-born Deri helped found Shas, a party that
represents ultra-Orthodox, Sephardic Jews. The Sephardic Jews come
from Asian and North African countries. Despite numbering half of
Israel's Jewish population, they have long felt excluded from power
by the Ashkenazi Jews, of European descent.
</P>
<P>
   The panel of three judges found Deri guilty of taking $155,000
in bribes and illegally steering government money to Shas
organizations. He plans to appeal the conviction, but will be
sentenced March 25 and could face up to seven years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The conviction disqualifies him from top posts in government but
he could be allowed to remain in the Israeli parliament, the
Knesset.
</P>
<P>
   Shas holds 10 seats in the 120-seat parliament. As a key swing
vote in creating government coalitions, the party has been
successful at winning government money for Shas schools and welfare
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The Sephardic-Ashkenazi divide is a bitter cleft in Israeli
culture and the Deri trial, which was held periodically over the
years with frequent breaks, created a tension somewhat like that
around racially charged trials in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Judges reported that their lives had been threatened, and by the
time the verdict was announced live on the radio -- cameras were
not allowed in the courtroom -- police braced for violent street
demonstrations from Deri's followers.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the several hundred Shas supporters outside the
district court were peaceful and the scene itself illustrated the
rifts in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The courthouse happens to be located in an Arab section of
Jerusalem, so ultra-Orthodox Sephardic Jews in their black suits
and black fedoras or skullcaps, chanted and prayed in front of Arab
storefronts while little Arab schoolgirls looked on in
bewilderment.
</P>
<P>
   They were separated from the court by hundreds of Israeli
police, some wielding assault rifles. A small group of college-aged
secular protesters, including women with dyed pinkish hair and
skimpy tank tops, demonstrated nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that two of the three judges were themselves
Sephardic Jews, Shas members vouched for Deri's innocence and said
he was being taken down by a racist system that is scared of Shas
and the ultra-Orthodox.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very painful for us,'' said 21-year-old David Amal, a
religious student. ``He is the man who made the whole Sephardic
world and Jewish world rise up.''
</P>
<P>
   Shas supporters predicted that Deri's prosecution would draw
more voters to their party in the May 17 elections for parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Material from the Associated Press was used for this story.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
