</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 15:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3905 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSCARS-HNS &LR;      03-17 1611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING THE REAL OSCAR WINNERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The problem with handicapping the Oscars is that you run the
risk of sounding like Joan or Melissa Rivers. Just standing there
like a fool telling Jeremy Irons he was robbed for his performance
in ``The Silence of the Lambs.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if you're going to do that, there's no place better
than E! _ a letter that could easily stand for ``Eeew,'' especially
when it comes to Oscar coverage. But this year ``eeew'' is an
accurate reaction to some of this year's nominees.
</P>
<P>
   While it's one of the closest recent collections of races _ the
only guarantee is that it will take more than three hours for all
the horses to round the track _ most of the options just seem
staid, safe, conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Five period films about heroism and sacrifice? If there was ever
a year screaming to enact some sort of Oscar affirmative action
policy to shake things up in the best picture category, this would
have been it. (Preferential treatment? Tokenism? String-pulling?
Being bought? Very, very Oscar.)
</P>
<P>
   Of course, on some level, it doesn't really matter how pointedly
inoffensive things get. Who among us is mighty enough to blow off
the whole thing with a flippant ``like I care''? Even with my
anticipation at an all-time low, any show that has the sense of
irony to honor name-naming director Elia Kazan, ``Saving Private
Ryan'' and ``Life Is Beautiful'' in the same year that a black
woman with a Jewish surname is hosting, should be better than
watchable, and at least as interesting, as anything the
mother-and-daughter Rivers have to contribute on the way in.
</P>
<P>
   Kazan's being selected to receive a life achievement Oscar has
so incensed his detractors that they're urging audience members to
sit on their hands when the 89-year-old director _ who was an
informant for the anti-commie House Un-American Affairs Committee
in the 1950s _ takes the stage. Not a bad plan for next time the
Academy expects us to give them props for their craven choices. In
the meantime, here are my takes on what we have to work with this
year:
</P>
<P>
   BEST PICTURE: It's been nominated for so many awards, it seems
to have sucked the suspense out of this year's Oscars. But what
gets lost in all the fawning hype is the fact that ``Saving Private
Ryan'' leaves an indelible impression on the soul. If not the
greatest war film we've ever seen, it's simply the greatest one
we've ever felt. Steven Spielberg has delivered a shattering
you-are-there postcard caked with entrails and earth.
</P>
<P>
   Naysayers groan that the film is just two great battle sequences
with a sentimental soldiers' journey sandwiched in between. But the
film moves from one grueling nightmare to the next guided by an
ambivalent, but steadily unwinding heroism.
</P>
<P>
   So much of the terror the film evokes comes from showing
something we've rarely seen: a hell recently reserved on film for
Vietnam. This will be the closest thing to a unanimous decision
there could be.
</P>
<P>
   Should win: ``Saving Private Ryan''
</P>
<P>
   Will win: ``Saving Private Ryan''
</P>
<P>
   BEST DIRECTOR: Steven Spielberg's commercial instincts have
always been married to his aesthetics, often to a fault, but with
``Saving Private Ryan'' he solidified his status as the most
impassioned commercially viable visionary we have. The fleet of
unshakeable images he crafts, from that armless soldier staggering
in and out of the camera frame to Jeremy Davies' paralyzed corporal
swathed in a belt of bullets weeping on the stairs, redefine the
face of visceral wartime suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Should win: Steven Spielberg
</P>
<P>
   Will win: Steven Spielberg
</P>
<P>
   BEST ACTOR: In the year's tightest race, only Edward Norton's
reformed skinhead seems misplaced, through no fault of his own.
</P>
<P>
   His character's transition from blistering to beatified was
cheated by how poorly structured ``American History X'' was.
</P>
<P>
   What this category comes down to is Tom Hanks' mesmerizing
subtlety, Ian McKellen's ability to de-camp James Whale without
sacrificing both his misery and his libido, and Nick Nolte
uncorking fury like he was playing Bruce Banner. Nolte's best at
playing grizzly bears with eruptive tendencies _ what he does here
is the method equivalent of Chernobyl.
</P>
<P>
   Should win: Nick Nolte
</P>
<P>
   Will win: Nick Nolte
</P>
<P>
   BEST ACTRESS: As the concocted muse of a smitten Will
Shakespeare, Gwyneth Paltrow is a frustrated fairy tale of the
stunning, starry variety the Academy stopped handing Oscars to back
when Julie Christie made black-and-white seem Technicolor in 1965's
``Darling.''
</P>
<P>
   Paltrow throws light all over ``Shakespeare in Love'' like she
didn't know the solar system already had a center. Still: This may
be too frivolous a part for an Oscar nod _ why notice her crocodile
tears and pretend British accent when voters can give the Oscar to
Aussie Cate Blanchett for her two beautiful scenes in a movie where
she otherwise sits there while various backstabbing men tell her
what to do?
</P>
<P>
   But Fernanda Montenegro has the worn look of a former clown too
depressed to even paint her lips, too cynical to smile straight; by
the end of ``Central Station,'' she's earned your heartbreak as the
joy creeps back into her sullen face. It's the performance of the
five that's more human than human should be.
</P>
<P>
   Should win: Fernanda Montenegro
</P>
<P>
   Will win: Cate Blanchett
</P>
<P>
   SUPPORTING ACTOR: Let me see if I get this: If I'm Robert
Duvall, I can get robbed _ lose for my ``Apostle'' performance _
and still show up for a couple weeks to glower at John Travolta,
and I might get another Oscar nomination? And if I'm Ed Harris, all
I have to do to likely win an Oscar is wear a beret and sit at a
console for my entire performance?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. Ferocity found a first name in James Coburn's bad, bad
dad. And what Billy Bob Thornton does as a wiser-than-he-looks half
of a pair of scheming brothers in ``A Simple Plan'' is so fine and
seemingly effortless you're reluctant to reduce what he's done so
affectingly by calling it acting.
</P>
<P>
   Should win: Billy Bob Thornton
</P>
<P>
   Will win: Ed Harris
</P>
<P>
   SUPPORTING ACTRESS: Judi Dench all but gave an acting class in
``Shakespeare in Love,'' still it's a glorified (glorious) cameo.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Griffiths has the task of getting sucked into the vortex
of Emily Watson's Jacqueline du Pres; she looks worn out the way a
woman dealing with a volatile, mentally ill genius who wants to
sleep with her husband would be.
</P>
<P>
   But amid the menagerie of phoniness and fakery Mike Nichols
assembled in ``Primary Colors,'' Kathy Bates emerges as the one
true thing. Her bulldozing but vulnerable campaign dustbuster is
one for our times: A woman so disgusted with the immoral state of
the world she has to leave it.
</P>
<P>
   Should win: Kathy Bates
</P>
<P>
   Will win: Kathy Bates
</P>
<P>
   ORIGINAL SCREENPLAY: While Marc Norman and Tom Stoppard's
elaborately cheeky script for ``Shakespeare in Love'' was not the
year's best _ that would be Todd Solondz's ``Happiness'' or Wes
Anderson and Owen Wilson's ``Rushmore'' _ it was the most inspired,
fusing Elizabethan English with anachronistic foolishness. Norman
and Stoppard did something not even Cliff's Notes could: make
accessible fun out of watered-down Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   Should win: Marc Norman, Tom Stoppard, ``Shakespeare in Love''
</P>
<P>
   Will win: ``Shakespeare in Love''
</P>
<P>
   ADAPTED SCREENPLAY: As fluidly and cinematically as Elmore
Leonard's pulp characters speak to one another, his narratives
always seem overweight. In his screenplay for ``Out of Sight,''
Scott Frank cuts away some of the fat from one of Leonard's more
conventional heist books, leaving this taut, intelligent romance
between a lady cop and the robber who kind of wants her to catch
him. But the Academy will take the opportunity to honor Terrence
Malick for making James Jones' difficult tome into a difficult tone
poem of a movie _ more a feat of bravura filmmaking than inventive
screenwriting.
</P>
<P>
   Should win: Scott Frank, ``Out of Sight''
</P>
<P>
   Will win: Terrence Malick, ``The Thin Red Line''
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN FILM
</P>
<P>
   Should Win: ``Central Station''
</P>
<P>
   Will Win: ``Life Is Beautiful''
</P>
<P>
   DOCUMENTARY
</P>
