<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT WE TRULY NEED IS A RIGHT TO AN EXIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once upon a time, when commercial air travel was an outrageously
expensive luxury and a delightful relief from the drudgery of
driving, people who avoided airplanes most often were folks who
couldn't afford the price of a ticket and those who suffered from a
fear of flying.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, just about everyone can afford some sort of airfare,
and safety statistics suggest that a jetliner is far less hazardous
to life and limb than an automobile.
</P>
<P>
   There are people who want no part of air travel, however, and
the reason is not that they are afraid of flying. The reason is
that they are afraid of ``not flying.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's travelers fear being forced to camp out in airport
terminals because flights are delayed or canceled because of
problems ranging from bad weather to labor disputes. Today's
travelers fear being imprisoned for hours on planes that either
can't take off or can't land because of overcrowded runways and/or
lousy planning by airports and airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Today's air travelers fear being abused, ignored, insulted and
patronized by an air travel industry that all too often seems to
care nothing for its customers once they have forked over their
hard-earned bucks for a ticket that may or may not guarantee that
they will reach their intended destination at the intended time.
</P>
<P>
   The collective patience of airline passengers finally neared the
breaking point in January when a horrendous snowstorm in Detroit
prompted Northwest Airlines to treat customers as hostages,
confining passengers for hours on end aboard grounded airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   The result? You guessed it: The politicians saw a parade forming
and immediately sprinted to the front in hopes of creating the
illusion that they are leading it.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress and the Clinton administration, in fact, are
tripping over one another as they rush to unveil assorted versions
of a ``bill of rights'' for air passengers. There's a bill in the
Senate and a bill in the House, and Vice President Al
``Program-a-Day'' Gore announced a third initiative designed ``to
ensure that airline consumers are treated fairly before, during and
after a flight.''
</P>
<P>
   The various proposals may differ in the specific details, but
the main thrust of each is to provide air travelers with more
information. If the airline honchos decide to strand you on a
runway for nine hours, in other words, they would be required to
tell you why. If they decide to dump you off to another airline for
part of your trip, they would be required to warn you ahead of
time.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah, and if they bump you from a scheduled flight or lose
your luggage, they would have to pay you more for your trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing wrong with any of that. The more information a traveler
can get, the better. And money is good.
</P>
<P>
   But there's one gigantic hole in all these proposals: None of
them would prohibit an airline from holding you on a plane against
your will.
</P>
<P>
   None of the proposals would give a passenger the right to rise
from his seat after being trapped for hours and say: ``I want off
this %!! airplane, and I want off now!''
</P>
<P>
   Well, actually, you probably have the right to say that even
now. You just don't have the right to enforce it _ and you wouldn't
have the right to enforce it under any of the passenger ``bill of
rights'' plans on the table.
</P>
<P>
   According to a spokesman for the House Transportation and
Infrastructure Committee _ where one of the plans is working its
way through the legislative obstacle course _ it is possible that
the right to deplane could be added at some point. The legislation
is ``a work in progress,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines have their reasons for imprisoning passengers on
stranded planes _ safety is a factor, a spokesman for Gore
suggested _ but any problem can be solved with sufficient effort.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers need more information. Rescuing lost luggage is
important.
</P>
<P>
   But if the politicians truly care about passenger rights, they
should figure out a way to rescue travelers from parked airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
