<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3950 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREENSPAN-HNS &LR;      03-17 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN WOWS BANKERS, AND RIGHTLY SO 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Cult of Greenspan descended on San
Francisco. Attired in suits and golf slacks, the Fedheads and
groupies _ thousands of bankers in town for a conference _ filled
Moscone Center for a fleeting glimpse of The Man.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a lot to get a rise from bankers. Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan did it Tuesday with a shy grin and a
half-hour of dull speech.
</P>
<P>
   If power is a turn-on, Greenspan is a sex god. If economics is a
dismal science, he's the Chief Dismal Scientist. Time magazine
wrote he has ``shaman-like power over the global economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Others call him the second mightiest man on the planet (next to
the president). I don't doubt it for a second. I saw his charm,
felt his allure. I stood next to misty-eyed bankers at a banking
conference Tuesday at the Moscone Center in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Balding and bespectacled at 73, the soft-spoken Greenspan
commands the room like a televangelist.
</P>
<P>
   Before his talk, a military color guard and rousing marching
music revved up the bankers. A mass prayer got them into a beatific
mood. Praised as a man of ``undisputed greatness'' who has led us
to ``the promised land of economic growth,'' Greenspan strode to
the dais and a long standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   After droning about the farm economy, Greenspan scampered from
the hall, tailed by autograph hounds. One waved a pen and paper,
hoping to snag the Omnipotent One.
</P>
<P>
   The fan was Stanley Carlson, head of the Washington Federal
Savings Bank in Washington, Iowa. He said he and his colleagues
crowded around the television when Greenspan spoke, devouring each
word, each grin or grimace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man is a master of the economy,'' gushed Carlson. ``We
won't truly understand how great he was until 20 years from now,
when historians look back at his record.''
</P>
<P>
   Why does Greenspan have such star power?
</P>
<P>
   Probably because he's steered the nation through a golden
economic era. Corporate profits and stocks have hit all-time highs.
The economy still is growing. Inflation has been whipped, and
unemployment is at a 28-year low. He's the right man for the right
time.
</P>
<P>
   A child of the Depression, Greenspan is a monetary wizard. He
cuts interest rates here, raises them there. He pumps cash into the
economy, or siphons the cash back. His goal: a stable economy. His
fine-tuned balancing act keeps everyone _ politicians, financiers,
investors, consumers _ happy and healthy.
</P>
<P>
   He's also the ultimate political animal. Over the decades, he's
thrived as an economic adviser and Fed chair under five presidents:
Nixon, Ford, Reagan, Bush and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In social settings, Greenspan loosens up a bit. He hops from
soiree to soiree in Washington with his wife, NBC broadcaster
Andrea Mitchell. A lover of jazz and classical music, he played sax
in a swing band during his youth.
</P>
<P>
   But on fiscal matters, he's super-cautious, a Yoda of
meaningless verbiage. Money experts have gone mad trying to decode
his nebulous remarks. He's a poker-faced cipher, revealing nothing
that might shake the markets.
</P>
<P>
   In a private meeting Tuesday with bankers, he dodged queries
about the Dow's flirting with 10,000. ``Do you want to comment?''
he was asked. ``No,'' was all he said.
</P>
<P>
   He should lighten up a bit. What's going on behind those
horn-rimmed glasses, that sheepish smile?
</P>
<P>
   Before Greenspan steps down, he should do something wild. Bash
some bankers. Slam the stock market. Raise interest rates and wreak
global havoc. Remember the famous John Maynard Keynes adage: ``In
the long run, we are all dead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
