<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3995 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-FINGERPRINTS-NYT &LR;      03-17 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-FINGERPRINTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIGNING ON WITH YOUR FINGERPRINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER WAYNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While people continue to repeat the New Yorker cartoon tag line
that no one knows you're a dog on the Internet, the computer
industry is working diligently to sort out the sheep from the
goats.
</P>
<P>
   Anonymity may offer a bit of excitement to chat rooms and keep
us safe from stalkers we meet on line, but careful industries like
banks and investment houses continue to look for better technology
for identifying people. Some of the latest solutions on the horizon
are devices for reading people's fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   A number of companies are making relatively inexpensive gadgets
that can capture an image of a fingerprint so that it can be
compared against a database. They are not in widespread use yet,
but biometrics, the term for using bodily features as
identification, is a field that is prompting a lot of interest and
a number of companies have hopes that the fingerprint scanners will
take off.
</P>
<P>
   American Biometric, a Canadian-based concern, offers a device
called a BioMouse for about $250 that reads fingerprints into a PC
and compares them with a database. Sony is also shipping similar
devices and the California based company I/O Software is selling
them packaged with its SecureSuite software at a price of around
$350.
</P>
<P>
   While these might be a bit too expensive to make it into every
PC, they're priced low enough for some business applications. Among
the places fingerprint scanners might be used are bank teller
windows or time clocks.
</P>
<P>
   Each of these devices takes an image of a fingerprint and
converts it into a relatively small file known as a template. This
records the locations of the unique parts of each fingerprint:
whorls, arches, ridges, valleys and loops. Fingerprints can be
compared and matched by looking at these locations.
</P>
<P>
   But keeping fingerprints on file worries privacy advocates,
because such information can be susceptible to abuse. While bank
customers may use different passwords on different accounts, for
example, their fingerprints remain the same. An unscrupulous
programmer at a bank could easily use data records to impersonate a
client.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fingerprint identification raises the difficult tension
between security and privacy,'' said Marc Rotenberg of the
Electronic Privacy Information Center. ``Security gives more
authentication and that's good because it means that the person
using an ATM is who they say they are. But on the privacy side we
create the risk of a new global identifier.''
</P>
<P>
   Both American Biometric's device and the package produced by
Sony and I/O Software come with a touch-sensitive screen that
reacts to a finger. The amount of pressure makes a big difference
in producing a machine-recognizable image, and it took me several
tries before I was able to do so consistently.
</P>
<P>
   It is also important to place the finger in the same position
each time an image is taken, because small shifts can make a big
difference in which features appear. If the machine can't find the
right whorls and loops, it won't recognize you.
</P>
<P>
   Both packages also come with some software that adds security to
a computer. I/O Software's SecureSuite package includes a tool that
lets the user log into a computer by checking the fingerprint.
While it took several tries to successfully program the system with
my fingerprint, it worked fairly well afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   The true effectiveness of these devices is hard to judge.
Stealing passwords is relatively easy to do, hard to defend
against, and difficult to detect when the password is taken.
Fingerprints, on the other hand, can't be stolen by looking over
someone's shoulder, but they can be found on water glasses and
other smooth-surfaced objects.
</P>
<P>
   Both products try to screen out forgeries. Both have
touch-sensitive screens that can detect dry-paper pictures of
fingerprints. Neither would accept a laser-printed version of my
right thumb print, even after I added some moisture to activate the
touch-sensitive screens.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Borza, a vice-president of American Biometric, says that
the only consistently successful way to fool the reader that has
been demonstrated in the company's labs has been by using a plaster
cast of a finger. Most latent finger prints left in everyday use,
he says, are smudged by tiny rotations of the moving fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers who try to use a copy of a fingerprint picked up
from a wine glass, a car door or a fingerprint file run into
trouble. Even printcards taken at police stations are often
distorted.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also selling a product known as the BioMouse Plus
which comes with a built-in reader for smartcards, identification
card often used for security. Borza says, ``You essentially need
the smartcard and the finger. It's a two-factor authentication.
Just having a `severed digit' isn't going to get you in.''
</P>
<P>
   He may have been referring to a favorite, apparently apocryphal,
story among security people about the mugger, who, faced with an
ATM that used fingerprint-identification security technology,
simply chopped off his victim's finger.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Schneier, the president of the computer security firm,
Counterpane, says, ``Biometrics are secure if you have an armed
guard watching the biometric reader; otherwise it can be fooled.''
For example, they may work at a bank teller's window, but couldn't
be trusted if installed on a home PC.
</P>
<P>
   He points out that all biometric devices are susceptible to a
``replay attack'' if an intruder is able to make a copy of the
description of the legitimate user's body part.
</P>
<P>
   This description is not supposed to change over time, so the
intruder may be able to get the system to replay it. This would
require some access to the software or the network connection,
however, making home PCs much more vulnerable than installations at
banks.
</P>
<P>
   Borza argues that endless cycles of counter-engineering and
counter-counter-engineering for security purposes have diminishing
returns. Citing the classic Mad magazine comic strip, he says, ``At
some level it becomes `Spy vs. Spy' and it's hard to justify it.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
