<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3996 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PASTRIES-JACQUESTORRE     03-17 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PASTRIES-JACQUESTORRES-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
DALLAS: step right up. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We met on the patio of Ziziki at lunch time. Torres, much to the
confusion of the waitress, asked for a pastis, or a Ricard.
</P>
<P>
   We ordered salads, and I leaned back in the wrought-iron chair,
waiting for a sort of silliness that never came.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Torres said he was tense, and that he's always tense
before a class, or before he tapes his show.
</P>
<P>
   Torres talked about his apprenticeship at 15 in a bakery in his
hometown of Bandol, and how on a bet, at about age 20, he walked
into the exclusive Hotel Negresco in Nice one day and somehow found
his way into the office of the world-famous chef, Jacques Maximin,
whom he asked for a job.
</P>
<P>
   He got it. And stayed for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone after that said, `How did you get in?' '' Torres
said. ``They have a waiting list. You have to write letters. You
have to have recommendations. It's impossible to get in. It was
pure luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Torres told me how he won, at 26, his country's prestigious
Meilleur Ouvrier competition, becoming the youngest pastry chef to
receive the honor. (''I didn't even invite my parents to the
ceremony. I didn't think I would win.'') In 1988, he became
corporate pastry chef of the Ritz Carlton Hotel Co. and then in
1989, accepted owner Sirio Maccioni's offer and became the pastry
chef at Le Cirque restaurant. In 1996, Le Cirque closed, reopening
the next year as Le Cirque 2000 in the New York Palace Hotel with a
million-dollar pastry kitchen built to Torres' specifications.
</P>
<P>
   It's in that kitchen that Torres still works, six days _ and
nights _ a week, he said, serving about 800 people every 24 hours.
He and his assistants also make about 100 12-piece boxes of
chocolates daily for the special guests of the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Torres also teaches once a week at the French Culinary
Institute, where he is dean of pastry arts; tapes his PBS show in
the fall; writes the cookbooks to accompany the show; and travels
throughout the year to promote both of the latter. He's in a
different city about once every other week, never spending the
night, because he has to be back in the kitchen the next day to
stand and stand, and create.
</P>
<P>
   I was tired just thinking about a life of such intensity, but
Torres was ready to roll.
</P>
<P>
   We hurried across the street to Sur La Table, where Torres
greeted a roomful of professional chefs ready to watch his
demonstrations on chocolate and sugar. For 2 1/2 hours, Torres
molded chocolate into curves and boxes, and poured the hot liquid
on unlikely surfaces _ bubble wrap, a fly swatter _ to create
texture.
</P>
<P>
   In a pot, he combined white vinegar, water and sugar, and boiled
it. He picked up the resulting mixture and began pulling it,
stretching it, folding it back on itself and pulling again,
creating an increasingly shiny matter that he then separated into
sections, coloring them red, blue and green. The crowd grew silent
as Torres put on his sugar show, transforming the blobs into a
colorful clown statue, a graceful flower blossom and a billowing,
striped ribbon sculpted into a 10-inch bow. While he worked, he
joked, telling stories like the one about a client who requested a
special sugar sculpture. ``The lady had her, how you say,
`poitrine' enlarged'' and wanted an anatomical sugar model to
celebrate the breast augmentation.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd burst into laughter, and in the spotlight, as the
class concluded, Torres was laughing, enjoying the moment in full.
</P>
<P>
   But the show was far from over. In less than half an hour,
Torres would be doing it all over again for another eager group,
beginning with a ladyfinger cake this time. He'd be at Sur La Table
for four more hours, minimum, and when he was done, he would pack
up and take his personal big top back to New York for another long
day of performances in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   And Torres, the ringmaster, had it all under control.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
