<SLUG> BC-PASTRIES-JACQUESTORRES-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LE CIRQUE 2000 PASTRY MASTER JACQUES TORRES IS WHIRLWIND OF
ACTIVITY
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by PASTRIES-RECIPES) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CATHERINE NEWTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The demonstration room at Sur La Table, the West
Coast-based, stock-your-chic-kitchen shop that recently spread its
gastronomic roots to Dallas, is packed. And loud.
</P>
<P>
   The audience eagerly clutches spoons and forks in anticipation
of the sweet treats ahead. Green-aproned employees drag in
additional chairs for the spillover crowd, many clutching Jacques
Torres' new cookbook, ``Dessert Circus at Home'' (William Morrow,
$28). At the front of the room, Torres, executive pastry chef at
New York's Le Cirque 2000 restaurant, is carefully matching a list
of supplies _ strawberries, grated chocolate, cake ring, piles and
piles of sugar _ with what he finds on the marble counter beside a
sugar-sculpted clown and a foot-high, glossy chocolate sculpture.
Behind Torres, four white-jacketed assistants scurry about,
prepping, prepping, prepping.
</P>
<P>
   The clock hits 6 and the show begins, with Torres launching into
his first creation _ a strawberry ladyfinger cake _ and delivering
the sort of animated play-by-play that he developed for his PBS
cooking show, now in its second season. Torres begins generously
pouring Stoli Strasberi vodka into the mixture, which prompts
chuckling from the crowd _ and a story from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did one show for PBS,'' he says, interrupting his frenetic
activity. ``Jacques Pepin (fellow PBS chef and friend) was in it.
We drank that stuff during the show. They removed the show from
television.'' He breaks into a so-you-caught-me grin. ``It was too
crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Crazy'' is a word often linked with the Provence native, who
tends to launch Silly String and egg attacks on the dessert
devotees who come to watch him perform. (Most of the time, the eggs
are fake; it was only that one show, really, he swears, where he
made the mistake.)
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was fate that a decade ago brought Torres the
chef-cum-entertainer to the four-star Manhattan restaurant with the
name that means, in English, ``The Circus.'' Creating
fanciful-verging-on-magical signature desserts, such as the clown
hat and the chocolate moose, Torres has often said that he's
``toujours'' the clown of the place.
</P>
<P>
   But the thing is, I don't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   This spring-kissed day in Dallas that Torres says reminds him of
the Riviera (''except it's so flat here, what do you do?'') is the
first time I've met Torres.
</P>
<P>
   And somehow, meeting him almost seemed redundant.
</P>
<P>
   My first taste of Torres came about five years ago, at my
parents' house one Christmas, in the form of an embarrassing
abundance of chocolates made by my brother-in-law, John.
</P>
<P>
   A shy and serious fellow who spends his days managing people's
investments, John shocked us when he unveiled the delights, dubbed
them his Small Presentations and then proceeded to carry on about
some chocolate-making class he'd been taking on Saturdays from a
gastronomic guru at New York's French Culinary Institute. In truth,
I didn't listen for the details. I just ate.
</P>
<P>
   Rice Krispies coated in white chocolate and milk chocolate.
Caramelized almonds coated with chocolate and rolled in cocoa.
Truffles.
</P>
<P>
   The Small Presentations made their way to the table each year,
but did not associate themselves, at least in my mind, with the
Torres name until 1997. That year, as a gift, John and my sister
Laura gave me a signed copy of Torres' cookbook, ``Dessert
Circus,'' which thanked them in the credits, Laura explained,
because they had attended every single taping of the 26-episode
first season of Torres' PBS show.
</P>
<P>
   They seemed a little out of control, I thought. And then it got
worse.
</P>
<P>
   The Torres circus train swept Laura and John along on its
fast-moving ride. John took a week off from his job in 1997 simply
to spend time with Torres in the kitchen at Le Cirque 2000, where
he could watch the master at work. Arriving at 7 or 8 a.m. and
finishing up about 9 each night, he found the work ``punishing
physically'' and requiring ``severe foot care.'' Still, he went
back for another week in the summer of '98 to learn more about
Torres' theories and the chemistry of gourmet desserts. When John
and Laura moved to California, they flew back to New York to catch
some tapings for the second season of Torres' show. At Christmas, I
got another signed cookbook, and felt the rumble of the train.
</P>
<P>
   In February, my sister spent two hours one night telling me
about the souffle Torres had invented that does not fall and about
his miniature chocolate stoves that cover pieces of hazelnut cake
and that have little tiny chocolate pots bearing fruit sauces to be
poured over the cake before consumption.
</P>
<P>
   I had to know what was making my family members so, well, crazy.
</P>
<P>
   So when I heard the Torres circus was coming to town, I had to
step right up.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
