r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIGNSFROMGOD-TEX     03-17 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIGNSFROMGOD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AD CAMPAIGN EMPHASIZING GOD KICKS OFF IN DALLAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARY DOCLAR 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ It's not exactly a bolt of lightning or a burning bush.
</P>
<P>
   But if the new ``God speaking'' billboard campaign can at least
get people thinking about the Almighty instead of topless joints or
cold brews, then its supporters will consider it a success.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take a look at what's happening in our society today,
it's not a pretty sight,'' said Andy Smith, president of the Fort
Lauderdale-based advertising agency that developed the campaign
last year at the request of an anonymous client. ``It's time to get
people to start thinking about God and the rules God set forth.''
</P>
<P>
   The nationwide program is being kicked off in Dallas with more
than 120 billboards and will eventually spread to 10,000 locations
in 200 U.S. markets. The program features stark black billboards
with white-lettered messages signed simply by ``God.''
</P>
<P>
   One billboard appears to chastise motorists: ``Keep using my
name in vain. I'll make rush hour longer.'' Another entreats
married couples: ``Loved the wedding, invite me to the marriage.''
A third message urges: ``Follow me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. William Carl III, pastor of First Presbyterian Church
of Dallas, said he liked the billboards so much that he decided to
mention them in a sermon several weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're more teasers than they are the real big
message,'' said Carl, whose church has about 1,700 members.
``They're teasers to get you into the church or synagogue or
whatever. Then you get the deeper message.''
</P>
<P>
   But a Southern Methodist University professor who specializes in
modern religion and culture doubts whether the 18 nondenominational
messages will make much of an impression on cynical Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a society where everything is sold by clever
advertising, so it's not surprising that religion would try its
hand at this,'' said Lonnie Kliever, chairman of the religious
studies department at SMU. ``But to think that this is somehow
going to spark a kind of national revival of God consciousness or
return to the church, I think that's pretty naive, theologically.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Dallas Outdoor Advertising Association, which
is donating $100,000 in billboard space for the 1999 campaign,
believes that the program can make a difference. The organization
was so enthusiastic that the Outdoor Advertising Association of
America decided to start the public-service campaign in Dallas,
Nancy Fletcher, president of the Outdoor Advertising Association of
America, said during a news conference Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign was developed in Florida last year at the request
of an anonymous Floridian who Smith said wanted to prompt people to
start thinking about God. Publicity about that initial effort
caught the attention of the national advertising group.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher described the billboard messages, which involve the
donation of $15 million in billboard space nationally, as ``a
modern interpretation of the Ten Commandments.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the campaign as an inspiration to get someone to be
thinking about their own spirituality,'' she said of the
billboards, which are also up in Fort Worth and Arlington and will
spread to more area locations this summer.
</P>
<P>
   For those who think it's a bit presumptuous for an advertising
agency to think it can speak for God, Smith said that most
Americans will accept the spirit in which the messages are offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel it was done in such a clever, reverent, humorous way
that people will understand the meaning behind them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
