r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX     03-17 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYTHING'S COMING UP CUCUMBERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We're all about cucumbers this week.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Baxter e-mails looking for a cucumber salad dressing. And
right after that, another e-mail arrives, from Brenda McPhail, who
is looking for a recipe for cucumber sandwiches, the very proper
British tea goody. Here are those recipes, plus one for cucumber
soup as a bonus. It's a little nippy for the soup right now, but it
will be most welcome when July hits.
</P>
<P>
   CUCUMBER-DILL DRESSING
</P>
<P>
   Yields 1/2 cup
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped cucumber (cucumber should be peeled and seeded,
or just peeled if an English cucumber is used, see Note)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons low-fat plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   Dash white pepper, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh dill (or 1/2 teaspoon dried dill weed)
</P>
<P>
   Note: English cucumbers (they're the long, cellophane-wrapped
cucumbers in the produce section) have thinner skins and fewer
seeds than standard cucumbers.
</P>
<P>
   Place all ingredients, except dill, in a blender. Puree until
smooth. Stir in dill. Taste; adjust seasonings. Chill. Stir before
serving.
</P>
<P>
   If using dried dill, allow dressing to stand for 15-30 minutes
before serving. With either form of dill, it's good to chill the
dressing before serving. This dressing will keep for up to 2 days
in a tightly closed container in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis for 2 tablespoons: 7 calories, trace fat, 1
gram carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, trace cholesterol, 6 milligrams
sodium, 4 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Complete Book of Dressings'' by Paulette Mitchell
(Macmillan, $12)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CUCUMBER SANDWICHES
</P>
<P>
   1 English cucumber, peeled and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   White wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Day-old brown or white bread, thinly sliced, see Note
</P>
<P>
   Butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   Parsley sprigs
</P>
<P>
   Note: Pepperidge Farm's ``thin sliced'' is good for these
sandwiches because it's a denser-than-normal bread.
</P>
<P>
   Lay cucumber slices on plate and sprinkle with vinegar. Cover
and set aside for 30 minutes. Then drain in a sieve or colander to
remove excess liquid. Butter slices of bread. Cover a slice of
bread with slices of drained cucumber, top with another slice of
bread and press firmly together. Cut off crust and cut each
sandwich into triangles or fingers. Arrange on serving plate and
garnish with sprigs of parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per sandwich: 161 calories, 7 grams fat, 21
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 16 milligrams cholesterol,
215 milligrams sodium, 39 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A Proper Tea'' by Joanna Isles (St. Martin's, $13.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CUCUMBER YOGURT SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   4 medium to large cucumbers, peeled and seeded
</P>
<P>
   Sprigs of fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   2 cups plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped fresh dill
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 scallions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Reserve a few cucumber slices and whole mint leaves for garnish.
Chop remaining cucumbers in large pieces, then puree with the
remaining mint and all other ingredients in blender or food
processor. Chill for several hours. Serve cold, garnished with
reserved mint leaves and cucumber slices.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 136 calories, 5 grams fat, 16
grams carbohydrates, 7 grams protein, 21 milligrams cholesterol, 80
milligrams sodium, 36 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Stonyfield Farm Yogurt Cookbook'' by Meg Hirshberg
(Camden House, $17.95)
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
