<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-HASBRO-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY'VE GOT MAIL, AND GAME; CHESS FANS MAKE THEIR MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ore.)   (af)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While slick online games like Baldur's Gate and Half-Life are
attracting plenty of players with their intense action and glorious
graphics, there is another group of gamers on the Internet that is
just as passionate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chess game anyone? If you would like to play, I am white and
my first move is 1. e4,'' reads a posting in one of the Usenet
chess newsgroups. In fact, Usenet, the worldwide bulletin board
system, has a forum called rec.games.chess.play-by-email that is
devoted to long-distance competitions. No longer do players have to
rely on the post office and mailing lists to take on faraway
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a serious chess player, but I play a decent game if
I'm not rushed,'' Chris Cooper of Silverton, Ore., said via e-mail.
``e-mail seemed to be the way to go. Spending 20 to 33 cents a
postcard or letter per chess move does not make any sense to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Working on one's endgame by e-mail is nothing new. But now
chess-heads can get a bit more graphic than sending a message that
reads ``1. Ng1-f3.'' With Hasbro Interactive's Grand Master Chess
program, (which also includes checkers and backgammon), a player
can send, via e-mail, an animated color chessboard to an opponent
that displays that kingside knight making his first move.
</P>
<P>
   The game is part of Hasbro's e-mail Games series of CD-ROMs,
which also include two other board-game staples, Battleship and
Scrabble. The company plans to release more games in the series
this spring, including football, golf and poker.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Battleship comes with explosive noises and digitized
fireballs that appear on the game-board grid when you score a hit
on the enemy fleet. Scrabble's distinctive letter tiles move just
as easily on screen, and having them in digital form relieves the
secret fear (especially for parents) of losing all the vowels under
the couch over the years.
</P>
<P>
   To participate in the games, a player needs to be running
Windows 95 or 98, have Internet access and run an e-mail program
that allows the sending and receiving of file attachments. Only the
player initiating the game needs to have the CD-ROM.
</P>
<P>
   Player 1 starts a game and sends the first move to Player 2. The
e-mail is routed through Hasbro's game server, and it takes about
five minutes for each move to go from Player 1 to Player 2. Player
2 gets the e-mail message and clicks on the attachment to download
and install the game. Then Player 2 can make a move, write a
message and send the game back to Player 1.
</P>
<P>
   Each title in Hasbro Interactive's e-mail Games series costs
$14.95, and all are available for purchase on line at
www.emailgames.com or in retail stores. People who want to try
before they buy can download a free 10-move game demo from the Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say it is pretty good,'' Cooper said of Hasbro's chess
game. ``I like not having to read chess notation. Now I have a
reason to look forward to my e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail games seem to be gaining popularity. Although the
games have been out for only a few months, there is already a fan
Web page devoted to them: Bill &AMP; John's e-mail Games Player's
Directory at pages.prodigy.net/n2netsurfn/pbem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
