<HEADER>
A4011 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-COOKING-3TAKES-NY     03-17 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COOKING-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT OF THE FRYING PAN AND INTO THE DESKTOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm not a Luddite, really. I enjoy using computers, and even own
two of them. But when it comes to CD-ROM cookbooks, I still need
persuading.
</P>
<P>
   You will understand my bias if you consider this: suppose you
have carried home your new $30 hardcover copy of ``Joy of
Cooking,'' and you have opened it to the recipe for Brunswick stew,
an old Southern recipe that I have actually used several times.
</P>
<P>
   You have begun to prepare the dish and _ oops _ you've spilled a
spoonful of bacon fat on the pages. Well, these things happen.
Unstained cookbooks are unused cookbooks. From now on, the recipe
for Brunswick stew will be easy to find: the page is indelibly
marked.
</P>
<P>
   Now imagine instead that you have carried home your new $20 Joy
of Cooking CD-ROM. You switch on the computer, wait for it to boot
up, install the program and use the Find function to call up the
recipe for Brunswick stew. You begin to prepare the dish and _ oops
_ there goes that bacon fat again. These things happen, except
$2,000 computers are considerably less forgiving than $30 books
when it comes to bacon fat. In fact, they are remarkably intolerant
of spills of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, might never happen. Does anybody, after all,
have a computer in the kitchen? Unlike conventional cookbooks,
cooking CD-ROMs are not kitchen tools. They are reference books for
the library. If you are going to use a recipe from a computerized
cookbook, you will probably print it out first, provided that,
unlike me, you have a printer.
</P>
<P>
   Then, even if you drop the fat, the recipe will be protected in
the computer. All you've damaged is the printout.
</P>
<P>
   A computerized cookbook clearly requires a different set of
instincts. For example, I like to browse through cookbooks until
something catches my eye. Opening up ``Joy of Cooking'' to
Brunswick stew, I can't help but notice the recipe immediately
before it, for country captain, another old-fashioned braised
chicken dish that I haven't thought about for ages.
</P>
<P>
   Flipping pages, I land by chance on a section describing the
characteristics of fish and learn that the black cod is the same as
the sable, which I never knew.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, to find the recipe for Brunswick stew on the
CD-ROM, I must go directly there. The only opportunity for detour
is a brief essay on chicken fricassees, stews and other braised
dishes. That will indeed give me the opportunity to click on
country captain, along with chicken cacciatore, chicken chile verde
and a dozen other recipes.
</P>
<P>
   But it takes an act of will, not chance, to get there, and I
won't end up learning about black cod, either.
</P>
<P>
   The real value of these CD-ROMs is in harnessing the organizing
power of the computer and applying it to the stuff of cooking.
CD-ROM cookbooks not only offer recipes, they also accept your own.
If you have the patience to type your personal set of recipes into
a computer, these CD-ROMs will arrange them for you, let you print
them out and analyze their nutritional values.
</P>
<P>
   No longer will you have tattered, stained and dog-eared recipes,
clipped from some defunct magazines, sticking haphazardly out of
cookbooks like so many loose ends. What's more, the CD-ROMs will
also organize shopping lists for you, refigure recipes depending on
the number of servings you desire, offer menu suggestions and even
search for recipes that meet your stated criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, these functions are not all welcomed by everybody.
Some of us prefer tattered, dog-eared recipes and shopping lists
scrawled on the backs of old envelopes. We have no use for a
function that searches for recipes that can be cooked in less than
an hour because that's not how we decide what to cook. We don't
want a computer's menu suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose somebody like that might be described as a Luddite
after all. At least I won't spill anything on my computer.
</P>
<P>
   JOY OF COOKING (Simon &AMP; Schuster Interactive/Compuworks; $19.99;
Windows 95 and 98.)
</P>
<P>
   The classic American cookbook ``Joy of Cooking'' was originally
published in 1931. In 1997, a thoroughly revised ``Joy of Cooking''
was published, the first major revision in more than 20 years. It
took only another year for ``Joy'' to appear on CD-ROM.
</P>
<P>
   Those who despair of America's disposable culture may find
comfort in the link between the Depression-era homemaker seeking
inspiration in this kitchen bible and the modern computer user
clicking through its pages.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, times have changed more than a little bit. No longer
does the cookbook offer helpful hints about skinning squirrels and
simmering porcupines. People interested in past editions can
consult the history link on Joy's Web site (www.simonsays.com/joy).
Those interested in the present can consult the CD-ROM, which
reprints the entire 1,000-plus pages of the bound volume and costs
$10 less than the hardcover edition.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   If you are familiar with the book, the CD-ROM will look
familiar, too. The typeface is the same, though proportionately
bigger on the computer screen, and while you may encounter the same
sort of black-and-white illustrations that adorn the book, the
CD-ROM does not add any visual aids that take advantage of computer
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Whether offering recipes or discussing cooking techniques, the
CD-ROM is text-heavy and gray, though not dense, just like the
book.
</P>
<P>
   It does offer organizing aids, though. After calling up the
recipe for boeuf bourguignonne, I clicked on Ingredients, which
gave me a blown-up screen of just the ingredients. That would make
a useful printout for checking supplies or taking to the market.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I don't have to settle for this list. Joy will create
a separate shopping list for me, organized by category. What's
more, if I'm planning more than one dish, Joy will consolidate the
ingredients for all the recipes on one list. It also lets you
delete and add ingredients if your needs go beyond these recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Joy offers other useful and flexible tools like scaling, in
which the computer will convert a recipe for 6 into a recipe for 4,
or 16. You can annotate recipes and keep the notes. You can add
your own recipes and organize them by categories like ingredients,
ethnicity and type of meal.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Joy is simple to operate, so simple it
doesn't even come with a printed user's guide. One area in which I
could have used help was the Weblink, which apparently allows you
to exchange recipes with other people on the Web and to download
recipes directly into the cookbook. I connected to the Web and
started up Weblink but was unable to make it work.
</P>
<P>
   But on the whole, Joy is easy to use, like the bound cookbook,
and it demonstrates its good taste with an absence _ except when
you sign off _ of the annoying heraldic music so common in other
programs.
</P>
<P>
   WILLIAMS-SONOMA GUIDE TO GOOD COOKING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Broderbund; $39.95; Windows 95 and 98, Power Macintosh.)
</P>
<P>
   There is music every step of the way with the Williams-Sonoma
Guide to Good Cooking. Music proclaims the opening of the program,
it underscores the movement from one area to another, it is
intensely irritating, and it is exactly what the mute button is
made for.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, this program is a likable cookbook, offering a
creatively organized set of recipes that are divisible in any
number of ways.
</P>
<P>
   The program opens with a Kitchen site. From there, you can go in
several directions: to the recipe index, which lists the 1,000
recipes from A to Z; to a useful glossary, which not only defines
ingredients like adzuki beans but also explains how to use them; to
a menu planner, where you can assemble your own menus, or to the
chief browsing device, the Recipe Finder.
</P>
<P>
   The finder allows you to search through the database in all
sorts of ways. You can seek out seasonal dishes, for example, or
search by cooking method, region, cooking time, ingredients or
courses. But that can get confusing. Let's say I want a main course
that can be made in 45 minutes or less, from Italy, with bacon as
an ingredient, that would be good in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   I plug all this into the recipe finder and come up with a grand
total of zero recipes. Yet if I replace ``spring'' with
``year-round,'' I find three recipes. The key, I guess, is to set a
couple of priorities and not be too precise.
</P>
<P>
   There are other confusing aspects. My search found 390 recipes
that take 60 minutes or less to prepare and 693 recipes that take
longer than an hour. Aside from the question of whether most people
want to spend that much time cooking, those recipes add up to
considerably more than the 1,000 supposedly in the database.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you need a mind like a computer to understand. Of the
1,000 or so recipes, more than 600 are from Europe and the United
States, while 67 come from Asia, 47 from Mexico and 4 from Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   It is not at all clear what the criteria are for selecting
recipes, except that Williams-Sonoma figured that these would
appeal to a knowledgeable, curious audience. Many of these dishes
seem as if they would be perfectly at home on the menus of high-end
restaurants _ dishes like adzuki beans with baked eggplant, baked
fresh figs in port, fusilli with radicchio and smoked salmon, and
pork tenderloin with onion marmalade.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't test the recipes, but two I inspected carefully _
spaghetti carbonara and red beans and rice _ seemed both authentic
and practical.
</P>
<P>
   The Williams-Sonoma Guide is occasionally clunky. It is not
immediately clear how to move forward or back. You can adjust the
scale of recipes, but the adjustments are inflexible; you can alter
a recipe for 6 to serve 3 or 12, but not 4 or 8.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, ingredients are intelligently linked to the
glossary and when you have questions about techniques, the answers
are readily available. I had no problem finding a guide to carving
a turkey, for example.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One thing the program does not do is organize your personal
recipes. You will just have to keep them in that tattered folder.
But the Williams-Sonoma Guide does many other things well. If only
it didn't have that music.
</P>
<P>
   THE COMPLETE INTERACTIVE COOKBOOK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Compton's; $29.95; Windows 3.1 and later.)
</P>
<P>
   A recipe for ``a la king sauce'' is the first entry in The
Complete Interactive Cookbook. It's all downhill from there.
</P>
<P>
   The cookbook abounds with such cafeteria-style recipes, the sort
that will appeal to you if you love Jell-O molds, as well as dishes
that read like a list of third-prize winners at the county fair.
</P>
<P>
   Watercress and apple souffle caught my eye, as did guava jelly
and avocado ice cream. There's also a recipe for gourmet avocado
ice cream, a preparation involving whipped cream, brown sugar, egg
whites, chopped bananas and kiwi slices.
</P>
<P>
   I used the search device to look for all recipes with avocado,
and it revealed two. Those two, however, did not include either ice
cream, nor did they include avocado and orange pasta, which I
happened upon. Who knows how many other recipes with avocado are
lurking?
</P>
<P>
   The recipes are organized by books. You can switch from the Book
of Afternoon Tea to the Book of Garnishes to the Book of One-Pot
Cooking, 26 books in all. I found few of the recipes appealing. Why
would anybody want to make Crab Burritos with one-half cup of
mozzarella cheese, sour cream and _ yes _ avocados?
</P>
<P>
   Many recipes are also difficult to follow. The recipe for bercy
sauce, the classic French shallot-and-wine sauce, includes fish
veloute sauce but doesn't tell you what it is or how to make it.
You can find a reference to it under Related Recipes, but it should
be more clearly linked.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the information offered under Chef's Tips seems esoteric
rather than practical. Under the heading Salmon: Farming, we are
told that salmon farmers avoid chemicals and antibiotics, but we
are told nothing about how farmed salmon taste compared with wild.
In general, this cookbook doesn't have a point of view, except
maybe on avocados.
</P>
<P>
   THE COMPLETE MASTERCOOK SUITE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sierra; $49.95; Windows 3.1 or higher, Macintosh.)
</P>
<P>
   The Complete Mastercook Suite must appeal to somebody; it calls
itself ``the No. 1 best-selling cooking series.'' I'm not sure what
that means, but its appeal is lost on me.
</P>
<P>
   When you begin the program, you are offered what looks to be a
bookshelf containing 12 volumes. It's a little too realistic; you
have to crane your neck uncomfortably to read the sideways writing
on the spines of the books. That's about as far as I got on my
desktop computer.
</P>
<P>
   An error message reading ``invalid printer'' stopped my computer
in its tracks. I managed to install Mastercook on my laptop,
though, and was able to proceed. I frankly found little of
interest, graphically or textually.
</P>
<P>
   After selecting one of those 12 volumes to open, you are
presented with a straightforward computer screen with a task bar
across the top. The text below is supposed to look like the pages
of a book. I chose Meatlovers Recipes, which included recipes for
chicken and beef, but not for any other meats.
</P>
<P>
   I guess pork and lamb don't count, or maybe the producers didn't
pay their dues _ all the chicken recipes seemed to come from the
National Broiler Council and the beef recipes from the National
Cattlemen's Beef Association, both big trade associations. You
could probably get these recipes free by writing to the trade
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the recipes come from trade groups. The volume called
American Chefs includes recipes from restaurant chefs, but that
doesn't make the recipes any more winning. Some are downright
incomprehensible. Take one called bowl of the wife of Kit Carson,
from Dudley Cable-Larche of the Fort, a restaurant near Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Why is it called that? No explanation, but before visions of the
Donner party appear, you should know that it's actually a kind of
chicken, rice and bean soup. The chef explains that it is properly
known as caldo tlalpeno, but what's that got to do with Kit
Carson's wife?
</P>
<P>
   We may never know the answer, but we can get a precise
nutritional analysis. Each serving contains 564.1 calories, 21.7
grams of saturated fat and 1,753 milligrams of sodium, in case you
were wondering.
</P>
<P>
   Other parts of Mastercook also defy comprehension. Eleven of the
12 volumes have titles that are self-explanatory, like Bartender's
Guide, Bake-It and Kitchen Classics, but one volume is called Cole
International.
</P>
<P>
   I have not the slightest idea why and could find nothing to
explain it. If you open Entertain, you find all sorts of hors
d'oeuvres and canapes as well as a recipe for catfish with mustard
sauce. Why is that there? Mastercook is not telling.
</P>
<P>
   This CD-ROM doubtless has more to offer than I could find. A
selection of mini-videos offers visual explanations of techniques
like butterflying, kneading and flattening. And according to the
extremely dry 173-page handbook, you can do all sorts of other
things with the disk, like find recipes instantly, create your own
cookbooks and manage your wines.
</P>
<P>
   The package even includes two other CD-ROMs: Cooking Light and
Graham Kerr's Swiftly Seasoned. Frankly, when I couldn't find out
about Kit Carson's wife, I didn't want to know any more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
