<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4015 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-NOISE-ART-2TAKES-     03-17 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-NOISE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AH! THE SOUNDS OF (ALMOST) SILENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn., Ill., Wis.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By CATHERINE GREENMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They can put a man on the moon _ but they can't silence the
teeth-rattling sputter of your neighbor's lawn mower on a Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Or can they?
</P>
<P>
   Well aware of the negative effects that an incessantly humming
generator, a suddenly whining siren or a sporadically grinding
power drill can have on the human psyche, scientists and
manufacturers have been searching for decades for a way to quiet
environmental noise.
</P>
<P>
   Most modern attempts to put a lid on the racket that surrounds
the human race have centered around a noise-canceling theory
developed in the 1870s by a British physicist, John William Strutt,
the third Baron Rayleigh. Although the theory is a relatively
simple one _ one type of noise is canceled by its opposite,
``anti-noise'' _ figuring out how to apply the theory to large,
loud machinery has been much more complex.
</P>
<P>
   The shrinking size of microprocessors and electronics has
spurred companies like the NCT Group of Stamford, Conn., to take
another look at noise cancellation. The bulky computers that were
used to analyze and reproduce sound 20 years ago have been replaced
by a single chip and a circuit board.
</P>
<P>
   The NCT Group, which developed noise cancellation technology in
the 1980s, is now focusing on consumer headsets, while it licenses
its technology to other companies for use in factories and cars.
</P>
<P>
   Individual consumer headsets using anti-noise technology to
muffle background din are now on the market from companies
including the NCT Group (its name comes from Noise Cancellation
Technologies), Sony Electronics and Sennheiser.
</P>
<P>
   But how does this technology use noise to quiet noise? Judging
from what happens when a 15-year-old stands next to his stereo
speaker with an electric guitar to play along with Led Zeppelin,
two noises definitely do not grow quieter when combined. The
objective of a noise cancellation system, however, is to create the
mirror opposite of the offending noise being produced so the two
noises cancel each other out.
</P>
<P>
   The technology revolves around what physicists call destructive
interference: a sound wave created by a noise can be canceled by a
sound wave that is the exact mirror opposite. The mirror-image
anti-noise sound wave has a trough where the noise wave has a peak,
and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   Does noise cancellation work? Well, yes, sort of. Most exhaust
noise is composed of both high and low frequencies, but active
noise canceling systems work most effectively on the
lower-frequency ones. High-frequency noise is harder to track
because of its more frequent peaks and crests.
</P>
<P>
   An active muffler is able to reduce constant low-frequency noise
levels by an average of 10 to 15 decibels. Because the noise level
that comes out of an average industrial generator is 90 to 100
decibels (the noise of a chain saw is about 100 decibels), the
active mufflers are able to cut generator noise by up to 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But such a device has virtually no effect on sudden
high-frequency sounds, like a dog's bark or baby's cry.
</P>
<P>
   The NCT Group (www.nct-active.com) licensed its technology to
Tenneco Automotive, a manufacturer in Illinois that makes silencers
for industrial generators, in the early 1990s. Tenneco Automotive
said it now had several hundred industrial silencers in operation.
When offending noise moves through a receiver of an industrial
noise cancellation silencer (which resembles some sort of
three-pronged lunar explorer module), a digital signal processor
analyzes the structure of the noise, copies it and creates its
anti-noise.
</P>
<P>
   Active Control, developed by Digisonix (a division of Nelson
Industries, itself owned by Cummins Engine Co., an exhaust and
filtration system manufacturer based in Stoughton, Wis.), is
another brand of noise cancellation technology. It is based on the
same principles but uses slightly different means to produce
anti-noise sound waves.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although active noise control mufflers have been used
successfully to quiet industrial generator exhausts, the initial
attempts to develop silencing mufflers in the automotive industry
have backfired, so to speak, because it is hard to build
electronics components that can withstand the heat of car exhaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to find processors that could live in that
environment,'' said Mary Woros, director of the Noise and Vibration
Center at General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, auto manufacturers like General Motors and
Ford were eager to develop active mufflers, and not just because
they would make cars quieter. The new mufflers would not generate
back pressure in the engine, as passive mufflers do, thereby
cutting fuel consumption by up to 5 percent and increasing engine
performance.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, noise-canceling mufflers almost made it onto
New York City buses as standard equipment. In 1993 the NCT Group,
in a joint venture with Walker Manufacturing, installed silencing
mufflers on buses.
</P>
<P>
   A processor chip analyzed the exhaust sound waves, and 220-watt
speakers at the tailpipes of each bus emitted noise-canceling sound
waves. Although the mufflers reduced fuel consumption by about 3
percent, they were ultimately too costly to maintain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tests didn't pan out because there were problems with
reliability and cost effectiveness,'' said Bob Slovak, a spokesman
for New York City Transit.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of building a noise-canceling muffler for a car starts
at about $200; that has been a problem because the cost of building
an ordinary muffler is about $60. But Clay Shipps, director of
automotive operations at Tenneco Automotive, speaking of the price
issue, said, ``I'm convinced that while it's been a hurdle in the
past, we're nearing the end.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, NCT Group has focused on designing Active Noise
Cancellation products for the consumer market, including individual
headsets marketed as Noisebusters. (NCT Group dissolved its
partnership with Walker Manufacturing and got out of the muffler
business in 1995. After that, Walker Manufacturing became known as
Walker Electronic Silencing, a division of Tenneco Automotive, and
licensed the technology from NCT Group.)
</P>
<P>
   Noise-canceling headsets use the same destructive interference
principle as industrial mufflers. A microphone detects the noise
signal and sends it to the system's processor, which immediately
copies it and creates an anti-noise signal that is sent through the
headset speakers. The headsets are best at muffling low-frequency
noise.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, United Airlines entered into an agreement with
NCT Group last year to supply its business-class passengers with
headsets as a weapon against monotonous engine noise. Many people
who buy these headsets are pilots of commercial and private planes,
who find that the headphones help reduce the steady low-frequency
noise that surrounds them.
</P>
<P>
   Ultra Electronics, an aerospace electronics company based in
Britain, also markets an active system for reducing airplane cabin
noise.
</P>
<P>
   NCT Group has also released a Clear Speech line of
communications products, including microphones for portable and car
cellular phones and a ``noise free'' speakerphone. Joanna Lipper, a
spokeswoman for NCT Group, said the company was also exploring ways
to apply the technology to home appliances like vacuum cleaners,
dishwashers and refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
   Now if they could just do something about those car alarms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
