<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWNSIZING SOUND FILES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. How can I convert a sound file in the WAV format used in the
Windows Sound Recorder to the smaller MIDI format so I can send the
file by e-mail?
</P>
<P>
   A. In general, it is quite hard, or almost impossible, to
convert a WAV file to a MIDI file accurately unless you have
high-end music editing software (like Sound2MIDI) and a simple WAV
file, featuring one instrument playing a single note at a time.
Sound-clip files in formats like the Windows WAV format (or AIFF in
Macintosh) can be rather large because they contain a great deal of
precise data.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, MIDI (Musical Instrument Digital Interface) files
are relatively small _ but there is a reason for that. The files do
not contain any actual sound content; instead, they hold data that
tell the computer which notes to play and what instruments to use.
Think of a WAV file as a cake, and a MIDI file as a recipe.
</P>
<P>
   If file size is the issue, try using PKZIP or other software
designed to compress files. You might also try converting the WAV
file to a different sound format that takes up less space, like
MP3.
</P>
<P>
   There are many shareware programs on the Web that will let you
listen to, edit and convert sound files to different formats. An
excellent place to start looking for just about anything related to
digital audio is the Shareware Music Machine page, at www
.hitsquad.com/smm.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West
43d Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
QandA(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
