<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4019 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-ALPHA-CENTAURI-GA     03-17 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ALPHA-CENTAURI-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON 2067 BATTLEGROUND, 1999 POLITICAL PASSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The year is 2067, and the United Nations Starship Unity hurtles
through space. Behind it: Earth, ravaged by war, famine and
disease. Ahead: a planet orbiting Alpha Centauri, where humankind
can make a new start. Aboard: thousands of cryogenically frozen men
and women with the skills to create a new society.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, things go disastrously awry. A reactor malfunction
destroys the ship's communications equipment and thaws the
passengers ahead of schedule. Aboard a damaged ship, with no way to
re-establish contact with Earth, the command team argues about how
best to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Without consensus, chaos ensues. Factions consolidate around the
seven most powerful leaders, each of whom has a different vision of
how society should function in the new world. As the planet rises
in the near distance, the ship literally splits along ideological
lines, with each faction boarding a separate landing pod to the
planet's surface.
</P>
<P>
   Thus begins Sid Meier's Alpha Centauri, a strategy game that
marries Sim City to Frank Herbert's ``Dune.'' Unlike most strategy
games, in which all players have the same agenda (economic
dominance or military conquest), Alpha Centauri simulates a complex
competitive world where agendas often diverge.
</P>
<P>
   Each faction plays by a different set of rules, based on its
values, economic behavior and political philosophy. The Gaians, for
instance, are die-hard Greens led by a lissome Scottish botanist.
Appalled by the environmental atrocities on Earth, they are
determined to live in harmony with the planet.
</P>
<P>
   They are incredibly good at harnessing natural resources in a
sustainable fashion. They are fabulously efficient and highly
democratic. They are also pacifists. That becomes a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast that with Morgan Industries, led by a Namibian diamond
tycoon whose only goal is untrammeled economic growth. The
Morganites' values are corporate, and their ideology is unfettered
laissez-faire capitalism. They require lots of resources to sustain
their high standard of living, and a healthy police force to keep
the underclass from burning down their luxury high-rises. But they
don't like war either. It's bad for business.
</P>
<P>
   War is no problem for the Lord's Believers, a fundamentalist
group whose leader hails from the Christian States of America.
Hostile acts against nonbelievers send morale through the roof. But
because its value system is based on faith, rather than knowledge,
the group has trouble developing new technology.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Planet, new technology is a way of life.
Led by a Russian cybernetics genius, these are the hackers, the
techno-utopians and pure scientists with fast network access and
really cool toys who believe that research and development will
solve everything. Open networks accelerate the pace of discovery.
Unfortunately, they also make those discoveries easy to steal, but
hey, information wants to be free.
</P>
<P>
   In the Human Hive, an atheist, totalitarian collective,
information is never free. By order of Chairman Sheng-Ji Yang,
private property and civil rights have been abolished. Any
individual sacrifice is justified for the greater good. Housed in
underground fortresses, the Hive is a paragon of centralized
control: xenophobic, disciplined and heavily armed.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the Spartan Federation, rallied by the ship's chief
of security, is a highly decentralized group of paramilitary
survivalists whose only binding philosophy is the right to bear
arms.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, there is the Peacekeeping Forces, whose East Indian
commissioner hews to the United Nations' humanitarian, democratic
ideals _ and battles the plague of bureaucratic inefficiency.
</P>
<P>
   As the leader of any given faction, you explore the planet,
build cities, conduct research and confront other groups. You may
resolve the inevitable conflicts diplomatically. If you are
suitably equipped, you may also wipe rival factions off the face of
the map. You can violate treaties. You can lie. You can commit
atrocities, if you're willing to make enemies and incur sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   You can spark dissent. Or you can cooperate to achieve a higher
goal _ engineering a global trade agreement, solving an
environmental crisis or pulling off a project that no single group
can achieve on its own.
</P>
<P>
   How you play depends on what you're trying to win. You can win a
standard military victory by conquering everyone. You can win a
diplomatic victory by getting yourself elected planetary governor.
Or you can achieve economic dominance by cornering the world energy
market.
</P>
<P>
   Alternately, you can shoot for Ascent to Transcendence, the
ultimate stage of human evolution _ a spiritual triumph that
requires staggering amounts of technology.
</P>
<P>
   When different players strive for different kinds of victory,
the game becomes something more than king of the hill or Monopoly.
It gets complicated _ and interesting. There are natural alliances
and natural antipathies and shifting constituencies, sudden
betrayals and conciliatory back-scratching.
</P>
<P>
   There are questions about expediency and questions about trust,
particularly when you're playing against other human beings in real
time _ or online games that involve a combination of human beings
and computer opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``On line, people mostly gang up on the computer,'' said Meier,
who has only recently turned to science fiction after designing
historical simulation games like Gettysburg and Civilization.
``They band together to beat the artificial intelligence. And then
when they've beaten the computer, they'll go after each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``But sometimes, maybe they're so invested in building these
cities and getting their societies up and running that they don't
want it to end. But when someone wins, by conquest or ascent or
whatever, that's it, the game's over.
</P>
<P>
   The world goes away. So someone says, `Hold off, I'm working on
a really cool technology right now, let's just keep it going.' If
someone looks like he's going to win militarily, they just all keep
him from doing that. They agree not to end the game.''
</P>
<P>
   In online geopolitics, sometimes a stalemate is as good as it
gets.
</P>
<P>
   Alpha Centauri, developed by Firaxis, published by Electronic
Arts; CD-ROM for Windows 95 and 98; $49.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 1605EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4020 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PASTRIES-RECIPES-2ndT     03-17 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PASTRIES-RECIPES-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: up the cooking. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When completely cooled, break apart any nut clusters that may
have formed. Use a rolling pin and roll over the nuts to crush
them. Another technique is to hold one end of the rolling pin on
the table and crush the nuts by bringing the other end of the
rolling pin up and down on top of them. Be gentle, or the nuts will
fly all over the place. Set praline aside until ready to use.
</P>
<P>
   Filling:
</P>
<P>
   Scant 2 1/4 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Grated zest of 1/2 orange
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Grand Marnier
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup golden raisins, hydrated with 1/4 cup dark rum, see Note
</P>
<P>
   1 cup M&AMP;M milk chocolate mini baking bits
</P>
<P>
   Note: Place raisins in glass jar and add water so it covers
raisins by at least 1/2 inch. Stir in rum. Cover with plastic wrap
and place in refrigerator for 24 hours. It's better to allow
raisins to hydrate for 2-3 days; they will become very plump as
they absorb the liquid. Strain the amount that you need through a
fine mesh sieve before adding to the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Place heavy cream in medium mixing bowl and whip to soft peaks
using an electric mixer set on medium-high speed. Store whipped
cream in refrigerator until ready to use.
</P>
<P>
   Italian meringue:
</P>
<P>
   2 large egg whites
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon water
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   Place egg whites in medium bowl and whip with electric mixer set
on medium for about 5 seconds. Pour water, sugar and corn syrup
into a 1-quart heavy-bottomed saucepan and place over medium-high
heat. Insert candy thermometer and cook mixture until it reaches
250 degrees. Remove cooked sugar from heat.
</P>
<P>
   Increase mixer speed to medium-high and make an Italian meringue
by pouring the hot sugar down the side of the mixing bowl into the
whipping whites. Be careful not to pour the hot sugar directly onto
the beaters, or it will splatter. Whip meringue until stiff and
glossy, about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Finish filling by folding orange zest and Grand Marnier into
whipped cream using a rubber spatula. Then fold the meringue into
the whipped cream, being careful not to deflate either mixture.
Fold in the crushed praline, raisins and the mini baking bits.
Don't mix the chocolate or too much of the color will fade.
</P>
<P>
   Pour mixture into a 10-inch loaf pan and use an offset spatula
to smooth the top. Place in freezer for a few hours to set.
</P>
<P>
   To unmold, dip pan in hot water for about 5 seconds. Invert a
flat plate over the loaf pan. Place one hand on either side,
grasping both plate and loaf pan, and flip them so the loaf pan is
on top. Gently lift off loaf pan. Use a hot chef's knife to slice
the dessert. To heat knife, dip in hot water and wipe it dry before
each slice. The dessert can be served with raspberry and mango
sauce; chocolate sauce is another good choice.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 549 calories, 41 grams fat, 41
grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 93 milligrams cholesterol, 52
milligrams sodium, 67 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CARAMEL-DIPPED FRUIT
</P>
<P>
   Yields 1 pound
</P>
<P>
   Scant 1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   Generous 2 1/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   Scant 2/3 cup light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   1 pound fresh fruit
</P>
<P>
   Note: The fruit must be at room temperature when you coat it.
The fruit should be coated about 3 hours before you plan to serve
it. Also, for safety's sake, when working with caramel, it is smart
to have a bowl of cold water nearby. If you get hot sugar on your
fingers, immediately dip them in cold water to remove it and avoid
a burn.
</P>
<P>
   Place water, sugar and corn syrup in a 2-quart heavy-bottomed
saucepan over medium-high heat. The corn syrup will make the cooked
sugar harder and crunchier; it will also help prevent the cooked
sugar from melting as quickly when it reacts to the humidity in the
air. Insert a candy thermometer and cook sugar mixture to 311
degrees, what is known as the hard-crack stage. Stir sugar slowly
as it cooks to ensure that it cooks evenly. If you don't stir it,
the mixture will develop hot spots and the sugar will cook faster
in those spots. Use a pastry brush to keep the inside of the
saucepan clean as the sugar cooks, or the sugar may recrystallize.
To do this, dip a clean brush in cold water and brush the inside of
the pan's sides clean.
</P>
<P>
   Remove cooked sugar from heat and pour into a medium-size
heat-proof glass bowl. The glass bowl will hold the temperature and
stop the cooking process. It will allow you to reheat the sugar in
the microwave if necessary. If you leave the sugar in the saucepan,
the sugar will continue to cook and turn dark brown. Occasionally
stir the hot sugar to keep it from darkening because of the
residual heat. Stirring also helps to keep the temperature even.
Put a towel under the bowl to keep it from tipping and to protect
your hands from the heat of the glass.
</P>
<P>
   Peel, core or pit, and halve the fruit as necessary. Use a sharp
knife to slice the fruit into small pieces. (This is not necessary
for berries or grapes.) Arrange fruit on toothpicks or small
skewers in any combination you like. Leave enough room at one end
of the toothpick or skewer so you will be able to hold it as you
dip it in the hot sugar. Dip each toothpick in the hot sugar,
coating the fruits completely. Wipe the toothpick against the rim
of the bowl to remove any excess sugar and place on a sheet of
parchment paper. Repeat until all of the fruit has been dipped. The
fruit skewers should release easily from the parchment paper as
soon as they cool. You can arrange them on a plate, or use your
imagination to make a fruit-skewer centerpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 160 calories, 0 fat, 42 grams
carbohydrates, trace protein, 0 cholesterol, 15 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
