<HEADER>
A4021 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PASTRIES-RECIPES-1000     03-17 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PASTRIES-RECIPES-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESSERT RECIPES FROM PASTRY MASTER JACQUES TORRES
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies PASTRIES-JACQUES TORRES) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STRAWBERRY SHORTCAKE
</P>
<P>
   Yields 8-10
</P>
<P>
   Scones:
</P>
<P>
   4 cups bread flour
</P>
<P>
   1 2/3 cups cake flour
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons PLUS 1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   Generous 1/2 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   3 1/3 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup golden raisins
</P>
<P>
   1 cup blanched almonds, toasted and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup whole milk
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Place first 6 ingredients in medium mixing bowl. Use an electric
mixer set on medium to mix ingredients just until combined. (This
can also be done by hand.) Stir in raisins and almonds. When
ingredients are fully incorporated and dough holds together, turn
it onto a lightly floured work surface. Knead gently for about 1
minute, just until dough is smooth. If you overwork dough, it will
shrink during baking. Use a rolling pin to roll dough gently into a
1/2-inch-thick rectangle. Use a 4-inch fluted cutter to cut circles
from the dough. Place them on a parchment paper-covered baking
sheet. Brush tops of scones with milk and place in oven. Bake until
well-risen and evenly golden brown, about 20 minutes. Remove from
oven and cool on wire rack until ready to use.
</P>
<P>
   Ganache:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/3 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons loose orange pekoe tea
</P>
<P>
   11.5 ounces bittersweet chocolate, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Grand Marnier
</P>
<P>
   Heat heavy cream and tea together in 2-quart heavy-bottomed
saucepan until bubbles begin to form around edge of pan. Make sure
you have chopped the chocolate as finely as possible so it will
melt quickly and easily. Place chopped chocolate in medium mixing
bowl. Make ganache by straining hot cream mixture through a
fine-mesh sieve into chocolate and letting it sit for 30 seconds to
melt the chocolate. Then slowly whisk until smooth and homogeneous.
A hand-held immersion blender ensures a smooth ganache and keeps
the emulsion of the chocolate. Mix until all the hot cream is
incorporated and ganache is smooth and homogeneous. If ganache
separates, it's easy to fix. It should come back together when you
add a small amount of chilled cream and whisk well. The ganache
should be thick, shiny and smooth. Add the Grand Marnier and mix
until fully incorporated. Pour ganache into a bowl. Cover with
plastic wrap and allow to cool for at least 4 hours at room
temperature. As it cools, it will thicken and set. The ganache is
ready to be used when consistency is similar to that of toothpaste.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   About 3 cups fresh strawberries
</P>
<P>
   Pour heavy cream and sugar into medium mixing bowl and whip to
soft peaks with electric mixer set on medium. Place whipped cream
in pastry bag fitted with 1/2-inch star tip.
</P>
<P>
   Use serrated knife to slice each scone in half. Each half can be
sprinkled with a little Grand Marnier, but that's optional. Spread
a 1/4-inch-thick layer of ganache over bottom half of scone. Hull
and halve strawberries. Cover ganache with the strawberries. Pipe
whipped cream on top of strawberries. Cover with top half of scone
and place on plate.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per shortcake for 10: 1,029 calories, 71
grams fat, 94 grams carbohydrates, 15 grams protein, 186 milligrams
cholesterol, 1,202 milligrams sodium, 62 percent of calories from
fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FROZEN NOUGAT PARFAIT
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   Praline:
</P>
<P>
   Scant 1/2 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cups plus 2 tablespoons hazelnuts, blanched
</P>
<P>
   Place sugar and water in copper pot or 2-quart heavy-bottomed
saucepan over medium-high heat and bring mixture to a boil. Add
hazelnuts and stir to coat them evenly in the sugar syrup. Your
goal is to cook the hazelnuts until sugar crystallizes and
caramelizes.
</P>
<P>
   When you added water to the sugar, you dissolved the crystals.
As it boils, the syrup becomes thicker as the water evaporates and
big soaplike bubbles begin to form. Soon, all the moisture
evaporates, and the mixture becomes sandy. The sandiness is the
sugar recrystallizing. It takes the re-formation of just one sugar
crystal to recrystallize the others. Keep stirring. Next, you see
the sugar closest to the heat change from sandy to a clear liquid.
The melted sugar clings to the hazelnuts. When the sugar changes
from clear to golden brown, the nuts are caramelized. Once this
happens, pay close attention; the time it takes to pass from
caramelized to burned is only a matter of seconds, especially when
making smaller batches. You know the nuts are finished when most of
the sandy sugar is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Tip: The first few times you make these, try this: When the
sugar closest to the heat changes from sandy to liquid, remove pan
from burner and continue to stir. The residual heat in the sugar
and nuts will continue to cook the mixture while you stir it.
Reduce heat to medium-low and continue to stir the nuts while
moving the saucepan on and off the heat at 10-second intervals.
This will give you more control as it cooks. When nuts begin to
caramelize, remove them from heat and finish stirring.
</P>
<P>
   Use a wooden spoon to spread the caramelized nuts onto a
parchment paper-covered baking sheet. Don't touch the nuts; they
are extremely hot. Let the nuts cool completely. If your freezer
will accommodate the baking sheet, you can place nuts in the
freezer for about 30 minutes to speed up the cooling.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
