<HEADER>
A4023 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-USED-COMPUTERS-AR     03-17 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-USED-COMPUTERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLAR FULL OF OLD COMPUTERS? GIVE THEM AWAY! 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., N.Y., Pa.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By DEBRA NUSSBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Lisa Castagliuolo, a teacher, sent a wish list of items for
her kindergarten classroom to parents, she asked for books, a new
rug and computers.
</P>
<P>
   Her wish came true about a year ago when Denise Madrigale, who
had a daughter in Miss Castagliuolo's class at Christ the King
Regional School in Haddonfield, N.J., replaced the IBM 386 she had
been using for about seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We upgraded to a 486, and I stuck the 386 in the closet to get
it out of the way,'' said Mrs. Madrigale. She thought about keeping
it around in case she ever needed a replacement monitor or
keyboard, because she was not sure anyone else could use it. Then
she offered it to Miss Castagliuolo.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I thought maybe I was just giving her a
paperweight,'' she said. ``But she was thrilled.''
</P>
<P>
   The teacher used the PC to create a computer center where
students could independently use reading and math learning programs
such as Reader Rabbit. A few months later, another parent donated
another computer.
</P>
<P>
   More than 49 million American households now have personal
computers, and Americans upgrade their computers on average about
once every five years, according to David Tremblay, senior industry
analyst for ZD Market Intelligence, based in La Jolla, Calif. That
means that every year, millions of computer owners wrestle with the
problem of how to dispose of a computer that is still in working
order.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown that relatively few computers are reused, and
that many of the rest wind up in the closet or the basement.
Sometimes those who try to give the computer another life cannot
find a willing recipient.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time people call us, they are frustrated,'' said John
L. German, director of Non-Profit Computing, Inc., a 15-year-old
New York City organization that places used computers with
nonprofit companies, government agencies and schools.
</P>
<P>
   He says donors often tell his group that they have made calls to
other institutions but rarely find any takers for computers less
advanced than 486 or Pentium level.
</P>
<P>
   But some pre-schools and elementary schools are still in the
market for less advanced second-hand computers because they don't
necessarily need Internet access or a lot of memory. For
kindergartens and pre-schools, a computer that can run simple
learning programs might be just enough.
</P>
<P>
   One Christ the King pre-school teacher, Donna Bigos, did not
have a computer for her 3- and 4-year-old students until this year
when she donated her own Packard Bell machine, with a 386 chip, to
her classroom. Her children use it for letter-matching games and
number recognition programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wait their turn to go on it,'' she said. ``They think
they're a big kid because they are on a computer. They all went
home and said, `Guess what we have now?'''
</P>
<P>
   High schools are not often in the market for used computers
these days, but middle schools, elementary and pre-schools often
can find uses for obsolete machines like an Apple II, said
Geraldine Russell, assistant director of the Pennsylvania Space
Grant Consortium, which oversees Scrounge (www.psu.edu/spacegrant),
a five-year-old nonprofit program at Penn State that accepts
donated computers and distributes them to schools and community
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Although many people want to give away old XTs and Commodores,
she said, few places will take them. Nevertheless, such computers
can be useful for giving young children experience in word
processing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In elementary school they are not going to need all the
capabilities,'' of new computers, said Janet Bird, who teaches
fifth grade at Jonestown Elementary School, in rural south-central
Pennsylvania. Ms. Bird, who received a donated Compaq with a 386
chip in 1998 through Scrounge, wanted a computer for her 23
students so that they could write stories and print them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not getting into big programs and we don't need
something that runs that fast,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   If schools cannot put second-hand computers into operation in
the classroom, teachers can often find other uses for them. At
Plymouth Meeting Friends School near Philadelphia, old donated
computers are the raw material for a class where students take them
apart and learn how they work.
</P>
<P>
   In Cherry Hill, N.J., only donated computers with Pentium chips
go into the classroom, said John Scarinci, the school district's
technology director.
</P>
<P>
   Donations of computers are most helpful when the manuals and
software come with the computer. If donating software, the owner
should read the manufacturer's licensing agreement first.
</P>
<P>
   Common practice in the industry suggests that if a person is
donating a computer, software goes along with it _ as long as the
person making the donation doesn't keep a copy. Nancy Anderson, a
Microsoft attorney, said that people donating Microsoft software
should also give the recipient all manuals and other materials, and
added, ``They should make sure there is no other copy that is being
retained.''
</P>
<P>
   Donors should also be careful to clean out all files. Just
reformatting the hard drive will not erase all information. It is
better to use a utility program to clean the disk.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some listings that may be useful to those wishing to
donate computers.
</P>
<P>
   NON-PROFIT COMPUTING A New York City group that places computers
with nonprofit companies, agencies and schools. e-mail:
npc(AT)igc.org; (212) 759-2368.
</P>
<P>
   SCROUNGE: www.psu.edu/spacegrant A nonprofit program at
Pennsylvania State University that distributes donated used
computers to schools and community groups.(814) 863-7688.
</P>
<P>
   EAST-WEST FOUNDATION: www.eastwest.org A Boston nonprofit
company that refurbishes old computers and passes them on to good
causes. (617) 261-6699.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRONIC PRODUCT RECOVERY AND RECYCLING PROJECT:
www.nsc.org/ehc/epr2.htm Information on a conference on March 23
and 24.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS FOR LEARNING: www.computers.fed.gov A federal
government page with information about federal and other reuse
programs.
</P>
<P>
   THE INSTITUTE FOR LOCAL SELF-RELIANCE IN WASHINGTON Has a large
list of recyclers and reusers in the back of its 1997 report,
``Plug Into Electronics Re-use,'' by Brenda Platt and Jennifer
Hyde. (202) 232-4108.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
