<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4025 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TULIPS-NYT &LR;      03-17 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TULIPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TULIP, FROM STEW POT TO CACHEPOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ ``You never know why a love affair starts,'' said
Anna Pavord, a British garden writer who has had quite an affair
with the tulip. Moreover, she said, ``an affair can't be sustained
over a long period unless that object of your affection is
mysterious and endlessly fascinating, revealing things you didn't
know _ it's such an incredibly complicated flower.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pavord, who grows 4,000 tulips in her garden in Dorset, was
in Philadelphia on March 13 for the annual flower show. After that
she was heading up to Boston, then down to New York, to rhapsodize
about the object of her affection, ``the flower that made men
mad,'' as she likes to say, and to stump for her new book, ``The
Tulip'' (Bloomsbury, $35).
</P>
<P>
   This is no dry, botanical tome, though its botany is gracefully
woven into the tale. ``The Tulip'' reads more like an adventure
story, written against a backdrop of a 16th- and 17th-century
Europe booming with trade _ first with the Ottoman Empire to the
East, and then with the New World to the West, its ports shifting
from the Mediterranean to Antwerp and Amsterdam. ``Those became the
places where everybody traded in and out,'' Ms. Pavord said. ``So
massive amounts of money were slopping around, and people had spare
cash to gamble.''
</P>
<P>
   The tall, hearty-looking writer had paused for coffee and
conversation at John Bartram's house on the Schuylkill, where the
Colonial plant explorer and botanist grew the stewartias and
scarlet maples that would eventually enliven the pastoral
landscapes of Capability Brown, landscapes that would supplant huge
plantings of tulips.
</P>
<P>
   Some 400 years ago, when European travelers brought news of a
``red lily'' back from Constantinople, and the first bulbs arrived
in Vienna, few Europeans had ever seen a tulip. ``When the first
bulbs came from the East,'' Ms. Pavord said, ``the Dutch thought
they were a type of onion and stewed them up in broth.''
</P>
<P>
   They became an immediate status symbol in a culture that loved
curiosities, be they insects, monkeys, shells or single flowers so
beautiful they were treasured like jewels. The tulip soon bewitched
those who grew it with its mysterious ability to transform itself
from plain red or yellow to petals fabulously feathered and flamed
with white and deep red.
</P>
<P>
   Just as alchemists of the day strove to turn base metal to gold,
tulip breeders were driven to discover the means of this flowery
transformation. They tried everything from pigeon dung to mixing
powdered paint into their tulip beds, as the price of ``broken'' or
flamed bulbs rose higher and higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``This tulip was worth more than gold,'' Ms. Pavord said.
``Nobody knew how to bring it about. They couldn't have known
because the whole thing could only be unraveled when man had
invented the electron microscope to see something as small as a
virus.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a virus spread by aphids that caused the tulip to
``break'' into various colors, something that was discovered only
earlier in this century. The virus also weakened the bulb, so that
it produced fewer offsets, or bulblets, for new tulips. So by its
very scarcity, the broken tulip became more valuable.
</P>
<P>
   By the beginning of the 17th century, tulip madness was sweeping
through France, where a thriving brewery was traded to a grower for
a single bulb called Tulipe Brasserie. One bride had a dowry of a
single bulb, a double red and white striped prize aptly named
Mariage de Ma Fille by her father.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1630s, tulipomania gripped Dutch growers. By the 1700s,
it had swirled back to Turkey, where Sultan Ahmed III imported
millions of bulbs from Holland for his imperial gardens. When his
subjects grew tired of seeing so much money squandered on tulip
festivals, his extravagance brought on a revolt.
</P>
<P>
   All this is skillfully told by Ms. Pavord, who started
collecting tulip lore 20 years ago, from postcards, prints and
tiles. She stumbled on the odd clue here and there while pursuing
topics for her weekly garden columns for The Independent in London
and for her frequent articles in Gardens Illustrated magazine. She
also collected the 150 color illustrations in the book: paintings,
woodcuts and other visual expressions of the tulip's reign.
</P>
<P>
   About seven years ago, when she felt she was drowning in her
material, she set to work writing the book, holing up for two weeks
every month in a rented cottage on an old Capability Brown estate
in Lincolnshire, an hour's drive from the libraries at Cambridge
University, the Cambridge Botanic Garden and the Fitzwilliam
Museum, which, she said, has the greatest collection of English
flower paintings in England. She roamed far and wide over the
Middle East in search of the wild tulips that started the craze.
And still, she is hungry for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to do a book on the British florists,'' she said,
meaning the amateur growers who brought the tulip back from
oblivion in the 18th and 19th centuries. ``Or write about the
tulip's influence on the decorative arts.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pavord, who graduated with honors in English from the
University of Leicester and is fluent in French, pored through
historic documents, many in their original language. That helped in
deciphering what she calls the ``muddle about the tulip's name.''
Ms. Pavord recalled an afternoon in the Royal Horticultural
Society's Lindley Library in London, where she was trolling through
a 17th century French text, ``bound in vellum, smelling of age.''
</P>
<P>
   She was reading the journals of Pierre Belon, who had a famous
garden in the south of France. Belon, an avid traveler, referred to
the ``red lilies'' the Turks tucked into their turbans in his
journal.
</P>
<P>
   ``My ears pricked up,'' she said. ``I knew there were lilies
growing in Turkey, but I couldn't remember any that were red. So I
double-checked in The Flora of Turkey, and I was right. No red
lilies in Turkey. So I thought those must be tulips. They just
weren't called tulips, because nobody in the West knew what to call
them.''
</P>
<P>
   So she went back to the very first botanical books in the 1500s.
There were woodcuts that clearly were of tulips, but the flowers
were called lilies.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that was one of those huge great shots of light into the
brain,'' Ms. Pavord said. She believes that the tulip got its name
from a mistranslation. The Flemish Ambassador pointed at the flower
in a Turk's turban and asked, ``What is that?'' Thinking he meant
the turban, not the flower, the translator answered ``tulipam.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time E.H. Krelage used the new Darwin tulips in massed
plantings in the Jardin du Trocadero to catch the eye of the crowds
flocking to the Universal Exhibition in Paris in 1889, the tulip
was becoming the darling of Victorian bedding schemes.
</P>
<P>
   Americans continued this love affair, as the first settlers of
New Amsterdam planted bulbs in their gardens. ``So underneath those
great Manhattan skyscrapers sit the ghosts of those very first
tulips that were ever grown in American soil,'' Ms. Pavord said.
And who knows, a descendant of one of them, broken into flames by a
virus, might be getting ready to push its way out of the ground
right now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
