17, 1999. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, PLEASE CALL US AT
202-628-3100.
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA-FCC-REAUTHORIZATION. (For the Hollywood Reporter.) In
an effort to head off congressional criticism, Federal
Communications Commission Chairman William Kennard Wednesday gave
lawmakers a report outlining the agency's plan for reform. (300
words.) By Robin Brown
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO-RUSSIA-SCHAFFER. The Russian parliament has inched
closer to ratifying the START II strategic arms treaty due in part
to a recent diplomatic mission by U.S. Rep. Bob Schaffer and six of
his colleagues, the Colorado Republican said Wednesday. (400
words.) By Charles Davant
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA-STEEL-IMPORTS. Hailed by steel workers as a life
preserver, but criticized by free-trade advocates as protectionism,
legislation that will limit the amount of foreign steel allowed
into the United States won the endorsement Wednesday of the House
of Representatives. (500 words.) By C.J. Karamargin
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-DRUGS-ALLEN. U.S. Rep. Tom Allen discusses the fate of his
Prescription Drug Fairness for Seniors Act, in light of the
Medicare Commission's failure to agree on how to fix the nation's
health-care system for older Americans. (600 words.) By Charles
Davant
</P>
<P>
   NEW JERSEY-FIRE. Rep. William Pascrell, D-Paterons, rolled out a
$5 billion, five-year plan to help local fire companies across the
country hire and train fighters and to purchase the most up-to-date
equipment. Modeled on the COPS program designed to put 100,000
community police officers on the streets, Pascrell's bill has an
equally catchy acronym, FIRE, or Firefighter Investment and
Response Emergency Act. (400 words.) By Paul Kane
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-STEEL-IMPORTS. After months of lobbying for tougher action
to cut levels of foreign steel imports, lawmakers from
steel-producing states Wednesday pushed for legislation to stem the
tide. (500 words.) By Sean Gorman
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA-DOT-TRUCK. The Department of Transportation
inspector general said the number of truck fatalities is
increasing. He said a review of the Office of Motor Carriers showed
a need to collect better data and to launch safety programs more
quickly to improve truck safety. (600 words.) By Lisa Fine
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA-STEEL. Reaction to House vote on steel bill, from
local congressional delegation. (500 words.) By Lisa Fine
</P>
<P>
   WYOMING-MEDICARE-REACT. Wyoming lawmakers react to the Medicare
Commission's failure to find a way to fix the nation's health-care
system for older Americans. (600 words.) By Charles Davant
</P>
