</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BOOK PROVIDES FRESH INSIGHTS INTO CLINTON'S CHARACTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 21)   (For Use By New York Times News Service Clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c. 1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Few observers have defined the tragedy and the
meaning of Bill Clinton's presidency more incisively than George
Stephanopoulos, who was practically a member of his family during
his first four years in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of Stephanopoulos' memoirs, ``All Too Human; A
Political Education,'' he writes, ``The Clinton I know is a
complicated man responding to the pressures and pleasures of public
life in ways I found both awesome and appealing. I have come to see
how his shamelessness is a key to his political success, how his
capacity for denial is tied to the optimism that is his greatest
political strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``For every reckless and expedient act, there are others of
leadership and vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Millions of words have been written about the 42nd president,
and millions more will be written in the future.
</P>
<P>
   But few will capture the essence and the paradox, the good and
the bad, of Clinton better than those brief observations by
Stephanopoulos.
</P>
<P>
   The onetime presidential aide has been criticized for writing
the intimate details about life in the Clinton White House as he
witnessed them. Some critics contend that he has laid bare for
public consumption the description of personal events that should
have remained private at least until Clinton's presidency ends.
</P>
<P>
   New York Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, appearing on television,
described the writing of such tell-tale books as part of the
``vulgarization'' of American politics. There are no longer any
gentlemen in American politics, Moynihan said.
</P>
<P>
   But the book for which Stephanopoulos reputedly was paid $2.7
million is not mean. It reflects the author's disappointment and
disenchantment as well as his bitterness. For a few brief years,
Stephanopoulos was extremely close to Bill and Hillary Clinton, and
the book conveys a belief that he still feels strong ties to them.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanopoulos is a highly intelligent young man, but it is
doubtful that he would be as wealthy and as prominent today had it
not been for Clinton. In other words, he has bit the hand that
anointed him.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by Newsweek magazine if he is proud that he worked for
Clinton, Stephanopoulos replied: ``It's a question I still struggle
with. We accomplished, and he has accomplished, more that I ever
thought humanly possible. But he lost the battle with himself,
tarnished his presidency and all of us associated with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I knew everything then that I know now, of course I
wouldn't (have worked for him). But he's been a good steward, and I
think he's been a good president, despite these horrible flaws.''
</P>
<P>
   Millions of Americans who opposed Clinton's impeachment and his
removal from office could identify with that assessment.
</P>
<P>
   But Stephanopoulos weakens his own claim to innocence by
recording that he got a candid view of Clinton's deceitfulness as
far back as the 1992 presidential campaign when the candidate lied
about reports that he had had a long-running affair with Gennifer
Flowers and that he had dodged the draft during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   By election night, when Clinton defeated George Bush and Ross
Perot, Stephanopoulos writes, ``I had learned to calculate, scheme
and maneuver _ to say things I didn't fully believe and do things I
might later regret while telling myself that, maybe, it would do
some good ... ''
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy lies not in Stephanopoulos' revelations about
Clinton's weaknesses and recklessness. During the lengthy
impeachment hearings in the House and trial in the Senate, the
public learned anew that the boy from Hope is not Little Lord
Fauntleroy. The tragedy stems from the fact that Clinton, through
his own misbehavior, plundered his own potential.
</P>
<P>
   The president has proved that he has the capacity to be an
outstanding, if sometimes vacillating, chief executive but often is
barred by his own character flaws from doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanopoulos provides his readers with some fascinating
insights into Bill Clinton's character and his temper tantrums and
Hillary Clinton's despair and loneliness as she watched the
Whitewater investigation expand and her health care reform plan
die.
</P>
<P>
   But Stephanopoulos also records some lighter moments, including
the on-again-off again efforts of Clinton, Stephanopoulos and
others in the White House to convince Mario Cuomo, who was the
highly regarded governor of New York and a powerful voice in the
Democratic Party, to accept an appointment to the Supreme Court in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, although annoyed with Cuomo's Hamlet-like indecision,
is quoted by Stephanopoulos as saying, ``Mario will sing the song
of America. It'll be like watching Pavarotti at Christmastime.''
But in the end, after lengthy negotiations through Cuomo's son,
Andrew, Mario refused to sing.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court seat, from which Byron White was retiring,
went to Ruth Bader Ginsberg.
</P>
<P>
   The same year, when Clinton needed a single Senate vote to win
passage of his economic plan that included a tax increase on the
richest Americans, that vote was held by Nebraska's Bob Kerrey. A
war hero who lost part of a leg in Vietnam, Kerrey, like Cuomo, was
held in high regard by Democrats even though he had been defeated
by Clinton in the 1992 presidential primaries.
</P>
<P>
   To provide the winning vote on the economic package,
Stephanopoulos writes, Kerrey wanted to be named chairman of a new
commission on economic priorities. It took a lot of negotiating,
including a private Kerrey audience with the president, but in the
end the Nebraskan cast the vote that provided Clinton with victory
in the Senate and Kerrey with his chairmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Tales such as those make for interesting reading. On the larger
question of whether White House insiders should record such
revelations while their former boss remains in the Oval Office, the
answer is: As long as publishers offer $2.7 million for such
memoirs, they will be written.
</P>
</TEXT>
