<TEXT>
<P>
   AIRLINE PASSENGER FAIRNESS ACT
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors: Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz., and Ron Wyden, D-Ore.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines would be required to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Tell passengers when a flight has been overbooked and there is
a possibility of being bumped.
</P>
<P>
   _ Provide full refunds for any unused tickets to passengers who
request them within 48 hours of purchase.
</P>
<P>
   _ Allow passengers to use portions of round-trip or multi-city
tickets however they choose.
</P>
<P>
   _ Inform passengers of all fares being charged on a given flight
and all reasons why a flight is being delayed, diverted or
canceled.
</P>
<P>
   _ Disclose more information about frequent flier programs and
how many tickets per flight are set aside for program participants.
</P>
<P>
   _ Deliver checked luggage to passengers within 24 hours of
landing unless additional delays are reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE PASSENGER BILL OF RIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   Sponsor: Rep. Bud Shuster, R-Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines would be required to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Pay compensation to passengers kept waiting on the runway for
more than two hours prior to take-off or after landing. The
compensation would be the value of the ticket times the number of
hours of waiting. Delays due to air traffic control would not
require compensation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Explain the reasons for a delay, cancellation or diversion to
a different airport, and pay penalties in cases of false or
misleading explanations.
</P>
<P>
   _ Refund the money to any passenger on a flight that is
cancelled for economic reasons.
</P>
<P>
   _ Notify passengers, in cases where airlines share their
two-letter designator code on a flight, if they will not actually
be flying on the airline whose code is being used. Airlines could
not use a single number to denote a flight that it knows will
involve a change of aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   _ Refrain from prohibiting or charging additional fees to
passengers who use only a portion of their tickets.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reveal, upon request, the number of seats on a flight that are
available for frequent fliers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make a good-faith effort to return lost property to the owner
if the person's name is on the property.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bar security screeners from separating babies from their
parents. In addition, the U.S. Transportation Department (DOT)
would study whether airlines are providing adequate supervision of
unaccompanied minors on flights.
</P>
<P>
   PASSENGER ENTITLEMENT AND COMPETITION ENHANCEMENT ACT
</P>
<P>
   Sponsor: Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines would be required to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Institute the same compensation formula as the Shuster plan
for passengers who are delayed for more than two hours after
boarding the plane.
</P>
<P>
   _ Doubles carrier liability for mishandled luggage from $1,250
to $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   _ Provide a full-value voucher or refund if a bumped passenger
is delayed more than two hours.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ensure that, in the event of an emergency, all boarded
passengers would have access to food, water, emergency medical
services and restroom facilities. The plan, which would be filed
with the DOT, would outline deplaning procedures.
</P>
<P>
   _ Spell out passenger rights on the safety placard provided on
the back of every airline seat.
</P>
<P>
   In addition:
</P>
<P>
   _ The transportation secretary would be granted the power to
create, withdraw or auction slots at airports for assignment to new
air carriers and some incumbent carriers in order to increase
competition.
</P>
<P>
   _ The secretary would issue quarterly reports ranking the top
and bottom 10 domestic routes based on average cost to the
passenger, and the large hub airports by market concentration
showing the market share of each airline.
</P>
<P>
   _ Penalties for carriers who engage in unfair competition would
increase from $1,000 to $10,000 a day.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE PASSENGER FAIR TREATMENT INITIATIVE
</P>
<P>
   Sponsor: Proposed by Clinton administration; not yet introduced
in Congress
</P>
<P>
   Airlines would be required to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Publicly disclose their policies regarding flight delays,
cancellations and diversions, provisions and evacuation procedures
for passengers kept on the runway for extended delays, and for
bumping on overbooked flights.
</P>
<P>
   _ Double the maximum payment for lost luggage to $2,500 and the
maximum compensation for being bumped to $800.
</P>
<P>
   _ Disclose to passengers at the time of ticket purchase any
code-sharing arrangements and plane changes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make monthly public filings with the DOT regarding the number
of complaints received in 15 categories.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
