<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4068 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIR-TRAVEL18-COX     03-17 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-TRAVEL18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FLEET OF BILLS WANT TO CARRY AIR TRAVELERS TO SATISFACTION
 &HT;    With AIR-COMPARE. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The airline industry had better fasten its seat
belt, because it is flying into congressional turbulence over
perceived abuses of travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is considering no fewer than four plans for expanding
and protecting the rights of air passengers.
</P>
<P>
   All the proposed legislation would compensate passengers for
lost luggage or being ``bumped'' from a flight, and all would
require more disclosure of more information about fares and
flights.
</P>
<P>
   Some go farther, including provisions that airlines _ and even
some passenger groups _ find worrisome.
</P>
<P>
   Two House bills would steadily increase payments to passengers
according to how many hours they were forced to wait on a runway.
One of those bills would let the government reassign airport slots
to new carriers to improve competition.
</P>
<P>
   A Senate bill would let passengers use portions of round-trip or
multi-city tickets however they choose. The Clinton
administration's plan would double the maximum payment for lost
luggage to $2,500 and the maximum compensation for being bumped to
$800.
</P>
<P>
   ``There sure are a lot of proposals,'' said David Fucus, a
spokesman for the Air Transport Association, which represents the
major carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are willing to work with the government'' to ensure the
comfort, safety and schedules of passengers, he said. ``But we want
to make sure that the legislation does not have non-intended
consequences'' of raising air fares or restricting consumer
choices.
</P>
<P>
   But with popular support from the flying public and powerful
bipartisan sponsors, the bills to protect passenger rights appear
to be taking off.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully the legislation will ``serve as a wake-up call to the
airline industry,'' said Shuster. ``The airlines must refocus their
efforts on providing better customer service. They need to start
treating their passengers as human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Propulsion for reforms was provided by passenger outrage over
shattered schedules caused by the ``sick-out'' by disgruntled
American Airlines pilots and the horror stories told by Northwest
Airlines passengers trapped for hours in planes parked on runways
in Detroit during a January blizzard. The Detroit travelers told of
overflowing toilets, ill seatmates, and flight attendants who
threatened to prosecute rebellious passengers rather than providing
comfort.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, members of Congress are among the nation's most
frequent fliers. Many shuttle back and forth weekly between home
states and the nation's capital. They have their own impressions of
air travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The price of an airline ticket is one of the great mysteries
of modern life,'' marveled Wyden. ``It costs one price if you buy
it over the phone and another if you buy it in person, one if you
buy it in the morning and another three hours from now. It
practically defies the laws of physics.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising that his bill requires airlines to tell
passengers about all the fares charged for a particular flight.
</P>
<P>
   Flying to Pennsylvania several months ago, Shuster and other
passengers were told by the pilot that the plane was being diverted
to Ohio because the Pittsburgh airport was closed. On the ground in
Columbus, the congressman called to find out when the Pittsburgh
airport would reopen and found that it wasn't closed. The pilot had
diverted the flight because of fuel concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress are hardly the only passengers airing their
problems. The U.S. Department of Transportation (DOT) reported that
passenger complaints filed against major air carriers increased
from 6,394 in 1997 to 7,994 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that the passenger rights movement is
riding a political wave,'' said David Stempler, president of the
Air Travelers Association, which represents the flying public.
``The underlying problem is that planes are very crowded now.
People are being forced to sit in that middle seat that used to be
empty. There is insufficient competition in the marketplace to give
people a sense that they have a choice _ that if they are unhappy
with one airline, can go to another and still get to their
destination.''
</P>
<P>
   The skies are likely to be even more crowded. DOT projects that
the number of domestic airline passengers will increase from around
600 million a year now to 1 billion a year by 2008.
</P>
<P>
   Stempler voices the same concern as the airline industry that
government intrusion could cause new problems as it seeks to remedy
old ones. Legislative provisions that would penalize airlines for
planes kept on runways for two hours or longer might push pilots to
take off in conditions they might otherwise wait out, he said. And
legislative restrictions on airline ticketing practices might well
push up airfares for leisure travelers even as they reduce them for
business fliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real question is: Do we want the government making these
decisions?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that this legislation is offered with the best of
intentions,'' ATA President Carol Hallett testified at a committee
hearing on the Senate bill. But ``its worst provisions would have
unintended, adverse and, worst of all, expensive consequences for
the consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Gibbs, a spokesman for Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga., said the
senator believes a compromise can be worked out that will protest
passenger rights without forcing the airlines to raise fares.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to make sure (Congress) works with the airlines to
get the appropriate response,'' said Gibbs.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
