<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4070 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAZER-HOME-970(2TAKE     03-17 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAZER-HOME-970(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PRODUCER'S BIG-BUDGET PROJECT: HIS HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (js) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What happens when one of Hollywood's most
successful producers buys a home in the high reaches of Pacific
Palisades and starts overhauling the interiors? He behaves like _
what else? _ a successful Hollywood producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like producing a movie _ it's funny how similar they
are,'' said Brian Grazer, who has produced such films as ``EdTV,''
which opens next week, and ``Apollo 13,'' and is a producer of the
television show ``Felicity.'' ``I hired the equivalent of
department heads. And things cost much more than I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the 48-year-old producer, who started the project in
1993, began with a star. Not Tom Hanks, a friend who lives only a
few streets away. In this case it was an architectural star, Cliff
May, the father of the California ranch house, whose low-pitched
shake roofs, rooms that flow freely into one another and
sliding-glass doors leading to patios were popular among the show
business elite in the 1960s and 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Grazer's home, on a choice four-acre site with views of nearby
canyons, downtown Los Angeles and the Pacific Ocean, was designed
by May in the late 1930s. When it belonged to Gregory Peck in the
late 1940s, Hedda Hopper, the gossip columnist, marveled at the
house's ``superb vista spreading out in panorama beneath his
windows.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Grazer bought the house, it belonged to a college
professor who used it as a compound for graduate students. ``It was
a dump,'' Grazer said. ``It was full of cats and dogs. He had eight
or nine graduate students living here. He didn't have fences
around, so deer would run in. And, like, the landscape was some
grass and a lot of dirt. I wanted to make it beautiful and restore
it to the same thing Cliff May had designed.''
</P>
<P>
   Grazer, a wiry and energetic Californian who grew up in the San
Fernando Valley, bought the house about six months after he was
divorced. His first priority was to find a home suitable for his
two children, Riley, now 13, and Sage, 11. ``I looked at a bunch of
houses, and I realized what I wanted,'' he said. ``The most
important thing was a view. And isolation. I live really social
daytime. But I'm kind of reclusive at night and on weekends. I like
to be alone.''
</P>
<P>
   After seeing the house, Grazer phoned Joel Schumacher, a former
production designer who directed such films as ``A Time to Kill''
and ``Batman Forever.'' ``I said, `How can I make this livable?'
because the rooms were teeny, and I didn't want to change the cool
ranch style architectural design,'' Grazer recalled. ``So Joel
walked around and said, `You can tear down the walls here, and
build a bar there, and have a play room for the kids there.' It was
doable.''
</P>
<P>
   Doable but expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Grazer bought the house for $2.5 million and put at least $2
million into the reconstruction, which included extensive work on
drainage and the structural bracing to meet present day city codes,
because of the hilly site. (This month, Forbes magazine listed
Grazer as one of the 50 highest-earning entertainment figures, with
1998 earnings the magazine calculated at $26 million.) Work on the
landscaping continues. Grazer was recently offered $10 million for
the home.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-room main house is accompanied by a guest house, which
includes a workroom used by Grazer, a weekend painter, and his
wife, Gigi Levangie, a screenwriter. She and Grazer were married a
year ago. Ms. Levangie was one of the writers of the recent film
``Stepmom,'' which was based loosely on her relationship with
Grazer's children.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after buying the house, Grazer hired Peter Choate, a
veteran architect who had built homes for Henry Mancini and Anne
Bancroft and Mel Brooks. His father, Chris Choate, had once been
Cliff May's partner in building prefabricated housing in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little by little the house evolved,'' Choate said. ``We wanted
to keep the Cliff May structure more or less intact. But Brian had
his priorities: it was for his kids; it was a house of comfort; it
was important to take advantage of those lovely views. We changed a
lot of things around to suit Brian.''
</P>
<P>
   That's probably an understatement. The interior was gutted,
walls removed, rooms made larger, some of the ceilings raised, an
elaborate series of decks and patios were built to take advantage
of the soaring views. A nature trail was built for his children and
their friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted everything done in one year, so I had to start
everything at the same time,'' Grazer said, walking into the airy,
white-walled living room with furniture covered in multicolored
fabrics, pale green, purple, pink and yellow. An Andy Warhol
canvas, one of several in the house, covers one wall.
</P>
<P>
   Like any producer, Grazer, who is in partnership with the
director Ron Howard in Imagine Entertainment, hired what he called
a line producer to oversee the project. (A line producer oversees
every detail on a movie set, from start to finish.) In this case,
his friend Jeffrey Katzenberg, a partner at Dreamworks, suggested
he hire Neal Jevyak, a contractor, to serve as his bridge with
builders, landscapers, the interior designer and numerous others
involved in the reconstruction of the house. Katzenberg had
employed Jevyak in a similar job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was exactly like producing a movie where you sort of have a
vision, a sense of where you want to end up, and then you have to
start everybody all at the same time so that you can make your
date,'' Grazer said.
</P>
<P>
   Construction on the house was completed on schedule, he said,
though the landscaping took somewhat longer. Grazer now says the
experience of redoing the house will inspire a movie he will call
``Experts.'' ``The pool guy is an expert,'' he said. ``The stereo
guy is an expert. And it all costs five times more than they
said.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Walking into the main bedroom, with its custom-made oak bed and
a Warhol painting that resembles a Rorschach test, Grazer said that
the start of the project reminded him of what happens when a new
team takes over a movie studio and starts spending lavish amounts
of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sense of euphoria,'' he said. ``There's ambition.
There's all this excitement. Like when we were building a deck, and
they said, `Oh, you need these cement caissons to prevent the deck
from moving.' And I said, `How much does it cost?' And they said,
`You need 12 of them at $30,000 each.' And I said, `OK, I want a
bigger deck. Let's put it in.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony is,'' he concluded, ``when you're all sort of done,
and they ask you if you want another tree for like $600, I became
apoplectic.''
</P>
<P>
   What seems most surprising about the house, despite its lavish
cost, is that the exterior seems far from ostentatious, almost
ordinary, in keeping with the ethos of Cliff May, who died in 1989
at the age of 81. From the street, Grazer's driveway is flanked by
two neighboring homes. It hardly gives the impression that, once
past the deceptively simple courtyard, a visitor will find a
certain grandeur.
</P>
<P>
   Grazer said he strongly believes in the credo espoused by May:
``Houses should be designed primarily not the way they will look
from the street, but with their practical use in mind. Houses
should be designed so people can live in them the way they want to,
not the way the architect wants them to.''
</P>
<P>
   May's style, which sought to capture the buoyancy and sunny
optimism of postwar Los Angeles, was marked by several innovations
that Grazer has honored. May moved the garage from the back yard to
the front and attached it to the house _ not only saving driveway
space but allowing young families to devote back yards to
children's play and entertaining. (``The only reason people had put
their cars in the back yard was because they had replaced horses
and that is where the barns were,'' May said in 1987.)
</P>
<P>
   Once construction began on the house, Grazer hired Shan Hinton,
the owner of Pour La Maison, an interior design company that had
previously done homes for Jane Seymour, and for Goldie Hawn and
Kurt Russell. Ms. Hinton said that Grazer wanted bold,
multi-patterned textiles on the furniture throughout his house _
yellow, purple, pink, pale green and burnt orange.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian has a strong personality, and it comes out in the
interior of his home,'' Ms. Hinton said. ``He knows what he wants.
He loves bold colors. He doesn't shy away from things.''
</P>
<P>
   Grazer stepped outdoors to point out the sweeping canyon vistas.
In the distance he identified the homes of Garry Shandling and
Norman Lear. ``I met Gregory Peck once, and I said, `Oh, I bought
your house.' He said, `I loved that house.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As an ocean breeze engulfed the patio, Grazer said, ``I know
what he means.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 1634EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
