<HEADER>
A4073 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOS-ANGELES-DESIGN-NY     03-17 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOS-ANGELES-DESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY BUILT LOS ANGELES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By FRANCES ANDERTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the revival of interest in post-World War II Los Angeles
architecture, coupled with a fascination for today's West Coast
architects, book publishers have been working furiously to meet the
demand. New books on Los Angeles design include Monacelli Press'
splendid ``Frank O. Gehry: The Complete Works,'' so heavy you would
need a few workouts to lift it, and two, yes, two volumes from the
Spanish company Editorial Gustavo Gili on R.M. Schindler, who was
among the first immigrants to plant the seeds of European modernism
in Los Angeles in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one publisher, the German Benedikt Taschen, who brought
out ``Julius Shulman: The Architecture and Its Photography,'' was
so taken with Los Angeles design that he bought and is restoring
the architectural landmark Chemosphere House by John Lautner.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few weeks, two books have arrived in this country
from Images Publishing in Australia, both by Michael Webb, on the
architects Ed Niles and Ray Kappe, heirs to the California
modernist tradition. Known to most as the founder of the
experimental SCI-Arc school (Southern California Institute of
Architecture), Kappe is also one of the most undersung architects
in Los Angeles. He began his career in the early '50s and wedded
the open spaces of Richard Neutra to the softer, more natural
modernism of Harwell Hamilton Harris. Then he added the complexity
and love of landscape of Frank Lloyd Wright. Eleven of Kappe's
projects are displayed in this long overdue monograph. Included is
his own, breathtaking 1965 Kappe House in Pacific Palisades, a
marvel of interlocking planes of wood, glass and concrete in
harmony with a lush canyon site. His works are so three-dimensional
that photos do not always do them justice.
</P>
<P>
   Hot on the heels of the Kappe book comes its seeming antithesis
_ an irregularly shaped and deeply personal book, ``Gnostic
Architecture,'' published by Monacelli, by and about the willful,
baffling but provocative architect Eric Owen Moss. Also recently
off the press from Rizzoli is ``Pacific Edge: Contemporary
Architecture on the Pacific Rim'' by Peter Zellner, a book that
places Los Angeles architects alongside their Pacific Rim
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   These books give a sense of the continuities in Los Angeles
architecture. The Malibu-based Niles, who has made a career of
sci-fi structures, was apprenticed to Carl Maston, the modernist,
as was Kappe. Moss was a student at Kappe's SCI-Arc and became a
teacher there. Kappe himself has gone from student of the
midcentury modernists to founder of the school that is breeding
future generations of Los Angeles architects.
</P>
<P>
   Still, better keep some space free on the coffee table: in the
next few months, even more books are coming on Los Angeles
architecture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
