<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LISTEN TO THIS BROWSER 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pop quiz for the generation that has grown up with the Internet:
</P>
<P>
   Name the information appliance that used to be the focal point
for family entertainment before the personal computer, and even
before television. (Yes, there was life before television.)
</P>
<P>
   Now, name the newest and most entertaining feature of the
Microsoft Corp.'s new Internet Explorer 5.0 Web browser, which is
available for downloading starting today at www.microsoft.com/ie.
</P>
<P>
   No, you young whippersnappers, not the telegraph (italics)or(end
italics) the Victrola, (pre-Internet equivalents of e-mail and MP3
music files). The answer to both questions is ``radio.''
</P>
<P>
   By adding radio to its Web browser and the multimedia tools to
go with the the browser, Microsoft is giving a clear signal of its
vision for the future of the Internet. Internet Explorer 5.0 has
been turned into a tool not just for searching for and viewing
information on the Internet's World Wide Web or a local hard disk,
but also for listening to talk and music, and for watching video
clips downloaded from the Net.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is evolving into an entertainment network,
augmenting its already established roles as a global information,
communications and electronic commerce network. The PC is the
primary vehicle for exploring this new medium, and Explorer 5.0 is
the dashboard, complete with a new set of radio buttons.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, the updated browser looks pretty much like
Version 4.0, which is comforting to those of us who have already
invested a few million precious brain cells learning how the
earlier version works, instead of employing them on something more
profitable, like dreaming up creative tax deductions.
</P>
<P>
   But on closer examination, Microsoft has streamlined and refined
this new edition of its browser in lots of small but significant
ways.
</P>
<P>
   Streamlined is a relative term. The new browser _ for
Windows-based machines only, at this point _ still consumes about
100 megabytes of hard disk space for a full installation, slightly
more than its predecessor. But once the browser is in action, it is
much more nimble and elegant.
</P>
<P>
   Gone, or at least hidden, are the annoying ``channels'' that
Microsoft included in earlier versions of Internet Explorer, in a
dubious effort to make it easier for users to get information from
their favorite Web sites. Instead, the new browser has a better
system for making and organizing bookmarks, or shortcuts to
favorite sites.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has made lots of improvements in version 5.0 that make
the browser easier to use. For example, a new ``go'' button has
been added to aid people who could not figure out that they should
push the ``enter'' key after typing a Web address.
</P>
<P>
   And if a user mis-types a Web address, a new auto-correction
feature in the updated browser often can fix the error
automatically. Microsoft has added a variety of automated features
in the new version, which makes it easier to revisit favorite Web
sites, to fill out forms, and to conduct searches for information
on line.
</P>
<P>
   Searching has been organized with buttons specifically for
finding people, finding Web sites, finding news groups, finding
maps, and so on. A ``next'' button enables the user to cycle
through different search engines if the first pass does not yield
the desired results.
</P>
<P>
   A search button has even been added to the ``history'' list of
previously visited Web sites. There are many times I can remember
seeing a nugget of information somewhere on a Web site I have
visited, but cannot remember which one. By entering a key word, one
can search through just the previously visited sites. Very handy.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also borrowed a clever feature from Netscape
Navigator, the ability to search for related links. For example, if
I'm viewing this newspaper's Web site at www.nytimes.com, and click
on ``show related links'' under the version 5.0 tools menu, I get a
list of sites belonging to other major newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Although the updated version has lots of new productivity
enhancements, the radio features are the most fun. Computers cannot
do as good a job with radio as radios can, and a television set is
still better at showing video. But computers do have special
skills, like pulling in radio stations from halfway around the
world, or downloading movie clips to watch over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   By clicking on version 5.0's new radio toolbar (click ``views,''
then ``toolbars,'' then ``radio''), I was able to choose from an
eclectic assortment of radio stations from around the world, most
of which delivered their signals as streams of digital bits over
the Internet, which were then converted to analogue sounds pumped
through my computer's stereo speakers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the preset radio links worked, a problem Microsoft
promised would be fixed by today, and woe to the Internet user
whose favorite stations, like mine, include such overlooked gems as
WOI-FM in Ames, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   I also used Explorer 5.0 and the Windows Media Player to listen
to old radio dramas _ the kind where, in our imaginations, the
villains neither sounded nor looked anything like Bill Gates,
Microsoft's co-founder and principal owner.
</P>
<P>
   In the current federal antitrust trial, Gates is being portrayed
by the government as the villain who sought to crush Netscape, a
competitor, by making Internet Explorer a seemingly inextricable
part of the Windows operating system, thereby unfairly leveraging
its Windows monopoly to gain market share for its browser.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft argues that Internet Explorer and other utilities
merely add value and convenience for its customers. And now
Microsoft is adding more value at an even deeper level, inside the
browser that itself is inside the operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Clicking on Explorer 5.0's radio buttons brings up Microsoft's
Windows Media Player. And by assembling the lists of radio
stations, Microsoft has invaded the turf of Internet radio and
video companies like Broadcast.com, thus generating instant rivals.
And so it goes.
</P>
<P>
   The browser is becoming the operating system of the Internet
age, and it, too, will inevitably become bloated with built-in
search engines, security tools, electronic payment systems, text
translators and whatever other new utilities become important as
the Internet grows.
</P>
<P>
   From a consumer perspective, having these tools tightly
integrated, and free, in the operating system and browser makes
computers easier and more enjoyable to use. The nice thing is that
one is also free to choose other tools like Navigator, Real Player,
Quicktime, and Broadcast.com.
</P>
<P>
   For regulators, the challenge is to make sure that the companies
that make the rival tools have a fair chance to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Internet radio is not new, of course. What is new is the easy
listening that Explorer 5.0's new radio buttons allow. However, to
take advantage of the radio functions, the user must install the
Windows Media Player, a free utility that launches automatically
when the browser sucks down a multimedia file.
</P>
<P>
   It also helps to have a fast Internet connection, like the cable
modem I'm lucky to have. When I tried listening to radio stations
via a 28.8 kilobit-per-second modem, it was slow death. The
stations that were loud and clear on my fast desktop machine were
wretched on the slow connection. A 56-kilobit modem is almost a
minimum requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Even if one never uses Explorer 5.0 for radio, it is still worth
getting, especially because it is free. I've been using a nearly
final copy of it for a couple of weeks without any serious (i.e.
harmful) glitches. But it is a new program, after all, and bugs are
bound to surface even though it has been tested for months by tens
of thousands of Microsoft's human laboratory mice. As with any new
software, be sure to back up your important files before loading
it.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft and its chief rival Netscape (soon to be a part of
America Online) have been playing leapfrog with their respective
Web browsers for several years, a competition that has been of
particular interest to the Justice Department in recent months.
From a consumer perspective, the competition has been a boon.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape's latest version, Navigator 4.51 (www.netscape.com) is
quite good and has some unique features, like Instant Messenger
2.0, which allows Web users to type real-time messages back and
forth with friends who are on line at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape is planning to release its own version 5.0 browser in a
few months, so Microsoft's current advantage may be only temporary.
As of today, however, the new Internet Explorer is the top frog.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
