<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4081 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      03-17 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LESLIE LAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Building Up Bulbs and Bulblets
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have more than two bushels of tuberoses, single and double.
Most have a larger center bulb surrounded by 10 or 20 bulblets. How
should they be divided? I don't get that many flowers, even though
I do get them in early.
</P>
<P>
   A. The wonderfully fragrant tuberose, Polianthes tuberosa, is
native to Mexico and does best when it has a long, hot summer in
which to grow.
</P>
<P>
   When you plant one of the large bulbs in spring, it spends most
of its energy producing a stalk of flowers. Anything left over goes
into the creation of daughter bulbs, the ones around the edge,
while the main bulb usually splits in two.
</P>
<P>
   As with most bulbs, energy for next year's flowers is gathered
by this year's leaves, but it takes a very long, warm growing
season _ think in the 70s in November _ for one year's leaves to
restore the strength of that hard-working central bulb. Because the
daughter bulbs have fewer leaves, they take at least a couple of
long-summered years to reach blooming size.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't mind running a tuberose farm, you can rebuild the
central bulb and grow out the bulblets. Under optimum conditions,
all will reach or recover blooming size in two or three years.
Separate the small bulbs from the larger one, and from each other.
Plant them after the weather has warmed, about 2 inches deep, 3 or
4 inches apart, in well-drained, highly fertile soil. (Larger bulbs
should be 3 inches deep and 6 inches apart.) Let the tuberoses grow
undisturbed all summer, being sure to water regularly, then dig
them up in fall before the greens are destroyed by frost.
</P>
<P>
   Brush off extra soil and set the plants indoors, where they will
be warm and dry, and let the leaves wither, then cut them off.
Store the dormant bulbs in peat moss in a dark place, at about 60
degrees. Repeat each year until the bulbs are at least the size of
ping pong balls, by which time they should be ready to flower.
</P>
<P>
   Tuberoses are not the only bulbs that behave this way.
Acidanthera, the Abyssinian gladiolus, is another daughter-maker
that usually fails to rebloom. It, too, can be increased by the
method described above, but most gardeners find it easier just to
buy new bulbs each year. Tuberoses are available from Park Seed, 1
Parkton Ave., Greenwood, S.C. 29647, (800) 845-3369, catalog free;
and Old House Gardens, 536 Third St., Ann Arbor, Mich. 48103, (734)
995-1486, catalog $2.
</P>
<P>
   Rewriting a Ritual
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'm in the early stages of the annual rite of starting a
number of vegetables from seed, transplanting the seedlings to
small pots in a few weeks, transplanting these to larger pots in a
few more weeks, and, finally, setting my plants in the garden.
Numerous gardening books recommend this ritual, yet plants don't
seem to mind the final transfer to the garden, a very large pot
indeed. Why can't I immediately transplant each seedling to a
fairly large pot, saving time and avoiding excess plant handling?
</P>
<P>
   A. There are a couple of reasons to go through the ritual. One
is that it conserves space. Whether on the windowsill, under lights
or even in a greenhouse, most home gardeners have only a limited
area where the light is bright enough for good seedling growth, and
they don't want to waste it on empty pot surface.
</P>
<P>
   The other reason to keep the plant in proportion to its
container is the danger of damp off. This fungus disease, which is
encouraged by large expanses of bare, damp soil, attacks the tender
stems of baby plants and can kill them overnight. The spores are
everywhere, so damp off is a danger even when you start out with a
sterile potting mix.
</P>
<P>
   You might want to compromise by skipping the middle step-up for
fast growers like tomatoes. And if you've got lots of growing space
there's nothing to prevent you from trying it with everything you
grow.
</P>
<P>
   Start a larger than usual number of seeds, then hold back a few
seedlings of each variety in the original starting pots. If the
transplants damp off, they'll probably do it fairly soon, and
you'll have backup seedlings. If the transplants do well, all
you've lost is those few extra seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Pruning and Pruning
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can you tell me the difference between ``pruning hard'' and
``prune dead wood only?''
</P>
<P>
   A. Pruning hard has different meanings depending on the plant
being pruned, but it always involves cutting away a fair amount of
living tissue. To give a few examples, hard pruning might be done
to rejuvenate an overgrown rosebush (as the canes grow old and
woody, they put out less bloom). It might be done to reshape a
straggly-looking forsythia, to keep a wisteria from eating your
house alive or to improve fruit quality by limiting the output of a
grapevine.
</P>
<P>
   Pruning dead wood, on the other hand, isn't really pruning at
all; it's just cleaning up. Dead wood is removed to keep plants
good looking and to keep them open to light and air. (Pruning to
fight disease is another story altogether.)
</P>
<P>
   Most summer-flowering shrubs and deciduous trees are pruned
while plants are still dormant. Though it's easier to see what's
dead and what isn't after growth has resumed, it's easier to remove
dead wood without damaging anything else when there's no new growth
in the way. As for hard pruning, you do it so that the plant will
put its energy into the parts that are left; letting it make lots
of stems and leaves right before you cut them off wastes the energy
it took to produce them.
</P>
<P>
   When in doubt about what's dead and what's not, scrape off a bit
of bark with a fingernail or knife. Living branches will be green
underneath.
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to:
</P>
<P>
   Garden Q&AMP;A
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times
</P>
<P>
   229 W. 43rd St.
</P>
<P>
   New York, N.Y. 10036
</P>
<P>
   or by e-mail to:
</P>
<P>
   gardening(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished
questions cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
