<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDTV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE COLLAR CHIC ON THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ed and Ray Pekurny are not what you would call stylish dudes.
Ed's idea of an accessory is the beer bottle hanging around his
neck. Ray wants to own a gym, and he has the gross tank tops and
baggy sweats to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew McConaughey and Woody Harrelson play the blue-collar
Pekurny brothers in Ron Howard's new movie, ``EDtv,'' which opens
on March 26. Part ``The Truman Show,'' part Bud Lite commercial,
this amiable romantic comedy imagines what would happen if a cable
network trained its cameras on a Regular Guy 24 hours a day and
turned his life into the ultimate reality-television show.
</P>
<P>
   Ed is a video clerk, his girlfriend works for UPS, and his
mother and wheelchair-bound stepfather live in a fixed-income
museum of clutter. And yet, despite the characters' low-rent
lifestyles, their apartments are all flawlessly decorated showrooms
of retro cool and recherche kitsch from the '60s and '70s. Ray has
a Jetsonian leather sofa that any space-age bachelor would envy.
The textured wallpaper in Ed's parents' place could be a page in
Wallpaper. Ed's own walls are adorned with dozens of artfully
displayed hubcaps. Collecting mundane objects to create a design
``concept'' is the oldest decorator trick in the book. But how did
this lummox come up with it?
</P>
<P>
   Of course he didn't. Merideth Boswell, the set decorator, did.
She bought the sofa, picked out the wallpaper, arranged the
hubcaps. No Hollywood movie in its right mind wants too much
verisimilitude. And few production design people can resist
imposing their upscale esthetic on even the most downscale
characters, said Jeannine Oppewal, the production designer for
``L.A. Confidential.'' Ms. Oppewal owned up to it herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this urge, because of one's design training, to make
things neater, to organize and make things more graphic for camera
purposes,'' she said. Can that urge be resisted, or at least toned
down? ``You need to put on your antidesign hat to get so-called
working class environments correct,'' Ms. Oppewal added.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe _ just maybe _ Ed would have done the wall of chrome.
But there is no way Ray went out and bought the reflecting metal
sculpture hanging above his sofa. In a brightly lighted feel-good
comedy like ``EDtv,'' it's OK for the jokes from a guy like Ray to
be in bad taste. But bad taste is not OK for his living room.
</P>
<P>
   To research the look of the movie, Ms. Boswell and the
production designer, Michael Corenblith, visited the
rent-controlled apartments of some real San Francisco video clerks.
Faithfully recreating those dumps was out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a fine line that we walk here,'' Corenblith said. ``An
audience has expectations for the quality of the environment around
these movie stars. We couldn't simply transplant them into the
actual environment of the video-store clerks that we found. I'm
trying to create interesting possibilities for the
cinematographer.''
</P>
<P>
   Furnishing those possibilities was Ms. Boswell's job. She
scoured flea markets, junk shops and Salvation Army stores in San
Francisco, Los Angeles and Petaluma. ``I tried to stay out of the
trendy '60s stores,'' she said. She wanted to stick to what the
characters in the movie could afford. A lot of her shopping hours
were spent at a Los Angeles junk emporium called the House of Paul,
where she found the coveted Dansk fondue set and Danish-modern
dining set in Ed's parents apartment. Ms. Boswell confessed to
having spent $1,500 for Ray's hipster couch, but with a rationale.
``I think it would have been important for a guy like him to go out
and find the perfect make-out couch,'' she said. Ray's girlfriend
dumps him for Ed, after the prying cameras of ``EDtv'' catch Ray
cheating on her.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, only a design pro might have noticed the
devilishly clever details in a movie like ``EDtv.'' But with the
current mania for home furnishings, everybody is an armchair
decorator and every ``look'' has been co-opted. ``It's hard to do a
farmhouse now without it looking like Ralph Lauren or Martha
Stewart,'' Ms. Boswell said. Even with the ugliest '70s decor in
the movie, she said, ``It's so hard to not look like you went to
the hot shopping place.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Ed's elaborately hubcapped walls, Ms. Boswell said: ``Ed
was a guy with a lot of time on his hands. I liked the idea that he
had done a sort of installation piece with hubcaps.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed doesn't really seem like an installation type of guy. In the
movie, the design innovation he's most proud of is a mirror inside
the lid of his laundry hamper that allows him to keep watching the
football game on television in the living room even when he's in
the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's realism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
