<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4148 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-WOMEN-PLAYWRIGH     03-17 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-WOMEN-PLAYWRIGHTS-ART-3TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK WOMEN PLAYWRIGHTS: A SELDOM-HEARD VOICE ON BROADWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 21)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By FELICIA R. LEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was a cold Thursday afternoon and the world of
Thulani Davis was a spare, softly lighted stage at the Joseph Papp
Public Theater. Ms. Davis' play ``Everybody's Ruby'' was in
rehearsals, with Phylicia Rashad as the writer Zora Neale Hurston
and Viola Davis as Ruby McCollum, a black woman in a small Florida
town who killed a prominent white doctor in the early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Viola Davis' monologue about being raped by the doctor was
etched with muted fury and weariness. The director, Kenny Leon, had
her deliver it from several vantage points on the stage as the
playwright listened, took notes and nibbled at a mix of cottage
cheese and fruit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do you go to learn to do this?'' Ms. Davis had said
earlier, referring to the relatively small number of black
playwrights whose work is seen in this country. ``It's totally like
playing tennis. How many tennis courts are there in black
neighborhoods?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ms. Davis, whose play runs through April 11 at the
Public Theater, belongs to a small subset of a small universe: she
is a working African-American woman playwright.
</P>
<P>
   In this 40th-anniversary year of the opening of Lorraine
Hansberry's ``Raisin in the Sun,'' the first commercially produced
straight play by a black woman dramatist on Broadway, the moment
seemed appropriate to ask why the generations that have followed
her have not, for the most part, reached that level _ as
distinguished from the world of musicals and comedy. The picture
that emerges from a series of interviews with members of this small
subset and others in the theater is one of a glass either half full
or half empty.
</P>
<P>
   While it is true that black women playwrights are being produced
in major off-Broadway and regional theaters, they have yet to
obtain the kind of consistent, high-profile presence and voice
accorded African-American women today in popular music and fiction
writing.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons offered for why there is no female equivalent, for
example, of the eminent black playwright August Wilson on Broadway
have to do not only with the vagaries of an outsize talent but also
the difficulties that have always faced women _ but especially
black and other minority women _ in the theater.
</P>
<P>
   They include what has become a truism in recent years, that
straight plays do not attract Broadway audiences, and that to do so
successfully they have to offer broad themes that mass audiences
can relate to; that a number of small theaters that nurtured
talent, both black and white, have closed at a time when government
financial support for the arts is dwindling; that there is a
perception of artistic and financial risk in mounting plays by
blacks and women; that in the male-dominated theater world, women
have traditionally had difficulty finding mentors and producers.
Also mentioned is the dearth of mainstream black critics to
understand and interpret what they see, as well as the biases of
the white men who remain, by and large, the main arbiters of
culture in this country.
</P>
<P>
   According to figures compiled by the Women's Project and
Productions, a nonprofit theater company created to promote the
work of women playwrights and directors, between 1985 and 1995,
women wrote 7 percent of the new plays produced on Broadway and 17
percent of those on off-Broadway (the figures were not broken down
annually by race). Within the project's own walls, during the
1998-99 season, 7 percent of the play readings put on were works by
African-American women who submitted 4 percent of the scripts in
the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays by black women writers that made the transfer to
Broadway from their origins in the nonprofit world were ``For
Colored Girls Who Have Considered Suicide/When the Rainbow Is
Enuf'' by Ntozake Shange in 1976 and ``Twilight: Los Angeles 1992''
by Anna Deavere Smith in 1994, both from the Public Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith, who is working on a post-impeachment version of her
play ``House Arrest,'' about the institution of the presidency,
said the absence of black women playwrights in the foreground of
American theater reflects a broader cultural gap. As much as white
Americans are still bewildered by black women _ ``Is she the mammy
or Angela Davis?'' _ they are still waiting to hear her voice, Ms.
Smith believes.
</P>
<P>
   There is a psychic tension between African-American women and
the rest of the culture,'' Ms. Smith said. ``There is not the
outlaw mythology in the theater. In music, there is room for Lauryn
Hill,'' the pop hip-hopper. ``I think the black woman is still an
outlaw, even as Cheryl Mills'' _ a black lawyer and member of
President Clinton's legal defense team _ ``goes to speak for the
president. This business about who we are has not been settled.
There are more black people in the middle class, but we haven't
healed our psychic wounds. As artists, we haven't done enough to
tap into that despair.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
