<HEADER>
A4149 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRAUD18-COX     03-17 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRAUD18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STUDY SAYS CONSUMERS BEING RIPPED OFF AT A FASTER CLIP
 &HT;    640&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One in six Americans reported being the victim of
major consumer fraud last year, with the elderly, the poor, and the
uneducated the most vulnerable, according to a study released
Wednesday by AARP.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, there is no level playing field for consumers,'' said
Anne Harvey, director of program development for AARP, formerly the
American Association of Retired Persons. ``Consumers are forced to
play by unfair rules hidden in fine print.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer vulnerability to fraud has increased from 14 percent to
17 percent since the last AARP study in 1993. The rapidly changing
marketplace, with new products and services and more information,
is responsible for the increase in vulnerability, said Katie Smith
Sloan, an AARP consumer expert.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 study by the Princeton Survey Research Associates
surveyed 1,500 adults nationwide on their consumer behavior and
experiences with fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest area of fraud was in the purchase and repair of
automobiles, with one out of six victims saying they had been
ripped off in these types of transactions. Other areas of abuse
included being overcharged for products and services, or being
misled by false advertising _ nearly one out of 10 victims.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer participants claimed they were scammed by mail order and
Internet fraud or credit card fraud. About 1 percent said they had
been the victims of bogus charity donation scams.
</P>
<P>
   The study used a consumer vulnerability index to determine how
susceptible Americans were to fraud. The level of the respondents'
vulnerability was gauged by their responses to questions on
consumer rights and protections. The survey also looked at how
knowledgeable Americans were about business practices and
investments in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   The responses indicated that 79 percent of those surveyed were
somewhat vulnerable to fraud, while 13 percent were not very
vulnerable. It also indicated that 44 percent of adults ages 18 to
49 had very low to low consumer vulnerability, and 28 percent were
knowledgeable about investments.
</P>
<P>
   The study revealed that older Americans are less knowledgeable,
with 26 percent of adults 65 and older having little to no
knowledge about investments in the marketplace. AARP said those
with little investment knowledge were more vulnerable to fraud and
bad buying experiences.
</P>
<P>
   According to the study, 64 percent of males 75 years or older,
and 70 percent of females 75 years and older were vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   But the survey found that the 50- to 64-year-old group was the
most likely to feel victimized. It found that 23 percent of
consumers in that age group felt they had been the victim of a
major fraud or swindle, and 72 percent had a bad buying experience
within the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Other variables that affected the level of vulnerability were
education and income. Respondents with a higher education or those
earning more per year were typically more knowledgeable about
investments and less vulnerable to scams than those with less
education and a lower annual income.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of the respondents surveyed, 94 percent, said they
took action as a result of fraud or a bad buying experience. The
study showed that 85 percent complained to a company or
salesperson, 81 percent stopped buying from a company, 80 percent
asked for a refund or replacement, and 76 percent told family and
friends not to buy from the company again.
</P>
<P>
   However, the survey also indicated that consumers failed to take
their complaints any further. Only 34 percent complained to the
Better Business Bureau, 19 percent sought assistance from a state
attorney general's office, and one in 20 complained to a federal
agency like the Federal Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The study shows that consumers do not necessarily know where
to go to get help,'' said Greg Marchildon, an AARP spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Marchildon added that often big business makes it very difficult
for consumers to get answers about a bad purchase or service. He
said the only way to make the system work is for consumers to
complain when they feel they have been cheated.
</P>
<P>
   The study also showed that consumers were more suspicious of
some industries than others. Consumers were most suspicious of used
car dealers and companies that sell products over the phone, and
least suspicious of drug stores and companies that sell hearing
aids.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers between the ages of 18 and 49 were most suspicious of
used car dealers, while those between the ages of 50 to 64 and
those over 65 were most suspicious of companies that sell products
over the phone. A majority, 58 percent, of respondents 18 to 49
years old said they mistrusted stores that rent furniture, while
almost half, 48 percent, of those surveyed over 65 years were
suspicious of funeral homes.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also looked at how much consumers trusted businesses
with their confidential financial information. It found that less
than half, 38 percent, trusted their main financial institutions,
26 percent trusted their insurance companies, 20 percent trusted
their supermarkets, and 14 percent trusted their credit card
companies with their confidential information.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
