<HEADER>
A4150 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-WOMEN-PLAYWRIGH     03-17 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-WOMEN-PLAYWRIGHTS-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADv21-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: that despair.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ms. Smith, 48, the author of such critically acclaimed works as
``Fires in the Mirror,'' about racial unrest in Crown Heights,
Brooklyn, and ``Twilight: Los Angeles 1992,'' about riots in that
city, is a professor at Stanford University and the founder and
director of the Institute on the Arts and Civic Dialogue at Harvard
University.
</P>
<P>
   In her case, she said, she has had to turn to the academic
community rather than the theater community to find kindred
spirits. ``There are no great numbers of black women producers and
directors,'' she emphasized. ``In our post-1960's theater
community, we have not come up with an atmosphere where we can
create alliances and understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the work of new generations of black women playwrights like
Ms. Davis, Pearl Cleage, Kia Corthron, Lynn Nottage, Suzan-Lori
Parks and Cheryl L. West has been produced in New York at nonprofit
theaters like the Public, the Manhattan Theater Club and
Playwrights Horizons, as well as at regional theaters in
Washington, Atlanta, Chicago, Houston and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Corthron, 36, just returned from London, where her play
``Splash Hatch on the E Going Down,'' involving a pregnant black
teen-ager and a plea for saving the environment, was produced as
part of a festival of American plays at the Donmar Warehouse. On
this side of the Atlantic, she has been criticized for being
didactic and praised for her sense of poetic rhythm and imagery.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are tons of playwrights out there,'' said George C.
Wolfe, the producer of the Public Theater, mentioning Ms. Davis and
Ms. Parks, whose work, including ``The America Play,'' has also
been presented at the theater. ``But Broadway shouldn't be a
barometer. The Broadway of Lorraine Hansberry doesn't exist
anymore. It has a peculiar, precarious commercial reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Mordecai has helped bring a number of August Wilson
plays to Broadway as a commercial producer, as he did Ms. Smith's
``Twilight: Los Angeles 1992.'' In the current climate, Mordecai
said, where the only new American play running on Broadway is
``Side Man'' by Warren Leight, which transferred from the nonprofit
Roundabout Theater, an American play needs a major star or a cast
of stars to have broad appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Broadway is a kind of unique marketplace,'' Mordecai said.
``You have to think: Are there elements in this work that will be
attractive to 6,000 to 8,000 people each week? That's not an
evaluation of the play. The fact that August Wilson is a black
writer is an asset. You have people who like serious plays and also
people interested in plays by African-Americans. I think if there
were a black woman who wrote a play that had broad appeal to it, it
could easily go to Broadway. But almost all American playwrights
now are writing plays that don't have that broad appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe said he did not look to any of the traditional measures of
a playwright's success _ a production by a major nonprofit New York
theater, or a Tony Award from commercial Broadway _ because they
are part of a system that writers in the theater today are
circumventing. It is his impression, he said, that more black women
are making names for themselves at regional theaters rather than
following the traditional route of having a hit in New York, with
regional theaters subsequently asking to produce the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The success of `For Colored Girls' reflects a more generous
era,'' Wolfe said. ``Once upon a time, people felt a responsibility
to know other people's stories. We had lost that, but I think now
people are again interested. There is a diversification of the
power structure going on in American theater. The system is opening
up, the process is opening up. It's a slow process and we're living
through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of those interviewed were in agreement that American
culture does not seem as interested in black women as in black men
and white men and women, except in the areas of pop music and in
fiction since the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   The work of black women playwrights, some said, is still viewed
as particularized, even politically correct, rather than being seen
as among any one of a number of theatrical experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a psychological struggle being waged and it's about
who represents America,'' said Cassandra Medley, a dramatist who
teaches playwriting at Sarah Lawrence College. ``When you get down
to what represents America, you are looking at Tennessee Williams,
Arthur Miller, Edward Albee and John Guare. That's the underlying
assumption of English-speaking theaters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that nothing happens,'' Ms. Medley said. ``What
doesn't happen is the ongoing attention to numbers, variety and the
mosaic of viewpoints that need to be heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Sanford, the artistic director of Playwrights Horizons,
where Ms. Nottage's hostage drama ``Mud, River, Stone,'' was
presented last year to mixed reviews, said: ``Why don't we see more
black women in New York? There are a lot of young writers of all
races who don't get produced in New York. It's a larger question as
to what the climate is in New York. You can get killed here.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl L. West, whose play ``Jar the Floor,'' about four
generations of African-American women, is scheduled to begin
previews at Second Stage on July 27, is a case in point. A 1992
Public Theater production of her play about AIDS, ``Before It Hits
Home,'' did so poorly that she decided to avoid the city altogether
and said so publicly.
</P>
<P>
   When her play ``Holiday Heart,'' about an adolescent and the
transvestite who looks after her, opened at the Manhattan Theater
Club in 1995, it received mixed notices. Since then, her work has
been in demand regionally, but the accepted wisdom is that failure
in New York can break a fledgling career.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
