<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4152 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-WOMEN-PLAYWRIGH     03-17 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-WOMEN-PLAYWRIGHTS-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: fledgling career.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ms. Davis' current drama, ``Everybody's Ruby,'' also received
mixed reviews when it opened March 8, with critics singling out
Viola Davis' performance for high praise. The playwright, the
author of two novels and two librettos for operas with music by her
cousin Anthony Davis, ``X: The Life and Times of Malcolm X'' and
``Amistad,'' sees the emergence of black women in the theater world
as in some ways reflecting the journey of blacks and women out of
segregation.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Davis, 49, recalled growing up in segregated Hampton, Va.,
and at age 12 integrating a theater club in Washington. Within the
New York theater community in the 1970s, she said, she met
hostility from whites because of her race and from black men
because of her sex. She survived by becoming a journalist and by
learning an array of theater skills, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think things have changed terribly much,'' Ms. Davis
added. ``I think black playwrights in general have to have a
relationship with a theater to get their scripts read. For years,
theaters have looked at doing black playwrights as a charitable
work.''
</P>
<P>
   The playwright and poet Adrienne Kennedy, 67, a visiting
professor at Harvard University and one of the black female
doyennes of theater, where she has become a role model for a
younger generation, was the subject of a yearlong celebration of
her work by the Signature Theater Company in 1995-96. Ms. Kennedy
said recently that she does not see the overall situation
improving.
</P>
<P>
   ``People seem reluctant to invest sums of money to put black
women playwrights onstage,'' she said. Mentioning that the late
Joseph Papp was her mentor and that her work, which includes
``Funnyhouse of a Negro'' and, with a son, ``Sleep Deprivation
Chamber,'' has found a home primarily in the academic world, she
said: ``The forces really have to come together. A person has to
somehow have those connections. Black women are left out of the
connections.''
</P>
<P>
   In her own case, she said, her plays were often turned down by
theaters that felt ``they'd appeal to only half the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   There are harbingers of a new audience. George Wachtel of
Audience Research and Analysis, an independent market research
company in Manhattan, said there has been a marked growth recently
in ethnic diversity among New York theatergoers under the age of
35. He attributed it to changing demographics _ the New York
population is increasingly Hispanic, black and Asian _ and the
appeal of Broadway shows like the Public Theater's recent ``Bring
In da Noise, Bring In da Funk,'' which traced the black experience
in America through music and dance, and ``Freak,'' the
semiautobiographical show by the Hispanic actor and comedian John
Leguizamo about growing up as a member of a minority in New York.
</P>
<P>
   On Broadway, Wachtel said, 1 out of every 5 playgoers ages 18 to
24 is nonwhite and 22 percent of those ages 25 to 34 are nonwhite,
compared with the total African-American audience on Broadway of
3.7 percent. Off-Broadway, 1 in 4 theatergoers ages 18 to 24 is
nonwhite, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A growing audience appetite for diversity and the desire of
women playwrights to have their work seen have resulted in various
forms of talent showcases. In February, the Ensemble Studio Theater
produced a two-week festival of staged readings by seven black
women playwrights, ranging from Ms. Cleage to lesser-known authors.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Women of Color Productions, a production company, enters
its third and final week of a festival of plays, readings, musicals
and films in association with the Playwrights Project at the Henry
Street Settlement, La Mama and Theater at the Riverside Church. The
festival, which is being presented at all three sites, includes the
work of more than 35 artists.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cleage, one of the best-known black women playwrights, with
13 plays to her name, said she has never felt the need for
Broadway. She lives in Atlanta and first found a home in black
theaters around the country with plays like ``Blues for an Alabama
Sky,'' about four friends in the summer of 1930. Her play ``Flyin'
West,'' about black women who traveled west during Reconstruction,
had its debut in 1992 at the Alliance Theater in Atlanta, where
Leon, who is directing Ms. Davis' play at the Public, is the
artistic director.
</P>
<P>
   ``Broadway is not even part of the reality of my life,'' said
Ms. Cleage, 50, who recently saw her first novel, ``What Looks Like
Crazy on an Ordinary Day,'' become an Oprah Book Club selection and
make the New York Times paperback best-seller list. ``Broadway is
probably not even the best audience for me. It's not the best place
to talk to people about change _ about changing the gender order,
about changing the racial order.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we getting our due in the big white theaters? What do they
owe us? I don't think any adult owes any adult,'' Ms. Cleage said.
``The question is how do we strengthen our own work and strengthen
our own institutions? There's a whole universe for us to work in as
black women.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nottage, who is based in New York, conceded that she has
been fortunate as a dramatist but still believes New York is
``extremely difficult.'' She has, she said, developed the kinds of
key relationships that elude so many black playwrights: with Second
Stage, where she received a commission as part of a grant; with the
Yale Repertory Theater, as a graduate of the Yale School of Drama;
and with the African-American writers' group at Playwrights
Horizons.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an African-American I would never think of Broadway,'' Ms.
Nottage said. ``The Hansberry play wasn't a breakthrough for
African-American women. It was an anomaly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
