<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS ITEMS ON COMPUTERS AND GADGETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   No Father of Computing, But Maybe He's an Uncle &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Vice President Al Gore said in an interview on CNN last
week that he ``took the initiative in creating the Internet,''
Republicans wasted no time ridiculing the assertion. Sen. Trent
Lott, the majority leader, announced that he himself invented the
paper clip, and Rep. Dick Armey, the House majority leader, laid
claim to the Interstate highway system.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Gore's political foes mocked him, a group of computer
scientists, policy makers and others who have worked with Gore over
the years quickly leaped to his defense. Gore, of course, did not
create the Internet but, his defenders say, he helped lift the
Internet from relative obscurity and turn it into a widely
accessible, commercial network.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was absolutely instrumental,'' said Steve Wolff, executive
director of the Advanced Internet Initiatives Division at Cisco
Systems in Washington. Wolff worked closely with Gore and his aides
in the early 1990s, when he was at the National Science Foundation.
``Although he exercised a certain amount of hyperbole,'' Wolff
said, ``his contributions were a lot more than many of his
colleagues in the Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolff was referring to the years Gore spent in Congress, then as
vice president, when he promoted technological advancements in
general, and the Internet in particular. While a senator, Gore
sponsored legislation that promoted high-performance computing and
networking projects. Gore's defenders also point out that he was
the first to popularize the phrase ``information superhighway.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing he did was champion the use of the
Internet,'' said Tony Rutkowski, an Internet consultant who was an
executive at Sprint in the early 1990s. ``He established a whole
dynamic that not only was in the government, but around the world.
Every place he went, he made the Internet popular. There was really
no one else at the time who had that kind of visibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the vice president's defenders sent their messages
through cyberspace. The electronic rush to Gore's defense
illustrated yet again the power of the Internet. ``It's not always
good because the Internet spreads stuff fast whether it's good,
bad, reliable, rumor or fact,'' Wolff said. ``But in this
particular case, it was a chance to set the record straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Katie Hafner &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IBM Conventional Monitor Will Challenge Flat Models &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For desktop computers, the trade-off for bigger monitors comes
down to a choice between less desk space and a lot less money. The
designers at IBM say they may have a solution: a new 19-inch
monitor that is moderately priced and uses conventional cathode ray
tube technology but takes up little more desktop real estate than a
15-inch monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Released last week, IBM's new monitor, the G96, offers a viewing
area that is 17.9 by 16.7 inches; it has an anti-reflective screen,
a short neck, a maximum resolution of 1,600 by 1,200 and a refresh
rate of 75 hertz.
</P>
<P>
   Its dot pitch is 0.25 millimeters, and it comes in two colors:
black and white. IBM spokesmen also note that the monitor has an
estimated street price of $599, a lot less than the $3,000 price
tag many flat-panel monitors carry.
</P>
<P>
   Michel Marriott &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Geocities Encourages Members To Make Their Web Pages Pay &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GeoCities is now offering a program that turns personal Web
sites into something like virtual Tupperware parties where hosts
earn a percentage of purchases made through their pages. The
program, called Pages that Pay
(http://www.geocities.com/pagesthatpay/), is available only to
people who have set up home pages on GeoCities, a Web-site
community of 3.5-million members.
</P>
<P>
   GeoCities members can make money by creating links to company
Web sites; they earn commissions on purchases that result. More
than 15 companies are participating, including Barnesandnoble.com,
Egghead.com, and MSN Expedia.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   About 120,000 affiliate relationships between GeoCities' members
and participating companies have been registered in the program's
first week. Commissions range from 4 percent to 33 percent of the
cost of items purchased after a customer goes from a Geocities
member's page to a merchant's link although a few arrangements are
based on clicks alond.
</P>
<P>
   For example, participants pocket 10 cents for every person who
clicks from their site to Expedia, and they earn 2 cents per search
on GoTo.Com.
</P>
<P>
   GeoCities cuts a check for the commissions every three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``This takes the terrestial world model of multi-level marketing
and puts a finer point on it,'' says Bruce J. Zanca, a GeoCities
spokesman. Of course, even if no one else visits their site,
Web-site creators can earn refunds on their own purchases simply by
clicking through their own pages. The merchants seem prepared to
live with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have no identity police at the computer terminal,''
says John D. Hough, a spokesman for Egghead.com. ``What we're
interested in is incremental sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Guernsey &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Least One Oscar Nominee Is Comfortable in Cyberspace &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Movie fans who don't want to line up for this year's Oscar
nominees can turn to a smaller screen. ``Bunny,'' one of the five
films nominated in the animated short film category, is being
broadcast over the Internet through Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shorts in general are hard to see,'' said Jeff Scher, an
adjunct professor of film at the School of the Arts at Columbia
University. ``There's no commercial venue, except for festivals or
museum collections.'' The Web broadcast is a first in the short
film category, a spokesman for the American Academy of Arts and
Sciences said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bunny'' is a seven-minute story about a rabbit's battle with a
moth who has invaded her kitchen. The film was written and directed
by Chris Wedge, the creative director of Blue Sky Studios, which
makes animation effects for television commercials and feature
films.
</P>
<P>
   Wedge said that the impetus for his film was mostly creative,
but the process went hand in hand with the company's development of
software to create more realistic lighting effects. ``Our
simulation takes into account the complexity of light as it is
reflected off of different surfaces,'' Wedge said. ``For example,
when you step from the curb onto the grass on a bright day, it
looks natural to your eyes. On a computer, we have to create a
program and apply it to the rendered image.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bunny'' will be broadcast daily through March 24 at
www.bunny.blueskystudios.com, at 11 a.m. and 1, 3, 5, 7, 8 and 10
p.m., Eastern standard time.
</P>
<P>
   Shelly Freierman &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AN IOMEGA HAZARD Iomega is recalling about 60,000 external Jaz
disk drives because of a potential electrical hazard. The problem,
the company said in a release issued along with the federal
Consumer Product Safety Commission, is that the housing for the
drives' power supply units can split, exposing the electronics
inside.
</P>
<P>
   The faulty units were sold with Jaz two-gigabyte drives,
remanufactured Jaz one-gigabyte drives and as replacements power
supply units. Consumers can exchange their units by calling Iomega
at 800-781-3296 or going to www.iomega.com, the company's Web
site. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Instant Postcards And Fast Food &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Say (italics)cheeeese(end italics) _ burger!
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Peter Allen Abramson, a Burger King franchisee who
turned his Manhattan restaurant into the world's first cyber-burger
joint, augmented his bank of 20 Internet-surfing computers with
five Big Picture video cameras from the 3Com Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The cameras, linked to the Internet through special high-speed
lines that are also supplied by 3Com, enable munchers to zap their
images _ in the form of an e-mail post card _ to anywhere that the
World Wide Web reaches.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Clemmons, vice president of consumer marketing for 3Com,
called the idea ``revolutionary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
