<SLUG> BC-COPS-BLACKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACKS ACCOUNT FOR MANY POLICE COMPLAINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ African-Americans file 27 percent of complaints
against the San Francisco police even though they make up only 11
percent of the city's population, according to a new report by the
Office of Citizen Complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage, included in the OCC's 1998 annual report,
``raises a still unanswered cluster of questions as to how and why
African-Americans experience and report police misconduct to OCC at
a rate that is consistently, substantially higher that their share
of the population,'' OCC Director Mary Dunlap wrote in the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the explanatory factors prove to be ... there is a
persistent, substantial disparity,'' Dunlap said. ``The answers
must be sought.''
</P>
<P>
   The OCC, an independent police watchdog agency in San Francisco,
primarily investigates individual cases of alleged wrongdoing by
officers. Dunlap said that this was the third year in a row in
which the rate of complaints by blacks was more than their
percentage of the population. Dunlap believes San Francisco should
look at broader factors behind the trend.
</P>
<P>
   Whites, who make up about 47 percent of the city's population,
filed 33 percent of the complaints. Meanwhile, Hispanics filed 11
percent and Asians filed 7 percent of complaints. Hispanics make up
an estimated 14 percent of the population, while Asians account for
28 percent of San Francisco's residents.
</P>
<P>
   Middle Easterners, Native Americans and people of mixed race
together accounted for 4 percent of the complaints. For 18 percent
of the complaints, the person did not give his or her race or
ethnicity, according to the OCC.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department acknowledged that blacks ``account for a
significantly larger number of the arrests than their population,''
police spokesman Sherman Ackerson said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   City authorities noted that nearly 50 percent of inmates in San
Francisco's jail were African Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do racial profiling,'' Ackerson said. ``We don't stop
anyone because of his race, but if you look at the total contacts
where African-Americans are witnesses or victims or suspects, it is
not surprising that they are over-represented. It's something we're
concerned about.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Civil Liberties Union said the OCC data were just a
small part of the larger national issue of race and policing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these numbers are important,'' said John Crew, an ACLU
attorney specializing in law enforcement issues. ``If any group is
filing complaints at 2 1/2 times their rate in population, that is
cause for concern. ... But these numbers have all kinds of
variables.''
</P>
<P>
   Crew said it was possible the percentage of complaints could
actually be lower. He estimated that as many as 50 percent of the
people who came into contact with the police as witnesses, victims
or arrestees were African-American.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are a 19-year-old minority male from a poor
neighborhood, you may not know your right or be willing to utilize
the complaint process as a white homeowner would in a more affluent
neighborhood,'' Crew said. ``These complaint numbers supply
confirmation of the feelings that have been expressed in poll
data.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 1724EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
