<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIVACY-0318-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSINESS UNIT OFFERS INTERNET PRIVACY SEAL
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON Seeking to fend off government steps to broaden
privacy rules on the Internet, the Better Business Bureau Wednesday
began offering its ``trustmark'' seal to Web site operators that
agree not to sell personal data about consumers without permission.
</P>
<P>
   To display the compliance seal, corporate participants have to
accept a code that requires them to tell consumers what information
is being collected and how it will be used.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came on the same day the American Association
of Retired Persons released a survey showing that when it comes to
personal data, just five percent of consumers trust companies
offering services or information over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Better Business Bureau program, called ``BBBOnLine,''
features enforcement mechanisms, a verification process, periodic
monitoring and reviews, provisions for resolving consumer disputes,
and privacy policy training for online managers.
</P>
<P>
   While the program will publicize the names of companies that
break privacy rules, it will not offer monetary compensation for
misuse of information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any relief for damages should be up to the courts,'' said
Steven Cole,
</P>
<P>
   general counsel to BBBOnLine. ``Our job is to induce
compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Cole said more than 300 companies have started the process ``to
become members of a program that will provide consumers with an
easy to recognize seal from an organization they know and trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Privacy activists said the program, while useful, should not
take the place of effective government regulations, such as the law
passed last October aimed at protecting children's' privacy of the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because there's a better Business Bureau doesn't mean we
don't need a Federal Trade Commission,'' said Deirdre Mulligan,
staff counsel at the Center for Democracy and Technology, a
Washington-based consumer advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Privacy is a very central concept of doing business in an
online environment,'' Mulligan added. ``We'll have to see whether
this new seal program be enough. The Internet is a big, big
ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim ends)
</P>
<P>
   Cole said he hoped the program will provide a ``safe harbor'' in
implementing proposed Commerce Department guidelines to comply with
stringent privacy rules recently adopted by the 15-nation European
Commission. ``If we have to tweak it, we will,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, Sen. Conrad Burns (R-Mont.) has drafted an
``Online Privacy Protection Act of 1999'' that would require
regulators to write specific rules making it ``unlawful for an
operator of a Web site or online service to collect, use or
disclose personal information in a manner that violates the
regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns' bill also contains a ``safe harbor'' clause that
apparently would be satisfied by the BBBOnLine program.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim starts)
</P>
<P>
   Under the Better Business Bureau program, compliant companies
with sales of $1 million or less will be charged $150 a year for
the right to display the seal. Participants need not be members of
the 86-year-old organization.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Austin-based Dell Computer became the first firm
to display the seal, having paid BBBOnLine the top $3,000 yearly
fee required of companies with annual sales of $2 billion of more.
Dell also posted its privacy policies on its web site in a
statement from Chairman Michael Dell.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you provide your personal information to Dell (such as
name, address, phone number, company name, or the products you are
shopping for or purchasing) we will not give or sell your
individual information to any outside company for its use in
marketing or solicitation,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Dell employees will have access to consumer data strictly on a
need-to-know basis and ``only to support your customer
relationship'' with the computer maker, Dell said.
</P>
<P>
   Further information about the program is available at
http://bbbonline.org (CQ).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
