<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4168 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARBARA-BARRY-DESIGN-     03-17 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARBARA-BARRY-DESIGN-1150(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGNER IN A STARRING ROLE: THE ENVELOPE, PLEASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (js) 
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ From the polished silver coffee urn with porcelain
cups to the silver chafing dish with pre-warmed blackberries to the
vase of roses, their petals carefully dropped on her bedside table,
each object in Barbara Barry's Hollywood Hills home is ready for
its close-up.
</P>
<P>
   The world of one of the brightest design stars in this land of
stars is so carefully composed _ like a Hurrell portrait _ that she
even peels the garish label off her toothpaste tube.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about trying to be a design Nazi,'' said Ms. Barry, a
furniture and interior designer. ``It's about honoring your daily
acts.''
</P>
<P>
   On this particular morning, Ms. Barry, 47, had a team of four
assisting her daily rituals, including a makeup artist who was
touching up her face in preparation for a slide show that would
draw 400 that afternoon to the Pacific Design Center.
</P>
<P>
   In a town that cultivates surface glow over darker depths, the
designer, known for her green-tea-and-mahogany-hued interiors that
look like colorized stills from Hepburn and Tracy's ``Desk Set,''
has the art of presentation down cold. And when it gets chilly,
despite the gas fire, Ms. Barry quickly produces matching pashmina
shawls. ``I want to help people live a beautiful life,'' she said.
``Design is a religion for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Clients who relish her work _ and her sermons _ include the
industrialist Eli Broad; Glenn Frey of the Eagles; the television
producer Darren Star; a William Morris agent, Nicole David, and the
actors Molly Ringwald, Kiefer Sutherland and Victoria Principal.
They have come to expect not only stylish furniture but also a
supply of Q-Tips _ made of wood, not blue plastic. And whether they
want to or not, they end up learning a lot about glamour _ the
newly minted retro kind _ as Sabrina revered it from the servants'
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Glamour in her world isn't about Jimmy Choo mules. Her homilies
to a visitor included how to wash the bed sheets twice _ once with
soap, once without _ and then iron them while misting with
lavender-infused water. When that advice was met with a look of
skeptical horror, Ms. Barry backtracked. It's not really necessary
to iron the sheets. You can take them, 80 percent dry, and by
snapping each corner _ she demonstrated crisply on a linen napkin _
achieve the same effect. The visitor was unconvinced. ``Well,'' she
insisted, ``at least you can do the pillows.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barry, a petite brunette with June Cleaver's bob and
Elizabeth Dole's steely gaze, talks of empowering the American
woman through pampering. She advocates putting emotional life into
a room, furnishing its ``soul places'' and decanting cleaning
products into plain white containers (one of life's little
upgrades).
</P>
<P>
   Her soft-focus approach has met with astonishing success in the
last 15 years, since she first moved to Los Angeles from Piedmont,
near Oakland, without much formal training, other than a year's
experience running a wine and cheese shop. In no time, her work had
attracted House &AMP; Garden, Vogue and members of the local press, as
well as clients ranging from Harold Williams, the former president
of the J. Paul Getty Trust, to Donna Mills, the vixen of ``Knots
Landing.''
</P>
<P>
   Only clients are allowed to shop at BB Home, her housewares
boutique near historic Carthay Circle, which stockpiles the
appurtenances of the good life, from Italian silver-plated coffee
urns and felt-covered ironing boards to crackled porcelain teacups.
(One tag reads, ``Barbara's favorite porcelain.'') Housed in her
former home, a 1930s bungalow, it's where she holds teas, gives
informal classes on how to make a bed or stock the linen closet,
and bolsters wavering egos. One pleased client, Janet Karatz,
described Ms. Barry's sessions this way: ``She brought us along the
education process. She taught me how one should feel when going
into a room to entertain.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time BB Home was mentioned in a local magazine, people
called to ask whether they could send their maids to the Barbara
Barry Finishing School.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbara Barry has done an excellent job at positioning herself
as a leading taste-maker,'' said Mayer Rus, editor in chief of
Interior Design.
</P>
<P>
   Her medium has included an exhausting array of licensing
arrangements with Baker Furniture (including this season's 30-piece
collection), Baccarat crystal, Kallista bath fixtures, rugs for
Tufenkian and Haviland Limoges. Last fall marked her commercial
debut with several major designs: the Avon Centre Spa in Manhattan;
the reopening of Brooks Brothers on Madison Avenue, and, back home,
the instant-scene Lucques, a new beam-and-brick restaurant on
Melrose Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Caplow, the architect at Barbara Barry Inc., who executes
most of her design concepts, estimates that Ms. Barry is worth as
much as $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, she started to take polo lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was Joseph Campbell who said the privilege of a
lifetime is being who you are,'' Ms. Barry said, sipping her tea
and overindulging her guest with a plate of cookies right after a
hefty breakfast of eggs, muffins, fruit and cheese. Comparisons are
made to Martha Stewart (``That's not for me to say,'' the designer
said, demurely), but Ms. Barry invoked Martha Graham, another
impresario, as ``someone who has a natural gift in her body, her
dancing and her dress.''
</P>
<P>
   One could say that Ms. Barry's esthetic was shaped by reversals
rather than fortune. The daughter of an insurance man and an art
student, Ms. Barry, along with her three sisters, grew up in a
flat-roofed ``somewhat modern'' 1950s house in Long Beach. When her
parents divorced, her mother worked two jobs. A closet decorator,
her mother cut gothic arches out of plywood and sprayed the
television peacock blue, telling her girls they had ``the first
color television set in the neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Young Barbara, who was 9 when her parents divorced, may have
sublimated some anxieties into domestic order: she recalls the
pleasure she felt folding and stacking the towels that her mother
had dyed purple, arranging them by hue, from aubergine to faded
violet. ``I was hurt the most by the split-up,'' said Ms. Barry,
who was married herself for 10 years before divorcing in 1988. ``So
I'm always trying to fix things up.''
</P>
<P>
   A trip to France when she was 17 opened her eyes to a world more
elegant and attentive to the finer things in life. Conversations
with Ms. Barry circle back to these little satisfactions _ like the
bar she designed for hanging quilts on the footboard of Swanson,
her new bed for Baker. If there is a monotony to her pale palette
and her interiors _ almost as if they were all inside the same
house _ her painstakingly arranged table-top tableaux recall the
precision of Vermeer. His compositions of burghers' homes promoted
middle-class virtues like decorum and restraint. Ms. Barry's
mantra? ``Composition. Reduction. Sensuality.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Her furniture for Baker has been praised for its clean, classic
lines, but it is also playful. There are exaggerated hips on her
signature circle-back chair, and an attenuated leg on a table. The
lineage leads to well-known classics, like Jean-Michel Frank and
the '40s in Paris. A scalloped edge recalls Jacques-Emile Ruhlmann,
the 1920s designer.
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing to update classics by dead designers; a number of
living ones complained privately that Ms. Barry imitated their
designs. ``My rugs and her rugs for Tufenkian don't look the same
in my eyes,'' said Stephanie Odegard, who for 15 years has been
designing rugs hand-knotted in Tibet and whose rugs are in Bill
Gates' house. ``But so many customers have come in saying they look
exactly the same. I view it as unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   After an article on Ms. Barry ran in Vogue in October 1994,
Kerry Joyce, a Los Angeles designer, complained to the editors that
two-thirds of the work shown had been designed in collaboration
with Joyce but that he did not receive credit. The magazine ran a
correction.
</P>
<P>
   In response to her critics, Ms. Barry said: ``When I talk about
being inspired by people, I am not inspired by Jean-Michel Frank as
much as we resonate to the same gods _ proportion and pared-down
lines. As designers, we all work from the same collective memory.
Besides, I don't get out that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, she addressed the faithful: 400 designers,
manufacturers and furniture buyers from all over the United States
who had thronged to the Pacific Design Center for West Week, the
area's most important furniture market.
</P>
<P>
   In a simple black boat-neck dress with a single diamond pin and
pumps, she gave full voice to her inspirations, clicking through
slides of the Comtesse de Noailles' and Dolores Del Rio's living
rooms. She wound up with a shot of her own bedside table, with its
signature water carafe and vase of roses.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime friend, Leslie Miretti, told a reporter a story about
Ms. Barry and a vase of roses. ``They were full blown and straight
from the garden,'' she recalled, ``but still Barbara couldn't
resist breaking off some rose petals and scattering them around. I
teased her that if she could have waited one more day they would
have dropped on their own. But that's typical Barbara; she has to
have it just so, right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Clients know when to draw the line. Nicole David, a talent agent
for Whitney Houston, John Travolta, Emma Thompson and Lauryn Hill,
lives with her husband, Brian Braff, a songwriter, in a house that
Ms. Barry outfitted. ``She strives for beauty, and I trust her, but
I'm no groupie,'' Ms. David said. ``Homemaking has never interested
me in the least. When my grandmother tried to tell me how to do
things, I wasn't about to listen.'' Braff called good-naturedly
from the massage table in the bedroom, ``Just say I need a massage
to get relief from Barbara Barry's bills!''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Newman, a designer and furniture maker, recalled his days
as Ms. Barry's consultant. ``She's a workaholic, and she expects
everyone else to work as hard as she does,'' he said. ``If you've
got another life, have friends visiting or just want to do a load
of laundry, forget it.'' On the other hand, he added that since
leaving her office he has internalized many of the lessons he
learned there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm buying more candles, using my silver-plate everyday and
dumping it in the dishwasher,'' Newman said. ``She's right, you
know; we don't do nice enough things for ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barry would have been proud to hear that. But it was
Saturday, and she was already off to the polo grounds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
