 &HT;    
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Thursday, March 18,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPICS
</P>
<P>
   OLY-IOC-EXPELL _ LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ The International
Olympic Committee expelled six members today for taking hundreds of
thousands of dollars in graft from officials who brought the 2002
Winter Games to Salt Lake City. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in ((i) International and (s) Sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SAMARANCH _ LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ IOC President Juan
Antonio Samaranch gets vote of confidence. (Roughton, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-BRIBERY _ JERUSALEM _ An Israeli court Wednesday
convicted on bribery charges the political leader of Israel's
ultra-religious Sephardic Jews, Aryeh Deri, who is also a key ally
of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu. Deri's devoted
followers, some of whom call him a messager from God, immediately
reacted that the old Israeli elites of European descent were
persecuting Deri for empowering the Sephardic Jews. They come from
Asia and have traditionally held little power despite numbering
half the country's population. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON/POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   AIR-TRAVEL _ WASHINGTON _ The airline industry had better fasten
its seat belt, because it is flying into congressional turbulence
over perceived abuses of travelers. Congress is considering no
fewer than four plans for expanding and protecting the rights of
air passengers. (Dart, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   w/AIR-COMPARE _ A look at the four bills.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   F-22 _ WASHINGTON _ A Senate Appropriations subcommittee is
scheduled to hear investigators' complaints Wednesday about the
F-22 stealth fighter program. Pentagon officials will also be on
hand to defend the program. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   WORK _ WASHINGTON _ Work and family pressures are undercutting
widespread job satisfaction among Americans, according to the
latest ``Work Trends'' survey by researchers at Rutgers University
and the University of Connecticut. An overwhelming majority of
those surveyed said the ability to balance work and family is more
important than any other job factor, including job security,
quality of working environment and relationships with co-workers
and supervisors. The survey found that telecommuting is a largely
untapped method of providing that balance, but only about 17
percent of employers offer such an opportunity to their employers.
(Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   FRAUD _ WASHNGTON _ Older Americans are less knowledgable about
their consumer rights than other Americans and are therefor more
vulnerable to fraud, a survey by the AARP showed Wednesday.
(Schultz, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY _ WASHINGTON _ Moving to head off government regulation,
the Better Business Bureau announces a 'good housekeeping seal'
program to protect the privacy of consumers who use the Internet.
The volunteer program is aimed at preventing misuse of data on
consumers. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   STPATS _ SAVANNAH, Ga. _ Live report from St. Patrick's Day in
Savannah _ the parade, other festivities, and another report on the
success of efforts to cut down on drunken revelry. (Davis, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   SUV-EMISSIONS _ A new report by the Public Interest Research
Group says that only five states would gain more than Georgia by
tightening emission standards on them. SUVs emit three times as
much pollution and chug 33 percent more gas than smaller cars. The
EPA proposes to tighten the standards, but would allow automakers
to take an extra two years for the largest, and most polluting
SUVs. (Goldberg, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   LOTTERIES-SOUTH _ Kentucky already is experiencing a drop in
lottery participation and expects to suffer much more if
neighboring Tennessee or North Carolina get their own lotteries.
Florida, which once stood alone in the South as a lottery state,
faces the prospect of new competition from Alabama and South
Carolina after five years of having Georgia as its main competitor.
A look at how the latest round of lottery mania in non-lottery
states could affect Southern states that already have the lottery.
(Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BLACKCOLLEGES _ATLANTA _ The state's Historically Black Colleges
have won a major technical victory in a federal court case that
could have threatened their primary reason for being. A Savannah
judge has ruled that five of the plaintiffs had no standing to sue
(because they were professors and couldn't prove they had been
damaged). Initially, the plaintiffs charged that because the HBCUs
had so many students in remedial programs, the schools were
preventing whites from attending. (Rankin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
