<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4173 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-ALPHA-NYTR &LR;      03-17 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-ALPHA-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFERENCE TO FOCUS ON ATTRACTING AND INSTRUCTING NEW CHRISTIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Mass., Md., Wis., Calif., Ariz., Colo)   (bl)  
 By CARY MCMULLEN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKELAND, Fla. _ Religious conferences in Orlando _ even those
that draw 1,000 people _ are fairly routine. But a two-day
conference starting Thursday could signal a modest counteroffensive
in the 30-year battle of mainline Protestants against declining
membership.
</P>
<P>
   The conference concerns Alpha, a program that is rapidly
expanding in Protestant and Catholic churches as a way of
attracting and educating new Christians. It is one of eight
regional conferences in the United States this year, and it will
train participants in how to conduct the 10-week course for the
``unchurched'' in their own churches.
</P>
<P>
   Although Alpha had its start in an Anglican church and the
conference is being sponsored by the Episcopal Diocese of Central
Florida, its leaders stress it will attract representatives of
Presbyterian, Methodist, Lutheran and Vineyard churches.
</P>
<P>
   The keynote speaker will be the Rev. Nicky Gumbel, the former
atheist lawyer who is largely responsible for Alpha's expansion
beyond a posh London parish. Gumbel is on the staff of Holy Trinity
Anglican Church of Brompton in London. Alpha got its start there in
the 1970s as a Bible study center for new Christians.
</P>
<P>
   After Gumbel took over the program in 1991, he revised it,
persuaded other churches to use it and, according to figures
supplied by Alpha North America, about 600 people took the course
that year. The organization estimates that figure was 500,000 in
1997. It has been endorsed by religious leaders including
evangelical pastor Jack Hayford, Archbishop of Canterbury George
Carey and TV minister Robert Schuller.
</P>
<P>
   Some Catholics have said the program's emphasis on the Bible and
downplaying of sacraments favors Protestant beliefs, but it has
been used in Catholic churches and won the endorsement of the
archbishop of Baltimore, Cardinal William Keeler.
</P>
<P>
   What accounts for such growth?
</P>
<P>
   The course's method is simplicity itself. Students gather once a
week for a meal, listen to a talk or video, then discuss the topic
in small groups. Each participant is provided a manual. In those 10
weeks, the students are exposed to the basic teachings of
Christianity and the Bible. Churches that have offered Alpha
usually open it to members of the congregation also, as a review of
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Christianity 101. It poses questions like `Who is Jesus?
What was he here to do? How do we respond to him?' '' said Jack
Eckbert, an investment banker from Winter Park who took the Alpha
course at Holy Trinity while studying at the London School of
Economics in 1988. At that time a new Christian, Eckbert says he
found the course made the Bible relevant to modern people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It recovers the basic message, but makes the packaging up to
date. It ended up working very well for me. It was the most rapid
spiritual growth I've ever been through,'' said Eckbert, who is now
a member of All Saints Episcopal Church in Winter Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Andrew Doan, rector of Holy Cross Episcopal Church in
Winter Haven, says his church offered the course for the first time
a year ago, with about 23 church members as students.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real nonthreatening way of presenting the gospel. It
uses nearly all the tools that Jesus did,'' he said. ``It has
meals, teaching, it doesn't water down the truth and it uses humor
_ we can poke fun at ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Holy Cross started a third class in February with 27 students,
which about half either new members or people outside the parish,
Doan said. He has made the class a requirement for a couple from
outside the parish who want him to perform their wedding, or a
non-parish couple wanting to have their baby baptized.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Alpha say that it doesn't dig deeply enough into
Christian doctrines, presenting them in a superficial or
marketing-oriented way. Doan replies that the course is intended
for people who may never have set foot in a church before, as a way
of getting them started.
</P>
<P>
   The Episcopal Diocese of Central Florida had a kick-off banquet
for the conference last October that was one of the largest
pre-conference events Alpha officials had seen, said Harry Griffith
of Winter Park, chairman of the conference committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The diocese decided a year ago to make evangelism a priority.
As the leadership discussed it, Alpha seemed the best answer,''
Griffith says.
</P>
<P>
   If Holy Trinity in London is an indicator, diocese leaders may
be right. Eckbert said Holy Trinity experienced such growth that
they began reopening closed churches and placing new members in
them. They also began social ministries in poor neighborhoods
adjoining the ritzy Knightsbridge section of London where the
church is located.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christianity isn't some sort of ritual; it's a relationship
with God. That's been underemphasized,'' Eckbert said. ``The
structure of Alpha works in terms of creating an environment of
being intimate with God and being real about spirituality.''
</P>
<P>
   Other regional Alpha conferences will be held in Boston, April
15-16; Baltimore, April 19-20; Minneapolis, July 26-27; and
Madison, Wis., July 29 and 30. Conferences have already been held
this year in San Diego, Phoenix and Colorado Springs, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   (Cary McMullen is a reporter for The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
