<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Thursday, March 18, 1999, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   CONTRACTORS-STUDY _ American consumers do not trust home
improvement contractors, according to a Princeton University study
commissioned by the American Association of Retired Persons. Using
income, age and education as its main indicators, the study found
that one in four people reported a problem, with older people
reporting the most difficulties. Although the authors attribute
this to the higher rate of home ownership among older Americans,
both high and low income groups are vulnerable to predatory
contractors. (Harte, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FRONTIER _ ATLANTA _Frontier Corp., a century-old telephone
carrier with a nationwide long-distance network, including
operations in Georgia, is being bought by Bermuda-based upstart
Global Crossing Ltd for $11.2 billion in stock by Global Crossing
Ltd., a Bermuda-based upstart in telecommunications, an upstard
telecommunications company. The deal provides a U.S. foothold for
Global Crossing, which has been building a fiber-optic network to
carry voice and data traffic worldwide.Together, the companies will
connect 159 cities with more than 71,000 miles of fiber-optic
cable. Frontier has done partnerships with Cox Communications.
(Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HAYES _ ATLANTA _ Hayes auction, a bittersweet mob scene,
hundreds of bidders and spectators, including many former Hayes
employees, poured into the former Hayes headquarters to be part of
the auctioning off of what's left of Hayes... The first item, a
hockey stick found in Dennis Hayes' office, made out to Dennis on
his birthday. The auctioneer said the signature looks like Wayne
Gretzsky. It sold for $500. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   APPLE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Apple Computers move into Unix-type
server software could help large Apple users such as the University
of Texas. (Mahoney, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRIC _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The Texas Senate on Wednesday will,
barring a major upset, approve a bill to open most of the state's
electric utilities to competition and let customers choose. No
electric deregulation bill has ever gotten out of committee, much
less out of the Senate or House. It this becomes law, competition
would begin in 2001. (Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   WORKPLACE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ It's about to get a lot
</P>
<P>
   easier for Motorola Inc. workers to cross items off their to-do
lists. The company today is announcing a new program designed to
handle the time consuming errands that eat up lunch hour and stress
out folks
</P>
<P>
   trying to balance work and family. Starting in July, a concierge
service will walk dogs, run errands, grocery shop, plan parties,
and handle car service, dry cleaning and gift buying. (Hawkins,
Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ A rundown of the week's financial press. (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET DOW PAGE
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service has prepared a page to mark the passing of the
10,000 mark in the Dow Jones Industrial Average on Tuesday. The
page can run any time through the week (barring a market collapse),
including use as a Sunday perspective-type page, or as a page on
the day the Dow closes above 10,000 (the Dow Tuesday fell below
10,000 almost immediately after going through the benchmark index
and closed 69.53 points below 10,000). The page is available
through Locations on the WAN desk of the AJC's database, and is on
the Cox server in the Business folder.
</P>
<P>
   Stories on the page include:
</P>
<P>
   DOW-FUTURE _Okay, what next? Now that the Dow Jones industrial
average has traded above 10,000 for the first time, investors would
like to know if it will close above that benchmark level any time
soon, drop back or go even higher. The answer is probably, ``All of
the above,'' which leaves open the matter of sequence. Big upward
moves in stock averages tend to be followed by at least small
setbacks _ especially when the market passes one of those historic
milestones. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DOW-HISTORY _ The Dow rises, the Dow falls, the Dow remains
unchanged, but most of all, the Dow makes news _ and in the latest
case, history. The Dow, of course, is the Dow Jones industrial
average. Why it should get so much attention is a matter of
considerable debate, between those who see the Dow at 10,000 as
historic and those who see 10,000 as ``just a number.'' (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED. WITH ILLUSTRATION
</P>
<P>
   DOW-FOURK _ Ordinary Americans, saving slowly and diligently for
their retirement years, helped push the Dow to 10,000 Tuesday.
Retirement accounts such as 401(k) plans now hold close to $1.4
trillion worth of stocks, or a 10th of the total value of U.S.
stocks. Add to that the stock investments in individual retirement
accounts and traditional pension plans, and the total shoots to an
estimated 30 percent of the total market value. (Ezell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DOW-WOMEN _ Women are claiming a stronger presence among
financial investors. (Luke, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
