<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4184 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEATTLE-CABARET-ART-N     03-17 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-CABARET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT TASTES LIKE DINNER, BUT IT SURE LOOKS LIKE A CIRCUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The tent in the vacant lot on the outskirts of
downtown is conspicuous but not particularly distinguished. It's
just a big white tent. Anything might be inside it; a farmer's
market, maybe, or a petting zoo or a traveling antique show. But
what goes on there four nights a week, a vaudevillian dinner
cabaret known as Teatro ZinZanni that has become this city's
hottest ticket, isn't even the biggest surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the show is odd enough. Imagine a slapstick movie being
filmed in a restaurant during dinner hour with deft clowns mingling
with waiters and various musicians, singers, dancers and posturing
actors (not to mention a juggler and a contortionist) making
frequent interruptions.
</P>
<P>
   The most disconcerting thing inside the tent may well be the
tent itself. Beneath the ordinary, inverted cones of white canvas
outside, it reveals itself inside to be a pretty good cross between
an old-style European beer hall and an old-style American saloon, a
round room complete with mirrored walls, wooden booths and dark,
heavy drapery to convey a lush and titillating sense of
roguishness.
</P>
<P>
   ``To build a theater in a place where nobody expected it, and to
create a whole unexpected world inside it, that was the idea,''
said Norman Langill, a local impresario whose production company,
One Reel, created Teatro ZinZanni _ the name is nonsensical, though
zanni is Italian for zany _ with an international cast of
performers for presentation specifically under this portable roof.
</P>
<P>
   Known as a Spiegeltent (Spiegel is German for mirror), it was
built in 1920. It is the oldest and, at about 72 feet across, among
the largest of the 12 surviving ones created by the Klessens family
of Belgium. It is the only one ever to make an extended visit to
the United States. The Klessens perfected an ingenious system of
locking pegs and rings and sliding rails that allows their tents to
be erected in a single day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is there are no tools required,'' said Steve Quinn,
the production manager for One Reel, who received his tutelage in
tenting from Willy Klessens, the grandson of the inventor and the
head of the family business. The tent, which has 4,200 pieces and
weighs about 40,000 pounds, is supported by its own interior
tension, Quinn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's about all I can say,'' he said. ``The design is a
trade secret. In Willy's mind, it's his Coca-Cola recipe.''
</P>
<P>
   What audiences react to is the startling interior that one
doesn't associate with a tent in a vacant lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a shock going from the outside to the inside,''
Langill said, that it prepares the audience for the other surprises
that await them. ``It appeals to me to present theater in an
ephemeral, Brigadoon style, create the theater along with the
show.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidently, that sense of dislocation has appealed to many other
Seattle residents as well. The show opened in October for a
scheduled six-week run, and despite an $88 ticket price (high for
entertainment in Seattle, even with a five-course dinner thrown
in), it has been extended at least through Memorial Day, and
Langill plans to take it on the road, probably to San Francisco or
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   To describe the show is tricky. Indeed, its subtitle, ``Love,
Chaos and Dinner,'' is spiritually accurate but hardly full of
clues. When a waiter innocently declared, ``The wine list is in
your program,'' the playful confusion began. Meanwhile, a clown
posing as a dishwasher (Nathalie Tarlet, an impish Frenchwoman),
circled the tables collecting champagne glasses, slowly commanding
the attention as the stack in her arms grew to several dozen and
she wobbled about unsteadily.
</P>
<P>
   It is a show loosely organized around the meal, with an actor,
Kevin Kent from Seattle, playing the chef and emerging to introduce
each course in the persona of a different character. Entering as an
evangelist with an assistant carrying a tureen, he opened the lid
and cried, as if to the heavens: ``I will fear no soup _ nor
consomme!'' (The kitchen, under the direction of an actual chef,
Monique Barbeau of Vancouver, performs admirably, cranking out 265
reasonably delicious meals all at once from a makeshift facility
built into a trailer.)
</P>
<P>
   Between (and during) courses, there is much singing (including a
handful of campy ballads, like ``The Man Who Got Away,'' delivered
by the full-throated Ann Wilson, formerly of the rock group Heart),
much slapstick clown work (including, of course, the public
ridicule of several audience members) and much music by a jazz band
whose members remain pointedly unperturbed by the raucous horseplay
around them.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a Ukrainian juggler, Sergey Krutikov, who at one
point balances an umbrella, a hat and a cigar on his instep, kicks
them into the air and catches them, respectively, in his hand, on
his head and in his mouth. And perhaps most notably there is
Aurelia Cats, a French contortionist who dresses in a cat suit
(could that possibly be a stage name?) and performs on a trapeze
with a manner that can only be described as insouciant. The whole
thing lasts about 3{ hours, and it isn't editorializing to say it
is nutty.
</P>
<P>
   But as Langill (pronounced LAN-jill) will tell you, it all works
because of the tent. As soon as you walk in, you're
discombobulated, he said. ``You walk in for dinner, and you look up
and you see the theater lighting all around you, and you go:
`Uh-oh. I'm onstage.'''
</P>
<P>
   A round, hirsute man and self-described hippie who looks
remarkably like a blond Jerry Garcia, Langill, 49, is an
iconoclastic showman, well known here as the producer of events
like the Bumbershoot Festival, an annual Labor Day weekend event
that features hundreds of dancers, musicians, actors and visual
artists in continuous performances on more than two dozen stages.
</P>
<P>
   Trained as a comic actor and long a fan of the disappearing art
of vaudeville, Langill came to Seattle from Milwaukee in the late
1960s to study acting at the University of Washington, where his
classmates included actors Pamela Reed, Kyle McLachlan, Patrick
Duffy and John Aylward. One Reel was formed in 1972 as a traveling
vaudeville show that performed in small towns all over the
Northwest. The company has grown in size and scope _ it produces
not only the mammoth Bumbershoot every year, but other festivals
and events as well _ and the players in Teatro ZinZanni were
assembled as part of the regular worldwide rounds of
talent-searching that go into putting those projects together.
Still, it took Langill six years to get the mix he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   But it all began in 1992 in Barcelona while he was there at the
Summer Olympics presenting a show that One Reel had created with a
Japanese theater troupe. He wandered into a tent on the Paseo de
las Ramblas, the city's main boulevard. It was the first Klessens
Spiegeltent he had ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked in, and I felt as if I'd entered the nightclub of my
dreams,'' Langill said. ``I thought, `This is a whole new kind of
presentation.' It was vaudeville of the sort that doesn't exist any
more, the kind I'd been trying to imitate my whole life, even
though I'd never seen it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
