<HEADER>
A4186 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDEPENDENT-COUNSEL-H     03-17 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDEPENDENT-COUNSEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS ATTACK RENO DECISION AGAINST INDEPENDENT COUNSEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno, who has argued against
renewing the independent counsel act, took strong criticism
Wednesday from two senators, a Democrat and a Republican, for
refusing to name a special prosecutor to probe possible campaign
finance violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision you made on campaign finance shows me that we
still need some type of independent counsel law,'' Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, D-Conn., told Reno at a Senate Governmental Affairs
Committee hearing on the future of the statute.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, Reno said she found no reasonable grounds to seek
the appointment of an independent counsel to investigate President
Clinton's role in the multi-million dollar Democratic fund-raising
campaign in 1996. Her decision was made despite the urgings of FBI
Director Louis Freeh and Charles LaBella, the former head of the
Justice Department's campaign finance task force, to appoint a
special prosecutor to probe the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., said he could not
understand why Reno, who has recommended the appointment of seven
independent counsels during her six-year term, seemed so reluctant
to pull the trigger on the possible campaign finance violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some cases you have quickly called for an independent
counsel, but in other cases that I believe cry out for a special
prosecutor, you don't,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said she made her decision ``based on the law and the
facts'' and that she felt it was correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that I would have been criticized no matter what
my decision was,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno told the Senate panel that she reconsidered her support for
the independent counsel law after many of her decisions on
appointing special prosecutors were ``plunged into the political
process.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The act was meant to instill public confidence in high-level
investigations ... and I believe it has not achieved that goal to
the level expected,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the Justice Department came out against the
statute, reversing the stance taken by the president and Reno five
year ago when they successfully lobbied for the law's renewal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I began as attorney general ... I didn't account for the
focus and the immediate posture of any decision I made, to see it
plunged into the political process,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   But Thompson challenged her, saying, ``Maybe it has to do just
with your decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel act will expire on June 30. So far,
those in favor of renewing the statute have found little support in
Congress for the law, which has led to investigations of both
Democratic or Republican administrations.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing, Reno suggested that investigations into the
president and upper-level administration officials should be
handled by the Justice Department in a manner similar to the system
used before passage of the 1978 independent counsel act.
</P>
<P>
   Under that system, the attorney general would turn over credible
allegations against the president, vice president, most Cabinet
officials, the CIA director and the FBI director to the Justice
Department's Public Integrity Section. The section would
investigate the allegations and recommend whether a special
prosecutor should be appointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are career lawyers who are outside the political
process, which would ensure that a fair, thorough job was done,''
Reno said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The independent counsel law was passed in the wake of the
1972-1974 scandal triggered by a Republican break-in at the
Democratic Party headquarters in the Watergate Office Building
here.
</P>
<P>
   During a probe of the scandal President Richard Nixon ordered
the attorney general to dismiss special Watergate prosecutor
Archibald Cox after Cox refused to drop a subpoena for
incriminating tapes of Nixon's White House conversations about the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   The law requires the attorney general to seek appointment of an
independent counsel when there is substantial and credible evidence
of a crime by any one of 49 top federal officials, including the
president. A panel of three federal appellate judges then picks an
attorney for the job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
