<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SCIFI-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVASION: SCI-FI CHANNEL EXPANDS ITS UNIVERSE WITH NEW
FRIDAY  LINEUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Check local listings for times)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c. 1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After seven years of relative obscurity, cable's Sci-Fi Channel
is taking a deep breath and plunking a ton of money onto the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   They call it the ``Sci-Fi 2.0 initiative'' _ the first time a TV
overhaul has been made to sound like a computer upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   It means a snappier image for a channel that had become schlocky
with campy sci-fi reruns. It means more original movies. Most of
all, it means a potent bloc of science-fiction series on Friday
nights.
</P>
<P>
   The big day is Friday, when the Sci-Fi Channel launches two new
series along with new episodes of ``Sliders'' _ that show is harder
to kill than Rasputin _ and ``Poltergeist: The Legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   The newcomers, ``Farscape'' and ``First Wave,'' are the linchpin
series. One sign is that the channel has lavished an unprecedented
66-episode commitment on ``First Wave,'' which is
executive-produced by Francis Ford Coppola.
</P>
<P>
   And the Sci-Fi Channel claims that ``Farscape,'' an
intergalactic fantasy featuring animatronic characters from the Jim
Henson Creature Shop, is the costliest series in basic cable
history.
</P>
<P>
   How costly? They're not saying; you just have to take their word
for it.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Farscape'' is a stunner, the most exotic show in the
batch, and a solid candidate to establish a new science-fiction
iconography two months before George Lucas splashes into movie
houses with his much-anticipated ``Star Wars'' prequel.
</P>
<P>
   Created by Rockne O'Bannon (``Alien Nation,'' ``SeaQuest DSV''),
``Farscape'' is filmed in Australia and stars Ben Browder (``Party
of Five'') as American astronaut John Crichton, a man who
experiences a major mishap.
</P>
<P>
   He's experimenting with using Earth's gravity to bolster the
speed of spacecraft. The experiment works all too well, propelling
Crichton through a wormhole and far into space, until he lands
aboard a prison ship whose strange alien occupants are trying to
escape their captors.
</P>
<P>
   Crichton's new companions: Ka D'Argo (Anthony Simcoe), a gruff
Luxan warrior more or less of the Chewbacca and Lt. Worf stripe;
Pa'u Zotoh Zhaan, a serene blue priestess from the planet Delvia;
Rygel XVI, a Henson concoction who is vain and the usurped ruler of
the Hynerian Empire; and Officer Aeryn Sun (Claudia Black), a
soldier captured by the refugees aboard the ship Moya. Which
happens to be a biomechanoid ``living ship.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems the Moya and its occupants are going to be on the run
from the ruthless Capt. Bialar Crais of the ``Peacekeeper'' forces.
</P>
<P>
   There may be a question whether the market for this type of show
is already worn down by the various ``Star Trek'' series and the
recently departed ``Babylon 5.''
</P>
<P>
   But if there's any remaining juice in the genre, ``Farscape''
could live long and prosper. The special effects are impressive,
the Henson workshop has produced an interesting foil in the
imperious Rygel and the show doesn't seem content standing still.
It's primed for action.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Farscape'' owes to ``Star Trek'' and ``Star Wars,'' ``First
Wave'' can trace its lineage back through ``The X-Files'' to ``The
Invaders'' and ``The Fugitive.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea, hardly original, is that our leading man learns of a
planned alien invasion of Earth, is framed by the invaders for the
murder of his wife and finds himself on the run from both the
invading enemies and from the earthly authorities.
</P>
<P>
   That's a frayed formula. But ``First Wave'' executes it sharply,
and with a few wrinkles of its own. And that 66-episode commitment
means a certain comfort level for viewers _ this show presumably
won't be departing any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian actor Sebastian Spence stars as Cade Foster, a former
safecracker turned corporate security salesman.
</P>
<P>
   To the invaders who are secretly infiltrating Earth, Cade is
Test Subject 117. They've identified 117 psychological archetypes
and are monitoring and manipulating all of them to test the
strength of their bodies and wills.
</P>
<P>
   (It figures that Subject 56, a tobacco lobbyist, was a real
wuss. He fell apart in only two weeks.)
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Cade escapes the aliens hours before they can kill him
and dissect his brain. His wife (Stacy Grant) is dead, though the
aliens have slapped together a tentacled facsimile.
</P>
<P>
   Cade's road map for solving and stopping the alien conspiracy is
none other than the 16th-century soothsayer Nostradamus. He
prophesied the alien takeover, and now his writings give Cade his
only advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``First Wave'' has just enough new twists to make it moderately
intriguing, but I'm not sold on Spence. The character is a man with
a past, and hence a full load of emotional baggage. If not exactly
callow, Spence's Cade Foster does seem too young and unmarred.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the show's maternal grandmother is ``The Fugitive,''
in which a mere glimpse of David Janssen told you that this was a
man burdened with more than carry-on luggage.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, by jiminy, one thing you can say about TV today is that
they don't make archetypes like they used to.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one of the problems is that they can hardly make them
at all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
