<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORK-0318-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WORK IS NO FAMILY VACATION
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Balancing work and family is more important to most
American workers than any other employment factor, including job
security, working conditions and relationships with co-workers and
bosses, according to a survey released today (Thursday).
</P>
<P>
   While job satisfaction is high in the current economy - 88
percent are satisfied with their job, 54 percent are ``very''
satisfied - 95 percent of the adults surveyed said they are
concerned that work takes too much time away from their families.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, 71 percent said they worried about job security
and 88 percent cited working conditions as a concern in the latest
``Working Trends'' survey by the John J. Heldrich Center for
Workforce Development at Rutgers University and the Center for
Survey Research and Analysis at the University of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Although job satisfaction holds steady across income, race and
gender lines, ``these same working Americans are telling us that
there's still something fundamentally wrong with how they work
today, and they see ways it can change,'' said Carl Van Horn, the
Heldrich Center director.
</P>
<P>
   (Note to newspapers: Numbers from next four graphs can be broken
out as employees wish list chart)
</P>
<P>
   At the top of workers' wish list is more flexibility in
schedules. Eighty-seven percent said they would like flexible work
hours or days. Currently, 61 percent (CQ) of employers offer
flexible hours and 48 percent (CQ) have flexible days, according to
the survey.
</P>
<P>
   To help them cope with stress, workers would like more
employer-provided benefits, such as reimbursement for education or
training, which was cited by 69 percent. Some 49 percent cited
on-site child care, while 42 percent picked athletic facilities at
work.
</P>
<P>
   Another high priority for workers would be expanding
opportunities for telecommuting. Eight percent of all workers
telecommute now. Fifty-nine percent said they would if given the
opportunity, even though 45 percent said they believe it would
reduce their chances for career advancement.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the relatively high interest in telecommuting, only 17
percent of U.S. employers currently allow it.
</P>
<P>
   The survey showed that 29 percent of employees with
post-graduate degrees work for employers that permit telecommuting;
24 percent of those with undergraduate degrees do so. Only 11
percent of high school graduates work for employers who offer
telecommuting.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found 46 percent said they work more than 40
hours a week. And a striking 87 percent reported not getting enough
sleep due to increased work demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rules of the new economy have created opportunity as well
as uncertainty,'' said Ken Dautrich (cq), director of the Center
for Research and Survey Analysis. ``Despite widespread job
satisfaction and the lowest unemployment rate in 30 years, anxiety
and stress levels associated with work remain high.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey results are based on telephone interviews of 1,000
adults randomly selected from the contiguous United States from
Feb. 5 through Feb. 22. It has a margin of error of plus or minus 3
percent. The ``Working Trends'' survey, conducted quarterly, does
not exclude the self- employed.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
