A4209 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOTRODS-BERNSTEIN-NYT     03-17 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOTRODS-BERNSTEIN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERNSTEIN   NOT READY TO GIVE UP THE DRIVER'S SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   PAT DOOLEY The Gainesville Sun   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ Maybe it will happen in Gainesville. One
day, Kenny Bernstein will climb out of bed and want to climb back
into it. He won't want to drive, won't want to feel the G-forces
pressing his body back into the seat, won't want to wash the smell
of nitro out of his hair.
</P>
<P>
   It would be fitting if it did happen here. It seems like
everything else has for Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   But it won't happen this year and when it does happen, it will
be quick and without fanfare. No farewell tour, no parade. Don't
even try.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are already talking about something like that,'' he
said. ``They'll have to talk real hard.''
</P>
<P>
   At 54, Bernstein knows he's nearing the end of his career as a
drag racer. But as he prepares for the Mac Tools Gatornationals
that begin here Thursday he says he still goes into each event with
the enthusiasm of a rookie. That, coupled with the experience of 52
victories, makes him a threat at every event he competes in.
</P>
<P>
   The only driver to win season titles in both Top Fuel and Funny
Car showed that last year when he won Gatornationals in his
Budweiser Top Fuel car. And he will be a factor again this year.
That you can count on.
</P>
<P>
   For how long you can count on it is anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I enjoy doing it, I will keep doing it,'' he said.
``I have to enjoy crawling in that car and competing. I'll wake up
one day and decide that's it. It's never going to be a question of
one more year. I'll get to the point where I don't want to do it
anymore. But I'm not the kind of guy who plans things out.''
</P>
<P>
   It was March 20, 1992, a little after 4 p.m. when it happened.
Bernstein became the first driver to exceed 300 mph. You knew it
would happen one day, but when, where and who were the questions.
Bernstein provided the answers at Gainesville Raceway that day
seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it doesn't seem that long ago,'' he said.
``Sometimes it does. It depends on how things are going. It's
amazing because now, everyone's going 300. But it was special. It's
part of why Gainesville is a special place for me.''
</P>
<P>
   That remarkable pass and four victories in Gainesville have made
him as popular as any driver at Gainesville Raceway. Go by his pit
sometime, anytime, and watch the fans gawking for a peek at his
car, his crew, himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love Gainesville. We love the people,'' Bernstein said.
``We really enjoy coming back. It has always been a special
place.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a special win for Bernstein last year when he qualified
fifth, but won all four elimination races to claim the title.
</P>
<P>
   It could have been a victory that propelled Bernstein to another
Winston points championship. It would have been his sixth and
second straight in Top Fuel. But too many early failures during the
season left him in fourth behind eventual champion Gary Scelzi.
</P>
<P>
   What exactly went wrong, Bernstein wishes he knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I did, we'd fix it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So far this season, Bernstein is second in the points standings
behind Mike Dunn after two races. But he'd like some more
consistency in his car.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten lucky a few times,'' he said. ``You can't count
on the breaks all the time. We're actually in better shape than we
deserve. Last year, we had a lot of first-round failures. That puts
you out of the running for the championship. I like our chances in
the semifinals and finals, but we have to get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our car's not quite as quick and as fast as I'd like it to be.
We're running 4.6s and we gotta be in the 4.55s.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein remains motivated to win. He's not going to rest on
his past success.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to realize it's gone, in the past,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He's gone into 26 of them with that same attitude. What's done
is done. What lies ahead, nobody knows for sure. All we know is
that Kenny Bernstein will keep driving, keep competing, until he
doesn't feel it anymore.
</P>
<P>
   That day will be a sad one for the National Hot Rod Association.
They couldn't find a better ambassador for their sport, a press
release in a jump suit. Don't count on it ending too soon. The look
is still in his eye, the fire in his gut.
</P>
<P>
   And when he's in Gainesville, he's as dangerous as any of the
drivers competing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Pat Dooley is a sports columnist for The Gainesville Sun.) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
