<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4225 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-CHATTERBOTS-AI-NY     03-17 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CHATTERBOTS-AI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILESTONES IN CHATTERBOT HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: With CIR-CHATTERBOTS, CIR-CHATTERBOTS-TALK) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are some milestones in the quest for digital creatures with
wit:
</P>
<P>
   1917: A Czech dramatist, Karl Capek, coins the word robot (from
the Czech word for worker) for mechanical servants in his play
``R.U.R.'' (Rossum's Universal Robots).
</P>
<P>
   1950: In a paper titled ``Computing Machinery and
Intelligence,'' Joseph Turing describes the Imitation Game, now
known as the Turing test, used to determine a computer's
``intelligence'' by its ability to simulate human conversation.
</P>
<P>
   1956: The field of artificial intelligence is named at the
Dartmouth Summer Research Project, attended by pioneers in the
field like Marvin Minsky and John McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   1959: Drs. Minsky and McCarthy establish the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology's Artificial Intelligence Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   1966: At MIT, Joseph Weizenbaum creates the first conversational
computer program, Eliza, which imitates a psychotherapist.
</P>
<P>
   1968: Arthur C. Clarke and Stanley Kubrick introduce HAL 9000 in
the film ``2001: A Space Odyssey.''
</P>
<P>
   1971: A former Weizenbaum colleague, Kenneth Colby, introduces
Perry, a chatterbot that simulates a paranoid-schizophrenic.
</P>
<P>
   1989: Michael Mauldin's Julia chatterbot appears on the Tiny
MUD, a text-based multi-user chat space on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   1991: The first annual Loebner Prize competition is established
for chatterbots to compete in a Turing test. PC Therapist, an
updated version of Eliza, places first.
</P>
<P>
   1995: Richard Wallace designs Alice, a chatterbot originally
used as an interface to control a Webcam.
</P>
<P>
   1995: Robby Garner's first Internet chatterbot, Agent Max
Headcold, makes its debut on the Fringeware Web site, in one of the
first commercial bot applications.
</P>
<P>
   1997: Publication of Andrew Leonard's book ``Bots: The Origin of
New Species,'' the first popular survey of the field of bots.
</P>
<P>
   1998: Neuromedia introduces Neurostudio, a commercial
chatterbot-authoring software program.
</P>
<P>
   1998: Virtual Personalities begins selling $14.95 Verbots,
chatterbots with computer-animated faces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 1806EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4227 &Cx1f; tth-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ITALY-HOMELAND-SPI &LR;      03-17 1773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-HOMELAND-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCH FOR PAST TURNS UP A FAMILY IN THE PRESENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TERESA TALERICO  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPEZZANO DELLA SILA, Italy _ Rosellina bounds up the marble
stairs with a squeal and a giggle.
</P>
<P>
   A giddy smile lights up her dark brown eyes. She twirls around
in her stylish black boot-cut pants. My 15-year-old Italian cousin
must be excited, I assume, about an evening stroll in the piazza
with her sweetheart.
</P>
<P>
   Think again. Even in this village of 5,000 in remote southern
Italy, Leonardo DiCaprio wields far more seductive power than any
``ragazzo,'' or boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Titanic!'' she shrieks, pronouncing it ``tee-tah-neek.'' She
waves around a pirated videotape of the American movie. A gift from
a classmate.
</P>
<P>
   In seconds, the whole family is gathered around the TV, watching
the herky-jerky, static-filled, copy-of-a-copy video. Rosellina and
her 14-year-old sister, Patrizia, sing along in English with the
theme song, and it occurs to me that in Italy, even Celine Dion
sounds good.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the song that always sounded so corny back home seems
more poignant and meaningful:
</P>
<P>
   ``Near, far, wherever you are, I believe that the heart does go
on ...''
</P>
<P>
   I TRAVELED TO Italy for the first time last fall. I was looking
for the past but found something even better _ an unforgettable
present.
</P>
<P>
   I went there, courtesy of a journalism fellowship from Columbia
University, to explore the homeland and history of my paternal
grandparents, who immigrated to Texas from Calabria, a rugged,
mountainous region deep in southern Italy.
</P>
<P>
   My grandparents both died before I was born. For hints about who
they were, I had often studied their black-and-white wedding
picture, taken in the early 1900s.
</P>
<P>
   Assunta's thick brown hair is pulled back into a tidy bun. Her
pretty dark eyes are wide with the expectations of a 20-year-old
woman. My grandfather Vito stands proudly in a black suit and
bristly black mustache.
</P>
<P>
   In 1921, they left this village to build a better life in
America.
</P>
<P>
   They were among 195,037 southern Italians who crossed the
Atlantic that year _ according to the U.S. National Archives _ to
escape problems such as poverty, political corruption and the
stranglehold of organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   For years, I had imagined what their Italian village was like
and dreamed of visiting it. I wondered if modern-day Spezzano would
be a sleepy town paralyzed by 'Ndrangheta, the Calabrian wing of
the Mafia, with crumbling buildings and elderly residents, where
the young people had all moved north or to America.
</P>
<P>
   Before I left on my trip, a Texas relative had remarked that
there were probably nothing but ``old fogeys'' left there.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I found a delightful blend of old and new, rustic and
modern, in a region rarely visited by American tourists. First, I
met Salvatore, my father's first cousin, whose parents had remained
in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to say which side of the family has the ``better''
life today.
</P>
<P>
   Salvatore, a retired truck driver in his 70s, was a robust slice
of the old world. A proud patriach, he picked me up at the bus stop
in a sturdy blue 31-year-old Fiat.
</P>
<P>
   He showed off the three cozy homes he built for his family. He
drove us past ``Seattle Blues,'' a bar opened by Seattle residents
and restaurant owners Rhonda and Gianfranco Bafaro in their native
Spezzano. He gave me a tour of his lush garden filled with tomatoes
(for sauce), grapes (for wine) and enough fruits and vegetables to
help feed his entire clan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guardi,'' he'd say in his tobacco-roughened voice. ``Look.''
And he'd pull a bunch of grapes from the vine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mangi,'' he'd command with a smile. ``Eat.'' And he'd peel a
sweet fig for me. For this American city girl, who'd never tasted a
fig that wasn't Newton'd, it was like paradise.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, his teenage grandchildren wore Levis jeans, Doc
Marten boots and blue nail polish.
</P>
<P>
   They swooned over the Backstreet Boys and battled like American
siblings over telephone privileges.
</P>
<P>
   On a trip to Calabria's majestic pine forest, La Sila, to pick
mushrooms for pizza, they popped in a cassette, turned up the car
stereo's volume and sang along with Natalie Imbruglia's ``Torn'' as
we whizzed in a Fiat along the autostrada.
</P>
<P>
   Later, 10-year-old Fabio pointed to a page in my American
Entertainment Weekly magazine and correctly identified a picture of
a smiling brunette.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica Lewinksy?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Life in this village was far from ``old fogey.''
</P>
<P>
   THE WORD ``SOLITUDE'' doesn't seem to exist in the Calabrese
vocabulary. Unlike in America, extended families here stay close
together.
</P>
<P>
   Very close, by U.S. standards.
</P>
<P>
   On a sun-drenched hillside, Salvatore has built three homes _
one for himself and his wife, and two for their grown daughters _
Maria and Antonietta _ and their families.
</P>
<P>
   Cousins live within shouting distance and seem more like
siblings. Grandparents live across a small driveway. Two of the
homes are connected by a balcony, which the kids climb over to
visit with each other.
</P>
<P>
   Salvatore's seven grandchildren range in age from 9-year-old
Valeria (who has a Barbie doll she named ``Cindy Crawford'') to
23-year-old Rossana, who studies economics at a nearby university
and has a boyfriend who rides a moped and plays soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are always together,'' teenager Rosellina explains.
</P>
<P>
   It seems so different from America, where sons and daughters
often move across the country and cousins rarely see each other
outside of holidays, weddings and funerals. My Italian relatives
are shocked that I must hop on a plane to visit my family in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a while for me, an only child accustomed to the
all-American sacrament of privacy, to adjust to constant
togetherness.
</P>
<P>
   One night I decide to take a solo walk before dinner. Apparently
this is rare in Calabria, especially for a young woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going alone?'' my cousins ask, puzzled. They all watch
from the balcony as I make my way down the road.
</P>
<P>
   But after a few days, the close-knit lifestyle feels cozy and
fun, and I find myself relaxing in and enchanted by this cocoon of
family.
</P>
<P>
   The food, by all means, helps my assimilation.
</P>
<P>
   Thick hunks of lasagna baked with tomato sauce, prosciutto, peas
and cheese. Main courses of chicken and veal. Glasses of strong red
wine made from the garden's grapes. For dessert: sweet, fresh figs
picked from the trees outside. Finally, after what seems like hours
at the table, tiny cups of strong Italian coffee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mangi, mangi, sei magra,'' the older women prod. ``Eat, eat,
you are too thin.'' It's like something out of a movie.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner table is always lively. Filippo, Maria's husband,
jokes so much, his daughters _ Rosellina, Patrizia and Valeria _
roll their eyes and laugh, ``Papa! Basta!'' Chill out, Dad!
</P>
<P>
   A 48-year-old wiry Sicilian, Filippo grills me about life in
America. What is the weather like? Is your house made of brick or
wood? Do you work? Why aren't you married if you live with your
boyfriend? What does your father do? Do you eat pasta in the United
States? Are most Americans fat?
</P>
<P>
   Mama mia! So many questions. But whenever I get my point across
in Italian, Filippo's eye's crinkle as he smiles and shouts,
``Perfetto!'' Perfect.
</P>
<P>
   He asks about differences between America and Italy. In the
midst of a boisterous crowd and unfamiliar language, I'm a bit
speechless. Off the top of my head, I blurt out my first thought _
seedless grapes.
</P>
<P>
   The table erupts in laughter.
</P>
<P>
   TRADITIONAL, CONSERVATIVE and buried deep in the toe of Italy's
boot, Spezzano is far removed, both geographically and culturally,
from Italian cities to the north, such as Rome and Milan.
</P>
<P>
   However attuned the young southern Italians are to American
fashions, music and movies, this remains a village where residents
revere patron saint Francesco di Paola (shrines to him are found in
every household and business), where people attend Mass every
Sunday and women live with their parents until marriage.
</P>
<P>
   One night I hear high-pitched, female screaming from the
driveway between the three houses. We all rush to our respective
balconies to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   It's Roberta, an 18-year-old cousin with smooth black hair and
olive skin. She screams at her mother in a flurry of Italian and
angrily stamps her foot.
</P>
<P>
   She is upset, I learn, because she can't go on a drive with her
boyfriend. Girls here are forbidden from riding in cars with boys,
lest they get a reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do they want to go?'' I ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the piazza,'' Rosellina explains.
</P>
<P>
   The plaza is only five minutes away. I am reminded again of
where I am _ a very conservative village in southern Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the young people here seem happy, and there's a mutual
respect between youths and elders. Grandchildren actually have
conversations with their grandparents. Valeria, 9, carries in some
wood for the fireplace without being asked. My cousins say they
don't ever want to leave _ very different from America, where many
small-town teens can't wait to flee to the big city.
</P>
<P>
   My last night at Maria's, I leave the family a sharp,
store-bought copy of ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrizia paints my fingernails blue, and the teenage girls and I
teach each other a few off-color words in each other's languages.
For a moment, I feel guilty for corrupting them. They just laugh
and teach me another.
</P>
<P>
   My heart breaks when it's time to leave. I wonder when I will be
able to see them again, this warm family that has made me feel like
one of the sorelle, or sisters.
</P>
<P>
   This might have been my life, I think, if my grandparents had
remained in Italy. Certainly, I probably have had more
opportunities and freedom than my Italian cousins. On the other
hand, they seem healthier, happier and far more grounded than most
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   It took a trip to Italy to really learn about family, and the
prime role it plays in both my cultures (Italian and Mexican). To
finally understand where my parents were coming from all these
years, why family has always been so important to them, why they
seemed to take it personally when I moved out of town, then out of
Texas, then 2,000 miles away for my jobs in journalism.
</P>
<P>
   After all, friends drift apart. Jobs end. Cities lose their
romance. In the end, family remains _ if you're lucky, with a cup
of espresso and a smile.
</P>
<P>
   My cousins in Italy know this by heart. Their culture has
preserved it.
</P>
<P>
   It took me a little longer to get the point. I had to cross the
Atlantic to finally come home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
