<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, March 18, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A slow-moving storm will drift north from the Rio Grande Valley,
resulting in widespread rain over Texas and Oklahoma. Flooding
downpours will accompany strong thunderstorms which will erupt over
central and eastern sections during midday and in the afternoon.
Farther west, areas of heavy, wet snow will occur from the higher
terrain of northeastern New Mexico to the panhandles of Texas and
Oklahoma. Drier air will surge into the Rio Grande Valley during
the day. Farther north, high pressure will promote mild and dry
conditions over most of the central and northern Plains. The rain
area will move north through Kansas Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Breezy and mild conditions will persist ahead of a cold front
near the Northeast coast. In the wake of the front, windy and
chilly weather will spread from the Midwest into the interior
Northeast. Most of the Northeast will stay dry with a mixture of
clouds and sun, although a few widely separated showers will occur
near the Appalachians as the front passes.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure east of Florida will keep most of the Southeast
warm and dry. Clouds will increase over the Tennessee and lower
Mississippi Valleys as a front arrives from the north. Otherwise,
ample sunshine will prevail.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, mild weather with abundant sunshine will linger
over most of the interior. Clouds will thicken near the Northwest
coast as a vigorous Pacific low pressure area approaches. Rain will
arrive over southwestern Oregon and northern California where
onshore winds develop.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Massive Storm
</P>
<P>
   A massive, powerful storm system bore down on Alaska's Pribilof
and Aleutian Islands Wednesday, armed with winds gusting to
hurricane force. Any comparison between hurricanes and winter
storms ends there. Hurricanes, which derive their energy from large
amounts of heat released when water vapor in sultry, tropical air
condenses, concentrates its fiercest winds in a small region around
the eye. Winter storms, which derive their energy from temperature
contrasts over the middle latitudes, spread their strongest winds
over a much larger region much farther away from the core of the
storm.
</P>
</TEXT>
