<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-TRAINING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL PANEL SAYS MALE-FEMALE MILITARY TRAINING O.K.
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Army, Navy and the Air Force should continue to
train male and female recruits together and allow them to live in
coed housing, according to a preliminary congressional commission
report released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The findings are a blow to conservative House Republicans who
have urged the military to train and house men and women separately
as is done in the Marine Corps.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Commission on Military Training and
Gender-Related Issues, which includes former Defense Department
officials and retired military personnel, was created in 1997 in
the wake of military sex scandals. One such scandal, revealed in
late 1996, involved drill instructors engaging in sexual relations
with recruits at the Army's Aberdeen Proving Ground in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problems of the past ... were created by serious failures
in leadership,'' said commission member Robert Dare, a retired Army
command sergeant major. ``They were clearly not a result of men and
women in a training environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission, however, was not unanimous in its recommendation
that the Army, Navy and Air Force continue to train men and women
together and in recommending that the Marine Corps maintain its
separate approach.
</P>
<P>
   The panel voted 6 to 1 in favor of the recommendation and three
members abstained. The panel, however, was ideologically polarized
from the beginning as Republicans and Democrats each had a role in
selecting the panel.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Stephen E. Buyer, R-Ind., chairman of the House Armed
Services subcommittee on military personnel, said Congress wanted a
diverse panel in hopes that its recommendations wouldn't be
dismissed as partisan.
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary report said the recommendation was ``based on
our conclusion that in general the ways in which the (military)
services are currently conducting their training, including gender
formats, sustain mission readiness.''
</P>
<P>
   But during a hearing before Buyer's subcommittee, one commission
member, retired Lt. Gen. William Keyes of the Marines, decided to
change his vote to no. He had originally voted to abstain.
</P>
<P>
   He said separate training is good for both sexes and noted that
separate, basic training only lasts for eight to 12 weeks before
male and female recruits would move onto the next training level
together.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines conduct separate training but integrate men and
women after boot camp.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's report is unlikely to settle the debate on coed
training.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's chairwoman, Washington lawyer Anita K. Blair,
voted to support the status quo in military training operations.
She admitted that ``there is no way to tell whether the benefits of
gender-integration outweigh the costs.''
</P>
<P>
   The report's recommendation differs from a panel appointed by
Defense Secretary William Cohen and headed by former Sen. Nancy
Kassebaum Baker, R-Kan., that studied military training issues.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Kassebaum Baker panel recommended that the
military train and house its male and female recruits separately.
</P>
<P>
   Those recommendations gave conservative House Republicans enough
ammunition to attempt to mandate separate training and housing of
male and female service members. The proposal was attached to a
Defense Department reauthorization bill last May, but it was
blocked by a bipartisan group of lawmakers in the Senate led by
Sen. Olympia J. Snowe, R-Maine.
</P>
<P>
   At the time Snowe and others argued that Congress should wait
for the congressional commission's report before deciding whether
to require changes in military training.
</P>
<P>
   Snowe said she was pleased with the congressional commission's
preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their conclusions reflect the best judgment of the officers
and enlisted ranks who run and participate in gender-integrated
training programs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   During the commission's year-long review, one member, retired
Lt. Gen. George Christmas of the Marines, said he heard much more
about shortages of military personnel and about military personnel
being deployed for longer time periods overseas than he did about
gender-related issues. He said the military is stretched
``perilously close to its limits.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission's final report is due April 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
