<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DAM-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE JOURNAL BOLDLY CRITICIZES GOVERNMENT'S DAM PROJECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ In an unusual critique of government policy, a
mainstream intellectual journal here has published a searing expose
of social problems caused by the construction of the giant Three
Gorges Dam.
</P>
<P>
   The article, by a Chinese scholar using a pseudonym, describes
in vivid detail the obstacles to successfully resettling at least
1.3 million people whose homes and farms are to be inundated as the
reservoir for the dam on the Yangtze River is filled in stages
starting in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   If current trends continue, the article warns, the plight of
these uprooted people ``may become an explosive social problem, and
the dam region will become a hotbed of sustained upheaval for
China.''
</P>
<P>
   While similar concerns were expressed here in the late 1980s,
before the dam's construction was approved, they were silenced in
the 1989 crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators at Tiananmen
Square; some of the opponents to the project were imprisoned. Such
blunt dissection of a major government initiative is almost never
seen in print in China now.
</P>
<P>
   The article's publication is likely to cause speculation about
possible cracks in high-level support for the dam, considered a pet
project of Li Peng, the former prime minister who remains
second-most important person in the Communist Party and also heads
the National People's Congress, China's parliament.
</P>
<P>
   When the dam was formally approved by the congress in 1992 at
Prime Minister Li's urging, a third of the delegates voted against
it or abstained, an unprecedented gesture of opposition by the
usually compliant body.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is no sign that the government intends to abandon
the project to build the world's largest dam, an idea blessed by
Mao Tse-tung himself decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Today's leaders publicly portray the dam as a triumph of the
national will and describe a resettlement program proceeding on
schedule. Project officials recently reported that more than
160,000 people have already been successfully relocated and that
another half million will be moved by 2003, when the reservoir will
be partially filled.
</P>
<P>
   The reservoir is to be filled to capacity in 2009, forcing more
than half a million additional people to move.
</P>
<P>
   When the project was formally approved in 1992, officials
promised that displaced people would be given a better life on
modern farms or in newly built towns where they would find jobs in
expanding industries.
</P>
<P>
   But the recently published article, which appeared in the
journal Strategy and Management, details the acute scarcity of
arable land in the mountains along the Yangtze where most of these
people are supposed to establish new lives and livelihoods. Initial
efforts to transplant farmers onto the steep, eroding hillsides
have fared poorly, it says, and it quotes some who are slated for
resettlement as saying: ``If you want me to move there, you'll have
to make me do it at gunpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   The region's industries are more often failing than booming, the
article notes, and promised jobs have often evaporated. The article
documents a serious lack of funds to pay for resettlement as well
as widespread corruption and deceptive reporting by local
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The article echoes arguments raised by longtime opponents of the
dam in China and abroad, who argue that the environmental,
archaeological and social costs will outweigh the promised benefits
to navigation, energy supplies and flood control.
</P>
<P>
   But domestic critics have been muted in recent years while the
official press has only hinted at problems amid a flood of praise
for the project _ making it all the more surprising to see such a
detailed critique appear in a journal that is seen by thousands of
officials and scholars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such an article could never be published in newspapers here,
which are strictly controlled by the authorities,'' said Li Rui, a
Communist Party elder and a rare open critic of the Three Gorges
Dam, in an interview. ``But as Chinese now have more freedom to
speak out,'' he added, ``I don't expect any actions against the
journal or the writer.''
</P>
<P>
   The article's author is given as Wei Yi, of Central China Normal
University in the city of Wuhan. That is a pseudonym for a Chinese
sociologist with long experience in the Three Gorges region, said a
person familiar with the research.
</P>
<P>
   Strategy and Management, a bimonthly, includes articles on a
range of domestic and foreign policy issues. About 6,000 copies are
sold or given out, mainly to government officials and scholars.
</P>
<P>
   The journal was long known for a conservative bent, but in the
last year or two, it has become more provocative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often we publish pieces that are not in keeping with official
views, in order to encourage discussion,'' said Zhang Jian, an
editor at the journal.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is hardly a radical forum. The journal is published by
the Strategy and Management Research Society, a small think tank
with close ties to the government and military, but which claims to
be operating with independent funds. The society's directors
include retired military and economic leaders including Wang
Daohan, an elder statesman regarded as the longtime mentor of
President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
   The journal was printed in mid-February as the Chinese New Year
holiday was winding down, and the critique of the dam project has
not yet been widely noticed in Beijing. Zhang said that he knew of
no official objections to the article up to now.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Relocation and Development Office of the Three
Gorges Project Construction Committee, in Beijing, said Wednesday
that they only saw the article this week and could not yet comment.
</P>
<P>
   Li Rui, the party elder and critic of the dam project, said he
believed that the project was too far along to cancel.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no second thought or debate on this among the
leaders,'' he said, dismissing speculation that Prime Minister Zhu
Rongji might try to kill the project, which by the latest official
estimate, widely seen as low, will cost $25 billion.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the official New China News Agency quoted officials
overseeing the dam project as saying it faces a $3 billion
shortfall for the current (1998-2003) phase of construction. They
expected to raise most of the needed money through domestic bank
loans and bond and stock issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Yangtze has already been diverted around the dam site near
the city of Yichang and construction is well under way. China is
hoping to gain international financing for a share of the costs.
</P>
<P>
   Li Rui said he and other domestic opponents hoped the government
would at least decide to hold the reservoir to a lower level than
planned. This could reduce the number of uprooted people but would
also cut the economic benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The journal article features a detailed case study of Yunyang
county, near the city of Chongqing, in which 120,000 of an
impoverished population of 1.24 million must be moved.
</P>
<P>
   To fight erosion and flooding, the government has declared that
steep slopes should not be cultivated. But in Yunyang county, the
article notes, nearly half the pre-existing farms are on illegally
steep slopes, and every patch of decent farmland is already in use.
</P>
<P>
   The funds allocated for terracing and other measures to create
sustainable cropland in the hills are less than half the needed
amount, the article says.
</P>
<P>
   With industry in the region faring poorly, so is the search for
new factory jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since 1995, Yunyang county has basically been unable to
relocate any more people into factories,'' the article says.
Instead, many displaced townspeople have been given a ``living
allowance'' of $8.50 a month, which is ``unable to satisfy the
elementary living needs.''
</P>
<P>
   In Yunyang county between 1993 and 1998, the article says, more
than $240,000 of the resettlement funds are known to have been
embezzled or otherwise misused and numerous officials have been
imprisoned or disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   Towns have commonly added fake names to the resettlement list to
get more funds, it says, creating ``a piggy bank from which
power-holders can extract private gain.''
</P>
<P>
   One way to relieve the overcrowding would be to transfer many
displaced people to distant regions. This is a government goal, but
has proved unpopular and made little headway.
</P>
<P>
   ``In China,'' the article says, ``all of the areas with better
natural conditions were filled with people long ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 1821EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
