<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4262 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-BOOK-CLUBS-ART-2T     03-17 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BOOK-CLUBS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE BOOK CLUBS: EVERYTHING BUT FOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.Y., S.C., Va., Ill.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(af) 
 By PAMELA LiCALZI O'CONNELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can a book club be a book club without muffins?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, according to the growing number of reading groups that meet
not in homes or libraries but online. These groups argue that it is
possible to have a successful, serial book discussion without
face-to-face interaction, neighborhood gossip, or even _ and this
is a tough one for ``offline'' groups to grasp _ edible
enticements.
</P>
<P>
   Take the example of the Virtual Reading Group. VRG operates like
the typical offline group in that books are selected by vote and
then read on a schedule. But its ``meetings'' are held on dedicated
message boards at the Web magazine Salon. There, discussion of a
single book can last for weeks, not for the hour or two a month
typical of face-to-face groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a real-life club, you have one night to say what you have
to say,'' said Ken Craft, one of the founders of VRG (where he is
known as ``Prentice Hall'') and a high school English teacher from
Massachusetts. ``Here, you have 30 days to chew over a book, time
for opinions to evolve and change. It's a different model, one of
particular appeal to those, like myself, who are much better
writers than speakers.''
</P>
<P>
   VRG's discussions are undiluted by the social niceties that
often regulate discourse in living rooms. A recent debate on
Hemingway's ``The Sun Also Rises'' drew more than 400 messages, and
virtual blows were nearly exchanged over questions of racism in the
text. It was even suggested, at one point, that those who favored
Hemingway's tome were ``living a lie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was merciless,'' Craft sighed.
</P>
<P>
   This is definitely not Oprah's Book Club.
</P>
<P>
   VRG is an example of how the Web has adopted, and in some ways
transformed, the popular book club concept. The obvious differences
in online versus offline communication aside, wired clubs appear
more difficult to start and manage but less social and more
intense, even academic, once they pick up steam.
</P>
<P>
   Because no clock is ticking, participants are free to parse
sentences in perpetuity. There are few concerns about how someone's
personality will fit in the mix; online, for better or worse,
members come and go with little or no commitment.
</P>
<P>
   In cyberspace, book chatter is everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Book talk abounds on AOL and the Web,'' confirms Lisa Mandel,
vice president and publisher of Simon &AMP; Schuster Online, which at
one time hosted online clubs on its site. ``It's been important to
the development of many successful sites such as Salon as well as
the online booksellers.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of book clubs are scouring the Web for reading
suggestions, reviews, author information, and reader guides for
specific books. Donna Paz, publisher of the annual guide ``Reading
Group Choices'' and its companion website, said that 76 percent of
book club members surveyed by her company were online. Publisher
sites and online bookstores teem with information targeted to book
clubs, and independent Web pages by individuals and clubs offer
advice on reading selections and club mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The availability of online information on a book often tips
the scale'' when making a selection, says Tom Smith, a member of a
face-to-face (and fork-to-mouth) club in New Jersey that has dubbed
itself ``Mostly, We Eat.'' At its website,
www.serve.com/tsmith/bookclub, the club rates the books it has
read.
</P>
<P>
   It also is the vehicle the club uses to vote on selections and,
of course, handle meal planning _ as the name of the group
suggests, culinary concerns loom large. A members-only area of the
site contains contact information for all and interactive maps to
lead them to the next meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the other members of the club work for high-tech
companies and are self-styled ``techies,'' yet they have no
interest in meeting online. ``It's much more important for the
couples to get together socially _ and eat. It would fall flat on
its face if we weren't sitting around a table,'' Smith said. ``We
need to keep it offline as a counterpoint to our work, where we
spend so much time on.''
</P>
<P>
   Lois Kohn-Claar is part of a reading club called Tertulia (a
Spanish term for a group of people discussing art or literature)
comprising 10 Manhattan women. The club also has a website,
www.bway.net/loiskc/homepge.htm. Although Ms. Kohn-Claar says
members use the Internet extensively, even starting some
discussions online before a physical meeting, she throws down the
gauntlet, somewhat ironically via an e-mail message: ``We would
never resort to becoming an online book group. I can't quite
understand how those can be very fulfilling.''
</P>
<P>
   Online groups do seem to fill the needs of a variety of readers,
though. Some gravitate to such clubs because of location, mobility,
or scheduling restrictions. ``No matter where you are or what your
situation, you can still talk books, even if it's the middle of the
night'' says Ginny Anderson, a retired Latin professor in Pauline,
S.C., the book club leader at SeniorNet, www.seniornet. org, which
supports nine reading groups in a message-board format.
</P>
<P>
   But many members of online reading groups say they simply prefer
discussing books online. Online clubs are more amorphous and open
to new members, adherents say. ``The image of reading groups is of
mostly a female thing,'' says Craft of Virtual Reading Group, ``so
I had this fear that I would go to one and stumble into a
Tupperware party. For someone like me, who is hesitant to enter
unfamiliar territory, an online club was a good option.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Anderson of Senior Net says her clubs turn what is generally
considered a disadvantage of online communication _ the lack of
facial and other physical cues _ into a plus.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no body language,'' she said, ``and it's quite
marvelous. It becomes a pure meeting of the minds. In real life,
all you need is one person to roll their eyes to shut someone up
for the rest of the night. That doesn't happen here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jill Lasker, a science writer based in Richmond, Va., has been a
``facilitator'' for both online and offline clubs since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``My experience with online groups has been much more rewarding
than that with face-to-face groups,'' she writes in an e-mail.
``People are more inhibited in person. Of course, online you don't
see the joyous expression of someone who has absolutely fallen in
love with a book. But it does get to the point in a good online
group where you swear you can hear the other person giggling.''
</P>
<P>
   Online clubs can also address genres and literary niches that it
may be more difficult to build an offline club around. Such is the
case with the African-American Literature Book Club, www.aalbc.com,
founded a year ago by a Brooklyn-based investment banker, Troy
Johnson.
 &UR;  &LR;   &UR; `` &LR; When I started my club,'' Johnson said, ``so many people
contacted me and said there was no access to these kind of books in
their town and no one to talk to about them. So an online group
really drew in people who were having a hard time finding other
people to discuss African-American works with.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the largest hub of online book-club activity can be
found at AOL's Book Central site (keyword: Cafe Booka), home to
more than 100 reading groups on everything from ancient history to
contemporary women's fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Although some groups are focused on individual authors, more
than 80 percent are genre-based and are run like traditional books
clubs, said Marsha Lipps, a semi-retired nuclear medical
technologist in Arlington Heights, Ill., who is co-manager of the
site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem we face in running an online reading group
is the transient nature of being online,'' she said. ``We fight
against the surf mentality of click, click, click. We're always
wondering if enough people are going to show.''
</P>
<P>
   The well-known independent bookstore WordsWorth Books in
Cambridge, Mass., experimented with a chat-centered club model in
late 1997 and plans to renew its efforts this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the physical world, we couldn't keep up with requests for
starting clubs out of the store _ we simply didn't have the
space,'' says Sanjay Kharbanda, WordsWorth's general manager. ``So
that prompted us to start virtual clubs run off our website. The
discussions were high quality but for some reason the concept
quickly ran out of steam. Now that technology has improved we're
hoping to give it another chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Online clubs typically require active management because there's
no ``muffin'' factor, said Rachel Jaffe, a court reporter in
Washington, D.C., who maintains a website,
www.his.com/allegria/compend.html, devoted to information about
online book clubs. It is this that makes them challenging, said Ms.
Jaffe, whose own attempt at running a club failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Members are coming in with less investment,'' she said. ``You
have to make the discussion enticing and be tenacious.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sampling of sites on the Web with material for book
clubs: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Rachel's Compendium of Online Book Discussions, et al.,
www.his.com/allegria/compend.html: A well-maintained, though
incomplete, listing of online book clubs. Also includes information
on general book discussions online and resources for offline
reading groups.
</P>
<P>
   _ The BookWire Index of Reading Groups,
www.bookwire.com/index/reading-groups. html: An eclectic listing of
online book clubs, though a bit outdated.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reading Group Choices, www.readinggroupchoices.com: A large
collection of reading guides, housed in a searchable database, for
use in book discussions. Also contains useful tips on how to start
_ and successfully manage _ clubs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Salon's Virtual Reading Group, www.salonmagazine.com: Visit
the Table Talk section and click on ``Books.'' You'll find a list
of topics, called ``threads.'' Look for any that begin ``TT Reading
Group'' or ``TT Book Discussion Group.'' In particular, the
discussion labeled ``Is a Virtual Reading Group at Salon
feasible?'' provides an inside view of how the groups evolved. But
beware: This thread already contains more than 2,500 posts and is
growing.
</P>
<P>
   _ AOL's Book Central (keyword: Cafe Booka): Home to more than
100 reading groups covering nearly every conceivable genre,
sub-genre, and sub-sub-genre. You only need three members to start
a new one.
</P>
<P>
   _ SeniorNet, www.seniornet.org: You do not have to be a senior
citizen to participate in one of these nine clubs, which range from
Great Books to Romance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
