<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRETTY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SUCH A PRETTY, PRETTY GIRL': LOVE IS LIKE AN UNHEALTHY OBSESSION
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Drayton Lightfoot, the hero-narrator of Winston Groom's new
novel, ``Such a Pretty, Pretty Girl,'' is not Forrest Gump. Nor is
there any reason that he should be. Groom has every right to move
on to other subjects after having written the novel named for his
lovably dimwitted hero, followed by ``Gump &AMP; Company'' and
``Gumpisms: The Wit and Wisdom of Forrest Gump.''
</P>
<P>
   And he ostensibly has moved on in ``Such a Pretty, Pretty
Girl,'' about a successful screenwriter who gets roped by an old
flame, Delia Jamison, into tracking down whoever is writing her
letters threatening to publicize her kinkier lovemaking habits if
she won't comply with his demands.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Johnny, despite being a former newspaper columnist, a
well-reviewed novelist and the winner of an Oscar, certainly has
his Gumpish moments.
</P>
<P>
   When Delia tells him that the blackmailer wants her to send him
secret signals on the nightly television news broadcast she
anchors, Johnny draws the astonishing conclusion that ``whoever was
sending the letters most likely lived in the L.A. TV-viewing
area.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You might have missed your calling,'' responds Rick Olsen, a
detective friend of Delia's husband, without apparent irony.
</P>
<P>
   When Delia informs him that the letters have been postmarked
Boston, New York, Miami, Chicago, Atlanta and Washington, Johnny
concludes that ``this guy sending the letters, he's obviously
shrewd.'' He adds, ``Sounds like he's either got accomplices or
he's a traveling man.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he warns Delia ``that if you keep off the air every time
he makes one of these demands, he's going to wise up.''
</P>
<P>
   And in still another burst of ratiocination he describes what
happened after Delia insisted on coming to the hotel room he lives
in. ``She got up and walked around the room, one hand on a hip. I
felt something stir inside me. Here was someone I found
passionately attractive, walking around in my own hotel room, so,
so ... Well, obviously this was neither the time nor place.
Besides, Rick most likely had his people `keeping an eye on her.'
It could look sticky.''
</P>
<P>
   As if her being there in the first place would not arouse the
suspicions of those following her.
</P>
<P>
   Groom's hero really isn't meant to appear as Inspector
Clouseau-like as he does in these instances. After all, he and
Delia originally bonded at a New Year's Eve party over a favorable
review of one of his novels that she had read in The New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   When he accepts an invitation to meet her husband after deciding
to help find her blackmailer, she invites him to go swimming: ``The
water's warm. We always swim here before lunch. It improves your
appetite. Besides, I want to talk to you about T.S. Eliot.''
</P>
<P>
   Filling us in on their past, Johnny describes a trip to Bermuda
they once took. After cooking her rock lobsters, ``we stayed up and
talked for a while. Delia wanted to discuss literature, mostly
mid-20th-century women writers of whom she had become fond.'' He
adds that the next day she turned out to have ``a half-finished
Edith Wharton novel in her purse,'' perhaps to show that she was
fond of early-20th-century women writers as well.
</P>
<P>
   Back in California it strikes him as paradoxical that on a sunny
morning he ``was feeling, to steal a line from Melville, `cloaked
in a damp, drizzly, foggy November of the soul.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all this pasted-on sophistication, Johnny finally
strikes you as stupid at the deepest level. This is because he
can't seem to get Delia out of his system, despite what he
describes as ``an unbreachable span developing between us.'' (As if
one could reduce a distance by breaking through it.)
</P>
<P>
   Johnny finds Delia absolutely fascinating, and he tries to sell
her to the reader as such by describing her as beautiful,
mysterious, passionately carnal and, above all, honest to a fault.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Delia's honesty turns out to be the engine of the
novel. It eventually explains the trouble she has gotten herself
into. The book's ironic epigraph is ``Honesty is the best policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet this reader did not find Delia attractive in the least.
Beautiful she may be, ``with incredibly long legs,'' ``dark green
eyes, almost like jade, and long auburn hair.'' But where Johnny
tries to paint her as mysterious, she comes across as infuriatingly
evasive. Where he offers her up as sexy, she seems little more than
a practiced tease. As for her vaunted honesty, she may have a gift
for blunt speech, but she could not be more dishonest in her
conduct, sending Johnny on a mission to explore her past, yet
withholding essential information lest he find out what he needs to
know.
</P>
<P>
   In his devotion to Delia, Johnny truly resembles Forrest Gump.
But where Forrest's loyalty to the neurotic Jenny is a redemptive
side of his dimwittedness, Johnny's obsession with Delia seems
nothing but stupid. Clearly Groom continues to be compelled by the
figure of the beautiful woman without mercy. But whatever more of
interest he has to say on the subject, this novel doesn't express
it. The prettiness of the ``pretty, pretty girl'' is barely even
skin deep.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SUCH A PRETTY, PRETTY GIRL'
</P>
<P>
   By Winston Groom
</P>
<P>
   306 pages. Random House. $23.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
