<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Thursday, March 18. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
AMWEST-STRIKE (Washington) - It is an emotionally charged standoff
between entrenched opponents _ flight attendants vs. America West _
with both sides fighting for the upper hand in the last hours of
negotiations before Friday night's strike deadline. By PETER
CORBETT. Story will move in the ``F'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
TOWNLAK-ECOLOGY (Tempe, Ariz.) - While Tempe city officials and
development boosters cheer the progress of Town Lake,
environmentalists are quietly bemoaning threats from the Rio Salado
Project. Mosquitoes, disease, birds in the flight paths of Sky
Harbor International Airport _ all could result from the creation
of a 1 billion gallon artificial lake, which Tempe officials plan
to fill this summer. The latest threat: exotic species of turtles
from the Phoenix Zoo, which are being removed from the zoo's
popular lagoon to prevent them from migrating into Town Lake. By
STEVE YOZWIAK. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ROCKET KID (Phoenix) - Thirteen-year-old David Silverstein is
suspended by the Deer Valley School District for the remainder of
the term by a hearing officer. A search of his locker two weeks ago
turned up a device that was deemed a ``firearm'' under district
guidelines. Even Homer Hickam of ``October Sky'' fame gets into the
act, telling the district to ``lighten up.'' By JIM GINTONIO. Story
will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BOOKS-NEW (Undated) _ Capsule reviews of new and notable books. By
ANNE STEPHENSON, Special to the Republic. Story moved in the ``E''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
NOTARO-COLUMN (Phoenix) - ``So, are you ready to get married?'' I
asked my best friend Jeff as he, my other best friend Jamie and I
sat down to eat lunch at a sidewalk cafe in Pasadena last Saturday.
I had flown to California for the three of us to have somewhat of a
last hurrah, since he was the final one of us to tie the knot and
would be a married man by the month's end. Jeff looked puzzled.
``I'm ready,'' he snapped as he spread a napkin over his lap. ``I
bought an extra pillow.'' By LAURI NOTARO. Story will move in the
``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
