<HEADER>
A4268 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-FARMERS-HNS &LR;      03-17 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-FARMERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LAWMAKERS COMPLAIN OF DELAYED FARM AID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas lawmakers criticized the Clinton
administration Wednesday for its delays in distributing $2 billion
in disaster assistance to offset crop and livestock losses last
year from a stubborn drought.
</P>
<P>
   A heavy demand for assistance nationwide has caused delays,
according to Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman, who has pledged to
release funds as ``expeditiously and as fairly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton declared all 254 Texas counties disaster areas
last year because of drought conditions in the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   But Texas farmers and ranchers who suffered losses are still
waiting for federal disaster assistance as this year's planting
season nears an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Texas farmers the money will be too late to provide any
assistance with spring planting,'' said Rep. Henry Bonilla,
R-Texas, a member of the House Appropriations subcommittee on
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Many Texas counties are enduring drought conditions again this
year. Last week, Gov. George W. Bush sought federal assistance for
167 counties due to the lack of rainfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we were hit with a tremendous drought, which ended
with a substantial flood. Now we are back in a drought situation,''
said William Mitchell, the judge of Uvalde County west of San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have declared Uvalde County a disaster area; we have filed
our applications,'' Mitchell said. ``We feel we have done what we
can do locally to trigger something from Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Phil Gramm and Kay Bailey Hutchison, both Texas
Republicans, told Glickman Wednesday of their ``deepening concern''
about the delay in disaster relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``These delays are building to a crisis,'' they wrote in a
letter to the secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Glickman told lawmakers earlier this month that the Department
of Agriculture has extended the application deadlines for disaster
assistance until April 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``Due to the heavy demand from farmers, USDA is taking longer
than we anticipated to implement (the program) fully,'' Glickman
said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said USDA has provided other forms of assistance to
farmers and ranchers who suffered losses due to weather in 1998 and
previous years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has really reached the point of being ridiculous,''
Bonilla said. ``Farmers and ranchers have not fully recovered from
last year's devastating drought, and we are facing more of the same
this year in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is bureaucracy at its worst,'' Bonilla said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Larry Combest, chairman of the House Agriculture Committee,
has called Glickman to appear before his panel later this month to
answer questions about delays in the disaster assistance program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
