<HEADLINE>
THE SCOOP ON THE OSCARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Talk, talk and more talk. No matter where you are
this month _ whether it's the beauty parlor, the grocery store
checkout line, or a black-tie dinner, folks are yakking about
Sunday's Academy Awards. There's the buzz about who's going (will
Monica Lewinsky really show up?), what they'll be wearing (Armani
is a front-runner), who the presenters are (the motion picture
academy isn't telling) and yadda, yadda, yadda.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for some fresh Oscar topics? We collected a few juicy
tidbits to share before the big night.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHOOPI GETS A BIG MACK(IE) ATTACK!
</P>
<P>
   glitz-and-glamour king bob mackie was cornered at a recent
fund-raiser at the Regent Beverly Wilshire Hotel, and he confirmed
that he and his partner, Ray Aghayan, will be dressing Whoopi
Goldberg in a number of glam gowns for her mistress of ceremonies
gig at the Academy Awards. We also heard she'll be wearing Harry
Winston jewels.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
OSCAR'S IN THE BAG
</P>
<P>
   That tres trendy purse designer Kathrine Baumann of Beverly
Hills held a press conference earlier this week to unveil her
latest one-of-a-kind designs that will be carried to the Academy
Awards. The tiny Austrian crystal-covered minaudieres (that's
French for tiny jeweled evening bag) include a grand piano style
for Celine Dion; a crown-shaped bag for ``Elizabeth'' star Cate
Blanchett; a military purple heart design to be carried by Steven
Spielberg's wife, Kate Capshaw; and a similar design made of real
gold bullion (valued at $150,000) for Rita Wilson in honor of
husband Tom Hanks' role in ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SEX SIRENS GO SHOPPING
</P>
<P>
   Melanie Griffith and Sharon Stone are busy with their Oscar gown
shopping, and we heard they're considering Elizabeth Galindo, a
couture designer from Sacramento. At least they've got appointments
to see her latest designs.
</P>
<P>
   While Galindo may not be a household name (yet), her celebrity
client list already includes Demi Moore and Sophia Loren.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
POLITICIANS GO HOLLYWOOD
</P>
<P>
   California's first lady Sharon Davis and Gov. Gray Davis are
going to the Oscars. And _ surprise, surprise _ she's already
chosen which gown she'll wear. It's a dropped-waist gown in black
and pewter taffeta by her favorite designer, Pol Atteu of Beverly
Hills.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HOTEL HANKY-PANKY
</P>
<P>
   The chi-chi (Mobil gave them five stars) Peninsula hotel in
Beverly Hills is already completely booked for Oscar night with
umpteen nominees and presenters, but they won't say which ones. We
also heard the hotel has arranged to ``buy'' the parking spaces up
and down the nearby streets that night to accommodate all the limos
that will be lining up to whisk the stars to the awards.
</P>
<P>
   But wait, there's more. According to the hotel publicist, Oscar
nominees are treated to jet-lag massages, personally monogrammed
pillow cases and Frette robes. And there's even a seamstress named
Lulu on hand to sew on missing bugle beads or let out seams that
shrank over night.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
COSTUMERS COME OUT OF THE CLOSET
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Every year there's an Oscar for best costumes, and this year
you can be the judge. Authentic costumes from each Academy Award
nominee are on display now through April 16 at the Fashion
Institute of Design and Merchandising, 919 S. Grand Ave., Los
Angeles. It's free, and the hours are 11 a.m. to 3 p.m. Monday
through Saturday. For more information, call (323) 624-1200.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FAMOUS DESIGNERS TELL ALL
</P>
<P>
   Halston designer Kevan Hall predicts we'll see a sportier look
on young Hollywood stars that will include billowy taffeta skirts
with cashmere tops, but there will still be plenty of beaded gowns.
The cost of a typical Oscar-worthy gown, he says, is $1,500 to
$4,000, depending on the amount of crystal beading.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hall hasn't dished any dirt on the stars he dresses,
Pamela Dennis has admitted she made a fashion faux pas on Kate
Winslet's Golden Globes gown. According to a story in this week's
TV Guide, Dennis said she should have made the dress with a black
lining instead of the less-flattering nude shade. She also revealed
who returns the dresses she loans, and she says Jamie Lee Curtis
returned her last gown with flowers and a note.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HAIR DRESSER CUTS AND TELLS
</P>
<P>
   Frederic Fekkai, the official hair dresser for the Oscars,
predicts stars and starlets are going for shiny, straight hair like
Gwyneth Paltrow's 'do, and several will be coloring their hair
blond or red. Men, he says, are going for a short,
clean-but-slightly rumpled look. And they may be sporting Clark
Gable moustaches instead of goatees.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PRESS GETS POLISHED
</P>
<P>
   There's so much hype with the Oscars that even the fashion press
is expected to dress up. Although designers aren't offering gowns,
several beauty experts, including Frederic Fekkai and Bobbi Brown,
have sent invitations to fashion editors for complimentary hair and
makeup applications just before the awards ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   TALK TO ME, HARRY
</P>
<P>
   Carol Broadie-Gelles of Harry Winston was in town for the annual
pre-Oscar fashion forecast earlier this month and she predicted
we'll be seeing a lot of stars with diamond tiaras or hairpins
instead of those tacky banana clips or cutesy daisies. It's a
glittery but understated look, she explained, and those who don't
put diamonds in their hair will most likely wear diamond necklaces
that rest on the collarbone and a pair of huge emerald-cut diamond
stud earrings. Like the designer gowns, these jewels are loaned for
one night only.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SURGEON SHOOTS STARS
</P>
<P>
   Talk about pressure. It's no longer enough that you get a new
'do for the Oscars. Now you're supposed to get a quickie pre-Oscar
touch-up at the plastic surgeon's office. Honest! Dr. Frank Ryan
says he has so many celebrity patients requesting quickie peels and
collagen injections that he's staying open until midnight on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
OSCAR GOWNS ON AUCTION BLOCK
</P>
<P>
   That gorgeous greenish-blue gown Kate Winslet wore to the Oscars
last year, as well as award-night ensembles from Julia Roberts,
Sharon Stone, Lauren Bacall and Janet Leigh, will be auctioned by
Christie's at a gala charity affair in New York tonight. Fashion
fans can still purchase Christie's coffee table-quality catalog,
``Unforgettable: Fashion of the Oscars,'' through the Home Shopping
Network for $39.95 (plus shipping and handling). Proceeds will
benefit the American Foundation for AIDS Research (AMFAR). For more
information, call (888) 872-3992.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A BAN ON BOW TIES
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Come Oscar night, the fashion police may be citing
Tinseltown's leading men for breaking the black-tie rule. For
years, the term ``black tie'' has meant a tuxedo with a black bow
tie, but according to Patty Fox, the official stylist for the
Academy Awards, we'll be seeing long ties with tuxedos.
</P>
<P>
   At the pre-Oscar fashion preview for the press, Fox confided,
``The long tie with a tuxedo is a more sleek, modern look than a
bow tie. And, yes, you could say it's more L.A., especially with a
black shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   She also hinted that a few Hollywood hunks may also exchange
their opera pumps for open-toed Birkenstock-style shoes accented
with rhinestone buckles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NOMINEES GET TICKED OFF
</P>
<P>
   The Movado Group, maker of Movado, Concord and Corum
wristwatches, is offering to loan diamond-encrusted timepieces to
Oscar nominees. According to spokesman Roger Joseph, Hollywood's
elite will be invited this week to L'Ermitage Hotel in Los Angeles
to choose which face they'll wear. Like other fab fashions on loan,
they'll need to give it back.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
OSCAR PARTIES CRASHED:
</P>
<P>
   Didn't get invited to the Oscars? You'll get star treatment at
the ``Night at the Academy Awards'' gala Sunday at the Twin Palms
restaurant in Pasadena. The benefit for Five Acres, the
Altadena-based center for abused children, will have the awards
coverage projected on several large screens while serving dinner.
Tickets are $135, and the number to call is (626) 798-6793, Ext.
244. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 1831EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
