<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
  
 For Release THURSDAY AMs, March 18, 1999  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-BOESAK (Johannesburg) _ The Rev. Allan Boesak,
courageous anti-apartheid leader, is found guilty of fraud and
theft of foreign donations aimed at helping apartheid victims. By
Kurt Shillinger. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Budapest) _ Talks to end the fighting in Kosovo
come close to ending in failure, with mediators complaining that
the Serbs are refusing to discuss the deployment of NATO troops. By
Susan Milligan. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SCANDAL (Lausanne, Switzerland) _ IOC expels all six members
in Salt Lake City deal. They are believed the first kicked out for
corruption in 105 years. By John Powers. 1000 words. (a and s
coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-MISSILE (Washington) -- Senate votes for a bill calling
for a nationwide defense against limited ballistic missile attack.
Measure had been opposed by President Clinton, many Senate
Democrats. By Anne E. Kornblut. 650 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HEARTBURN-CANCER (Undated) _ Heartburn deserves respect. That's
the warning researchers sounded based on new evidence that severe,
recurrent, long-lasting heartburn can be an early warning sign for
a virulent form of cancer of the esophagus. By Larry Tye. 800
words.
</P>
<P>
   MARIJUANA-MEDICAL (Undated) _ Study finds legitimate medical use
for marijuana in people with AIDS, cancer and other diseases.
There's no evidence that pot is a ``gateway'' to harder drugs. By
Dolores Kong. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   PATRIOTS-MOVE (Hartford, Conn.) _ Governor John Rowland says
reports that the Patriots stadium deal is deadlocked and may die
are wrong. But the April 2 deadline for an agreement to move the
most famous steam plant in New England could well be missed, giving
the the team the opportunity to pull out. By Tina Cassidy. (a and s
coding)
</P>
<P>
   NHAMP-TAXES (Concord, N.H.) _ Senate, under pressure and
hopelessly fractured, to hear plans on how to raise the money
needed to end New Hampshire's education-funding crisis. By Ralph
Jiminez and Royal Ford. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HKN-BRUINS-LEAFS (Toronto) _ By Kevin Paul Dupont.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-CLIPPERS-CELTICS (Boston) By Michael Holley.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   BKN-COMMENT (Boston) _ By Peter May.
</P>
