NYT-03-17-99 1847EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4286 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IOC-SCANDAL-0318-COX     03-17 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOC-SCANDAL-0318-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IOC EXPULSION OF MEMBERS MAY NOT BE ENOUGH TO APPEASE CRITICS
 &HT;    EDs: With IOC-SAMARANCH-0318.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (s) Sports categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ The International Olympic Committee on
Wednesday took steps to move beyond the humiliation of the Salt
Lake City bidding scandal, but it may take some time to tell if the
committee can stay ahead of its legion of critics.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC expelled six members accused of accepting cash, favors
and other gifts during Salt Lake's successful campaign for the 2002
Winter Olympics. The case that involved more than $1 million in
improper inducements has now claimed 10 IOC members. Four others
have resigned.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also promised to begin reform efforts immediately
with the creation of an ethics board to guard against further
corruption plus a special commission to recommend changes to the
bidding process by host cities and the way the 105-year-old
organization conducts its business.
</P>
<P>
   However, the IOC stopped short of satisfying those critics who
have called for the ouster of president Juan Antonio Samaranch. The
membership overwhelmingly granted him a vote of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   After the wrenching exercise of expelling their colleagues, some
IOC members were clearly relieved. Anita DeFrantz, the senior U.S.
member, managed a smile as she waited for an elevator in the lobby
of the Lausanne Palace hotel. ``But this is only the first step,''
she said. ``We have a lot of work to do, but it must start with the
first step.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Rogge, an IOC member from Belgium who was on the special
commission that investigated the Salt Lake allegations, expressed
similar sentiments. ``This was the first turning point, but we have
to continue with reform. We must show we mean business.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one key critic was unimpressed. In a statement released
Wednesday, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., expressed disappointment.
``Expelling members does nothing to address the utter lack of
transparency and accountability in IOC processes,'' McCain said.
``What we must see are concrete reforms. These reforms must
eliminate completely and forever a culture based on gifts and
lavish travel that has brought a dark cloud over the integrity of
the entire Olympic movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Commerce Committee member, Sen. Ted Stevens, has drawn
up legislation that would strip the IOC of tax-exempt status.
Congressional hearings into the Salt Lake scandal are scheduled for
next month.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction among corporate sponsors, which could lose the
privilege of writing off their sponsorships, ranged from positive
to guardedly optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically from the onset, we have been telling the IOC to go
deep and go wide in their investigations, and it appears they are
now doing that,'' said John LaBella, a spokesman for Eastman Kodak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is the beginning of change,'' said Susan
Rosenberg, spokeswoman for United Parcel Service. ``It is a step in
the right direction. It is a demonstration that the IOC membership
is intent on making change, but just how far and how wide remains
to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will reserve judgement on whether we think the change has
gone far enough until we see the full outcome of the meeting (that
concludes today),'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference after the expulsions, Dick Pound, the IOC
member who chaired the commission that investigated the
allegations, said the committee was at the ``end of the
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to deliver on what we said at the beginning of
the crisis,'' said Pound, also an IOC vice president. ``It is good
to have this difficult part of our work completed so we can go
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Pound said the IOC intends to reform the host city bidding
process, enact ethical reforms and begin to make basic changes in
the committee's openness and accountability by the end of the year,
which is an Olympic year that will culminate in the 2000 Sydney
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a fair amount of work ahead of us to recover, regroup
and move on,'' Pound said.
</P>
<P>
   At least one of the expelled members seemed to accept the idea
that he was sacrificed for the IOC. Agustin Arroyo, who had been
the IOC member from Ecuador since 1968, said it was his misfortune
to be selected for slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press, they wanted to have heads knocked off,'' Arroyo
told a surging mass of reporters and photographers. ``Mine happened
to be in the way.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Arroyo, the IOC expelled Zein El Abdin Ahmed
Abdel Gadir of the Sudan, Jean-Claude Ganga of the Republic of
Congo, Lamine Keita of Mali, Sergio Santander of Chile and Paul
Wallwork of Samoa. They are believed to be the first IOC members
ejected for corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Ganga, the most prominent IOC member expelled, said he would
accept the IOC decision, but he complained that the investigation
was done hastily and incompletely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're also thinking at this moment of the African sportsmen;
who will have to realize that our fight faces a new test,'' Ganga
said. ``We have known others, such as racial discrimination,
poverty and indifference. This what we face day to day. Starting
from today this will be the case for injustice and exclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Ganga, who organized the boycott by African countries of the
1976 Montreal Games, has said in recent days that his case was
politically motivated and that the IOC was targeting its African
members. Three of the six expelled members are Africans.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
