<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-BERBERIAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMPARTZOUM BERBERIAN, 93; PROLIFIC SYMPHONIC COMPOSER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hampartzoum Berberian, a prolific composer whose work showed
both Western and Eastern musical influences, died of cancer
Saturday in the Armenian Nursing Home in Boston. He was 93.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Berberian, of Watertown, Mass., was the composer of many
vocal, choral and operatic works as well as symphonic and chamber
pieces. His works includes the choral work ``Lincoln at
Gettysburg,'' which was inspired by the Gettysburg address, and
``Requiem Aeternam,'' which was written to commemorate the the
massacre of some 1.5 million Armenians by the Ottoman Turks from
1915 to 1920.
</P>
<P>
   The Masterworks Chorale and Orchestra, performed ``Requiem
Aeternam'' at Cary Memorial Hall in Lexington in December 1980. It
is an ambitious piece for orchestra, chorus and vocal sextet drawn
from a long poem by Yeghishe Charentz
</P>
<P>
   ``Of its sincerity, and of the directness with which that
sincerity was communicated, there was never any doubt,'' Richard
Buell wrote in a review published in the Globe on Dec. 8, 1980.
``The work's strongest qualities came across cumulatively, rather
than through any particularly felicitous local detail. . . . The
work's large spiritedness certainly came through, particularly in
the big choruses that might have harkened distantly to Prokofiev's
`Alexander Nevsky.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Because it was sung in Armenian, Buell admitted that he could
say nothing of the chorus's enuniciation, though, ``there was a
full in-tune, hearty sound to everything they undertook.''
</P>
<P>
   The composer, Buell wrote, ``looked quite pleased to be
receiving the acclaim that came his way at the end of the
evening.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Berberian was born in Adana, Turkey. He became a US citizen
in 1968. His musical engagements took him to many countries in
Latin America, Europe and the Middle East. He was a founder of the
Teketan Cultural Association.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves three sons, Hratch of South Dakota, Vahe of
Pennsylvania and Shahe ``Charlie'' of Somerville, Mass.; a
daughter, Nayiri of Watertown; and four grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
