<SLUG> BC-TOSCA-OPERA-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN `TOSCA,' A PAVAROTTI RENEWED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Infirmities of various kinds have made Luciano
Pavarotti's appearances at the Metropolitan Opera fairly rare over
the last couple of years, but he did turn up for his
30th-anniversary gala early this season _ the performance is to be
broadcast by PBS on March 31 _ and soon after it, the Met announced
that he would sing three performances as Cavaradossi in the
company's production of ``Tosca.''
</P>
<P>
   The first was on Tuesday evening, when Carol Vaness also joined
the cast in the title role, and James Morris took over the role of
Scarpia. The new cast is to sing the Saturday afternoon
performance, which is one of the Met's international radio
broadcasts, and again next Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lesson to be learned about the clash of evil and
virtue in ``Tosca,'' but a cynical one, because although Scarpia is
dead and his regime is crumbling, evil still crushes Cavaradossi
and Tosca in the end. The lesson a listener took away on Tuesday
was more mundane, perhaps, but noteworthy nevertheless. Mainly, it
was that one should not underestimate Pavarotti's power to
re-create himself.
</P>
<P>
   The indications had suggested otherwise in recent years: His
voice was sounding tattered, his acting, never very supple, had
become increasingly stiff, and he often seemed wholly uninterested
in what he was doing. Yet here he was, 50 pounds lighter and
looking comparatively trim, and having undergone hip and knee
replacement surgery that made him considerably more agile than he
has seemed in years. Instead of slowly lowering himself to the
ground after the firing squad execution, as has been his manner in
recent performances, he did a somewhat more realistic fall and
roll, with help from a pile of sandbags. And vocally, he sounded
fresh, powerful and engaged in the role.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that this was the ``Tosca'' of one's dreams,
if anyone dreams of ``Tosca.'' Nello Santi conducted a thoughtful
performance that flowed at a leisurely pace, and although that made
for some lovely effects, there were moments when both Pavarotti and
Ms. Vaness often seemed intent on pushing him forward, and tended
to anticipate the beat.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Vaness was fighting other problems, including a wobble on
sustained notes and a strident edge. Yet there were moments of
beauty, not least in her rendering of ``Vissi d'arte.'' Morris was
in good voice, and is a compelling presence on the stage. His
Scarpia is slightly distant, slightly bland, but there may be a
point: Instead of portraying him as a pillar of malevolent power,
Morris makes him aristocratic and rather ordinary, as if to show
that evil can be as virulent when it is banal as when it is
monumental.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
