<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-BOESAK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-APARTHEID LEADER GUILTY IN FUNDS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ The Rev. Allan Boesak, a charismatic leader of
the struggle against apartheid, was convicted Wednesday of
mishandling funds donated in support of his prodemocracy work in
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The Cape High Court found Boesak guilty of three counts of theft
and one of fraud totaling $208,000, including funds raised by
musician Paul Simon during his ``Graceland'' tour.
</P>
<P>
   He was exonerated on 23 similar charges. The ruling marks the
first time a leading antiapartheid figure was held responsible for
a serious crime since Winnie Mandela's 1991 conviction on
kidnapping and assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``The accused wrongfully and unlawfully appropriated money
intended for children of South Africa,'' said Judge John Foxcroft
in his lengthy judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Boesak, a close friend of President Nelson Mandela, was visible
shaken by the verdict. Sentencing was reserved until next Tuesday,
and it was unclear whether the cleric would serve jail time.
However, a former accountant of Boesak is serving a six-year
sentence after being found guilty on similar charges.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to the ruling reflected the tensions in a society
struggling to reestablish the rule of law after decades of
apartheid. Opposition parties hailed the verdict as a victory
against ruling class corruption. But many blacks resent any move
that tarnishes the struggle and its heroes. Supporters of the
fallen cleric left the courtroom shouting ``Viva Boesak'' and
``Long Live Boesak.''
</P>
<P>
   Boesak was at the forefront of the liberation struggle in South
Africa during the 1980s. He was one of the founding members of the
United Democratic Front, the internal wing of the then-outlawed
African National Congress. He aided those who suffered at the hands
of the state and spent time in solitary confinement on more than
one occasion.
</P>
<P>
   A week before F. W. de Klerk became president in 1989, Boesak
led 30,000 marchers with Archbishop Desmond Tutu to the steps of
Cape Town's city hall in protest over police brutality in the
townships. He was one of the first allowed to visit Mandela prior
to the future president's release from prison in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The cleric's legal troubles started soon after Mandela's
government rose to power in 1994. Boesak became leader of the ANC
in the Western Cape, but accusations of misuse of funds prevented
him from becoming South Africa's ambassador to the United Nations
in Geneva, a post to which he had been nominated.
</P>
<P>
   Boesak's Foundation for Peace and Justice, a now-defunct
organization whose stated goal was to educate votersand help
victims of apartheid, has been at the center of allegations of
misuse of funds since the early 1990s. The Danish charity DanChurch
Aid alleged in 1994 that money it sent to finance the building of a
church and other facilities in the town of Caravan was instead used
to pay for Boesak's house. Coca-Cola later suspected that at least
part of its $50,000 contribution was similarly misappropriated.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations around Boesak and his organization snowballed. A
local newspaper reported in late 1995 that the cleric had
established a secret trust fund and was diverting charitable
contributions from the foundation without the knowledge of the
donors.
</P>
<P>
   Also in 1995, allegations arose over the apparent misuse of
funds raised by Paul Simon in 1988 for the Children's Trust, a
separate concern of which Boesak, Tutu, and antiapartheid activist
Mary Burton were trustees. Both Tutu and Burton later resigned
their posts.
</P>
<P>
   At the time these details emerged Boesak led a conspicuous
lifestyle: Living in an expensive home, driving an Italian sports
car, and sporting a young new wife shortly after obtaining a
divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Boesak originally faced 32 charges of fraud and theft. Five were
dismissed after a former bookkeeper and key state witness, Freddie
Steenkamp, admitted during the trial last December that he had
falsely accused his former boss to cover his own misdeeds.
Steenkamp is now serving six years for theft.
</P>
<P>
   Foxcroft acquitted Boesak of 23 other charges Wednesday,
including those pertaining to contributions from Coca-Cola,
DanChurch, and the Church of Norway. He was found guilty of
misappropriating $72,000 from funds donated by Simon for the
Children's Trust, stealing more than $120,000 given by a Swedish
aid agency to promote voter education, and diverting $50,000 from
his foundation toward two private homes and sundry comforts for his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   The ANC remained silent after the verdict. So did Mandela, who
twice called on supporters to help Boesak pay for legal costs
during the trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 1900EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
