<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4308 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TALK-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      03-17 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN JUSTIFYING INDISCRETION, A SPIN DOCTOR DOES A TANGO
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In just a few days, George Stephanopoulos' book has replaced
Monica Lewinsky's as No. 1 on the New York Times best-seller list
(for March 28), outselling her book in some places by nearly four
to one.
</P>
<P>
   To many people, not necessarily those in book publishing, this
is perhaps surprising because one has the feeling she must be known
to everyone in the world. Even her persona has been reduced to one
word, Monica, like Madonna.
</P>
<P>
   But last week ``Monica's Story'' (St. Martin's Press) by Andrew
Morton was a happening. Now it's merely a book. And there's very
little in it that hasn't been known for months, and even those tiny
slivers of fresh confession were bestowed on us in her bland
television interview with Barbara Walters.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanopoulos' ``All Too Human: A Political Education'' (Little
Brown), on the other hand, has for many the slight sense of
betrayal that intrigues the peeper in all of us.
</P>
<P>
   It does present a sketchy new look at the Clinton White House,
with little discussion of policy, and Stephanopoulos, who has
started a 25-city book tour that includes national television
interviews and is scheduled to last into May, is after all a
professional spin-master who was there and who told, somewhat.
</P>
<P>
   Knowledgeable and boyishly self-deprecatory, he is an effective
interviewee, so it's not entirely surprising that his book's sales
got off to such a fast start. What was surprising to many in book
publishing was the increase that followed a long excerpt in
Newsweek last week.
</P>
<P>
   Usually such extensive excerpting sates the public's need to
know; in this case the excerpt resonated into more book sales, in
part because of Stephanopoulos' skills in presenting his material,
both in the book and in person in interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, while few in book publishing thought that Ms.
Lewinsky's book would have but a hasty moment at the top because of
the familiarity and tedium of the material, Stephanopoulos' book is
not only a good read but also has the embroidery of controversy
about it, the question of propriety.
</P>
<P>
   He signed on to be the president's man. He had the access. And
he talked about the lies and the quirkiness and even the
domesticity of the White House. The tidbits have the appeal of
salted peanuts. One is not enough. (Ms. Lewinsky's book dropped to
No. 3 on the Times hard-cover nonfiction list for March 28 and is
expected to keep falling. ``The Greatest Generation'' by Tom
Brokaw, published by Random House, is No. 2).
</P>
<P>
   Stephanopoulos rode being the president's man to fame and a
reported $2.85 million book contract. So far the publisher has gone
back to press five times, and nearly 600,000 copies are in print.
Ms. Lewinsky's sexual fumblings with the president earned a book
advance that was said to be about $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Stephanopoulos, the Kennedy men _ Theodore C.
Sorensen, Pierre Salinger and Arthur Schlesinger Jr. _ signed on
and have stayed quiet, except for policy matters, for all these
years, and the mind reels when one thinks of the gamy tales they
might have told. Also, by contrast, President Kennedy was loyal to
his people.
</P>
<P>
   What has changed between the two presidencies are the public's
standards for presidential behavior, the apparent national craving
for dish, and book publishing, which since President Reagan's
administration has been willing to pay so much money for
presidential literary bric-a-brac.
</P>
<P>
   John Lewis Gaddis, a Yale history professor, said: ``It's
probably fair to say that in the end most'' important presidential
advisers ``have broken down and overcome whatever scruples they
have and have done memoirs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There used to be the Marshall principle, he said, invoking the
creator of the postwar plan for European recovery. ``When General
Marshall left after being secretary of state and secretary of
defense, he said he wouldn't write a memoir, that it would be a
betrayal of confidence, and he never did.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, professor Gaddis said: ``Is writing
the memoir a betrayal or not? The dilemma is basically that if you
don't write your memoir, then you tend to sink into the obscurity
of history. It's too lucrative not to; I would guess that for any
president or Cabinet officer who hires anyone to work for them in a
confidential capacity, it would only be realistic for them to
expect a memoir to come.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, Henry Kissinger, in his memoirs, the third volume of
which, ``Years of Renewal'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster), is in the
bookstores, took a somewhat middle ground. He lets the reader know
there were certain people he didn't like; he had a rueful attitude
toward President Nixon; but, in the end, he didn't serve people up
with trivia.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanopoulos' editor, Bill Phillips, senior executive editor
at Little, Brown, said that it was not fair to criticize the former
White House aide for betrayal ``when the book is more critical of
the author's shortcomings than of anyone else.'' Stephanopoulos
added that he saw his book not as an insider tell-all, but a story
of his adventure in government, a sort of Andy Hardy in the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Stephanopoulos' experiences are his to sell, and he
can make the case that in lying to him and other staff members
about Ms. Lewinsky, it was the president who betrayed, not his
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought to myself, the tests I made, was what I had to say
relevant, fair and accurate,'' Stephanopoulos said in a telephone
interview on his book tour. ``I did my best to pick representative
moments that were fun and interesting.'' The book came before the
Monica Lewinsky story, but now, he said, ``the issues raised by
Gennifer Flowers and the draft became more important after Monica;
they showed the stepping stones of a pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It's like the novel `Portnoy's Complaint.' It was
quite controversial at first, and then it became a novel. Now my
book is an event, but soon it will be a book again.''
</P>
<P>
   Such presidential events are not new, we all now know. When
James T. Callender broke the story of President Jefferson and Sally
Hemings in The Richmond Recorder in 1802, the president's men
denied it, in essence wagging their fingers and insisting he didn't
have sex with that woman. One can only wonder if Jefferson had a
Stephanopoulos who chose silence and discretion rather than, say, a
$500 book advance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
