<HEADER>
A4313 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARTBURN-CANCER-BOS &LR;      03-17 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARTBURN-CANCER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS REPORT HEARTBURN-CANCER LINK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Heartburn deserves respect.
</P>
<P>
   That's the warning researchers sounded Wednesday based on new
evidence that severe, recurrent, long-lasting heartburn can be an
early warning sign for a virulent form of cancer of the esophagus.
That warning is especially significant because while the overall
incidence of such cancers is small, it's increasing faster than any
other cancer in America.
</P>
<P>
   Heartburn may be the most common health complaint, with an
estimated 20 million Americans suffering it every day and 120
million getting it once a month.
</P>
<P>
   So who should worry, and what should they do?
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember the funny commercial about spicy meatballs? We've
trivialized heartburn when we should be taking it seriously,'' says
Dr. Michael Wolfe, chief of gastroenterology at Boston Medical
Center and a national expert on the condition. Any patient whose
heartburn persists for more than five years, he adds, should be
given an endoscopy test to look for pre-cancerous cells.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stuart Spechler, another renowned specialist in the field
who teaches at the University of Texas, is a bit slower to order
the test. His approach, he says, is, ``If someone comes in with
heartburn and has no other warning symptoms like difficulty
swallowing, fever, bleeding or weight loss, I tell them to treat
the heartburn for four to eight weeks with whatever medications we
have. If the symptoms go away and never come back I don't do
anything, but if they don't go away I do an endoscopy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line,'' he adds, ``is that heartburn is a symptom
that has to be taken seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about heartburn and its links to cancer aren't new, but
the study in the current New England Journal of Medicine is giving
them new weight. Researchers at Sweden's Karolinska Institute
looked at all Swedes under 80 living there from the end of 1994 to
the end of 1997, identifying those with esophageal adenocarcinoma,
or the glandular form of cancer of the esophagus that is rising so
fast. Then, using those patients and others with cancer of the
stomach or with no cancer, they explored whether the esophageal
cancer was linked with heartburn and with the regurgitation of
acidified food.
</P>
<P>
   The findings were dramatic: The risk of esophageal
adenocarcinoma was nearly eight times higher among people in whom
heartburn, regurgitation or both occurred at least once a week, and
it was almost 11 times higher among those who suffered the symptoms
at night.
</P>
<P>
   The risk of esophageal cancer rose again when the heartburn and
regurgitation lasted longer, were more severe and kept coming back,
although the link was weak between those symptoms and stomach
cancer. And while antacids and other treatments can relieve
heartburn, there's no evidence that they reduce the risk of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The attention to that glandular form of esophageal cancer, and
its possible warning signs or causes, has grown in recent years as
the cancer itself has spread. While the chance that anyone with
heartburn has the disease is extremely slight, since there are only
about 6,000 cases of adenocarcinoma a year in America, it is the
nation's fastest-growing form of cancer, and is especially
prevalent among white men.
</P>
<P>
   The rapid increase of this cancer may be linked to recent
success in battling Helicobacter pylori, a bacterial infection that
causes ulcers and gastric cancer but apparently offers protection
against cancer of the esophagus.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe believes that the acid that causes heartburn also damages
the lining of the esophagus and may produce a precancerous
condition known as Barrett's esophagus. Others aren't sure of the
mechanism, but say what matters is that heartburn can signal the
potential for cancer, and that if precancerous cells are detected
early the chance of effective treatment rises dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   The question that doctors are debating is which heartburn
patients are at risk of cancer, and whether they should be given an
edoscopy, which costs about $500 and involves the insertion of a
small flexible tube through the mouth into the esophagus. Biopsies
typically are taken of any suspicious-looking areas.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Sidney Cohen, chairman of medicine at Temple University
Medical School in Philadelphia and author of an editorial on the
topic in the current New England Journal, says that while ``99
percent of the individuals with heartburn will not get cancer, the
individuals who get this type of cancer have a very bad outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen worries that by the time additional symptoms show up it
may be too late to check the cancer. ``I'm very bullish,'' he adds.
``I say that if heartburn is serious enough to bring a patient to a
doctor, that patient should have an endoscopy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. J. Thomas LaMont, chief of gastroenterology at Beth
Israel Deaconess Medical Center in Boston, calls that approach ``a
little radical. You'd need an army of endoscopists and the yield
would be so low.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are having frequent heartburn which is not responsive
to medications, and if you're having difficulty swallowing, then
you should consult a physician,'' LaMont adds. ``And the physician
should consider a look with an endoscope.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
