<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4315 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-F22-0318-COX     03-17 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-F22-0318-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    F-22 UNDER FIRE
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal auditors Wednesday urged Congress to slow
production of the futuristic F-22 fighter and warned that
insufficient testing plus delays in computer systems have put the
program on a course toward major cost overruns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a high risk endeavor,'' Louis J. Rodrigues, a defense
auditor for the General Accounting Office, told a Senate Armed
Services subcommittee hearing at which defenders offered generally
glowing reports about the F-22.
</P>
<P>
   Rodrigues said that ``it is unlikely'' that the Air Force will
be able to keep its schedule or its $18.9 billion budget for the
aircraft, which will be assembled by Lockheed Martin at the
company's Marietta, Ga., plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying we don't need the F-22,'' said Rodrigues, whose
agency serves as the investigative arm of Congress. However, he
told the senators that he opposed ``increasing the rate of
production on an aircraft that we're having trouble producing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force wants to start production of the F-22 this year,
with an initial contract for six fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Rodrigues noted that only 5 percent of the planned flight tests
have been completed, in part because of troubles with wing
attachment fittings and welding in the fuselage, work that is being
performed by Seattle-based Boeing. Rodrigues estimated that cost
overruns were already as much as $767 million and recommended
Congress require the Air Force to make certain that the high-tech
prototypes work before opening up the production line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know what happens once we get everybody in jobs,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The remark drew a rejoinder from one avowed booster of the F-22.
``I know what happens when we get everybody employed,'' said Sen.
Max Cleland (D-Ga.). ``They're in Georgia!''
</P>
<P>
   Cleland, who had visited Edwards Air Force Base in California to
see the first two F-22s, said he was pleased with the
``meticulous'' testing.
</P>
<P>
   Under his friendly questioning, Air Force acquisition and
management official Darleen A. Druyun said that despite some
``slips'' in the schedule, she had a ``high level of confidence''
that the program would be back on track and that ``costs will be
back under control'' by next June.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Druyun testified earlier that the Air Force had listed
the savings from reduced testing as one of the efficiencies to
offset rising costs elsewhere in the program.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman (D-Conn.), said he was ``troubled by
potential for cost growth'' for the aircraft, and called the
testimony ''unsettling.'' He said, ''It seems we're having serious
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
