<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4323 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ETHIOPIA-ERITREA-ART-     03-17 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHIOPIA-ERITREA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERITREA CLAIMS VICTORY N BATTLE WITH ETHIOPIANS; HUNDREDS DIE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscriber can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ Eritrea said Wednesday that it had repulsed
Ethiopian troops after a three-day battle along their disputed
border, in fighting that cost the lives of at least several hundred
soldiers and perhaps many more.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrea seemed so confident of victory that the army escorted
foreign journalists to the front on Tuesday for the first time in
nearly a month. Reuters reported that at least 300 Ethiopian
soldiers lay dead along a small stretch of the central front.
</P>
<P>
   But Ethiopia called it a ``drama staged for foreign
journalists,'' accusing Eritrea of planting its own dead and
burnt-out tanks in the battlefield to improve its image after
suffering a major defeat to the west late last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do those reporting know that the destroyed tanks that are
presented belong to Ethiopia, or that the smell of rotting corpses
indeed comes from dead Ethiopian soldiers?'' Ethiopia said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign diplomats in both nations said they generally believed
Eritrea's version of the battles, which began early Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A Western diplomat in the Ethiopian capital, Addis Ababa, said
he believed that Ethiopia had tried to repeat the success it had
had in late February, when it expelled Eritrean forces from the
Badame region, the main area in dispute. But he said it was unclear
if the fighting was in fact Ethiopia's major push in the region,
near Tsorona, Eritrea, about 70 miles southeast of Asmara, the
capital. They speculated that the attack may have been partly a
probe for weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrea, however, said it had ``completely foiled'' a ``major
offensive,'' destroying 57 tanks, capturing another six and
shooting down an Ethiopian fighter plane, a MIG-23, on Monday.
Yemane Ghebremeskel, an Eritrean spokesman, ridiculed Ethiopia's
suggestion that it had planted the bodies. ``They have suffered a
big defeat and they want to downplay it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While refusing to disclose Eritrean casualties, he said that
well over 9,000 Ethiopians had died in the fighting. Ethiopia
denied the claim.
</P>
<P>
   The war between Ethiopia and Eritrea, though a local dispute in
the remote highlands on the Horn of Africa, has been a major
concern to outside nations, in part because of the question of
casualties. Estimates by diplomats and military analysts run from
10,000 dead to twice that or more. Each side is well armed.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute traces back to 1993, when Eritrea separated amicably
from Ethiopia but their 600-mile border was not settled. Fighting
broke out in May 1998, when Eritrea claimed the Badame region and
sent in troops.
</P>
<P>
   After an eight-month lull, fighting resumed last month, and
Ethiopia pushed Eritrean soldiers out of Badame. But fighting
continues because Ethiopia asserts that Eritrean troops still
occupy three other areas it says belong to Ethiopia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 1911EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0351 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4328 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-CAR-FLA-HOTRODS-835     03-17 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CAR-FLA-HOTRODS-835(2TAKES)-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SPORT THAT'S FASTER THAN A JET FIGHTER 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating to correct slug)  (DUPLICATION NOTICE: Also filed in category `s') 
(mk) 
 By DAVE REARDON The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ Take your 100 mph fastballs. Forget about
your Indy racers, your jet fighters and your spaceships, too. They
are all icebergs when compared to National Hot Rod Association drag
racers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the fastest-accelerating creations in the world,''
said Don Robertson, general manager of Gainesville Raceway and
point man for the Mac Tools Gatornationals. ``They're faster than
an F-15 flying off an aircraft carrier. People ask, `Faster than
the space shuttle?' Yes, faster than the space shuttle.''
</P>
<P>
   Gatornationals, one of the NHRA Winston Drag Racing Series'
longest-running events, turns 30 this year and shows no signs of
slowing down _ and that's whether you're talking about the raw
speed spectacle or the more than 100,000 speed worshippers who come
to experience it. Qualifying races begin Thursday and the final
race is Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Although corporate sponsorship is a major force in the sport
today, there are many drivers who don't have big backing. They
invest huge amounts of time, work and money in their cars, trucks
and bikes.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, despite continually improving safety features, they
pay a price by being seriously injured, or even killed. But they
know that risk is part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The element of danger might be part of the attraction for
spectators. But I think if the drivers had their choice, they'd
like to drive 300 mph in perfectly safe conditions,'' said Mike
Lewis, a former driver and NHRA announcer who has been a part of
every Gatornationals. ``The Top Fuel and Funny Car people are like
Chuck Yeager in the X-1 days. They're in uncharted territory.''
</P>
<P>
   It's always been that way for Gatornationals and drag racing in
general.
</P>
<P>
   The NHRA was already a few years old when organization founder
Wally Parks toured the newly built Gainesville Raceway in 1969 and
approved a new event. The other venues were in the West; one in the
South made sense, in part because of the weather.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Gainesville became a meeting point, not only for
rival racers, but also for merchandisers and distributors to show
new wares and make contacts, and for car buffs to get away from the
chill of March.
</P>
<P>
   Times in the early years were slow by today's standards. But it
wasn't long before Gainesville and Gatornationals gained a
reputation for hospitality and a fast track.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd all come to town and there would be billboards welcoming
us,'' Lewis said. ``People really made us feel special when we came
to Gainesville, whether they were the hotel people, law enforcement
or the community in general. It probably helped that it was also
very fun for the people coming out of the cold weather.''
</P>
<P>
   On the track, Don ``Big Daddy'' Garlits became the first
dominant figure. He won the first of four Top Fuel titles in 1972,
running a 6.17-second lap at 243.90 mph. He set the pace through
the '70s with two more championships at Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Garlits came back with the radically designed JP-1,
which he said was designed to ``punch a hole in the atmosphere,
allowing the rest of the car to drive through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Garlits knows if he truly entered another dimension, but
the car did blow away previous course records with a 5.503-second
lap at 268.65 mph, good for his fourth Gatornationals win.
</P>
<P>
   Don ``The Snake'' Prudhomme was to Funny Cars in the early years
what Garlits was to Top Fuel _ the best and the fastest at
Gainesville and a huge crowd favorite. He won three titles in the
'70s. In 1975, his Monza ran 6.52 at 172.74 _ more than a second
better than Dale Funk's winning elapsed time of that year in Top
Fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every now and then the funny cars catch up and the dragsters
pick themselves up and assert themselves again,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Enough numbers. You want human interest? How about a father-son
story.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Connie and Scott Kalitta met in the final of the Top
Fuel competition. Scott was faster in the early rounds, but Dad was
faster when it counted _ in the final.
</P>
<P>
   Drag racing is one of the few sports where age and gender truly
don't matter. This has been proved often at Gatornationals, where
Eddie Hill won his second consecutive Top Fuel title in 1993 _ at
age 57.
</P>
<P>
   In the early '90s, Warren Johnson ruled the pro stock category,
winning here every year from 1991 to 1994. Toss in his victories in
1984 and '85 and you have the most dominant Gatornationals racer in
any class.
</P>
<P>
   Today, at an age when many mull retirement, Johnson, 55, still
works on getting that extra microsecond. Johnson won again at
Gainesville last year _ one of his nine victories during the 1998
Winston Series.
</P>
<P>
   Woman-driver jokes don't fly at Gainesville Raceway, but woman
drivers do. Shirley Muldowney captured Top Fuel honors in 1981 and
1982. In 1990 Vonnie Mills and Janice Siegal won in Super Gas and
Super Comp, respectively. Mills was injured when her '88 Beretta
caught fire at the end of her final run, but she returned from the
hospital in time to be honored at the winners' circle.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The recent performance exploits of John Force in Funny Cars, and
Kenny Bernstein and Joe Amato in Top Fuel, are well-documented;
they've paved the way to make 300 mph passes as close to routine as
anything can be in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Some drag racing veterans say the increased speeds are mostly
due to big-money sponsorship allowing the best in technology.
</P>
<P>
   Although tracks, especially Gainesville, are safer now, and drag
racing does have a bit of a video game feel to it because of the
high-tech aspect, the sport is still tough _ and still dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Darrell Gwynn. In 1989 and '90, he won Top Fuel at
Gainesville and was the NHRA's rising star. But he was paralyzed
below the chest and lost part of an arm at an exhibition in England
one month after his 1990 Gatornationals win. Gwynn later made an
emotional return to Gainesville as a team manager and car owner.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who still doesn't believe the danger only has to look
back to 1997 and Al Hofmann. He came to Gatornationals that year
without corporate backing and had lost ace crew chief Tom Anderson.
He left with a Funny Car victory but with terrible injuries as his
car caught fire at the end of his victorious run.
</P>
<P>
   ``The engine let go near the finish line,'' Lewis said. ``The
resulting fire burned away the parachutes and exploded the rear
tires, sending Hofmann on a collision course with the top-end
guardrail.
</P>
<P>
   When the team should have been sipping champagne, they found
themselves gathered instead at the hospital to comfort Hofmann.
``The financial gain of the victory was wiped out and Hofmann
required months to recover from his injuries,'' Lewis said
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Hofmann was back competing at Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's tough.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's the allure of drag racing. In most sports, pure
speed is a natural gift _ a God-given talent that a few have and
most cannot even dream to attain.
</P>
<P>
   In drag racing, the fastest of sports, there is, of course, some
natural ability involved _ reflexes are of paramount importance.
But so are teamwork, technology and tenacity. Drag racing success
today comes from a marriage of Space Age wizardry and undeniable
human spirit. Speed thrills _ especially when it's obvious some
work was put into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The status quo is never good enough in this sport,'' said
Robertson, the general manager of Gainesville Raceway. ``Drag
racers are by nature a very innovative, cutting-edge type of group.
It's never a sport of complacency.''
</P>
<P>
   Age 30 is when the speed merchants in other sports start slowing
down. But, born in 1970, Gatornationals will just get faster and
faster.`
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Dave Reardon is a sportswriter for The Gainesville, Fla., Sun.
This story was distributed by The N.Y. Times News Service.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
