<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-COUNSEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO URGES LAWMAKERS TO END INDEPENDENT COUNSEL LAW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno, under fire for not
seeking an outside prosecutor to examine presidential fund-raising,
urged Congress on Wednesday to let the Independent Counsel Act die
July 1 and allow the Justice Department to conduct criminal
investigations of high-level officials.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., Reno's staunchest congressional
critic, said the attorney general cannot be trusted to conduct a
vigorous investigation of senior government officials, particularly
her boss, President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The senator, who chairs the Senate Governmental Affairs
Committee, cited Reno's refusal to seek an independent counsel to
examine Clinton's alleged illegal fund-raising during his 1996
re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, appearing before Thompson's committee, said the
post-Watergate era independent counsel law has failed to accomplish
its goal of ensuring public confidence in the U.S. government's
ability to prosecute federal executive-branch officials. Instead
the statute has fomented widespread cynicism of prosecutors and the
way they investigate officials, and deepened the partisan divide on
Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Reno pointedly referred to the Republican senator's vociferous
criticism of the Democratic Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Under the controversial law, an attorney general may ask a
special panel of three federal judges to appoint an independent
counsel if she receives specific and credible evidence of
wrongdoing by a senior executive-branch official. In her six years
as attorney general, Reno has sought the appointment of seven
independent counsels, including Kenneth Starr, whose controversial
investigation of Clinton's effort to conceal an extramarital affair
with Monica Lewinsky led to the president's impeachment and Senate
acquittal last month.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the independent counsel that Reno did not seek that
has drawn the most criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who conducted several months of hearings on the
Clinton campaign issue in 1997, said Reno should have sought an
independent counsel to investigate credible allegations that the
president raised $44 million for the re-election campaign, even
though his acceptance of $62 million in public campaign funds
legally barred him from raising more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The failure to appoint an independent counsel when it is
clearly called for, not only defeats the purpose of the statute,
but enhances the very cynicism and loss of public confidence that
motivated the creation of the statute in the first place,'' said
Thompson. The senator said he has not decided whether the
independent counsel law should be killed, retained or amended.
</P>
<P>
   FBI Director Louis Freeh and Charles La Bella, former head of
the Justice Department's investigation of campaign irregularities,
had privately urged Reno to name an independent counsel in the
campaign-finance case. Freeh and La Bella, in separate memos to
Reno, expressed the same concerns Thompson did about her conflict
of interest.
</P>
<P>
   But Reno defended her actions, indicating that the Justice
Department is investigating the alleged campaign violations. She
cited Thompson's criticism of her actions as evidence that the
independent counsel law improperly brings politics into what is
supposed to be the neutral decision of whether to launch a criminal
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have come to believe that the statute puts the attorney
general in a no-win situation,'' Reno said. ``An attorney general
is criticized if she triggers the statute and criticized if she
doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno, who had endorsed reauthorization of the act in 1993, said
she now seeks the ``structurally flawed'' law's demise because her
six years of experience with the controversial statute has shown
her that the law gives independent counsels too much power. Unlike
other prosecutors, independent counsels have unlimited budgets and
time to investigate alleged wrongdoing, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is as if we have created a fourth branch of government,''
Reno said. ``In trying to ensure independence, the statute creates
a new category of prosecutors who have ... no competing public
duties and no need to make difficult decisions about how to
allocate scarce resources.''
</P>
<P>
   But Reno conceded that attorneys general, to avoid a conflict of
interest, might need to appoint special prosecutors from outside
the Justice Department to handle investigations of alleged
wrongdoing by high-ranking officials. But these outside attorneys
should have limited budgets, be well-qualified and preferably be
from the party not in office, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In defense of her proposal, Reno said a special prosecutor, Leon
Jaworski, successfully investigated the Watergate scandal, which
led to President Richard Nixon's 1974 resignation and the
conviction of many of his aides. Despite that success, Congress
reacted to the episode by enacting the independent counsel law four
years later, the attorney general said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps the real lesson of our nation's experience with the
special prosecutor during Watergate is not that the old system was
broken, but that it worked,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   La Bella, also appearing before Thompson's Committee, said
independent counsels are not needed to investigate official
wrongdoing. Instead, attorneys general should turn to experienced
career prosecutors who have no ties to any particular
administration to conduct the investigations.
</P>
<P>
   John Barrett, who was an aid to independent counsel Lawrence
Walsh during the Iran-Contra investigation, said the law should be
amended rather than scrapped. For example, he said the Justice
Department should be empowered to conduct preliminary
investigations of high-ranking government officials, complete with
grand juries, subpoenas and plea bargains.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would help attorneys general make better-informed choices
about which matters really need to be investigated by an
outsider,'' Barrett told the committee.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 1918EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
