<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4337 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-CORRUPTION-800     03-17 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-CORRUPTION-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI POLITICIAN CONVICTED OF CORRUPTION
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ A powerful, charismatic Israeli politician was
convicted Wednesday on corruption charges in a verdict that
outraged the ultra-Orthodox Sephardic Jews who consider him the
champion of their underclass community.
</P>
<P>
   While the Jerusalem District Court was ringed with police
officers after death threats against the judges, supporters of the
politician, Aryeh Deri, greeted the decision with angry words and
protest songs but not violence.
</P>
<P>
   They proclaimed Deri, a Moroccan-born rabbi who heads the Shas
Party, to be a victim of bias against religious Jews and Sephardic
Jews of Middle Eastern and North African origin.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had to take him down because he was getting too
powerful,'' said David Abergil, a Moroccan immigrant who traveled
from southern Israel to await the verdict outside the courthouse.
``We feel that all the Sephardi people are being convicted because
Deri had the God-blessed brains to put the rest of us on the map.''
</P>
<P>
   Deri, whose party holds 10 seats in the 120-member Parliament,
has played a pivotal role in many governments and exercised a good
deal of influence in Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's governing
coalition. Netanyahu wants and needs the support of Shas to win
re-election on May 17.
</P>
<P>
   The court, in a two-hour live broadcast, handed down its
blistering decision against Deri, 40, who built Shas into Israel's
third-largest party, after Likud and Labor. Reading excerpts from
the long verdict, Deputy Chief Judge Yaacov Tzemah pronounced Deri
guilty of bribery, fraud and breach of public trust. He also
accused him of obstructing justice during the nine-year case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deri waged a war against the police during the investigation,
and against the prosecution during the trial,'' the judge said as
Deri fixed his gaze on the courtroom floor. ``Deri alleged they
were trying not only to ruin him but to ruin his party, that they
were conducting blood libel against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Deri is now forced to place his faith in the liberal Supreme
Court; his lawyer announced Wednesday that he is appealing the
conviction to the institution that religious Jews most malign.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon Deri gave a brief statement at his office.
``I'm sure if I was acquitted, I'd feel happier,'' he said. ``But I
must say I bear no grudge against anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, in an unusually brief news conference, expressed his
sympathy to the family of Deri, saying, ``My heart is with them.''
At the same time, he called on Deri's supporters to ``show
restraint and respect the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Deri's colleagues in Shas vowed that the verdict would not
derail the party. ``No power in the world will destroy us,'' said
Shlomo Benizri, a member of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts said they expected that Shas would
successfully use the verdict to redouble its partisans' commitment
to a party that defends their rights against a system that they say
seeks to keep them down.
</P>
<P>
   With a trim black beard and small black skullcap, the
street-smart Deri made a political splash when he was still in his
20s.
</P>
<P>
   Under the tutelage of the party's spiritual adviser, Rabbi
Ovadia Yosef, Deri built Shas into a political force by defending
the interests of Sephardim and by building a social service and an
educational system, with free clinics, free nursery schools and
state-subsidized yeshivas, or religious schools.
</P>
<P>
   Deri started his professional life as an administrator of the
Yad Labanim Yeshiva in Jerusalem. He left to become a civil servant
at the Interior Ministry, ending up as interior minister under
three different governments from 1988 to 1993. During that time he
became a master of backroom politics.
</P>
<P>
   He resigned when he was indicted on the corruption charges in
this case, in which the court found that he had developed and
sustained an illegal relationship with his old yeshiva friends once
in government.
</P>
<P>
   The court found that from 1985 to 1989, Deri accepted $155,000
in bribes in exchange for steering ``substantial'' public funds to
the yeshiva, whose directors paid him off partly with the public
funds themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was as if Deri received a tithing of the money given to the
yeshiva, and often it was much more than 10 percent,'' Tzemah said.
</P>
<P>
   The court determined that the bribes included cash payments
directly into his bank accounts, trips to London and New York and
help in buying a $445,000 luxury duplex apartment in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Deri also appointed one yeshiva director to be his assistant at
the Interior Ministry and named another to a salaried post as the
head of a municipal council in the Negev region.
</P>
<P>
   The three men who ran the yeshiva were also convicted of
corruption charges today.
</P>
<P>
   Sentencing is scheduled for next week. The charges carry a
possible maximum penalty of 21 years in prison.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Israelis, who are fascinated by Deri, were riveted to their
radios and televisions Wednesday morning. Although the police
feared riots, Deri and Yosef cautioned their followers to remain
calm, and their followers generally obey.
</P>
<P>
   At 4:30 a.m., Deri started his day in prayer at the Cave of the
Patriarchs in Hebron. From there he proceeded to a circumcision
ceremony, which is supposed to bring those attending a blessing
from the prophet Elijah. Then he sought blessings from both Yosef
and Rabbi Yitzhak Kedouri, a kabalist rabbi who is an important
mystical figure in the religious Sephardic community. Finally, he
proceeded to the courthouse, from which he emerged pale, to cheers
from his supporters, who yelled, ``They spilt your blood.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Nazism, racism,'' said Ezra Levy, 21, a yeshiva student.
``It's the black and white reality of our society.''
</P>
<P>
   By evening, when Deri gave a televised news conference, he was
back in fighting form, seated beside Yosef in his luxury duplex
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't take bribes from anyone and certainly not from my
beloved friends,'' he said. ``This is a trial that the Holy One,
blessed be He, has given me to test me, and I hope that I will
pass.''
</P>
<P>
   When reporters tried to ask Deri questions, Yosef grew angry.
``What do you want?'' he said. ``Get out of here. Aryeh is
innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning to Deri as Shas members pushed cameramen out the door,
Yosef said: ``They're hostile. I forbid you to answer them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
