<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-AWARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AD LOGO ON EDITORIAL INSERT KILLS AWARD FOR A MAGAZINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the first time in its 33-year history, the American Society
of Magazine Editors has stripped a magazine of nominations for the
society's National Magazine awards for not complying with
guidelines regarding the separation of advertising and editorial
content.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine in question, This Old House, which is published by
Time Publishing Ventures Inc., a Time Inc. unit of Time Warner, was
to receive one nomination for the coveted category of General
Excellence and one for Design.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, however, the judging committee, made up of 67
magazine editors and publishers, decided that the magazine was in
violation because for the last several months it had published a
five-page editorial insert poster that read at the bottom, ``This
poster is brought to you by Ace Hardware, the source for all your
hardware needs.'' The word ``Ace'' appears in the distinctive bold
red letters of the company logo. Ace Hardware did not pay for the
placement in the poster, which has featured themes like hardware
and insects.
</P>
<P>
   The positioning of the Ace Hardware logo on an editorial section
creates the impression that the magazine editors are endorsing a
product, according to ASME.
</P>
<P>
   The society's nominee list was compiled several weeks ago and is
to be announced Thursday. The actual awards, chosen by the same
67-member panel, are to be announced in late April. Removal of This
Old House from the list points to the growing concern about
dissolving barriers between advertising and editorial content.
</P>
<P>
   Marlene Kahan, executive director of the society, said it had
previously called the violation to the attention of the magazine's
editors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pointed out a very clear violation of our guidelines
several times,'' she said. ``One of our rules clearly states that
you cannot have an advertiser logo on an editorial page of the
magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric G. Thorkilsen, president of This Old House, argued that
because Ace Hardware was one of three national sponsors for the
magazine's popular companion public television program, ``This Old
House,'' he felt obliged to give the hardware company ``the
opportunity to have premium placing _ we consider it an obligation
as a licensee.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the editorial team at This Old House magazine considered
the poster ``an extra level of editorial content.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And we don't consider it advertising,'' he said, ``and we
don't bill it as advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he found the magazine society's move ``very regretful.''
He added: ``I think it is going to be deeply disappointing to our
editorial team and to our magazine, especially with so many other
more egregious examples across the industry. We look through
shelter magazines all the time who in their editorial wells we find
one brand name after another that is featured in the content and is
followed by advertising by the same guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Thorkilsen would not cite specific examples in the industry, but
he said shelter magazines were a particular category in which
advertisers expect favorable attention. ``I find it ironic that
we're the ones taking the bullet here,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
