<SLUG> BC-POPE-SONY-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN PAUL ON CD, FOR EASTER AND THE MILLENNIUM
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ First came the book, then the show, and now the
major-label compact disk.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II, whose book ``Crossing the Threshold of
Hope,'' was a best seller in 1994 and whose play, ``The Jeweler's
Shop,'' opened at St. Bart's Playhouse in Manhattan later that
year, was given a copy Wednesday of his first music CD, which is to
be released internationally by Sony Classical on March 23.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the pope's first CD. Last April, RCA Victor issued a
CD and cassette of poems by Pope John Paul, recited in Italian by
actor Vittorio Gassmann. And last summer designers at a Rome
fashion show used a CD in which the pope is heard singing a
Gregorian chant electronically melded with a hip-hop background
beat, despite Vatican threats to sue. And a double CD of the pope
reciting the rosary went platinum in Spain in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   But Pasquale Borgomeo, director of Radio Vatican, said the CD
offered Wednesday was ``the first time there has been a real
artistically integrated musical use of the pope's voice.''
</P>
<P>
   The CD, called ``Abba Pater,'' will go on sale in more than 30
countries, including the United States, where it will retail for
$16.98. A selection of prayers, chants and homilies in five
languages recorded by Radio Vatican over the last 20 years, it
includes a background of classical and easy-listening music by
Italian composers.
</P>
<P>
   While the CD's release is timed to coincide with the Easter
season, Joaquin Navarro-Valls, the papal spokesman, said it came
``in close connection with the Jubilee'' declared by the pope for
the year 2000 to mark the start of Christianity's third millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal Roger Etchegaray, president of the Vatican's Jubilee
committee, said at a news conference that the pope's voice ``is
offered, not as a star'' but as a pastor, ``to render visible to
men, women and youth the inner pilgrimage'' that the Jubilee
outwardly represents.
</P>
<P>
   Sony is paying a distribution fee plus royalties to Vatican
Radio and the Society of St. Paul, an Italian order of priests
specializing in publishing that produced the CD, plus a video clip
for music television and a single for pop radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Gelb, president of Sony Classical, would not say how much
Sony is paying, but he said it was ``a lot less'' than the $9
million Alfred A. Knopf paid for the pope's book.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The video clip features scenes from the pope's many trips around
the world. John Paul recites or sings prayers and homilies,
including a Gregorian chant version of the Our Father. The words of
the title, ``Abba Pater,'' the Aramaic and Latin words for
``father,'' are the words spoken by Jesus in prayer in Gethsemane.
</P>
<P>
   Leonardo De Amicis, one of the composers, said the technique was
to take the papal recordings and fit the music around them. ``What
amazed us,'' he said of the pope, was that ``his rhythmic cadences
and expression helped us immensely.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly Sony is hoping to cash in on the popularity of music
like the recordings of Gregorian chant by Spanish Benedictines,
which in recent years have sold millions of copies. In an unusual
arrangement, Sony will promote the CD in cooperation with local
Catholic bishops conferences, which will share the royalties.
</P>
<P>
   Gelb said that in the United States he expected particularly
strong sales in Spanish-speaking communities in which church
leaders have designated the royalties for scholarship funds.
</P>
<P>
   Gelb declined to give a figure on Sony's promotion budget,
saying it was ``what would be typically spent for a popular record
of which you would expect to sell a million copies or more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
