<HEADER>
A4348 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOTTERIES-SOUTH18-COX     03-17 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTTERIES-SOUTH18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Analysts: Jackpot from state lotteries dwindling in South
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Researchers who keep tabs on the growth industry of
state lotteries have some sobering words for states eager to cash
in:
</P>
<P>
   There's still a lot of potential loot out there, but don't count
on the huge profits snared by the early birds. And there's still
that nagging question of whether gambling serves the public good.
</P>
<P>
   Money streams into state lotteries, but slower than before. Over
the past six years, sales have flattened or declined in five of six
Southern lotteries. Only Georgia's ticket sales have increased
every year since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, says Marcy Goodfleisch, spokeswoman for the Texas
Lottery Commission, ``If you have a lottery, it will make money for
your state. Period.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas made a bundle last year even as ticket sales dropped more
than 17 percent over fiscal year 1997. Sales totaled $3 billion,
more than any state in the South, and contributed more than $1
billion to the Texas general fund.
</P>
<P>
   David Gale, executive director of the North American Association
of State and Provincial Lotteries, says there's enough money and
people in the South for everyone to generate lottery profits, even
if Alabama, South Carolina, North Carolina and Tennessee all
started their own games.
</P>
<P>
   The key elements are the South's growing population and
industry. In the Northeast, Gale said, 11 contiguous states operate
profitable games.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a cost, analysts warn.
</P>
<P>
   According to two Duke University researchers who have studied
lotteries over the last decade, states should stop the aggressive
advertising that glamorizes lottery gambling. Charles Clotfelter
and Phil Cook will discuss their findings at a two-day meeting of
the National Gambling Impact Study Commission that begins today in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Congress created the gambling commission in 1996. The group's
final report on the nation's gambling habits is due in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think the messages that are being used in advertising
are appropriate for the state government to deliver to the
public,'' Cook said. ``Thematically, it would be: Trust your luck,
play the lottery as a plan for getting ahead in life, that money
will solve your problems (and) ... look at all the lavishness that
could be part of your life if you won the big jackpot.''
</P>
<P>
   In Alabama and South Carolina, Democrats won governorships last
November over incumbent Republicans by promising lotteries for
education. The prospect of a statewide lottery also has been raised
in North Carolina and in Tennessee, where a House committee Tuesday
approved a bill calling for a constitutional convention to consider
a lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia estimates that 16 of every 100 tickets sold are bought
by residents of Alabama, South Carolina, North Carolina and
Tennessee. Georgia Lottery Corp. President Rebecca Paul says
there's no way to forecast what new lotteries would do to Georgia
sales since none of the would-be lottery states have authorized or
designed their games, which may not appear for years.
</P>
<P>
   For Alabama residents, lotteries in Georgia and Florida remain
the closest thing to having their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer you establish those buying patterns, the harder it
is to break those buying patterns for a new consumer product,''
Paul said. ``It's way, way too early to tell what impact lotteries
around us will have. We had virtually no impact on the Florida
lottery.''
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, which enjoyed a brief reign as the South's only
lottery state, sales dropped 2.7 percent in 1993, the first year of
Georgia's lottery, and climbed just 1.8 percent the following year.
Since 80 percent of their tickets are sold to residents, Florida
officials are confident despite potential competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that we're all that concerned with neighboring
states offering lotteries because they wouldn't be able to offer
the same size jackpots,'' said Florida lottery spokesman Tim
Bottcher.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky lottery officials are more pessimistic. Indiana casinos
have been cutting into possible lottery sales for years. For the
first time in its 10-year history, the Kentucky lottery set an
annual sales goal that was less than actual sales the previous
year. To attract more players, the Kentucky Lottery Corp. this week
added a midday drawing for its Pick 3 and Pick 4 games.
</P>
<P>
   More worry looms as Tennessee continues a lottery debate that
has run hot and cold the past several years. Kentucky generates 15
percent of its ticket sales from Tennessee residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If and when Tennessee starts a lottery, Kentucky will be faced
with a major revenue shortfall,'' said Rick Redman, spokesman for
the Kentucky lottery.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, the lottery started in 1992 and posted double-digit
sales gains in four of its next seven years, selling more tickets
than any game in the South. Unexpectedly, ticket sales dropped last
year nearly 18 percent. Lottery studies showed some players quit
because they perceived their odds of winning had dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the drop in sales, the Texas lottery remains very much
in the black. ``We're declining in sales, but we're not losing
money,'' Goodfleisch said. ``We're just making less.''
</P>
<P>
   While researcher Cook questions whether lotteries are a proper
way for governments to raise revenue, he concedes that the state
monopolies stand to reap continued profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be true that Wyoming would have a hard time making
money on a lottery because the density is so low,'' said Cook.
``But I don't think that's true (in the South). They would make
some money off of it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the $35.9 billion U.S. lottery industry has nearly
doubled sales since 1989, the last time the Duke professors
analyzed the country's lotteries. In 1989, lotteries in 29 states
plus the District of Columbia generated $18.5 billion in annual
sales. Today, there are 38 lotteries, including six in the Southern
states of Florida, Georgia, Kentucky, Louisiana, Texas and
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the success of lotteries, say some lottery
officials, is the type of advertising that the Duke researchers
suggest the states should abandon.
</P>
<P>
   During her testimony last year to the gambling commission,
Georgia's Paul declared, ``Lottery tickets compete with Mars candy,
Frito-Lay and Coca-Cola. When a customer buys $18 worth of gas at a
convenience store and pays with a $20 bill, I hope they'll spend
their $2 worth of change on lottery tickets to support HOPE
scholarships rather than soda or Slim Jims.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
