<HEADER>
A4349 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIZZA-CLASS18-COX     03-17 2177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIZZA-CLASS18-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Points on pizza
</P>
<P>
   By Kitty Crider
</P>
<P>
   c. Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Call it a moment of March Madness. But enough of
all these basketballs in the air. Let's mix it up, toss up
something else. Like pizzas.
</P>
<P>
   Haven't you wondered how hard it really is to throw a disc of
dough in the air and have it come back down in one piece, in your
hands, not on the floor?
</P>
<P>
   Well, pizza dough is floppier to throw than a Frisbee or a
basketball, that's for sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's just dough. And you can't hurt it,'' reassures Brian
Smith, owner of DoubleDave's, who has taught many a novice to toss
a pizza.
</P>
<P>
   One day last week this pizza coach gave a quick lesson to some
basketball players recruited to try their hands at throwing
something besides orange balls. You don't have to be an athlete to
master the pizza layup, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very uncoordinated. I was horrible,'' confessed Smith,
who now can pat, roll, toss and build a pizza in an impressive 45
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Your goal, explains Smith, is not a slam dunk. It's not height.
It's centrifugal force to shape and stretch the dough. And, yeah,
it's a lot for show, too.
</P>
<P>
   While some pizza makers may shape the dough almost exclusively
by tossing it, Smith prefers to pat and roll it before giving it a
couple of flings in the air. (For DoubleDave's famous Peproni
Rolls, he throws the dough even longer and larger.)
</P>
<P>
   Smith says the secret is not to roll the dough too thin in the
center but more around the edges, working in a circle so you don't
end up with a square. ``Thickness doesn't matter but you don't want
to see light through the dough,'' says Smith, deftly wielding a
rolling pin the jocks estimated at five pounds.
</P>
<P>
   When the dough is about 15 inches, he spins the floury circle,
tossing it a foot or two in the air before catching it on his hand
and settling it in a pizza pan. Gee, it looks easy.
</P>
<P>
   But now, it's Django Walker's turn. No. 45, senior, power
forward for Austin High, Walker steps up to the kitchen goal line.
He sprinkles flour on the counter, he pats out the dough, he rolls,
he throws. . . . It's up. It's spinning. It comes back down. On his
hand. In one piece. He smiles and tosses it again. Nothing to it.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure's on for Nic Dukes, No. 12, senior point guard for
Westwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do what now?'' he asks as he grabs a dough ball and starts
working with it, sprinkling flour and flopping it around like a
pro. Wait a minute, Nic. This isn't the first time you've handled
dough. Do you work in a pizza shop? Nope, he grins. But he's made
pizza at home, with store-bought dough. He goes through the pizza
warm-up and throws. It swirls. Perfectly. And again.
</P>
<P>
   Man, these guys are hitting 100 percent. Must be that great hand
coordination. Or a good pizza coach. Or they are hungry.
</P>
<P>
   Smith shows them how to finish up the dough for pizzas and
Peproni Rolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the hardest part,'' says Walker, trying to spread the
sauce evenly on the pizza crust. Easy for him to say.
</P>
<P>
   Dukes, meanwhile, is fine-tuning his Peproni Rolls technique.
When he's got it, he turns and invites Smith to his new place:
DomiNic's.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO TOSS A PIZZA
</P>
<P>
   DoubleDave's starts with dough straight from the mixer without
letting it rise. (If the dough is allowed to rise, it becomes
softer and tears more easily when tossed. Dough also tears more
easily on a humid day.)
</P>
<P>
   Some DoubleDave's locations (including Smith's) will sell dough
balls for you to take home and make your own pizzas or Peproni
Rolls. If you need a large order, like 20 or more, call ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Take a ball of dough (about 19 ounces for a 15-inch pizza) and
on a floured surface, pat it into a circle, working out the air
with the tips of fingers like a kitten making a bed with its paws.
Sprinkle flour on dough top to keep from sticking.
</P>
<P>
   With a heavy rolling pin (about 3 to 5 pounds), use about half
of the pin to roll or push the edges of the dough away from the
center. Flour rolling pin as needed to keep from sticking. Turn
dough as you work, to maintain a circle shape. Do not slam down pin
and roll across the dough, or the center will be too thin.
(Thickness of dough does not matter particularly, but you do not
want to be able to see through it.)
</P>
<P>
   Roll dough to size of finished pizza, 15 inches, for example.
(Tip: Hold pizza pan over dough so you can gauge the right size.)
</P>
<P>
   Pick up the dough and drape it over one fist close to the edge.
Using other hand, give about a half circle spin, releasing dough.
Do not try to go too high. Catch the dough with both hands and spin
again. (If it falls on the floor, throw away. If it tears, try to
patch it by overlapping the dough or adding a small new piece of
dough.)
</P>
<P>
   Place dough on ungreased pizza pan. Dough should overlap edge
about 3/4 inch. Fold under the overlap and pinch to form pizza
edge. (You do not want to see the metal edge of the pan.)
</P>
<P>
   Brush pizza edge with melted garlic butter made with 1/2 stick
of butter and a scant teaspoon each garlic powder and oregano.
</P>
<P>
   Ladle 1/2 cup pizza sauce in center of pizza and spread evenly
with a large spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle on 6 ounces of shredded mozzarella cheese all the way
to edge of pizza.
</P>
<P>
   Top pizza as desired. If using pepperoni, put slices close
together but do not overlap or pizza will be too greasy.
</P>
<P>
   Do not put topping ingredient in very center of pizza, as it
will be decimated when it is sliced 8 times.
</P>
<P>
   Bake pizza at 450 degrees until done, about 15-20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   DOUBLEDAVE'S SPECIALTY: PEPRONI ROLLS
</P>
<P>
   DoubleDave's is famous for these rolls, made with pizza dough
and filled with smoked provolone cheese and pepperoni slices.
</P>
<P>
   Start with about a 19-ounce ball of pizza dough and prepare as
for pizza, except roll or toss to 22-inch diameter. (It is harder
to toss to 22 inches than to a 15-inch pizza. Use a rolling pin as
needed.)
</P>
<P>
   Take 4 round 1-ounce slices of smoked provolone cheese and cut
in half. Place the half-circles of cheese around the edge of dough.
</P>
<P>
   Place 6 overlapping slices of pepperoni on top of cheese.
</P>
<P>
   With a pizza cutter or knife, cut dough into 8 wedges, between
the cheese slices.
</P>
<P>
   Fold in the two edges of the top of the wedge over the cheese.
Then, folding cheese in half, roll up tightly, stretching dough and
rolling toward point, like a crescent roll. Repeat with remaining
wedges.
</P>
<P>
   If desired, bend roll into an angle for an attractive
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Bake until done at 450 degrees for 15-20 minutes. Makes 8
Peproni Rolls. Serve with marinara sauce or ranch dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Note: For the closest match to the real thing, start with a
dough ball purchased from DoubleDave's. In fact, they have
customers who come in and buy the dough, cheese and pepperoni and
go home and make the rolls.
</P>
<P>
   BREAD MACHINE PIZZA DOUGH
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cups flour, all purpose or bread
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons fast-rise yeast
</P>
<P>
   Add lukewarm water and vegetable oil to pan of bread machine.
Add flour, sugar and salt to pan. Make a well in center of dry
ingredients, add yeast. Lock pan into bread maker. Program for
dough. When dough is well mixed and kneaded, it can be shaped for
pizza or allowed to rise, then kneaded down. Let rest about 10
minutes and then roll, pat or toss dough to fit an ungreased 14 to
15 inch pizza pan, which has been sprinkled with corn meal.
</P>
<P>
   To make pizza: top dough with 1/2 to 3/4 cup pizza sauce,
shredded mozzarella cheese, and meats or veggies of choice. Bake at
450 degrees 15-20 minutes or until done.
</P>
<P>
   QUICK TOMATO PIZZA SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 cloves garlic, peeled and minced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 can (8 to 10 ounces) tomato puree or tomato sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried basil
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   Several grindings of black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Over low heat, saute garlic in olive oil until garlic is
softened but not brown. Add remaining ingredients and stir to
combine. Simmer, covered, over very low heat for 15 minutes. Makes
1 cup. _ ``32 Zesty Pizzas'' by Bev Bennett and
</P>
<P>
   KIM UPTON BASIC PIZZA DOUGH
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup warm (110 degrees to 115 degrees) water
</P>
<P>
   1 envelope ( 1/4 ounce) active dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   3 1/4 cups bread, semolina, or unbleached all-purpose flour, or
a combination
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   This basic dough can be used for any type of pizza: traditional
or contemporary; flat or deep-dish; topped, stuffed, or folded. The
recipe can be doubled if you're entertaining a crowd or just want
to prepare extra dough for freezing.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, dissolve the sugar in warm tap water that
registers 110 degrees to 115 degrees. For temperature accuracy,
insert an instant-read thermometer in the water. Alternatively,
learn to judge by touch; the water should be warm to your finger
but not too hot _ the temperature of a comfortable bath. Water that
is too hot will kill the yeast, while water that is too cold will
not activate it.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle the yeast over the water and stir gently until it
dissolves, about 1 minute. When yeast is mixed with the water at
the proper temperature, a smooth, beige-colored mixture results.
(If the yeast clumps together and the water stays clear, discard
the mixture and start over). Let stand in a warm spot until a thin
layer of foam covers the surface, about 5 minutes, indicating that
the yeast is effective. (Discard mixture and start over with a
fresh package of yeast if bubbles have not formed within 5
minutes.)
</P>
<P>
   To mix and knead the dough by hand: Combine 3 cups of the flour
with the salt in a mixing bowl. Make a well in the center of the
flour and pour in the yeast mixture and the oil, if using. Using a
wooden spoon, vigorously stir the flour into the well, beginning in
the center and working toward the sides of the bowl, until the
flour is incorporated and the soft dough just begins to hold
together.
</P>
<P>
   Turn the dough out onto a lightly floured surface. Dust your
hands with flour and knead the dough gently in the following
manner: press down on the dough with the heels of your hands and
push it away from you, then partially fold it back over itself.
Shift it a quarter turn and repeat the procedure. While kneading,
very gradually add just enough of the remaining 1/4 cup flour until
the dough is no longer sticky or tacky; this should take about 5
minutes. As you work, use a metal dough scraper to pry up any bits
of dough that stick to the work surface. Continue kneading until
the dough is smooth, elastic and shiny, 10 to 15 minutes longer.
Knead the dough only until it feels smooth and springy; too much
kneading results in a tough crust.
</P>
<P>
   To mix and knead the dough in a heavy-duty food processor: Add 3
cups of the flour and the salt to the beaker fitted with either a
steel blade or a dough hook. Turn the machine on to combine the
ingredients, about 5 seconds. Add the yeast mixture and oil, if
using, and process continuously until the dough forms a single ball
or several masses on top of the blade, about 30 seconds. Pinch off
a piece of dough and feel it. If it is sticky, continue processing
while gradually adding just enough of the remaining 1/4 cup flour
for the dough to lose its stickiness. If the dough is dry and
crumbly, add warm water, a tablespoon at a time, until the dough is
smooth. Turn the dough out onto a lightly floured surface and knead
by hand as described above for about 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   If freezing Wrap tightly in plastic wrap or seal in airtight
plastic containers and freeze for up to 4 months. Before using,
thaw in the refrigerator for 1 or 2 days or for a few hours at room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Shape the dough into circles.
</P>
<P>
   Top dough as desired.
</P>
<P>
   For the crispiest crust, bake flat pizzas directly on a baking
surface formed of unglazed quarry tiles or on a baking stone. In a
gas oven, position the tiles or stone directly on the oven floor.
In an electric stove, arrange the tiles or stone on the lowest rack
of the oven. When using tiles, leave a 1-inch clearance between the
tiles and the oven walls. Preheat the oven at 500 degrees for 1
hour before assembling the pizza. Bake until the crust is golden or
as directed in individual recipes, usually about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   To bake on a pizza screen, brush the wire screen lightly with
vegetable oil and top with the shaped dough. Assemble the pizza as
quickly as possible and give the screen a quick jerk to be sure the
dough is not stuck to the wire. Place the screen directly on the
hot tiles or pizza stone. If you choose not to use tiles or a
stone, place the screen on the top rack of a preheated 500-degree
oven to prevent the direct heat from burning the bottom crust. Bake
until the crust is golden or as directed in individual recipes,
usually about 10 minutes on tiles or a stone and about 15 minutes
on an oven rack. _ ``Pizza'' by James McNair
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
