<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Savannah parade pulls out the stops for St. Pat's
 &HT;    By Jingle Davis
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVANNAH, Ga. _ The 300,000-plus people who turned out to watch
this old city's 175th annual St. Patrick's Day parade _ billed as
the nation's second-largest _ were often just as colorful and
entertaining as the parade itself.
</P>
<P>
   Two white-haired women lounging in deck chairs along the parade
route proudly waved a sign reading, ``two old foxes wearing green
soxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Green hair was commonplace, but one red-haired spectator with a
brilliant green beard stood out from the crowd. A small black
poodle wore a green and white garter around its middle as a frilly
tutu.
</P>
<P>
   Shamrocks showed up in every guise imaginable _ as pins,
earrings, hair ornaments, beads, and on every article of clothing:
T-shirts, neckties, hats, balloons and sunglasses. The parade wound
through downtown, with marching bands, kilted bagpipers, floats,
Irish families, dignitaries, Irish dancers, military units, little
kids in decorated wagons and babies in beribboned carriages, all
curving around the picturesque parks where red and pink azaleas
flamed against the moving sea of green.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beautiful! Beautiful! Out of this world!'' raved Emolo
Garosi, a retiree from Hershey, Penn., who was in town visiting his
son, a helicopter pilot at Hunter Army Airfield.
</P>
<P>
   Officials praised a new policy requiring people to pass through
entrance gates and buy $4 wristbands in order to drink alcohol
outdoors on River Street, where much rowdy behavior has occurred in
the past. The gates went up Friday night, stayed up through Sunday
night and were up against Tuesday and Wednesday for pre- and
post-parade partying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arrests dropped 65 percent this year over last,'' said Bucky
Burnsed, spokesman for the Savannah police. ``We are seeing a
kinder, gentler crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the citations issued were for disorderly conduct,
public indecency _ including public urination and trading Mardi
Gras-style beads for displays of nudity _ and underage drinking, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Varnedoe, executive director of the Savannah Waterfront
Association, said he believes most merchants, even those who
initially opposed the wristbands, were pleased with this year's
event, both in terms of sales and the reduction of problems on
River Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think we will do this again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
