<SLUG> BC-REPKENNEDY-SENATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME SEE CHAFEE ANNOUNCEMENT AS CUE FOR REP. KENNEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He has said ``no.'' He has said ``absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   But in an environment where parsing words is considered sport,
it should be no surprise that Representative Patrick J. Kennedy's
pledge not to run for the Senate has come under scrutiny. And
because he comes from a family that has sent three legends into the
Senate chamber, it should be no surprise that he is under
increasing pressure to change his mind.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, despite Kennedy's insistence over a three-month period
that he will stay planted in the House, there remains a conviction
among many of his colleagues that he should start campaigning now
for the Rhode Island seat that has been held by a Republican for 24
years. That whisper campaign has crescendoed since Monday, when
Senator John H. Chafee, a Republican, announced plans to retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said to Patrick, `I think you're crazy,' '' said
Representative J. Joseph Moakley, a Massachusetts Democrat, who has
worked closely with Kennedy since his arrival in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be another 24 years before there's an open seat,''
agreed Senator Jack Reed, the Democrat from Rhode Island. ``He's an
obvious person people would want to think about having run for the
Senate, especially at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy made his decision not to run last fall, when Minority
Leader Richard Gephardt tapped him to become chairman of the
Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee, an influential
position from which he will help shape all the House races in 2000.
This election will be even more rigorous than most; with only a
six-seat margin, and after Republican losses last fall, Gephardt is
determined to see Democrats regain the majority in the House.
</P>
<P>
   For Kennedy, that responsibility is reason enough not to bail
out. But he has other reasons, too. At age 31, he can afford to
wait two decades to decide to run for another seat _ and carve his
own niche of the Kennedy legend out of another part of Washington
in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having watched my father in the US Senate, I know what it's
about. I know the pace of it. I know the profile of a senator and
what their general disposition is, and the way they conduct
themselves as US senators,'' Kennedy said Wednesday, referring to
his father, Senator Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts. ``And I
know the hurly-burly of the House. I feel like I'm more suited to
the House and the character of this place.''
</P>
<P>
   That logic is mystifying to many outsiders, however, and has
prompted not only forceful prodding from many Democrats but sharp
criticism from Republicans as well _ particularly when it comes to
Kennedy's aspirations for higher leadership in the House. Some
members of the GOP see Kennedy's resoluteness against running as
``putting a happy face on a really bad political decision,''
according to Chafee spokesman Nicholas Graham.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Kennedy has the impression that if Democrats take back
the House, he's got it made, he'll be Speaker in 10 years,'' he
said. ``I don't think that's the case. I think he's taking a lot
for granted...The path to higher office in the House is riddled
with more chutes than ladders.''
</P>
<P>
   Poll numbers are tantalizing as well, according to Darrell West,
professor of political science at Brown University, who has
conducted many Rhode Island polls for Chafee. If the Senate race
were split among three candidates, as many expect it to be _ with
Senator Chafee's son, Lincoln, on the Republican ticket, and
Providence Mayor Buddy Cianci running as an Independent _ Kennedy
would have an easy slide to victory, West said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised he doesn't reconsider and think about running,''
West said. ``Basically, the Senate will disappear as an option for
two, three decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Kennedy, who some three decades ago served in the Senate
alongside his brother, Robert, said simply that he will ``respect
Patrick's decision.'' The younger Kennedy also said his father _
and his entire family _ have stayed out of the debate, both in
public and in private.
</P>
<P>
   The outside speculation has taken its toll, however. Though
Kennedy says he is fully ``comfortable with the decision'' and
``very honored'' that so many people think he would make a viable
candidate, he also seems to wish the speculation would stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this town, it's inconceivable to anybody that if they had
the opportunity I have now that they wouldn't take it,'' he said.
``It's pretty heady stuff, and it's exciting. But even good things
can be stressful, sometimes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
