<HEADER>
A4359 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKCOLLEGES18-COX     03-17 0427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKCOLLEGES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Court ruling thrills Georgia's black colleges
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin and Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A federal judge in Savannah has handed the state's
three historically black public universities a major court victory
by dismissing claims brought by plaintiffs who accused the schools
of providing a second-class education and being unconstitutionally
segregated.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge B. Avant Edenfield said the four plaintiffs
who raised those claims lacked standing to file suit against the
historically black colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``While all of the named plaintiffs are to some degree involved
with Georgia's public education system, none have alleged that they
were directly injured by the Board of Regents' alleged
wrongdoing,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Edenfield's order addressed only half of a major lawsuit filed
two years ago against the state university system. In January, the
judge ruled that a racial dual-track admission policy at the
University of Georgia in 1995 led to the illegal rejection of a
white applicant and allowed this student's claims to proceed.
Edenfield is still considering whether to allow similar reverse
discrimination claims raised by another white student denied
admission in 1997 under UGA's revised admission policy.
</P>
<P>
   While Edenfield did not address the merits of the claims raised
against the HBCUs, his ruling had school officials turning
cartwheels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew there was no basis to his claim,'' said Linda Hall,
vice president for university advancement at Fort Valley State
University. ``Our institutions are open to everyone. We don't and
have never kept anybody out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall also defended the role of black colleges and denounced
claims in the lawsuit that they were second-rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find that very offensive,'' she said. If Edenfield had
ruled that the four plaintiffs could pursue the claims against the
HBCUs, the regents would have been forced to defend the racial
composition of the schools and show that they deliver adequate
educational opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Black student enrollment at each of the three HBCUs _ Albany
State, Fort Valley State and Savannah State _ exceeds 91 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Adams, one of the plaintiffs' lawyers, said her office is
considering whether to file an appeal or ask Edenfield to
reconsider his decision. Adams would not comment as to whether her
firm will try to bring new plaintiffs into the case against the
HBCUs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
