<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4363 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SCANDAL-BOS &LR;      03-17 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SCANDAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC OUTS SIX FOR TAKING PAYOFFS FROM SALT LAKE CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ The International Olympic Committee
began its radical makeover with an unprecedented purge Wednesday,
expelling six members who took improper payoffs from the Salt Lake
City bidders for the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   The expulsions came on the heels of a rousing vote of confidence
for the embattled IOC president, Juan Antonio Samaranch, who has
weathered months of calls for his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday the IOC is expected to follow through on the rest of
the changes it promised in the wake of the worst scandal in its
105-year history: allowing members to vote for future host cities
only after a smaller selection group has picked two finalists;
creating an independent ethics commission to oversee members'
behavior; and setting up a study group of two dozen people, half of
them prominent outsiders, to reform by year's end everything from
how the IOC chooses its members to how it distributes its money.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC has been under strong pressure from corporate sponsors
and political leaders to right itself in the aftermath of the Salt
Lake scandal, in which organizers were found to have plied IOC
members with some $1.2 million worth of gifts, cash, travel,
scholarships, medical care, and other inducements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to deliver on what we've said we would from the
beginning of the crisis,'' said IOC vice president Richard Pound of
Canada, who chaired the investigative panel that recommended the
expulsions. ``We will put our own house in order and respond to the
concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   The first step was Wednesday's purge. The IOC, which had not
ousted a member in 37 years, voted by secret ballot to dismiss
Jean-Claude Ganga of the Congo, Zein El Abdin Ahmed Abdel Gadir of
Sudan, Sergio Santander Fantini of Chile, Agustin Arroyo of
Ecuador, Lamine Keita of Mali, and Seiuli Paul Wallwork of Western
Samoa. Four other members _ Bashir Mohamed Attarabulsi of Libya,
Pirjo Haggman of Finland, Charles Mukora of Kenya, and David
Sibandze of Swaziland _ had already resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch, the IOC president since 1980, received an 86-2 vote
of confidence, with two incomplete ballots among the 90 members
voting by secret ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the best person to see us through this crisis,'' said US
member Anita DeFrantz, of the 78-year-old Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   Calling this the IOC's most important meeting ever, Samaranch
opened the session with a frank and somber speech urging the
members to expel the wrongdoers and approve the reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my firm conviction that unless we act quickly,
decisively, and unanimously at this extraordinary session,''
Samaranch said, ``the damage which may be done to the Olympic
movement and to the IOC as a result of the recent disclosures will
be very, very serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch said he accepted responsibility for the Salt Lake
scandal ``even if some of the conduct by bidding cities has itself
been unethical.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the IOC that is being judged, and the IOC that must deal
with the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch said he wanted to lead the IOC through its period of
crisis and the implementation of reforms, but he signaled that he
might not serve out his entire term, which expires in 2001. ``I
have personally given the best of myself to the Olympic movement
over the last 18 years and. . . . my last service to Olympism would
be to structure our organization in order to enter the new
millennium stronger than ever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1962, when Saul Cristavao Ferreira Pires of Portugal
was thrown out for allowing his family's expenses to be paid to the
1960 Summer Olympics, had the IOC expelled one of its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one in the room had gone through the expulsion of a
member,'' said Craig Reedie of Great Britain. ``People were
uncomfortable with the fact that they had to be doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet had the six not been expelled, members said, the IOC would
have been widely seen as incapable of policing itself and the
executive board, which was unanimous for expulsion, would have
stepped down in protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all would have resigned,'' said Jacques Rogge of Belgium.
``That is for certain.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the six members were excluded from voting, each was given
20 minutes to defend himself before the full body, which considered
the issue behind closed doors for five hours. ``They all came, they
were all eloquent, and they all did their best to explain why they
should not be expelled,'' said DeFrantz.
</P>
<P>
   But all six were dismissed by more than the required two-thirds
margin. The vote against Ganga, who allegedly took more than a
quarter-million dollars in payoffs and gifts for himself and his
family, was 88-2. The only remotely close vote was for Wallwork,
who denied knowing that his wife had solicited a $30,000 loan from
former Salt Lake bid chief Tom Welch. The vote against Wallwork was
67-19.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who have been expelled today, I do not plead for them at
all,'' said Hein Verbruggen of the Netherlands, whose countryman,
Anthonius Geesink, earlier had received a warning after Salt Lake
committee members contributed $5,000 to a foundation in his name.
</P>
<P>
   Some members were said to be annoyed that the six hadn't
resigned earlier and spared their colleagues the distasteful duty
of drumming them out. But the prevailing mood in the meeting room
at the Palais de Beaulieu, said Rogge, was ``dignified sadness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated every second of it,'' he added. ``I hated the last
three months of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The scandal has turned the august IOC inside out and set
colleague against colleague. At Tuesday's board meeting, director
general Francois Carrard and Kim Un-yong of South Korea, who has
been censured and is still under investigation for his role in the
Salt Lake scandal, squared off in a shouting match that nearly came
to blows when the 67-year-old Kim, who heads the world taekwondo
federation, struck a menacing martial arts pose that sent Carrard
fleeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A minor incident,'' Carrard said Wednesday. ``I'm physically
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The tensions, building since December, finally achieved
catharsis in the most public and painful day the Lords of the Rings
had ever endured.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're reaching the end of the beginning,'' said Pound. ``It
was painful, but if we hadn't done it, it would have been difficult
to move on. It would be something on our back all the time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
