<HEADLINE>
WAR PREPARATION INTENSIFIES AS KOSOVO TALKS FALTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST _ Talks to end the fighting in Kosovo came close to
ending in failure Wednesday, with international mediators in Paris
complaining that the Serbs are refusing to discuss the deployment
of 30,000 NATO troops to patrol the troubled province.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Yugoslav army moved thousands of troops
closer to Kosovo, fearing a possible NATO attack.
</P>
<P>
   The war preparations also came as European Union forensic
experts issued a report saying that dozens of ethnic Kosovo
Albanians slain in January appeared to be civilians, not
combatants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yugoslav side has chosen not to engage on the
implementation side,'' US mediator Chris Hill told reporters in
Paris. He said the Albanians will sign the agreement ``before the
(peace) conference ends,'' which will be ``very shortly,'' implying
that the talks are nearly finished.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian signature is key because it would put extra
pressure on the Serbs to sign the pact as well. The possibility of
a punitive NATO strike against the Yugoslav republic of Serbia _
which the United States has threatened several times, but not
executed - would also be heightened after the Albanians ink the
document.
</P>
<P>
   US Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has said that NATO
would not strike if both sides failed to sign, but might do so if
only the Serbs refused.
</P>
<P>
   The US and European Union mediators were clearly losing patience
Wednesday with the Serbs, whom EU mediator Wolfgang Petritsch said
held ``the larger part of the responsibility'' for the lack of
progress.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian mediator, Boris Maiorsky, was less pessimistic. ``As
long as there is time and there is hope, we will continue
working,'' said Maiorsky, whose nation has traditionally had closer
ties with the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs and ethnic Albanians are fighting over control of Kosovo,
a southern Serbian province largely inhabited by Albanians. The
Western-crafted peace pact would give the Kosovars political
autonomy for three years, with a possibility of independence from
Serbia later.
</P>
<P>
   On the ground, the situation looked bleak. Yugoslav army troops
set up anti-aircraft missiles in the mountains northwest of
Kosovo's capital, Pristina, rebel leader Suleiman Selimi said
Wednesday in his first interview since being appointed supreme
commander of the Kosovo Liberation Army last month.
</P>
<P>
   Senior officials with the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe said the missiles could be the Yugoslav
version of a heat-seeking, Soviet-built short-range missile that
monitors have seen on regional roads.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting near Prizren, in southern Kosovo, forced 1,500 people
to flee into the mountains, a spokesman for the Organization on
Security and Cooperation in Europe's verification mission said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the forensics expert assigned to examine perhaps the
ugliest episode in the year-long battle -- the murder of 45,
civilian-clothed Albanians in January -- Wednesday called the deed
a ``crime against humanity,'' and said the victims were unarmed.
</P>
<P>
   The Finnish forensic scientist, Helena Ranta, declined to term
the murders a ``massacre,'' but when pressed, she said it appeared
that there had not been an exchange of gunfire before the Racak
residents were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs have insisted that the dead -- found dumped in a Racak
hillside -- were killed during a firefight between Serbs and the
rogue Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   The gruesome murders drew international horror, and sparked
peace talks in Rambouillet, France in February.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to preapre this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
