<SLUG> BC-OUT-OPENER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICE A MERE MEMORY AT LAKES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUNE LAKE, Calif. _ Anglers can expect better access to fishing
holes and campgrounds and more active fish when this year's Eastern
Sierra trout season rolls around April 24.
</P>
<P>
   The region's three ``biggies'' _ Crowley, Convict and June
lakes, the most popular major roadside fishing attractions _ are
already free of ice, and crews are a month ahead of schedule in
readying docks, gas pumps and campgrounds for business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all a lot different than last year,'' said John
Frederickson, who operates June Lake Marina and Crowley Lake Fish
Camp. ``This year it's just completely turned around.''
</P>
<P>
   Frederickson won't soon forget last year's ``nightmare,'' when
the ice on Crowley Lake was unusually thick. Fishermen were unsure
as to whether they could launch boats because the ice didn't thaw
until two days before the Saturday opener. Ice-covered Convict Lake
was closed to the general public for the opening.
</P>
<P>
   But 1998 seemed a distant memory as Frederickson enjoyed
Wednesday's sunny skies and warm temperatures at June Lake, where
patchy ice broke loose three weeks ago in 80 mph winds. Crowley has
been ice-free since March 3. Convict is clear, too, as are all
remaining waters in the June Lake Loop, Bridgeport Reservoir and
nearby Twin Lakes, according to Department of Fish and Game
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the public, they have more opportunities to go to more
lakes,'' said Al Zamudio, a game warden for the Mammoth Lakes,
which, to no one's great surprise, are still laden with ice. ``It
will be more dispersed, which means popular sites will be less
crowded. Some years, people come and, unless they have snowmobiles,
can only get into Crowley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be a really good opener.''
</P>
<P>
   The fishing also should be better; DFG statistics show that
opening-day catch rates improve at Crowley the earlier the lake
thaws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 1938EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4367 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     03-17 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN:   SAMARANCH'S TROUBLES CAN ONLY GET WORSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (With OLY-SCANDAL)  
(rk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This was the easy part, expelling six delegates whose
arms had been caught elbow-deep in the goody bag. The hard part
will be wiping the smirk off people's faces when they talk about
the International Olympic Committee. And they will talk.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the overwhelming 86-2 vote of confidence Juan Antonio
Samaranch received Wednesday in Switzerland, he is now a lame duck
doomed to waddle through his final two years as the president of
this damaged organization. Americans can surely relate to that.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been better if somebody could have persuaded
Samaranch it was time to leave, but he had enough support from his
cadre of hand-picked delegates to enable himself to survive, at
least for the moment. The question is whether association with
Samaranch will taint the visible younger leaders like Richard Pound
of Canada, Anita DeFrantz of the United States and Kevan Gosper of
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   They really have no alternative but to appear loyal to His
Excellency and the system, which is about to be poked and prodded
by irreverent waves of sponsors and news media and American
congressional committee members.
</P>
<P>
   Fevered imagination says it could yet come down to Strom
Thurmond interrogating Juan Antonio Samaranch, live on C-Span:
``Now Senor Samaranch, could you describe for us poor backwards
Americans this-here chateau you folks use in Switzerland?''
</P>
<P>
   Even if that scenario doesn't come true, people will titter
about the IOC and Juan Antonio Samaranch the way they will titter
about President Clinton for the rest of his term. Salt Lake City
was His Excellency's own personal Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   He talked a good game Wednesday, saying, ``It is the IOC that is
being judged, and the IOC that must deal with the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Bidding cities which may have acted improperly are a
matter of the past; it is our IOC which is now on trial.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what he says, Samaranch cannot possibly be the agent
for reform in his short time remaining _ Fightin' Juan Antonio, the
People's Choice. Hardly. There is nothing in his style, his
training, his history, to suggest cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   They were always a semipreposterous lot, with their blue blazers
and their badges and their titles, hiding behind barricades at
swank hotels while athletes sweltered in non-air-conditioned
dormitories in Barcelona, for example. Now it turns out there was
widespread corruption, too. Samaranch tolerated a system of
delegates beholden to him, who roamed the aspiring cities of the
earth, going out with empty trunks, coming home with full trunks.
</P>
<P>
   Now he says it was the other guys, that he knew nothing. But
Samaranch does not get off easily because the action now shifts to
the antithesis of the insular clubbiness of the IOC _ the
scatter-shot openness of the American Congress. Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., the chairman of the Commerce Committee, intends to hold a
hearing on the IOC on April 14.
</P>
<P>
   Used to operating behind walls and moats and electric fences,
the IOC must now go public because of that old Woodward and
Bernstein Watergate dictum _ follow the money.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese corporations donated copious amounts of money to the
IOC to get the 1998 Winter Games in Nagano. Sydney leaders made
sure there was enough money to hold off China for the 2000 Summer
Games. And the pious burghers of Salt Lake City instinctively
greased every delegate who asked for a little favor.
</P>
<P>
   But for truly big money, the trail goes to American-based
international corporations that sponsor the Olympic movement and
also advertise on television. These corporations would, of course,
never commit unethical acts such as bribing business contacts to
influence a bidding contest. That would be wrong, as President
Nixon once put it. These companies do not want their good names
besmirched by bad publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Money also comes into play because American tax dollars support
the IOC as well as the U.S. Olympic Committee. Normal American
citizens _ the little people _ are regularly cajoled to dip into
their piggy banks to support the Olympic ``movement.'' What are
they to think now?
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Olympic movement is only highly visible for 16
days every two years, it commands the world's attention because of
the slobbering obeisance paid by its television network partners
and the hushed, somber tones of the official films. Now people
titter about the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   It can only get worse for His Excellency. The bloodhounds are
out. The subcommittees haven't had anything interesting to do since
that nice Starr finished up. The IOC, in its dependence on American
money, could somehow fall into the province of Dick Armey and Bob
Barr. His Excellency may soon regret Wednesday's vote of support.
There is still time for His Excellency _ as we say in the States _
to do the right thing.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 1938EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
