<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4380 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAYES18-COX     03-17 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAYES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Auction clears out Hayes headquarters
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Some searched for bargains, others for the past. And
some were seeking both.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 people Wednesday poured into what once was Hayes
Corp.'s headquarters in Norcross, Ga., to be part of the two-day
auction to empty the four buildings that once housed the world's
dominant modem maker.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds of former Hayes employees were there, including many who
have landed at companies now bearing the technology torch once
carried by Hayes. They chatted in the halls or strolled outside in
the sun, stopping occasionally to peer in an office window.
</P>
<P>
   But some were bidding.
</P>
<P>
   R. Nuri Otus, president of Emerald Asset Management, which was
hired to run the auction, kicked off the event with the injunction
that participants enjoy themselves. ``It is more fun buying
something at an auction than anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   That judgment seemed to quickly win endorsement as item after
item drew enthusiastic bidding and a sometimes feverish will to
win. That victory sometimes came with a price that some spectators
found inflated _ compared to Internet sales or even prices for new
machines.
</P>
<P>
   Otus, hired to raise as much money as possible to pay off Hayes
Corp. debts, defended it all. A 400 MHz Pentium system sold for
$1,300. ``That's only 30 cents on the dollar,'' Otus said. ``It's
worth that. It's a great value.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a chorus of boos from the crowd. Otus smiled.
</P>
<P>
   Bidders had been permitted to view items Monday and Tuesday.
Wednesday, they had a catalog listing and only had to waggle their
registration cards to bid. Some potential bidders said they were
discouraged by the lack of bargains in the early going.
</P>
<P>
   A map of the world sold for $1,300. A roomful of plants went for
$200.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Ragusa, who worked for five years at Hayes, was at the
auction to flesh out an office at Solectron in Duluth, where he now
works. Joe Anderson of Buford was hoping to pick up a computer for
his personal use. Sam Davis of Telesync in Norcross was looking for
electronic test equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Tift, owner of Leesburg-based Digital Depot, bought a
room of office basics like shelves for $750. ``I'd like a few
computers and modems, if the prices don't get too high.''
</P>
<P>
   In one hallway, a vendor sold candy and soda. Nearby hung a
painting of neckties and another of dogs. Above a cluster of empty
chairs hung a banner proclaiming Project Overture ``Prelude to the
Information Age.''
</P>
<P>
   In what seemed a live demonstration of crowd psychology, Otus
rapped out a rapid-fire narration, coaxing bidders to outdo each
other, hyping whatever item was on the block. ``Eight hundred, bid
825 _ are we all done?'' he snapped.
</P>
<P>
   A coffee table sold for $75. A notebook computer went for
$1,200. Some 56k bps modems sold for $100 each. A microwave oven
sold for $40, a refrigerator for $600.
</P>
<P>
   ``IBM typewriters,'' Otus sang out. ``Listen to me. You don't
need this computer stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Some items were clearly obsolete. Some hardly seemed dated at
all.
</P>
<P>
   The contents of ``Room 4,'' workstations and chairs, sold for
$4,500. One of many Hewlett-Packard laserjet printers sold for
$450. Up came a Compaq 80486 with a Gateway monitor and Epson
printer. ``Can I have $5,000?'' shouted Otus in mock seriousness.
``How about 50 bucks to go?''
</P>
<P>
   The winning bid was $175.
</P>
<P>
   Offers on a table started at $100 and leaped to $900 in seconds
while a woman held a wireless phone and relayed the interest of a
bidder at the other end. Finally, she nodded to the spotter. ``He's
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Otus called for bids on an executive desk and chair. ``These
were in the office of Dennis Hayes ... and others.''
</P>
<P>
   It sold for $3,250.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spotters'' for Otus roamed the aisles, pointing, shouting,
cajoling and signaling for ever-higher bids.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just wanted to be part of the show,'' said William Hooper,
who worked at Hayes for six years, and is now principal engineer at
Advanced Charger Technology. He was sent to the auction to buy a
digitizing oscilloscope, a $10,000 machine he had first purchased
for Hayes. He ended up paying more than he expected _ $5,500.
</P>
<P>
   Hooper found himself bidding against Dale Heatherington, a
co-founder with Dennis Hayes of the company that became Hayes Corp.
As it turned out, there were two devices. Hooper and Heatherington
each came away with one.
</P>
<P>
   By day's end today, Emerald plans to have called for bids 4,115
times, counting the very first, unnumbered item.
</P>
<P>
   Holding up a hockey stick that had been found in the former
office of founder Dennis Hayes, Otus read the 1993 inscription:
``Happy B-Day, Dennis Hayes.'' The signature, he said, was that of
superstar Wayne Gretzky. ``That's my story and I'm sticking to
it,'' Otus said.
</P>
<P>
   The stick sold for $500.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
