u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRONTIER18-COX     03-17 0386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRONTIER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Frontier phone company bought by Bermuda's Global Crossing
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Frontier Corp., a telephone company that has its
regional headquarters in Atlanta, is being acquired by
Bermuda-based upstart Global Crossing Ltd. for $11.2 billion in
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Frontier is the fifth-largest long-distance company and the
tenth-largest local phone company in the nation, mainly serving
small and medium-sized businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to phone service, the company offers high-speed data
and Internet services. Its customers in Atlanta include InfoCure
and Habitat for Humanity.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, Atlanta-based Cox Communications partnered with
Frontier to provide long-distance telephone service. For all
practical purposes, however, that business arrangement has ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are anticipating virtually no impact (from the proposed
merger). We have a very limited relationship with Frontier,'' said
Amy Porter, a spokeswoman for Cox. Porter said the long-distance
service is no longer being marketed but that the a few thousand
remaining customers are still being served. None of those customers
are in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications is controlled by Cox Enterprises Inc., which
owns The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's deal provides a U.S. foothold for Global Crossing, a
2-year-old company that's building a worldwide fiber-optic network
to carry voice, data, video and Internet traffic.
</P>
<P>
   With the addition of Frontier, that network would connect 159
cities in the United States, Japan, Europe and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing recently hired a top AT&AMP;T executive to become
its chief executive. Robert Annunziata was the former head of
Teleport Communications Group, a local telephone company he built
up and sold to AT&AMP;T for $12 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing is offering $62 a share in stock for each
Frontier share, a 40 percent premium over Frontier's closing price
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, Frontier climbed $5.87 1/2 to
$50.50 a share, or 13 percent, after hitting a 52-week high of
52.75. The stock is up nearly 50 percnet year to date.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
