<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BLAKE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAKE DOWNPLAYS ROLE MEETING PLAYED IN TURNAROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Rob Blake is right.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Blake's players-only meeting last week, and subsequent
meetings with the Kings' coaching staff, had nothing to do with the
impressive victories that followed.
</P>
<P>
   This is what the low-key Blake would have you believe,
downplaying to the bitter end the impact of his words, even as his
teammates continue to praise him for standing up and asserting
himself as the Kings' captain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody makes a pretty big deal of it,'' Blake said
following Wednesday's practice at the Forum. ``I don't think it's
that big a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   His teammates and coaches disagree.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the meeting, Coach Larry Robinson spoke of
the need for a captain to be able to stand before his teammates
``and maybe hurt a few feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Luc Robitaille said, ``I know how much things were
bothering him the last few months. The truth is always the best
remedy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings (26-36-5) play host to the Mighty Ducks tonight,
seeking their fourth consecutive victory in a late-season bid to
squeak into the playoffs, which begin next month.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Kings achieve their objective, Blake's vocal role
will be remembered as the turning point, whether he likes it or
not.
</P>
<P>
   It also probably will be remembered as a moment when the
29-year-old Blake matured into his role as the Kings' captain, a
position he has held since the 1996-97 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's taken more of a take-charge attitude,'' Robinson said.
``That's great to see. The respect has always been there. But he's
never been a vocal type, to really show his feelings and speak up.
You look at the good teams. (Detroit's Steve Yzerman) is more of a
silent type. But the last four or five years, he's really spoken up
and gotten everybody on the same page, and look at the change
they've had.''
</P>
<P>
   After years of disappointment, the Red Wings have won the last
two Stanley Cups, and Yzerman has been credited with leading the
way on and off the ice. No one expects the Kings to win the Stanley
Cup this year, but if Blake's words catapult them into the
playoffs, he will have done his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Robby came out and talked to us, it really hit home for a
lot of us,'' winger Russ Courtnall said. ``I think we're a better
team for it. We all think a lot of Rob as a person and a player. It
was tough for him because it's not like him to get up and speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did it, and he did it so well. I was really proud of him. I
have even more respect for Rob than I did before. If some guys
didn't know it before, they definitely know now that he is in
control of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake always has been a leader on the ice, but the opportunity
or need for him to lead off it never had been greater.
</P>
<P>
   The first five years of Blake's career, the Kings were Wayne
Gretzky's team. Gretzky was traded during Blake's sixth season, but
Blake missed almost the entire year with a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   The next season, the Kings were in the depths of a rebuilding
program, and Blake was battling his way back from the knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, during which Blake won the Norris Trophy as the
NHL's top defenseman, there was no single moment when the critical
mass of negative events called for the measures Blake took last
week.
</P>
<P>
   He may wish he'd acted sooner, but there is little point in
second-guessing. The point is that he acted.
</P>
<P>
   He called the meeting and spoke honestly, not sparing feelings.
Then, in a separate meeting, Blake asked Robinson to stick with a
lineup, and Robinson listened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll run the dressing room, I'll take that responsibility,''
Blake said, ``but Larry has got to respect what I have to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson has continued to listen to Blake this week, and the
Kings haven't made a false step since their captain stepped
forward.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't mean the Kings will go undefeated the rest of the
season, or that they'll definitely make the playoffs. But that
would seem to miss the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen him grow,'' Courtnall said. ``I think it took a lot
of guts to talk to us. When you're not a speaker, to talk to a lot
of guys, it's tough. He's a quiet man. He leads by his actions. It
took a lot for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
