<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Apple in sharing mood with Mac OS X software
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Apple Computer Inc. has little to lose and potentially
much to gain by letting software developers tweak its new operating
system for servers, computing experts said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Mac OS X Server, which went on sale Tuesday for $499, is
Apple's first true system for servers and gives Apple a powerful
entry in the low end of that market, said James Staten of
DataQuest.
</P>
<P>
   Servers are powerful computers that support networks of PCs in
offices, process bank-teller machine transactions, handle the
world's e-mail and host Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   While Apple's new system will look and ``feel'' like the Mac OS,
it is rooted in Unix, the powerful operating system used in most of
the world's ``mission critical'' jobs. Those are applications, such
as data retrieval, whose loss during a computer crash could cripple
a company or government agency.
</P>
<P>
   Apple acknowledged it is aiming considerably lower than those
jobs with Mac OS X, which it is bundling on its $4,999 Macintosh
Server G3.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts agree there may be a market for the system among
less-experienced users who want to set up a Web site as well as
many schools that have remained loyal to Macs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're focusing on departments within companies, small
businesses, education institutions and even individuals who want a
high-performance server (and) who are not Unix geeks,'' said Henry
Norr, former editor of MacWeek.
</P>
<P>
   He said that setting up a Web site is simple on Mac OS X, while
features such as NetBoot simplify the process of adding
applications for networks of PCs and make it less likely students
can tamper with the applications.
</P>
<P>
   Apple hopes that making its ``source code,'' the original lines
of instructions, available to software developers will result in
improvements that will be added to future versions.
</P>
<P>
   In that, it joins the growing ``open source'' movement that has
been highlighted by the popularity of Linux.
</P>
<P>
   That is the Unix-based system that has evolved quickly in recent
months as developers downloaded it free from the Internet and
shared improvements they made. As a result, major computer
companies such as Dell Computer Corp. and IBM will include Linux in
some of their server products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linux adherents have been passionate about it,'' said Tom
Edgar, associate vice president of computing at the University of
Texas. ``Apple is hoping to capitalize on the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
