<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4388 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABORTION-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      03-17 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE GIVES INITIAL OK TO `PARENTAL RIGHTS BILL' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Girls 17 and younger could no longer seek legal
abortions in Texas without notifying a parent or judge under a bill
initially approved, 23-8, by the Texas Senate on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a parental rights bill,'' said Sen. Florence Shapiro,
R-Plano, sponsor of the measure. ``In fact, most parents are
shocked ... that their minor child can have this invasive medical
procedure without their knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Bill 30, known as the parental notification bill, is
nearly identical to a measure passed by the Senate in 1997 but
killed in the House on a technicality. The sponsor, Rep. Arlene
Wohlgemuth, R-Burleson, reacted to the death of the bill by using
the same technicality to wipe out dozens of bills in a retaliation
dubbed the ``Memorial Day Massacre.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, even family planning groups opposed to the
legislation are predicting it will pass in some form this session,
saying there are enough votes in the House in favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate the leadership Senator Shapiro has shown on this
issue,'' said Gov. George W. Bush, calling the bill ``a positive
step to reduce the number of abortions in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   However, opponents predicted that frightened young girls will
turn to illegal and unsafe abortions or suicide rather than admit
to a parent or judge that they are pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you prevent her from going to some back-room doctor in
Houston, Texas, or down to Mexico and crossing the border and
getting an abortion?'' asked Sen. John Whitmire, D-Houston.
</P>
<P>
   For 3 1/2 hours, however, those arguments were shot down by
backers of the bill who said parents' rights must be restored.
</P>
<P>
   ``As legislators,'' said Shapiro, ``we owe this not only to the
children of this state, but we owe it even more to the parents of
this state.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill requires doctors to notify a parent or guardian 48
hours before an abortion can be performed on a minor. If the parent
can't be notified by phone, the waiting period begins the day a
certified letter is mailed. Doctors who don't comply could be
prosecuted for a Class A misdemeanor, with a maximum penalty of a
year in the county jail and/or a $4,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   In cases where a teen-aged girl insists her parents not be told,
a judge can make the decision to authorize or deny the abortion
instead. This process, called ``judicial bypass'' troubled many of
the senators, although an amendment allowing clergy or mental
health professionals also to act in behalf of parents, failed.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jeff Wentworth, R-San Antonio, said under the proposal a
judge who determines a minor is mature and informed can authorize
an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reverse of that is if the court finds out that the minor
is not mature, she can become a mother,'' he said. ``She has to
become a mother under this law.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the percentage of Texas teens who don't involve their
parents voluntarily is 10 percent or 39 percent, society _ their
parents, schools and churches _ have failed them, he argued.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these girls that are 12 and 13 and 14 years old who
watch MTV, who are surrounded by a society that is all too
concentrated on sex, don't know that fooling around with their
boyfriend who is two or three years older can get them pregnant.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, judges from county courts at law, probate courts
or district courts can act as the judicial bypass. Whitmire offered
an unsuccessful amendment that would also allow justices of the
peace who are ``closer to the community'' to also make the
decision. For one thing, he said, many more of them speak Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mike Moncrief, D-Fort Worth, questioned whether candidates
who run on anti-abortion platforms are in the best position to
decide the issue. Shapiro said judges routinely refuse to take
public positions on matters that come before them in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you about Harris County,'' said Whitmire, noting
that several judges there ``run on an anti-abortion slate. We're
going to force her to the Harris County Courthouse where we all
know locally there is an anti-abortion atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Steve Ogden, R-Bryan, praised a provision that would
require a judge to report any child abuse _ such as incest _ to
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think your bill addresses a very powerful issue that needs
to get up to the surface,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Human Services Committee Chairman Judith Zaffirini,
D-Laredo, said Shapiro's parental notification measure has support
from 74 percent of Texans polled. She also cited numbers showing
nearly three times as many people registered or testified in favor
of the bill than against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to ask you this question and ask you to ponder it
once again,'' Shapiro said at the close of the debate. ``Who should
be involved in the important decision making for children?''
</P>
<P>
   Senators agreed to wait another day before voting on final
passage of the bill. They first wish to draft and consider an
amendment that would offer doctors a defense against criminal
prosecution for unwittingly accepting fake identification from a
minor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
