<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-PINOCHET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENGLISH COURT TO DELIVER PINOCHET'S FATE MARCH 24  
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Gen. Augusto Pinochet will learn next week whether he
is free to return to Chile or must remain in England to face
possible extradition to Spain on charges of crimes against
humanity.
</P>
<P>
   The Law Lords, Britain's highest court, said Wednesday that they
would make public next Wednesday their ruling on his claim that as
a former head of state he has immunity from arrest. He has been
held under house arrest in England since Oct. 16 in response to an
application from a Spanish judge seeking his extradition to Madrid
to stand trial on charges of murder, torture and kidnapping in
connection with the deaths or disappearances of more than 3,000
people in the 17 years he ruled Chile.
</P>
<P>
   The High Court ruled in Pinochet's favor on Oct. 28, but the Law
Lords a month later reversed the verdict in a decision that in
effect obliged him to stay in England for what was expected to be
at least a year of extradition hearings and appeals. That decision
was set aside when it emerged that one of the judges had failed to
declare his connection to Amnesty International, a party to the
case. A new panel held 12 days of hearings that ended Feb. 4.
</P>
<P>
   The former Chilean dictator, 83, has been living in a rented
house in a London suburb since being released on Dec. 1 from a
hospital where he was recovering from back surgery. He has
denounced the charges against him as ``the lies of Spain,'' and in
his sole court appearance he told a British judge he did not
recognize the judge's authority.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
