<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4415 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKART-SHOW18-COX     03-17 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKART-SHOW18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rich `Legacy' thrives through black colleges
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Museum directors like to tout their exhibitions, but
Kinshasha Holman Conwill is hardly overstating her case when she
calls the Studio Museum in Harlem's new show a ``revelation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To Conserve a Legacy: American Art From Historically Black
Colleges and Universities,'' which opened Wednesday, brings
together 175 works selected from the collections of six colleges,
including Clark Atlanta University.
</P>
<P>
   The very existence of these collections will be a surprise to
many people, and yet, until very recently, the schools served as
the primary patrons for black artists denied access to the
mainstream art world.
</P>
<P>
   ``This show presents American art through an African-American
lens,'' said co-curator Richard Powell, chairman of Duke
University's art and art history department.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, for every famous artist such as Elizabeth
Catlett or Romare Bearden, there's a name you don't know, an artist
whose work might have disappeared but for the support of these
institutions. Works by white and Native American artists from the
collections are also included, though they are in the minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a show about discovery,'' said Powell, who worked with
Jock Reynolds, director of the Yale Art Gallery. ``I was, for
example, surprised at how many African-American abstractionists
there were.''
</P>
<P>
   The show will travel to seven cities after closing here July 11.
CAU and the High Museum of Art will co-host the Atlanta stop in
June 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Co-sponsored by the Studio Museum and the Addison Gallery of
American Art at Phillips Academy in Andover, Mass., ``Legacy'' is
also concerned with conservation. Experts at the Williamstown
(Mass.) Art Conservation Center restored 1,400 works _ more than
will be exhibited _ belonging to the participating schools. In an
effort to encourage minority participation in the conservation
field, students from each of the six schools represented served as
interns at the conservation center.
</P>
<P>
   A hefty catalog (MIT Press, $60) documents the project and the
conservation efforts, and each of the works was researched, some by
rising African-American scholars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see this as a great boost to the institutions,'' said Tina
Dunkley, director of the Clark Atlanta University Galleries. ``It's
also a thrill to see all of this work together. I think the show is
a work of art in itself.''
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB: For more on the show and related programs, go
to:http://www.studiomuseuminharlem.org.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Fox writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
