<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4416 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GANGSCOM18-COX     03-17 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GANGS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 COM18-COX &HT;    Crips, Bloods hailed on the Web: The gangs all here
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Visitors to the FlyPlaya Web site will see the words
``C'z Up,'' a greeting used by the Crips, an infamous street gang.
Scrolling down, visitors can view pictures of slain rapper Tupac
Shakur, animated marijuana leaves and an insulting reference to
``slobs'' _ Crips slang for the Bloods, their archrivals.
</P>
<P>
   The creator of the site, Atlanta resident Kris Lester _ ``Shawty
K'' on the Web _ insists she's not a real Crip. She maintains she's
just a virtual gangsta, part of a small group of computer users who
identify with the underground chic of gang life, but who have more
experience firing up PCs than firing Uzis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is just a way for me to associate with Crips from
all over the country and the world,'' Lester said by way of e-mail,
in answer to a request to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lester has latched on to a real subcurrent on the Web.
Just like baggy, jailhouse-style jeans and gangsta rap,
Web-disseminated images of gang life have attracted a following.
It's impossible to tell how many aficionados are genuine gang
members and how many are simply drawn by the cachet of the ``thug
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Lester declined to discuss her Crip-obsessed Web site further,
fearing she might ``get arrested for trying to get people to join a
gang.'' And she may have good reason to be concerned.
</P>
<P>
   This week, a group of Fayette County teenagers, who had dubbed
themselves the Rollin' 5 Crackas, were charged with ``tagging'' a
bridge with spray paint and attempting to recruit gang members with
their Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Their Web site has been shut down, and the father of one of the
teens claims the gang was ``a joke.'' But the Fayette County
Sheriff's Office missed the punch line.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids claimed to be a spin-off of the Crips,'' said Maj.
Bruce Jordan of the sheriff's department. ``I don't know if they're
for real, but everybody is jumping on the information highway.
There's no doubt in my mind that real gangs are doing it also.''
</P>
<P>
   Gang presence on the web can be traced in large part to Dirk
Lemmons, a 41-year-old former accountant from rural Missouri, who
is webmaster for two websites: www.crips.com and www.bloods.com, a
growing cyber-network of what appear to be real-life gang-bangers
and wannabes.
</P>
<P>
   Working from his family farm near Branson, Lemmons has been
helping gang devotees who want to get their homepages on the
Internet, including Lester's Atlanta-based Crips site.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the websites are crude. They typically include pictures
of souped-up cars, a chronology of the gang's origins and
descriptions of their favorite automatic weapons. A common feature
is a computer-generated Cadillac with the words ``Pimp Mail,''
which users click to send e-mail. Many of the images on the sites
are disturbing _ one link takes visitors to gory autopsy photo of
Shakur.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the sites list the names and members of purported
gangs in the Atlanta area, such as the East Point Crips and the
Coweta County Crips.
</P>
<P>
   Lemmons says he gets about 50,000 hits to his site daily, most
of which he speculates are generated from young gang poseurs more
likely to be grounded by their parents than arrested by the police.
</P>
<P>
   He claims his sites have a law-and-order motive: to show the
scary reality of gang life. ``It's like taking a kid for a visit to
prison to scare the snot out of them,'' Lemmons said in a telephone
interview. ``We're trying to scare kids into seeing what gang life
can do to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, if the aim is to discourage gang members, the message is
subtle, and easily lost among the pictures of kids giving gang
signs and e-mails dissing rivals. Following the arrests in Fayette
County, Lemmons pulled the sites off his server for several days,
fearing that he also might be accused of trying to lure people into
gangs.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Jordan of Fayette said he's never heard of Lemmons, and
doubts his department would be interested in his activities. But
Detective Chuck Zeglin, a gang specialist with the Los Angeles
Police Department, has surfed some of the sites Lemmons helped
create.
</P>
<P>
   Zeglin, though, doubts virtual gangstas are much of a threat to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about 10 percent are gang members, the rest are
probably phonies and wannabes,'' Zeglin said. ``Out here, gang
members are street thugs with no education, broken families and are
not computer-literate.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemmons argues that gang members are more Internet-savvy than
Zeglin believes, and even if they don't have computers at home,
they do have access. His can trace the location of his users, and
most of them are turning up at schools and public libraries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a misconception to think that a gang-banger can't use a
computer,'' Lemmons said, ``and just about any kid knows how to get
on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB: For more on virtual gangstas, go to these sites:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.crips.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.bloods.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.crips.com/FlyPlaya/
</P>
<P>
   http://hometown.aol.com/countkrazy/index.html
</P>
<P>
   www.mafiacrip.com/ocg/
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
