<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Small investors offered a multitude of advice
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Whether the Dow Jones industrial average trades at or
above 10,000 is probably a remote issue for most small investors.
They're more interested in advice on how to pick stock and mutual
funds _ advice the business press gladly provides.
</P>
<P>
   _ Money (April) cautions small investors against ``betting the
ranch'' on S&AMP;P 500 index funds, since they expose you ``to more
risk than you probably realize.''
</P>
<P>
   Unmanaged index funds are tied to a stock index such as the S&AMP;P
500. They can't underperform the market, but they can't outperform
it either. Money suggests indexing be used to build ``a sensibly
diversified portfolio'' of different index funds, or a mix of index
funds, stocks and managed mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kiplinger's Personal Finance Magazine (April) joins forces
with investors who prefer the big, reliable blue chip stocks to
even the good small stocks because ``giant companies are driving
the nation's can't-shut-me-down economy to new heights.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are 10 big ones: Microsoft (ticker symbol MSFT), Intel
(INTC), Cisco Systems (CSCO), MCI WorldCom (WCOM), Coca-Cola (KO),
Walt Disney (DIS), Time Warner (TWX), Pfizer (PFE), Merck &AMP; Co.
(MRK) and Medtronic (MDT).
</P>
<P>
   _ Individual Investor (April), meanwhile, recommends that now is
a good time for small investors to review their holdings, in light
of the stock market's recent gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't know when stocks will crash next, but you can be
prepared. And should the market continue to soar, you don't want to
miss out on all the gains it offers,'' the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine looks at risk-reward ratios and suggests there are
some fail-safe stocks and fail-safe funds.
</P>
<P>
   _ P.O.V. Magazine (April) celebrates four years of publishing by
looking at ``lessons from the street,'' meaning Wall Street. The
magazine looks at various investing strategies but comes back to
that old-fashioned piece of advice: ``Smart investing is founded on
long-term goals.''
</P>
<P>
   THE BUZZ ABOUT E-BIZ
</P>
<P>
   Business Week (March 22) offers a magazine-within-a-magazine,
called ``e.biz'' _ the catchword for electronic commerce, the
Internet, electronic money transfer, e-mail and cyber-this and
cyber-that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Electronic business is perhaps the most sweeping
transformation of the corporate landscape in decades,'' says the
magazine. ``It means re-engineering and throwing out the old
business models.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
