<HEADER>
A4429 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      03-17 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: COMPLEX AND POLITICAL, MEDICARE DEFIES A QUICK FIX
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ira C. Magaziner, the politically tone-deaf
architect of President Clinton's ill-fated health plan, and Sen.
John Breaux, D-La., the deal-making chairman of a commission that
failed to find a solution to Medicare's financial woes, share what
might be called the hubris of health care reformers: the belief
that they could devise an all-encompassing scheme to redesign a
huge swath of America's health care system.
</P>
<P>
   Both failed spectacularly. Their efforts suggest that piecemeal,
incremental changes are the only ones feasible at the moment, given
the political and technical complexity of the subject.
</P>
<P>
   After a year of work, the 17-member Medicare commission expired
on Tuesday, one vote short of the 11 needed to endorse any formal
recommendations to Congress or the president. Breaux said he would
continue his effort to inject free-market competition into
Medicare, and even a harsh critic of the plan, Sen. John D.
Rockefeller, D-W.Va., said Wednesday that some version of it might
eventually ``land on the president's desk.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaux's proposal for Medicare and Magaziner's scheme for the
entire health care system were both built on the idea of ``managed
competition'': that the government would set rules for private
health plans to compete for business, in the hope that they would
offer more benefits and higher-quality care at lower prices. Health
maintenance organizations would compete against traditional health
insurance plans, which pay a fixed fee for each service.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux and Magaziner would both have offered new benefits,
including prescription drug coverage, while creating strong
incentives for subscribers to choose lower-cost health plans.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of these efforts suggests once again the difficulty,
maybe even the futility, of comprehensive proposals to overhaul the
way health care is financed and delivered. The technical substance
of health policy and the politics of the issue are so complex that
they frustrate such ambitious efforts.
</P>
<P>
   But the complexity of health care and the rapid pace of medical
discoveries also make it difficult for government to regulate this
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is absolutely impossible to micro-manage health care in the
21st century'' as Congress has required, Breaux said, noting that
Medicare uses many convoluted formulas to pay doctors, hospitals,
nursing homes, HMOs and home health care agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The promise of simplicity is one reason for the appeal of the
plan that Breaux drafted with help from Rep. Bill Thomas of
California, the leading Republican on the commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are at least 10,000 Medicare reimbursement codes for
hospital and physician services, and there are more than 3,000
counties in the United States,'' said Len M. Nichols, a health care
economist at the Urban Institute. ``It's very difficult for
Medicare to get 10,000 prices right in 3,000 counties. It would be
simpler for the government to learn how to pay the right price for
a package of services. The Breaux plan promised to move in that
direction, but it didn't specify enough details to engender a
consensus that we were ready to move now.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the Breaux-Thomas plan say it will use the magic
of the market to save money, encouraging greater efficiency among
providers of health care. ``The market can accomplish very good
things,'' said Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., a commission member.
</P>
<P>
   But anyone who thinks federal regulation would vanish under
Breaux's plan is dreaming. Breaux would create a powerful new
government agency, the Medicare Board. The board would negotiate
with health plans, approve their benefits, determine the federal
payment to each plan and compute the premiums charged to
beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   For those who want to redesign Medicare, the thorniest issue is
how to provide a new prescription drug benefit. Of the 39 million
Medicare beneficiaries, more than 6 million are in HMOs, and most
of these HMOs already offer drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in Congress say drug coverage must also be available
to people in the original fee-for-service Medicare program. But
that makes drug companies nervous because it raises the possibility
that Medicare would regulate drug prices, just as it regulates what
doctors charge Medicare patients. Judith H. Bello, executive vice
president of the Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of
America, said that to date she had not seen any proposal for drug
coverage that relied adequately on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare costs are growing faster than the program's revenues,
and the gap will widen as baby boomers become eligible for Medicare
after 2010. But Congress usually responds only to pressing
problems, and Medicare's financial troubles seem less urgent today
than in 1997, when Congress created the Medicare commission.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare spending rose last year just 1.5 percent, the smallest
increase since the beginning of the program in 1965. Nancy-Ann Min
DeParle, the head of the Medicare program, said this was ``probably
an aberration,'' reflecting a decline in the use of home health
care and a reduction in fraud and abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, Breaux and many Republicans are talking about
comprehensive changes in the structure of Medicare. But Congress
will have its hands full fixing the law it passed in 1997. That law
was intended to create new health insurance options for the elderly
and to entice more HMOs into the Medicare market, under a new
program known as Medicare+Choice.
</P>
<P>
   Many HMOs unexpectedly pulled out of Medicare or reduced their
service areas, causing confusion and alarm for more than 440,000
beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing that he would offer his own proposal to revamp
Medicare, Clinton said: ``We must find agreement this year.
Medicare is too important to let partisan politics stand in the way
of vital progress.''
</P>
<P>
   The outlook for action is unclear, but one thing is certain.
Politics will pervade the debate. It could be no other way in a
program that spends more than $200 billion a year to care for 39
million people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 2023EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
