<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4432 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-MEMORIALS-440&AMP;     03-17 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-MEMORIALS-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 LATE ISRAELI LEADERS, 2 GRAND MUSEUMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In what will inevitably be seen as competing
memorials, the families and allies of Yitzhak Rabin and Menachem
Begin are raising millions of dollars to build museum-scale centers
to honor the late prime ministers.
</P>
<P>
   In New York and Washington this week, Rabin's wife, Leah, is
starting a $30 million fund-raising drive for the planned Yitzhak
Rabin Center for Israel Studies. It would be modeled after what she
called ``the grand tradition of American presidential libraries.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Mrs. Rabin, her children and granddaughter will be
received at the White House by President Clinton and Hillary Rodham
Clinton, whose friendship with the Rabins is to be highlighted at
the center.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Thursday, in Jerusalem, the governing board of the
planned Menachem Begin Heritage Center will hold its first meeting,
with Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu expected to attend. The
board will review plans to start construction in the fall of the
privately financed $14 million building. It, too, has been
consciously patterned after American presidential libraries.
</P>
<P>
   Years after their deaths, the two former prime ministers still
represent the governing poles of Israeli politics. Making the
issues especially charged, both projects are advancing during a
bitter election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I had in mind was something like the Kennedy Library at
Harvard,'' said Rabin's daughter, Dalia Rabin-Pelossof, a driving
force behind the Rabin center. ``My father's assassination should
be remembered in Israel for national reasons, not for political
reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   The center would be built in the modern heart of Tel Aviv, where
Rabin lived for most of his adult life and where, in 1995, he was
the victim of an Israeli assassin opposed to his peace pact with
the Palestinians. Tel Aviv is also the heartland of the staunchly
secular Labor rank and file, for whom Rabin remains an inspiring
party symbol.
</P>
<P>
   The Begin Center, by contrast, would be on a hillside that
overlooks Mount Zion and the ancient walls of Jerusalem, the city
Begin built into the national political base for his right-wing
Likud party. In a controversial ruling to forgive taxes,
Netanyahu's Likud government let the private foundation of the
center acquire the site at almost no cost.
</P>
<P>
   As with the Rabin center, the Begin memorial would contain
archives and artifacts from the prime minister's years in office, a
collection of writings by and about him and a headquarters for
planned educational projects.
</P>
<P>
   The Parliament voted to provide public funds for the annual
operating costs of both centers, estimated at $5 million yearly.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A presidential-style memorial in the American mold strikes some
Israelis as too grandiose, and too individualized, for a country
that has historically cultivated a collective and personally
austere leadership style.
</P>
<P>
   The prototype for a prime ministerial library is still David
Ben-Gurion's red-roofed kibbutz cottage in the Negev, a one-story
frame dwelling crammed with 5,000 worn volumes collected over his
lifetime. Later prime ministers have been honored after their
deaths with research archives, but not museum-scale memorials.
</P>
<P>
   More than $10 million has been raised from private Israeli
donors for the $25 million Rabin Center building and a $15 million
endowment, according to the family. The center is to feature a
research institute and a museum to commemorate Rabin's career and
response to his assassination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
