<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE HAS THE ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ The Journal of the American Medical Association quotes Dr.
 &UR; James Wyatt &LR;  of Harvard Medical School, a specialist in sleep
disorders, who has determined that: Sleep itself is ``without a
doubt, hands down, the best countermeasure to sleep deprivation.''
</P>
<P>
   _ A reader from Lake Ann, Mich., inquires of the editors of
Sports Afield: ``Is it true that red squirrels chew the _ should I
say this? _ `balls' off black squirrels?'' The answer: no.
</P>
<P>
   _ Appearing on San Francisco's BayTV's ``Morning Show'' last
Friday,  &UR; Angela Alioto &LR;  flaunted her seismological expertise. In
response to host  &UR; Joe Oliver &LR; , who asked whether there is a safety
concern about getting Bay Bridge improvements done before the next
big earthquake, Alioto asserted: ``As a native San Franciscan, I
can tell you there will not be a big earthquake.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE NOT-SO-FINE ART OF LYING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Most people lie three or four times a day, says POV magazine,
and most people ``deceive 30 percent of the folks they interact
with''; major conversations between spouses are 10 percent lies;
and dating conversation is 30 percent lies.
</P>
<P>
   One way to tell a lie, says  &UR; David Lieberman &LR; , author of ``Never
Be Lied to Again,'' is to check out ``eye accessing clues.'' If you
ask a right-handed person where he's been and he's telling the
truth, he'll look up and left ``because that's the side of the
brain that's used for recalling visual information.'' If the answer
is a lie, he'll ``look up and to the right'' while making up an
untruthful scenario.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Diana Rigg &LR; , who is Cameron Mackintosh professor of
contemporary theater at Oxford University, attracted an overflowing
roomful of students to her first lecture, 25 to her second and 11
to her third. Her first lecture consisted of her reading aloud her
worst reviews, which was ``amusing,'' one student told the
Telegraph, ``but perhaps not quite what everyone expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Rigg is placing an ad in the Drama Society newsletter to elicit
suggestions for lecture ideas.
</P>
<P>
   _ Does nepotism help film careers? The cast of  &UR; Clint &LR; 
 &UR; Eastwood &LR; 's new movie, ``True Crime,'' which opens Friday, includes
Eastwood, former significant other  &UR; Frances Fisher &LR; ,
 &UR; Francesca Fisher Eastwood &LR; , their 5-year-old daughter, and  &UR; Sydney &LR; 
 &UR; Poitier &LR; , the daughter of  &UR; Sidney Poitier &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Salman Rushdie &LR; 's adventures with U2 are the inspiration for
his next novel, ``The Ground Beneath Her Feet,'' in conjunction
with which he has written a song. U2 guitarist  &UR; the &LR; 
 &UR; Edge &LR;  told Rolling Stone that Rushdie ``faxed through lyrics and
 &UR; Bono &LR;  came up with this melody.'' He said U2 is considering
recording the tune for its next album.
</P>
<P>
   The book is to be published April 13, and Rolling Stone
theorizes that the song will be available over the Net around that
time.
</P>
<P>
   _ Howdy from the land of hospitality: Looking through the
Champion America Inc. industrial sign catalog,  &UR; Vernon Waight &LR;  ran
across: ``No Trespassing, Violators Will Be Shot!''; ``No
Trespassing'' (with skull and crossbones); ``Trespass Here and
You'll Wish We Called the Cops''; ``Trespassers Used for Target
Practice''; ``Unauthorized Vehicles Keep Out, Police Summoned
Immediately''; ``No Trespassing, We Arm Bears''; ``These Premises
Protected by Smith &AMP; Wesson''; ``These Premises Patrolled by
Psychotic Gun Owner''; ``We Shoot First and Ask Questions Later.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SLIP-SLIDING AWAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Michael Hancock &LR;  forwarded a citation from the latest issue of
the Paris Bar Association newsletter:
</P>
<P>
   ``Our colleagues are reminded that the use of roller-blades
between the Criminal Chamber and the Bar Association offices is
henceforth prohibited. ... A recent accident, which occurred in
front of the office of the bailiff of the 9th chamber, reminds us
of the dangers of this practice, especially when still dressed in
court robes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Few people are neutral about pasta these days.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Health magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
