A4445 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABORTION-BILL18-COX     03-17 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-BILL18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas senaors approve abortion notification bill
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas senators voted Wednesday to require
doctors to notify parents before performing abortions on minors,
but another bill requiring parental consent was pronounced all but
dead.
</P>
<P>
   After the 23-8 vote on her parental notification bill, Sen.
Florence Shapiro said she sees no chance of getting the 21 Senate
votes it would take to approve parental consent for abortions on
girls younger than 18.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro (R-Plano) said seven senators have told her they are for
notification but could not support consent.
</P>
<P>
   The parental notification bill faces a final Senate vote,
probably today, that would send it to the House, where supporters
and opponents are predicting passage.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate approved a similar measure in 1997, only to see it
die in the House in a closing-days procedural move that scuttled
scores of bills.
</P>
<P>
   The House has never voted on a parental notification bill.
Shapiro, who characterized the bill as a parental rights issue and
noted that 39 other states have some form of parental notification,
She said the House version of it has 82 co-authors, more than
enough to guarantee approval if it gets to the floor. ``This is a
parental rights bill,'' Shapiro said. ``As legislators, we owe this
not only to the children of this state, but we owe it even more to
the parents of this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Kae McLaughlin, executive director of the Texas Abortion and
Reproductive Rights Action League, agreed that the bill has the
votes to pass. ``But anything can happen, and we hope it does.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin said she also expected Wednesday's Senate outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``The closer it gets, I get more terrified for young Texas women
and for parents who think this bill somehow gives them safety when
in fact it jeopardizes their daughters' ability to seek legal and
safe abortion,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush and Lt. Gov. Rick Perry support both
measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a positive step to reduce the number of abortions in
Texas and involve parents in this major medical decision for their
minor daughters,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Perry pitched parental notification as a no-brainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texans on all sides of this emotional issue can agree that
parents have the right to be involved in the major medical
decisions of their children,'' said Perry, who serves as Senate
president.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. John Whitmire (D-Houston) said the Shapiro bill will
cause great harm to girls and young women who will seek illegal,
potentially dangerous abortions, rather than allow their parents to
know about the pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a thing 31 senators can do to prevent it,'' he
said. ``In fact, we're encouraging it through your legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro was unmoved by Whitmire's plea.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can do that today, and they are doing that today,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, 5,523 minors in Texas underwent abortions, according to
the Texas Department of Health. Thirty-nine percent of them did not
include a parent or legal guardian in their decisions, the agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio Sen. Jeff Wentworth, the only Republican who voted
against the bill, blasted it as nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some things in our society we are not capable of
passing laws here to solve,'' he said, agreeing with Whitmire's
prediction that the law will drive some young women to unsafe
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Wentworth and Whitmire in voting against the bill were
Democrats Gonzalo Barrientos of Austin, Rodney Ellis of Houston,
Mario Gallegos of Galena Park, Gregory Luna of San Antonio, Mike
Moncrief of Fort Worth and Eliot Shapleigh of El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, doctors must try to contact a parent or guardian
in person or by telephone. If the doctor is unsuccessful, he or she
must send a certified letter to the parent or guardian. No abortion
could be performed within 48 hours of the letter being sent. An
abortion can proceed after 48 hours even if the letter is not
delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the debate involved bypass procedures that would protect
minors who are victims of incest or sexual abuse, or who feel they
cannot let a parent know they are seeking an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Shapiro bill, a pregnant minor could ask a judge in a
state district, county or probate court to allow the abortion to
proceed without parental notification. The hearing would be held in
private and the minor could use an alias in official court records,
which would be sealed.
</P>
<P>
   The judge would have to decide whether the minor is mature
enough and sufficiently well informed to make a decision on
abortion. In states with similar laws, 99 percent of the cases that
go to judges result in approval for abortion, according to Shapiro.
</P>
<P>
   Wentworth argued that the bypass procedure is backwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the court finds the minor is not mature I she has to become
a mother under this law,'' he said. ``I don't think that is very
good public policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
