<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBAL-FRONTIER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRONTIER TO BE ACQUIRED BY GLOBAL CROSSING FOR $10.8 BILLION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Iowa, Wis.)   (rk) 
 By   SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moving to gain a foothold in the United States, Global
Crossing &UR;  &LR; Ltd. of Bermuda, a new international communications
carrier, said Wednesday that it had agreed to acquire Frontier
Corp. for $10.8 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Frontier, which from 1900 until 1995 was called Rochester
Telephone, serves almost 1 million local telephone customers in 13
states. Far more important from Global Crossing's point of view,
though, is that Frontier owns about one-third of an advanced fiber
optic communications network being built by Qwest Communications
International, the communications company controlled by Philip F.
Anschutz, the reclusive oil and railroad magnate.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Winnick, Global Crossing's founder and once an associate of
Michael R. Milken at Drexel Burnham Lambert, has raised more than
$4 billion for Global Crossing to build and operate undersea fiber
optic networks. But the company has lacked a significant presence
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Frontier's piece of the Qwest network may give Global Crossing a
lift in competing for corporate customers in the United States. It
could also help win business from American phone companies,
including the regional Bells, which may be looking for
long-distance partners to carry calls outside their regions.
</P>
<P>
   Just three weeks ago, Global Crossing hired as its chief
executive Robert Annunziata, who had briefly run AT&AMP;T Corp.'s
business services unit after selling his previous company, Teleport
Communications Group, to AT&AMP;T for more than $11 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merging with Frontier will enable us to greatly accelerate our
aggressive growth strategy,'' Annunziata said in a statement
Wednesday. Referring to Internet protocol, he added, ``We will now
have a strong U.S. infrastructure to complement the IP-based fiber
network we are building in Europe, Japan, Mexico and Central and
South America.''
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing has never said, however, that its strategic
plans include serving residential customers in places like
Monroeville, Ala., Mondovi, Wis., or Fort Dodge, Iowa, all small
towns served by Frontier's local phone operations. Global Crossing
said Wednesday that it was not planning to sell Frontier's local
units, but some analysts said it was unlikely Global Crossing would
retain them for long.
</P>
<P>
   It was those slow-growing local phone operations, in fact, that
helped make Frontier's stock a chronic underperformer for the
industry in the last few years, even after Joseph P. Clayton, a
former sales chief for Thomson Consumer Electronics, was hired as
chief executive in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, Frontier's shareholders would get
$62 worth of Global Crossing stock for each of their shares. That
is almost 40 percent more than Frontier's closing share price
Tuesday of $44.625.
</P>
<P>
   Frontier's shares closed at $50.50 Wednesday, up $5.875, on the
New York Stock Exchange. Global Crossing's shares lost $4.375, to
close at $47.125, in Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   Frontier's shareholders could receive more or less than $62 a
share if the price of Global Crossing's stock changes drastically
before the deal is completed.
</P>
<P>
   If Global Crossing's shares move higher than $56.78, for
example, owners of Frontier stock are to receive 1.0919 shares of
Global Crossing for each of their Frontier shares. If Global
Crossing's stock falls below $34.56, Frontier stock owners will get
1.7939 shares of Global Crossing.
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing also agreed to assume Frontier's debt of about
$1.3 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
