A4453 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-LEGIS-KIDHEALTH18     03-17 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-LEGIS-KIDHEALTH18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Caucuses come out against Texas child insurance program
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A coalition of House lawmakers has pledged to
oppose a Senate compromise and push for a health insurance program
that would cover all children whose families make as much as twice
the federal poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Mexican American Legislative Caucus, the Texas
Legislative Black Caucus and the Legislative Study Group, who
describe themselves as progressive lawmakers, said Wednesday that
they aren't satisfied with a Senate bill that would create a
Children's Health Insurance Program, or CHIP, that excludes older
children in families making more than 150 percent of the federal
poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   The three caucuses represent 74 of the 150 House members.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be wrong to arbitrarily exclude some children from
this program,'' said Rep. Kevin Bailey (D-Houston), who heads the
Legislative Study Group. ``Nothing we do this session will have a
greater impact on families and children in Texas than passing CHIP
for all children up to the 200 percent level.''
</P>
<P>
   CHIP would use federal and state money to insure children whose
families earn too much to qualify for Medicaid, the federal-state
health care program for the poor, but can't afford private health
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   About 1.4 million Texas children don't have health insurance,
and CHIP has nearly unanimous support. The question has been
whether it should cover children in households making as much as
200 percent of the federal poverty level or only those making 150
percent of that level. The federal poverty level for a family of
four is $16,450.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the Senate approved a bill that would cover
children up to age 10 whose families make as much as twice the
poverty level. But children between 11 and 18 would initially be
covered only if their families make 150 percent or less of the
poverty standard.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Senate bill, the Health and Human Services Commission
would take a look at the program's enrollment every six months to
determine whether the state can afford to ratchet up the income
levels for older kids.
</P>
<P>
   The House leaders at Wednesday's news conference say that's not
good enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must take this opportunity to provide health coverage for
all of our children,'' said Rep. Yvonne Davis (D-Dallas),who is
head of the Black Caucus. ``Anything less than 200 percent coverage
just means we aren't making the kind of commitment we ought to.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of lower income limits have argued that it would be
fiscally irresponsible to set a 200 percent limit for children of
all ages because future federal CHIP contributions are uncertain,
and nobody knows how many people will enroll in the program.
Supporters of the 200 percent standard have said that advocates of
lower levels overestimate the number of people who would
participate.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 471,000 Texas children would be eligible for CHIP
under the 200 percent threshold. About 220,000 are in families
making between 150 percent and 200 percent of the poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush, who will send the state's CHIP plan to
Washington for federal approval, has suggested that he will abide
by the will of the Legislature on the question of income limits.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
