<HEADER>
A4454 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CLINTON-GIULIANI-P     03-17 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CLINTON-GIULIANI-POLL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF IT'S CLINTON VS. GIULIANI FOR SENATE, EXPECT A TIGHT RACE, POLL
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With poll methods box) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(wg) 
 By JAMES DAO   with MARJORIE CONNELLY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Hillary Rodham Clinton and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
test the waters for Senate campaigns next year, a New York
Times/CBS News poll shows that New York state voters hold strongly
partisan opinions, but also nagging reservations, about both
politicians, indicating that a contest between them would be highly
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   The survey shows Mrs. Clinton leading Giuliani in several
categories at this early juncture. A larger number of voters view
her favorably, saying they think she is more caring and would
likely be more effective than the mayor, a Republican. When asked
which candidate they would vote for if the election were held
today, 48 percent said Mrs. Clinton and 39 percent said Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Still 20 months away from the election, most voters' opinions
about the race are fluid, and are likely to have been influenced by
factors that may have no bearing on the final outcome, from the
name recognition of the potential candidates to recent events like
the shooting of Amadou Diallo by the New York City police and the
impeachment trial of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also suggested in several ways that Giuliani might not
be quite as vulnerable as the figures indicate, and that Mrs.
Clinton might not be quite as strong.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the survey showed that a significant number of
voters, 4 out of 10, think that the first lady would not be an
effective representative for New York in the Senate because she has
never lived in the state. Republicans have already said that they
would make Mrs. Clinton's residency a campaign issue, and the poll
indicates that a vigorous effort to portray the first lady as a
carpetbagger could work with some voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't seem right that just because she's the president's
wife that she can suddenly decide that she can run for Senate from
this state,'' Sherry Groff, 24, a Democrat from the town of
Copenhagen, north of Syracuse, said in a follow-up interview.
``It's as if she's got her pick of all 50 and decided New York will
be the one.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll also showed that 6 out of 10 voters north of the New
York City suburbs were unable to give an opinion of Giuliani, more
than double the number for Mrs. Clinton. The upstate region has
historically been a Republican stronghold, and Giuliani would be
widely expected to win a higher percentage of that bloc of voters.
</P>
<P>
   But the poll also underscored a potential vulnerability for
Giuliani: voters were evenly split over whether he had the right
disposition to be a senator. Democrats have said they believe
voters will reject Giuliani out of concerns that his iron-fisted
style, while perhaps appropriate for a big city executive, will
alienate colleagues in the collegial halls of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's too autocratic,'' said Ellen Smith, 38, a social worker
from Westchester County who is not registered in either major
party. ``When you're mayor of New York City and you want to make
sure people cross the street at the right time, that's one thing.
But when you're a senator dealing with a whole state and lots of
issues, you have to be more flexible.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll comes at a low point in the mayor's job-approval
rating, which has been hurt in the city by concerns about police
brutality and race relations. Conversely, Mrs. Clinton is basking
in high ratings that stem in part from voter sympathy for her stoic
handling of the Monica Lewinsky affair and the president's
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton has also probably benefited from her husband's 75
percent job-approval rating in the state, which is down just
slightly from his all-time high of 78 percent last October. And
because she has never run for office before, Mrs. Clinton has yet
to endure the level of campaign stress and scrutiny from the news
media that can cause a candidate's approval ratings to drop.
</P>
<P>
   The Times/CBS News poll was conducted by telephone March 8
through Sunday and surveyed 1,469 registered voters across the
state. The margin of sampling error is plus or minus three
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Though Mrs. Clinton's aides say she is far from a decision on
whether to run, she has been studying the race with extraordinary
care, having met with or telephoned scores of state Democratic
leaders and county chairmen.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nita Lowey, D-Westchester County, has said she would
probably enter the race if Mrs. Clinton decided not to run. Rep.
Rick Lazio, R-Suffolk County, has said he may run whether or not
Giuliani becomes a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Other recent public opinion polls have produced a wide range of
results for a Clinton-Giuliani contest, indicating that voters have
not thought much yet about the race or its potential candidates. On
one end of the scale, a poll by Zogby International released this
week showed Giuliani leading by 11 points; at the other end, a
Quinnipiac College poll conducted last month had Mrs. Clinton ahead
by 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Times/CBS News poll, 52 percent of all state
voters had a favorable opinion of Mrs. Clinton, while 22 percent
had an unfavorable opinion and 26 percent were undecided or did not
know enough about her to offer a viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers were more evenly divided in their views of Giuliani:
34 percent had a favorable opinion of the mayor _ down from 43
percent last October _ 28 percent had an unfavorable opinion, and
38 percent were undecided or did not know enough about him to
formulate an opinion.
</P>
<P>
   In follow-up interviews, people with favorable opinions of Mrs.
Clinton often praised the way she coped with her husband's ordeals
last year, while those with favorable opinions of Giuliani almost
invariably credited him with reducing crime in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``What she's endured with her husband, the philanderer, has
endeared her to a lot of people,'' said Thomas Phelan, 50, a
Suffolk County Republican who likes Mrs. Clinton. ``She has
toughness.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll showed Mrs. Clinton drawing the vast majority of her
support from core Democratic groups: black and Hispanic voters,
liberals and New York City voters. Giuliani is strongest in the
suburbs and among white Catholic voters, according to the poll.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the two was starkest among voters who are
members of minorities: 89 percent of black New Yorkers and 78
percent of Hispanic voters said they would support Mrs. Clinton
over Giuliani. White Catholics favored the mayor by 52 percent to
37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, where Democratic statewide candidates have
historically needed about 70 percent of the vote to win, voters
favored Mrs. Clinton by 66 percent to 25 percent. In the suburbs,
49 percent of all voters said they would vote for Giuliani, against
38 percent for Mrs. Clinton. The two almost evenly split the
upstate region.
</P>
<P>
   The poll showed that Mrs. Clinton has stronger support among
women, with 50 percent saying they would vote for the first lady,
compared with 36 percent for the mayor. Men were almost evenly
split between the two: 46 percent favored Mrs. Clinton to 43
percent for the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The poll suggested that a Giuliani-Clinton race would be a
fiercely partisan affair. Roughly 7 in 10 Democrats said they would
support Mrs. Clinton, and 2 in 10 would favor Giuliani. Republicans
divided in almost identical ratios in supporting Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   In a clear indication of how close the race might be,
independent voters _ often a barometer of which candidate is ahead
_ were evenly split between the two politicians, with 41 percent
saying they would vote for each.
</P>
<P>
   Slightly more people said they thought Mrs. Clinton would be an
effective senator, with 61 percent saying she would be good at
getting things done for the state, and 54 percent saying the same
of Giuliani. Half of all voters said Mrs. Clinton had the right
experience to be a senator, while 56 percent said they thought
Giuliani did.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Mrs. Clinton cares about the needs and problems of
``people like yourself,'' 63 percent answered yes; 42 percent
answered yes for the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   POLL METHODS BOX
</P>
<P>
   Although the election is 20 months away, and neither candidate
has formally declared an intention to run for U.S. Senate, several
polling organizations have asked voters in New York state about
their preference if Hillary Rodham Clinton and Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani were paired in the contest. Their results have varied.
</P>
<P>
   The latest New York Times/CBS News Poll showed Mrs. Clinton
leading by 9 percentage points over Giuliani. But in the poll
conducted by Zogby International with 708 likely voters during the
same period, Giuliani was ahead by 11 points. Earlier this month,
the Marist College Poll of 702 registered voters showed Mrs.
Clinton ahead by 5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Two polls conducted last month also showed Mrs. Clinton leading
Giuliani. In the Quinnipiac College Poll of 1,270 registered
voters, Mrs. Clinton was ahead by 18 points. A poll of 819 adults
conducted for Time and CNN by Yankelovich Partners showed Mrs.
Clinton leading by 9 points.
</P>
<P>
   There can be a variety of reasons for differences in polls,
including how the questions are worded, the order in which the
questions are asked, the timing of the poll, how the sample of
respondents is drawn and how the responses are adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   The Times/CBS News poll was based on registered voters who voted
in the 1996 Presidential election or in the election for U.S.
Senate last year, adjusted to reflect the 1996 voter turnout in New
York City, the suburban counties around the city and the rest of
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Other organizations base their results on different types of
respondents. Zogby International's likely voters, for example, are
registered voters who voted last year, have some party
identification and said they were likely to vote in November 2000.
The percentages are also adjusted to reflect usual turnout in New
York City, and turnout by race and by religion based on previous
voting patterns.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the results from the Time/CNN poll are based
on all adults, whether or not they said they were registered to
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Marist Poll and the Quinnipiac Poll are based on
registered voters with adjustments to take into account the
traditionally lower voter turnout in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The margin of sampling error of these polls was three or four
percentage points in either direction.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
