<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ENVOY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. DIPLOMAT IN KOSOVO TALKS COMES UNDER FIRE IN CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO, KOSOVO-TALKS) 
(wg) 
 By RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A senior State Department officer, now the head of
the American delegation to the Kosovo peace talks, may have lied
when he testified before Congress three years ago about death
squads in Haiti, according to an investigation by the State
Department's inspector general.
</P>
<P>
   Depite the conclusions of the inspector general's office, in a
report in February of 1998, the diplomat, James Dobbins, remained
in high-level government positions and has been promoted.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general, Jacquelyn Williams-Bridgers, concluded
that Dobbins ``acted with reckless disregard'' for the consequences
when he testified before the House International Relations
Committee on two occasions. The testimony was ``incomplete,
misleading and possibly perjurious,'' the report said, adding that
Dobbins presented testimony his colleagues warned him was slanted,
and failed to exercise the integrity expected of a senior Executive
Branch officer.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbins testified about an investigation into the death of a
politically prominent Haitian. He said that the only word he had
received about the inquiry by the FBI was that it was continuing.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general had evidence, in fact, that the bureau had
briefed Dobbins on its work, which had ended in frustration and a
lack of cooperation from the government of President Jean-Bertrand
Aristide, which the United States supported.
</P>
<P>
   The internal investigation, which was never made public, has
come back to haunt Dobbins, a 56-year old career diplomat who has
won numerous awards and honors. Last month, he was named the
secretary of state's special envoy to the Balkans, replacing Robert
Gelbard. At the time of his testimony, he was the senior State
Department coordinator of Haitian policy.
</P>
<P>
   The existence of the inspector general's 700-page report on
Dobbins was disclosed provided by two Clinton administration
officials who are opposed to the appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbins, who challenged the inspector general's report, declined
on Wednesday to discuss it publicly. He referred questions to the
State Department.
</P>
<P>
   James Foley, deputy State Department spokesman, said Wednesday,
``The allegations were thoroughly investigated, and it was
determined that Ambassador Dobbins testified in good faith and did
not intentionally mislead Congress.'' He said Dobbins ``retains the
full confidence'' of Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Foley declined to say what if any disciplinary action had been
taken against Dobbins.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony Dobbins was defending Washington's Haiti
policy, which was under attack at the time by Republicans who are
also using Dobbins to strike out at the Clinton administration's
policy on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   One recent blow to the Kosovo policy came from chairman of the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee, Jesse Helms, has wrote to
Albright expressing concerns about the appointment of Dobbins.
</P>
<P>
   Helms urged Albright to ``renew your search for the very best
candidate for the position of special adviser on Kosovo _
preferably one who has not been accused by the State Department's
inspector general of lying to Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is the decision of the department not to discipline
Dobbins for lying to Congress, at the very least his alleged
conduct does not merit a promotion,'' Helms concluded his letter of
Feb. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Helms' office said he had received no response to the letter.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After completing her investigation, the inspector general
referred the matter to the Justice Department's Office of Public
Integrity for possible prosecution. The Department declined to
prosecute and sent the matter back to the State Department for
``appropriate disciplinary action.''
</P>
<P>
   Dobbins' problems arose out of an investigation into the murder,
in 1995, of Mireille Durocher Bertin, a prominent right-wing critic
of President Aristide.
</P>
<P>
   Following 30 years of brutal dictatorship in Haiti, Aristide, a
populist Roman Catholic priest with leftist politics, had been
elected president in 1990, only to be overthrown by a military coup
several months later.
</P>
<P>
   Violence accelerated and in September 1994, President Clinton,
over strong Republican opposition in Congress, sent in troops to
Haiti to establish order and restore Aristide to the presidency.
Shootings and violence continued, with charges that they were now
the work of Aristide's government.
</P>
<P>
   When Mrs. Durocher Bertin was killed, President Clinton
dispatched an FBI team to help investigate.
</P>
<P>
   After eight months, the FBI left, frustrated with a lack of
cooperation from the Aristide government.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not what Dobbins, who was the Clinton
administration's coordinator of Haiti policy, told Congress,
according to a transcript of the hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are still conducting their investigation, and as far as I
know have not come to a conclusion,'' Dobbins testified.
</P>
<P>
   In a State Department memorandum, declassified for the hearings,
the author, not identified, wrote that ``the more compelling theory
developed by the FBI'' pointed to the involvement of Haitian
officials and police officers. This was contrary to speculation
that the killing was drug-related or the work of right-wing
extremists. The killing remains unsolved.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbins also said that the FBI had not briefed him or anyone
else in the administration about its work, and so he could not
provide any information to the committee.
</P>
<P>
   But the FBI provided the committee with communications from the
agency to the Department of State during the investigation. ``The
contacts listed above clearly illustrate that the DOS was kept
apprised of the investigation based on the regular meetings between
DOS personnel and FBI agents in Haiti, and the requests by the FBI
for DOS assistance,'' the FBI said in a 16-page secret report.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general's office began its investigation in
mid-1996 after a request from the Republican chairman of the House
International Relations Committee, Benjamin Gilman, and the
chairman of the subcommittee on the Western Hemisphere, Dan Burton.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators interviewed officials at the State Department,
National Security Council, Department of Justice, Central
Intelligence Agency and FBI, and also looked at cable traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ambassador Dobbins acted with reckless disregard for the
clearly foreseeable adverse consequences of his actions,'' the
report's summary said, ``both in his lack of candor with''
Congress, ``and in his failure to heed the warnings of colleagues
that his intended presentation to the Congress was slanted and
one-sided.''
</P>
<P>
   Such conduct, the inspector general found, ``was in
contravention of his responsibilities as a senior Executive Branch
officer to act with integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   After the commencement of the inspector general's investigation,
Dobbins was made a special assistant to president and senior
director of Latin American at the National Security Council, a
position that did not require Senate confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbins' promotion to the post as special envoy to the Balkans
also does not require confirmation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
