<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4467 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NHAMP-TAXES-BOS &LR;      03-17 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NHAMP-TAXES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSION GROWS AS SCHOOL TAX DEALINE NEARS IN NEW HAMPSHIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ As New Hampshire's legislature searched for a
way out of an education funding crisis that has consumed the state,
one group that included conservative legislators took to handing
out bright yellow cards with a Latin inscription: Ite Ut Harebnam
Pulsetis.
</P>
<P>
   Their translation: Go pound sand.
</P>
<P>
   The message, intended for the high court which imposed an April
1 deadline on lawmakers, captured well an increasing sense of
desperation here. With two weeks to go, the badly fractured New
Hampshire Senate held hearings Wednesday on a range of conflicting
proposals to solve the education funding crisis. But, with no vote
scheduled in the Senate until next week, and no clear consensus
emerging, key players from Gov. Jeanne Shaheen on down are saying
there is little hope of meeting the court's deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there was any chance that the legislature would come to
agreement by April 1, House Minority Leader Peter Burling said
flatly, ``None.''
</P>
<P>
   Missing the deadline by a few days would not spell disaster. But
if the deadlock drags on, officials will be forced to issue pink
slips to everyone who works in the schools, notifying them that
their jobs end with this school year. School cannot begin until a
tax is agreed on that passes constitutional muster.
</P>
<P>
   Political action is now focused in the Senate. The House this
month narrowly passed a measure that included what would be the
state's first income tax. Shaheen, who vowed before elected to
reject any broad-based tax increase, warned legislators not to send
her any proposal that includes an income tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``Veto, veto, veto,'' said Judy Reardon, the governor's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, which Democrats control for the first time in 86
years, would pass an income tax as well, were it not for the veto
threat. Observers agree that the legislature would not have the
votes to overcome a veto.
</P>
<P>
   For now, it seems, virtually everything is on the table: the $1
increase in the liquor tax; a 4 percent sales tax proposal from one
senator; plans to permit video slot machines at the state's four
racetracks and four White Mountain hotels; an income tax, a sales
tax, a tax on rental cars and a slew of plans to increase the
state's business taxes. One plan suggested taxing movie tickets.
</P>
<P>
   All the serious plans include some form of statewide property
tax.
</P>
<P>
   One plan that seemed to be gaining ground this week is a
European-style 1 percent consumption tax on all sales and services
sponsored by Rep. Andy Peterson, son of former Gov. Walter
Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my 29th year and I haven't seen it quite so chaotic,''
said Clesson ``Junie'' Blaisdell, an income tax proponent and
president of the bealeagured Senate. Part of the blame, she
insisted, lay with the Shaheen's refusal to consider an income tax.
``The governor's position has changed over the past few months and
now her pledge to veto any broad base tax applies only to an income
tax.''
</P>
<P>
   Blaisdell, a basketball referee for 30 years, keeps Bruins
greast Bobby Orr's number 4 jersey on the wall above his desk along
with photographs signed by Orr and Bruin Derek Sanderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just about ready to bring out my whistle and put it on and
start calling some offensive fouls,'' he said of the agonizing end
game that will change the state's tax structure.
</P>
<P>
   The confusion is in part a reflection of the public's
ambivalence. Voters themselves have only recently begun paying
close attention to a debate that could change their tax bills and
New Hampshire's image of its parsimonious self. A poll commissioned
by two newspapers found that 57 percent opposed an income tax, but
60 percent supported the idea of a tax system based on ability to
pay.
</P>
<P>
   Respect for New Hampshire's traditional pledge never to enact a
broad-based sales or income tax has all but vanished. The numbing
process has resulted in a ``lessening of resistance'' to a myriad
of tax options that might never have been considered in the past,
said Democratic Sen. Rick Trombley, pointing to the the tiny room
where tax plans were being aired.
</P>
<P>
   Trombley's own plan to answer the challenge first posed by the
city of Claremont and other property-poor communities that sued the
state would include raising taxes on liquor and imposing a business
tax, though not as high as the one suggested by Shaheen.
</P>
<P>
   ``One lobbyist will get something put in that they want, and
another one will take somebody else aside and get it taken and and
something else substituted for it.'' Trombley pointed to a 14-foot
mural on the State House wall depicting Gen. Pickett's charge into
cannon fire on July 3, 1863 and said, ``That's Claremont.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 2037EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
