<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4473 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SCANDAL-NYT &LR;      03-17 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SCANDAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC EXPELS 6 MEMBERS OVER SALT LAKE CITY SCANDAL
</HEADLINE>
  (See also OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN) 
 (sw) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ Under tremendous pressure to reform, the
International Olympic Committee formally expelled six members on
Wednesday for corruption related to the Salt Lake City bribery
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Antonio Samaranch, the president of the IOC, also received
a resounding vote of confidence on Wednesday from the 90 attending
members to carry out change, but speculation continued among
Olympic officials that he would not remain in office until his term
is completed in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The expulsions, which had been proposed in January, were the
first relating to corruption in the history of the IOC. Their
ratification was portrayed by IOC officials as a sign that they are
serious about cleaning up the environment of improper cash
payments, medical treatment, lavish gifts and extravagant favors
that has debased the process by which cities bid on the Winter and
Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   Had the six members not been expelled, IOC officials believed
they would not have had the credibility to begin enacting such
reforms as democratic elections, term limits, open financial
records and open meetings.
</P>
<P>
   However, the IOC is still facing an investigation by the U.S.
Justice Department, threats to curb its power by the U.S. Congress,
and demands for accountability from corporate sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expelling members does nothing to address the utter lack of
transparency and accountability in IOC processes,'' said Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., who is considering stripping the IOC of its
tax-exempt status in the United States and limiting its access to
American television money. ``What we must see are concrete reforms.
These reforms must eliminate completely and forever a culture,
based on gifts and lavish travel, that has brought a dark cloud
over the integrity of the entire Olympic movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior IOC officials stressed that Wednesday's expulsions were
only the first steps on a long road to reform. On Thursday, the IOC
is expected to form an ethics commission and a reform commission
and to make an experimental change in the way cities are chosen to
play host to the Games. It expects to have all reforms in place by
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a fair amount of work ahead to recover,
regroup and move along,'' said Richard W. Pound of Canada, who
headed the IOC's investigation of the Salt Lake City scandal. ``I
think this is a good start. Had we not done it, it would have been
difficult to move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   By secret ballot, the members who were formally expelled were
Agustin Arroyo of Ecuador, Zein El Abdin Ahmed Gadir of Sudan,
Jean-Claude Ganga of Congo Republic, Lamine Keita of Mali, Sergio
Santander Fantini of Chile and Paul Wallwork of Samoa.
</P>
<P>
   The six accused members were given 20 minutes each to defend
themselves, but, except in the case of Wallwork, all were ousted by
substantially more than the required two-thirds vote among the 90
members. IOC members described the meeting, which was closed to the
news media, as somber, tense and occasionally emotional.
</P>
<P>
   Ganga, who was accused of taking more than $250,000 in improper
inducements from Salt Lake City, was removed by a vote of 88 to 2.
He said the ouster was an unjustified effort to exclude African
members but accepted the decision with sporting good will.
</P>
<P>
   Arroyo, who was accused of violating travel guidelines and whose
family members received $19,000 in financial support from the Salt
Lake City bid committee, said the investigation was too hasty, and
that ``the press wanted heads knocked out and mine happened to be
in the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Santander, who was accused of receiving cash payments of $20,050
from the bid committee, said that the expulsions ousted only
members from relatively powerless countries. Of the 10 members who
have resigned or been expelled in the Salt Lake City scandal, all
but one are from developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a political decision,'' Santander said. ``The little
countries are being made to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Pound denied that more powerful members who were implicated in
the scandal had been given preferential treatment.
</P>
<P>
   One case remaining open is that of Kim Un-yong, a member of the
executive board from South Korea, who has been given a severe
warning for allegedly arranging jobs for his daughter and son
through the Salt Lake City bid committee. He has denied the
accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently upset that he has not yet been cleared, Kim had a
confrontation on Tuesday with Pound and with Francois Carrard, the
executive director of the IOC, during a break of a meeting of the
executive board.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses to the incident, first reported by The Associated
Press, said that angry words were exchanged and that Kim struck a
martial arts stance, which led Carrard to leave the room. Kim is
president of the world tae kwon do federation.
</P>
<P>
   Kim then approached Pound, who, along with Samaranch, forcefully
urged him to calm down, a witness said. An associate of Kim's said
on Wednesday that Kim had been most angry with Pound and had been
concerned that Pound was making a threatening move toward him.
</P>
<P>
   An IOC official said that Kim had sent letters of apology to
Carrard and Pound. Both men joked about the incident on Wednesday,
even though sponsors are certain not to look kindly on the fact
that three of the IOC's senior leaders nearly came to blows at a
time when the Olympic movement is seeking to end divisiveness and
to restore its gravely damaged reputation.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech before Wednesday's expulsions were carried out,
Samaranch said he accepted responsibility for the development of a
crisis that is greater in magnitude than any the IOC has faced.
</P>
<P>
   He proposed the formation on Thursday of a reform commission,
called IOC 2000, that would be composed of 20 to 24 members, half
from the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first step we must take is to clean our house,'' Samaranch
said.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch asked for a vote of confidence from the 90 members,
and in a secret ballot, he received 86 votes in his favor and 2
against, with 2 abstentions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a clear statement to the outside world that the
president has the total confidence and trust of the membership to
get this issue fixed,'' said Michael Payne, the IOC's marketing
director.
</P>
<P>
   However, IOC officials continued to speculate that Samaranch
would step down once reforms were put in place and he could claim a
legacy of cleaning up a mess that began on his watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to be able to say he created the framework to move
forward into the next millennium,'' one official said on the
condition of anonymity.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
