<HEADLINE>
THE PARABLE OF `PLEASANTVILLE`
</HEADLINE>
 (For use  Friday, March 19  by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Like a weird dream, ``Pleasantville'' is black and
white and in color.
</P>
<P>
   It's the story of a couple of teens, David (Tobey Maguire) and
his libidinous sister Jennifer (Reese Witherspoon), who are
transported ``Twilight Zone''-fashion into David's favorite 1950s
sitcom with the help of a strange TV repairman (Don Knotts).
</P>
<P>
   The simplicity of the show that David has escaped into for
countless hours suddenly becomes a trap. The two have become Bud
and Mary Sue. Their parents are a ``Father Knows Best'' types
George (William H. Macy) and Betty (Joan Allen). They live in the
small town of Pleasantville, where no one has been beyond its
borders and _ more bizarre _ everything is in black and white.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're supposed to be at home, David,'' Jennifer, now dressed
in a poodle skirt and sweater, whines to her brother. ``We're
supposed to be in color.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, which hits video stores Tuesday, is an engaging
parable. This Pleasantville, an idealized town of '50s sitcoms or
Jimmy Stewart movies, is a place of no double beds, toilets or
people of color. The townspeople never feel real joy or anger or
lust. At first, David acts like he's in ``Star Trek'' and insists
that he and his sister follow the prime directive of no
interference. Because he knows all the episodes, it's easy for
David to fit in. But Jennifer has her own hormones to follow, and
soon she introduces a bit of naughtiness into the town. The result
is that the people of Pleasantville literally start blushing
colors, and in certain cases it's like a scarlet letter. (There's
an amusing moment when Jennifer tells her sitcom mom the facts of
life.)
</P>
<P>
   But as certain townsfolk begin to revel in their new-found
freedoms and emotions, others become fearful. A conflict develops
between those of color and those (white males) who want to keep
things in black and white. It's easy to substitute color for
``coloreds,'' especially during the climactic courtroom scene. But
the analogy goes beyond race to include all who unshackle their
mind and rebel _ from rock 'n' rollers to women's libbers to street
artists.
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Gary Ross (who wrote ``Big,'' the 1988
movie in which Tom Hanks was a kid trapped in a grown-up's body),
``Pleasantville'' is a bit too pat for its own good at times and
it's hardly profound, but it has a sincere quality that gives us
reason to rethink our own world, especially in light of the
nostalgia crazes that constantly sweep through the culture.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, Ross keeps ``Pleasantville amusing as its inhabitants
discover a new world _ whether when David misses a shot in
basketball practice, which shocks the entire team (``Stand back,
boys!'' warns the coach as the ball rolls away. ``Don't touch
it!''), or when Betty finds out about pleasuring herself while
taking a bath and a tree goes up in flames in full color outside
her window. It also boasts winning performances, particularly from
malt shop owner Mr. Johnson (Jeff Daniels) and Allen, who many
thought would get an Oscar nomination. It also marks the last
performance for the late J.T. Walsh, who was one of those terrific
actors who left an impression even if you didn't know his name.
</P>
<P>
   And music adds tremendously to the film, whether it's Randy
Newman's rich score, which makes you almost yearn for that
imaginary small town, or the sultry jazz beat of Dave Brubeck's
``Take Five'' to the rock of Buddy Holly. It's worth seeing the
film just for that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MIGHTY JOE YOUNG: Charlize Theron never gets to say, ``Take your
hands off me, you big ape'' to either of her ``Mighty Joe Young''
co-stars _ Bill Paxton or the giant gorilla of the title. But she
does get to run around a couple of jungles _ one in Africa, the
other the asphalt one of L.A. _ and cuddle up to both of them in
this rousing adventure tale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mighty Joe'' is the kind of family fare that Disney excels at
_ not too violent for kids but with enough action for adults. The
animatronics and computer-generated images are convincing and even
spectacular at times, and the story of a young woman raised in
Africa trying to save her extra-large but sweet and well-meaning
gorilla is told amusingly and with feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mighty Joe'' is a film you can enjoy even if you don't have
children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
