u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-630&AMP;A     03-17 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY WIDE MARGIN, SENATE APPROVES MISSILE DEFENSE SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Ill., Vt., Minn., Del., Mass., Iowa, Miss.)  (See also MISSILE-CLINTON) 
(mk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Embracing a new national policy, the Senate on
Wednesday overwhelmingly approved legislation to field a system to
defend the country against limited long-range missile attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, 97-3, marks a watershed of bipartisan support for a
bill that declares that the United States build _ ``as soon as
technologically possible'' _ a network of radars and interceptors
to shoot down missiles fired by rogue nations like North Korea or
Iran, or accidental launches from Russia or China.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's action does not authorize the construction of an
anti-missile system or appropriate money for it. But it puts more
pressure on the Clinton administration, which has planned to make a
decision in June 2000 about whether it should build such a system.
</P>
<P>
   If such a system is approved, the Pentagon says it would be
ready by 2005, two years later than earlier estimates. The Defense
Department has budgeted $10.5 billion over the next six years for a
system that, in theory, could knock down a handful of ballistic
missiles. It would not protect the country against an all-out
attack, which the original and much grander ``Star Wars'' plan by
President Reagan had envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   The lopsided vote came after the Senate on Tuesday had adopted
two compromise amendments that prompted the White House to abandon
a threatened veto by Clinton. One amendment assures that Democrats
will have a say on any system's cost, by requiring its funding to
go through the regular congressional appropriations process. The
other amendment states that any system be consistent with policies
to reduce Russia's nuclear stockpile.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow has long opposed an American anti-missile system, fearing
it would tilt the strategic balance of power, and arms-control
advocates here have voiced concern that such a system could disrupt
arms control negotiations with Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The vexing issue is likely to come up when the Russian prime
minister, Yevgeny Primakov, visits Washington next week. The
Senate's action could also influence a tentative step the Russian
Parliament took on Tuesday to approve the long-delayed, second
strategic arms reduction treaty, or START 2.
</P>
<P>
   The White House on Wednesday sought to put the best face on what
administration aides said privately was still a troubling bill.
Senate Democrats told Clinton's aides this week that they could not
guarantee at least 34 senators would vote to sustain a presidential
veto. So the White House sought a graceful way out rather than risk
an embarrassing political defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate took a very constructive step in adopting an
approach which is consistent with the one the administration has
advocated,'' said James Steinberg, the deputy national security
adviser.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans sarcastically cheered what they said was the
administration's eleventh-hour conversion to a bill that most
Senate Democrats and the White House have long opposed. Republicans
dismissed the two amendments as too obvious or too general to be
objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a battle which should have been recognized by the
administration months ago as one not to be waged,'' said Sen. John
Warner, R-Va., who heads the Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., said, ``On the surface, this appears
to be one of the president's more propitious policy reversals.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats had until this year effectively bottled up the
same bill before it could reach the Senate floor. The White House
had threatened a veto, fearing the measure's impact on relations
with Russia.
</P>
<P>
   But the White House found itself in a losing battle after North
Korea and Iran both tested missiles last year, and recent
disclosures revealed that China might have stolen nuclear secrets
that enhanced Beijing's small nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Only three Democratic senators _ Richard Durbin of Illinois,
Patrick Leahy of Vermont and Paul Wellstone of Minnesota _ voted
against the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Many other Democrats who initially opposed the bill supported it
after the two amendments passed, both by 99-0. But many were
holding their noses as they voted, careful not to hand Republicans
a potent political issue.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Biden Jr., D-Del., the ranking Democrat on the
Foreign Relations Committee, who on Tuesday called the bill
``nothing more than an exercise in political theater,'' said
Wednesday that the two amendments ``removed the most dangerous
implications of the original bill.''
</P>
<P>
   He added dismissively that the measure ``fails to address in a
serious manner the national security challenges facing the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other Democrats, Sen. John Kerry of Massachusetts and Sen.
Tom Harkin of Iowa, said a national missile defense would not stop
many other threats, from cruise missiles to terrorist car-bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Harkin, invoking France's vaunted but ineffective Maginot Line
against the German army in World War II, said: ``Are we going to
spend tens of billions of dollars to defend against a single
threat? The enemy will simply go around. We seem to want one simple
silver bullet.''
</P>
<P>
   But the bill's chief Republican sponsor, Sen. Thad Cochran of
Mississippi, called the Democrats' complaints exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill is intended to establish a broad policy,'' Cochran
said. ``It does not intend to micromanage the Defense Department's
conduct of the program.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
