u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RENO-COUNSEL-LAW-NYT &LR;      03-17 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-COUNSEL-LAW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDEPENDENT COUNSEL LAW IS TOO FLAWED TO RENEW, RENO TELLS SENATE
PANEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno said at a Senate
hearing on Wednesday that she was prepared to abandon the
independent counsel statute because it had failed to remove
politics from cases involving top administration officials, was
fatally flawed by procedural ambiguities and seriously distorted
critical prosecution decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``My change of heart about this statute has not come lightly,''
Reno told the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee. ``To those who
question me about this or who tell me that they told me so, I can
only say this: I've now seen how the statute operates close up,
probably more close up than anybody in this country. And I know
more than I did before.''
</P>
<P>
   But several senators from both political parties seemed
unprepared to accept Reno's recommendation that the law be allowed
to expire in June. Lawmakers said the efforts to amend the statute
would be worthwhile if the changes could achieve the law's original
purpose to assure independent investigations of high-level
administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   Sen/ Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., who is chairman of the committee,
expressed skepticism about Reno's views and her conversion from
supporter to critic of the statute. She announced her opposition
publicly only after she had repeatedly refused to accede to
Republican demands to seek an independent counsel to investigate
how the Democrats had financed the 1996 presidential election, a
subject that Thompson's committee investigated in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that you disagree with me on some of my decisions
and that you agree with me on others,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which ones do you think I agree with you on?'' Thompson asked,
suggesting that he might not agree with her on anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea,'' she said, ``but I am sure you would be
raising all of them if you disagreed with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Several senators pressed Reno to discuss the specific cases, but
she refused to answer any questions about the conduct of the
Whitewater prosecutor, Kenneth Starr, or any other independent
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, she seemed to refer to Starr, along with other
independent counsels, when she said that some of them had ``unduly
expansive'' views of their jurisdictions and had gone ``down every
investigative side street'' in pursuit of their subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said the law also distorted prosecutorial decision making
because independent counsels investigating a single official had
unlimited time and money, unlike career prosecutors who must
constantly juggle competing priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``An independent counsel typically is charged with investigating
one person, and so all his or her energy, ingenuity and resources
are pointed in one direction,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``An independent counsel,'' she added, ``will not be judged on
the basis of a broad track record, but on one case alone. If the
counsel uncovers nothing, or fails to secure an indictment or
conviction, some may conclude that he or she has wasted both time
and money.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno said the procedural mechanisms that triggered the law were
unworkable. As an example, she pointed to the statute's requirement
that the attorney general must refer a case to an independent
prosecutor if she concludes that reasonable grounds exist to
believe that further investigation is warranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us think that some further investigation can almost
always be warranted,'' Reno said, ``and there is usually a doubt or
two that you'd like to resolve, especially if there are no
constraints on time and money. But should an investigation proceed
even where there is no reasonable prospect of making a prosecutable
case? The statute does not provide a clear answer to that question.
And any effort to read reason into the standard in particular cases
often generates much criticism and controversy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
