<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, MARCH 18
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-RENO-COUNSEL-LAW-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Mar. 16)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Mar. 16,
about Attorney General Janet Reno's changed view of the independent
counsel law misspelled the surname of the Interior Secretary in
some copies. He is Bruce Babbitt, not Babbit. The article also
misstated the background of Labor Secretary Alexis Herman. She was
formerly head of the White House Public Liaison Office, not Energy
Secretary.
</P>
<P>
   BC-DEL-MURDER-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Mar. 16)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Mar. 16,
about Thomas J. Capano, a wealthy Delaware lawyer who was sentenced
to death for the murder of a former mistress, misstated his
lawyers' plan for an appeal. They said they would appeal his charge
of first-degree murder, not his death sentence. Appeal of a death
sentence is automatic in Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MARINE-NAVIGATOR-NYT (moved on Monday, Mar. 15)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Mar. 15,
about two Marine aviators charged with obstruction of justice
included an erroneous report from the Marine Corps about the
potential penalties for the officers' handling of a videotape made
from the cockpit of their plane, which sliced a gondola cable in
the Italian Alps last year.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, the officers face a maximum of five years'
confinement for obstruction of justice and an additional five years
for conspiracy to obstruct justice.
</P>
</TEXT>
