<SLUG> BC-BIGFORD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD EXCURSION HEADS INTO SUBURBAN COUNTRY, LOOKING FOR A SALES
FIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) By BARBARA POWELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Ford Motor Co. has waltzed into the heart of
Chevrolet/GMC Suburban country to strut its own giant sport utility
vehicle, the bigger, longer Ford Excursion.
</P>
<P>
   Texas consumers _ who bought 23 percent of the 151,356 Suburbans
sold last year _ are the first to climb up into the nearly 19-feet
long Excursion, whose four-wheel drive version is featured at the
Dallas Auto Show this week.
</P>
<P>
   Ford dealers, already reaping strong sales with the smaller, but
still large, Expedition, gleefully await deliveries of the
Excursion and the chance to challenge the Suburban, which has been
hauling loads for 64 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This puts the cream on the pie for our lineup'' said Mickey
McHale, president of Hillard Auto Group in Ford Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Ford deliberately chose a market that loves trucks for the
public unveiling of the Excursion, which was announced in February.
Prestige Ford in suburban Dallas, for example, is the world's
leader in Ford F-Series truck sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why wouldn't we want to come to Texas, the truck capital of
the world, to show this vehicle? This is Ford country,'' Ford
Division President Jim O'Connor told a group of 75 Texas and
Oklahoma Ford dealers who gawked and grinned at the toreador red
Excursion on display Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors isn't taking Ford's challenge lying down.
</P>
<P>
   It will unveil a slightly disguised redesign of the Chevy
Suburban and GMC Yukon at the March 30 New York Auto Show. But it
is saving the complete unveiling of the redesigned Suburban and its
smaller siblings, the GMC Yukon and the Chevy Tahoe, for the Texas
State Fair in September, just a few weeks before the Excursion goes
on sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Texas, we're very much in the fight,'' GM spokesman Craig
Eppling said.
</P>
<P>
   The first Excursions will hit the market in October. The
Suburban and Tahoe/Yukon redesigns will go on sale in late winter.
</P>
<P>
   GM is already riding high with Suburban sales. In 1998, GMC and
Chevrolet dealers sold 151,356 Suburbans, the model's best year
ever, despite a strike that shut down production for nearly two
months. Nationally, the Expedition outsold it in 1998, with
225,705.
</P>
<P>
   But GM had the edge in Texas, where it sold nearly 35,000 Chevy
or GMC Suburbans, Eppling said, while Ford sold nearly 29,000
Expeditions and its upscale twin, Lincoln Navigators.
</P>
<P>
   Area Ford dealers say they're ready for a fight. Their only
gripe is that they won't be allotted as many Excursions as they
could sell; Ford only plans to make 50,000 to 60,000 Excursions for
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Ford dealers say the Excursion will draw Suburban owners, buyers
moving up from the Expedition and other smaller vehicles, as well
as commercial accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there will be a big market for commercial use,'' said
Ken Nichols, owner of Nichols Ford in Fort Worth. ``It will be a
great carpool vehicle. We would put it in our rental fleet also.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Reynolds, whose Prestige Ford sold 405 Expeditions in
1998, says the Excursion will attract two types of customers: ``The
executive who wants the biggest, baddest SUV out there, and also
the female buyer who carries a lot of kids who wants something big
and safe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Both buyers will come from Suburbans and Expeditions,'' he
added. ``I don't think you will see any first-time SUV buyers.''
</P>
<P>
   John Dee Sledge, owner of Cleburne Ford southwest of Fort Worth,
said the 76.5-inch height for the two-wheel drive model or the
79.5-inch four-wheel drive model height won't be a problem for most
of his customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of farm and ranch people here who will be
parking outside anyway,'' Sledge said. ``But I imagine it will be a
little hard to park in the Metroplex.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Ford's eagerness for battle, auto industry analyst Jim
Wangers said the Excursion won't hurt the Suburban's market. GM,
mindful of federal requirements on producing fuel-efficient
vehicles, has never made as many Suburbans as motorists wanted to
buy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Ford will take some folk from the Tahoe and the Yukon,
and they may get those who already have a Suburban and find they
have to wait for a new one,'' Wangers said.
</P>
<P>
   And Chevy dealers aren't willingly giving ground.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Lowrie, owner of Bruce Lowrie Chevrolet in Fort Worth,
said he is used to competing with his neighbor, Ken Nichols of
Nichols Ford. Lowrie said most of his customers are confirmed
Chevrolet owners who won't switch to a Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers, at least ours, very seldom change brands,'' Lowrie
said.
</P>
<P>
   And that probably means there's plenty of room for both brands.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Stapp, sales manager for Pioneer Aggregates in the Dallas
suburb of Irving and arena director for the Houston Livestock Show
&AMP; Rodeo, drives a Ford F250 Crew Cab. He has owned a Suburban, but
says he may buy an Excursion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like Fords,'' said Stapp, who has seen pictures of the
Excursion and plans to go to the Dallas show to see the one on
display. ``Plus this has got the size to hook up a trailer any
size, and the comfort and luxury to take a trip in. This will blow
right past the Suburban.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chad Hullender, who drives a 1992 Suburban, said he has no
interest in an Excursion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really care for Fords,'' said Hullender, a resident of
the Fort Worth suburb of Arlington, and a senior customer service
representative for an airline. ``And bigger than this (his
Suburban) isn't necessarily better.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
