<HEADER>
A4495 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTEL-ANTITRUST-580&AMP;A     03-17 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-ANTITRUST-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. APPROVES ACCORD IN CASE AGAINST INTEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Trade Commission approved a settlement
Wednesday of its antitrust case against Intel Corp., the world's
largest maker of computer chips.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, reached last week, settles the government's
complaint that Intel violated federal law by retaliating against
three computer makers that had accused Intel of violating their
patent rights. After the patent dispute arose, Intel withheld
valuable technical information that was essential for the computer
makers to develop the latest models of personal computers and
specialized work stations.
</P>
<P>
   Intel resolved the dispute with the FTC by agreeing to an order
that limits the giant chip maker from withholding crucial technical
details about its chips when it becomes embroiled in patent
disputes with some of its customers.
</P>
<P>
   While the order prohibits Intel from denying the technical
information as a way of maintaining the company's dominant market
position, it does permit Intel to withhold the information for
legitimate business reasons unrelated to the patent disputes. For
instance, Intel can withhold the information from computer makers
who are not paying their bills or are developing competing
microprocessors. Intel may also cut off information to a company
that, in violation of nondisclosure agreements, leaks details of
the technology to third parties.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, computer companies seeking injunctions to block Intel
from selling its chips as part of their patent disputes would not
be protected by the order.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC had accused Intel of withholding the information from
computer makers to coerce them into handing over their innovations
to Intel. The technical chip information is the lifeblood for
computer makers. But in three cases, the government said, Intel
withheld the information after the computer companies _ Compaq
Computer, Digital Equipment and Intergraph _ had complained that
Intel was infringing on their patents.
</P>
<P>
   Intel contested the government's accusation that the company
``sought to extort'' technology from its customers ``in order to
preserve its monopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission voted 3-0 to accept the agreement for public
comment. If the commission follows its usual practice, it is all
but certain to make the agreement final after a 60-day public
comment period.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pitofsky, the chairman of the FTC, said the settlement
upheld the principle that ``a monopolist cannot withhold products
or information about products in order to retaliate against
customers who find themselves in intellectual property disputes.''
</P>
<P>
   The order, Pitofsky said in an interview, sets up a ``balanced
approach'' that enables Intel and its potential rivals to negotiate
and litigate patent issues in the courts while stripping Intel of
its ability to cripple a possible rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intel can do what they need to do for legitimate business
reasons,'' Pitofsky said. ``But they cannot make the potential
rivals bend at their will.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the settlement, the agency reached no conclusion
about whether Intel is a monopoly, a finding that would have had
broad legal consequences for the company by enabling rivals and
customers to file their own suits. But it seemed clear that senior
officials had concluded that Intel, whose chips power more than 80
percent of personal computers, was a monopoly. If the company were
not a monopoly, then it could have lawfully retaliated against
potential rivals by withholding the technical information.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The settlement was praised by executives of Intel and
Intergraph, which makes specialized workstations and was the
company hit hardest by the Intel dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although we have different interpretations regarding Intel's
market position and the legality of our past actions, the
compromise provides a framework for resolving future intellectual
property disputes with our customers,'' said Craig Barrett, the
president of Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Intergraph said the settlement vindicated the
accusations they had made in a separate civil lawsuit that Intel
was heavy-handed when it cut off Intergraph from the technology. In
that suit, Intel has denied Intergraph's accusations of fraud,
theft of trade secrets and anti-competitive conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you give in to a consent decree, it's an admission
that you did something wrong,'' said James Meadlock, the chairman
and chief executive of Intergraph. ``The settlement is clearly
consistent with the opinion by the judge in our case,'' who found
that Intel violated its duties as a monopolist not to misuse its
market power.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's findings came in an early opinion in a case that is
set to be tried next February.
</P>
<P>
   Intel executives and officials at the FTC said the settlement
would have no effect on a broader antitrust investigation of the
company that has been under way at the agency.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has been examining a variety of Intel's business
practices, including the contract restrictions imposed on customers
through nondisclosure agreements, Intel's control of industry
standards, and the special pricing agreements and restrictions
required of computer makers as part of Intel's ``Intel Inside''
marketing campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
