<SLUG> BC-SENATE-MISSILE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE BILL PLEDGES DEFENSE AGAINST MISSILES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Reacting to warnings that missiles from several
emerging nations could soon be capable of hitting the United
States, the Senate Wednesday pledged to build a national defense
system as soon as the technology is developed, overcoming earlier
opposition from Democrats and the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The national missile defense bill said virtually nothing about
how that system would work, how much it cost, or when it would be
ready. But it cemented the Senate's commitment to defend against
missile attack in all 50 states, raising the profile of a plan that
has been discussed in various forms since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which the Senate overwhelmingly approved 97 to
3, comes on the heels of several unexpected missile launches
abroad, including a medium-range ballistic missile tested by North
Korea last August and similar tests by Iran. The fear is that those
nations will soon have the capacity to fire rockets to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Thad Cochran, the Mississippi Republican who sponsored
the bill, lauded the Senate for taking ``the necessary first step
to protecting the United States from long-range ballistic missile
attack.''
</P>
<P>
   But the political landscape played a key role in the bill's
swift passage as well, several senators said. Despite strong
opposition to the same bill last year _ and the threat that
President Clinton might veto this one _ Democrats Wednesday offered
their support.
</P>
<P>
   They did so in part because the Senate passed an amendment
promising the system would not disturb arms control negotiations
with Russia _ a key concern as the Russian Parliament debates
whether to sign the second strategic arms reduction treaty. Russian
officials have indicated they will refuse to sign the treaty, Start
2, if the US shifts the balance of nuclear power with a massive
defense system.
</P>
<P>
   But by passing the amended bill, Democrats also denied
Republicans the opportunity to use national missile defense as a
political issue in the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Jack Reed, Democrat of Rhode Island, said there was a
``real, substantive reason'' to bring the system to the top of the
list of foreign policy concerns, citing tests by Iran and North
Korea as reasons ``this has become a front-burner issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the Republicans certainly have a real political reason to
start talking about it,'' he said. ``It allows them to play to
their strengths at this particular moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The system, which remains largely undeveloped, uses a
combination of sensors, trackers and a defense missile to monitor
the location of enemy missiles and shoot them down. Analysts say it
is analagous to ``hitting a bullet with a bullet'' _ and is equally
difficult, part of the reason the more than $40 billion spent on
building the program so far has led to relatively few results.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, three Democratic senators voted against the bill:
Senators Patrick Leahy of Vermont, Paul Wellstone of Minnesota and
Richard Durbin of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States Senate, with this vote, is virtually giving
a blank check to this project,'' Durbin said. ``It would give us a
false sense of security and be completely ineffective.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Massachusetts senators voted in favor of the bill, even
though Senator John F. Kerry voiced concerns about ``the building
of a system that simply creates greater unrest, greater
instability, greater question marks.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill is expected to meet equally few opponents in the House
of Representatives, where it is scheduled to be voted upon
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, Democrat of Missouri,
said there were concerns among Democrats that the Republicans were
``trying to take this beyond what the President intended.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The President has decided to do something, but the minute you
do that, the Republicans want to run off and turn it into Star Wars
again,'' Gephardt said in a telephone interview, referring to the
wide-ranging space laser initiative first promoted by President
Ronald Reagan in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats voiced different concerns _ particularly
budgetary ones. Calling the initiative a ``political gambit,''
Representative Barney Frank accused House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert
of seizing on a no-brainer issue in order to ``claim they
accomplished some things.''
</P>
<P>
   But the cost will soon outweigh the benefit, particularly
because no missile defense system has yet been developed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if I did a census of the older women in my district,
more of them would be afraid of the adverse consequences of other
things besides getting bopped on the head with a nuclear missile
from Korea,'' said Frank, a Democrat from Massachusetts. ``The
money they want to use for this is taken from every other piece of
the budget, including defense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 2059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
