<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4497 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-BOESAK-NYT &LR;      03-17 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-BOESAK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-APARTHEID CLERIC IS GUILTY OF STEALING MONEY FROM CHARITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ The former anti-apartheid activist
Allan Boesak was found guilty Wednesday of stealing hundreds of
thousands of dollars donated to his foundation. The money was
supposed to help needy children and to educate black voters before
South Africa's first all-race election in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   A judge found Boesak guilty of three counts of theft and one of
fraud, saying he had used money given to him for charitable
purposes ``as if it was his own'' to buy two luxury homes and a
radio studio for his second wife, Elna, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   Boesak, once one of South Africa's liberation heroes, sat
stone-faced as the judge, John Foxcroft, read his lengthy decision.
He was originally charged with 32 counts of theft and fraud; five
were dismissed, and he was acquitted on the other 23.
</P>
<P>
   Boesak's case has gripped this nation in part because it has
offered a peek at the former cleric's lavish style during the early
1990s, and in part because President Nelson Mandela intervened
several times to help him.
</P>
<P>
   When Boesak first returned to South Africa from the United
States to face trial, Mandela sent his justice minister, Dullah
Omar, to meet him at the airport. Later, when Boesak ran out of
money to pay his lawyers, Mandela raised funds for him and
criticized the prosecutor's case.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela later apologized for his remarks. He was in Norway
Wednesday and had no comment on the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Boesak had maintained that all he was guilty of was ``struggle
bookkeeping.'' And in arriving at his verdict, Foxcroft
acknowledged that in some cases proper records of how donations
were being used could not be kept because of the close attention of
the security police.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge found that in several cases Boesak had used money
donated to his Foundation for Peace and Justice ``as his own.''
</P>
<P>
   The charges of theft and fraud are not Boesak's first brush with
scandal. A fiery speaker against apartheid in the 1980s, Boesak
came to prominence when he became the head of the World Alliance of
Reformed Churches. But he was forced to resign in 1990, when news
broke that he was having an extramarital affair.
</P>
<P>
   He was not abandoned by the ruling African National Congress,
however. Boesak had been appointed South Africa's representative at
the United Nations in Geneva when the charges of theft and fraud
surfaced in 1994. He was forced to leave that job and soon moved to
the United States, where he was a fellow at the American Baptist
Seminary of the West in Berkeley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial many prominent South Africans who had been
board members for Boesak's foundation testified that they believed
they were deliberately kept in the dark about what was happening to
the money. Some said they had resigned because of the problems. But
other witnesses were clearly reluctant to speak out against a man
they admired.
</P>
<P>
   The courtroom was packed with Boesak's supporters, and once or
twice there were shouts of ``Viva Boesak!'' But mostly the crowd
remained silent.
</P>
<P>
   Boesak and his wife refused to comment after the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   The court adjourned until next Tuesday for the lawyers to
prepare their arguments for sentencing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
