<SLUG> BC-USWEB-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 USWeb Moving Headquarters to the Gulch
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Jon Swartz &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
USWeb/CKS, a billion-dollar Internet consulting company, yesterday
said it is moving its headquarters from the South Bay to San
Francisco's Multimedia Gulch this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The company's executive team is heading north to be part of the
region's multimedia epicenter. It represents one of the biggest
recruiting coups yet for the burgeoning South of Market high-tech
neighborhood, city officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco is a booming source for technology and creative
talent, which is critical as we continue to scale up over the
coming years,'' company CEO Robert Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the change of address is largely symbolic for the moment.
USWeb/CKS, now based in Santa Clara, will consolidate more than 300
employees already located in three downtown offices and import 100
more workers from other offices around the Bay Area to a four-story
building at 410 Townsend St., between Fifth and Sixth streets. The
fast-growing firm, which employs 2,250 people worldwide, will
maintain 200 administrative, financial and consulting positions in
Silicon Valley, according to a spokesman. USWeb/CKS has added 1,000
positions worldwide in the past year and plans to continue its
rapid expansion, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This move further solidifies the city as a hub for
multimedia,'' said Laura Paden, a spokeswoman for the San Francisco
Partnership, a public-private consortium formed to attract and
retain businesses in the city.
</P>
<P>
   The city's multimedia industry has mushroomed by some 6,000
full-time jobs _ to 17,600 _ over the past four years, according to
Paden. That total does not include another 17,000 high-tech
contract jobs in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   USWeb/CKS' 94,000-square-foot Townsend building is located down
the street from two other large tech employers: Sega of America and
Macromedia.
</P>
<P>
   Sega is the city's biggest high-tech recruit from Silicon Valley
so far. The computer-console game-maker started transferring an
estimated 800 employees from Redwood Shores earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen more interest (from prospective renters) in our
buildings the last six weeks than we have space to accommodate by
three or four times. The Internet industry has created a
real-estate boom in South of Market,'' said Douglas Rosenberg,
president of the Rosenberg Co., the San Francisco developer that
owns the USWeb/CKS building.
</P>
<P>
   ``USWeb/CKS is a welcome addition to San Francisco's high-tech
and Internet community,'' Mayor Willie Brown said in a statement.
``(It) represents the kind of innovative and forward-thinking
companies Multimedia Gulch continues to attract.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also surely one of the most colorful.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Firmage, 28, the company's eccentric founder, resigned in
January so he could promote his belief that many of today's
high-tech advancements, including semiconductors, optics and
lasers, came from aliens.
</P>
<P>
   USWeb merged last year with Net marketing firm CKS to form a
public company worth $2.1 billion. Its customers include Apple
Computer, Levi Strauss and Harley-Davidson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 2112EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
