r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILLIAMS-SFCHRON &LR;      03-17 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLIAMS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Shares of Williams-Sonoma Tumble 19%
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Carol Emert &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Williams-Sonoma Inc. stock swooned 19 percent yesterday on news of
a top executive's retirement and earnings that came in one penny
below projections.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Chantland, Williams-Sonoma's chief administrative officer
and an executive vice president, will retire July 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 56 years old, I've decided it's time to learn how to relax,
do some traveling and improve my golf handicap,'' he said in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts credited Chantland, who is in charge of
finance and systems, with fattening Williams-Sonoma's margins,
improving its systems and lowering costs since joining the San
Francisco retailer in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of his departure was made before the market
opened, and trading of Williams-Sonoma shares was delayed for two
hours. The first trade was made at $26.75, down from $36 at
Tuesday's close. Shares ended the day at $29, down from a 52-week
high of $40.75, reached on December 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market doesn't react to surprises very well,'' said
Chantland, who called yesterday's plunge an ``overreaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Wall Street pummeled Williams-Sonoma's stock, the
company reported robust increases in both sales and profits.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended January 31, net earnings hit $43.9 million
(75 cents per share), up from $34.3 million (61 cents) in last
year's fourth quarter. Analysts had expected per-share earnings of
76 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Sales at stores open at least a year grew 6 percent for the
quarter, while mail-order sales jumped 18.8 percent. Total sales
hit $441.2 million, a 19 percent increase over the fourth quarter
of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   When Chantland joined Williams-Sonoma, selling general and
administrative expenses represented about 35 percent of revenues.
Last year, they had fallen to 32.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Chantland ``has been the driving force behind those improvements
so people are a bit antsy,'' said Jason Klein, an analyst with
Blackford Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Chantland was an important player in overhauling the company's
inventory distribution systems, which were responsible for stock
outages and sales shortfalls in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Chantland said the company's Internet gift registry will go
online in May. The company continues to look for a buyer for its
catalog Gardeners Eden, which has annual revenues of $20 million to
$25 million, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the 1998 fiscal year, also reported yesterday,
Williams-Sonoma announced a sales increase of 18.3 percent to $1.1
billion on a 21.5 percent increase in retail square footage.
Comparable store sales rose 5 percent, while mail order sales grew
15.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Net earnings, meanwhile, rose 33 percent to $54.9 million (96
cents per share) from $41.3 million (75 cents, adjusted to reflect
a stock split) in fiscal 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Williams-Sonoma runs stores and catalogs under the
Williams-Sonoma, Pottery Barn and Hold Everything names, and
catalogs called Chambers and Gardeners Eden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 2112EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0441 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4508 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BABY-SFCHRON &LR;      03-17 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Toddlers Discover Computers
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Dan Fost &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Harrison Eagle, 19 months old, doesn't talk much, but he does share
his emotions freely. And this much is clear: He loves his BabyWow
software.
</P>
<P>
   When it is in the computer, he is happily banging away on the
keyboard, squealing with delight at the bananas and giraffes and
other simple images and words coming from the PC.
</P>
<P>
   And when his mom closes the program, he does what any Silicon
Valley toddler would do: He cries until she restarts it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sees everybody on the computer, and he wants to be on the
computer,'' said Barbara Eagle, his San Jose mom who runs a film
and video production company with her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to take advantage of an untapped niche in the crowded
consumer software market _ and of parents who want to get their
kids on the high-tech fast track _ companies have recently started
pitching computer games for children as young as 9 months.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of software for children under age 4 grew 50 percent last
year to $13 million, according to Ann Stephens, president of PC
Data, a market research firm in Reston, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's growing fast,'' she said. ``Who's making the decisions?
It's not the kids. It's parents who don't want their kids left
behind. How you can be left behind when you're 9 months old is
beyond me, but so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Child-development experts say that parents should mellow out and
let their infants and toddlers make mud pies or play with blocks,
and that getting babies hooked on computers doesn't guarantee
they'll get into MIT.
</P>
<P>
   But the experts, and the software-makers, say that if used only
occasionally, for brief periods, with a parent around, such
programs can be a healthy part of a child's development.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be seen as another toy, but one with limited value
in the early years,'' said Claire Lerner, a child development
specialist with Zero to Three, a Washington, D.C., nonprofit
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner said puzzles, wooden blocks and walks in the woods are
preferable to spending time with a computer. ``If your child does
not play on the computer in the first two years, it's not going to
hurt the child's development,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Candace Kaye, a lecturer in the department of teacher education
at California State University at Long Beach, is skeptical of the
software.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a baby is between zero and 2, children respond to the
environment with their senses and their physical interaction,''
Kaye said. ``I wonder how many children will be tasting the
keyboard or the screen? Can a baby get their hands around it? Can
they enfold it and play with it? This may be a wonderful addendum.
My concern is (that) this would be a primary thing for some
parents.''
</P>
<P>
   The software, most of which sells for $20 to $25, all work
basically the same way, according to Stephens at PC Data: ``You
whack the thing and you watch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Software-makers say this simple system gives children
familiarity with the computer, if nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe software is meant to be a replacement for
traditional learning activities,'' said Debbie Galdin, a
spokeswoman for the Learning Co., a Cambridge, Mass., company that
makes Reader Rabbit's Toddler software for children ages 18 months
to 3 years. It also makes Sesame Street Toddlers Deluxe, which is
designed for children ages 2 to 4.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which has divisions in the Bay Area, developed the
products to meet customer demand, she said. ``Because kids this age
do love to emulate their parents, it's important to have something
on the market that lets them do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowledge Adventure, another children's software-maker, last
year extended its popular JumpStart educational line with JumpStart
Baby, for children as young as 9 months. The company also sells
Play with the Teletubbies software, based on the hit television
show, for children ages 1 to 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely view this software as lapware,'' said Jennifer
Johnson, a spokeswoman for Knowledge Adventure, a division of the
French firm Havas Interactive. ``It's not a baby sitter, but
something parents and children should use together.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Fernandes, maker of BabyWow, said he was inspired by his
son, Sean, who was born in July 1995. ``He was really curious about
the computer, probably because I spent a lot of time on it,''
Fernandes said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, there was no software for children under age 3 on
the market. So Fernandes wrote a program for Sean, ``so that when
he pressed the keyboard, he'd see certain things pop up. He liked
that.''
</P>
<P>
   As he heard similar stories from other Silicon Valley parents,
Fernandes decided there might be a market for baby software.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; After researching child development and the software market,
Fernandes, a software &UR;  &LR; designer, quit his job at Netscape
Communications Corp. in February 1998 and started a company, BowWow
House, with his own money.
</P>
<P>
   By August, he had launched BabyWow. In the program, no matter
what key a toddler presses, something happens on screen: a giraffe
appears, or it  &LR; the program counts up to 10 bananas, or it
introduces concepts like ``behind'' or ``in front.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents can run the program in eight languages, in case they are
multilingual or just want to teach their toddler a second language.
</P>
<P>
   BabyWow, on CD-ROM, is only for sale through his  &LR; Fernandes' Web
site,  &LR; www.babywow.com &LR; . He plans to release three new programs for
kids ages 1 to 4 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Sean is approaching his fourth birthday, Fernandes and
his wife and business partner, Kathy, have a new product tester,
1-year-old Ryan. ``He is the leading edge of refinement,''
Fernandes said. ``We need to keep reproducing.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandes is accustomed to strident criticism from people who
don't like the idea of software for babies. His answer to
critics: &UR;  &LR; ``The computer is part of their environment. The computer
is going to be there in the home. The only question is, should we
put something on it to reward their curiosity?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
