 Column: Salon Hoping to Attract More Web Surfers
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Dan Fost &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Salon is getting a makeover.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds like it might be bad news for loyalists, who love
the San Francisco online literary magazine for its writerly
craftsmanship; long, in-depth stories; and worldly array of topics.
</P>
<P>
   Those traits make Salon _ at  &LR; www.salonmagazine.com &LR;  _ stand out
compared to many other Web publications, which tend to be
hyperactive, up-to-the-minute accounts of technology news.
</P>
<P>
   So it might be disappointing to devotees that Salon's redesign
will include more tech news and up-to-the-minute reports _ exactly
what dozens of other computer-crazy Web sites already do.
</P>
<P>
   Salon says don't worry: It will still have its distinctive
voice, its literary bent and its wide array of topics. Editors say
the site mostly needs to change the way it presents itself to its
readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We publish tons of new material every day already,'' said
Scott Rosenberg, Salon's technology editor. However, focus groups
revealed that its readers aren't aware of this.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web, fresh material draws a steady stream of surfers and
clicks, the lifeblood of any site. The redesigned site will launch
March 29, and Rosenberg said many of the details are still being
worked out. ``We'll be making changes up to the last minute,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But fans of treatises, take heart: ``We're not giving up the
in-depth stuff,'' Rosenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Salon has already started some changes. Today marks the debut of
a serial novel about six geeks trying to get ahead. ``Silicon
Follies,'' by Thomas Scoville &UR;  &LR; will be updated every Monday and
Thursday. Salon describes it as a geeky ``Tales of the City.''
</P>
<P>
   Scoville, a 15-year Silicon Valley veteran, writes essays on
digital culture and created ``The Silicon Valley Tarot,'' an online
deck of fortune-telling cards for nerds, such as the Five of
Cubicles and the Ace of Networks.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Salon hired six new writers from such
ink-and-paper stalwarts as The New Yorker, U.S. News and World
Report and Time magazine, who are charged with beefing up expanded
sections on health and books.
</P>
<P>
   Now if only Salon could get rid of its real competition:
 &LR; www.salon-magazine.com &LR;  and  &LR; www.salon.com &LR;  and _ Web sites about
beauty products that, thanks to their similar monikers, lure the
Web literati to discussions of the finer points of manicures and
pedicures.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEBBIES TONIGHT &LR; : Get out your feather boa. It's Webbies night.
</P>
<P>
   You know the Webbies, the awards ceremony that started from a
San Francisco magazine, the Web, and have survived the mag's demise
to become an institution unto themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany Shlain, the diva of the Webbies, sees the event as
poking fun at the self-importance of a certain other awards
ceremony taking place in Los Angeles this weekend. She limits
acceptance speeches to five words, and jokes about a red carpet
area for the ``celebrity'' nominees _ the HTML code-slingers behind
sites ranging from www.superbad.com to the Smithsonian magazine's
site.
</P>
<P>
   But some see Shlain's establishment of an International Academy
of Digital Arts and Sciences to nominate Webby contenders as
sliding toward pomposity.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Trying to knock the Webbies off their pedestal, Manish Vij,
CEO of a Mountain View Web graphics firm, NetStudio, last year
launched the ``Mud Brick Awards'' for the world's ugliest Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to be the opposite of the Webbies,'' says Vij.
``They're an elitist ceremony. We're trailer-park, beer-drinking
folks.''
</P>
<P>
   Vij will announce the Mud Brick finalists tomorrow with a beer
bash for the ``winners'' coming later in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Shlain sees the Muddies as having the difficult task of
parodying a parody: ``We're already poking fun at ourselves,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SMALL PLANET CONFRONTS Y2K: &LR;  Frances Moore Lappe first made a
name for herself in 1972 as a 27-year-old Berkeley prodigy when she
wrote the best-selling ``Diet for a Small Planet.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 55 and living in Brattleboro, Vt., Lappe is planning a
return to the Bay Area next month to hawk her latest effort: News
you can use about the Year 2000 computer problem.
</P>
<P>
   Lappe will be lobbying scribes at a conference for the American
Society of Newspaper Editors, meeting in San Francisco the week of
April 12. She wants to sell subscriptions to her American News
Service, a nonprofit that syndicates ``solutions-based'' articles
by its 40 writers to newspapers and magazines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The service is predicated on the notion that people are sick
of reading only about problems and want articles that also propose
solutions. The Y2K glitch is only one area it's focusing on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really want to widen the news lens,'' Lappe said. ``We
think it's a great hazard for democracy when news is defined as
what's breaking, what's shocking or what's happening in Washington,
D.C. If we see only a small slice of life around us, we get a very
distorted sense of what we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the service launched a Y2K news bureau, and now more
than 40 stories are posted on its Web site at
 &LR; www.americannews.com &LR; . The stories are available only to
subscribers, who pay $39.95 a year for access to the site.
Newspapers like the Boston Globe and Los Angeles Times also pay for
the right to reprint the stories.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CRAMER STRIKES BACK: &LR;  His salary and stock options were laid
bare in Securities and Exchange Commission filings. His hedge fund
reported results on a lousy year. All this on the heels of
continued criticism of his skirting ethical lines between trading
in stocks and writing about them.
</P>
<P>
   James Cramer, the co-founder and columnist at the online
financial news site TheStreet.com, hasn't been able to answer many
of his critics, as the SEC places a virtual muzzle on any company
about to launch a public stock offering. (TheStreet.com announced a
pending public offering last month.)
</P>
<P>
   But Cramer does churn out the columns, and this week he lashed
back: ``Looks like the dead-tree press is having a field day at my
expense, and will continue to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   In true Cramer fashion, he says, ``I am not taking the bait'' _
and then he bites.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my business, there are two kinds of people, those who make
money and those who critique those who make money. I am proud to be
in the former, and I will not let the latter stop me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Media Bytes appears every Thursday in The San Francisco Chronicle.
Send buzz, dirt, tips and comments to fostd(AT SIGN)sfgate.com,
call (415) 777-6004 or fax (415) 543-2482. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
