 Legislation Would Restrict Gun Sales Over the Internet
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Jamie Beckett &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
A U.S. senator on Tuesday introduced legislation that would crack
down on weapons sales on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet Gun Trafficking Act, sponsored by Senator Charles
Schumer, D-N.Y., would make it illegal for anyone who is not a
licensed gun dealer to advertise or sell firearms on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, federal law allows unlicensed dealers to sell guns
over the Internet. However, if the buyer and seller are in
different states, the gun must first be shipped to a licensed gun
dealer, who performs the background check and releases the gun to
the buyer.
</P>
<P>
   California has its own laws governing sales of guns within the
state.
</P>
<P>
   The new bill also would require Web sites that advertise or sell
guns to register with the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our laws to keep felons from buying guns are based on a
face-to-face sale using proper ID and a criminal background
check,'' said Schumer. ``The Internet is a gaping loophole that has
the potential of arming those who no one in their right mind would
trust with a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said he found thousands of guns for sale _ from cheap
pistols to automatic assault-style weapons _ on dozens of
unregulated, unlicensed Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``The firepower which can be acquired simply going online is
chilling,'' he said in a press release. ``Ensuring the fitness of a
person to own a gun must go farther than requiring only a computer
and an e-mail address.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the National Rifle Association called the bill
unnecessary, saying that federal laws already apply to Internet
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer isn't the only lawmaker concerned about unregulated gun
sales. U.S. Senator Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., is drafting
legislation that would require unlicensed gun dealers selling
across state lines to perform background checks on the buyer.
Currently, only licensed dealers must perform the criminal
background check, as required by the Brady Bill, according to
Feinstein's office.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, modeled on California law, would apply to guns sold
over the Internet, at gun shows, through classified ads and in
other person-to-person transactions, a Feinstein spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Online auction giant eBay recently banned sales of guns and
ammunition on its site. The San Jose company said firearms sales
had been an area of growing concern because online sellers cannot
readily guarantee that buyers meet all the qualifications and
comply with the laws governing firearms sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
