 Column: How to Get Alert for New E-Mail
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By David Einstein &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  Are you aware of any software that will provide an alert
on the desktop when new e-mail arrives? I would like this to work
if my modem cord is plugged into the wall telephone socket, but I
am not online.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  If you're not online, how is your computer going to
know if you have new mail? Sorry, but to get mail, or even to be
alerted that you have it, you must be connected to your e-mail
server, and that means you must be online.
</P>
<P>
   That said, a number of programs are available that can
automatically log onto the Internet at scheduled times, check your
mailboxes and provide visual or audio alerts about new messages.
Among the most popular are MailAlert, a $15 shareware program from
Diamond Ridge; E-Mail Notify, $20 shareware from Cyber-Info; and
AvirMail, a freebie from Avir. All can be downloaded from the ZDNet
software library at  &LR; www.hotfiles.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It bears mentioning that America Online also has a sophisticated
mail-alert feature that beeps when new mail arrives while you're
online and lets you schedule ``Flash Sessions'' to check mail
periodically when you're away from your computer.
</P>
<P>
   Maximizing Your Modem
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have an LT Win Modem that came with my Hewlett-Packard
Pavilion PC in July of 1997. It's a K56Flex modem, but the highest
speed I could get on AOL's 56K lines in Walnut Creek was 31.2. I
went to Lucent Technologies' Web site (they made the modem) and
downloaded and installed the software for upgrading to the new V.90
standard. But now, my top speed is just 28.8. I have written to
Lucent twice and have gotten no response. AOL says go to the PC
manufacturer, HP says go to the modem-maker and CompUSA, from whom
I bought the system along with a 3-year warranty, says they're
stumped.
</P>
<P>
   A: Before you start casting blame, you should determine whether
your telephone line can handle 56K speeds. 3Com, a big modem-maker,
offers an online feature that lets you do that. Go to 3Com's site
 &LR; (www.3com.com)  &LR; and search for ``linetest.''
</P>
<P>
   If your line is OK, I'd recommend going to HP's site and
downloading the upgrade software from there. The program available
from HP supposedly is designed specifically for your modem, while
Lucent's upgrade software is a generic version.
</P>
<P>
   To locate the program on HP's site  &LR; (www.hp.com), &LR;  go to
Services &AMP; Support, then to Personal Computers, then find your
model.
</P>
<P>
   Cheaper Chips
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am thinking about buying a new computer and I was wondering
if the Intel Celeron and AMD K6 chips are really good deals. Are
there any problems running software written for Pentium chips? And
are they more prone to crashing and glitches? I mostly use
Microsoft Word and am most interested in how Word performs on these
cheaper chips. I am graduating from law school soon and then going
into government service, so cost is a great factor to me.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: A PC that uses either the Celeron or the K6 should
perform just fine for you. Both are fully compatible with Windows
and all Windows software. The Celeron is slower than the Pentium
II, but the K6 isn't. In fact, systems boasting AMD's latest K6
chips are real bargains these days.
</P>
<P>
   Help With RealPlayer
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently changed Internet service providers from America
Online to the Microsoft Network. I now find that I can no longer
use my RealPlayer with MSN. The program refuses to open. MSN's
less-than-helpful technical support blew me off by claiming that
this did not fall within their support boundaries. RealNetworks'
solution involves altering the registry, a procedure a neophyte
like myself is not comfortable with. Any suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: A suspicious person might think that the Microsoft
software was designed to disable the RealPlayer, which competes
against Microsoft's Windows Media Player. But RealNetworks' people
say their technical wizards are unaware of anything in MSN that
could have caused your RealPlayer to stop working. They said it
might be ``an anomaly.''
</P>
<P>
   I know that doesn't help much. Best advice I can offer is to
uninstall both MSN and the RealPlayer, then reinstall them in that
order.
</P>
<P>
   Copy Your Contacts
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm running Windows 98 and using Outlook Express 5 for my
e-mail. Is there a way to back up my address book so I can keep a
safe copy of all contacts on a floppy?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: There are a couple of ways to go on this. You can simply
copy the actual address book file, which contains all your
contacts. Open Windows Explorer, then locate the file, which is
located in Windows/Application Data/Microsoft/Address Book. You'll
recognize the file because it starts with your e-mail ID and ends
with .wab. Insert a floppy disk and drag the address book file to
the floppy.
</P>
<P>
   Another option is to save the address book as a text file that
can be opened in a word processor, spreadsheet or database. To do
this, go to the address book's File menu and choose Export, then
Other Address Book. In the Export Tool window that appears, choose
Text File, then click the Export button and follow the
instructions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to  &LR; computers(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
