<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0445 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4512 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RENAULT-NISSAN-430&AMP;AD     03-17 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENAULT-NISSAN-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENAULT OFFER TO NISSAN IS QUESTIONED
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Having failed in previous international mergers in the
United States and elsewhere, Renault &UR;  &LR; SA is encountering
considerable skepticism in financial markets following the French
automaker's offer for a large stake in heavily indebted Nissan
Motor &UR;  &LR; Co. of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Credit rating agencies said Wednesday that they were reviewing
Renault's finances, the company's stock fell sharply and investors
questioned whether the proposal Renault announced on Tuesday would
solve either company's problems.
</P>
<P>
   While Mack Trucks has done fairly well since Renault bought it
nearly a decade ago, a planned merger with AB Volvo &UR;  &LR; fell apart in
1993 after Swedish managers complained that their French colleagues
were pushing them around.
</P>
<P>
   Renault's most notable failure in an auto marriage came when it
took control of American Motors Corp. in several stages in the
early 1980s. Cultural differences produced managerial chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Then Renault sold the company to Chrysler &UR;  &LR; Corp. in 1987, just a
few years before the sport utility vehicle boom made American
Motors' Jeep brand one of the most valuable businesses in the auto
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Meyers, a chairman and chief executive of American Motors
who quit in 1982 after clashing with Renault, predicted Wednesday
that Renault and Nissan would not be able to work together. ``I
can't think of any two cultures that are in more conflicts than
these _ they're both not interested in somebody else's ideas,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the question of what Renault sees in Nissan that
other automakers have already dismissed as unworthy of their time.
DaimlerChrysler &UR;  &LR; quit talks with Nissan a week ago. The Ford
Motor &UR;  &LR; Co. held talks with Nissan about taking a stake earlier this
year, but the two sides never even reached the point of exchanging
detailed financial information, said auto executives who insisted
on anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's leeriness of Nissan reflects the American automaker's
suspicion of Japanese automaker finances in general. Ford bought 25
percent of Mazda &UR;  &LR; in 1979, but only after increasing its stake to
33.4 percent in 1996, and installing some of its own executives to
help run Mazda, did Ford discover that Mazda's dealerships had
incurred enormous debts for which Mazda was liable, the auto
executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Renault's stock fell 6.2 percent in trading in Paris Wednesday,
following its announcement late Tuesday that it would seek to buy
35 percent of Nissan, and reportedly offering $5.3 billion for it.
Renault's shares have tumbled 28 percent since it confirmed on Jan.
18 that it wanted to invest in Nissan.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One of the main concerns among credit rating agencies in their
review of Renault is the debt load of Nissan. Scott Sprinzen, the
managing director for auto ratings at Standard &AMP; Poor's, said that
the ratings agency had concerns about ``the extent to which Renault
could benefit from an investment in such a financially weak
company, and whether the two companies working together could
effect an operational turnaround at Nissan.''
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of Nissan's debt start at $20 billion but run much
higher because no one outside the company knows its full liability
for borrowing by various Nissan affiliates. Nissan's shares also
fell 1.7 percent in Tokyo Wednesday as investors fretted over how
long it will take the company to find a partner.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue for auto industry experts Wednesday lay in
Renault's willingness to take a stake in Nissan without divulging
any plan for combining activities and cutting costs. To increase
their profits significantly, the two companies must combine vehicle
development programs, auto parts purchasing and their distribution
of cars and other vehicles, said John A. Casesa, an auto analyst at
Schroder &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``To take advantage of 4 million units of volume, the two
companies really have to become one,'' Casesa said. ``That'll mean
head count reductions, a lot of management reshuffling.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Nissan and Renault are each approaching the deal as a way to
avoid cutbacks while retaining separate management structures. The
French government owns 44.2 percent of Renault, and the French
transport minister, Jean-Claude Gayssot, portrayed the potential
business combination Wednesday as a way to avoid reductions in
staffing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no concerns about decisions over merging or
restructuring,'' he said. ``My concern is that the potential to
develop our businesses and our activities should translate into a
strengthening of those activities and in the defense and promotion
of employment.''
</P>
<P>
   Acquiring a large stake in Nissan would make Renault less
reliant on the French market. Renault is only now developing sport
utility vehicles and luxury sedans, the two market segments in
which other global automakers are making most of their profits, and
could tap Nissan's experience in both classes of vehicles. Nissan
also has more factories than it needs, and some of this extra
capacity could be used to sell Nissan cars through Renault's
extensive distribution network in France and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The most profitable auto market in the world now is in the
United States, because of the strong economy. But Renault only
sells Mack trucks here, and it's unclear to what extent Nissan's
American operations will help Renault.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan lost nearly $700 million here last year as it relied too
heavily on discounts and offered small, fuel efficient vehicles
that did not sell well because of cheap gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan's American operations plan to introduce six new or
redesigned models later this year and have already reduced
inventories and limited discounts, which should make the operations
break even this year, said Jason Vines, a company spokesman. But
Casesa said that while Nissan's coming cars were better designed,
stiff competition would make a quick financial improvement
difficult.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
