u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-660&AMP;ADD-     03-17 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO TALKS NEAR END AS SERBS BUILD UP
</HEADLINE>
   (With KOSOVO, KOSOVO-ENVOY) 
(nk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ As the Serbs continued to pour troops and tanks into
Kosovo, European and American intermediaries in peace talks here
prepared Wednesday to shut down the negotiations without any
agreement, probably on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   American officials in Washington and French Foreign Ministry
officials here warned that the NATO allies were ready to carry out
their threat of a vast bombing campaign against Serbian military
targets in Kosovo and beyond unless the Yugoslav president,
Slobodan Milosevic, accepted an accord.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wesley Clark, the alliance's supreme commander, testified
before the House Armed Services Committee on Wednesday that Serbian
forces were ``prepared to resume the conflict on a very large scale
should these peace talks fail to result in an agreement or should
they conclude that for some reason NATO wasn't serious in its
expressed intent.''
</P>
<P>
   French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine, co-chairman of the peace
talks here with British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, said on
Tuesday that NATO's decision to use force if the Serbs were the
main obstacle to peace remained in effect. French diplomats said
Wednesday that France and the United States stood firmly with the
rest of the allies in their determination to carry out the threat.
</P>
<P>
   Before the talks break off, the ethnic Albanians who have been
fighting for the last year for independence for the province will
sign the draft agreement that was worked out at Rambouillet outside
Paris last month, according to mediators and representatives of the
Albanian delegation.
</P>
<P>
   ``One signature, unfortunately, doesn't make an agreement,''
said the Russian mediator, Boris Mayorsky. The draft provides for
autonomy for Kosovo under Serbian sovereignty for a three-year
transition period, and 28,000 peacekeepers under NATO command to
enforce its terms.
</P>
<P>
   But mediators said Wednesday that Serbian negotiators were
refusing even to discuss terms of how to put the agreement into
effect. ``Based on talks the last few days with the Yugoslav side,
we are not anticipating any further progress,'' said Christopher R.
Hill, a mediator and the U.S. ambassador to Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Vedrine and Cook will confer with the mediators on Thursday
afternoon about ending the talks, officials said, and could decide
to make one more trip to Belgrade to try to get Milosevic to change
his mind and accept the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But diplomats said that it might take the bombing that NATO has
been threatening since last fall to get the Serbian side to change
its position and sign a peace settlement with the ethnic Albanians
who make up 90 percent of Kosovo's 2 million people.
</P>
<P>
   An adviser to the ethnic Albanians said that most members of the
delegation were anxious to get back to Kosovo as soon as possible,
in view of reports that Milosevic has moved 30,000 to 40,000 troops
into or close to Kosovo, defying an agreement he made last October
to pull out most of his military and police forces.
</P>
<P>
   James Rubin, the State Department spokesman, who arrived here
Wednesday, said Secretary of State Madeleine Albright had invited
the Kosovo Albanian leaders to come to Washington after they signed
the agreement and the talks ended. Ms. Albright got the Albanian
delegation to accept the accord in principle when the first phase
of negotiations in Rambouillet ended on Feb. 23, but they asked for
time to consult with local military commanders in Kosovo before
actually agreeing to sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs continue to have problems with the political part of
the agreement and are not prepared to discuss issues of
implementation,'' said Wolfgang Petritsch, the European Union
mediator in the talks, at the end of the third day of sessions
Wednesday. The United States, Britain, France, Germany and Italy,
co-sponsors of the talks with Russia, say that the 28,000 NATO
peacekeepers are an indispensable part of the 81-page draft accord.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   If the Serbs remain opposed, or intensify the fighting in Kosovo
significantly in coming days, and the allies decided to bomb, they
probably would not be ready to take action for at least a week,
according to officials in Brussels. The 400 American and British
warplanes would not begin striking until after diplomats had been
evacuated from Belgrade, the capital of Serbia and what remains of
Yugoslavia, and 2,000 cease-fire observers had been pulled out of
Kosovo, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   After that, probably next week, NATO Secretary General Javier
Solana could order attacks against selected Serbian military
targets by American cruise missiles launched from Navy ships
standing off the Balkan coast in the Adriatic.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on Milosevic's response to those strikes, Solana could
then order a phased bombing campaign with the aim of destroying
most of Serbia's ability to shoot down allied warplanes with
ground-to-air artillery and rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Allied diplomats said they hoped that the threat of further
destruction would be enough to get Milosevic to accept the accord.
Under the agreement, peacekeepers would deploy throughout the
province to oversee the disbanding of the Kosovo Liberation Army
guerrillas; make sure Serbian police and military forces now
attacking civilian areas withdraw to selected areas, leaving the
province altogether within a year; and provide security while the
Albanians take responsibility for their own affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
