<HEADER>
A4515 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-PROSECUTOR-2TA     03-17 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PROSECUTOR-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN RUSSIA, SCANDAL AND INTRIGUE EMBOLDEN A YELTSIN FOE 
</HEADLINE>
  (wg) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Six weeks ago, Russia's top prosecutor, Yuri Skuratov,
handed in his resignation and disappeared from sight, causing a
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   As that scandal took on new and ominous dimensions on Wednesday,
Skuratov returned to view, twice. The first time was in the upper
house of parliament, where he suddenly announced that he planned to
stay in his job, in open defiance of President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   The second time was on a midnight television news program on a
government channel, where for a few minutes Skuratov, 46, appeared
as the star of a black-and-white videotape, naked and in bed with
two young women, also naked and neither his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The first scene rocked the uneasy political truce here, setting
the stage for another showdown between Yeltsin and his opposition,
which seems to be gathering strength daily. The second _ clearly
aimed at discrediting the Yeltsin opposition's latest hero _ sets a
new low for Russian politics, which long ago lost all ideological
luster and is now sinking deep into a mudbath.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two conclusions you can draw from this affair,''
said Pavel Voshchanov, a radio commentator and former press
secretary to Yeltsin. ``The first is that there are no politics in
Russia, only political intrigues. And the second is that everyone
has compromising material on everyone else, and usually, it is
true.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing before the council on Wednesday, Skuratov said that
before his resignation six weeks ago, he had been the target of a
blackmail attempt that he traced to political and financial figures
who, he said, fearing ongoing inquiries by the prosecutor's office,
had driven a wedge between him and Yeltsin. He did not say whom he
had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could almost feel that the activity of law-enforcement
agencies stuck in their throat like a bone, that we had stepped on
their sore spots, especially when it came to illegal privatization
and reorganization of enterprises into joint stock companies,
illegal banking activities, economic management, abuses by top
level officials,'' he told the council members.
</P>
<P>
   He vowed to press ahead with a series of potentially sensational
investigations _ into financial misdeeds at the Central Bank of
Russia, into illegal trading in government securities during last
summer's financial crisis, and into the blackmail attempt itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The information they obtained was obtained in violation of the
law, egregious violation of the law,'' Skuratov said, referring to
the video, adding that ``the way it has been used can also be
punishable.''
</P>
<P>
   As the day's remarkable events unfolded, it became clear that
this scandal _ unlike so many others in Russia _ could actually
have lasting consequences, above all for Yeltsin, who apparently
was caught off guard by Skuratov's abrupt about-face.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious political challenge for the ailing president
came from the normally loyal Federation Council, made up of
regional governors and administrators, which voted overwhelmingly
to back Skuratov, by 142-6, with 3 abstentions.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday evening, Yeltsin signaled that he would fight back,
saying through a spokesman that he would resubmit Skuratov's
resignation to the council, which under the constitution has the
sole authority to hire and fire Russia's top prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Kremlin spokesman Dmitri Yakushkin said Yeltsin _ who is in a
Moscow hospital recovering from a bleeding ulcer _ was ``very
uneasy about the unhealthy situation'' created by Skuratov's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   After summoning Prime Minister Yevgeni Primakov for an
unscheduled meeting earlier on Wednesday, Yeltsin and Primakov
issued a joint statement that pointedly praised the Federation
Council for its campaign against corruption, but challenged
Skuratov's moral authority to lead it.
</P>
<P>
   ``While fully supporting the efforts of the upper house of
parliament to combat crime and corruption, the president and prime
minister agreed that unscrupulousness and politicking are
incompatible with the high post of prosecutor general,'' Yeltsin's
press service said. ``Senators also realize that only morally
untainted persons can combat crime.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin's last word came during the late-night news program
when it aired the video. According to news reports that broke last
month, the video was taped more than a year ago in an apartment in
central Moscow belonging to a top employee of the prosecutor's
office with ties to shady bankers.
</P>
<P>
   Before airing the tape Wednesday night, the anchor advised that
the material _ which had already been shown on a television station
in Georgia _ was not suitable for viewers under 18 years old.
</P>
<P>
   If the video was meant to freeze Skuratov out of public life, it
failed, at least for now. ``When everyone is watched, their
pictures taken, watched through a key hole, taped etc, this is
disgusting to use such dirty, illegal methods,'' said Gov.
Amangeldy Tueleyv of Kemerovo.
</P>
<P>
   But there were also signs that the Federation Council was
already prepared to do battle with the Yeltsin government on other
issues. At its Wednesday session, the upper house of parliament
voted to lower Russia's value-added tax, rejecting pleas by the
government to delay the reduction, and to create a council that
would review television programs for their ``moral'' content _ a
measure seen by the Russian media as a first step on the road to
censorship.
</P>
<P>
   The news of the upper house's rebellion was greeted with
applause by the communist party-dominated opposition in the lower
house. Other deputies detected the telltale signs of a worsening
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   ``These developments are a sign of an approaching serious
political crisis because this decision is aimed, in essence,
against the president,'' said Sergei Ivanenko, a leader of the
liberal Yabloko faction, commenting on the Federation Council's
vote for Skuratov.
</P>
<P>
   Political observers were mostly struck by the audacity of
Skuratov's surprise announcement, which ended six weeks of studied
silence. His original resignation, made on Feb. 1, was never fully
explained: no one believed the official explanation that he was
quitting for health reasons.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement Wednesday to the Federation council, Skuratov
said that his resignation had been engineered by forces that were
worried about his office's investigations into ``dubious
operations'' in government securities. He named no names, but
sprinkled his text with tantalizing tips about parliamentary
deputies, ``two former vice prime ministers, former and incumbent
ministers and their deputies, some of the Central Bank's
high-ranking officials.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be sure that they did their best to create an
intolerable climate for the prosecutor general's office and me as
its head,'' he said. ``They have made sure that the president gets
the right word about me.''
</P>
<P>
   Skuratov did not name Boris Berezovsky, a tycoon whose
businesses are already under investigation, but by ticking off a
list of well-known Berezovsky-linked companies, he clearly meant to
imply that Berezovsky was behind the campaign to blackmail him.
``It became known during the investigation that they knew about my
coming resignation at least a month in advance,'' Skuratov said.
</P>
<P>
   As several observers noted, Skuratov is now in good position to
take revenge. ``We're facing a new political phenomenon in
Russia,'' noted Vladimir Ryzhkov, parliamentary leader of Our Home
is Russia, a centrist party, ``when the prosecutor general's
office, having received a vote of confidence at the Federation
Council, is becoming an absolutely politically independent organ
from the main branches of power, including the Federation Council
itself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
