<SLUG> BC-AMWEST-STRIKE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA WEST FLIGHT ATTEND ANTS BUOYED BY SALARY OFFER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER CORBETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As final contract negotiations began Wednesday,
America West Airlines flight attendants were buoyed by a salary
proposal from the airline that could bring their pay scale to
within 90 percent of Southwest Airline's.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may form the basis of a settlement,'' Bill McGlashen,
president of the Association of Flight Attendants Council 66, said
outside the offices of the National Mediation Board just before the
start of talks.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest's wage scale ranges from $15,500 to $44,000 per year,
according to the AFA. America West's current scale ranges from
about $12,000 to $22,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   America West Chairman William Franke disclosed the offer in a
letter Feb. 12 to each flight attendant.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, the union presented its latest offer, which
includes new provisions on salary and sick leave.
</P>
<P>
   The AFA's sick-leave proposal presented Wednesday clarifies a
policy that had previously been agreed to in general terms,
McGlashen said. No details were available about the salary
provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Johnson, senior vice president for corporate affairs,
said America West had not seen the AFA's offer and would not
comment on the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Franke's letter to the flight attendants outlines the company's
$68.7 million proposal, which is $15.2 million above a tentative
agreement that flight attendants rejected in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The union's latest offer is valued at $85.3 million, according
to McGlashen.
</P>
<P>
   The company is offering starting pay of $16.13 per hour, up to
$34.59 after 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The AFA is willing to accept starting pay of just over $15 per
hour, but wants the top pay increased to nearly $40 per hour. About
75 percent of the flight attendants are at the top of the pay
scale.
</P>
<P>
   America West, the ninth-largest carrier, says it cannot meet the
flight attendants' wage demands because its revenues are only 78
percent of the average revenue of the combined major carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our other work groups, both union and non-union, as well as
our management employees, are paid on a basis consistent with our
revenues,'' said Anthony Mule, vice president of inflight services,
in a March 10 letter to flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue is travel expenses or per diem for the flight
attendants. Union members want $1.80 per hour for overnight trips,
while the company is offering $1.30 initially. That would increase
to $1.50 after 30 months and to $1.75 at the end of the five-year
contract.
</P>
<P>
   America West's proposal would increase total compensation _
salary and travel expenses _ on average 20.8 percent or $5,434 the
first year and 44.7 percent or $11,438 in the fifth year of the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The company and union negotiators went to Washington in good
faith to make a deal, according to Johnson, adding that he is
hopeful there will be an agreement by late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators for Tempe-based America West and the AFA have less
48 than hours to resolve their dispute over an initial contract for
the flight attendants, who organized in 1994. Talks on the latest
contract began last spring.
</P>
<P>
   A strike deadline of 10:01 p.m. Friday (Arizona time) is hanging
over negotiators, with both sides saying they hope to head off a
shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   If a settlement is not reached, AFA will consider filing a
complaint against America West management for illegal ``direct
dealing'' with the flight attendants through letters and possible
conversations with Negotiating Committee members outside of
negotiations, the AFA said in a statement, adding that the company
is bound by law to deal with the flight attendants' representative,
which is AFA.
</P>
<P>
   McGlashen said the AFA is prepared to strike if there's no deal.
</P>
<P>
   A strike tactic called CHAOS _ Create Havoc Around Our System _
will target selected flights at the last minute to disrupt the
airline.
</P>
<P>
   America West says it might shut down entirely if CHAOS causes
too much disruption.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves travelers wondering whether they will be stranded
and other America West workers worried that they will be forced to
go without a paycheck if the carrier follows through on its threat
to close.
</P>
<P>
   Short of an agreement, a very busy spring travel season in
Arizona will be crippled by a work stoppage.
</P>
<P>
   America West carries about 40 percent of the travelers using Sky
Harbor International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Union members are not concerned that they will alienate America
West passengers if there is a strike, McGlashen said, adding that
travelers have been supportive of the flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   Talks are expected to continue today and Friday at the National
Mediation Board offices in Washington. &QL; 
Peter Corbett can be reached at 444-4815 or at
peter.corbett(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
