r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAMES-SFCHRON &LR;      03-17 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Sega Talks a Good Game at Conference
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Benny Evangelista &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Sega of America is dreaming big about selling consumers its new
Dreamcast gaming console later this year, but still has a way to go
to convince skeptical game developers to create titles for it.
</P>
<P>
   Attendees at the 13th Annual Game Developers Conference in San
Jose yesterday gave Sega of America President Bernard Stolar only
lukewarm applause when he flexed some of Dreamcast's advanced video
game muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Game developers say they aren't convinced Sega can beat market
leaders Sony and Nintendo. Current game devices cost about $130 and
connect to a TV for display; next-generation devices are expected
to be more than $200.
</P>
<P>
   Some developers said they were delaying plans for Dreamcast
games to learn more about market leader Sony Corp.'s competing
PlayStation II.
</P>
<P>
   Sega's Dreamcast, which features better graphics and Internet
connectivity, is due out in the United States this fall, giving it
a full year's head start on the new Sony machine, which is coming
in fall 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But Sony, with 50 million users worldwide _ 17 million of them
in the United States _ for its current PlayStation, has a huge,
fanatical market primed for its new machine.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 2 player, Nintendo 64, has sold almost 20 million units
worldwide, 11 million of them in the United States. Sega's two
previous consoles, the Saturn and Genesis, never achieved that kind
of popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Lane Kiriyama, chief financial officer of Saffire Corp., a game
developer in Utah, said Sony's announcement of a PlayStation II has
stopped his firm's Dreamcast development projects ``in their
tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now (game publishers) are saying `Put it on hold, we want to
do the PlayStation,''' Kiriyama said.
</P>
<P>
   Another game company executive said game-makers are reluctant to
commit to Sega because of the current PlayStation's dominance in
the market, the greater marketing muscle of both Sony and Nintendo,
and Sega's past failures with two other platforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``With game development costs as high as they are, if you're a
game developer, are you going to bet on the guy who's coming from
the back or the guy who's got the front seat right now?'' said the
executive, who did not want to be identified because his firm works
with all three console makers.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said this year's conference is particularly important
to both Sony and Sega because game developers are starting to make
decisions about games that won't appear on store shelves for 18
months or more.
</P>
<P>
   Sega does have some big-name players that have pledged support
for Dreamcast, including Acclaim, Accolade, Capcom, GT Interactive,
Hasbro Interactive and Midway.
</P>
<P>
   And Stoler said during his keynote speech that about 100
companies worldwide are working on Dreamcast games. Titles like
Mortal Kombat 5, Ready to Rumble and PowerStone will be available
when Dreamcast, already on sale in Japan, makes its U.S. debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sega is going to take back market share from Sony and Nintendo
with Dreamcast,'' Stoler said. ``Dreamcast is a platform that will
change more than a few minds. Like they say in the movies, `Hold on
folks, you ain't seen nothing yet.' We're dreaming big and we're
delivering big.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hindorf, vice president of product development for Midway's
Atari Games division in Milpitas, which is creating Mortal Kombat
5, said he is impressed by what he has seen so far of the Dreamcast
and Sega's plans for better technical support for game developers
than it offered in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Sega may have an advantage because its new platform is already
on sale in Japan, while Sony's is still only in the pipeline, but
``the smart publishers are going to place bets on as many machines
as possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No. 2 Nintendo also plans a competing next-generation console
dubbed the Nintendo 2000, but is content to let Sega and Sony slug
it out first.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a company that focuses on the present,'' said Perrin
Kaplan, corporate affairs director for Nintendo of America Inc.
Thanks to sales of hits like The Legend of Zelda: Ocarina of Time,
the Nintendo 64 has sold nearly 11 million units in the U.S. since
its launch in September 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Nintendo plans to spend $250 million on marketing the N64 this
year, more than double the $100 million Sega has budgeted to pitch
the Dreamcast. Sony's marketing expenses were not available.
</P>
<P>
   Nintendo has done well in handheld devices, selling more than 2
million units of the new color version of its 10-year-old Game Boy
in less than a year. &UR;  &LR; Kaplan said Nintendo in May will start
selling new Game Boy Colors in six colorful cases _ teal,
tangerine, berry, kiwi, grape and transparent grape.
</P>
<P>
   Sony officials have maintained a low-key profile so far at the
conference, but Sony Computer Entertainment of America Vice
President Phil Harrison is expected to reveal more details of the
new PlayStation II during a keynote speech this morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
