<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Motorola adds concierge, child care to entice workers
 &HT;    By Lori Hawkins
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It's about to get a lot easier for Motorola Inc.
workers to cross items off their to-do lists.
</P>
<P>
   The company, for its part, hopes a new program called Etc. will
help it keep workers and attract new ones in Austin's tight job
market.
</P>
<P>
   Etc. is designed to handle the time-consuming errands that eat
up lunch hour and stress out folks trying to balance work and
family. Motorola is Austin's second-biggest (behind Dell Computer
Corp.) private sector employer with 10,000 workers in its local
semiconductor operations.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, Motorola will open child development centers at its
Ed Bluestein and Oak Hill campuses that will care for 400 children
from 6 weeks to 6 years old at what the company says will be a
``competitive cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting in July, a concierge service will charge $5 an hour to
walk dogs, run errands, grocery shop and mail packages, and handle
car service, dry cleaning and gift buying.
</P>
<P>
   And it is adding activity centers with offerings including
exercise equipment, personal trainers, kick boxing and yoga
classes, and massages. Monthly memberships for employees and
spouses will cost $20 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The company is pumping up its perks because of the intense
competition for workers in Austin, where the jobless rate was 2.7
percent in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Austin's unemployment rate is so low that it takes a heck of
lot more than a paycheck to lure employees,'' says Sandi Aitken,
manager of Premiere Services at Motorola Austin. ``People here have
an opportunity to choose from a variety of employers, and in
addition to compensation and leading edge technology, employees
value perks.''
</P>
<P>
   Motorola's program is an example of how chronic labor shortages
in fields such as computers and finance are forcing companies to
get creative with benefits. Many are offering CEO-style perks to
rank and file employees in an effort to attract and keep talent.
</P>
<P>
   Other Austin companies are also competing with perks. First USA,
which has more than 1,200 employees in Austin, has a fitness
center, a basketball court, a sand volleyball pit and a jogging
trail. Plans are in the works to add a concierge desk this year.
</P>
<P>
   Etc. will be offered in Austin and in Phoenix, where Motorola
also has extensive chip operations.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which is still struggling for profitability in its
chip business, is subsidizing the offerings, but declines to
disclose how much it is investing on concierge services or on the
new fitness and child-care centers.
</P>
<P>
   The child-care centers, scheduled to open in the fall, will be
operated by Bright Horizons Family Solutions, a corporate
child-care provider with offices in Boston and Nashville. The
centers will have slots for children from families who don't work
at Motorola.
</P>
<P>
   The Oak Hill center will be 15,000 square feet and will take 225
children: 175 from Motorola and 50 from the community. The Ed
Bluestein site will be 11,000 square feet and will care for 175
children, 125 of them from Motorola.
</P>
<P>
   Etc. is the result of 18 months of brainstorming by a group of
senior level employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we were aiming for is peace of mind with what's going on
with your family, and having more time to focus on the things that
are meaningful to you,'' Aitken says. ``We think we succeeded.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
