<HEADER>
A4522 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAIN-CRASH-700&AMP;ADD-N     03-17 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAIN-CRASH-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAIN CRASH INQUIRY FOCUSES ON TIRE TRACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Miss., La.)  (See also TRAIN-VICTIMS) 
(mk) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Federal safety investigators on Wednesday began trying
to identify the source of a set of tire tracks inside the crossing
gate at the site of a deadly crash between an Amtrak train and a
semi-trailer truck Monday night in Bourbonnais, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   The tracks ``would indicate somebody tried to go around the
gates,'' said John Goglia, a member of the National Transportation
Safety Board. Investigators were trying to determine whether the
tracks matched those of the truck, which would suggest that the
truck driver had tried to cross the tracks after being warned that
the train was coming.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, at the exact time the crash occurred,
investigators were using another locomotive and truck in the
positions of the vehicles to determine when and if the truck driver
could have seen the oncoming train.
</P>
<P>
   As the investigation continued, forensic pathologists were
trying to determine how many people had died, and who they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were all mangled and burned,'' said Bill Cotter, a deputy
coroner with the Kankakee County coroner's office. ``They are so
badly damaged there is no way we can visually identify the bodies
that we do have.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, National Transportation Safety Board officials
said that 13 people were dead and that three or four others were
missing. On Wednesday they said the number of dead had been lowered
to 11. Based on updated Amtrak figures that indicated only 11
people on the train were unaccounted for, the officials said they
believed there were no others missing. Amtrak officials said they
originally thought that 13 people were unaccounted for but
discovered that two of those people had walked away from the crash.
</P>
<P>
   But officials from the coroner's office said they still did not
know how many people died and they criticized the safety board for
releasing any figures. Cotter said he believed the confusion might
have arisen because the coroner's office had 13 body bags, although
it was not clear that that meant there were 13 bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have body bags, but some of the body bags may contain body
parts,'' Cotter said. ``And they may contain other body parts from
the people who survived the wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   A federal team of 20 forensic pathologists, forensic dentists
and FBI fingerprint experts drove in from Washington Wednesday with
a van packed with equipment and began working in a makeshift morgue
in an abandoned lumber company.
</P>
<P>
   They were gathering dental and medical records from families of
the missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since most of the people are out of this area, this is going
to take some time,'' Cotter said. ``We've got dental records coming
from Mississippi and all over the United States, and Japan, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those presumed dead, according to relatives, were three
young girls and the grandmother of one of the girls, who were
returning home to Nesbit, Miss., after a trip to Chicago to see the
aquarium and shop at the American Girl doll store. They were
traveling with two children and two adults, some of whom were
injured. One of the relatives, Max Bonnin, who believes his wife
and granddaughter are among the dead, said Wednesday that the
confusion about the number of victims has been frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   Cotter said each family was assigned a representative from the
coroner's office and a local minister to help them through the
ordeal of waiting. He said the coroner, James Orrison, has been
meeting with the families twice a day.
</P>
<P>
   The train, the City of New Orleans, left Chicago shortly after 8
p.m. Monday bound for New Orleans. Traveling 79 mph, it struck the
truck, which was packed full of heavy steel bars from a nearby
steel plant, at a railroad crossing in Bourbonnais, a rural
community about 55 miles south of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The crash crumpled the train's two locomotives and the first
three of its 14 cars, smashing them together like an accordion. One
car flipped on its side and another, a double-decker sleeper car,
crashed into a locomotive, split in half and caught fire, burning
the passengers inside. Officials said Wednesday that all of the
dead were in the sleeper car.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 216 passengers and crew on board, 116 were injured, 49 of
them hospitalized.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The truck was heading east across the tracks and was driven by
John Stokes, 58, of Manteno, Ill., who was using a probationary
permit after his license had been suspended because of speeding
tickets. Stokes, who could not be reached for comment, was treated
and released.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators said the gates, signal lights and bells at
the crossing were all functioning properly and started warning of
the oncoming train 27 seconds before it reached the crossing. They
said the train was blowing its whistle and had slammed on the
emergency brake.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators were planning to re-interview the truck driver,
who said he did not see the train or the warning lights until he
had started driving across the tracks and that the gates closed
before he could get out of the path of the train.
</P>
<P>
   They also wanted to re-interview the engineer, who was
hospitalized after the accident, and on medication that officials
said impaired him from giving a thorough account. In early
interviews, the engineer reportedly told investigators that he saw
the truck try to get around the gates as they were closing.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Illinois Central Railroad, which operates the
crossing, said it would not have been possible for the truck to
start crossing the tracks before the gates began to close and then
become trapped by the gates, because the gates would have hit the
truck and broken.
</P>
<P>
   Goglia said Wednesday that the truck driver tested below the
legal limit on a Breathalyzer test. He said the results of a urine
and blood test were not yet available. The truck was not carrying
more than the legal weight limit of steel.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Highway Administration and the Illinois state police
began an audit Wednesday of the training, staffing and
safety-compliance records of the company Stokes was driving for,
Melco Transfer of Peotone, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Officials reopened the track Wednesday, allowing trains to
proceed at no more than 10 mph, for now.
</P>
<P>
   And they bused some of the relatives of the victims into the
accident site, where, amid the twisted metal, they created a
makeshift memorial: a pyramid of hay bales, potted flower
arrangements, roses and a wreath.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
