<SLUG> BC-BOX-EVANDER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holyfield regrets his prediction
 &HT;    By Jeff Schult
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Evander Holyfield apologized Wednesday for predicting
a third-round knockout over Lennox Lewis and reiterated his desire
for a rematch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was wrong by even saying that, even though I felt I would
take him out in three rounds,'' Holyfield said in his first
interview since Saturday night, following a disputed draw with
Lewis in New York. ``By saying that, I made it hard, and I refused
to turn from it. I apologize for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield said he watched a tape of the fight Sunday, but when
asked how he scored it, he said, ``I never took a pen to it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both champions,'' Holyfield said, referring to his WBA
and IBF belts and Lewis's WBC title. ``I could see why the judges
thought neither one of us took the fight from the other guy. The
judges said it's a draw. Realistically, he didn't knock me out, and
I didn't knock him out. It's all based on a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with the punch stats, people say, `Well, this man hit you
600 times.' But if he hit me that much, why didn't I fall? How come
I was never staggered or hurt? Obviously, because a lot of times he
was tapping me. Why? Because I was trying to get him to get close
to me so that I could nail him with a big shot. But it didn't work.
When boxers don't do what they're supposed to do, it falls into the
judges' hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time (Lewis) didn' get a decision. His whole
thing was to let it go to the scorecards. My thing is I never want
it to go to the scorecards. It never works out for me. People say,
`But you didn't raise your hands after the fight, and Lennox raised
his hands.' But even when I knock people out, I don't raise my
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he could see why most people felt he was outpointed,
Holyfield reiterated, ``When I watch a fight, I'm watching to see
what mistakes I made, to get something out of it. If I start
scoring it, I'd start looking for why I thought I won instead of
getting something out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield spoke on a variety subjects, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ His health. He confirmed remarks from his attorney Jim Thomas,
who said that he did not feel well immediately before the fight and
that it was a ``difficult camp,'' alluding to a virus and other
ailments, including leg cramps during the bout. Holyfield was
examined by physician Christopher Vaughns on Wednesday and might
see an endocrinologist.
</P>
<P>
   _ Conclusions that he ``grew old'' in this fight. ``Those are
just excuses. I'm 36. I don't know why people want me to be old.
Things happen. But when things happen, I don't go looking for
excuses. Lennox fought a good fight.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Whether the prediction of a third-round KO was a distraction.
``No, I had a game plan. Unfortunately, the cramps in my legs
prevented me from taking those steps away from his jab. Boxing is
all about position. In one sense, (the prediction) helped me
because I felt real bad before the fight, but I was thinking,
`Shoot, it'll be a short night, so let me get in there.' When it
didn't happen, I thought, `Well, Lord, I was wrong.' God wasn't
wrong. I was wrong _ and now that I know I'm wrong, Lord help me.
... (But) I truly believe (Lewis) was scared in the third round.
When I hit him with some big shots, his eyes got big.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The rematch. ``He can't beat me the same way. Don't think that
I'm going to come back and be the same. What he did was very
effective. I've got the bruises to show that he was effective. I
got punished enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield said he is ``willing to be flexible'' in negotiations
and fight for a lower guarantee than the $20 million he earned
Saturday. He also said he wrote letters to his trainers and camp
members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted them to know how appreciative I was for this last
camp, and how important it was that we stay together,'' Holyfield
said. ``Sometimes when things don't go well, a fighter fires
everybody. I wanted them to know I'm not putting the blame on
anybody.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
