<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Robinson's future in doubt
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Coach Dan Reeves conceded here Wednesday that it is
``a possibility'' free safety Eugene Robinson might not be back
with the Falcons in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But Reeves said no decision has been made and emphasized that
the decision will have nothing to do with the 14-year veteran's
arrest the night before Super Bowl XXXIV on charges of soliciting
oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he is not back with us,'' Reeves said during the annual
coaches' breakfast with the media, ``it won't have anything to do
with that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves was asked frequently about Robinson during the one-hour
session and allowed that, while originally angered by the incident,
he quickly became more concerned on Super Bowl eve with Robinson
and his family. He said he left the decision on whether to play
Robinson to the player himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was I disappointed?'' Reeves said. ``Sure. But not every
response is done by anger. My immediate reaction was what could I
do to get Eugene through this. I don't really know that Eugene
understands why it happened. All of us have done something in our
lives where we have looked back and said, `Why did I do that?' ''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of last week's acquisition of unrestricted free
agent strong safety Marty Carter, there have been rumors that
Robinson's release is imminent. Reeves noted during an afternoon
interview that the two men play different positions. He said,
though, that the size of Carter's contract _ a five-year, $15
million deal with a $1.42 million salary cap figure for 1999 _
might force the club to make some adjustments to fill other needs.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson is entering the final season of a two-year, $3.55
million contract. His salary cap figure for 1999 is $2.3 million,
and the Falcons will be rebated $1.8 million if he is released.
Reeves said cornerback Ronnie Bradford, re-signed to a four-year
deal for $7 million, could possibly be used at free safety. ``We
re-signed Ronnie with the intent he might play there,'' Reeves
said.
</P>
<P>
   BRIEFLY ...
</P>
<P>
   New York financier Howard Milstein, whose bid to purchase the
Redskins would not have been approved had it come to a vote, was
granted an extension to allow him time to address issues raised by
the Finance Committee. ... Owners passed a rule change that makes
it illegal for blockers to clip defensive linemen between the
tackles and in a 3-yard area on either side of the line of
scrimmage. Falcons defensive end Chuck Smith was among the players
who pushed for the change. ... Seattle is close to a trade to
acquire backup quarterback Glenn Foley from the New York Jets. ...
New Orleans coach Mike Ditka offered all of his '99 picks to
Philadelphia for the second overall choice in the draft. Ditka has
targeted Heisman tailback Ricky Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
