<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFL-OWNERS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Mood right' to OK replay
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ It may have been a mid-February suggestion by
commissioner Paul Tagliabue _ one that permits the league's coaches
to concentrate on game action in the final two minutes of each half
instead of some officiating injustice _ that spurred the
resurrection of instant replay for the 1999 NFL season.
</P>
<P>
   More likely, however, it was a '98 campaign marred by frequent
officiating gaffes that prompted owners on Wednesday to haul the
sideline monitors out of mothballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mood,'' acknowledged Seattle coach Mike Holmgren,
co-chairman of the Competition Committee, ``was right. We had to do
this thing now.''
</P>
<P>
   Following several controversial officiating errors last season,
the mood actually was ugly. With public confidence in the officials
ebbing after highly publicized decisions in some late-season games,
the NFL was left with very little recourse. So heightened was the
need for replay that seven franchises that voted against it in '98
voted to approve it Wednesday. Even the staunchest proponents said
they were surprised by the overwhelming 28-3 vote to afford replay
another chance.
</P>
<P>
   The three teams that voted against replay were Cincinnati,
Arizona and the New York Jets. The Bengals and Cardinals have voted
against replay every time it's been brought before the membership,
dating back to 1986. Among the owners who changed their votes was
Ralph Wilson of Buffalo, who traditionally has opposed replay but
whose team was victimized by poor calls in at least two games in
'98.
</P>
<P>
   Approval of the system is for 1999 only and it will be revisited
next spring.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most vocal replay supporters has been Falcons coach
Dan Reeves, and he was pleased by Wednesday's lopsided vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just never want to lose a game on a play everyone clearly
sees as wrong,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that the new system is being implemented to correct
glaring errors at key junctures of a game was one espoused by
Holmgren, committee co-chairman Rich McKay and director of
officiating Jerry Seeman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't going to correct every (bad) call and it's not
designed to do that,'' said McKay, general manager of the Tampa Bay
Buccaneers. ``It's really meant to correct the huge oversight or
official's error.''
</P>
<P>
   The system affords coaches two ``challenges'' per game. If the
original call is upheld, a challenging team will be charged with a
timeout. In the final two minutes of a half a review may be
triggered only by a replay assistant in a booth above field level.
Plays that fall under the purview of replay include sideline, end
zone and possession calls.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 2124EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0457 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4526 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-LOWSCORES18-COX     03-17 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LOWSCORES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Amid game's flash, scoring slows
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ College basketball owns March: Everyone
from your accountant to your grandmother to your favorite zoologist
has filled out an NCAA Tournament bracket.
</P>
<P>
   But beneath the surface exist real concerns that the game is in
trouble. Somewhere along the line, college basketball teams have
forgotten how to score. Like it or not, scoring sells tickets and
turns on television sets.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few symptoms of the offensive drought:
</P>
<P>
   _ Eight years ago, Division I college basketball teams averaged
76.7 points per game during the regular season. This season, that
figure was down to 70.5.
</P>
<P>
   _ The average shooting percentage per team, which was 47.3 in
1989, has dropped to 43.7.
</P>
<P>
   _ In last week's 48 NCAA Tournament games, 28 teams scored fewer
than 60 points, twice as many teams as in the first two rounds in
1998. In the six games of the Charlotte site in the East, eight of
the 12 teams shot under 40 percent. Four shot under 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wisconsin was held to an NCAA Tournament low 32 points after
shooting 25.5 percent against Southwest Missouri State. The
Badgers' football team scored more points in the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm embarrassed,'' coach Dick Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   The guardians of the game are more than embarrassed. With
television ratings down for this tournament, they are worried that
the game could be in a decline and are wondering if anything can be
done about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It needs some tinkering,'' former Providence coach Dave Gavitt
told the Washington Post earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Logically, scoring should not be down. College basketball has a
short three-point line, at 19 feet, 9 inches; a lot of TV timeouts
that keep players fresh; and a 35-second shot clock to keep things
moving. Those rules changes were put in for the 1986-87 season in
an attempt to generate more offense.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened? The reasons for the decline in scoring are
many, but here are the most common ones, according to coaches and
basketball analysts:
</P>
<P>
   _ The SportsCenter Syndrome. Players no longer work on or have
the discipline for the finer points of the game _ passing, cutting,
screening _ that create high-percentage shots. The plays that make
the TV highlights are dunks and long 3-point shots. The
medium-range jump shot is in decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kind of hard to blame a guy for passing up the 15-footer when
he can take one big step back and get three,'' said Steve Alford,
the head coach at Southwest Missouri State.
</P>
<P>
   _ Defensive domination. Coaches have learned to control the game
with a sophisticated combination of defenses played by bigger and
faster athletes. Where college basketball once was a finesse game,
a player strolling uncontested down the lane now is more likely to
end up in the seats. Every shot, every pass, every movement on the
floor is contested. Coaches encourage the physical play on the
theory that the officials can't call everything.
</P>
<P>
   _ Talent drain. Early defections to the NBA are starting to take
their toll on the quality of play. The ACC, for example, should
have had a senior class of 29 this season. Instead, there were 12
seniors playing meaningful roles on the nine ACC teams.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Krzyzewski, who won national championships in 1991 and 1992
with senior-oriented teams, has never had a player leave early for
the pros in 19 seasons as Duke's coach. That could change this year
with talented sophomores William Avery and Elton Brand. Krzyzewski
says it is something college basketball will have to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be very difficult to have the great, old
experienced teams again,'' Krzyzewski said. ``My '92 team knew
everything. They were juniors and seniors and talented sophomores.
I'm not sure you'll get it at that level any more.''
</P>
<P>
   While the departure of talent might continue, basketball can
make changes to open up the game and make it less physical, coaches
say.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-point line, for example, could be moved out at least a
foot. That move would bring back the medium-range jumper, a
higher-percentage shot, and open up the inside, because perimeter
defenders would have a tougher time dropping back to help.
</P>
<P>
   The three-second lane could be widened at the base, as is the
case in international basketball. That would bring the big guys
farther from the basket and create passing and driving lanes.
</P>
<P>
   Some people have talked about shortening the shot clock, because
coaches, particularly at tournament time, have become adept at
milking it to reduce the number of possessions in a game.
</P>
<P>
   If the basketball powers are smart, they will make some changes
soon, because the players are not having a whole lot of fun with
the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys get tight in the tournament, because it's one game and
out, but they really like to run and shoot and have fun,'' Duke's
Chris Carrawell said. ``Players don't like grabbing and holding and
banging.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
