<SLUG> BC-BKC-PRICE-COACH18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Price joins Georgia Tech staff
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With his second losing season in three years in the
books, Bobby Cremins has taken some steps that should bolster his
coaching staff and improve Georgia Tech's overall appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Former All-NBA guard Mark Price, who played for Cremins at Tech
from 1983-86, is joining the Yellow Jackets coaching staff as an
assistant coach. Price, who retired in February from the NBA, will
join Cremins' staff immediately as an assistant coach in a
nonrecruiting capacity.
</P>
<P>
   In related moves, Frank Beall, who held the title of director of
basketball operations, is leaving Tech to go into private business
and present assistant coach Gary Leiner will assume Beall's
noncoaching duties. Price will likely assume Leiner's current role.
</P>
<P>
   Unrelated to Price's hiring, assistant coach Dereck Whittenburg
has interviewed for the head coaching job at the University of
North Carolina-Greensboro, and it has been reported that East
Carolina also is interested in talking to the former N.C. State
star. Whittenburg's status on the Tech staff is unaffected by the
hiring of Price.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since Mark retired, he's been thinking about getting into
coaching,'' said Cremins. ``The opportunity to have him on our
staff is just tremendous for us. Mark will be heavily involved in
individual player development and all aspects of coaching. He has
my utmost respect as a person and as a player.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a thrill to be able to come back to my alma mater and be
a part of (Cremins') coaching staff,'' Price said from his home in
Duluth. ``I feel I can be an asset in the development of the
players. I look forward to helping in any way I can.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
