A4528 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-SOUTH-CAPSULES18-     03-17 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SOUTH-CAPSULES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South Regional scouting report
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   AUBURN VS. OHIO STATE
</P>
<P>
   When; where: 9:55 p.m. today; Thompson-Boling Arena, Knoxville.
</P>
<P>
   TV: CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Records: Auburn 29-3, Ohio State 25-8.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches: Cliff Ellis is 96-58 in five seasons at Auburn, 444-270
overall; Jim O'Brien is 33-30 in two seasons at Ohio State, 268-247
overall.
</P>
<P>
   How they got here: Auburn, the top seed, routed Winthrop 81-42
in the first round, then held off Oklahoma State 81-74 in the
second round. Ohio State, the fourth seed, beat Murray State 72-58
in the first round, then beat Detroit 75-44 in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Probable lineups: Auburn _ guards, Doc Robinson (6-2, jr., 11.3
ppg) and Scott Pohlman (6-2, so., 12.3 ppg); center, Mamadou
N'diaye (7-0, jr., 7.4 ppg); forwards, Chris Porter (6-7, jr., 16.2
ppg) and Bryant Smith (6-5, sr., 10.8 ppg). Ohio State _ guards,
Scoonie Penn (5-10, jr., 16.7 ppg) and Brian Brown (6-3, fr., 3.9
ppg); center, Ken Johnson (6-11, jr., 6.3 ppg); forwards, Michael
Redd (6-6, so., 19.7 ppg) and Jason Singleton (6-5, sr., 8.8 ppg).
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Both teams have had major turnarounds this season,
Auburn improving from 16 wins to 29 and Ohio State from eight to
25. Auburn's seven-point victory over Oklahoma State was just the
Tigers' third single-digit win all season. Their full-court game,
trapping defense and offensive-rebounding ability are major
concerns for Ohio State. Auburn had 242 more offensive boards than
its opponents and an overall rebounding count of 44.1-34.8. Ohio
State, with point guard Scoonie Penn, will try to slow down the
Tigers, and forward Jason Singleton must keep Chris Porter, the SEC
Player of the Year, off the offensive glass. The Buckeyes played
terrific defense in the first two rounds, holding Murray State to
27.3 per cent shooting and Detroit to 30.8. But Auburn should prove
far tougher.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Auburn 79-72.
</P>
<P>
   MARYLAND VS. ST. JOHN'S
</P>
<P>
   When; where: 7:38 p.m. today; Thompson-Boling Arena, Knoxville.
</P>
<P>
   TV/radio: CBS; WQXI (790 AM).
</P>
<P>
   Records: Maryland 28-5, St. John's 27-8.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches: Gary Williams is 192-117 in 10 seasons at Maryland,
399-244 overall; Mike Jarvis is 27-8 in his first season at St.
John's, 280-149 overall.
</P>
<P>
   How they got here: Maryland, the second seed, defeated
Valparaiso 82-60 in the first round, then eliminated Creighton
75-63. St. John's, the third seed, crushed Samford 69-43 in the
first round, then gave Indiana its worst NCAA Tournament loss,
86-61.
</P>
<P>
   Probable lineups: Maryland _ guards, Steve Francis (6-3, jr.,
16.6 ppg) and Terrell Stokes (6-0, sr., 6.5 ppg); center, Lonny
Baxter (6-8, fr., 6.1 ppg); forwards Terence Morris (6-9, so., 15.8
ppg) and Laron Profit (6-5, sr., 14.8 ppg). St. John's _ guards,
Erick Barkley (6-1, fr., 13.2 ppg) and Bootsy Thornton (6-4, jr.,
14.7 ppg); center, Tyrone Grant (6-7, sr., 10.8 ppg); forwards, Ron
Artest (6-7, so., 14.8 ppg) and Lavor Postell (6-6, jr., 12.9 ppg).
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Potentially, this could be the most exciting game of
the tournament thus far. The teams are talented and explosive, with
an array of scorers, each coming off two solids wins in Orlando.
The Terps want to run, especially when the aerodynamic Francis can
get the ball in transition or on lobs to the hoop. He might be the
college game's only leaper to rival Chris Porter. Maryland also has
played tough defense the first two rounds, limiting Valparaiso to
35.6 per cent shooting and Creighton 34.4. Although St. John's has
the ability to run with the Terps, the Johnnies are better suited
to a half-court game against a club averaging 85.2 points. Look for
the Red Storm to use the 2-3 zone Mike Jarvis employed after
Indiana took a 15-9 lead against the St. John's man-to-man defense.
The Johnnies moved the ball beautifully against the Hoosiers.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Maryland 82-80.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
