<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SOUTHADVANCE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Top seeds remain in South Regional
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ Up here in the Smokies sits an oasis of
sanity in the madness that is March. No demon seeds are left. Let
the other three sites salute those wacky college kids from
Southwest Missouri State, Miami of Ohio and Gonzaga. This is the
only place that offers some semblance of order on the court in the
NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   That, and much more.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the South Regional, it is almost like a Final
Four,'' said Auburn coach Cliff Ellis, whose top-seeded Tigers meet
No. 4 Ohio State tonight in the regional semifinals, following the
opener between No. 2 Maryland and No. 3 St. John's. Of the four
regions, only the South had all four top seeds reach the Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duke's not here, and let's assume they're going to be there
(in the Final Four),'' Ellis said. ``Any one of these teams could
be there. This is the one region that has really proven to be
strong, and whoever comes out of here is going to be a great
representative.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at this region and the four teams that are here,
you're looking at not good basketball teams but great basketball
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Four great teams with an aggregate record of 109-24, who won
their eight first- and second-round games by an average margin of
22 points. Only one victory _ Auburn's 81-74 win over Oklahoma
State on Saturday _ was a single-digit affair. Although all four
top seeds are still alive, only one other region _ the Midwest,
with No. 1 Michigan State and No. 3 Kentucky _ has more than one of
its top four remaining. Here in the deep South, in the upper
left-hand corner of your NCAA brackets, favoritism is not a dirty
word.
</P>
<P>
   ``This regional is a little different. Every team that was
supposed to make the Sweet 16 made it,'' St. John's forward Ron
Artest said. Artest was limping in practice Wednesday because he
got sick after supper Tuesday night, tripped over his roommate's
bed trying to make it to the bathroom and hurt a foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of upsets in the other regionals,'' said
Artest, one of five St. John's starters who scored in double
figures in Saturday's 86-61 humbling of Indiana. ``This regional is
probably a little more competitive. People know they can't slack
up. The games here are going to be real hard, and we have to fight
fatigue or anything else to win.''
</P>
<P>
   That's if the Johnnies are to prolong what first-year coach Mike
Jarvis calls ``a fantastic journey.''
</P>
<P>
   St. John's, seeking its first Final Four appearance since 1985,
must contend with quicksilver Maryland, which is in its third Sweet
16 in a row and is two wins away from the school's first Final
Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told everyone when the brackets first came out our region
was the toughest and most exciting,'' Terps forward Laron Profit
said. ``It's proven out. If you look at the four teams, they're all
very similar. They're all very athletic. All have great guard play.
All put defensive pressure on you.''
</P>
<P>
   And all four are here on merit. ``The four teams that are seeded
(highest) here really played well,'' Maryland coach Gary Williams
said. ``In some other regions, the top seeds didn't play well.
Nobody (here) really had a bad game in those first four seeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Including Ohio State, which staggered through an 8-22 death
march last season. But guard Scoonie Penn, who sat out last season
after transferring from Boston College, predicted at the start of
this season that the Buckeyes would make the NCAAs. ``I thought he
was off the wall,'' said Jim O'Brien, the coach Penn followed from
B.C. to Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   Now Ohio State is nearly off the charts with Scoonie. A 17-win
improvement has the Buckeyes 25-8, which, even so, is the worst
record of the four teams here. Not that seeds or records matter
now, O'Brien said. ``If you get a chance to win this game, it puts
you one game away from the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
