<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    West Regional scouting report
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   GONZAGA VS. FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   When, where: 7:55 p.m. today; America West Arena, Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   TV: CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Records: Gonzaga 27-6, Florida 22-8.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches: Don Monson is 51-16 in two seasons at Gonzaga. Billy
Donovan is 48-40 in three seasons at Florida and 83-60 overall.
</P>
<P>
   How they got here: Gonzaga upset seventh-seeded Minnesota 75-63
in the first round and second-seed Stanford 82-74 in the second.
Florida defeated Pennsylvania 75-61 in the first round and beat
Weber State 82-74 in overtime in Round 2.
</P>
<P>
   Probable lineups: Gonzaga _ guards, Quentin Hall (5-8, sr., 11.4
ppg) and Matt Santangelo (6-1, jr., 12.7 ppg); center, Jeremy Eaton
(6-11, sr., 12.1 ppg); forwards, Richie Frahm (6-5, jr., 14.2 ppg)
and Casey Calvary (6-8, so., 9.4 ppg). Florida _ guards, Eddie
Shannon (5-11, sr., 6.8 ppg) and Kenyan Weaks (6-4, jr., 11.4 ppg);
forwards, Greg Stolt (6-9, sr., 10.3 ppg), Major Parker (6-4, so.,
5.2 ppg) and Brent Wright (6-8, so., 8.0 ppg).
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Florida coach Billy Donovan, like mentor Rick Pitino,
likes to go 10 players deep; two of the Gators' top three scorers,
Mike Miller (12.4) and Teddy Dupay (11.0) come off the bench.
Florida, with 11 players averaging at least 10 minutes, will try to
wear down a slightly thinner Gonzaga squad in the second half. Like
Florida, the Bulldogs shoot the 3-pointer well; they have three
snipers with more than 50 each.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Florida 79-72.
</P>
<P>
   CONNECTICUT VS. IOWA
</P>
<P>
   When, where: 10:15 p.m. today; America West Arena, Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   TV/radio: CBS; WQXI (790 AM).
</P>
<P>
   Records: Connecticut 30-2, Iowa 20-9.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches: Jim Calhoun is 300-120 in 13 seasons at Connecticut,
550-257 overall. Tom Davis is 269-139 in 13 seasons at Iowa and
543-289 overall.
</P>
<P>
   How they got here: The top-seeded Huskies routed Texas-San
Antonio in the first round 91-66 and defeated New Mexico 78-56 in
the second. The Hawkeyes beat Alabama-Birmingham 77-64 in the first
round before upsetting No. 4-seed Arkansas 82-72.
</P>
<P>
   Possible lineups: Connecticut _ guards, Khalid El-Amin (5-11,
so., 13.5 ppg) and Ricky Moore (6-2, sr., 6.5 ppg); center, Jake
Voskuhl (6-11, jr., 5.8 ppg); forwards, Kevin Freeman (6-7, jr.,
12.8 ppg) and Richard Hamilton (6-6, jr., 21.2 ppg). Iowa _ guards,
Dean Oliver (5-11, so., 12.0 ppg), Kent McCausland (6-3, sr., 8.3
ppg) and Jason Bauer (6-3, sr., 2.7 ppg); forwards, Jess Settles
(6-7, sr., 9.8 ppg) and J.R. Koch (6-10, sr., 9.8 ppg).
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Although the Hawkeyes won just five of their last 13
regular-season games, the team is riding an NCAA high in coach Tom
Davis' farewell campaign. Iowa's grit and deep bench, however,
won't be enough against an athletic UConn outfit. Richard Hamilton
is a player-of-the-year candidate and, like his teammates, runs the
floor well. Underrated pivot Jake Voskuhl is playing with a stress
fracture in his foot and coach Jim Calhoun has to limit his
minutes, but Voskuhl is a key.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Connecticut 84-69.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
