</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-GATORS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gators' success has Donovan a hot commodity
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ As he settled into the chair kept warm for the
previous half-hour by Billy Donovan, a reporter asked Tom Davis
about the irony of following the Florida coach to the podium for
Wednesday's news conferences here. The Iowa coach, forced to
announce his retirement even before this season began, smiled as if
to confirm that he has heard the rumors Donovan might succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has done a tremendous job in a very, very short time,''
Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   The surprising Gators, a team that seems to be about a season
ahead of expectations, hope the instant success doesn't make
Donovan a short-timer. Florida meets upstart Gonzaga here this
evening seeking a berth in the Elite Eight. The second matchup at
America West Arena is top-seeded Connecticut against Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Donovan rebuffed all efforts to suggest that
he merely is passing through Gainesville on his way to a job at a
higher-profile basketball school. And given that Gators coffers are
even deeper than his bench, and that Donovan has elevated the
program in only three years, perhaps he will spend his entire
career in orange-and-blue neckties.
</P>
<P>
   But even the most youthful Gators realize that Donovan's 48-40
record, along with the promise of continued success fueled by a
superior freshman class, means the rumors of their coach being
pursued by other schools figure to be an annual rite of spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have to be naive to think people aren't going to be
interested in him,'' said freshman forward Mike Miller, the team's
leading scorer. ``The guy is a hot commodity, and deservedly so.
But I don't think he's going anywhere. There are a lot of things he
wants to accomplish here. We have people to accomplish them.''
Typical of a coaching style he learned from Rick Pitino, his
acknowledged mentor, Donovan will attempt to extend the Gators'
tournament run tonight with the tag-team approach, going to his
reserves early and often against Gonzaga, one of the Cinderella
sagas of the past two weeks. The Bulldogs are aptly named, a gritty
bunch that scraps for every loose ball. What's been overlooked is
that Gonzaga, a No. 10 seed in the West, also possesses some pretty
nice talent.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Santangelo, a junior and one of three guards to connect on
50 or more three-point shots, has overcome a late-season shooting
slump to spark Gonzaga. Donovan insisted, though, that the
Bulldogs' quickness and ballhandling won't keep him from pressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's who we are, and it's what we do,'' Donovan said. ``We
won't change, and I doubt they will, either. They're a very nice
team, and they're the sweethearts out here. People are pulling for
them, and no one in the West knows much about us. But if we keep
going forward, our team will get plenty of exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
