<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0464 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4537 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEEL-IMPORTS-1STLD-W     03-17 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEEL-IMPORTS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE VOTES TO LIMIT STEEL IMPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Subs penultimate graf to correctly identify Rep. Sander
Levin. Story is being refiled in one take) (Eds.: 2nd take is scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET) 
(sw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House voted decisively on Wednesday to limit
steel imports, ignoring opposition from the Republican leadership
and a White House warning that the measure would violate world
trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The 289-141 vote _ one short of the two-thirds margin needed to
override a presidential veto _ displayed the division in the
Democratic Party over President Clinton's free trade policies as
well as the draw of protectionism to Republicans from the Rust
Belt. All but 13 of the House Democrats deserted the
administration. And 91 Republicans, a surprisingly strong number,
also bolted from their party's traditional free-trade position.
</P>
<P>
   The bill _ the first major trade measure of the congressional
session _ directs the United States to limit steel imports from
other nations to their average monthly volume for the three-year
period ending July 1997. It would be up to the administration to
decide whether to do so through quotas, tariffs or voluntary
agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The day's debate and off-stage lobbying showed the strange
coalitions that have developed over trade policy and the growth in
protectionist sentiments. When a measure to give the president
broader powers to negotiate trade deals was defeated last year, 71
Republicans voted against it. In this instance, 20 more Republicans
took a stand against unfettered free trade. Steel and fast-track
trade negotiations are the two targets of protectionists lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   With worldwide demand hurt by Asia's financial crisis, foreign
steel makers have been selling at below-market levels. The American
steel industry has seen a drop in business while imports rose 33
percent in 1998 before they began to subside in December. The
Clinton administration last month announced that it would impose
anti-dumping tariffs to punish Japan and Brazil and negotiated an
agreement with Russia to limit imports.
</P>
<P>
   The stricter limits passed by the House are unlikely to become
law. The bill's fate in the Senate is uncertain, but a presidential
veto is likely. In a letter to the House, the White House chief of
staff, John Podesta, acknowledged the steel crisis but warned that
the measure ``constitutes a violation of our international
obligations'' under the World Trade Organization and ``is not in
our nation's economic interest.'' He said Clinton's senior advisers
would recommend that he veto the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the vote showed how difficult, if not impossible, it will
be to pass in this Congress a long sought measure, known as
``fast-track,'' to give the president sweeping powers to negotiate
new trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dennis Hastert of Illinois, the speaker of the House, also
opposed the bill as a violation of free trade. But the bill's
supporters had enough backing to likely be able to force a vote,
and he let the measure come to the floor. His spokesman, John P.
Feehery, said that some Republicans ``were pushing very strongly
for a debate, and we also wanted to avoid the other parliamentary
shenanigans.'' The House Ways and Means Committee, strongly in
favor of free trade, reported the bill to the floor with the
recommendation that it be defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan, the Republican presidential contender who has
challenged the party establishment, wrote to House Republicans on
Tuesday urging them to support the bill to ``regain the loyalty of
working Americans.'' And Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the
minority leader, despite his recent endorsement of Vice President
Al Gore, spoke out in favor of the bill, giving a hint of the
debate that might have been if he had run for president.
</P>
<P>
   Organized labor was also working hard for the bill, and the
United Steelworkers had several hundred rank-and-file members on
hand for the final push.
</P>
<P>
   ``An economic collapse has swept the globe,'' Gephardt said,
``first striking Asia, but now impacting Latin America and other
developing countries as well. During the debate over IMF emergency
funding to stabilize these economies, I warned that import surges
would result from the Asian economic crisis and that a plan needed
to be in place to combat unfair imports. Unfortunately, no such
plan was forthcoming.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that 10,000 steel jobs had been lost to the import
surge. ``Our steel industry is the most productive in the world.
The U.S. should not be forced to unilaterally take in a massive
global import surge.''
</P>
<P>
   Several senior Republicans argued against the bill, which was
sponsored by Rep. Pete Visclosky, D-Ind. They contended that the
American economy was thriving because of the new markets provided
by international trade. They also said the limits could hurt other
U.S. manufacturers by raising steel prices and cutting off the
supply of specialized steel products only available through
imports.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, the chairman of the Ways and Means Committee,
said that the president and his advisers had studied the steel
situation and chose not to set quotas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's logic is clear,'' Archer, R-Texas, said. ``if
the U.S. were to set up trade barriers now in our fragile world
economy, we could have a much bigger problem on our hands that
would affect thousands more American jobs and threaten our economy.
In addition, we would set a terrible example for countries in real
economic trouble, countries whose leaders are under tremendous
pressure to retaliate against American-made products.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rust-belt Republicans as well as Democrats, took the side of
the steelworkers and steel industry. ``We're going to stand up for
Main Street today, not Wall Street,'' said Rep. Robert Ney, R-Ohio.
``That's why this bill is here. We're here because thousands of
steelworkers and citizens would not let this issue go, would not
let this issue die.''
</P>
<P>
   The limits in the House bill would reduce steel imports by 12
million tons from the levels of 1998, while still allowing about 29
million tons of steel into the country. At the height of the steel
import surge in 1998, 41 million tons of foreign steel was being
imported.
</P>
<P>
   The administration argued that the bill violated U.S.
obligations to the World Trade Organization because it would impose
a global limit on imports, instead of using allowed tools such as
tariffs to fight illegal dumping of imports.
</P>
<P>
   But confronted with the vote, Charlene Barshevsky, the U.S.
trade representative, said: ``While we oppose this legislation, we
are going to work with the Congress to address this issue.'' The
administration hopes eventually this session to muster support for
an alternate approach to the steel crisis and to support a bill
sponsored by Reps. Sander Levin, D-Mich., and Amo Houghton, R-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Their measure would change the trade law to make it easier and
quicker for the administration to take action in cases of import
surges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
