<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES TO PUT LIMITS ON STEEL IMPORTS
</P>
<P>
   The House voted decisively to limit steel imports, ignoring
opposition from the Republican leadership and an almost certain
veto by the White House, which argues that the measure would
violate world trade agreements. The bill _ the first major trade
measure of the new session of Congress _ directs the United States
to limit steel imports from other nations to about 29 million tons
of steel. It would be up to the Administration to decide whether to
do so through quotas, tariffs or voluntary agreements.
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL CROSSING TO BUY FRONTIER
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing of Bermuda, a new international communications
carrier, said that it had agreed to acquire Frontier, which serves
almost one million telephone customers in 13 states, for $10.8
billion in stock. Just three weeks ago, Global Crossing hired as
its chief executive Robert Annunziata, who had run AT&AMP;T's business
services unit after selling his previous company, Teleport
Communications Group, to AT&AMP;T for more than $11 billion.
</P>
<P>
   KODAK TO SELL COPIER OPERATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Eastman Kodak, which has long viewed its copier business as a
liability, said it would sell most of its copier manufacturing
operations to a German company.
</P>
<P>
   AIRBUS TO POSTPONE REORGANIZATION
</P>
<P>
   Airbus Industrie, the passenger jet consortium owned by four
European companies, will not transform itself into a single
corporation this year, its chief financial officer said.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS BACK OFF FROM 10,000
</P>
<P>
   Stocks fell a day after the Dow Jones industrial average briefly
topped 10,000 for the first time. The Dow fell 51.06 points, to
9,879.41. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index dropped 8.54
points, to 1,297.82. The Nasdaq composite index declined 10.30
points, to 2,428.97. In the bond market, Treasury prices fell as
the yield on the 30-year issue rose to 5.50 percent from 5.47
percent on Tuesday. Prices declined on concern that $15 billion of
debt sales will draw demand from Treasury securities in coming
days.
</P>
<P>
   DONALDSON, LUFKIN MAKING ITS MARK
</P>
<P>
   The investment bank Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, which rarely
holds a top spot among mergers-and-acquisitions advisers, has made
an impressive showing so far this year, advising on several recent
high-profile deals. The company's shares, which fell $3.0625, to
$65.75, in part because of uncertainty about plans for a stock that
tracks its on-line business, are up 39 percent since January.
</P>
<P>
   FED SURVEY SEES MORE GROWTH
</P>
<P>
   The economy's run of strong growth and low inflation shows few
signs of changing, the Federal Reserve's latest regional survey
showed, citing rising consumer spending, expanded manufacturing,
gains in construction and a pickup in business lending.
</P>
<P>
   OLIVETTI ADDS TO TAKEOVER OFFER
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti sweetened its $60 billion takeover offer for Telecom
Italia by proposing to buy back 30 percent of the phone company's
savings shares if its hostile bid succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINE STRIPPED OF NOMINATION
</P>
<P>
   The American Society of Magazine Editors has stripped a magazine
of nominations for the society's National Magazine awards for not
complying with guidelines regarding the separation of advertising
and editorial content. This Old House was to receive one nomination
for the coveted category of general excellence and one for design.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
