<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK'S AGENT MAKES PITCHES OF HIS OWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Chan Ho Park was determined to focus on the
catcher's mitt even as agent Steve Kim began contract talks with
Los Angeles Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's Steve Kim?'' Park said facetiously after giving up one
run in five innings in a 7-4 exhibition victory over the Montreal
Expos at Holman Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing his job,'' the pitcher said, ``and I'm doing my
job.''
</P>
<P>
   If Park does his job as he has in three improving seasons in Los
Angeles, he'll earn many times his current $2.3 million salary,
either by going free-agent upon becoming eligible in 2001 or by
signing a long-term contract before then.
</P>
<P>
   How much the 25-year-old Korean will make, and for how long,
could be determined by negotiations that began with a 20-minute
``exploratory'' meeting between Kim, Malone and Dodgers general
counsel Sam Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks around and sees Kevin Brown making $(105) million and
(Raul) Mondesi and others making $10 million a year ... I'd say
he's underpaid,'' said the L.A.-based Kim, who went home late
Wednesday. ``The ball's in the Dodgers' court.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone said the timing adds to the negotiating variables _ Park
can go to salary arbitration the next two winters, and free agency
is three seasons away. Malone also acknowledged the pitcher's
unique appeal to Korean-Americans ``carries some weight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like Chan Ho to be here for a long time,'' Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   Park, whose spring ERA is 0.82, had success Wednesday with the
changeup he's adding to his repertoire, throwing it 10 to 12 times
in a 72-pitch outing and producing several ground balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about (contract issues) in the offseason,'' said
Park, who agreed to a two-year contract in February 1998, signing
away his first year of arbitration eligibility. ``But now I just
concentrate on training. I'm trying to get a good season, and after
that _ arbitration, free agency ... whew!''
</P>
<P>
   Lineup card: Here's one less complaint for Gary Sheffield: In a
switch, manager Davey Johnson indicated Sheffield will bat third,
which he prefers, and Raul Mondesi fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi's on-base percentage: .269.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield waved away reporters who approached his locker-room
stall Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Jack(s) of all trades: Outfielder Todd Hollandsworth earned a
``B-plus'' from Johnson in his second error-free start at first
base, where he could back up Eric Karros.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take (versatile infielder Jose Vizcaino) and
Hollandsworth, and they're as valuable as my top eight, even more
so,'' Johnson said. ``You don't win unless you have those kind of
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said Vizcaino is so valuable on the bench that if Eric
Young got hurt, he might put minor-leaguer Adam Riggs at second
base, keeping Vizcaino in the utility role.
</P>
<P>
   Medical dept.: Sidelined catcher Todd Hundley (elbow) and left
fielder Sheffield (shoulder) played catch from 75 feet as physical
therapist Pat Screnar watched.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, in his second day of activity following a two-day
leave, had no pain, Screnar said. Hundley was ``stiff but
improved.''
</P>
<P>
   Good sign: Johnson liked what he saw in set-up reliever Mel
Rojas' perfect inning against the Expos: more fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is to break the 32-year-old's reliance on split-finger
and breaking pitches, which Johnson thinks cost him arm strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he thrives on a lot of work,'' the manager said.
``Well, I can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rojas (6.05 ERA in 1998) was happy to leave the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going well in New York, you're in trouble,'' he
said. ``They booed Mike Piazza in New York!''
</P>
<P>
   In L.A. too, now.
</P>
<P>
   Bad sign: Johnson was unhappy with Young and outfielder Jacob
Brumfield for failing to try to hit to the right side with runners
on second.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (adhering to the fundamentals) impresses me more than the
bomb,'' he said. ``This is part of the spring and learning what I
expect.''
</P>
<P>
   A tradition lives on: Even though they're owned now by an
Australian, not an Irish-American, the Dodgers wore their green
caps in Wednesday's game, and the staff had the annual Dodgertown
St. Patrick's Day party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
