category this year has intense competition, from best film down to
best supporting actor. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- March 17, 1999 -- TOSCA-OPERA-REVIEW, 3-17
-- Luciano Pavarotti and Carol Vaness in the Metropolitan Opera
production of ``Tosca'' on Tuesday night. Vocally, Pavarotti
sounded fresh, powerful and engaged in the role. That's not to say
that this was the ``Tosca'' of one's dreams. (Sara Krulwich/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) BEIJING, China -- March 17, 1999 -- CHINA-ENTREPENEURS,
3-14 -- On Monday, China's Parliament amended its constitution to
declare private business ``an important component of the socialist
market economy.'' ``I do think the official recognition will give
us better opportunities and more space to develop,'' says Zhang
Lifan, whose company designs computer networks. ``As a businessman
and as an individual, I appreciate the amendment.'' (Elisabeth
Rosenthal/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) GREJKOVCE, Yugoslavia -- March 17, 1999 -- KOSOVO-2,
3-17 -- Sabrije Tafaj takes a last look at one of her brothers
during funeral services on Wednesday. Locals said four men,
including Tafaj, were killed by Serb snipers while they were
chopping wood. As Serbian forces continued to pour troops and tanks
into Kosovo, European and American intermediaries in Paris prepared
to shut down peace negotiations because there is no agreeement in
sight. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) GREJKOVCE, Yugoslavia -- March 17, 1999 -- KOSOVO, 3-17
-- Family members grieve at the funeral of four ethnic Albanian men
on Wednesday, some 40 miles southwest of Pristina. Locals claim the
men were killed by Serb snipers while chopping wood. As Serbian
forces continued to pour troops and tanks into Kosovo, European and
American intermediaries in Paris prepared to shut down peace
negotiations because there is no agreeement in sight. (Alan
Chin/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) HOLLYWOOD -- March 17, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 21
-- RACHEL-GRIFFITHS-FILMS, 3-17 -- Australian native Rachel
Griffiths in Los Angeles, a nominee for best supporting actress as
the sister of Jacqueline du Pre in ``Hilary and Jackie.'' For her
role as Muriel's party-girl sidekick in ``Muriel's Wedding,'' Ms.
Griffiths took home the Australian version of the Oscar for best
supporting actress and wound up with theatrical representatives
wrangling deals for her around the globe. (Ted Soqui/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- March 17, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 21 --
BLACK-WOMEN-PLAYWRIGHTS-1, 3-17 -- Viola Davis as Ruby McCollum and
Phylicia Rashad as Zora Neale Hurston in ``Everybody's Ruby,'' a
drama set in Florida in the 1950s by Thulani Davis. There is a
perception of artistic and financial risk in mounting plays by
blacks and women; in the male-dominated theater world, women have
traditionally had difficulty finding mentors and producers. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- March 17, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 21 --
BLACK-WOMEN-PLAYWRIGHTS-2, 3-17 -- Thulani Davis, author of
``Everybody's Ruby,'' a drama set in Florida in the 1950s. While it
is true that black women playwrights are being produced in major
Off Broadway and regional theaters, they have yet to obtain the
kind of consistent, high-profile presence and voice accorded
African-American women today in popular music and fiction writing.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- March 17, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 21 --
RED-THEATER-2, 3-17 -- Jodi Long, above left, and Ric Young in
``Red'' by Chay Yew at the Manhattan Theater Club. The play,
directed by David Petrarca, explores the Cultural Revolution in
China and the brutal crackdown on artists that began in the 1960s.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- March 17, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 21 --
RED-THEATER-1, 3-17 -- In his mind's eye, Chay Yew is a clumsy,
gawky crow craving acceptance from a tribe of graceful sparrows.
This methaphor best reflects his existence as a gay
Chinese-American writer struggling to succeed in a white world.
``It's how I see myself in America, living on the periphery and
longing to be in the midst of it,'' says Yew, 33, one of a handful
of critically acclaimed Asian-American writers actively working in
the theater in this country. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) SAN FRANCISCO -- March 17, 1999 -- CALIF-JOHNS-SCHOOL,
3-17 -- Tracy Helton, left, and Angel Cassidy, former prostitutes,
take part in the First Offender Prostitution Program earlier this
month. A man arrested on charges of soliciting a prostitute, is at
right. The ``john school,'' as locals call it, is tackling the sex
trade by trying to drum some sense into those who perpetuate it.
(Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) SEATTLE -- March 17, 1999 -- SEATTLE-CABARET, 3-17 --
Norman Langill in the center of his 1920 Spiegeltent near downtown
Seattle. Langill, a local impresario, created Teatro ZinZanni, a
show specifically designed to be held under a portable roof. (Dan
Lamont/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- March 17, 1999 -- RENO-COUNSEL-LAW-2, 3-17
-- Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., second from foreground in image at
left, leans forward to address Attorney General Janet Reno, right,
during her testimony before the Senate Governmental Affairs
Committee on Wednesday. Reno announced at the hearing that the
independent counsel statute is unworkable, a striking reversal of
her past enthusiasm for the law. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- March 17, 1999 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 3-17
-- Skim-coating is the best way to repair hairline cracks on
plaster walls. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) HOUSTON -- March 17, 1999 -- BKN-PERROT-HNS, 03-17 --
Houston Comets guard Kim Perrot looks through a stack of cards and
letters she has received from fans from around the world. The
popular WNBA player was diagnosed with lung cancer and brain tumors
earlier this year. ``All those who have written and said prayers
we're all on a team now,'' says Perrot. ``They're part of my team,
and I feel good, because if I'm praying and doing what I need to do
and other people are praying for me, I can't lose.'' (Kevin
Fujii/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WATTENS, Austria -- March 17, 1999 --
TRAVEL-CRYSTAL-WORLDS-HNS, 3-18 -- A crystal-eyed ``giant'' gets a
haircut at Swarovski's Crystal Worlds. The landscape here serves as
an entrance to subterranean chambers that showcase crystal in
previously unexplored dimensions. Among the first displays is the
world's largest crystal stone, 15 inches in diameter, weighing
300,000 carats. (Harry Shattuck/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) RAFAEL, Calif. -- March 17, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH
21 -- LUCAS-FILM-FLOATER, 3-17 -- George Lucas at home in Northern
California with his 6-year-old son Jet, wrapped in a Jedi cape.
``Children are the whole point of life,'' says the director, whose
new ``Star Wars'' film is opening in May. ``Even as I was getting
divorced, I decided that taking care of the kids was the most
important thing I could do. You have to open yourself up to it, but
I don't think there is any greater spiritual joy.'' (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- March 17, 1999 -- RENO-COUNSEL-LAW, 3-17 --
Attorney General Janet Reno reviews her reference materials during
testimony before the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee on
Wednesday. Reno announced publicly at a Senate hearing that the
independent counsel statute is unworkable, a striking reversal of
her past enthusiasm for the law. The statute is set to expire in
June. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) JERUSALEM -- March 17, 1999 -- ISRAEL-CORRUPTION, 3-17 --
Aryeh Deri, leaves a district court in Jerusalem after his
conviction on Wednesday. Deri, a former interior minister and head
of the ultra-Orthodox Shas Party, Israel's third largest, was
convicted of corruption after a five-year trial. Thousands of
ultra-Orthodox Jews, who consider him the champion of their
underclass community, took to the streets in his support. (Rina
Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- March 17, 1999 -- CIR-BOOK-CLUBS-2, 3-17 --
Troy Johnson poses next to his books during a recent interview.
On-line clubs can address genres and literary niches not often
found in face-to-face clubs. Such is the case with the
African-American Literature Book Club founded by Johnson a year
ago. (Nancy Siesel/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WARREN, N.J. -- March 17, 1999 -- CIR-BOOK-CLUBS-1, 3-17
-- A typical dinner meeting of the ``Mostly, We Eat'' book club.
Members of the club rate the books they have read on their web site
and also use the site to set up dinner meetings. (Norman Y.
Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) HADDONFIELD, N.J. -- March 17, 1999 --
CIR-USED-COMPUTERS, 3-17 -- Pre-kindergarten students at Christ the
King Elementary School gather around their classroom's computer
which was donated by a parent. Some pre-schools and elementary
schools are a perfect place for those old, non-Pentium computers
because they don't necessarily need Internet access or a lot of
memory to run basic reading and math programs. (Sal DiMarco/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SAN FRANCISCO -- March 17, 1999 -- CIR-CHATTERBOTS, 3-17
-- Dr. Richard Wallace poses next to his laptop which is running
Alice, a Web chatterbot he designed at Lehigh University. Alice, an
acronym for Artificial Linguistic Computer Entity, is a software
program known as a chatterbot, which simulates conversations with
humans. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) LOS ANGELES -- March 17, 1999 -- CIR-HATE-SITES, 3-17 --
Rabbi Abraham Cooper, associate dean at The Simon Wiesenthal
Center, outside the organization's headquarters recently. Cooper
says the subculture of hate on the internet is growing at an
alarming rate. (Edward Carreon/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
