<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 03/17/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) UNDATED -- March 17, 1999 -- OBIT-CALLAHAN, 3-17 --
Photographer Robert Callahan is seen in an undated photo. Callahan,
a whose pictures married the elegant precision of American
modernists like Ansel Adams with the restless experimental spirit
of European modernists like Laszlo Moholy-Nagy, died on Monday at
his home in Atlanta. He was 86. (Alan S. Weiner/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) WASHINGTON -- March 17, 1999 -- CLINTON-MISSILE, 3-17 --
Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., discusses the Senate's vote to pass
the Ballistic Missle Defense Bill on Wednesday. this afternoon
during a press conference. With Lieberman are, from left, Sens.
Thad Cochran, Blanche Lincoln, and John Warner. President Clinton
on Tuesday abruptly withdrew his objections to a
Republican-sponsored Senate bill calling for the development of a
limited missile defense system. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) SAN FRANCISCO -- March 17, 1999 -- CALIF-JOHNS-SCHOOL-2,
3-17 -- An undercover police officer posing as a prostitute, at
rear of car at left, makes her way to the passenger side as her
backup team moves in to arrest the driver who allegedly solicited
her for sex. san Francisco's First Offender Prostitution Program,
or the ``john school'' as locals call it, is tackling the sex trade
by trying to drum some sense into those who perpetuate it. (Peter
DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) WHITMAN, Mass. -- March 17, 1999 -- MORE-QUADS-BOS, 3-17
-- Joe and Kathy McDonough with daughter Caroline, 7, and their
2-year-old quadruplets, from left, Elise, Thomas, Stephen and
Andrew. The McDonough kids are one of 560 sets of quadruplets born
in the U.S. in 1996, a year when ``higher-order multiple births''
(triplets and up) grew 19 percent over the year before. Over the
previous 10 years, such births had already more than doubled. Call
it the multiple baby boom. (Tom Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- March 17, 1999 -- SHAKESPEARE, 3-17 -- Paul
Rudd and Helen Hunt in the play ``Twelfth Night'' last year.
Shakespeare is still the most produced playwright in 1990s America,
and in England he was recently voted in one BBC poll ``the Briton
of the Millennium.'' (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) BOSTON -- March 17, 1999 -- HOSPITAL-ERRORS-BOS, 3-17 --
Dr. Barry Simmons signs patient Dominick Minot's wrist prior to
surgery at the Brigham and Womens Hospital. Good hospitals
generally don't tweak their operations only after something goes
wrong; they do it all the time as part of the health care
industry's new mantra of continuous quality improvement. (Bill
Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- March 17, 1999 -- NY-STPATRICK-PARADE-2,
3-17 -- A police officer empties beer cups seized from arriving
railroad passengers at Pennsylvania Station on Wednesday. Police
were patrolling train and subway stations enforcing liquor
ordinances as people arrived to the city to take part in the St.
Patrick's Day Parade. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- March 17, 1999 -- NY-STPATRICK-PARADE-1,
3-17 -- Members of the Tokyo Pipe Band, making their New York
debut, parade up Fifth Avenue on Wednesday during the St. Patrick's
Day Parade. Bright sunshine and warm weather made for a great 238th
St. Patrick's Day Parade in New York, the nation's largest. (James
Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) LOS ANGELES -- March 17, 1999 -- OSCAR-FLOATER, 3-17 --
Portraits are used to mark the seats where nominated actors will
sit on Sunday during preparations on Wednesday for this weekend's
Academy Awards ceremony at the Dorothy Chandler Pavalion. Unlike
last year when iceberg-prone ``Titanic'' swamped the opposition and
captured 11 Oscars to tie the record held by ``Ben Hur,'' every
category this year has intense competition, from best film down to
best supporting actor. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- March 17, 1999 -- TOSCA-OPERA-REVIEW, 3-17
-- Luciano Pavarotti and Carol Vaness in the Metropolitan Opera
production of ``Tosca'' on Tuesday night. Vocally, Pavarotti
sounded fresh, powerful and engaged in the role. That's not to say
that this was the ``Tosca'' of one's dreams. (Sara Krulwich/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) BEIJING, China -- March 17, 1999 -- CHINA-ENTREPENEURS,
3-14 -- On Monday, China's Parliament amended its constitution to
declare private business ``an important component of the socialist
market economy.'' ``I do think the official recognition will give
us better opportunities and more space to develop,'' says Zhang
Lifan, whose company designs computer networks. ``As a businessman
and as an individual, I appreciate the amendment.'' (Elisabeth
Rosenthal/New York Times Photo)
