<HEADLINE>
NFL BACKS LIMITED REPLAY AFTER COMPLAINTS OF BAD CALLS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ After a seven-year absence, instant replay will return
this fall in the National Football League for a one-year trial.
</P>
<P>
   The move was approved by NFL owners, 28-3, Wednesday at their
annual meeting in the wake of an outcry stemming from controversial
calls by officials that had major impacts on several games last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Instant replay _ the use of television replays to correct
officials' obviously erroneous calls _ was used in the NFL from
1986 through 1991. It was dropped in 1992 after coaches and owners
complained that the system was cumbersome and slowed the pace of
games. The owners voted on whether to restore instant replay before
each of the last two seasons, but it was rejected both times.
</P>
<P>
   Rich McKay, general manager of the Tampa Bay Buccaneers and
co-chairman of the league's competition committee, said officials
have told him that ``they typically preferred not to have replay
but were ready and willing to work with the system if that is what
the league wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of different points of view among us and it
has taken a long time to create a system that addressed three
issues,'' McKay said. ``First, in replay, we want to get the play
right. Then, we don't want to lengthen the game. Finally, we don't
want to ruin the pace of the game. We've come up with a system that
deals with all three of those issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The new instant-replay format has several elements.
</P>
<P>
   _ In each game, a team receives two chances to challenge an
official's call. If the team has no timeouts, it cannot challenge.
If the play call is overturned by the referee, who will review it
on a TV monitor on the sideline, the team making the challenge
retains its existing timeouts. If the play call is not overturned,
the team loses a timeout. (A team has three timeouts per half in
each game.)
</P>
<P>
   A call can be changed only if there is indisputable visual
evidence warranting the change.
</P>
<P>
   Under the old system, coaches could not challenge a call; only a
replay assistant could order a review.
</P>
<P>
   _ During the final two minutes of each half and in overtime, a
referee assistant located overhead in a booth can call for a
review.
</P>
<P>
   _ Each review will take a maximum of 90 seconds beginning when
the referee looks into his monitor.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewable matters include plays governed by the sideline,
goal line, end zone and end line and passing plays primarily
dealing with completion and possession.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 24 votes was needed for restoration. Last year,
Arizona, Buffalo, Chicago, Cincinnati, Kansas City, Oakland, Tampa
Bay, San Diego and the Giants voted against replay.
</P>
<P>
   This year only Arizona, Cincinnati and the Jets voted against
it. All three argued in similar fashion with long-time opponents of
replay: that the game is played by humans and is officiated by
humans and, thus, is prone to human error. Leave it as such. These
teams also felt that the system did not work efficiently before and
would not do so now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight of the last nine years I've voted against replay,'' said
Lamar Hunt, owner of the Kansas City Chiefs. ``I voted for it this
time because I see an opportunity to use improved technology. I
have some misgivings. I still think there are imperfections in the
system, but let's see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Davis, general manager of the Oakland Raiders, liked the idea
of instant replay, but said: ``The use of the timeouts changes the
game. I'm going for it for one year and then maybe we can get the
challenges out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Dungy, head coach of Tampa Bay, felt that officials may
become more whistle-shy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a whistle blows, the play is over,'' Dungy said. ``No
official wants to blow a play dead on a possession call and then TV
shows the call was wrong. The officials now might say, `Hey, I'm
not going to blow my whistle; let replay do the work.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Seeman, the league's director of officiating, said: ``This
is not an all-encompassing system; it's the type of system that
helps out, that tries to take TV replays and turn them into a
positive. It's being used on a limited basis and it's not
obtrusive. It will correct those three or four controversial calls
a year out of the entire season that are so high profile.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Rooney, the Pittsburgh Steelers' owner, said: ``My greatest
hope is that it works. My greatest fear is that it won't.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The outcry for instant replay, which reached a fevered pitch
before the playoffs in December, was driven by a highly publicized
series of gaffes and questionable calls late in the season.
</P>
<P>
   _ On Thanksgiving Day in Detroit, officials botched the coin
toss at the beginning of overtime, giving the ball to Detroit even
though replays showed Pittsburgh's Jerome Bettis correctly calling
``tails.'' The Lions drove for the winning field goal. Instant
replay would not have been used in that case, but the mistake was
broadcast repeatedly and began to focus attention on the officials'
performance.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two calls made the difference in the Buffalo Bills' 25-21 loss
to the New England Patriots three days later. Patriots receiver
Shawn Jefferson was called inbounds on a fourth-and-9 pass play,
though replays showed he was out. Then Buffalo was called for
interference on a desperation pass into the end zone as players on
both teams jostled for the ball. That call set up the Patriots'
winning touchdown. The Bills' owner, Ralph Wilson, lashed out at
the officiating afterward and was fined $50,000 by Commissioner
Paul Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vinny Testaverde scored the winning touchdown on a
last-second, fourth-down quarterback sneak in the Jets' 32-31
victory over the Seattle Seahawks on Dec. 6. Replays clearly showed
that Testaverde was down before he reached the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL announced the day after the Jets-Seahawks game that it
would ask owners to vote on instant replay for the playoffs and
Super Bowl, but retracted the proposal before the first playoff
round. That first round then saw two more controversial calls:
Jerry Rice of the 49ers was ruled down before he lost a fumble to
the Green Bay Packers, on a drive that led to San Francisco's
game-winning touchdown; and in a final indignity for the Bills,
receiver Andre Reed was called for unsportsmanlike conduct and
ejected for bumping an official after he was not awarded a
touchdown on a pass play, even though he appeared to be over the
goal line. The call forced the Bills to settle for a field goal
when they trailed Miami by 10 points, in a game they eventually
lost, 24-17.
</P>
</TEXT>
