<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-CMGI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CMGI CHIEF TO DELAY EFFORT TO BLOCK DEAL FOR LYCOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The chief executive of the largest investor in Lycos Inc. said
Wednesday that his firm might wait several months before launching
a counterbid for control of the Waltham, Mass. Internet company, in
part to deny possible stock benefits to USA Networks Inc. and
thwart its takeover bid.
</P>
<P>
   David Wetherell, head of Andover, Mass. Internet venture captial
firm CMGI Inc., said his company is still trying to arrange a rival
bid for Lycos. But he added he might wait for other dissastified
Lycos shareholders to turn down the pending offer from USA Networks
before launching any counterbid.
</P>
<P>
   Such a strategy could spare Lycos from having to issue stock
obligations that could be worth as much as $176 million to USA
Networks, the New York media firm controlled by Barry Diller.
</P>
<P>
   But such a move would also add to the uncertainty faced by Lycos
investors as they decide whether to approve a deal announced Feb. 9
to combine their company with elements of USA Networks. A
shareholder meeting to vote on the agreement is not expected for
several months.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI, which holds about 18.5 percent of Lycos shares, believes
that a majority of the company's investors would join CMGI in
rejecting the deal under its present terms.
</P>
<P>
   In making his bid for Lycos, Diller obtained a pledge that USA
Networks and its affiliates would have the right to purchase as
much as 19.9 percent of Lycos stock at $127.14 per share if the
company were sold to another bidder at that price or more. Lycos
stock reached that level the day before the USA Networks bid was
announced.
</P>
<P>
   Wetherell has said that at least four other parties have
expressed interest in topping USA Network's bid but has not
identified them or given any indication of how much they would be
willing to pay for Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   In an exchange of e-mails Wednesday, Wetherell also said that
CMGI might wait until after a shareholders' vote on USA Network's
bid before announcing any other offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting the (Lycos-USA Networks) deal voted down first, thus
avoiding tripping the topping fee options, and making an offer at
that time'' is one approach under consideration, Wetherell wrote.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for USA Networks could not be reached for comment.
A Lycos executives declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Wetherell resigned from the Lycos board of directors last week
and vowed to find a better for deal for Lycos, whose shares sank
after the deal with USA Networks was announced. They recovered
after Wetherell's actions, which were unusual because he had
originally backed the deal as a board member.
</P>
<P>
   Wetherell's actions have also put Lycos executives in an awkward
position, because a pending deadline for certain securities filings
prevents them from responding publicly. Lycos executives say only
that the company remains committed to the terms of its agreement.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Wetherell's campaign has also helped bolster
Lycos shares, which had traded as low as 83 7/8 after the deal was
announced. Wednesday they closed at $101 3/4, down 3 1/4 in Nasdaq
trading.
</P>
<P>
   Sources familiar with the terms of the agreement note that it
prevents Diller's USA Networks from earning more than $176 million
from the options, a small fraction of Lycos' total market
capitalization. Given Wednesday's closing price, the company's
total valuation was about $4.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in CMGI fell 5 3/8 to close at $175 3/8. CMGI said
Wednesday that its board of directors has approved a two-for-one
split of its common shares to holders of record on May 13, pending
shareholder approvals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
