<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS WIDOW'S SUIT SETS $100M VALUE ON POSSIBLE EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KURKJIAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Lawyers for the widow of the late Boston Celtics star
Reggie Lewis will argue in their upcoming malpractice suit that
despite his heart condition Lewis might have been able to continue
playing basketball had he received proper medical treatment from
Dr. Gilbert H. Mudge Jr., his lead cardiologist.
</P>
<P>
   In documents provided to Mudge's lawyers this week, attorneys
Robert G. Harley and Bridget Asaro contended that had Lewis not
suffered a fatal heart attack at age 27 he could have earned a
maximum of more than $100 million from a variety of positions
during his life, including as a player, coach, broadcaster, and
from endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lewis's heart was found to be badly scarred, Harley
said Wednesday that he will argue that Lewis might have been able
to keep playing by taking heart medication or by wearing a
defibrillator. Harley said Wednesday that he knows of at least one
college football player with a heart condition who competes while
wearing a defibrillator, and a professional basketball player who
is able to play by taking a heart medication.
</P>
<P>
   If Lewis's heart condition precluded him from returning as a
basketball player, he probably would have followed the path of
other captains of Celtics teams and become an NBA coach and then a
broadcaster, the lawyers said. Combined with endorsements and other
paid appearances, he would have earned a minimum of $40 million
even without playing another professional game, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   The setting of Lewis's earning potential at between $40 million
and more than $100 million is the first time that Donna
Harris-Lewis and her lawyers have hinted at the amount they are
seeking to recover if they can prove Lewis's death was a result of
negligence by Mudge.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is scheduled to begin April 26 in Suffolk Superior
Court, three days short of the sixth anniversary of Lewis's
collapse during a Celtics playoff game at Boston Garden.
</P>
<P>
   While a team of the city's top cardiologists concluded within
days that Lewis probably had a life-threatening heart condition, he
spurned their advice and instead went to Mudge and Brigham and
Women's Hospital in Boston for treatment. After 10 days of testing,
Mudge and his team concluded that there were no problems with
Lewis's heart, and that his collapse was caused by a neurological
condition that caused him at times to feel faint during workouts.
Lewis died three months later while shooting baskets at the
Brandeis University gym in Waltham.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge's lead attorney, William J. Dailey Jr., of the firm Sloane
&AMP; Walsh, did not respond to questions Wednesday. In previously
filed documents, Mudge has contended that he provided a more
pessimistic view of Lewis's heart condition to the couple privately
than he had publicly, particularly after receiving the results of
tests done on Lewis by a third group of doctors a month before his
death.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Mudge's lawyers are seeking to show that the scarring to
Lewis's heart was caused by cocaine use, a charge that has been
strenuously denied by Harris-Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Although she has repeatedly denied requests for an interview,
Harris-Lewis released a statement Wednesday saying that she has not
decided what she might do with any money won from the lawsuit. ``I
am still searching my heart and soul for the proper way to capture
Reggie's unique spirit, and the legacy he would want to leave
(their children) Reggie Jr. and Reggiena, and to the community.''
</P>
<P>
   She also responded to some public criticism that she was not
satisfied with the $14 million she received from life insurance
benefits taken out on Lewis's contract and had filed suit against
Mudge to win more money. ``This case has never been about money or
about what killed Reggie. This case is about what could have saved
his life. It's Reggie's life that was most important, not his
death,'' said Harris-Lewis's statement.
</P>
<P>
   And in a veiled reference to reports that Lewis used cocaine
while a standout basketball player at Northeastern University,
Harris-Lewis said: ``My hope is that the conclusion of this case
will finally allow Reggie to rest in peace by restoring his
reputation for our children, our family and friends, and his
fans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
