<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STPATRICK-PARADE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CELEBRATION OF THE IRISH IN ST. PATRICK'S DAY PARADE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By   JODI WILGOREN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Everything but the cloudless sky was green Wednesday,
as record numbers packed St. Patrick's Cathedral, marched up Fifth
Avenue in the 238th annual St. Patrick's Day parade and lined the
2{-mile route to hoot and holler in support.
</P>
<P>
   The sky, of course, was a parade-perfect powder blue, as the
snowstorm of a few days ago became a distant memory and the mercury
in Central Park hit a springlike 64 degrees. The sun shone down on
green-painted faces and green-dyed flattops, green-tinted
sunglasses, green shoelaces and a haberdasher's smorgasbord of
green hats, from plastic bowlers to felt Dr. Seuss specials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've marched in snow, and we've had some rainy days, soaked
to the skin,'' said Michael McCormack, 60, the national historian
for the Ancient Order of Hibernians, who has been in 39 of the past
42 parades. ``There's no feeling in the world like coming out of
one of those canyons onto the avenue: the sun hits your face, the
people cheer you. You can see the people actually grow taller.''
</P>
<P>
   The parade was relatively peaceful, although three young men
were arrested in two separate incidents of assault. In addition, 17
gay and lesbian demonstrators, protesting their exclusion in a
pre-parade event that has become an annual ritual, were arrested on
disorderly conduct charges.
</P>
<P>
   The incidents did not mar the smiling Irish eyes in the crowd _
of 2 million, according to organizers, 275,000 according to the
police _ who lined up a dozen deep along both sides of Fifth Avenue
to cheer some 200,000 people, led by the actress Maureen O'Hara,
the grand marshall, from 44th street to 86th street.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Gov. George Pataki, marching
separately, received rock-star receptions along the route, with
several suggestions shouted out for each man's political future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go Senator!'' one man yelled to Giuliani, who is considering a
bid for the U.S. Senate seat being vacated in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``President, run for president!'' someone urged Pataki, who wore
a fisherman-knit sweater with a shamrock insignia sewn onto the
chest.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor and Cardinal John O'Connor declared this year's the
best parade ever. In his homily at morning Mass, which drew 4,000
people to the cathedral, O'Connor urged the Irish to avoid
prejudice against others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our forefathers, our foremothers, came from some other
country,'' he said later, as he received a bouquet from a New
Jersey high school drum major outside the cathedral. ``It is
imperative that Irish, above all, remember their roots.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, the question of relations between the police
and the community, which has dominated public debate in the six
weeks since four white officers fatally shot an unarmed West
African immigrant in the Bronx, bubbled near the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Support for Giuliani and the Police Department was overwhelming,
though the crowd was largely from out of town: ``Burn in Hell Al
Sharpton and Company, Police Officers are the Greatest,'' read an
eight-foot sign carried by Gene Roos, a drywall contractor from
Patchogue, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   But most remained oblivious to the politics as they enjoyed the
lively bagpipe music and row after row of marchers, some of the men
and women in uniform and some in skirts.
</P>
<P>
   Three women from Long Island, of Italian descent but merrily
clad in two-foot-tall hats decorated with shamrocks, wondered at
the age-old question of whether men wore underwear under their
kilts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw on line, there was a picture of a guy in a kilt,'' piped
in Danielle Lichaa, 17, a student from Staten Island who was
perched on a nearby (very dark green) mailbox. ``He definitely
didn't have underwear on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
