<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-MEETING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL TO REPLAY REPLAY _ FOR A YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ For an instant at least, the NFL will have instant
replay.
</P>
<P>
   A one-year experiment with a replay challenge system was
approved Wednesday by the widest margin in its often stormy history
at the final day of the NFL's annual league meeting, bringing
electronic refereeing back to the NFL for the first time since
1991.
</P>
<P>
   The newly installed system allows for up to two challenges per
team per game plus additional challenges in the final two minutes
of each half and throughout overtime at the descretion of a replay
assistant working in a replay booth near the press box.
</P>
<P>
   During the 56 minutes the coaches are free to make the decision
they will face losing a timeout if their challenge is not upheld by
the referee on the field. When the replay assistant is in charge of
signalling the referee of the need for a review no timeouts would
be effected.
</P>
<P>
   It was that shifting of the responsibility for making the replay
request away from the coaches when a game is at its most critical
that swayed several teams to vote for the proposal, which passed
28-3. That far exceeds any previous votes dating back to the first
replay proposal in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Replay was first approved in 1986 and was used for six seasons
before it was voted out in 1992 by a 17-11 margin. It failed in
both 1997 and 1998 by slight margins but a series of questionable
calls in late season games that appeared to be proven wrong by
television cameras last season swayed several teams, including the
Buffalo Bills who had traditionally opposed it, to change their
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a few high profile calls that people felt could
have been turned around (with replay),'' Tampa Bay coach Tony Dungy
said. ``My thought is those things even out but a couple of teams
got burned in key games and it changed some votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the new system, the referee on the field will review the
plays on a field-level monitor and must make a decision within 90
seconds of the replay first rolling. A decision will be reversed
only when there is ``indisputable visual evidence'' that warrants a
change.
</P>
<P>
   Limiting the review time to 90 seconds was to avoid slowing down
the flow of the game and to make it clear the error was an obvious
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it takes more than 90 seconds, it's not irrefutible,'' said
Seattle Seahawks' head coach Mike Holmgren, who co-chairs the
competition committee with Tampa's Rich McKay. ``This is a system
to correct major, major errors, human errors, game-changing
errors.''
</P>
<P>
   The only reviewable plays will be:
</P>
<P>
   --Those governed by the sideline, goal line, end zone or end
line.
</P>
<P>
   --A pass ruled complete, incomplete or intercepted in the field
of play.
</P>
<P>
   --Touching of a forward pass by an ineligible receiver or a
defensive player.
</P>
<P>
   --Whether a quarterback has fumbled or was throwing a forward
pass.
</P>
<P>
   --Illegal forward pass when passer goes beyond the line of
scrimmage or after a change of possession.
</P>
<P>
   --A forward or backward pass thrown from behind the line of
scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   --Runner down by contact.
</P>
<P>
   --Forward progress with respect to first downs.
</P>
<P>
   --Touching of a kick.
</P>
<P>
   --Number of players on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't to correct every play,'' said McKay, who voted
against replay last year. ``What changed my opinion was the media,
the fans, the players and the coaches all wanted some replay
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakland Raiders' owner Al Davis had also voted against the
return of replay the past two years but changed his mind this time
despite still being opposed to the challenge system that ties
replay requests to potentially lost timeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want replay but I don't like the challenge system,'' Davis
said. ``But this was the quickest way to get replay back and try
the technology. We can get the challenge out after we try the
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   In the six-year history of replay, from 1986-1991, 2,967 plays
were reviewed with only 376 overturned but both numbers increased
nearly every season. The first year, only 38 of the 374 calls
reviewed were reversed. By 1991, 90 of 570 reviewed calls were
reversed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One other rule change was to outlaw the chop block from behind
below the waist along the line of scrimmage. This has long been a
bane of defensive linemen's existence, resulting in more than a few
knee injuries and many hot tempers. In addition, ``if an offensive
player's block is followed by the blocker rolling up on the back of
the defender, it is illegal and will be called unnecessary
roughness . . . The league announced its preseason nationally
televised games and the Patriots are involved in one. Their Aug. 21
game at home against Dallas will be televised nationally at 8 p.m.
on ESPN . . . The request for approval of Howard Milstein and
Daniel Snyder's $800 million offer to buy the Washington Redskins
was tabled for another 60 days. The league contends Milstein is not
putting up enough of his own money to buy the team from a trust set
up by late owner Jack Kent Cooke. In addition, some owners would
like to see Cooke's son, John Kent Cooke, retain the team. The
younger Cooke bid $700 million . . . The NFL announced it would not
play the 2003 Super Bowl in San Francisco because their new stadium
plans have gone awary. No alternate location was announced but San
Diego may have the inside track . . . New Orleans head coach
shocked media members when he said Wednesday he would be willing to
trade the Saints' entiree draft to land Heisman Trophy winner Ricky
Williams. Ditka, whose Saints draft No. 12, was ready to make the
offer to both Cleveland and Philadelphia, which hold the first two
selections. Cleveland head coach Chris Palmer said he had little
interest in that and personnel director Dwight Clark reiterated
that point. Saints president Bill Kuharich admitted ``it would take
much more than that'' to get into one of the first two drafting
slots. ``We're not interested in the No. 1 pick,'' Kuharich said.
``We're interested in Ricky Williams.'' . . . The Jets have told
quarterback Glenn Foley he is free to try and make a trade for
himself with another NFL team. If he does, it would be pending the
Jets' approval.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 2200EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
