<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0483 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4573 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-TOBACCO-BONDS-NYT &LR;      03-17 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TOBACCO-BONDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS WARY OF NEW YORK PLAN TO USE TOBACCO MONEY TO BACK BONDS
</HEADLINE>
   (wg) 
 By LESLIE EATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York City is likely to become the first
government in the country to raise money based on future payments
it will receive from the $206 billion tobacco settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has the city already set up a special agency to sell
``tobacco bonds,'' but it has also hired three Wall Street firms to
help it with the bond deal, which could be arranged as early as
July.
</P>
<P>
   City officials estimate that they could borrow $2.5 billion over
the next four years; the bonds would be repaid from the $6.7
billion the city expects to get from the tobacco settlement fund by
2025.
</P>
<P>
   But financial experts are warning the city and other local and
state governments around the country not to count their deals
before they are completed.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, which 46 state governments reached last year
with the country's largest tobacco companies, is highly complex and
somewhat conditional, financial analysts said. Most of the states
are planning to share the proceeds with local governments, but the
amount that any government receives could be reduced by several
factors including the federal government's effort to claim some of
the money, and the smokers' success in giving up their nicotine
habits.
</P>
<P>
   By selling bonds backed by tobacco settlement money, the
governments hope to get a big sum all at once rather than having
the money trickle in over 25 years. Those governments, including
Maine, Texas and Washington, D.C., could then use the bond proceeds
for buildings, roads, bridges, and other capital projects.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, analysts are wary. ``There are still a lot of
things that have to happen, in our opinion, before bonds could be
secured'' by money from the tobacco settlement, said Steven J.
Murphy, managing director for public finance at Standard &AMP; Poor's
Ratings Services, which analyzes bond issues. The firm has just
issued a report calling on governments to adopt ``a cautionary
approach'' to using the tobacco money.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts are even more cautious. ``Because of the
uncertainty of future years' payments, the revenue should not be
viewed as a long-term, stable source of security for bonds,'' wrote
Kevin D. Taylor of Prudential Securities in a research report for
possible clients, ``Payment Uncertainties Are Built Into Tobacco
Settlement Agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials say they are well aware of the potential
problems. ``This is not a done deal, because some issues must still
be resolved,'' said Comptroller Alan Hevesi, who would supervise
bond sales along with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. But the city decided
it would be prudent to prepare for the bond sale, Hevesi said, so
it can move quickly once some of the questions are answered.
</P>
<P>
   Under the tobacco agreement, New York State is likely to get at
least $25 billion over the life of the deal, and has agreed to
split the money with cities and counties. Gov. George Pataki has
proposed giving the city $6.7 billion. But New York City and
Westchester and Erie counties think they should get more, and have
filed an appeal with the Appellate Division of state Supreme Court.
Such an appeal could delay distribution of the money, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   A larger problem, for all state and local governments, is that
the federal government is threatening to claim some of the money,
which would reduce the amount available to everyone else. The
administration is more likely to claim a state's tobacco funds if
they are not used for health and education purposes, said Murphy,
of Standard &AMP; Poor's.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, Giuliani has said he plans to use the money
primarily for school construction, although the bond proceeds will
go into the capital budget and could be used for any major project,
city officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature could decide to change the formula that Pataki
has set for who gets the state money and how it will be spent; in
any case, the Legislature must also pass a bill that would make the
settlement binding on all companies that sell tobacco in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The signing companies _ Philip Morris, R.J. Reynolds, Brown &AMP;
Williamson and Lorillard Tobacco _ control almost all tobacco sales
in the state, but the new law would be important if any of them
said financial problems kept them from making the payments, or
other companies took over their share of the market.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the settlement payments are backed by just four
companies is a concern to analysts at Moody's Investors Service,
another bond ratings agency. ``The problem is that anything that is
likely to tank one is likely to impact all of the companies,'' said
Michael Knef, a vice president and senior analyst.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
