NYT-03-17-99 2200EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0484 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4574 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LONNIEHOLLEY-PART1-CO     03-17 3000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONNIEHOLLEY-PART1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern folk artist Lonnie Holley at a crossroads
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARPERSVILLE, Ala. _ A dozen vehicles squat in the yard, but
none of them work. There are bedpans and televisions, and piles of
plywood and stands of Styrofoam, and nylon mesh flapping in the
breeze and cats brushing between the rusty legs of discarded lawn
chairs. If you didn't know this was a folk art environment, you'd
swear it was a trailer park after a tornado.
</P>
<P>
   But the white-columned home in the middle of the property is no
doublewide; it's two stories, six bedrooms, 2 1/2 baths. Inside the
garage, at the end of a passageway constricted like a cave with
more stuff, the man of the house is pounding an electric keyboard,
growling a sort of blues: ``Sittin' in a cotton field ... down here
in Harpersville ... thinking about America ... livin' in the last
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Lonnie Holley looks up, his eyes as wide and bright as a
7-year-old's, and extends a hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never take anything to the junkyard,'' he says, gesturing at
the clutter that threatens to engulf him.
</P>
<P>
   You notice a battered wooden sign in the corner: ``Hi Kids _ the
Sandman.'' Holley, one of the most important figures in Southern
folk art, started his career 20 years ago by carving the soft
sandstone that steel mills use as molds. Since then, he's led so
many workshops at schools and churches that children around
Birmingham know him as the Sandman.
</P>
<P>
   He wonders what the children would think now.
</P>
<P>
   It was a rainy Tuesday afternoon in December. Holley had just
returned from an errand in town and was unwinding in his bedroom
when he heard a commotion downstairs. He hurried down the steps.
Voices were shouting. ``Get down!'' It was the police. ``Get down
now!'' They ordered him to the floor, face down on the living room
carpet, and clamped handcuffs around his wrists.
</P>
<P>
   On a wall above them, a framed picture showed Holley decked out
in a black suit, grinning with unabashed pride as he shook hands
with Hillary Clinton. Four years before, a sculpture of his had
been part of an exhibition at the White House. The first lady
called him a ``master artist.'' It was one of the highlights of his
career, of his life, which is why he decorated the photo with faux
flowers and hung it in a place of honor on a wall facing the front
entrance _ the first thing sheriff's deputies would have seen when
they kicked in his door with a search warrant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this some kind of a joke?'' Holley asked them.
</P>
<P>
   It was no joke. He was under arrest.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   Lonnie Holley has known a world of trouble in his 49 years. He
has been beaten, shot, jailed. He has been abandoned, cheated,
stolen from. He has watched as his home of 18 years _ along with
much of the art and debris he carefully placed around it _ was
bulldozed into a trench to make way for an airport expansion. But
nothing in a life of Job-like tribulations has prepared him for the
misfortunes of the past few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like somebody's been holding a black candle over me,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Holley is credited with creating some of the most sophisticated,
conceptual work in Southern folk art, an increasingly popular field
that has won international acclaim in recent years. Museums and
galleries from New York to Japan have displayed his paintings,
sandstone carvings and assemblages, the symbolic sculptures he
crafts from things other people have thrown out. His vision burned
brightly during the 1996 Olympics, when a re-creation of his
art-bedazzled yard formed the focal point of ``Souls Grown Deep,''
a major folk art exhibition at City Hall East in Atlanta. Newsweek
magazine judged it the best part of the Olympic Arts Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Given the praise and publicity, this should be the best of times
for Holley. Instead, he finds himself spending more time talking to
lawyers and judges than making art.
</P>
<P>
   First he was uprooted from his Birmingham home in a tortuous
condemnation proceeding that dragged on for five years. Then, after
he moved to the small town of Harpersville, 25 miles away, his new
neighbors feuded with his family, one of them going so far as to
assault him, police say. Finally, on Dec. 8, he and his three sons
_ Ezekial, Kubra and A.J. _ were arrested in connection with a
burglary and arson at a golf course behind their house. The Holleys
face multiple charges that could bring the father and his oldest
son prison time _ although Holley says he had nothing to do with
the incident.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that his boys' actions landed him in jail is especially
hurtful. Holley is raising five children and two grandchildren more
or less by himself. He has taught them to pray, to say ``ma'am''
and ``sir'' to their elders, to cultivate their imaginations and
elevate their spirits by creating art. And now they get him
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, Holley is broke. With his spotty income
and a large family to support, he has always lived on poverty's
front porch. Art collectors who visited his old place in Birmingham
were never surprised when he asked for a little cash on top of
their checks for his work. He often needed the money for dinner.
Now he has an additional bill to worry about: bail.
</P>
<P>
   It's a familiar story in the world of folk art. Howard Finster,
the Georgia preacher who has made a bundle selling angels and
Elvises, is a shining exception. Many of his peers live in
primitive conditions, scrambling from weekend to weekend when the
yuppies show up with their checkbooks and cameras. The reasons for
their struggle are more complicated than they might seem. Whatever
the causes, the result is dispiriting: Renowned, respected artists
like Holley wouldn't qualify for an auto loan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we were the hit of the South,'' says Charlie Lucas,
a Prattville, Ala., sculptor and friend of Holley's. ``Now it looks
like we were the ones getting hit.''
</P>
<P>
   For Holley, the blows started early.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   The artist ambles out to his driveway, where chunks of sandstone
sit amid the general rubble. He's tall and thin, wearing dusty work
clothes of black and blue, with a scraggly goatee and a crown of
dreadlocks that springs from his head like a clump of fantastic
weeds. He speaks in silver streams of thought that can leap like an
evangelist's altar call or flow like a jazzman's saxophone solo. As
he begins to tell about his hard life and times _ a folklore saga
in itself _ he picks up a broken-off hacksaw blade, crouches over a
block of stone and begins to work it with fingers that are as long
and supple as a guitarist's.
</P>
<P>
   He was born poor in 1950 to a Birmingham woman who gave him to
another woman, who then ran off with him. That woman traded him to
another for a pint of whiskey. And that woman died and left him
with her husband, a man he knew as Big Daddy, who was so mean that
Lonnie took to running away, one time jumping a train and riding
all the way to New Orleans. He was sent to reform school, and he
ran away from there, too, but they always caught him and sent him
back and beat him for having run.
</P>
<P>
   Holley tells the story in a mesmerizing monotone that's much
gentler than his singing voice. As he gouges and shaves the
sandstone, a woman's face begins to take shape.
</P>
<P>
   He was released from reform school as a teen-ager and went back
to Birmingham to live with his grandmother. She showed him how to
scavenge at the dump. Taught him about recycling. A good woman.
Then he left for Florida, where he had a brother and sister _ two
of the 27 ``live babies'' he says his mother had _ and he supported
himself as a cook. Worked at Disney World. Made him dress up like
Goofy one time, when Goofy didn't show.
</P>
<P>
   Holley laughs and bares a snaggle-toothed smile that's a bit,
well, goofy. The sandstone has two faces.
</P>
<P>
   And then he came back to Alabama to help his mother with all
those children. And he was drinking too much and depressed, and one
time, after he was robbed, he took a fistful of sleeping pills, but
lived. Then a favorite niece and nephew died in a house fire, and
no one could afford tombstones, so he carved them himself from
discarded sandstone. He'd never done anything like that before. It
made him feel better to create something so beautiful when he was
in such despair. So he carved some more, and people told him he
wasn't a bum, he was an artist. And he called the Birmingham Museum
of Art and made an appointment and showed the curators some of his
carvings, and they thought he was so good that they got him
included in a show at the Smithsonian Institution.
</P>
<P>
   The fingers are flying. The sandstone has three faces.
</P>
<P>
   And he met a woman and started a family and fashioned a home out
of a hovel overlooking the Birmingham airport. And he remembered
his grandmother in the city dump and hauled stuff home to make
found-object sculptures _ visual allegories in which every piece of
trash found new meaning. A skillet might mean motherhood. Barbed
wire might mean injustice. And people started driving miles to see
his yard, which was spooky and beautiful like a jungle. Most of
them wanted to watch him work and buy pieces, but some of them took
without paying or paying enough. So he put mirrors on the trees to
ward off evil spirits. But it must not have worked, or he wouldn't
be sitting here singing about the last days in a cotton field in
Harpersville.
</P>
<P>
   Four faces, full lipped and broad nosed, look out from the
sandstone. Holley looks back tenderly, like a new father.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   Holley first heard he was going to have to move in 1992.
Birmingham International Airport wanted to extend a runway and was
required to expand the no man's land beyond the end of the tarmac.
The project would require buying and demolishing hundreds of homes
in the predominantly black, low-income neighborhood of Airport
Hills.
</P>
<P>
   The airport authority offered Holley $14,000 for his acre of
land. But his acre was nothing like the others. While his house was
crude _ a dank, rambling shed with earth floors and rudimentary
wiring and plumbing _ his yard contained thousands of pieces of art
that seemed to be as rooted in the soil as the trees. Sometimes
they had been there so long that trees dropped seeds in them and
they literally took root. The work was potentially worth far more
than the offer, which he turned down.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, the surrounding homes vanished as his neighbors
accepted resettlement checks. Friends took Holley out to look at
other houses in Alabama and west Georgia, but his heart wasn't in
it.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Trechsel, director of the Birmingham Museum of Art,
remembers driving him around. ``Nothing was ever quite right. I
decided it was a waste of time because he really didn't want to
leave.''
</P>
<P>
   And the bulldozers crept closer.
</P>
<P>
   Holley almost left once. Keeping his home, he rented a house in
the nearby Woodlawn neighborhood and opened a studio. But when he
carted in some junk and started making assemblages in the yard,
residents complained and he was repeatedly cited by the sanitation
department. His landlord evicted him.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wanted me to live behind a white picket fence,'' Holley
says, chuckling at the very thought.
</P>
<P>
   So it was back to the old place. The bleak atmosphere seemed to
invite thieves. They took his materials for scrap. They helped
themselves to his art. They stole five of his vehicles, which he
had packed with hundreds of paintings in anticipation of the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd get these calls,'' says Monty Stabler, a Birmingham art
dealer, who was suspicious of some the inquiries she was fielding
from people who wanted to sell Holley's work. They always seemed to
lose interest when they were asked where a piece came from.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was one house _ Holley's _ surrounded by a
moonscape of driveways without homes and sidewalks without yards.
</P>
<P>
   The artist was trapped. He knew he would have to leave, but he
couldn't afford to buy another home until the airport offered him
more money. In 1995, Joseph Strickland, a Birmingham probate
attorney whose wife admired Holley's work, volunteered to represent
him. He enlisted a litigator friend of his, Frank Galloway, and
they negotiated for two years. In October 1997, with a trial date
looming, the authority finally agreed to pay Holley $165,700 _ more
than two-thirds of it for the estimated cost of relocating his
environment lock, stock and sandstone to a new home in
Harpersville.
</P>
<P>
   It was a do-it-yourself move. Over several weekends last spring,
Holley and some friends loaded rental trucks with everything they
could hoist. They couldn't get it all _ there was just too much.
Holley figures that almost half his pieces had been left behind
when the earthmoving equipment rumbled in to level the property.
Witnesses say it was like an archaeological dig turned upside down,
with workers burying, rather than unearthing, the artifacts of a
lost civilization.
</P>
<P>
   Holley had a compelling reason for not hiring professional
movers: He needed the money for his new home. His lawyers thought
he had no chance of getting a mortgage loan, with his erratic
earnings, so he paid $91,500 cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lonnie sat here and cried at the closing,'' Strickland
recalls. He was so happy and relieved that his troubles were
finally over.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   Harpersville is a town of 1,000 that's little more than a 45-mph
hurdle on the four-lane sprint from Birmingham to Auburn. It's
known for its sod and Christmas tree farms, and for being something
of a speed trap; police cruisers often lay in wait at the city
limits on U.S. 231-280.
</P>
<P>
   The cops know Holley's neighborhood well. The official name is
Creswell, but people call it ``Crackwell'' because of all the drug
dealing. When a reporter stopped to talk to one of Holley's
neighbors recently, a sheriff's deputy followed him for a mile,
pulled him over and asked what he was doing at one of the biggest
crack houses in Shelby County. ``People get shot out here,'' she
warned.
</P>
<P>
   Holley and his lawyers knew nothing of the area's reputation
when they found the house in an 11th-hour rush to settle with the
airport. There was something else they didn't know: His new
neighbors did not want him there.
</P>
<P>
   Holley's house was a foreclosure. Annie Jews, the woman who had
lived there for years, lost the property in 1996 and was still
enraged. One night shortly after Holley moved in, he says, she
burst into the house and his bedroom demanding that he vacate the
premises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know who you are!'' he yelled.
</P>
<P>
   His new home was a fragile egg in a nest of resentment. The
woman's brother lived next door, another brother across the street
and their mother down the road. None of the kin was pleased to see
trucks dumping piles of rubbish and peculiar art on what had been
their relative's neatly mowed lawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lord have mercy, I wish somebody would get rid of that mess,''
says Annie Lou Garrett, the mother. ``I have to look at it every
time I drive to the doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   The bad feelings boiled over in a dispute over a small building
just within Holley's property. The Garretts use it as a sort of
juke joint; there's a pool table inside, and dozens of cans and
half-pints litter the parking lot on weekend mornings. Holley's
oldest son, 18-year-old Ezekial, wanted to set up a silk-screen
T-shirt shop in the building, but the Garretts refused to surrender
it.
</P>
<P>
   One day last summer, Ezekial got into a fistfight with Maurice
Garrett, the 28-year-old nephew of the woman who used to own their
house. That night, Holley says, Garrett burst into their home with
a gun vowing to kill Ezekial. Holley says he calmed him down and he
left.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, the Holleys discovered that someone had slashed
their tires. ``We knew who did it,'' Ezekial says. ``I saw Maurice
over there, so I told him he was going to have to pay for it, and
we got to arguing.''
</P>
<P>
   Police aren't clear on exactly what happened next. Someone
opened fire with a rifle. Ezekial ran into his house, and he and
his brothers starting firing back with a rifle, a shotgun and a
pistol. The shooting lasted 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like the OK Corral,'' Holley says. He had been upstairs
in his bedroom when the gunfire began. A shot crashed through the
window, shattering glass and frame, driving more than a dozen
slithers into his left forearm. As he waited, bleeding, for the
ambulance that would take him to the Coosa Valley Medical Center,
Holley spoke by phone to a hot-headed brother in Birmingham and
convinced him not to come down with a truckload of relatives and
guns to retaliate.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Garrett, the only man charged in the incident, doesn't
come around the neighborhood much anymore. The other Garretts
remain. Holley recently sent an emissary to show them survey maps
to prove that the building is on his property. Unconvinced, they
continue to occupy it.
</P>
<P>
   The uneasy truce is palpable. Richard Garrett, the relative who
runs the juke joint, stands in front of his yellow frame house as a
chained dog snarls beneath a ``No Trespassing'' sign. ``I kept up
that lawn for my sister. That was a beautiful yard when she lived
over there. Nice flowers, nice shrubberies.'' He lights a cigarette
and his eyes narrow as he takes in the never-ending rummage sale
across the street. ``I know the man is an artist, but I think the
order of the place could be better.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the road, Holley looks up warily every time
he catches a hint of movement from the Garretts' direction. ``Those
people watch me like a hawk watches a chicken,'' he says.
``Sometimes I wish I could move again, but I can't afford to. It
looks like I got to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Above him, the second-floor windows are still shot out. He has
replaced one of the panes with a jagged piece of mirror facing
outward, as if to guard against evil spirits. That old African folk
belief would be tested again soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
