</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0485 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4575 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LONNIEHOLLEY-PART4-CO     03-17 1819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONNIEHOLLEY-PART4-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lonnie Holley's boys are going places _ good and bad
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIANA, Ala. _ Lonnie Holley's workshops have as much to do
with redemption as art.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Koontz, an Atlanta psychiatrist who collects his work,
witnessed a remarkable session a few years ago at Laurel Ridge
Elementary School in DeKalb County. Holley's opening line jarred
everyone: He asked the first- and second-graders if any of them had
ever thought of killing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could hear a pin drop,'' Koontz says. ``The adults were
all thinking, `What have we done inviting this man here?'''
</P>
<P>
   Silence hung over the classroom for 30 seconds. Then,
hesitantly, a few hands went up. The artist nodded understandingly
and told the students that, as a young man, he had once felt so bad
that he tried to hurt himself, but that he climbed out of his
despair after he discovered something he was good at _ carving
sandstone. With that, the Sandman took out his hacksaw blade and
showed the kids how to turn rocks into art. By the end of the day,
janitors and cafeteria workers were stopping by to listen.
</P>
<P>
   At 49, Holley has conducted hundreds of workshops over the
years. On the last Thursday in February, he conducted one that must
have been his most heartfelt. It was for teen-agers at the Shelby
County Regional Juvenile Detention Facility in Columbiana. One of
them, locked up since December, was his son Kubra.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING FOR A WAY OUT
</P>
<P>
   It's little wonder that Holley has been thinking lately about
the biblical story of Shadrach, Meshach and Abednego. His three
sons were jailed in December after the golf clubhouse behind their
home was burglarized and burned to the ground. Holley, who was
arrested as well, prays that his boys can come out of the fiery
furnace of crime and punishment unharmed, like the three captives
in the Book of Daniel. Having spent part of his childhood in a
brutal reform school, he knows how detention can singe a young
man's soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``My children are artists,'' he says, ``not criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   As winter warms to spring, this cold passage in Holley's life is
beginning to show the first signs of thaw. His bank account remains
empty, and he may yet serve time for allegedly receiving stolen
goods from the golf course (although his lawyer expects the charge
to be dropped or greatly reduced). The good news is that the
dispute with his neighbors seems to be diminishing; they finally
agreed to pay him rent for the building they have been using as a
juke joint. And the golf course may not sue after all, because
prosecutors hope to make any plea bargains contingent on some
restitution. The payments would be hard to make, but at least
Holley could keep his home.
</P>
<P>
   All those matters still weigh on him. But the matter that has
always weighed most heavily is the question of what happens to his
family. Its fate remains cloudy.
</P>
<P>
   Life is returning to normal for three of his children. Carlonie,
the 12-year-old, is attending her sixth-grade classes more
faithfully. Angela, 20, plans to work on her high school
equivalency degree as she raises her infant son and 3-year-old
daughter at her father's house. A.J., the youngest son, was
released from the transitional juvenile home where he spent most of
the winter. The high-spirited 13-year-old was sentenced to
probation and community service, and has resumed the seventh grade.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the oldest sons, Ezekial and Kubra, who have always
assumed that they would become artists like their father. Both
started drawing when they were in diapers. Both tagged along to art
fairs and museum openings in a dozen states. Both have grown up to
be slender, strikingly handsome young men who show real potential
in their paintings and sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   Ezekial is the quiet one. At 18, he seems to carry a chip on his
shoulder from all the troubles he has seen befall his family. Not
that he hasn't added to them. After the Holleys moved to
Harpersville, he admits, he took part in another car theft _ his
second in two years _ and spent four months in the same reform
school his father had hated four decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Kubra (pronounced co-BAR) is the outgoing one. When he was
arrested in December _ his first serious brush with the law _ he
went to work winning over his new keepers. Rebecca Seals, his
teacher at the juvenile center, was charmed by his personality and
impressed with his drawings. Soon her boss was taking the
16-year-old out of his cellblock and driving him to the Holley home
to fetch sandstone to sculpt.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I drove up,'' says John Miller, director of juvenile
court services, ``I thought, Oh, my God. I mean, I wouldn't want to
be their next-door neighbors. But all of that stuff means something
to them.'' He watched Kubra reach into a 50-gallon drum full of
rainwater and remove some sandstones that had been wrapped in old
sheets and insulation.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the detention center, Seals pointed to one piece and
asked Kubra if he could carve her a lion. She's a Leo. ``Yes,'' he
replied, smoothly. ``I believe I can see the lion in there.''
</P>
<P>
   The juvenile authorities were so taken with Kubra that they
nominated him for the Alabama School of Fine Arts, a magnet program
in Birmingham for gifted children from throughout the state. Seals
pulled together samples of his work and solicited recommendation
letters from museum officials who had worked with Holley. If he
were accepted, Kubra would likely serve at least a month in a
juvenile boot camp, then go to art school in the fall. The
worst-case scenario: He could be rejected and sentenced to the
reform school where his father and Ezekial had been put away.
</P>
<P>
   Being accepted was far from a sure thing. A few years ago,
Ezekial applied to the school and was turned down.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Zeke had gotten in, I don't think he would've gotten into
all this trouble,'' Holley says. ``An idle mind is the devil's
chance to whisper.''
</P>
<P>
   THE PLACES THEY WILL GO
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the workshop, Holley arrived at the juvenile
center looking very different from the way he looks when he's
making art in his yard. His hair was pulled back _ no dreadlocks _
and he wore green slacks, a blue banded-collar shirt and half-moon
glasses on a chain. He could have been Professor Holley.
</P>
<P>
   His lesson, as always, was the transformative power of art.
After Kubra introduced his father, Holley bent copper wire into
mobiles as he told the dozen or so teen-agers about the dicey
childhood that once landed him in a place like this. He sat at a
computer screen and drew faces with the mouse as he talked about
how he found art as a young man. He showed his listeners how to
carve and gave them blocks of sandstone to try for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like magic,'' Holley encouraged as he moved from boy to
boy. ``Your mind is magic.''
</P>
<P>
   When the two-hour session was finished, Miller, the juvenile
services director, was so pleased he fished into his billfold and
presented Holley with an impromptu honorarium of $50.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, the artist returned to visit Kubra, this time with
Ezekial. They were shown into the same classroom, where Kubra's
sandstones and drawings were displayed prominently. His father
smiled and said, ``He's going places, ain't he, Zeke?''
</P>
<P>
   Ezekial nodded. He seemed distracted. Perhaps he was thinking
about the places he might be going.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still want to follow in my father's footsteps,'' he said,
mentioning his interest in drawing and silk-screen printing, ``but
I've just had some problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Ezekial was charged, as an adult, with three felonies and two
misdemeanors in connection with the golf course raid. The two
gravest counts _ theft and arson _ could send him to prison for two
to 20 years apiece. ``I know I'm going to do time,'' he said,
softly.
</P>
<P>
   As Ezekial was contemplating punishment, his little brother
spent much of the winter in counseling with the teacher he calls
Miss Becky. ``Kubra and I have talked a lot about the lessons he
can draw from his family's problems,'' Seals confided. ``He has
seen his father used, abused and refused. But he's second
generation. He can learn about the business end of art and try to
stay away from the negatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Kubra definitely intends to become an artist and talks about
opening a gallery someday. ``I want to make sure my father's name
will not be lost,'' he said. ``I want us to be remembered.''
</P>
<P>
   As his visitors were leaving, Kubra delivered a line you don't
often hear from a juvenile detainee. ``Do you have my card?'' he
asked, digging into his pants pocket to present a colorful design
he had produced on a detention center computer. The focal point was
a surreal profile of his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``You made this?'' Holley said, examining the card with wonder,
as if it were a ten thousand dollar (CQ spelling out of word for
effect/ja) bill. ``You think you could make me one of these, son?''
</P>
<P>
   When word finally came that Kubra had been accepted at the
school of fine arts, he asked his teacher if she could help him
with a subject he needed to know more about. Not art. Math.
</P>
<P>
   THE ASSEMBLAGE OF LIFE
</P>
<P>
   Over the past couple of years, Holley says that he has sometimes
felt like he was watching a movie of his life. He sees a poor
family forced from their home, their yard and sculpture plowed
under. He sees their new home in the country surrounded by
resentful neighbors with guns. He sees his boys slipping out of the
house after midnight to do things he doesn't want to see. He sees
himself sitting in a cell thinking about the movie his life has
become.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, the creative flame has continued to burn within
him. The uprooting, the shooting, the arrests _ like the clutter in
his yard, the pieces of his life are so many materials for art.
</P>
<P>
   After he was released from jail in December, Holley went home
and made an assemblage from a rusty gate and a metal disk that he
called ``Through These Bars I See the Sun.'' When he went back to
jail in February, he fabricated a doll from toilet paper and towel
strings, and carved faces in the soap with his fingernails.
``There's nothing I can't make art from,'' he says, and you get the
feeling he's talking about something more than junk.
</P>
<P>
   Late last month, Holley finally got his hands on some spare cash
and asked a friend to drive him to the nearest Wal-Mart. He bought
$50 worth of generic house paint and set up the cans on a table in
his living room, across from the framed picture of him and Hillary
Clinton at the White House, during the exhibition that featured a
piece of his sculpture. In the same room, 10 weeks before, police
had handcuffed him and taken him to the county jail.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for the first time in months, Holley dipped a brush into a
can and began to paint.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
