</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0486 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4577 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LONNIEHOLLEY-PART3-CO     03-17 2674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONNIEHOLLEY-PART3-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Family in the fire: Artist struggles with crime, consequences
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARPERSVILLE, Ala. _ When Lonnie Holley moved to his new home in
a cotton field outside Birmingham, he noticed that one of his
closest neighbors was a golf course, the Meadows. The adjoining
properties are like living museums of disparate cultures _ the
undulating fairways and close-cropped greens that hark back to
Scotland, the untamed yard of junk and eerie sculpture that harks
back to Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Holley knew something about that other culture. Years before he
emerged as one of the most imaginative Southern folk artists, he
had tended the grounds at a country club in Orlando. Now, looking
out his back yard toward the links, he had an idea: Maybe some of
those fellows in the Easter egg shirts would like to see his art
after they finished playing a round. Maybe he could set up a studio
and call it the 19th Hole. Maybe he'd just go over there and
introduce himself.
</P>
<P>
   He never got the chance. On the morning of Dec. 8, the
superintendent at the Meadows arrived for work before dawn to find
the clubhouse burned down. Police followed muddy golf cart tracks
as they led back to Holley's property and, ultimately, to his three
teen-age sons.
</P>
<P>
   And then the tracks turned on Holley himself.
</P>
<P>
   CHANCES HE NEVER HAD
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the cruelest aspect of Holley's current predicament is
the knowledge that his children got him into it. He is charged with
receiving stolen property: golf shirts, liquor, walkie-talkies and
other items deputies found inside his house. His oldest son is
accused of stealing the goods the night before, with help from his
two younger brothers, and then burning down the clubhouse in a
clumsy attempt to conceal the burglary. Holley says he was asleep
when it happened, sometime after midnight.
</P>
<P>
   In the annals of crime, such an incident might not rate a
footnote to a footnote. Teens stray into foolish destructiveness
all too
</P>
<P>
   often. But for the 49-year-old Holley, the consequences could be
far more serious than they would be for the father of a
middle-class delinquent in posh Atlanta suburbs. In the weeks after
the golf course caper, he worried that he could lose his freedom,
his home, even his family. At his first appearance before a judge,
he broke down in tears.
</P>
<P>
   It was a cold slap in the face to a man who has struggled for 20
years to give his children the chances he never had.
</P>
<P>
   If ever there was a motherless child, in the words of the old
spiritual, it was Lonnie Bradley Holley. The seventh of 27
children, he was taken away from his mother when he was 1 1/2 and
grew up in a blur of foster homes and reform schools. As a young
man, he started out repeating the cycle, fathering 10 children out
of wedlock before he was 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sisters would throw parties for me and introduce me to
girls,'' he says, sheepishly, ``and every time there was a party,
it seemed like there was another baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the babies came in Florida. When he was 15, Holley moved
to Orlando and worked as a cook for most of the next dozen years.
He lived with a woman there and had four children, all in their 20s
now. They stay in touch.
</P>
<P>
   Holley's second family began when he moved back to Alabama in
the late '70s and married a woman visiting from Ohio. Lonnie and
Carolyn Holley had five children together _ three boys and two
girls _ and made their home in an abandoned structure they bought
next to the Birmingham airport. It was a primitive place, with no
electricity or running water before Holley made some modest
improvements. Still, Carolyn grew unhappy with the conditions and
started spending more time with her relatives up North, moving out
for good in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, she was arrested as an accomplice in the
armed robbery of a pizza delivery man in Newark, Ohio. She spent
six years in prison and took a factory job in Cincinnati after she
was paroled. She has no plans to rejoin her husband in Alabama.
``Lonnie wanted me to do art,'' she explains. ``I want to work.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, his wife's absence left Holley motherless again. He
had fathered 15 children and was suddenly left to be both father
and mother to his youngest five, none of whom was older than 10.
Until then, the artist admits, he had drunk excessively _ as much
as two or three bottles of wine a day at the beginning of his
marriage. He could have gone back to the heavy boozing. He could
have turned his kids over to the state. He could have run away.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he says, he sobered up. He took his children to the
Holiness church. He insisted they attend school. He taught them how
to draw and sculpt, and carried them to art fairs so they could
sell their work and buy shoes and clothes with the money. Angela,
the firstborn, kept records of her father's artwork. Ezekial, the
oldest son, liked to paint. Kubra (pronounced coo-BAR) took to
carving, while little brother Arthur James gravitated toward music.
Carlonie, the kid sister, won a blue ribbon at school for a
painting that she said was about ``women who forget to take care of
their children.'' They were handsome youngsters, growing tall and
lean like their daddy, and people were impressed with their polite
manners and creative potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lonnie has been a wonderful father to those children,'' says
Marcia Weber, a Montgomery art dealer who befriended the family.
She remembers visiting Holley when Carlonie would come home from
school and climb into his lap to tell him what she had learned that
day. She was an honors student, and he loved it when she read to
him. Never having made it past the seventh grade, he couldn't read
very well himself.
</P>
<P>
   A VERY BAD NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   The Holleys inhabited one of the oddest worlds a father ever
created for his family. Their home was in the middle of a wooded
acre that looked like something between a junkyard and an enchanted
forest teeming with carved African faces. Through the years, the
thickets of art and scrap multiplied as Holley hauled salvage home
and made found-object assemblages from it. And then, as his
children were entering their teens, their strange, magical world
crumbled around them.
</P>
<P>
   For five years, the Holleys fought the Birmingham airport
expansion that was obliterating all the surrounding houses. Vandals
and thieves picked apart the family's environment, stealing art,
carting off materials, once even breaking into the house to snatch
Christmas gifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard watching what they were doing to my father,'' says
Ezekial, 18, who got into fights with grown men who were trying to
pilfer from their yard.
</P>
<P>
   One theft really set him off. His father, who liked to tinker
with old cars, would bring junkers home and promise a different one
to each child. Ezekial had been pledged a white Chevy Suburban. One
morning it wasn't there; someone had swiped it.
</P>
<P>
   Not long afterward, he and a friend stole a car in Birmingham,
and police caught them. Ezekial was sent to an Alabama boot camp
for juvenile offenders and ordered to pay $3,500 in restitution for
running into the police cruiser that pulled them over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zeke just came unhinged,'' says Atlanta art collector Bill
Arnett, who has been intimately involved with the family for 13
years. ``He had never had any problems until the mid-'90s. Then he
saw all these things happening to his father and their property,
and he started missing school and disappearing for two or three
days at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Things grew worse last year when the family settled with the
airport and moved to a foreclosed house in Harpersville. First
Holley was shot in a dispute with a neighbor. Then all his children
started skipping school. Kubra, 16, missed 43 days of the first
semester alone. Even Carlonie, the 12-year-old honors student,
began staying out.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 8, a juvenile judge warned Holley that if he wanted to
keep his children, the truancy had to stop. He had just returned
from court that afternoon, worried sick, when the police stormed in
with a search warrant.
</P>
<P>
   They found most of the things that had been stolen from the golf
course in Holley's basement. They also found marijuana, smoking
pipes and, out in the yard, a dead dog hanging from the nylon mesh
where, Holley assumes, it had strangled in one of his assemblages.
</P>
<P>
   Father and sons were led away in handcuffs. Kubra and
13-year-old A.J. were taken to a juvenile detention facility.
Ezekial was thrown in jail and charged with theft, arson, burglary
and possession of marijuana. In addition to receiving stolen
property, Holley was charged with cruelty to animals and possession
of marijuana and drug paraphernalia.
</P>
<P>
   The boys have been advised not to talk about what happened that
night, but they have unburdened themselves to their father. ``They
got drunk and went on a late-night ride at the golf course,'' he
says. ``They feel bad about it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Holley does not seem furious with his children, perhaps it is
because he understands their frustrations. ``I got angry with Zeke
when he stole the car. I got angry with Angela when she got
pregnant at 16 and dropped out of school. But I'm not in that angry
mood now,'' he says. ``My children have been through so much. I
think what happened in December, they were getting back at the
community. It was like they were saying, `Daddy, we need to get out
of here.' They were running away from the hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the other charges, Holley admits that Ezekial was smoking
marijuana with some friends. ``I don't do that stuff,'' he says,
noting that it would not be unusual to find paraphernalia in the
house because he sometimes uses it in anti-drug artwork.
</P>
<P>
   The animal cruelty count particularly rankles him. Holley sees
himself as a teacher who has shown thousands of schoolchildren how
to carve sandstone at his workshops. ``I don't want them thinking
the Sandman kills dogs,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   COMING TOGETHER
</P>
<P>
   On a cool February afternoon, Holley was puttering with some
materials in his yard when a car pulled into the driveway. Three
child welfare officers were coming to inspect. He had company and
persuaded them to return later, but the prospect of strangers
probing his domestic life clearly vexed him. Outsiders might not
understand.
</P>
<P>
   The Holley home is dedicated to the proposition that every child
is an artist waiting to blossom. The inside of the house feels as
jumbled and untidy as the yard. Daddy planned it that way. Every
room is cluttered with scrap or drawing paper or cans of paint,
because the urge to create can strike anywhere. That burnt smell in
the kitchen isn't cookies; it's a gingerbread man Carlonie
fashioned from mud and popped into the microwave. She's always
making something as she half-watches the TV that blares in the
living room.
</P>
<P>
   As unusual as it looks and smells, the home radiates the
unmistakable warmth of old-fashioned family love. The Holleys are
close, and the misfortunes of the past year seem to have pulled
them closer. The child welfare inspectors picked up on it. ``Mr.
Holley loves his children and wants them in his house,'' one report
said. ``The children love their father and respect his art.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that day, Holley and half his brood piled into a
reporter's car to visit Kubra at the juvenile detention center in
the county seat of Columbiana. A.J. squeezed into the back seat
with Angela and a friend of hers and Carlonie, who held her
20-year-old sister's infant son in her lap. (Ezekial, out on bail,
was staying with an aunt.) After a stop for chips and Mello Yellos,
the conversation took an unexpected turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angela,'' her father instructed, ``tell him about the bus.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems that a week after the golf course incident, Angela was
visiting her mother in Cincinnati and got into a fight with a bus
driver who had closed the door in her mother's face. She was
charged with disorderly conduct and spent the night behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like Rosa Parks,'' Angela said, in a defiant tone that
hints at how the incident might have happened.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see: four arrests in Alabama, one in Ohio _ that would
leave Carlonie the only family member unhassled by the authorities,
right?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Holley answered, with uncommon honesty, ``the
juveniles were on me about her about missing school, so I guess she
was in trouble, too.''
</P>
<P>
   At the detention center, father and son disappeared into the
Plexiglas visiting room to talk with Kubra, as the rest of them
tried to watch through a tiny security-mesh window. Then the girls
got a chance to hug their brother. Everyone was quiet as they came
out and the heavy door slammed shut behind them.
</P>
<P>
   On the way home, the conversation took another unexpected turn.
Holley mentioned that he had one more brush with law and order in
December _ this time as a victim. When he was released after two
nights in jail, he returned home to discover that someone had
broken in and stolen his family's Christmas gifts _ A.J. and
Carlonie's bicycles, everything. It was just like being back at the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   Most fathers would have reported such an incident. Holley didn't
bother. ``I didn't want to see the police just then,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   `HE NEEDS TO LOSE ALL THAT'
</P>
<P>
   The law is only one of Holley's worries.
</P>
<P>
   On a hill less than a mile behind his house, at the end of a
winding lane grandly named Plantation Drive, there's a rectangle of
naked earth where the clubhouse and pro shop of the Meadows once
stood. It was a custom manufactured doublewide, 55 by 28 feet, with
a large deck on the back. Now there's a single trailer parked on
the ashes, looking less like a clubhouse than a construction
office.
</P>
<P>
   Elbert Buckelew, the course's majority owner, estimates the loss
at more than $100,000. ``Unfortunately,'' he says, ``we were
somewhat underinsured.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckelew is not ignorant of his neighbor's fame. His wife was
head of the Jefferson County Commission in Birmingham when a group
of arts lovers asked the panel to help move Holley's environment
from the path of the airport expansion. The request was denied.
It's safe to say that Buckelew would not have been a likely
candidate for Holley's idea about inviting golfers over to see his
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same people who appreciate his art probably liked that pee
in the bottle,'' Buckelew says, referring to Andres Serrano's
``Piss Christ,'' the crucifix-in-urine piece that Sen. Jesse Helms
crucified as an example of the horrors of government funding for
the arts.
</P>
<P>
   But this isn't about taste in art, Bucklelew says. This is about
property rights and wrongs.
</P>
<P>
   It has happened to him before. He used to be a pharmacist and
was robbed at gunpoint three times. The golf course itself was
burglarized last fall before the arson. ``We were robbed _ I don't
have a problem with that,'' he says. ``But, dammit, why'd they have
to burn it down? I don't care if he's a damn Picasso, he's got to
be responsible for his kids.''
</P>
<P>
   To recover his losses, Buckelew is considering suing Holley
under an Alabama law that holds parents accountable for the actions
of their children. ``I find it hard to fathom that he didn't know
something about what his sons were doing,'' he says. ``We need to
see if he was involved in any way. Because if he was, he needs to
lose all that.''
</P>
<P>
   He means Holley's property, the white-columned house and 16
acres he bought for $91,500. Holley may rue the day he moved to
Harpersville, into an area known for crack-dealing, onto a street
where he would be assaulted, into a school district his children
would despise. But this is the only home he's got, the only thing
of tangible value that he has to show for 20 years of making art
and raising a family against the odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all I've been through, I don't need to be losing this,''
Holley says. ``If I lose this ...''
</P>
<P>
   He draws a deep breath and falls silent. He cannot bear to
finish the thought.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
