</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990317.0487 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4578 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LONNIEHOLLEY-PART2-CO     03-17 2185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONNIEHOLLEY-PART2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lonnie Holley has rich imagination but thin wallet
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    WITH SEE-ART sidebar at end of file
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ It's not easy to create art when a neighbor
is shooting at you. Yet somehow, in the midst of such troubles, the
acclaimed folk artist Lonnie Holley managed to make enough
paintings and sculptures for a show of his work last fall. The
pieces, priced from $170 to $5,000, sold reasonably well and
provided virtually his only income for 1998. The remaining works
are still on display at the Monty Stabler Galleries, a posh salon
in the upscale Birmingham suburb of Homewood.
</P>
<P>
   As she flips through the paintings _ all of them on paper _
Stabler wishes she had more on canvas, but knows why she doesn't.
``Lonnie works on what he can afford,'' she says. ``He can't afford
canvas.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years into a career that has brought him national
recognition, Lonnie Holley has no money. His phone has been cut off
several times. He owes his lawyer, his oldest son's lawyer, the
hospital that treated him after he was wounded, the ambulance
service that took him to the hospital. His '87 Dodge van was
repossessed in January. His '74 Chevy van, in need of a new
transmission, sat in the driveway for weeks like another of his
found objects.
</P>
<P>
   One day last month, Holley was crouched in front of his house
working on a carving when his 12-year-old daughter, Carlonie,
walked up with the mail. Good, maybe there was a check. He ripped
into a promising-looking letter and rolled his eyes. It was a $72
fine for driving with a busted headlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be self-sufficient,'' he said. ``I thought I had
enough art out there to support us. But it looks like I might be
going back on food stamps, and I hate that.''
</P>
<P>
   `WE AIN'T BOOKKEEPERS'
</P>
<P>
   The perpetually struggling artist is a figure as old as clay.
Perhaps nowhere in the art world is the stereotype more fitting
than in the realm of folk art. Like the blues singers of old, the
self-taught artists of the South have invented a fresh, personal
form of expression from the rough material of their lives. And like
those blues pioneers, their work has seldom brought prosperity to
them or their families.
</P>
<P>
   As folk art has grown more popular during the 1980s and '90s, a
few artists have fared well _ Georgia's Howard Finster and
Alabama's Thornton Dial, for example. But most remained poor or
close to it. Many felt that they had been taken advantage of by
collectors who paid too little or dealers who took works on
consignment and kept most of the proceeds when they sold at greatly
inflated prices.
</P>
<P>
   Today, at the annual Folk Fest in Atlanta or the Outsider Art
Fair in New York, conversations often turn to the hard-luck tales
behind the work. You might hear that Joe Light, a Memphis painter,
has filed for bankruptcy again. Or that Richard Burnside, a painter
in Pendleton, S.C., is still living in a shack worthy of a Walker
Evans photo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad story,'' says New Orleans dealer Richard Gasperi.
``It looks like the artists are getting ripped off, and sometimes
they are. But usually it has more to do with them having large
families to support and not knowing how to handle money.''
</P>
<P>
   Gasperi once tried to help an artist named David Butler, an
elderly disabled laborer who was living in crude conditions in
Morgan City, La. ``I gave him money and tried to get him to improve
his house, but it went straight to family members who were using
drugs. I couldn't intervene and change things.''
</P>
<P>
   When Butler died two years ago, Gasperi says, he was penniless.
</P>
<P>
   Holley is only 49 and certainly has the talent to escape such a
fate. The question is whether he has the savvy _ or can find
someone who does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and Lonnie, we don't know how to do business,'' says
Holley's longtime friend Charlie Lucas, an Alabama sculptor who has
not mastered the art of making ends meet either. ``We ain't
bookkeepers. We don't have secretaries. We're very rich people; we
just don't have none of the money.''
</P>
<P>
   `WE BELONG IN THE DIRT'
</P>
<P>
   Before he became an artist in 1979, Holley earned solid wages as
a cook and construction worker. Those were jobs. When he discovered
art, he saw it as a calling. Unfortunately, the sandstone
priesthood didn't pay as well as blue-collar work. Holley estimates
that he has never cleared more than $21,000 a year as an artist
(although friends who have helped support the family believe the
amount must be higher). The federal poverty level for a single
parent supporting five children is $21,373.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Holley's patronage has come from one man, Atlanta
collector Bill Arnett, a bespectacled 59-year-old whose combative
personality and zealous pursuit of folk art have made him one of
the most controversial names in the field. Arnett first beheld
Holley's environment in 1986 and was so moved that he agreed to
advance the artist a regular income in exchange for the right of
first refusal on his symbolic assemblages. Arnett reckons that he
has paid Holley well over $100,000 since then and has received
perhaps 200 sculptures and 50 to 100 paintings in return.
</P>
<P>
   Once, early on, Arnett tried to persuade Holley to move his
family from their primitive home at the Birmingham airport to a
much nicer farmhouse near Villa Rica, Ga. He even offered to
finance the purchase. But the thought of dwelling in such
middle-class surroundings made Holley uncomfortable, and he backed
out, telling Arnett, ``We belong in the dirt.''
</P>
<P>
   After the airport ousted him a year and a half ago, Holley got a
middle-class home, in Harpersville, whether he wanted it or not.
But he no longer had Arnett's financial support.
</P>
<P>
   The collector says he is nearly broke from years of acquiring
art and supporting Holley and more than a dozen other artists
across the South. Arnett's latest project, self-publishing a lavish
book about self-taught artists, has left him so strapped that he
says he'll have to sell his house on a very expensive street near
the Governor's Mansion in Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't given Lonnie a penny in three years,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Arnett did take more than 75 assemblages for a
re-creation of Holley's environment in ``Souls Grown Deep,'' the
Olympic Arts Festival exhibition that was drawn from his
collection. Arnett says they belong to Holley and he is storing
them for safekeeping. Holley does not object to the arrangement; he
figures the pieces would have vanished if they had stayed at his
airport property as the thieves and bulldozers were closing in. Now
there's talk of putting some of the work up for sale at an Atlanta
show.
</P>
<P>
   As much as Holley's alliance with Arnett has helped him, it may
have hampered him in other ways. Some dealers have shied away from
the artist because of the perception that they were poaching on
Arnett's territory. ``I like Lonnie's work very much,'' says Robert
Cargo, a veteran dealer in Tuscaloosa, ``but I was uncomfortable
with the thought that someone else was getting his best work.''
</P>
<P>
   The roots of Holley's money problems go much deeper than one
relationship, however.
</P>
<P>
   Some galleries have found the logistics of dealing with him too
taxing. ``He was never easy to get on the phone, and you never knew
whether he was going to be there if you went,'' says New York
dealer Luise Ross, who last showed Holley's work in 1994. ``He's a
very good artist, but is he good enough that I should go crazy to
get his stuff?''
</P>
<P>
   Others have found Holley's art difficult to sell. While his
colorful paintings and sinuous sandstones have fetched as much as
$5,000, the conceptual sculptures he makes from trash are another
matter.
</P>
<P>
   Curators and critics adore Holley's junk. His assemblages are
the pieces that usually end up in museums, from the Smithsonian
Institution to the High Museum of Art in Atlanta. Holley may mangle
the king's English when he speaks, but he has a rare eloquence when
he employs his visual vocabulary. ``He uses objects like a poet
uses words,'' says Joanne Cubbs, the High's first folk art curator,
who was amazed by Holley's ability to improvise ideas and meanings
from the humblest of materials. She once saw him take a hanger, a
ratty T-shirt, a plastic flower and a rusty lock, and create a
moving assemblage about remembering a dead child. Family, religion,
racial pride, the environment _ his sculpture is always about
something. ``I've never met anyone who can spin ideas from almost
nothing the way he does,'' Cubbs says.
</P>
<P>
   As thought-provoking as such work can be in a museum, it isn't
the sort of thing many people want in their homes. Dealers say
there is little market for Holley's assemblages. They are not cute
like so much popular folk art. In fact, they can be grim and
disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time I got there and he was making this assemblage out of
IV needles,'' says Montgomery gallery owner Marcia Weber. ``I
wouldn't touch it with a 10-foot pole. Think of the liability. It
may have been a great work of art, but I can't imagine anyone
buying medical waste to put in their living room.''
</P>
<P>
   There's one other reason for Holley's money woes. Almost
everyone who knows him believes he can be too generous for his own
good.
</P>
<P>
   Holley has contributed to the United Negro College Fund and to
famine relief at the same time he was haunting supermarket loading
docks to get out-of-date groceries to feed his family. He has
always given money and meals to relatives and neighbors, even those
who treated him shabbily.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Holley, his estranged wife, remembers how people scoffed
at the weird environment they inhabited in Birmingham. ``They'd
call him the voodoo man. But those same people, whenever they
wanted something to drink or some food or money, they'd come to
Lonnie because they knew he'd help.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Holley is looking for someone to help him.
</P>
<P>
   TRYING TO 'STOP THE BLEEDING'
</P>
<P>
   For years, Holley has asked acquaintances in the art world if
they would assist him in managing his affairs. A long line of good
Samaritans has come to his aid, but no one ever had the time or
stamina to stay with it. This winter, as Holley's life scraped
bottom, the lawyers who represented him in his airport battle found
a new recruit.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Lasseter, an owlish Birmingham furniture maker who has
known Holley for a few years, read about his arrest in the December
golf course burglary and drove to Harpersville to see whether the
family had enough food. He ended up delivering considerably more
than dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm Lonnie's manager,'' he says, with the wry smile of
a man who got more than he bargained for. ``It's taken over my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past six weeks, in addition to his regular job, Lasseter
has been driving the Holleys to stores, courts, jails and
junkyards. He has confronted their hostile neighbors over the
building they refuse to vacate even though it's on Holley's
property. And he is working with Arnett to contact galleries across
the nation in an effort to account for any art Holley might have
out on consignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lonnie is one of the most decent people I've ever met,''
Lasseter says. ``I'm doing everything I can to ease his mind and
let him get back to his art. People have taken advantage of him.
I'm just trying to stop the bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   The triage has not been simple.
</P>
<P>
   One Saturday last month, Arnett drove over from Atlanta to meet
Lasseter and Holley for dinner at Richey's B-B-Q in Harpersville.
As they talked about how to get his career restarted, Arnett showed
them proofs of his book. Holley was excited to see slick color
reproductions of so much of his work.
</P>
<P>
   They were walking out to the parking lot afterward when a
policeman intercepted them. He was polite; he had noticed them
inside and didn't want to interrupt their conference ... but the
thing was, well, there was another warrant out for Holley's arrest.
It seems he had missed a juvenile hearing for his sons.
</P>
<P>
   Holley winced. He remembered. Some child welfare workers had
dropped by to inspect the house that day, and he had just plain
forgotten about court.
</P>
<P>
   The artist was taken straight from his barbecued chicken plate
to jail, where he spent the next three nights locked up, wondering
what else could go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO SEE THE ART OF LONNIE HOLLEY
</P>
<P>
   _ The High Museum of Art owns two assemblages. The smaller one,
``Obstacles Before the Goal,'' is on view as part of ``Multiple
Choices: Themes and Variations in Our Collection.'' 1280 Peachtree
St. N.E., Atlanta, Ga. 404-733-4444.
</P>
<P>
   _ Barbara Archer Gallery. Various works. 1123 Zonolite Road
N.E., Suite 27, Atlanta, Ga. 404-815-1545.
</P>
<P>
   _ Monty Stabler Galleries. Sandstone carvings, paintings on
paper, wire mobiles. 1811 29th Ave. S., Birmingham, Ala.
205-879-9888.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet
</P>
<P>
   Many sites carry information and pictures of folk art. One of
the most varied is North Georgia's Rosehips Gallery at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .rosehipsart.com/index.htmart
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
