<HEADER>
A4579 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-RESIGN-NYT &LR;      03-17 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-RESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELLING DETAILS IN REPORT THAT FELLED EUROPEAN GROUP
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium &UR;  &LR; _ As a retired dentist from the French
provincial town of Chatellerault, Rene Berthelot had no obvious
qualifications to work as a scientific adviser to the 15-nation
European Union.
</P>
<P>
   But work he did, for three years, earning close to $200,000 and
undertaking no less than 13 ``missions'' to Chatellerault, during
which time he produced no report of even remote value to the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
   What Berthelot did do, it seems, is help out Edith Cresson, the
former French prime minister who, as the European Union's
commissioner for education and training, hired him in 1995. Ms.
Cresson also happened to be the mayor of Chatellerault until the
end of 1997 and an old friend of the dentist.
</P>
<P>
   Berthelot's activities _ or lack of them _ figure prominently in
an independent report published this week on the European
Commission, the Brussels-based executive body that controls a wide
range of European policy. The ``fictitious nature of his scientific
advice,'' as the report described Berthelot's contribution, at the
expense of European taxpayers illustrates the failings that led all
20 commissioners to resign.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps more extraordinary than his deeds is the reaction of
Ms. Cresson, who has said she feels ``satisfied'' with her
``considerable achievements.'' In her defiance, it seems, a gulf
has been revealed between the old pliant political culture of
Europe and an emerging one that is far less tolerant of cronyism.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, with the Cold War over, moral concerns in European
politics have grown where strategic imperatives were once
paramount, bringing first a political revolution in Italy driven by
a magistrate, then investigations of corruption in France, Spain
and Belgium, and, this week, the collapse of the European
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Olivier Duhamel, a French political scientist, warned Wednesday
of ``a Ken Starrization of European politics.'' But the real issue
seems to be the demands for accountability among the more than 300
million citizens of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cresson, a 65-year-old Socialist, is a product of the
Mitterrand era, one marked by corruption scandals that are still
under investigation and a style of rule that sometimes appeared to
place the Elysee Palace and its acolytes beyond the law.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Santer of Luxembourg, the commission president, and at
61 a man of the same political generation as Ms. Cresson, also
appeared to misread the continent's mood. On Tuesday, the day after
the report's publication, he said he was ``whiter than white,''
although the report accuses him of being ``evasive'' and
``misleading'' in response to inquiries from the European
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   His appearance of stonewalling evidently failed to impress a new
generation of leaders _ including Prime Minister Tony Blair of
Britain and Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder of Germany, who said
Wednesday that there was no possibility of Santer's being
reinstated and made clear that the search for a successor had
begun.
</P>
<P>
   Santer changed his tone Wednesday, approving a commission
statement that said, ``We request member states to name a new
commission without delay.'' It added that while the departing
20-member executive body would not take ``any new political
initiatives.''
</P>
<P>
   What becomes clear in the 144-page report prepared by a
five-member panel is that, with $100 billion a year to spend, the
European Union had undertaken many initiatives: aid for countries
in the southern Mediterranean, aid for vocational training, and
other areas.
</P>
<P>
   But the commission, which oversees a 17,000-member bureaucracy,
had neither the trained personnel nor the commitment to openness in
financial matters to insure that the initiatives were properly
controlled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commission has seen its direct management responsibilities
increase substantially,'' the report said. But ``its administrative
and financial culture'' have not ``developed at the same speed.''
</P>
<P>
   More than $2 million was lost or misspent, the report says,
after the commission entered into contracts with three companies
(two of which were controlled by the third Luxembourg-based
company), for the distribution of aid in the former Yugoslavia and
in the Rift Valley of Africa. In fact, none of the contracted
services were ever performed.
</P>
<P>
   Another contract with a French company called Agenor that was
supposed to provide ``technical assistance'' for a $600 million
program of vocational training started in 1995 turned out to be a
thinly disguised cover for fraud, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   Double or fraudulent invoicing, wildly inflated fees, a printing
contract with a company that did not in fact exist _ all this was
standard practice at Agenor, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite an audit in July 1997, and repeated requests for
corrective action to Ms. Cresson, who oversaw the program, the
situation was allowed to fester for more than a year. It was on
this matter that Santer also proved ``evasive'' when questioned by
the European Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course these matters are grave,'' said Patrick Child, a
spokesman for Yves Thibault de Silguy, a French commissioner. ``But
there is some regret here that a wholesale portrait of a shambles
has been drawn as a result of the actions of a few people.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the report's conclusion that nobody with ``the
slightest sense of responsibility'' appears exaggerated to those
who believe that there are many dedicated servants of Europe at the
commission. But the high moral tone of the investigators accurately
reflects a new European mood that the commission failed to read
before it was too late.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
