<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4580 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAIN-VICTIMS-NYT &LR;      03-17 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAIN-VICTIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASH VICTIMS' FAMILIES FIND SOLACE IN FAITH AND PRAYER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., Tenn., Ill., La.)  (Eds: See also TRAIN-CRASH) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE with BILL DEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NESBIT, Miss. _ No one here ever truly understood how June
Bonnin managed to stay alive, holding cancer at bay, refusing all
treatment and relying on prayer to consume her tumors and growths.
But she did survive, building a splendid white inn here with the
extra years granted to her, and the delight she took in beating the
odds magnified the impact on her friends of her sudden death on
Monday night on the Amtrak train that crashed outside of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bonnin, 46, along with her 11-year-old granddaughter,
Jessica Whitaker, and two young girls from this same rural suburb
of Memphis, Tenn., Rainey Lipscomb, 10, and her sister Lacey, 8,
were aboard the sleeper car that took the brunt in the wreck, which
killed them and is believed to have killed seven others. They had
gone to Chicago, with four other family members, for a long
weekend, touring the aquarium and the Children's Museum. The girls
were particularly thrilled to have visited a store that sells
American Girls historical dolls, their favorites.
</P>
<P>
   The Lipscombs and the Bonnins, neighbors and best of friends,
shared substantial prosperity and a love of the lakes of
northwestern Mississippi. They both owned large properties here in
DeSoto County, at the edge of Memphis' growth south into the
sloping farmland of Mississippi. But what tied their lives
together, particularly in the final years, was a deep religious
faith that family members repeatedly called on Wednesday in an
effort to fathom three very short lives and one that had been
extended.
</P>
<P>
   ``June amazed me, all the time,'' said Ada Johnston, a neighbor
and friend who held her 50th wedding anniversary party at the Bonne
Terre Country Inn, a luxurious bed-and-breakfast on 50 acres owned
by the Bonnin family, which drew a devoted clientele from several
nearby states. ``She was an upright Christian woman, which I guess
is what kept her going,'' Ms. Johnston continued. ``She fought so
hard and now it's all over in a train wreck. So sad.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Mrs. Bonnin was told she had advanced non-Hodgkin's
lymphoma, which is usually fatal. Her doctors urged her to undergo
chemotherapy and radiation, but even though she was brought up a
Roman Catholic and had never believed in faith healing, she decided
to seek treatment only through prayer and natural medication. After
a tumor the size of a golf ball was found in her brain in 1997, she
refused to have it removed. Mrs. Bonnin's doctors told The Memphis
Commercial-Appeal last year that they did not know how she had
survived. Everyone else in Mrs. Bonnin's natural-treatment group
died, but Mrs. Bonnin remained well enough that many guests at
Bonne Terre never knew of her illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you didn't know she was sick, you would never have been
able to tell,'' said Erling Jensen, a Memphis chef whom Ms. Bonnin
and her husband, Max, hired to consult on the inn's menu of roasted
meats and seafood. ``She seemed like a 19-year-old, always laughing
and running around the grounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Max Bonnin, 44, said Wednesday that he would get through his
ordeal the same way she did.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's in a place she's dreamed about, and everyone up in
heaven is having a good time with her,'' Bonnin said. ``Her
successful battle with cancer has been a result of faith in God and
friends. That's how we got through, and that's how we'll get
through this.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Lipscomb, the father of the two girls who died on the
train, said his family, members of the United Methodist Church,
were in a prayer group with the Bonnins, and shared a faith that he
considered life-giving.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way I can sit here and talk with you about this is
that I have the assurance of knowing that our little girls are with
Jesus,'' Lipscomb said Wednesday, after returning from Illinois,
where he identified their bodies. ``Just a week ago, we had what we
now know was a little gift given to us by God _ one of the girls
was asking us a lot of questions about what heaven would be like.
As bizarre as that sounds, that was not a coincidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Lipscomb, whose family owns the largest independent insurance
agency in Tennessee, said the girls played tennis and went fishing.
Rainey played a Von Trapp child in a recent school production of
``The Sound of Music.'' Before the girls headed to the sleeping car
to join Mrs. Bonnin and Jessica, Lipscomb said, they gave their
mother, Cindy, who was in a different car, a thank-you note for the
week and they also thanked her for letting them stay in the
sleeping car that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just getting ready to go to bed when it hit,'' said
Jessica's mother, Kelley Whitaker, 31, who went back to the
railroad tracks Wednesday with Bonnin to lay a wreath.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnin said he and his wife had planned to build a white prayer
chapel with a steeple at Bonne Terre. He said he may still build
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
