<HEADER>
A4581 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELECTRIC-COX     03-17 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTRIC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bill to deregulate most of the state's electric industry OK'd
 &HT;    By Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A bill to deregulate most of the state's $17 billion electric
industry won easy approval from the Texas Senate on Wednesday, but
almost four hours of debate and several dozen amendments by
senators revealed some nagging doubts that likely will be aired
more fully in the House.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, by Sen. David Sibley, R-Waco, got final approval on a
voice vote with only three senators registering their opposition:
Sen. Gonzalo Barrientos, D-Austin; Sen. Carlos Truan, D-Corpus
Christi; and Sen. Drew Nixon, R-Carthage.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Senate finished work on Sibley's bill early
Wednesday evening, the man who will carry it in the House, state
Rep. Steve Wolens, D-Dallas, perched on the brass rail surrounding
the senators' desks watching the closing minutes of the debate.
Wolens, chairman of the House State Affairs Committee, said he
expects the committee to take up the bill in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Under Sibley's deregulation bill, customers of investor-owned
utilities would automatically get a 5 percent rate cut when
competition begins Jan. 1, 2002 _ saving them as much as $800
million, Sibley said. Consumers also should be able to buy power at
an additional 10 percent off or more from competitors ``if they're
willing to shop,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers who want to stick with their old utility could; no one
would be required to switch.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jane Nelson, R-Flower Mound, said that competition would
bring ``not only lower rates but improved service.''
</P>
<P>
   Only investor-owned utilities would be required to open
themselves to competition. The Austin City Council would retain the
power to decide whether to open its utility, Austin Energy, to
competition. Likewise, other municipalities and electric
cooperatives such as Pedernales Electric Cooperative Inc. also
would be able to decide for themselves whether they wanted to
participate in a competitive market.
</P>
<P>
   One amendment added by Sibley was of special interest to Austin:
the state will not sell power generated with fuels from state lands
to state and local government agencies in areas not opened to
competition. Austin Energy had feared the original provision,
expected to generate money for public education as well as cut
utility costs for governments which buy the power, would cut into
the extensive business it does with state government here.
</P>
<P>
   Barrientos said he voted against the bill, however, because no
residential or small business customer called on him for the right
to shop for power. He also voted against it, he said, because
``when my gut, my intuition has a question, I vote no.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Nixon said, ``I don't see the great public necessity
for what we're doing here.'' Only the utility companies and their
big industrial consumers want competition, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of unease about the impact of opening the electric
business to competition in Texas came in two other ways. One was an
amendment by Sen. Bill Ratliff, R-Mt. Pleasant, chairman of the
Senate Finance Committee. His amendment would have allowed a city
government to declare itself the representative of all residential
and small business consumers in its jurisdiction in order to buy
power for them wholesale.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff said he knew industrial and other big business customers
could take care of themselves, but he worried that many a
residential and small business customer, especially in smaller
towns, would be ``left to find for himself or herself without any
negotiating leverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Sibley, who seldom differs with Ratliff, opposed the amendment,
saying that the Dallas and Houston city councils, ``or some other
benevolent group,'' could keep too many customers who want to shop
for power from doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff's amendment was defeated on a voice vote.
</P>
<P>
   Another sign of unease about the deregulation bill was
indicative in an amendment proposed by Barrientos, to shift more of
an estimated $3.3 billion in stranded costs from residential to
commercial and industrial customers. Stranded cost is the
difference between what the utilities invested in their facilities,
mostly nuclear power plants, and their market value, which is
expected to be much less.
</P>
<P>
   The Barrientos amendment failed, but by the relatively narrow
margin of 19-12.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those ruffles, Sibley had clear command of the Senate.
Without exception, if he favored an amendment, it passed; if he
didn't, it failed.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Sen. Steve Ogden, R-Bryan, proposed an amendment to
require municipally owned utilities to notify their customers if
they decide not to open themselves to competition. The public,
Ogden said, ``should be fully informed about what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Eddie Lucio, D-Brownsville, who rose to object that Ogden
was trying to ``strongarm municipals to opt into the marketplace.''
Brownsville and Bryan both have city-owned utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Sibley opposed the amendment, and it died after the Senate set
it aside on a voice vote. One amendment that did pass was proposed
by Sen. Royce West, D-Dallas to bar electric competitors from
refusing service to a customer because of ``race, creed, color,
national origin, ancestry, sex, marital status, lawful source of
income, disability or familial status.'' Nor could a provider
refuse a customer because he or she lives in a low-income area.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Bruce Hight at bhight(at)statesman.com or
445-3977.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
