<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIPPO-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KETCHUM TAKES ON HOW TO REMAKE ZIPPOS AS SOMETHING OTHER THAN
LIGHTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa.)  (af) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The assignment was not exactly straightforward: create an
advertising campaign that recasts the famous Zippo lighter as
something _ anything _ other than a lighter. And, most importantly,
aim the campaign at young people, but not too young.
</P>
<P>
   Ketchum Advertising Pittsburgh accepted the challenge. Employing
the theme ``Use it to start something,'' an ambitious new campaign
shows Zippos lighting birthday candles, romantic fires on the beach
and even conversations.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not cigarette lighters; they are ignition devices,''
St. Lee James, creative director at Ketchum Advertising Pittsburgh,
part of Omnicom Group, said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   While the lighters could be used to ignite cigarettes, he
acknowledged, ``I like to think of it as portable fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to attract significantly younger buyers _ Zippo's current
customers average 45 years old _ Zippo has introduced a decidedly
irreverent print and television campaign toeing a very fine line
between promoting its lighters and promoting smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a really weird position for me because I don't want to be
advocating cigarette smoking, but people are still going to light
cigarettes with them,'' James said. ``The hope was to find
alternative uses for the product and not link it to cigarette
smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the campaign is aimed squarely at 21- to
26-year-olds, a generation perhaps unfamiliar with Zippo's place in
American culture. The Zippo Manufacturing Co., based in Bradford,
Pa., was founded in 1932 and gained notice in World War II when the
lighters became popular among American soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Zippos have become a staple of a community of
collectors. In fact, 21 percent of owners are lighter collectors,
according to the company.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is estimated to cost $10 million, which is by far
the largest advertising budget ever for the family-owned company.
It began running in the fall and returns next week with a new
series of print, television and outdoor ads.
</P>
<P>
   The push to use humor and sophisticated imagery for Zippo is
meant to convey a new sense of nicotine-free cool. For example, the
print ads include images of a surfer meditating on an exotic beach
encircled by candles and a young couple lying on a couch at a
trendy lounge bar, staring into the flame of the Zippo lighter
seemingly transfixed.
</P>
<P>
   The print ads have appeared or will appear in Details, Detour,
Elle, Entertainment Weekly, Maxim, P.O.V., Premiere, Spin, Rolling
Stone and Vibe magazines.
</P>
<P>
   The television commercials, blending humor with bizarre plot
twists, are aimed directly at the MTV generation. In all four
spots, a fictitious character referred to as ``Zippo Guy'' gets in
trouble using his Zippo in outlandish situations. In one
commercial, he is caught by two farmhands trying to light the
excreted gas from a cow.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to recent studies the ozone layer is rapidly
depleting,'' Zippo Guy is heard saying. ``The main cause for this
phenomenon is the mass release of bovine gases. Igniting these
gases early on will keep them form rising into the ozone.'' He
adds, ``I will save the planet for the ages.`
</P>
<P>
   The commercials have run or are running on the Comedy Central,
ESPN, ESPN2 and MTV cable networks.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Zippo's traditionally older customers, Patrick
Grandy, marketing communications manager for Zippo, said, ``If they
don't get it, that's OK, because it's not a message that was
directed and designed for them in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``I don't think we're turning them off.''
</P>
<P>
   Other media vehicles for the campaign include radio commercials
that ran in the fall during the Howard Stern syndicated morning
radio show, a Web site (www.zippomfg.com) and postcards aimed at
college students.
</P>
<P>
   Outdoor advertising is being added to the mix with posters to
appear on telephone kiosks throughout Manhattan; Zippo hopes to
expand the posters to include Los Angeles by next fall.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the campaign's mandate not to promote cigarette smoking,
one publication, The Source, a hip-hop magazine for young people,
declined to run the ads after briefly entering into talks with
Zippo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a policy not to accept any liquor or tobacco
advertisements in the magazine,'' said Peter Ferraro, associate
publisher for advertising at The Source.
</P>
<P>
   ``When push came to shove I sat down with the publisher and we
decided not to take it,'' he added, ``because in the end you know
anyone is going to associate a lighter with lighting cigarettes.
And whether they had a surfer lighting candles on the beach or
somebody lighting birthday candles, it was still just a little too
close to comfort for us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our 16- and 18-year-old kids are at an age when they are
making decisions about whether or not to smoke,'' Ferraro said.
``What do you do with a lighter? You know?''
</P>
</TEXT>
