<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-PAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PER DIEMS IN HOUSE MAY BE GOOD, BUT A VOTE ON THEM ISN'T
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif. )   (nk) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There are few things members of Congress want more
than a raise and little they like less than to be seen voting for
one.
</P>
<P>
   This year Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., chairman of the committee
that sets the rules for expense accounts, began shopping around for
a way to solve the conundrum.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas proposed having his committee change the rules so that
representatives, if they chose to, could pocket a portion of their
expense accounts tax free in the form of a $125 per diem. The
matter would never have to come to a vote.
</P>
<P>
   But The Hill, a weekly newspaper about Congress, got wind of the
plan and published an account of it Wednesday. By the afternoon, it
stood about as much chance of being carried out as a surtax on
comb-overs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This dog ain't going to hunt,'' said a top staff assistant who
had taken soundings on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, who heads the Committee on House Administration, did not
return telephone calls. He issued a statement Wednesday night
saying that his committee would consider the per diem proposal only
if it had the approval of the leadership of both parties, which by
then it clearly did not.
</P>
<P>
   John P. Feehery, a spokesman for Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, said
the speaker had not endorsed the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Nichols, a spokeswoman for Rep. Dick Gephardt, the
Democratic leader, said Gephardt had told the speaker he would
think about the proposal but would support it only if a vote was
allowed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Congress thought it had solved the pay problem once and
for all.
</P>
<P>
   Under a measure passed that year, lawmakers became entitled to
an automatic annual raise _ 0.5 percentage points less than the
employment cost index, a measure of inflation that many businesses
use to give their workers cost of living raises.
</P>
<P>
   For a few years, this worked. But almost every year since 1993,
one representative or another has proposed that the raise be
blocked. That required a vote. And except for 1997, the lawmakers
denied themselves the automatic pay increase.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives and senators now make $136,700 a year. They also
get an expense account, or representational allowance, that ranges
from $859,000 to $1.3 million. The money is used for rents and
other office expenses, air fares home and other costs.
</P>
<P>
   The actual amount is based on factors including how far their
district is from Washington and how much it costs to rent office
space in their districts.
</P>
<P>
   Under Thomas' plan, representatives would have been permitted to
dip into this account and pay themselves $125 every day the House
was in session. If the House met 160 days during a year _ an
average of four days a week for 40 weeks _ that would amount to
$20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Per diems are common practice in state legislatures, where
salaries are generally lower. In his statement, Thomas said he had
often been asked by colleagues why the House did not have a similar
allowance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a good question, which is why members of both parties
have discussed this,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
