<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOPANTS-COURT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKIRT'S THE ISSUE IN THIS COURT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LAURA VOZZELLA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Massie Tillman wants
lawyers who practice before him to come to court prepared and on
time.
</P>
<P>
   And, if they're women, he wants them in skirts.
</P>
<P>
   Tillman, 61, banned female lawyers and witnesses from wearing
pants in courtroom rules that took effect Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are to wear a dress, skirt and jacket or skirt and
blouse in the courtroom,'' the rules state. ``Women are not to wear
pants or pantsuits.''
</P>
<P>
   Women can sport slacks in nearly every other courtroom in
Tarrant County and in federal courtrooms in North Texas..MDNM/ They
can wear them on the floor of the Texas House and Senate. Ditto for
the federal appeals court in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The highest court of the land simply requires ``conservative
business dress,'' although no one at the Supreme Court could say if
a woman had ever argued there in slacks.
</P>
<P>
   Tillman, who like most judges requires male attorneys to wear
coats and ties, declined to discuss the policy. But a good bit of
the local bar is buzzing about it. The National Organization
for.MDNM/ Women called the rules ``silly'' and ``old-fashioned.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone who says women shouldn't be wearing anything
but skirts for the courtroom, they should just try it for
themselves for a few days and see how they like it,'' said Mollee
Westfall, a felony prosecutor with the Tarrant County District
Attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   Westfall, who does not appear in Tillman's court, said she has
had to lie down on the floor in some trials to reenact a crime for
a jury. She sometimes must bend over to dig through boxes of
documents, and to pick up bulky evidence, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't exactly take the kinds of positions that you might
be able to in pants,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the matter of comfort in courtrooms, which can
be drafty in winter and overly air-conditioned in summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those courtrooms are set for the comfort level of the judge,
who is in a wool robe,'' said Westfall, who often wears pantsuits,
including a blue wool pinstriped number identical to one her
lawyer/husband wears.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 17 other federal district and bankruptcy judges in the
Northern District of Texas, staff members for 13 said they have no
ban on slacks. At least one district judge, Joe Fish of Dallas, has
told female lawyers not to wear pants, although he has no written
policy on the matter, a staff member said.
</P>
<P>
   Three could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Courtroom dress codes have relaxed considerably from the days
when female jurors were instructed to wear dresses and male jurors
had to wear coats and ties, said U.S. District Judge Eldon Mahon,
who took the bench in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in the early days, I even loaned my personal coat to a
juror,'' Mahon said.
</P>
<P>
   Mahon, who turns 82 next month, still thinks that dress codes
are needed because court is a formal occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mean you have to wear a tuxedo, but I do think they
ought to dress very presentably,'' Mahon said.
</P>
<P>
   And.MDNM/ he includes.MDNM/ pants in that category.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no problem with women in a nice slacks suit,'' Mahon
said. ``It's probably more ladylike than these extremely short
skirts.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if judges do not forbid pantsuits, many lawyers still think
they are taboo.
</P>
<P>
   As Supreme Court counsel for the National Association of
Attorneys General, Dan Schweitzer advises to attorneys who will
appear before the high court. Schweitzer said he wouldn't recommend
slacks for women, even though the court's only official demand is
for ``conservative business dress.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor would Schweitzer recommend anything but dark suits and white
shirts for men.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a social question of what we consider to be
conservative dress,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Or rather, what the court considers to be conservative dress.
And judges, he acknowledged, tend to be older, maler and less
sartorially hip than much of America.
</P>
<P>
   For Supreme Court justices and perhaps many judges around the
country, he said, conservative dress means bared gams.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not really on the cutting edge of fashion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
