<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-EARNINGS-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMR PROFITS WORSE THAN EXPECTED BECAUSE OF PILOT SICKOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The parent of American Airlines, AMR Corp., said Wednesday that
the financial pain caused by the crippling 10-day sickout by its
pilots last month had been worse than expected and that its
first-quarter profit would be about half of Wall Street's current
estimate.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement, which came after the close of the New York
Stock Exchange, sent AMR shares lower in after-hours trading, from
a close of $59.0625 to $57.50; they rose later to $58.
</P>
<P>
   AMR said the sickout, which forced American to cancel more than
6,600 flights, would reduce its sales by an estimated $200 million
to $225 million in the first quarter. The company had previously
estimated the effect of the protest at $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had used that figure to reduce their estimates of
first-quarter earnings to 65 cents a share from about $1.10. AMR
said Wednesday that it would earn 30 to 35 cents in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Gerard J. Arpey, AMR's chief financial officer, said in a
statement that the sickout caused American, the nation's
second-largest airline, to lose a greater number of high-paying
business travelers than the airline had thought and that it had
also encouraged a greater number of potential passengers to book
their future travel on other airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, a quarter that looked like it would come in
generally in line with analyst expectations has been dramatically
impacted by the job action,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To soften the blow, AMR also announced Wednesday that its board
had authorized the company to buy back an additional $500 million
worth of its stock. The company said it expected to complete a
previous $500 million stock buyback by the end of the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The news caused some airline analysts to wonder whether
American's unexpected pain was responsible for the unexpected gains
recently announced at other airlines. On Monday, UAL Corp., the
parent of United Airlines, said it would surpass analysts'
estimates for the first quarter by 23 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Airline revenue has been down in recent months in what some
analysts think is the beginning of the end of four years of record
profits for the industry.
</P>
<P>
   United, which is the nation's largest airline, said its earnings
were a result of not just the sickout at American but also strong
domestic bookings that it said signaled a ``reversal in the decline
in domestic revenue strength.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Samuel Buttrick, an analyst at Paine Webber in New
York, now estimates United's one-time benefit from the American
sickout to be 28 cents a share, more than the gain UAL is
predicting for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greater the impact at American, the greater the
nonrecurring benefit at other carriers,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   American and its pilots have been at odds over AMR's recent
purchase of Reno Air, a small carrier that operates mostly in the
West. The Allied Pilots Association, the union representing
American's 9,200 pilots, contends that the Reno purchase, which was
completed in December, violates a guarantee in their contract that
their members do all the flying at American and other AMR
subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   AMR has said that it plans to integrate Reno's 300 pilots into
American's larger network but that it will take as long as 18
months. The union wants the Reno pilots to be paid under the more
beneficial terms in their contact immediately.
</P>
<P>
   After negotiations between the company and the union failed to
resolve the issue, some pilots began calling in sick in early
February. The protest grew to the point that on one day American
had to cancel about half of its 2,250 daily flights. After a
federal judge petitioned by AMR ordered the pilots back to work and
threatened to fine them more than $10 million, the union and the
company agreed to mediation, but the dispute is still not resolved.
</P>
<P>
   In a message to employees last week, Donald J. Carty, chairman
and chief executive of AMR, said American planned to expand more
slowly. He also said it would try to reduce its dependence on its
pilots by decreasing the amount of overtime flying built into the
airline's schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's simply not fair to anybody,'' he said. ``to continue our
reliance on a resource that has become less than predictable.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
