<SLUG> BC-KODAK-COPIERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN CONCERN TO BUY EASTMAN KODAK'S COPIER BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)  (af) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eastman Kodak Co., which has long viewed its copier business as
a liability, announced Wednesday that it would sell most of its
copier manufacturing operations to Heidelberger Druckmaschinen AG
of Germany
</P>
<P>
   It also said it would transfer toner manufacturing and various
patents and intellectual property to Nexpress, a joint venture it
formed with Heidelberger, a $4 billion printing company, in late
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the announcement, which was reported Wednesday by
The Wall Street Journal, is no coincidence. Thursday, at a trade
show in Hanover, Germany, Kodak will introduce its Digisource 9110,
a digital copier that can produce 110 pages a minute, making it the
first copier fast enough to compete with the Xerox Corp.'s
highest-end products. Most analysts suspect that it was the
Digisource, which will carry the Kodak name for at least another
year, that lured Heidelberger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without this product, Kodak could never have made the sale,''
said Gary Schneider, an analyst at Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Financially, the deal will not have much impact on Kodak. Its
office imaging business barely broke even on about $450 million in
revenues last year. It lost money in the fourth quarter, in good
part because Danka Business Systems, the ailing distributor that
bought Kodak's copier sales and service operations in 1996, had
fallen behind on payments for Kodak equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Kodak, the deal means getting rid of a small per-share
loss,'' said Jack L. Kelly, an analyst at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak will get $100 million cash from Heidelberger, while it
will transfer about $100 million worth of assets to the joint
venture.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak's stock inched up 43.75 cents Wednesday, closing at
$68.125, but few analysts believed this deal was behind the rise.
``All this really did was eliminate a big headache for Kodak,''
said Peter J. Enderlin, an analyst with First Albany Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The impact on Heidelberger, Danka and Xerox may be greater. The
Digisource could provide a vital strategic cog for Heidelberger,
which faces a challenge from the growing number of customers who
use high-speed copiers to print manuals, brochures and other items
that were once the purview of the offset printers that Heidelberger
makes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives Heidelberger its first alternative to offset
printing,'' said Ulysses Yannas, an analyst with Mercer, Bokert,
Buckman &AMP; Reid.
</P>
<P>
   For Danka, the blessing is mixed. It loses its exclusive
distribution rights to Kodak copiers. Mark Weber, a Kodak vice
president of office imaging, said three other distributors had
signed on to sell the Digisource, and a fourth was close.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Danka's president, Brian L. Merriman, called the deal
``wonderful for us.'' He said potential copier customers balked
because they knew Kodak wanted to leave the copier market, and that
having the Heidelberger name in place would allay their fears. And
he said that Danka's employees are already trained to sell and
service the Digisource, giving Danka at least a three-month head
start on any rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may not have contractual exclusivity, but we have
functional exclusivity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal could pose problems for Xerox, which has until now
owned the market for high-speed digital copiers. Still, Xerox
insists it is not worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working on this product line for nearly 10 years,
and our sales and service people understand it fully,'' said
Christa Carone, a Xerox spokeswoman. ``Our ears are perked up,
we're monitoring the situation, but we're not going to let anyone
overtake us.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
