u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRBUS-INVEST-410&AMP;ADD     03-17 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRBUS-INVEST-410&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRBUS WON'T BE TRANSFORMED THIS YEAR, FINANCE CHIEF SAYS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Airbus Industrie, the passenger jet consortium jointly owned by
four European companies, will not transform itself into a single
corporation this year, its chief financial officer said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus had planned to complete the transition from a relatively
loose partnership to a private company by January. But bickering
among its partners _ Aerospatiale of France, DaimlerChrysler
Aerospace AG of Germany, British Aerospace and Construcciones
Aeronauticas SA of Spain, known as CASA _ over the value of their
stakes in a unified company has delayed the move indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is going to be a mighty negotiation before it is done,''
Ian Massey, financial controller of the consortium, said after
addressing Wall Street analysts in New York Wednesday. ``I don't
have a sense of how it is going to play out.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year was the strongest for Airbus since its founding in
1970. The consortium delivered 229 airplanes, for a total of $13.3
billion in revenue, a 26 percent increase over 1997. Airbus now
offers a broad family of airplanes, from 100-seat single-aisle jets
to 400-passenger wide bodies, and it is near its goal of splitting
the market for new orders with its rival, the Boeing Co.
</P>
<P>
   But Massey said that unless it altered its structure, Airbus
would have a harder time cutting its costs and building a proposed
new super jumbo jet capable of carrying up to 1,000 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Aerospatiale and DaimlerChrysler each own 37.9 percent of the
consortium; British Aerospace owns 20 percent, and CASA owns 4.2
percent. Each partner produces different parts for the Airbus
planes, which are assembled in Toulouse, France. In this odd
arrangement, each partner earned money as Airbus subcontractors
last year while the consortium itself lost money.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus engaged in a bruising price war with Boeing in recent
years that has hurt both. After suffering costly production
foul-ups as it increased production in 1997, Boeing is now
struggling to cut costs so that planes ordered at rock-bottom
prices two and three years ago but not yet delivered will yield
more profits.
</P>
<P>
   Massey said Airbus faced the same problem. It plans to deliver
295 airplanes this year, a 29 percent increase over 1998, for
revenue of $16 billion. But many of these jets were ordered by
airlines in 1996 and 1997, at the height of the price war with
Boeing, and they are being built at a time when Airbus cost
reductions are leveling off.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   John J. Leahy, Airbus senior vice president in charge of sales,
said the consortium was able to command higher prices for its
airplanes in recent months as Boeing has focused on increasing its
financial return. Massey added that the market in Asia, which
accounted for only 3 percent of Airbus sales last year, was also
beginning to turn around.
</P>
<P>
   The two men reiterated a commitment by Airbus to build the A3XX,
a super jumbo jet that will cost upward of $10 billion to develop.
Earlier this year, Airbus announced that it was pushing back the
introduction of the plane by one year, to 2005, because many Asian
carriers were still not ready to place orders.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, which has a monopoly on planes carrying more than 400
passengers with its 747, says demand for a new jumbo does not
justify its cost. But Airbus has been consulting 19 airlines on the
design of the plane, including Federal Express, which has agreed to
be the first customer for a freighter version of the four-engine
jet.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Airbus has the A3XX, it says, Boeing will have the entire
market for large planes to itself. Massey predicted that $300
billion, or 26 percent, of the industry's overall sales in the next
20 years would be planes with more than 400 seats. That, he said,
is a slice too big to ignore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
