<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4604 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLATKIN-MUSIC-2TAKES-     03-17 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLATKIN-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ORCHESTRA BUILDER WHO WON'T JUST WALK AWAY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For an American conductor like Leonard Slatkin, it
would seem to be a seller's market. The major American orchestras
are exhorted these days to get in tune with the times and in touch
with the nation, and in those regards, Slatkin could be a quick
fix: a champion of many current composers and a century's worth of
American music as well as a respected interpreter of standard
repertory.
</P>
<P>
   Conductors are being courted to replace the lame-duck German
music directors of the New York Philharmonic and the Philadelphia
and Cleveland Orchestras, to name just the most prominent ensembles
with vacancies looming, and Slatkin, with an established reputation
as an orchestra builder at the St. Louis Symphony and a growing one
here at the National Symphony, should be a contender.
</P>
<P>
   Yet to hear him tell it, the orchestras are not buying, and he
would not in any case be selling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's to say we're not happy where we are?'' he said of
himself and a like-minded colleague at another orchestra of the
``second'' rank, Michael Tilson Thomas at the San Francisco
Symphony. ``Not that I wouldn't be flattered if they asked, but
there is no reason for anybody to assume that I wouldn't be happy
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Slatkin, who is 54, still young for a conductor, took over the
National Symphony in 1996, two years after the departure of
Mstislav Rostropovich, on a three-year contract, which he says he
is about to renew. He spoke recently at the Kennedy Center for the
Performing Arts after an arduous rehearsal of John Corigliano's
``Dylan Thomas Trilogy,'' which the orchestra will present on
Friday at Carnegie Hall in the second of two programs consisting
entirely of New York premieres.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier program, on Thursday, also offers typical Slatkin
fare: William Bolcom's Sixth Symphony, Ellen Taaffe Zwilich's
``Images'' and Elgar's unfinished Third Symphony, in an elaboration
by Anthony Payne.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are very risky programs,'' Slatkin said. ``I know,
because Carnegie won't let us do it next year.''
</P>
<P>
   His New York appearances come on the heels of two impressive
Carnegie concerts by his alma mater, the St. Louis Symphony. When
Slatkin left it for the National Symphony, many were puzzled.
Despite the greater prominence he could enjoy in Washington as a
public figure, a role he seemed to relish, musically the move
seemed a step sideways if not down, from an orchestra perennially
on the verge of a major breakthrough to one firmly ensconced in the
second rank.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, a breakthrough to what? The Big Five of American
orchestras (comprising, with New York, Philadelphia and Cleveland,
the Chicago and Boston Symphony Orchestras) is either a permanently
closed club or a hopelessly outmoded concept. In fact, Time
magazine's declaration in 1983 that the St. Louis Symphony was the
second-best orchestra in the country (to the Chicago Symphony) may
have gained it an asterisk but scarcely dented the notion of the
Big Five in the popular imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big Five comes from an era in American life when there
were only eight major-league baseball teams,'' said Don Roth, who
became president of the St. Louis Symphony last year. ``If there
were only five top orchestras in the country, we really
(italics)would(end italics) be in bad shape.''
</P>
<P>
   It is certainly true that on a given evening the St. Louis, like
the Los Angeles Philharmonic and the San Francisco, Pittsburgh and
Baltimore Symphony Orchestras, can perform on a par with most of
the great ensembles in the world. Some maintain that the top
American orchestras more properly form a cluster of 10 or 12, and
in fact, a group of managers of leading orchestras meets
periodically under the rubric ``The 10'' and now has 11 members.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Symphony gained a reputation of another sort
during the Slatkin years, one surely more valuable in the long run,
as an innovator in establishing ties to the community. It undertook
major initiatives in education, audience development and service to
the city with, among other things, its own music school.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all this, Slatkin explains, even before he learned of an
opportunity in Washington, he had decided it was time for a change,
time to leave St. Louis. He was music director of the orchestra for
17 years, beginning in 1979, having spent much of the previous
decade as its assistant or associate conductor. And he was given
most of the credit for restoring the orchestra, the nation's
second-oldest, to a position at or near the top of American
ensembles.
</P>
<P>
   With Slatkin's departure, the St. Louis Symphony reverted to
typical American form in 1996, hiring a European, the Dutchman Hans
Vonk, just as the Baltimore Symphony has since done, replacing the
American David Zinman with the Russian Yuri Temirkanov as of next
season.
</P>
<P>
   Such moves are undoubtedly intended at least in part to redress
the balance, to nurture more standard areas of repertory after an
astringent period of adventure. In Slatkin's case, his
interpretations of the Germanic canon may be easier to respect than
to warm to and love, and questions are often raised about the depth
of his inspiration in such music.
</P>
<P>
   Vonk, speaking recently after an arduous rehearsal of his own,
in works of Messiaen at Carnegie Hall, cited American music _
second only to Dvorak, of all things _ as repertory he is
(italics)not(end italics_ good at. But he is a seasoned interpreter
of standard fare, and he pointed to versatility as his prime
strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Holland we do everything, German, French, new music,
original instruments,'' he said. ``It's a very lively scene,
without a real specialty.''
</P>
<P>
   Vonk is enamored of the St. Louis Symphony's own versatility
and, still more, its spirit and morale. ``It is the friendliest
orchestra in the world,'' he said. ``They are nice, open people,
very disciplined, with a wonderful approach to music.'' It is also
a relatively young orchestra, hired in large part by Slatkin.
</P>
<P>
   In this case and others, American orchestras' tendency to hire
foreign music directors creates at least small vacuums, which are
themselves opportunities for Slatkin and his ilk. Vonk welcomes
Slatkin back as conductor laureate to keep his specialties alive.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Slatkin already works for both the New York
Philharmonic, where he has covered much of the American repertory
in regular visits as guest conductor during Kurt Masur's tenure,
and the Cleveland Orchestra, where he directs the summer festival
at the Blossom Music Center, injecting some of his own tastes and
emphases.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
