<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-COLLEGE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM SNUBBED TO SWEET IN SPOKANE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ This was not about the West Coast Conference
championship. It was not about beating Minnesota or Stanford. It's
not about Florida, tonight's opponent, or No.1 seed Connecticut,
which looms as the last obstacle before the Final Four
</P>
<P>
   No, this is about sticking it to nine men in a Kansas City hotel
who welcomed Florida State to the NCAA Tournament last March and
tossed Gonzaga into the at-large trash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were sitting there feeling good about our season,'' Gonzaga
forward Casey Calvary said. ``Then they pushed us out of what we
had earned. This is payback. The NCAA (selection committee) didn't
believe in us, and the NIT didn't believe in us. Nobody believed in
us. But we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything Gonzaga (27-6) is today _ angry, bitter, confident, a
No.10 seed with an attitude _ it became on Selection Sunday '98.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in jeans and T-shirts, the Bulldogs gathered in coach
Dan Monson's Spokane basement to watch their name appear in the
64-team field. Sure, they had fumbled away the WCC's automatic bid
with a loss to San Francisco in the league tournament. But their
record (23-9) and non-conference wins (Tulsa, Mississippi State and
Clemson) were definitely good enough for an at-large berth.
</P>
<P>
   Or so they thought. When their name did not appear, there was
silence in the basement. Not anger, not yet, just stunned silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first time I didn't have an answer for them,''
Monson said. ``I didn't know what to tell them. I didn't know why
we weren't invited. It was a tough moment for me, and it's been a
tremendous responsibility for me to get them (into the tournament)
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Monson immediately took steps to prevent it from happening
again. First, he upgraded the Bulldogs' schedule.
</P>
<P>
   They opened the season at Kansas and led midway through the
second half before faltering. They entered the preseason NIT and
played at Memphis and at Purdue. They played in the Hawkeye
Invitational in Ames, Iowa, where they lost by one point to Detroit
_ UCLA's Detroit _ and beat South Alabama. They played Washington
State and Washington and Boise State and won all three.
</P>
<P>
   After experiencing Purdue's Mackey Arena and Kansas' Allen
Fieldhouse, the Bulldogs had no fear facing Stanford in Seattle
last weekend in a second-round showdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no doubt we were going to win that game,'' Calvary
said. ``We're confident. Hey, we're 3-0 against the Pac-10 this
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Monson didn't stop with the schedule. To get his best five on
the floor, he inserted 5-foot-8 point guard Quentin Hall into the
lineup and moved junior Matt Santangelo, his best player, from
point guard to shooting guard. Santangelo struggled throughout the
season _ his shooting dropped from 43.5 percent to 38.7 percent _
and quietly fretted the move would hurt his NBA chances.
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo's struggles didn't stop Gonzaga, didn't even slow it
down. With Monson's coaching, with their relentless attack and the
all-around skills of Calvary (9.3 ppg), Richie Frahm (14.5) and
Jeremy Eaton (11.9), the Bulldogs rolled through the WCC with just
two defeats.
</P>
<P>
   When the conference tournament arrived, Santangelo took charge.
He had 23 assists and 61 points in three games, including a
34-point masterpiece as Gonzaga beat Santa Clara 91-66 in the title
game to secure the coveted automatic berth.
</P>
<P>
   The ensuing celebration was 51 weeks in the making.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always reminded them of last season,'' Monson said. ``I
wanted the pain to be with them. When practices didn't go well, I'd
say, `Do you want to go to Laramie to play Wyoming in the NIT?' And
right away, they'd refocus. It was the same focus they had on
Selection Sunday last year when we didn't get in.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida better be ready. This is no ordinary 10th seed.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching roulette: Monson apparently considers Washington State
a dead-end position and will not replace departed coach Kevin
Eastman. Smart move. Monson has most of his best players back next
year and should be in line for a better job.
</P>
<P>
   Watch for former Arizona State interim coach Don Newman to get
the Wazu gig. He was an assistant there under Kelvin Sampson.
</P>
<P>
   Monson is a candidate for the San Diego State opening behind
Utah's Rick Majerus, who won't take it, and former St. John's coach
Fran Fraschilla, who will. Majerus, a practicing Catholic, may end
up at Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt is pursuing Washington coach Bob Bender, who is
respected and well-liked but may be sensing it's time to leave
Seattle. The Huskies underachieved this season and lost their
stars, Todd MacCulloch and Donald Watts.
</P>
<P>
   If Bender leaves, watch for Washington to put Colorado State's
Ritchie McKay and Pepperdine's Lorenzo Romar on its short list.
After the Rick Neuheisel fiasco, the pressure's on athletic
director Barbara Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   Death, taxes and corruption at UNLV: It's tough to keep anything
clean in Sin City, and Billy Bayno may be the latest coach to
collapse under the sleaze that envelops the Nevada-Las Vegas
program.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA's enforcement staff arrived on campus Wednesday to
investigate allegations of recruiting violations and extra
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Sources told the Las Vegas Sun that the NCAA will interview four
players, including star forward Shawn Marion, and assistant coach
Greg Vetrone. According to a Las Vegas television station, an
assistant coach allegedly gave a student manager money to make car
payments for former player (and current Clipper) Tyrone Nesby.
</P>
<P>
   If true, the violations could give UNLV reason to dismiss Bayno,
who is neither popular nor successful. He'd join his former boss at
Massachusetts, John Calipari, on the unemployed list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
