<HEADER>
A4606 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLATKIN-MUSIC-2NDTAKE     03-17 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLATKIN-MUSIC-2NDTAKE-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: and emphases.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   These roles, serving both parties, may obviate the need for a
permanent affiliation. The Cleveland connection, in particular,
seems to have had a formative influence on Slatkin in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Coming from St. Louis's Powell Hall, a converted movie theater
with acclaimed acoustics, he expressed the wish (not, he insists,
the demand, as has been reported) early on at the National Symphony
for an acoustical renovation of the Kennedy Center Concert Hall.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to presenting uneven and erratic sound to listeners,
the old acoustics prevented the players from hearing one another on
stage, thus threatening to hold back the orchestra's progress.
</P>
<P>
   Powell Hall, with its rich, reverberant acoustics, Slatkin says,
showed him the extent to which an orchestra derives its sound from
its home. The lesson has been reinforced by his experience with the
Cleveland Orchestra, which developed its elegant precision partly
in response to the dry, detailed acoustics of Severance Hall in
Cleveland (itself now under renovation) and carries it along even
to outdoor concerts at Blossom.
</P>
<P>
   By the time of the Kennedy Center Concert Hall renovation, which
was undertaken for other reasons as well as acoustical ones and
completed before last season, Slatkin's sound ideal had evolved to
favor greater clarity, he says, largely on the basis of the
Cleveland Orchestra experience. So would it be accurate to describe
the sound he is seeking at the National Symphony as basically the
plush, dark St. Louis sound with an overlay of Cleveland clarity?
</P>
<P>
   ``You could say that,'' he said. ``Or you could call it the
sound of the Boston Symphony in the Monteux years, or the Chicago
Symphony in the Reiner years.'' If the National Symphony fails to
reach the top in the days ahead, it will not be for lack of
ambition.
</P>
<P>
   And the orchestra seems indeed to be headed in the right
direction, to judge from a rehearsal and performance of the big,
burly Corigliano piece. Between the beneficial effects of the hall
renovation and Slatkin's furtherance of his sound ideal, there is
little question that the quality of its playing has improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slava was known for his interpretations of Tchaikovsky and
Shostakovich, and we played like a Russian orchestra, with a lot of
extremes,'' David Bragunier, the orchestra's tuba player and
personnel manager, said of its 17 years with Rostropovich. ``I'm
not sure anyone ever played louder than us. Or softer. Some
listeners must have found us harsh. Leonard is going for a new,
full, blended, darker sound, a Bruckner sound, perhaps.''
</P>
<P>
   Rostropovich left in 1994, and once he had announced his
decision to do so, in 1992, he generously left vacancies in the
orchestra to be filled by his successor. As a result, Slatkin has
already had the opportunity to hire 14 of the orchestra's 100
players. It, too, is a young ensemble, and one that Slatkin calls
friendly, eager and disciplined. He deals with the players on a
slightly more formal basis than in St. Louis, where many musicians
had known him virtually from childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Slatkin's programming ideas obviously make greater demands on
the National Symphony players than those many orchestras face. ``We
have so much literature to deal with here,'' Bragunier said. ``But
Leonard is extremely quick, and we can do it, though it does get a
little hectic at times.''
</P>
<P>
   Audiences, too, seem receptive to Slatkin's proclivities.
Subscriptions are up to 76 percent of capacity, from ``the 60s''
before Slatkin arrived, said Robert C. Jones, the orchestra's
president. Overall seat occupancy is expected to rise from 88
percent last season to 90 percent this season, he added.
</P>
<P>
   (The St. Louis Symphony, Roth said, is filling about 70 percent
of capacity, essentially the same as during the Slatkin years.) And
some of the most clamorous ovations are reserved for the most
challenging pieces.
</P>
<P>
   The National Symphony gives Slatkin scope for his interests in
community relations and, especially, education, not only locally
but also nationally. Before his arrival the orchestra had a series
of ``American Residencies'' in place. Next month Slatkin leads a
10-day residency in Mississippi, with some 150 events presented in
Biloxi, Cleveland, Jackson, Tupelo and other cities and towns.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, he does have access to the corridors of power. ``I know
politicians on a social basis,'' said Slatkin who lives in Potomac,
Md., with his wife, Linda Hohenfeld, and their son, Daniel. ``I
haven't used this as a political forum, but I try to keep the issue
of music education in the schools alive.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the surprises: ``Newt Gingrich was a very
interesting person to know and a great supporter of the Kennedy
Center,'' Slatkin said. ``Sometimes you get fooled by what people
have to do or say in public.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who calls himself Slatkin's biggest fan, was perhaps
engaging in wishful thinking when he said, ``Leonard and I both
consider this our last job.'' Slatkin seems disinclined to look so
far ahead. But it appears unlikely that he will leave before he
has, at least in his own mind, made the National Symphony the equal
of the St. Louis Symphony and a rival of any orchestra anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   That, after all, is what an orchestra builder does.
</P>
</TEXT>
