<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PALMER-WOODS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALMER'S ADVICE TO WOODS: ENJOY THE GAME, AND LAUGH
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Arnold Palmer and Tiger Woods are at different
stages in life, but they shared the spotlight Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer, 69, had a news conference at his Florida residence, Bay
Hill Club and Lodge, to promote his autobiography, ``A Golfer's
Life,'' written with James Dodson. About 30 minutes after Palmer
finished, Woods stepped to the podium and received an award for
being the No. 1 player in the world ranking during 1998.
</P>
<P>
   It was an interesting contrast. At 23, Woods is still in the
early chapters of his career, facing challenges that Palmer has
overcome. Like Palmer, Woods has drawn new fans to golf, elevating
the game's popularity with his talent and charisma. But while
Palmer's impressive accomplishments are in the record books, Woods
will spend the next 15 to 20 years trying to set records.
</P>
<P>
   The most immediate challenge facing Woods is the Bay Hill
Invitational, which begins Thursday. Bay Hill is one of the PGA
Tour's most popular events because it is hosted by Palmer and
because it falls a week before The Players Championship and three
weeks before the Masters. Eight of the top 10 players in the world
will compete _ Woods, Mark O'Meara, the defending champion Ernie
Els, Davis Love III, Lee Westwood, Vijay Singh, Colin Montgomerie
and Justin Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   That field alone will make the event intriguing. And for Woods,
it will be his first tournament since he fired his former caddie,
Mike (Fluff) Cowan, and replaced him with Steve Williams, the
former caddie for both Greg Norman and Raymond Floyd. Woods said he
was already impressed with Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be fine,'' said Woods, who has not gone into
detail about why he fired Cowan. ``His credentials speak for
themselves, caddying for Norman all those years around the world
and caddying for Raymond Floyd the past 12 years. He has won
numerous tournaments. He has a lot of guts, and it's going to be a
lot of fun for both of us. He's very professional. He's a great
caddie.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods' last tournament was two weeks ago, when he was eliminated
in the third round of the Andersen Consulting Match Play
Championship by the winner, Jeff Maggert. On the final hole, Woods
violently slammed his club to the ground after hitting a poor tee
shot, and Palmer, who has given advice to Woods, was not pleased
with that outburst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take some pride in Tiger and his ability,'' said Palmer, who
is also playing Thursday in a threesome that includes another
legend, Seve Ballesteros. ``That frown, and slamming the club down,
doesn't do anything for him or for his game. He's got the world in
his hands. All he has to do is enjoy it, laugh, and enjoy the
ability that he has to the fullest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not convincing anyone of anything when he slams the club
down, or gets mad out there. They know he's good. He has proven
that. Now he has to sustain it. Sustain it with enjoyment. I talked
to him about that before he turned pro.''
</P>
<P>
   Told of Palmer's comments, Woods mildly protested. ``It has
decreased quite a bit, but it's part of me,'' said Woods of his
temper. ``I'm just curious why the press doesn't get on Craig
Stadler for doing that. People think it's funny when Stadler does
it, but hate when I do it. I'm not saying it's right, but we're out
there fighting. We're trying to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods did return to the winner's circle last month, capturing
the Buick Invitational, his first victory on tour since April 1998.
However, Woods has been the game's most consistent top-10 finisher
since the start of 1998, and he already has five top-10 finishes in
six starts this year.
</P>
<P>
   While some believe David Duval should be ranked No. 1 instead of
No. 2 behind Woods, others are not so sure. ``Tiger is probably the
most talented player on the PGA Tour,'' said O'Meara, Woods'
closest friend in the game. ``Not to take anything away from David
Duval, because David is a super golfer, a great player. But Tiger
Woods has got it all. This kid has got an incredible 12 to 15 years
ahead of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods hopes O'Meara is right. While Woods has been consistent,
he has not won a major since his Masters' victory in 1997. Woods
believes he has become a much more complete player, improving both
his short game and his distance control. And this year, he hopes
that improvement translates into at least one more major
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``My swing is improving, my game is improving,'' Woods said.
``The things I'm working on are starting to come to fruition. I'm
excited.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
