<SLUG> BC-BBA-JAYS-JOHNSON-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOGGED BY WAR TALES, JOHNSON IS LET GO BY JAYS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Tim Johnson proclaimed his Vietnam problem was
behind him. He obviously did not know what lay ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto Blue Jays fired Johnson as their manager Wednesday,
saying his fantasy life as a Vietnam veteran had become an
unsettling distraction in the team's spring camp. Jim Fregosi, who
has previously managed three other teams, was named to replace
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's tenure as the Blue Jays' manager seemed doomed from
the time last fall when he admitted to manufacturing an account of
combat duty as a Marine during the Vietnam War as well as having
concocted a tale about being offered a basketball scholarship at
UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Under threat of losing his job, the 49-year-old Johnson met
early in spring training with players who were with the team last
season and apologized to them. He said he felt the meeting enabled
him to put the matter behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to talk to them about a problem I had, guilt I had
for so many years, 30 years,'' Johnson said two weeks ago in Tampa,
Fla., meaning guilt he felt for never having served in Vietnam
while he was in the Marines. ``We talked about it and the response
was unbelievable. I got all choked up because of the support I got
from these players.''
</P>
<P>
   Gord Ash, the Toronto general manager, said Johnson did what he
had to do to try to make his presence as manager work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he tried to get things settled,'' Ash said by
telephone from Dunedin, Fla., ``but there continued to be an
unsettled feeling in camp, a distracted feeling that interfered
with players getting the job done on the field. My intuition told
me if not now, it would happen 30 or 45 days from now. I couldn't
risk the season.''
</P>
<P>
   A managerial firing in spring training is not unprecedented, but
it is rare. Johnson, who managed in the major leagues for the first
time last season, was the first manager fired in spring training
since the San Diego Padres jettisoned Alvin Dark 17 days before the
start of the 1978 season. Some of Dark's players complained about
him, and Ray Kroc, the owner, said Dark overmanaged and tried to do
everything himself.
</P>
<P>
   In 1954, the Chicago Cubs fired Phil Cavaretta after he told the
owner, P.K. Wrigley, the team was headed for another
second-division finish. Wrigley said he didn't like Cavaretta's
``defeatist'' attitude.
</P>
<P>
   The beginning of Johnson's end came Friday when Ash spoke with
the club's ownership and recommended a change. Told to make it, Ash
received permission to talk to Fregosi from the San Francisco
Giants, for whom he was a special assistant to the general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Ash met with Fregosi on Sunday, informed Johnson after a Monday
night exhibition game with the Yankees and met with the players at
9 a.m. Wednesday. ``My feeling is there's a sense of relief that
that chapter is behind us,'' Ash said of the players' perceived
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Fregosi compiled an 861-937 record as manager of the Angels
(1978-81), the White Sox (1986-88) and the Phillies (1991-96).
Under his direction, the Phillies lost the 1993 World Series to the
Blue Jays. Fregosi, 56, was one of the also-rans when Johnson was
hired to replace Cito Gaston before last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mandate was not to go with recycled managers then,'' Ash
said. ``We wanted a fresh face and fresh approach. But a year later
I feel our club is different. We have a more reasonable chance of
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Blue Jays had an 88-74 record and finished
third after briefly making a late-season run at the wild-card spot
for the playoffs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Speaking in Tampa two weeks ago, Johnson was upbeat and ready to
compete for the wild-card spot again. He said he did not foresee a
credibility problem with the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was never an issue with them,'' he said, then recounted
the meeting he had with them. ``They came forward and talked. That
was really impressive. They all had a lot to say. It was all
positive and great.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ash said: ``Each day brought a new revelation from a new
source. The media would go to players and say what do you think
about what this guy said.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't offer specifics, but Ed Sprague, the Blue Jays' third
baseman for more than half of last season, was recently quoted as
calling Johnson a ``liar'' and a ``back stabber.''
</P>
<P>
   Darrin Fletcher, the Blue Jays' catcher, said the change was
probably the right move. ``I was willing to give him a second
chance,'' he said, ``but with all that stuff hanging over his head,
would he have survived the scrutiny the first time we lost two in a
row? I don't think so.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
