<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WALLY-WORLD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SZCZERBIAK LIVING OUT HIS DREAM AS A COLLEGE TOWN RIDES HIS
COATTAILS  (nk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXFORD, Ohio _ Wally Szczerbiak carefully slid out of the
Chevrolet Lumina on High Street, a bounce pass off Miami
University's campus, and the traffic soon stopped. The cars and the
pedestrians. Horns honked and people pointed. Some of the
admittedly apathetic students, who might have yawned if Bill
Clinton had cruised by in a convertible, acted like 3-year-olds who
had just seen Barney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it him?'' one woman asked, half giggling and half
breathless. ``Is that him?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was. It was Szczerbiak, who has long been known as Wally
World here and who has seen his nickname spread throughout the,
well, world, because of his superior play in the National
Collegiate Athletic Association tournament.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to know the main reason that Miami, little Miami of
Ohio, is still alive and playing the defending national champion
Kentucky in the Round of 16 on Friday night in St. Louis, he was
sauntering along High Street on Tuesday night, casually
acknowledging the adulation.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that was because Szczerbiak was too engrossed in the new
T-shirt in the dark window of Follett's Miami Coop Bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   The white shirt had brilliant red letters that said ``Wally's
World'' next to a basketball that resembled a globe. Szczerbiak
studied the shirt as if it were an engagement ring, vowing to buy a
bunch at $16.99 a pop. ``I'm so happy and excited about what has
happened,'' Szczerbiak said. ``This last week has been so
tremendous. I never expected to have a week like this. When you're
in this, you just want to see it continue.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a little-boy quality to Szczerbiak as he discussed
these hoop dreams, which are unfolding before the nation after four
years of his blossoming into a legend. This has been a hectic and
rewarding time for Szczerbiak, the dynamic shooter who has scored
67 of Miami's 125 points in the first two Midwest Regional games
and who revealed that he has the Redhawks winning the NCAA title in
his private pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is a Cinderella story,'' Szczerbiak said. ``Why
not?''
</P>
<P>
   Szczerbiak has been called the best shooter in America. He might
also be the best feel-good story on the best feel-good school in
the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Szczerbiak is handsome enough to be the next tenant on ``Melrose
Place.'' His girlfriend, Shannon Ward, is a part-time model who
could join him there.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Szczerbiak wants to play in the National Basketball
Association, because his father, Walt, a tremendous player in
Europe, was deprived of that chance. Besides that, Szczerbiak is a
gracious 22-year-old from Cold Spring Harbor, N.Y., who, so far,
has not let the endless attention inflate his cranium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone said I was going to be the next Larry Bird,''
Szczerbiak said. ``So I said, `Wow.' I never thought that there
would be another Larry Bird. I still don't think there will be.
This attention is great, but the people close to me to know I'm
never going to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Before dinner, the 6-foot-8-inch, 242-pound senior had
sheepishly warned a visitor that he might receive some attention.
Some? Three women in a silver car stopped and gawked at Szczerbiak
before hollering, ``Waaalllleeeee,'' causing Ward to grimace.
</P>
<P>
   Through the mayhem, Szczerbiak kept grinning and nodding and
making everyone feel comfortable. When Szczerbiak ordered the new
Szczerbiak bagel (turkey with cheese on a salt bagel) at Deli and
Bagel, he giddily pointed to his picture on the wall and was as
excited as the woman making the sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so secure in himself that he never needed to fill any
void,'' said Ward, who started dating Szczerbiak after they met
four years ago at freshmen orientation. ``It's not like he says,
`I'm the man.' He always thought he was the man. But, as important
as it is to be a good basketball player, he wants to be a good
person, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Walt Szczerbiak, a cautious father who knows better than anyone
that dreams, even careers, can disappear in one moment, said:
``Wally is incredible in that he's enjoying the ride. He has that
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Before there was a Wally World, there was a little Wally who
followed around his sweet-shooting father. Walt played for the
Pittsburgh Condors of the American Basketball Association for the
1971-72 season and, after the team folded, he was offered a
one-year contract by the Buffalo Braves in the NBA. But Real
Madrid, the premier team in Europe, guaranteed him a five-year deal
so Szczerbiak bolted to Spain. He helped Madrid win three
championships and his 65 points in one game remains a league
record. Still, even though Walt played against NBA-caliber players,
he never played in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a little piece of me that wonders what I could have
done,'' Walt Szczerbiak said.
</P>
<P>
   Wally, who averaged 23.6 points during the regular season, does
not feel pressure to do what his father did not. In fact, the
lessons that Walt gave Wally were always reassuring. When they
played one-on-one in the driveway, Walt always gave himself a
handicap _ such as not being able to block Wally's shots _ even
when Wally was averaging 36.6 points a game as a senior at Cold
Spring Harbor High School on Long Island. So, with each skirmish,
Wally gained more confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father should write a book on how to raise an athlete,''
Szczerbiak said. ``Every time we played, it would be 14-14 and I
would win, 15-14. He kept me excited to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Walt said: ``I didn't want to knock him on his pants like the
Great Santini. I stressed positive reinforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Szczerbiak was well known in the Mid-American Conference before
this season, but said a defining moment of his career came during
the Goodwill Games. The United States snatched the gold medal last
summer and Szczerbiak led the team with 17.6 points a game, but it
was a scrimmage that convinced him of his worth. He dropped 47
points against his future teammates, dropping at least 47 dozen
jaws, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I knew,'' Wally said, ``that I could do
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, he can. Szczerbiak excels at the fundamental aspects
of the game that older fans adore and is adept at the flashy
aspects of the game that playground kids adore. Szczerbiak knows
when and how to set a screen as if it were 1960 and when and how to
explode to the hoop as if it were 2000. He always looks in sync,
but it has taken thousands of hours of devotion. Even after dinner
Tuesday, Szczerbiak prolonged a 14-hour day by lifting weights.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the beauty of Wally: he kept working and working,''
Miami Coach Charlie Coles said. ``He didn't start as a sophomore.
He waited his turn and worked hard. He made himself a great
player.''
</P>
<P>
   About an hour before Szczerbiak traipsed along High Street, a
visitor arbitrarily walked into two stores on the block and heard
employees in each discussing the star player. When these eerie
scenes were mentioned to Szczerbiak, he simply shrugged. He is
accustomed to it. But Szczerbiak did not shrug when asked if he was
absorbing every detail of this amazing college experience that will
never occur again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I should sit back and appreciate this a little more,''
he said. ``There's just something about college basketball. You
only go through this once. Everyone is so anxious to get to the NBA
for money, but there's nothing like this. What better thing could I
be doing right now?''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
