r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERSTATE-ABUSE-CASE     03-17 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERSTATE-ABUSE-CASE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENTUCKY JUDGE ORDERS TEXAS TO TURN OVER 5 SIBLINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE LEE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Kentucky judge has ordered Texas child welfare workers to turn
over five children, despite allegations that their parents abused
them and neglected their education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state of Texas is ordered to return the children to their
home state of Kentucky ... pending the reunion with their
biological parents, Doug and Kathie Harless,'' District Judge
Kimberly Shumate wrote in a ruling released Wednesday in Hardin
County, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Texas authorities have said they have jurisdiction over the
children, that they will not release them to Kentucky and that they
intend to put them up for adoption.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers on both sides said the custody issue may be decided in
federal court.
</P>
<P>
   The Hardin County Attorney's Office has sided with Texas
officials and has argued against returning the children, who range
in age from 5 to 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obvious the Harlesses have a prolonged history of child
abuse and neglect investigation spanning several states,''
Assistant County Attorney Jennifer Pitts wrote in a court filing.
``It is the sincere belief of the commonwealth that the Harlesses
have filed this motion in Kentucky as one more attempt to prevent
the system from catching up with them. Thankfully, Texas has
managed to conduct a thorough investigation, which has uncovered
not only the deplorable conditions under which the Harless children
were living, but also the history of the Harless family in other
states.''
</P>
<P>
   The Harlesses contend that Texas officials are persecuting them
because of their unconventional lifestyle and because they
home-school their children. They have enlisted the help of the
Rutherford Institute, a nonprofit legal group that specializes in
religious and human rights cases and worked on Paula Jones' lawsuit
against President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Haden, a Rutherford Institute litigation counselor,
promised ``vigorous efforts on their behalf, both in Kentucky and
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Texas improperly removed the children from their parents
because the children had lived in a trailer or were behind on their
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that were the case, half the families in rural areas of
America would have their children taken away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Smith, an associate judge in North Texas' Tarrant County
juvenile court who has been handling the case, said she had not
seen the Kentucky ruling and declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Harlesses make a living selling T-shirts and other
merchandise at car races. They say they were living in North Texas
temporarily in 1997 to attend the opening of Texas Motor Speedway
in Fort Worth when Child Protective Services workers put their five
children in foster homes.
</P>
<P>
   Workers with the Texas agency began investigating the Harlesses
in April 1997, when their oldest daughter told police that her
father had slapped her and thrown her against a wall.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Harless said the red mark on his daughter's face was caused
by a skin condition, and no criminal charges were filed.
</P>
<P>
   The agency continued to investigate and found that the Harlesses
had been reported on suspicion of child neglect in Alabama and
Tennessee. In 1996, the family was living outside Talladega, Ala.,
in the trailer of an 18-wheeler with no running water. One of the
children, who was 9, could not recite the alphabet, a report
stated. The Tennessee investigation found nothing because the
Harlesses had moved.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 5, 1997, police and Child Protective Services workers
took the children from a motel room in Denton, Texas, where the
family was living.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just pretty much cluttered, trash piled up, dirty
clothes, toys. The older girl was the one basically taking care of
the kids,'' Denton police Detective Bryan Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 13-year-old boy, I asked him that particular night to say
his alphabet, and he couldn't say his alphabet. They said they
home-schooled the children, and we looked in the motel room for any
type of books, and there weren't any books.''
</P>
<P>
   The Harlesses cooperated with Child Protective Services workers
for about two months, attending parenting classes and renting a
house to be near the children. During a Thanksgiving visit, police
said, they took the four youngest children and left the state.
</P>
<P>
   Texas police issued a warrant accusing the Harlesses of
interference with child custody. The family was found in
Carrollton, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Doug Harless) was dead set about how he wanted to go back
and get this straightened out,'' Carrollton County sheriff's Deputy
Mike Townley said. ``Then we were taking them down the hall, and I
had my back turned and he bolted out the back door.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Harless was picked up by police about a month later in
Pennsylvania and returned to Texas. Doug and Kathie Harless served
three months in jail, then moved to Kentucky to fight for custody
of their children.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Harless said yesterday that none of the abuse allegations
against him had been proved.
</P>
<P>
   Haden, from the Rutherford Institute, said that even if Harless
had slapped his daughter, ``to discipline a child by limited
corporal punishment is a parental right.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the incident in Georgia, Harless said, he was never
there.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
