<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4616 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-POLICE-PROFILING-N     03-17 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-POLICE-PROFILING-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Conn., Calif.) 
 (nk) 
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HACKENSACK, N.J. _ Twenty-five black and Hispanic criminal
defendants are in legal limbo after the New Jersey Attorney
General's office postponed their prosecutions because all were
arrested or stopped by two troopers involved in a controversial
shooting on the New Jersey Turnpike last April.
</P>
<P>
   Their defense lawyers have said that the unusual legal step has
denied their clients' rights to speedy trials and stalled court
challenges to the arrests. In addition, the suspended cases have
prevented two defense lawyers from getting documents they want to
examine for evidence that the state police singled out black and
Hispanic motorists in their search for drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the lawyers are eager to get to court to press
contentions that their clients were the victims of such racial
profiling. If a judge agrees, the lawyers said, both the stops and
charges stemming from them would be illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Despite grumbling about the right to a speedy trial, other
defense lawyers said they are content to wait because they think
the troopers will be indicted by a state grand jury investigating
the April shooting. If indicted, the lawyers said, the troopers
would be useless as prosecution witnesses and the charges against
their clients would probably be thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   Under court rules, state prosecutors must give defense lawyers
state police reports on the arrests, statements by witnesses and
any material that could establish the innocence of the suspects,
who have been indicted on drugs or weapons charges.
</P>
<P>
   But last December, a state judge granted a motion by a senior
deputy attorney general, John M. Fahy, to withhold such documents
in these cases.
</P>
<P>
   The troopers, John Hogan and James Kenna, have been under
investigation by a state grand jury since May for shooting three
unarmed minority men after their van was stopped on the turnpike.
Hogan has been on medical leave since the day after the shooting,
although the State Police would not say why. Kenna has been on desk
duty since then.
</P>
<P>
   Fahy said in court papers that Hogan and Kenna were important
witnesses in all the cases because they either stopped, questioned
or arrested the suspects in 1997 or early 1998. Fahy argued that
the state's Division of Criminal Justice could not decide which
documents to give defense lawyers until the state grand jury
finished investigating the van shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that the matter involving Troopers Hogan and Kenna is
an ongoing investigation strongly favors maintaining the secrecy of
information developed to protect the integrity of the
investigation,'' Fahy said in his motion.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 11, a state Superior Court Judge Barnett E. Hoffman
granted Fahy's request to place the cases on an inactive list for
120 days, until early April.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman's ruling prevented defense lawyers from appearing in
court to argue that their clients were the victims of illegal stops
and searches. It spared Hogan and Kenna from attending court
hearings and facing defense lawyers' questions about racial
profiling.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 25 cases involving black or Hispanic
defendants, one other case was also put on hold by the attorney
general's office. The ethnic backgrounds of this defendant could
not be determined from his arrest file.
</P>
<P>
   One of the 26 with a suspended case, Michael G. Moye, a
television producer, said the ruling has delayed his right to
challenge Hogan on the details of his arrest on weapons charges on
March 31, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Moye, co-creator of the situation comedy ``Married ... with
Children,'' contended that Hogan stopped him _ erroneously _ for
speeding and then told him he smelled marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the biggest pile of hooey,'' Moye said. ``I don't
even smoke cigarettes. This was an absolutely illegal stop. I'm a
black guy and I had braids. I'm sure I scored a 10 out of 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Moye said he was taking two handguns and a shotgun, all legally
purchased and registered, from his home in California to his home
in Greenwich, Conn., when he was arrested. The weapons are part of
a collection he and his wife take to shooting ranges on the West
Coast, Moye said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I had the guns,'' Moye said. He was arrested and
the guns were confiscated because two of them were loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Moye called the delay unfair. ``I have no record,'' he said.
``I'm an honest citizen. I can't purchase a weapon until they
finish this. My bail money is tied up. I'm being punished.''
</P>
<P>
   Moye's lawyer, Linda Smink, said the delay prevents her from
questioning Hogan in court about profiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt in the world that troopers are doing profile
stops,'' Ms. Smink said. ``Anyone who says they're not is asleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Davis, a spokesman for the attorney general's office, said
Fahy declined to comment on the case, except to say that Hoffman's
ruling was upheld by a state appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman said his December order would not have any bearing on
defense motions for speedy trials. But so far, few have been filed.
</P>
<P>
   Early last month, a state judge rejected a motion filed for a
black man from North Carolina who was arrested on drug charges
after Hogan stopped him last March 17.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Marain, who represents the suspect, Elijah M. Roberts,
said a state judge ruled that Roberts had no standing to seek a
speedy trial because Hoffman had rendered his case inactive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a ruling from the twilight zone,'' Marain said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
