<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE INVESTIGATING COMPLAINTS OF BIAS AGAINST NEW YORK CITY
POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Attorney General Eliot L. Spitzer said Wednesday that
his office would investigate allegations that New York City police
officers stop people on the streets and frisk them without
justification.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer, who took office in January, said that he decided to
begin the state inquiry after hearing many complaints during
campaign stops last year at churches, business forums and colleges
that blacks and other minority residents were often subjected to
improper searches and frisks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tidal wave of concern about this issue,'' he said.
``It is impossible to be out there and not get a sense that this is
perceived as the overwhelming civil rights issue facing the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said that his investigators would use their subpoena
powers to collect data, interview officials and talk to people who
complain that they were unfairly stopped and frisked by the police
to try to determine if there is a systematic problem. Several
lawyers will be assigned to the inquiry full-time, and more will be
added when they are needed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And depending on what the investigation yields, Spitzer said,
its outcome could range from a written report of its findings and
recommendations to a civil-rights lawsuit to try to force the
Police Department to change its practices.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has been brought to the fore since the Feb. 4 shooting
of Amadou Diallo by four police officers, which focused attention
on the city's street crimes unit, which has been crediting with
taking more illegal handguns off the streets then any other.
</P>
<P>
   But critics have warned that its success has come at a price. Of
the 27,061 people frisked by the unit last year, only 4,647 were
arrested _ meaning more than 22,000 people were frisked because
they were mistakenly thought to be armed. The year before was only
marginally better: of 18,023 people frisked in 1997, only 4,899
were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Police Department, Marilyn Mode, said:
``We will cooperate fully with the attorney general.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael D. Hess, the city's corporation counsel, said that the
Giuliani administration had been apprised of the pending
investigation and added that he was confident that it would find
that the police follow proper procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always try to cooperate and respond to a legitimate
inquiry,'' he said. ``I think there are probably thousands of such
stops and frisks a year, and I'm confident that overall, this is
done is a proper and constitutional way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 2253EST &QL; 
