<HEADLINE>
TRAVELING WILL COST RODMAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Worm Watch reached Day 5, and the tale grew stranger
still.
</P>
<P>
   A source told the Daily News that Dennis Rodman is no longer in
Las Vegas or Newport Beach, but Cancun, Mexico (a destination, of
course, once touted by ex-Laker Nick Van Exel, in a moment of
personal infamy).
</P>
<P>
   And the Los Angeles Lakers, who have called Rodman's absence
``excused,'' nevertheless plan to fine him.
</P>
<P>
   But it was management that made that decision, not the players _
as alleged by TNT reporter Craig Sager on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sager's report that Shaquille O'Neal called a team vote to fine
Rodman was greeted with amusement and puzzlement Wednesday. Sager's
source for the report was supposedly Rodman himself, with whom
Sager is chummy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Craig Sager's a liar,'' O'Neal said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Players haven't even discussed Rodman as an issue, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kurt (Rambis), Jerry West and Mitch Kupchak handle that,''
O'Neal said. ``Any votes that go down are called by the president,
handled by the president and tallied up by the president _ me.
There was no votes, so I don't know what the hell Craig's talking
about....
</P>
<P>
   ``If TNT said that, then I'm taking _ what's his name, the owner
of TNT? _ I'll take Ted Turner to court, and I'll settle out for a
million. I'm gonna sue Ted.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis was absolutely befuddled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now how would Rodman know about a team vote if (he's) not
here? Why would (Sager) report that we took a team vote? That's
crazy, that's ludicrous, that's a bunch of B.S.,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The story was reminiscent of last year's report by Fox Sports _
also erroneous _ that players had voted unanimously to oust coach
Del Harris.
</P>
<P>
   ``We handle our disciplinary problems internally, through
management,'' Rambis said. ``(Players) don't determine who gets
fined, they don't have a say in it.... They can vote 'til their
heads blow off.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Rodman ``definitely will be fined,'' Rambis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has nothing to do with Vegas.... You're allowed certain
leniencies for some things, but you're still responsible to being
with the team,'' he said. ``I think the difference lies in how long
an excused absence is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have not set a deadline for Rodman to return, nor
have they reached the point of considering more drastic measures,
such as releasing him.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis still believes Rodman might return by the time this
six-game road trip ends, Monday in Dallas, but assumes nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until I see his glowing, orange head walk through the door, I
don't know when he's coming back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sam's town: Homecoming wasn't as enjoyable this time when Lakers
rookie Sam Jacobson returned to his home state of Minnesota on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   His alma mater, the University of Minnesota, is embroiled in an
academic fraud scandal, stemming from an ex-university tutor's
claim she did players' homework for them. Four players were held
out of the Gophers' NCAA Tournament opener, which they lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked,'' Jacobson said. ``Coach (Clem) Haskins, he
stresses academics pretty strongly.''
</P>
<P>
   The entire state has been consumed by the scandal, to the point
that Gov. Jesse Ventura has even weighed in with a critique of the
newspaper that broke the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Monica Lewinsky out there,'' Jacobson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
