u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-BUDGET-1STLD     03-17 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-BUDGET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PANEL PASSES REPUBLICAN BLUEPRINT FOR TAX CUTS AND SPENDING
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: SUBS 5th graf, The plan ..., to CORRECT figure to $1.8
TRillion, sted billion, for excess revenue over next decade.)  
 (rk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Budget Committee passed a Republican tax
and spending blueprint Wednesday night, sweeping aside objections
from Democrats who said the plan promised too much in tax cuts and
did too little to deal with the looming problems in Social Security
and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The party-line vote of 22 to 18 came after another day of
partisan clashes over how the nation should take advantage of its
improving fiscal outlook. The Senate Budget Committee also moved
toward approval of the Republican plan, with a vote expected on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The full House and Senate plan to take up the Republican budget
next week. With approval likely in both chambers, Congress appears
headed toward months of battles with the Clinton administration
encompassing both the annual tax and spending bills and efforts to
shore up Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The budget outline approved by the House Budget Committee
tonight provides for a tax cut of at least $15 billion next year
and nearly $800 billion over the next decade. It would increase
spending for the military and education, but to remain with the
tight spending limits imposed by the bipartisan 1997 balanced
budget deal, it would scale back a broad array of other programs.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would also require that all excess revenue generated by
the Social Security payroll tax _ $1.8 trillion over the next
decade _ be set aside by Congress and used only for reducing the
federal debt or to pay for a change to the retirement system, such
as the establishment of individual investment accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to establish their credentials for fiscal responsibility,
Democrats have also pledged to stick to the spending limits,
constraining their ability to attack Republicans for slashing
domestic programs.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Democrats have been hammering at the Republican plan as
failing to set aside for Medicare any specific amount of money out
of the projected non-Social Security surplus of almost $800 billion
over the next 10 years. The budget proposed last month by President
Clinton set aside $350 billion over that period to help keep
Medicare, the health insurance system for the elderly, from going
broke as the population ages.
</P>
<P>
   The administration also opened an attack Wednesday on the
Republican proposal to lock away the Social Security surpluses by
writing into law a gradual reduction in the amount of public debt
the government could have outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Democratic leaders in Congress, Treasury
Secretary Robert E. Rubin said the Republican ``lockbox'' plan
could leave the treasury unable to refinance debt or issue new debt
in an unexpected economic downturn. As a result, Rubin said, he
would recommend that Clinton veto the bill.
</P>
<P>
   In both the House and Senate committees, Democrats offered
proposals that would have blocked or reduced the Republican tax
cuts, but were thwarted on party-line votes.
</P>
<P>
   The budget resolutions making their way through the two chambers
will not become law and are not subject to a veto. But they set the
priorities for the tax-writing and appropriations committees as
they develop legislation over the rest of the year, and they amount
to a detailed agenda for the Republican-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest hurdle facing the Republican plan may come not from
the White House, but from the difficulty Congress will have in
voting to cut dozens of popular programs at a time when the economy
is strong and projections of future surpluses continue to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Even Republicans on the appropriations committees are skeptical
that they can pass bills enacting deep spending cuts. Both parties
are hopeful that projections of next year's surplus will be
increased in coming months.
</P>
<P>
   And in both parties there is a growing sense that the most
likely way out of the problem is a deal late in the year that would
split any fiscal windfall between spending and bigger tax cuts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
