<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-MAVS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARBURY'S 29 INVIGORATES NETS AND FANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ With 16 friends and family members plus
thousands of eager Nets fans watching, Stephon Marbury proved he
could live up to the hype Wednesday night at Continental Arena. In
his first home game as a Net, the Brooklyn-bred playmaker scored a
game-high 29 points to lead the Nets to an 88-87 victory over the
Dallas Mavericks and end New Jersey's eight-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   While Marbury made numerous clutch baskets, his backcourt mate,
Kerry Kittles, scored the game-winning points by hitting two free
throws with 17 seconds remaining. Kittles, who scored just 8
points, earned the chance for redemption by rebounding a missed
running jumper by Marbury and being fouled.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas, which dropped to 8-16, had a chance to win, but Michael
Finley's 16-footer over Kendall Gill bounced in and out of the rim
as the buzzer sounded. The missed shot sent the Nets, and
particularly Marbury, into a frenzy, as they jumped around the
court with outstretched arms.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury was more emotional than anyone, and it was not the first
time of the night. After tying the score at 85-85 on a 3-point play
with 57 seconds left, the newest Net ran across midcourt, raising
both arms to get the crowd involved on his way to the bench after a
timeout was called.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas regained the lead, 87-85, when Gary Trent backed in
Jayson Williams to score with 38 seconds left. That set up the
Nets' final offensive sequence, highlighted by Marbury and Kittles.
</P>
<P>
   For the Nets (4-18), Williams grabbed 21 rebounds and Keith Van
Horn had 19 points and 10 rebounds. Gill scored 15 points. Trent
and Finley led the Mavericks with 21 points apiece.
</P>
<P>
   In his first major change since replacing John Calipari as
coach, Don Casey essentially used Marbury as a shooting guard and
ran the offense through him. While Kittles and Doug Overton handled
the ball above the 3-point line, Marbury ran off screens to get
open on the wings. Once he received the ball, the offense was in
his hands.
</P>
<P>
   Using his quickness and a number of electrifying moves, he
created shots for himself and his teammates. His breathtaking
crossover and behind-the-back dribbles drew buzzes from the crowd
and enabled him to get to the basket for shots in the lane. When
his own shot wasn't there, he kicked the ball out to open
teammates. But the Nets' inability to make jumpers kept them from
capitalizing.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Nets' dismal shooting _ they were 9 for 33 (27
percent) midway through the second quarter _ enabled Dallas to go
ahead by 35-23 five minutes before the half. But just when it
seemed the Nets would fall to yet another less-talented opponent,
they erupted.
</P>
<P>
   With Horn waking from a first-quarter slumber in which he scored
just 2 points, the Nets finished the half with a 19-4 run. And most
impressively, all of the points came on driving layups, tip-in
dunks or free throws. It was an example of the Nets doing something
they had failed to do all season _ adjusting.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn scored two baskets on penetration moves and hit three
free throws for 7 points during the run. He gave the Nets their
first lead under Casey when hitting two foul shots with 36 seconds
remaining in the half to give the Nets a 41-39 advantage. After
Marbury scored his 12th point on a free throw just before the
break, the Nets went into the locker room ahead by 3.
</P>
<P>
   While the strategy to play through Marbury was neither brilliant
nor creative, it was at least a plan, and that pleased the former
Brooklyn Lincoln High School star. After his first two games with
the Nets, Marbury complained about the club's lack of a game plan.
He had come from the system-strong Minnesota Timberwolves to a team
that he said was basically playing street ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a strategy,'' Marbury said before the game in
reference to losses in Miami and Toronto. ``We just came out and
played basketball, and in order to win games in the NBA, you have
to have a strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Things got rough less than two minutes into the third, when Van
Horn reacted to the slinging elbows of Shawn Bradley, the former
Nets' disappointment. While Bradley was putting up a shot, Van Horn
dumped him with a forearm shiver to the chest that sent Bradley
into a fury. Though the two players began yapping, no fracas ensued
because players and referees intervened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-99 2325EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
