<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-PRICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAUDI PLAN TO CUT PRODUCTION PUSHES CRUDE OIL PRICES HIGHER
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Crude oil futures surged Wednesday, with prices nearing a
five-month high, after Saudi Aramco, the state-owned oil company in
Saudi Arabia, said it would cut sales of crude oil to all its major
clients by 12 percent April 1.
</P>
<P>
   A much larger-than-expected drop in gasoline inventories in the
United States and reports that Russia would also cut production
also contributed to the rise.
</P>
<P>
   Crude oil for April delivery was up 59 cents, or 4.1 percent,
closing at $15.05 a barrel in trading on the New York Mercantile
Exchange _ its highest closing price since Oct. 7. And on the
London International Petroleum Exchange, oil futures for delivery
in May were up by 59 cents, to $13.27 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in crude oil comes as gasoline prices at the pump,
falling since October, have shown a slight increase, according to a
survey released this week by the American Automobile Association.
</P>
<P>
   The average price of self-serve regular gasoline rose by one
cent, to 97 cents, in March _ the first increase since October. It
was still 11.1 cents lower than the average price in March last
year. The survey was based on 65,000 gasoline transactions from
March 12 through March 15.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have predicted that gasoline prices could rise by
five cents or more because of the higher crude oil prices. There
could also be attempts by refiners and station owners to put
through price increases more quickly than actual changes in crude
oil prices would warrant to increase their profits, which have been
under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The stance by Saudi Aramco re-affirmed the Saudis' commitment,
made Friday, to cut their production by 585,000 barrels a day. That
pledge was part of an effort by a coalition of major oil producers
who vowed to cut output by a total of two million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts called the step a major concession by the Saudis,
who have refused to limit their output to fewer than eight million
barrels a day. Analysts added that it was a major reason why other
producers were willing to make their cuts and why the cuts would
stand.
</P>
<P>
   Other major oil producers have been upset with Saudi Arabia for
increasing its market share after the gulf war at the expense of
Iraq, then not cutting back even as Iraq began to export two
million barrels a day. The Iraqi exports are being made through a
special allowance for humanitarian aid under the sanctions imposed
by the United Nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
