A4785 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-IOWA-COACH-NYT &LR;      03-17 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-IOWA-COACH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAME-DUCK COACH GIVES IOWA AN `EDGE' AGAINST UCONN
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ If they stop to think about it, the Iowa players are
already feeling deprived over the pending departure of their coach,
Tom Davis, whose contract is running out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never been a distraction, but maybe it's a subconscious
reason to fight,'' said Kent McCausland, the senior shooter.
``Sure, you think about things like, `This is the last time I'll
play Illinois.' It gives you a little edge. You're always looking
for a little edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Iowa, seeded fifth in the West Regional, will need some edge
Thursday night when it runs into top-seeded Connecticut in the
Round of 16 of the National Collegiate Athletic Association
tournament. In the first game of the doubleheader, 10th-seeded
Gonzaga meets sixth-seeded Florida.
</P>
<P>
   This is obviously a year of upsets, a year of parity, a year of
edges. But only Iowa is playing with a coach who has known for
nearly a year that he would not be retained after this season. The
athletic director, Bob Bowlsby, has not explained why he did not
retain the 60-year-old Davis, and there seems to be no leeway for
reconsideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always critics,'' Davis said Wednesday. ``The
grandmothers will write you: `Play these kids. Get on the officials
more. Get onto the court.'''
</P>
<P>
   Davis is an extremely popular coach who had successful terms at
Lafayette, Boston College and Stanford before coming here 12 years
ago. He is relatively short, white-thatched and rational, as well
as the possessor of a Ph.D. in history. He has the reputation as a
gentleman, which has held up as reporters badgered him to say
something crabby or controversial about his dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something I would use as a tool,'' Davis said, ``but
I haven't ducked it or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis tries to convince people that his players are not affected
by his status. ``Maybe it's an issue in their minds,'' he said,
``but if you work with 18-year-olds the way I do, you know that the
exuberance of being here overwhelms a lot of other things. They
have been responsive. They pay close attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of his seniors say they are most definitely thinking about
Davis. ``He gave you a chance to play Big 10 basketball,''
McCausland said. ``You enjoy playing golf with him in the summer. I
feel like I'm being robbed a little, after I graduate.''
</P>
<P>
   Jess Settles, the burly senior, said: ``He's going to clean out
the office. I hope I'm not around when he does it. It's always nice
when guys can come back to meet the coach _ to get free tickets, if
nothing else. The coach is the university. That's why you go to a
university. When you come back, you want to swing into coach's
office.''
</P>
<P>
   That will not happen for McCausland and Settles at Iowa, but
Davis just might be coaching somewhere else. Davis said he did not
want to think about his next step until the season is over because
``most of us are wiped out, even the younger guys. You just want to
take time off and reflect.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis was sanguine about his tough game against Jim Calhoun, the
Connecticut coach, who raved about Davis' innovations with the
pressing defense and also praised Davis as a ``role model'' for not
grousing in public.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun needs to get past his colleague in his quest to reach
the Final Four for the first time. Davis has never been there,
either. His Iowa teams have qualified for this tournament in nine
of his 12 seasons, previously losing to Nevada-Las Vegas, Arizona,
North Carolina State, Duke, Wake Forest and Kentucky, none of them
outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, his next loss with the Hawkeyes will be his last.
And his next public complaint will be his first.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
