<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW HERBIE CAN SAVE THE BALLPARK AT ARLINGTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Save us, Herb.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Mr. Kelleher, only you can bring some form of dignity to an
otherwise disgusting process.
</P>
<P>
   Herb, I'm talking about The Ballpark in Arlington. About the
selling of the naming rights of this cathedral, this shrine, this
Venice of all ballyards.
</P>
<P>
   The plane is making it's final approach, Herb. In protest, we
could ask for volunteers to be tied to the runway _ but who cleans
up the mess?
</P>
<P>
   As of this week, the landing gear is locked. Herb, your pals at
American Airlines have come with the cash, and the new downtown
Dallas sports arena will forever be known as...
</P>
<P>
   Really, it's not so bad. American Airlines Arena. But Tom Hicks,
who has half a say on the arena, is the lone voice when it comes to
The Ballpark. And his next major business transaction will be
selling that name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sacrilege,'' I say. ``A down-payment for Curt Schilling,''
Hicks says.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us on the losing end of the argument can now only hope
that Weed-Eater, Drano, and Listerine aren't under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Already around the country there's such silliness as National
Rental Car Stadium, PSINet Stadium, 3Comm Park, Qualcomm Stadium
... they all have such a nice ring, don't you think?
</P>
<P>
   But none of those were exactly classic structures to begin with.
To cheese-up something like The Ballpark in Arlington would leave a
permanent scar on Hicks' otherwise stellar ownership credentials of
the Rangers and Stars.
</P>
<P>
   This is where Herb Kelleher, head of Southwest Airlines can come
fly with us. Gas up the company plane and reach for the hip pocket,
Herb.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Airlines Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, take out ``Airlines.'' Make it just ``Southwest
Ballpark in Arlington.''
</P>
<P>
   That's you, Herb. And at least some geographical flavor is
involved. I can live with it.
</P>
<P>
   And don't anybody else come around here preaching that a man who
pays $250 million for a team and ballpark can name it anything he
wants. Don't give me that Jerry Jones stuff about he can wander the
sidelines and swap sweat with Nine-Toed Deion if he so desires.
</P>
<P>
   Public money built the ballpark. Just because your title reads
``owner'' doesn't mean you have the right to make a fool of
yourself or the hallowed grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks said from the start he would sell the rights in Arlington,
but would do so in the name of dignity. He did so with the Dallas
arena, but there's never been an arena to ever compare to this
ballpark, because even the new ones are basically all the same.
Junior Perot and Hicks will deliver the first class goods in
Dallas, but it won't be different.
</P>
<P>
   The Ballpark in Arlington was built to be a one-and-only, and
is.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I blame Kevin Brown for this cultural disaster. Then
again, I blame everything on the former Rangers pitcher and
snot-ball. If Brown wasn't signing hundred million dollar-plus
contracts, commerical names attached to ballparks wouldn't be
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't figured out yet how to finger Brown for American
Airlines Arena in Dallas. But in time I'll think of something.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal American cut with Perot and Hicks is said to be for a
base financial package of $90 million for 20 years, and then it may
go twice that much with other promotional opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   One person familiar with these kinds of transactions said
yesterday the name-selling of The Ballpark would fetch at least
that, probably more. But another voice disagreed, with his estimate
being The Ballpark topping out at $3 million a season for the base
package.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the amount, Mr. Kelleher can afford it, plus he can
trump his rival airline, plus ``Southwest Ballpark in Arlington''
is almost a turbulence-free flight.
</P>
<P>
   True confession:
</P>
<P>
   At first, I hated The Ballpark in Arlington for a name. The
summer day it was announced seven years ago, George W. Bush
wandered into the Arlington Stadium press box seeking reaction,
which was mostly all negative.
</P>
<P>
   As the Rangers' managing general partner, Bush had also just
announced his candidacy for governor against the incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, what do you think we should have named it?'' George
barked at me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ann Richards Field,'' I barked back.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has never let me forget that two years later I was praising
the name. OK, it grew on me. I love The Ballpark in Arlington, both
in name and structure.
</P>
<P>
   With help from Herb, not much would have to change.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
