<SLUG> BC-MERGER-ADVISER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DONALDSON, LUFKIN MAKES A MOVE UP MERGER CHARTS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Business has been so good for the investment bankers
at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette lately, even they can hardly
believe it.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson, Lufkin, which rarely holds a top spot among
mergers-and-acquisitions advisers, has made an impressive showing
so far this year, advising on several recent high-profile deals.
According to the Securities Data Co., Donaldson, Lufkin now ranks
third in dollar volume of worldwide transactions through Wednesday,
a far cry from its seventh-place showing this time last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years ago, we weren't as focused on mergers and
acquisitions,'' said Hal Ritch, global co-head of the firm's merger
department. Since then, Donaldson, Lufkin, which is 74 percent
owned by the Equitable Co., a unit of the French insurer AXA SA,
``has intelligently grown as an investment banking shop.''
</P>
<P>
   The firm has been on a hiring binge over the last five years,
expanding its banking staff almost fourfold. It has aggressively
wooed bankers from competitors like Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.,
Wasserstein Perella &AMP; Co. and Lazard Freres. In the financial
services arena, for instance, Donaldson, Lufkin hired a team of
bankers from UBS Securities last year.
</P>
<P>
   Those investments are beginning to pay off. At this time last
year, Donaldson, Lufkin had advised on only $39 billion worth of
mergers. This year, its total is $136 billion and spans several
industries.
</P>
<P>
   The firm has advised two Dutch insurers, including Aegon NV on
its $9.7 billion deal for the TransAmerica Corp. It also played a
key role in Allied Waste Industries' recent $9 billion buyout of
Browning-Ferris Industries and the Adelphia Communications Corp.'s
$3.6 billion merger with the Century Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at their strategy, they have always focused on
niche, high-margin businesses that come up and surprise people,''
said Henry McVey, an analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. On
Tuesday, McVey raised his stock price target for the company to $72
from $64 in the next 12 months, in part because of the industry's
pickup in merger business as well as growth in Donaldson, Lufkin's
online brokerage service, DLJ Direct.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Donaldson, Lufkin said Wednesday that it planned to file
an initial public offering of stock that will track the performance
of its online business. The firm's shares dropped $3.0625
Wednesday, or 4.5 percent, to $65.75, in part because of
uncertainty about the tracking stock.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   McVey said that the company was also starting to profit from
relationships in Europe as well as other departments, including its
high-yield and bank-loan divisions. And its business of processing
trades for other companies should keep providing steady pretax
profit margins _ as much as 25 percent, McVey said.
</P>
<P>
   Security Data's current rankings include other surprises. Lazard
Freres has moved up from eighth place to fourth. Merrill Lynch, No.
1 this time last year, has fallen to sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill lost out when its client, the Bell Atlantic Corp. failed
to buy Airtouch Communications after Vodafone Group PLC came in
with a higher bid. So far this year, Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. and
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, perennial heavyweights, are No. 1 and
No. 2, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Another surprise is Citigroup's Salomon Smith Barney unit, which
has slipped from No. 5 last year to No. 12 in merger advice. In a
twist, two ex-Salomon bankers now at Donaldson, Lufkin are advising
Olivetti in its $60 billion hostile bid for Telecom Italia.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent flurry of activity, Ritch acknowledged that
no one knows who will end this year atop the rankings. ``We don't
stay up at night worrying,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
