<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4803 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-FRANCIS-ART-2TAKE     03-17 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-FRANCIS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR FRANCIS, MARYLAND WAS THE END OF THE YELLOW BRICK ROAD
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ It was during the long, lonely rides across
Texas that Steve Francis had his doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was on those six-hour junior college bus trips from,
like, Houston to Brownsville, I didn't think it would happen,''
Francis said. ``I had so much stuff to think about.''
</P>
<P>
   So much stuff before the 21-year-old Francis, Maryland's
peripatetic guard, would wend his way through an extraordinary
odyssey to become a sure-fire NBA lottery pick if he enters the
draft after this season.
</P>
<P>
   From the oblivion of those junior college days, Francis has a
starring role Thursday in a much-anticipated South Regional
semifinal game between the second-seeded Terrapins (28-5) and
third-seeded St. John's (27-8).
</P>
<P>
   The second part of the NCAA doubleheader has top-seeded Auburn
facing fourth-seeded Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   Francis, a junior averaging 17.2 points and 4.6 assists, toiled
in obscurity for years before bursting onto the college basketball
highlight reel this season with gravity-defying lean-in dunks so
spectacular that they caught the eye of St. John's Ron Artest.
</P>
<P>
   Artest had never heard of Francis before this year. But few had,
save the hoops junkie trolling the Internet and the NBA scouts who
descended on little Allegany Community College in western Maryland
last season.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to keep a bead on the moving player, so perhaps the
Red Storm is still not fully aware of the Francis phenomenon.
Perhaps St. John's has not seen enough of the 43-inch vertical leap
or appreciates the 93 steals this season _ the fifth-highest
single-season total in Atlantic Coast Conference history _ or heard
that Francis was a second-team all-ACC pick before he had played a
single game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can contain him, without those high-flying dunks, he's
just an average player,'' said St. John's forward Lavor Postell,
who will likely be one of the players trying to guard him.
</P>
<P>
   Containing Francis, who primarily plays shooting guard although
he came to Maryland as a point guard, is precisely the problem. His
journey from Takoma Park, Md., to the University of Maryland in
College Park, just five minutes away _ which includes stops at two
high schools, one prep school, a firehouse and two junior colleges
_ means he has not been followed by the buzz of the next anointed
star.
</P>
<P>
   College Park is Francis' sixth campus in six years. He played
just one year of high school ball as a sophomore, mostly as a
third-string point, missing the other three seasons because of
academic problems, injuries and transfers.
</P>
<P>
   When he was a senior, the death of his mother, Brenda, from
cancer at age 39, left Francis so despondent that he stopped going
to school. Later, he went to a Connecticut prep school, but left it
because he couldn't afford to pay the tuition.
</P>
<P>
   That was nearly the end. At 18, Francis was working toward a
high school equivalency degree and playing pick-up games in the
basement of a firehouse near his Takoma Park home against teams
stocked largely with firemen. He was on the precipice of losing the
dreams his mother told him never to give up.
</P>
<P>
   Francis' break came when he was invited to join the Maryland
Amateur Athletic Union team that played in the 19-and-under
nationals in 1996 in Winter Park, Fla. He made the all-tournament
team and got a scholarship to the junior college powerhouse, San
Jacinto College in Texas. He took the team to the 1997 national
junior college final, where they lost to Iowa's Indian Hills.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But it was only last winter, when Francis transferred to
Allegany in Cumberland, Md., because he was homesick, that the
legend began to bloom. Francis became the first guard to lead two
junior college teams to undefeated seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went to the junior college championships, they were
putting two and three guys on me,'' Francis said, ``so I knew it
wasn't going to be the last time I played basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a firm believer in God, and all the nights I prayed, all
the times I wondered when it was going to happen. It's slowly
coming true. Where I came from there is always someone better.
Since I got the chance to represent where I came from, I thought
I'd take advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   When Francis brought his springy legs, a wicked crossover
dribble and a tattoo in memory of his mother _ he rubs it before
every free throw _ to Maryland, the hype spread through basketball
circles. After all, during the summer league he dunked over Chris
Webber in a pickup game, didn't he, and dunked three times in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   So great were the expectations that there was concern his
teammates would resent him and suspect he was there just to
showcase his talent and move on yet again. But Francis moved
seemlessly into an already talented team, playing both guard
positions, becoming an integral part of the Terrapins' pressure
defense and quickly shooting down a broadcast report that he is
going to the NBA after this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I liked was his willingness to blend in with the rest of
the players,'' Maryland coach Gary Williams said. ``He's not
averaging many more shots than anybody else. If you watch ESPN, you
think he just dunks at the end of transition.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last eight games, Francis is averaging 21.9 points and is
shooting 62.4 percent from the field, an enormous part of a
Maryland offense that thrives on the turnovers its pressure defense
causes. But Artest refuted Postell's theory that if you take away
the dunks, Francis can be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen him crossing people over and he's very active on the
boards,'' Artest said. ``I don't think you can take him out of his
game.''
</P>
<P>
   St. John's coach Mike Jarvis said: ``He's a highlight film. I'm
probably not going to sleep all night trying to think about how to
stop him. The kid is one of the top five prospects in the country.
How many weaknesses can he have?''
</P>
<P>
   Not many, especially now that Francis has earned the respect of
one person who knows how to stop him one on one, the person who
recognized his talent when their games were the only games Francis
was playing: his older brother Terry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was intimidated by going up against him,'' Francis said.
``He was the high school player of the year on defense his junior
and senior years. He has a lot of respect for my game now, too.
Now, I don't think there's anybody who can stop me individually.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
